<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE BLOCKS AMENDMENTS ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE LEGISLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TTN: Calif., Conn., Ky. Mass., N.Y., Texas)  (Eds: Sub ne lede and grafs throughout reporting on the rejection
of several campaign finance amendments Thursday evening and adding
information on a spending bill that was pulled from the floor.)
(js) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Picking up the pace on the campaign finance debate,
a majority of the House voted repeatedly on Thursday night to
preserve intact bipartisan legislation to cut back on money in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Like hockey goalies, Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Rep.
Martin Meehan, D-Mass., kept up an effort to block 16 of the 37
amendments proposed to their bill. They asserted that the proposals
were intended to divide their coalition and drive away supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective today is to defeat all the poison pills,'' Shays
said. ``We're still alive. This is the bill that won't die. But
we're in the middle of a minefield.''
</P>
<P>
   In a series of votes Thursday night, the two lawmakers handily
defeated eight amendments, including six that most concerned them.
The votes showed their coalition holding strong against the
onslaught. More amendments will be considered on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan legislation would effectively ban unlimited and
unregulated contributions to political parties, or soft money,
which were at the heart of the 1996 campaign finance abuses. The
bill would also restrict independent advertising by single-issue
advocacy groups in specified periods before elections.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation _ with a companion bill in the Senate _ is
fiercely opposed by the Republican leadership and most
rank-and-file Republicans. Some view it as a way to erode their
party's traditional advantage in fund-raising while others call it
an unconstitutional abridgement of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout weeks of intermittent night-time debate, the
coalition supporting the Shays-Meehan bill has managed to defeat
several amendments and competing proposals and show that it has
majority support.
</P>
<P>
   After stretching out the debate for months, the House is now
pushing toward a final vote on the overhaul of the campaign finance
laws early next week, when the Senate will already be on its August
recess.
</P>
<P>
   With Shays-Meehan supporters increasingly confident of victory,
the Senate recess will eliminate the possibility that Democrats
could capitalize on House action and try to force the Senate to
take up campaign finance legislation immediately. Similar
legislation died in the Senate earlier this year when it drew a
slim majority but not enough votes to cut off a filibuster.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Among the amendments defeated Thursday night were several,
strongly opposed by Democrats, that would change the ``motor voter
law'' on voter registration to allow states to eliminate mail-in
registrations and to require photo IDs for voters.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans crafted such proposals in response to a contested
California congressional election in which Rep. Loretta Sanchez, a
Democrat, drew strong support among voters of Hispanic origin and
toppled Robert Dornan, the Republican incumbent. The Republicans
charged that a number of illegal immigrants had voted but
ultimately allowed Ms. Sanchez to keep her seat.
</P>
<P>
   Another amendment that was defeated 278-147 would have required
candidates for congressional seats to raise at least 50 percent of
their campaign contributions inside their districts. Democrats get
more of their money from political action committees than
Republicans do and this change would have made it harder for them
to rely on such committees.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of why Shays and Meehan have been leery of amendments,
a wide array of 65 groups concerned with immigrants' rights came
out against the campaign finance legislation on Thursday because of
passage earlier in the month of an amendment sponsored by Rep. Vito
Fossella of Staten Island. The amendment would ban contributions by
noncitizens who are legal residents of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Rep. Tom Delay, the House majority whip, welcomed the
opposition, consisting of groups ranging from Catholic Charities
Immigrant Services in Honolulu to the Jewish Federation of
Metropolitan Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, R-Texas, has led the fight against Shays-Meehan _ as well
as the strategy of trying to sink it through amendments. ``We've
always been against Shays-Meehan,'' said John Feehery, DeLay's
spokesman. ``Now we've won some converts.'' But even some of the
staunchest opponents of the campaign finance legislation were
admitting on Thursday night that they no longer thought they could
stop it from being approved by the House.
</P>
<P>
   On a related issue, Senate Republicans were forced to pull a
spending bill from the floor Thursday after Sen. Mitch McConnell,
R-Ky., attacked an amendment that would limit the term of the
general counsel for the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats threatened to tie up the bill if Republicans did not
allow a full debate on McConnell's measure, which they called a
backdoor attempt to stop the Federal Election Commission from doing
its job overseeing campaign spending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
