<HEADLINE>
GUZMAN DAZZLES RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Rangers did not score.
</P>
<P>
   Their lineup produced only five hits and went 0-for-11 with
runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   It tantalized general manager Doug Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Juan Guzman, who pitched eight scoreless innings in
the Blue Jays' 1-0 victory last night at SkyDome, became Melvin's
latest potential acquisition, according to a high-ranking Blue Jays
official.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rangers joined the Yankees, Indians, Angels and
Orioles as potential suitors interested in acquiring Guzman (6-12,
4.41) before tonight's 11 p.m. trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, who last night remained in Toronto, could not be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly say \RMelvin\S has not told me that we're close
to making `this' or `that' deal,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates
said before last night's game, and he receives at least two updates
from the general manager every day.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers assistant general manager Dan O'Brien acknowledged the
organization's discussions regarding White Sox third baseman Robin
Ventura, but he also added ``that has not been a topic of
conversation'' within the last couple of days in the front office.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' recent discussions regarding the potential
acquisition of position players, O'Brien said, should not be
interpreted as the end of Melvin's attempts to strengthen the
rotation, which entered last night's game with the league's highest
earned-run average (5.86).
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't draw that conclusion,'' O'Brien said. ``Doug is
very cautious and thorough. I think he's trying to explore every
potential opportunity that becomes available.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin's most recent acquisition, right-hander Esteban Loaiza,
drew rave reviews from Oates with his performance against the Blue
Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza, who registered a career-high nine strikeouts,
surrendered only one run on four hits and two walks in the fourth
complete-game effort of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was in total command all night,'' Oates said. ``I
like what I see _ hearing the mitt pop and doing it against good
fastball hitters like Jose Canseco and Shawn Green. He had enough
velocity to make them swing and miss, and it didn't just happen
once or twice. That's good stuff right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza, whom the Rangers acquired July 17 from the Pirates for
right-hander Todd Van Poppel and minor-league second baseman Warren
Morris, surrendered the game's lone run on a two-out, fifth-inning
single to center fielder Shannon Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The play reflected one of the Rangers' defensive limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza's 94-mph fastball on the inner half of the plate broke
Stewart's bat, but the ground ball rolled through the middle of the
infield. Shortstop Kevin Elster, who does not possess great range
at his position, chased the ball behind second base and made a
sliding attempt to prevent it from reaching the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Elster's range failed him, and the ball rolled into center field
on SkyDome's artificial surface. Catcher Darrin Fletcher scored
from second base without a throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good pitch,'' Loaiza said. ``It might have been an
out or an infield hit on grass.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza (0-2, 4.19) responded with an inning-ending strikeout of
left fielder Tony Phillips and retired right fielder Green,
designated hitter Canseco and first baseman Carlos Delgado in order
on strikes during the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman recorded three strikeouts and surrendered only five hits
and three walks during his 106-pitch appearance. The right-hander
expects it to be his final start as a member of the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking that this was my last game here,'' said
Guzman, who owns a 3-4 record during his past eight starts despite
a 2.01 ERA during that period. ``I'm going to miss this place
because, as you can imagine, I've been here eight years. Plus, this
is one of the best organizations there is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers might be his next organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
