<HEADLINE>
DATA OVERLOAD EASED BY PARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Two months ago, Chan Ho Park was thinking too
much and not winning enough.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Dodgers ace had no confidence after lasting just
21/3 innings May 24 in a loss at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past month, Park has turned it all around. He won his
fifth straight and 10th overall Thursday, allowing two hits and one
run in eight innings in a 3-1 victory over Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was his best start of the year,'' first baseman Eric
Karros said. ``When you think that we no longer have Ramon
Martinez, Hideo Nomo and Ismael Valdes, three of our opening day
starters, what he is doing is phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Park, who tied Nomo last year for the club lead with 14
victories, has allowed just seven runs in 491/3 innings (1.10 ERA).
</P>
<P>
   He says the difference is eliminating the negative thoughts that
distracted him on the mound. He rarely pitched under adversity last
year and got rattled when he did earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now everything is positive,'' said Park, who hasn't lost since
June 21. ``I just make sure to keep things simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard time: With left-hander Matt Beech on the mound, the
Dodgers went with right-handed Trenidad Hubbard in left field.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard has three of his four homers against right-handed
pitching, but he came in hitting .417 against left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   He was 0 for 2 with a sacrifice fly against Beech, but in the
field, he took extra bases away from Rico Brogna with the bases
loaded in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That catch turned the game around,'' manager Glenn Hoffman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed hitting Matt Luke has five homers in his last 11
games, but Hoffman said he would continue to use Hubbard against
left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give Hubbard at-bats to keep him sharp,'' Hoffman
said. ``And we think Luke is better in this setup as well. Everyone
stays sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   The odd man out is Jim Eisenreich, who has just 10 at-bats since
the All-Star break. Eisenreich had one hit in three pinch at-bats
in this series and received a standing ovation before and after
each plate appearance. Eisenreich played with the Phillies from
1993-96.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were the greatest days of my career,'' said Eisenreich,
who batted .318 in 1993 for the NL-champion Phillies. ``Ever since
I left, the fans have done that for me. It's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: Korean right-hander Jin Ho Cho, demoted to Double-A
Trenton, N.J., by the Boston Red Sox, attended the game to watch
Park. Cho was 0-3 with an 8.20 ERA at Boston. ... Beech struck out
10 after not striking anyone out in his last start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
