<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: COOPERSTOWN GETS SHORT SHRIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ceremony to induct Mike Singletary, Anthony Munoz, Dwight
Stephenson, Paul Krause and Tommy McDonald into the Pro Football
Hall of Fame Saturday will be carried live on ESPN2 from noon to 2
p.m. That's live. For two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, the inductions of Don Sutton, Larry Doby and Lee
MacPhail into the Baseball Hall of Fame were carried by ESPN2 on
tape, for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Why such different treatment? Is baseball unworthy? If the
Cooperstown, N.Y., ceremony was renamed the ``ESPY Baseball Hall of
Fame Dudes Show Hosted by Norm McDonald,'' would it air live in
prime time?
</P>
<P>
   ESPN insists the treatment of pro pigskin has nothing to do with
its new deal to spend $600 million annually for National Football
League cable television rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the beginning of the football season, so the timing is
great as a promotional opportunity,'' said Mike Soltys, an ESPN
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The football ceremony in Canton, Ohio, usually occurs on the
same day as ESPN's first preseason game _ the Green Bay-Kansas City
game will be seen at 10 p.m. Eastern time, from Tokyo _ although
the events did not coincide last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL usually has five players to induct, and it's a good
way to lead into our game,'' Soltys said.
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget that ABC, ESPN's corporate cousin, is
showing the Hall of Fame Game between Pittsburgh and Tampa Bay at 7
p.m. Saturday. Boomer Esiason, the new co-host of the Miss America
pageant, will make his debut with his ``Monday Night Football''
colleagues, Al Michaels and Dan Dierdorf.
</P>
<P>
   Yet five hours will elapse between the induction ceremony and
ABC's game and eight before ESPN's, during which ESPN will carry
loads of golf and ESPN2 will show a lot of auto and horse racing.
So the Canton fete is less ESPN's lead-in than a reminder.
</P>
<P>
   But if properly programmed, ESPN could have turned the baseball
festivities into a dandy lead-in to Sunday night baseball. It could
have replaced a ``Superbouts'' rerun from 6-7 p.m. and led in to
``SportsCenter,'' the baseball pregame show and the 8 p.m.
Rockies-Cardinals game. It's astonishing that ESPN _a positive
baseball force since 1990 _ hasn't chosen to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN has not done as much as possible with the Baseball Hall of
Fame show to make it an event. It has expanded the program to 60
minutes on occasion, depending on the allure of the inductees. But
rarely has it looked like more than a hastily edited rehash, with
hardly a sense of place. And there is no rationale for showing only
84 seconds from Doby, a racial trailblazer, 53 seconds from
MacPhail or nothing from Sam Lacy, the legendary African-American
writer, and Jaime Jarrin, the Spanish-language voice of the
Dodgers, who entered the hall's writers and broadcasters section.
</P>
<P>
   How would ESPN have sliced and diced Mike Webster's emotional
induction speech last year _ and his former Steeler teammate Terry
Bradshaw's madcap accompaniment _ if the football show were wedged
into a 30-minute time slot? If Pete Rose is ever inducted, what
will he get? An hour? On tape?
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Soltys said, the baseball show will very likely
expand to 90 minutes, assuming that Nolan Ryan, George Brett and
Carlton Fisk are the inductees. But it will still be on tape, from
5:30 to 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe next year both Hall of Fame shows will shift to ESPN
Classic Sports.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's treatment of baseball, in another way, is part of a
dispute that must culminate soon: the shift of ESPN's three Sunday
night baseball games in September to ESPN2 when ESPN televises the
NFL. The conflict never existed when ESPN aired only the second
half of the Sunday night cable package. But when TNT would not pay
outlandishly to keep its half, ESPN bought it all.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has rejected ESPN's settlement entreaties, which
included putting some regular-season games on ESPN2 and trying to
place the September games on the local stations of the teams
playing. It has not offered to push cable systems that don't carry
ESPN2 to add it on a temporary basis.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball wants nothing less than to keep the games of Sept. 6,
13 and 20 on ESPN, with its 74 million subscribers, and off ESPN2,
with its 57 million.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball insists that staying on ESPN is contractually
guaranteed. ESPN has countered that it has the contractual option
to make the shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Games on ESPN2 are a non-starter for us,'' said Paul Beeston,
the president of Major League Baseball, who would not say what
resolution would be satisfactory short of the status quo. ``We're
discussing it internally. It has to be resolved. It has an
end-time. We hope it's sooner than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's Flare-Up
</P>
<P>
   The hearing on Mike Tyson's application for a boxing license in
New Jersey on Wednesday was fascinating viewing. There was silly
and funny stuff from Chuck Wepner and Bobby Czyz, plus incongruous
allusions to Tyson as Christ-like. But the highlight _ Tyson
seething and cursing once _ was not a surprise, though not because
a flare-up from him, at any time, is expected.
</P>
<P>
   Put yourself in his seat. Imagine you are being deposed before a
nationwide audience on CNN about a car accident by a tireless
lawyer. After an hour, your nerves might fray. You might cuss. If
there are legal grounds to deny Tyson a license, fine. But to judge
a fighter who engaged us with his fury on a televised profanity is
wrong. It's just a word. Ask George Carlin about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
