<HEADLINE>
KWAN STANDS OUT ON A POOR NIGHT OF SKATING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ It was the end of July and she was displaying
a bikini tan line, but Michelle Kwan still managed two and a half
minutes of elegance that brought a moment of perfection to an
otherwise clumsy night of figure skating at the Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   Performing for the last time a short program that was judged as
the greatest for any woman ever at the national championships last
January, Kwan skated exquisitely again Thursday night and received
one perfect mark of 6 for presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she needed to be flawless. Simply staying on her feet
would have also put Kwan in first place on a night when only two of
the eight skaters managed clean routines. Of course, simple
competence has never been sufficient for Kwan, the two-time world
champion and Olympic silver medalist.
</P>
<P>
   She has performed this routine to two Rachmaninov piano pieces
nine times this season, and not once has Kwan made a mistake in a
program that is technically challenging, mesmerizing in its
dramatic buildup and sweeping with its changes of speed and mood.
But this is the end of the season, and by the fall, she will need
new costumes, new music, new routines to keep her performances from
becoming overly familiar and predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should keep this program until I make a mistake,'' Kwan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Carroll, who coaches the 18-year-old Kwan in Lake
Arrowhead, Calif., said: ``I'm kind of sad to give it up. It's
special, a signature piece for Michelle. There is a very special
feeling it impacts on the audience and judges. It will be difficult
to do something equally as good, but it is our job to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Butyrskaya of Russia finished second Thursday night
despite an awkward short program that left her with her hands down
on her triple-lutz-double-loop combination. A more revelatory
performance came from the third-place finisher, Viktoriya Volchkova
of Russia, who was third at the 1998 world junior championships and
who celebrated her 16th birthday Thursday with a performance of
light wholesomeness.
</P>
<P>
   The short program counted for one-third of the scoring.
Saturday's long program will count for two-thirds. But Kwan will
need some unforeseen collapse not to defeat this depleted field.
Only Tara Lipinski, the Olympic champion, can challenge Kwan, and
she has decided to turn professional at the doddering old age of
15.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Kwan is looking toward the 2002 Winter Games in Salt
Lake City and only injury or her own lack of interest would prevent
her from dominating women's Olympic-style skating in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
   The audience of 5,581 at Nassau Coliseum cheered her loudly and
adoringly, extending their applause during her graceful spiral
maneuver, and showering the ice with flowers and stuffed animals.
</P>
<P>
   During warm-ups, Kwan fell on her lutz and then landed the jump
tentatively during her routine, but she quickly gathered herself
and skated confidently and joyously through the remainder of the
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started off, I knew I was going to do it,'' Kwan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe and imagine yourself performing, it's already
done in your head before you step on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   At the national championship last January, she received perfect
scores of 6 from seven of the nine judges for presentation in the
short program. Thursday night, the seven judges gave her one 6 and
a bouquet of 5.9's for her farewell performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best part of my program was the footwork,'' Kwan said.
``That's what I'll miss most. In this program, I was dramatic,
soft, I could be all emotions at the same time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
