<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOLLE CRASHES PARTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sandon Stolle expected to spend a quiet, relaxing week in Los
Angeles, watching the Mercedes-Benz Cup. Instead, he's playing in
today's quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian was ousted from the qualifying rounds, losing a
tough third-set tiebreaker to Mexico's Alejandro Hernandez. But
when fourth-seeded Thomas Enqvist withdrew with an injury Monday
night, Stolle's name topped the list of possible subs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came over here (to Los Angeles Tennis Center) to do a
cocktail party for Mercedes, and they told me, `You're going to
play tonight.' I had to run back to the hotel and grab my gear,''
Stolle said.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to defeat Taylor Dent of Newport Beach on Monday
then advanced to the quarterfinals with Thursday's victory over
fellow Aussie Andrew Ilie.
</P>
<P>
   He had extra incentive to win after his father, former tennis
great Fred Stolle, told him the night before to win one for
countryman and hall-of-famer Rod Laver, who is recovering from a
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tough thing when someone tells you,'' Stolle said.
``It's like an extra incentive. I really wanted to do it. Now that
I've won, I can say I won it for Rod.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory also boosted Stolle's confidence, which suffered as
he struggled in the past couple months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught a break this week and got into the tournament,'' he
said. ``Now I've won a few matches. I couldn't be happier. Whatever
happens, it's been a great week for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Healthy crowds: A strong field and heavy advance sales have the
tournament on pace to surpass last year's attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Through Wednesday's matches, the event had drawn 35,647,
including sellouts for the Monday and Tuesday evening sessions,
tournament officials said. With four days and seven sessions to go
(Thursday's figures were available at press time), the tournament
appears a safe beat to beat last year's total attendance of 70,000.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament's initial lineup _ used for early marketing _ was
possibly the best this decade, and it boosted advance sales. That
was before Greg Rusedski withdrew and before Pete Sampras and
Enqvist pulled out at the last minute with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But Andre Agassi, Patrick Rafter, Goran Ivanisevic and Tim
Henman provided sufficient star power, and the tournament has had
healthy walk-up sales. Of that group, only Ivanisevic has been
ousted.
</P>
<P>
   Healthy Sampras: Wimbledon champion Sampras is practicing again.
His ``injury'' turned out to be a wart on the bottom of his right
foot. Sampras had it surgically removed July 15, and the lingering
soreness prompted him to withdraw only three days before the
tournament opened.
</P>
<P>
   He expects to play next week at the du Maurier Open in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Fade to black: Wednesday's late doubles match _ pitting
Camarillo twins Bob and Mike Bryan against John Lafnie De Jager and
Robbie Koenig _ was interrupted for 15 minutes when the stadium
lights mysteriously went out with the Bryans trailing 1-6, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Koenig and De Jager did their best to keep the crowd from
leaving, putting on an impromptu dance show and boogeying to
``Disco Inferno'' as officials worked to fix the problem. They went
on to beat the Bryans 6-1, 4-6, 6-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
