<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAFTER PLEASED WITH QUARTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Patrick Rafter is ready to script his own verse to
add to the classic ditty, ``I Love L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   After dispatching his second-round opponent Thursday to advance
to the Mercedes-Benz Cup quarterfinals, the Australian enthused
about his own game and about the host city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it. We all love it,'' the No.1 seed said of the
tournament, following his 6-3, 5-7, 6-1 victory over Czech Martin
Damm.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. is just a lot of fun to be in for the week we're here.
It's a really popular spot on the tour.... And they spoil us
rotten,'' Rafter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They give you all these nice gifts. They give you these CDs
and this shampoo in your room.''
</P>
<P>
   Er, shampoo? Isn't that, well, standard?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice shampoo,'' clarified Rafter, wearing his long
tresses up in a Pebbles Flintstone ponytail. ``And when I got to
the hotel, they had a robe for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Life is apparently good on the ATP Tour. And it's not going too
badly on the court either for the world's fifth-ranked player.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, preparing to defend his U.S. Open title, advanced to the
quarterfinals at Los Angeles Tennis Center for the second time. He
takes on former UCLA standout Justin Gimelstob in the featured
match this evening.
</P>
<P>
   Against Damm, Rafter looked like he was set to cruise after the
6-3 win in the first set. But Damm, leading 6-5 in the second,
broke Rafter's serve for the first time to take the set. Rafter
lost a key point in the deciding game when he lobbed too deep.
</P>
<P>
   He wouldn't make the same mistake twice. Rafter broke Damm's
serve on the first game of the third set, denying Damm a single
point and clinching on a deep lob that stayed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very happy with the performance,'' Rafter said. ``It's
the best I've played in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter is also happy with the state of his left knee, which had
bothered him throughout much of the year. He's been dealing with an
undiagnosed soreness in the knee for several years and it was
particularly troublesome during the clay- court season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite annoying, actually,'' he said. ``Today it felt
great.''
</P>
<P>
   The quarterfinals field was completed Thursday: Fifth-seed Andre
Agassi advanced with a 6-4, 6-4 victory over Jan-Michael Gambill of
Spokane, Wash.; Gimelstob advanced when Boca Raton's Vince Spadea,
the eighth seed, retired while trailing 6-3, 6-0, and Australian
Sandon Stolle advanced with a 6-3, 7-6 (8-6) win over countryman
Andrew Ilie.
</P>
<P>
   In doubles, Wayne Ferreira and Marcos Ondruska of South Africa
upended the second-seeded team of Damm and Tucson's Jim Grabb 7-6
(6-2), 6-3. In the late match, the third-seeded pair of Rafter and
Stolle were scheduled to take on South Africa's Grant Stafford and
Kevin Ullyet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
