<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS CALL UP GLAUS, ACQUIRE O'BRIEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- While the ``big trade has yet to come, the Angels
made a couple moves Thursday that changed the look of their roster.
</P>
<P>
   They called up third baseman Troy Glaus from triple-A Vancouver
and made a trade with the White Sox for catcher Charlie O'Brien.
Glaus joined the team Thursday but did not start. He'll start
tonight against the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, acquired for single-A pitchers Jason Stockstill and
Brian Tokarse, is currently on the disabled list with a broken
right thumb. He has not yet joined the team and is eligible to be
activated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion of Glaus, who hit 35 home runs between double-A
Midland and triple-A Vancouver this season, means less playing time
for both Dave Hollins and Cecil Fielder. On occassion, Glaus will
start at third in place of Hollins, and there will be times Hollins
moves to first base, putting Fielder on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said this is the time to bring him up, Angels
manager Terry Collins said. ``If you're going to bring him up,
bring him up now.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he talked to Hollins and Fielder about how Glaus'
presence affects them, and Fielder responded by saying he'll do
anything to help the team. Hollins wasn't exactly thrilled, and to
make matters worse, he made an error and struck out in the first
inning Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he also spoke with catchers Phil Nevin and Matt
Walbeck about the trade for O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect what they've done for the team, Collins said. ``They
need an explanation. Some people don't care (to give an
explanation). But Billy (Bavasi, general manager) and I didn't
think that was the thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're probably all upset with me, but that comes with the
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus, the Angels' first-round pick (third overall) in last
year's draft, was hitting .306 with 16 homers and 42 RBIs in 59
games for Vancouver when called up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect it, he said. ``I didn't know what was going to
happen. Obviously, I'm pleased it did happen. ... I can't predict
the future but I'd like to be here and stay here. I'll do whatever
I can in any situation they put me in.
</P>
<P>
   In order to make room on the roster for Glaus, the Angels
optioned pitcher Jarrod Washburn to Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   In O'Brien, the Angels have a catcher they believe will help
them primarily defensively. The Angels have been happy with Nevin's
progress in his first full major league season as a catcher, but
O'Brien's experience should help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys (Walbeck and Nevin) have done a tremendous job,
Collins said. ``We got those guys to fill certain roles and they've
had to play outside those roles (because of Todd Greene's injury).
I think Phil Nevin is going to be an outstanding catcher. But at
this particular time of year veteran help makes us better.
</P>
<P>
   Said Nevin: ``I'd be lying if I said I wasn't mad or (ticked)
off. But some guys never get the opportunity to win a ring. If this
helps us out and it means fewer opportunities but I'm wearing a
World Series ring, I won't complain.
</P>
<P>
   With the Angels sending Washburn to the minors, Allen Watson
gets a spot in the rotation again, and he'll start Saturday against
Pedro Martinez and the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is (starting) is where we can get the most out
of Allen Watson, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   That is, as long as he's still an Angel. His name has come up in
trade talks and it was conspicuously missing from the roster in the
pregame notes Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Randy Velarde went 2-for-5, including a double,
RBI and a stolen base in his second rehab game for triple-A
Vancouver Thursday. ... Ken Hill (elbow) threw off the mound for 15
minutes Thursday and reported no problems. ... Todd Greene will
start in left field for Vancouver tonight. He's ready to play for
the Angels now, but they don't have a spot for him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The SAN GABRIEL VALLEY TRIBUNE, WEST COVINA,
CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
