</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-TRESTMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS  RIGHT TO PUT TRUST IN TRESTMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   His mind is on one track. Football, football, football. He
thinks about it day and night.
</P>
<P>
   Marc, when's the last time you shaved? With a self-conscious
smile, he scrubs a hand over his angular face. ``Two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   We are walking through the woods, along a hilly nature trail
between the practice fields where he lives, and a campus dorm where
he sleeps. No time to sit and chat. There's a coaches meeting.
Players meeting. Another practice. Football, football, football.
</P>
<P>
   We are in the shadows of the pines, walking at his pace. Making
small talk, I ask him what he did with his 49ers stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Trestman, the Cardinals new offensive coordinator, says,
``We're still running most of it'' never breaking stride.
</P>
<P>
   No, Marc. Not the 49ers offense. ``Your'' old stuff. You know,
those 49ers caps and T-shirts and Windbreakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' he says, aware the clock is ticking. The new offense has
to be in place by Tuesday. Three days later, the Cardinals play
their first preseason game in Detroit. He shrugs and keeps walking.
``It's in a closet somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Trestman spent two restive seasons in San Francisco. He coached
Steve Young, the NFL's top-rated quarterback and Jerry Rice, who
led the league in receptions. In 1996, under his direction the
49ers ranked second in the NFL in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   But the 49ers twice lost to the Packers in the playoffs.
Trestman took much of the heat.
</P>
<P>
   He spent his second season with Bill Walsh looking over his
shoulder as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not an easy situation,'' Trestman says.
</P>
<P>
   An understatement. Everyone in the Bay area has an opinion about
the 49ers offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone,'' Trestman says, ``is an offensive coordinator.''
</P>
<P>
   One local sports columnist went on a radio show and offered free
advice about what plays the offense should call inside the
opponents' 20-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was listening to the radio,'' said George Seifert, then the
head coach, ``and this fellow said we had to throw the ball into
the end zone. What happened was that Eddie (DeBartolo) heard the
program, Eddie our owner. And so Eddie called Carmen (Policy, 49ers
president) and Carmen called me in to tell me that Eddie said I
should tell Bill (Walsh, administrative assistant) that during the
game he should write a note telling Trestman to throw the ball into
the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The day the 49ers announced Seifert's ``resignation,''
management was asked at a news conference whether Trestman would
remain on the staff. The microphone was passed around like a track
baton until DeBartolo finally seized it and said, ``He's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Trestman was in Mobile, Ala., at the Senior Bowl.
The team didn't bother to fire him face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was coming,'' Trestman says, no trace of bitterness
in his voice. That was then. His 49ers stuff is in a closet now.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cardinals play the Lions, they will unveil their new
offense. The so-called ``West Coast'' attack fits the team's time
zone and its personnel. Last year the Cardinals were predictable,
often unimaginative. In Trestman's hands, the offense should be
neither. Quick-rhythm passes. Play action. The plan is to utilize
all their weapons and spread the ball around.
</P>
<P>
   He was a quiet voice at San Francisco. ``Not much bluster in
him,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   But this thoughtful 42-year-old former investment banker who
knows something about risk and reward finds himself in a different
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the 49ers I didn't express myself in a passionate way
because we had a veteran team. I didn't have to preach concepts to
the players. They already knew what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a new group, his team. Trestman will call the plays,
initially from the sideline. ``The Genius'' won't be handing him
little notes.
</P>
<P>
   He won't say it, but I will. The 49ers loss will prove to be the
Cardinals gain. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
