<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVANS WANTS ASU TO LURE LOCAL STARS 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-EVANS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the past four months, two things have kept Arizona State
basketball Coach Rob Evans from going home, kicking off his shoes
and settling into his favorite chair.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't had time, and he hasn't had a home.
</P>
<P>
   Evans has been living out of a hotel since April, when he left
the University of Mississippi for ASU, assuming control of one of
the biggest reclamation projects in college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Evans had no intention of emulating Utah's Rick Majerus, who
lives in a Salt Lake City hotel and excited the local tourism
industry when he flirted with the ASU job.
</P>
<P>
   Evans and his wife, Carolyn, will move into a home next month,
and soon after, the Sun Devils coach will step out of the whirlwind
of work to enjoy some peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a little bit difficult living out of hotels,'' Evans
said. ``Once we get moved into our home and get adjusted, it's
going to be a little bit easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who replaced interim Coach Don Newman, inherited a
program that he views as a treasure but looked more like a landfill
packed with college basketball's worst garbage: a point-shaving
scandal, player misbehavior, an apathetic public.
</P>
<P>
   Converting that mess into a program that can compete with
Arizona, a perennial power, would be an astounding makeover. That
is Evans' goal, and he has spent the past four months pursuing it.
</P>
<P>
   Any returning players in academic or other trouble were told to
straighten up or find somewhere else to play. Evans and his staff
began recruiting immediately, placing special emphasis on making
contacts with local coaches and identifying local prospects. In
between, Evans made time to help coach the USA Junior World team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob Evans has worked night and day to put his program in place
and headed in the direction wherein we could realize our
objectives, to consistently be in the top three in the Pac-10 and
the top 10 in the NCAA,'' said Kevin White, ASU athletics director.
</P>
<P>
   Evans received help earlier this month, when Wells Fargo agreed
to pay $5 million to become the title sponsor for the arena
formerly known as the University Activity Center. That money will
help fund improvements to a facility that Evans was satisfied with
already.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have everything you need here to have the opportunity to
be successful,'' Evans said. ``You have nice facilities that will
get nicer. You have a nice city, a good league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that is a question mark is that all kids look for
high-profile situations _ TV, the NCAA Tournament, things like
that. We have to do a good job of selling them that we are headed
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans believes a good college program begins at home. You get to
know the coaches and players in your back yard, and you don't let
the good ones get away.
</P>
<P>
   That was one problem during the Bill Frieder area. He never
successfully recruited a local player who made an impact, while
others such as Shadow Mountain's Mike Bibby (Arizona), Tempe Corona
del Sol's Lamont Long (New Mexico) and Moon Valley High's Richard
Jefferson (Arizona) went elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Frieder, the state has more high school talent
now than during most of his tenure. Evans has already received a
commitment from Donnell Knight, a 6-foot-8 forward, who is rated by
most scouting services as one of the top 20 seniors in the country.
He also is recruiting forwards Tommy Smith from North and Tanner
Shell from Mesa Mountain View.
</P>
<P>
   ``I and my staff have been very visible,'' Evans said. ``We hit
the ground running, trying to visit as many of the schools as we
could. We've had a lot of coaches who have told us they appreciate
that we've been coming to their schools and calling them. And you
have to go when people don't have players. Everybody goes when they
have players.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU's difficulties under Frieder, who resigned nearly a year
ago, have had little effect on recruiting so far, Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   Knight would have considered ASU even if Frieder had stayed,
said his father, Donnell Sr., but the program's problems would have
been difficult to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been more concerned if (the Sun Devils) wouldn't
have wiped the slate clean and started over,'' Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   ASU also is recruiting several players outside the state,
including Brian Wethers, a 6-5 swingman from Georgia, and Jason
Burns, a 6-4 guard from Durham (N.C.) Mount Zion Academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the kids know about it (the point-shaving
scandal) until the people recruiting against (ASU) throw it in
their faces,'' said Van Johnson, director of scouting for Game Plan
Sports, a sports consulting and marketing firm.
</P>
<P>
   With the commitment of Knight, Evans has the beginning of a
solid recruiting class. While ASU is high on the list of several
prominent players, Evans admits that means little unless those
players sign with the Sun Devils. Frieder, too, was a finalist for
several high-profile players, including Juwan Howard and Ed
O'Bannon, who went to Michigan and UCLA, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have a real legitimate shot to get that player, or are
you just one of five?'' Evans said. ``You do have to get the
breakthrough players, but you have to put a high priority on making
sure you get the kids in your area who are quality players and
quality people.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans has a reputation of running a strict program. At
Mississippi, his players were required to drop by his office daily,
and if they didn't fulfill their obligations, they joined his
``Five at Five Club,'' running five miles at 5 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Part of his plan to rebuild ASU's program is not only to win,
but to do it with players who won't embarrass the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have a responsibility to these guys that they
not only become good basketball players, but good citizens,'' Evans
said. ``That's the charge that I have, and I'm going to be
unbending on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans is in a honeymoon period now, and with a thin talent base
returning, ASU figures to struggle for at least a season or two.
But fans are more likely to stick with the program if they believe
the players are good citizens, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I won't support something if I don't feel like they are
good folks,'' he said. ``I always tell the players, if you want
people to come see you play, you have to carry yourself a certain
way.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
