<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-KNIGHT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT INJURES SHOULDER, WILL NOT PLAY IN SCRIMMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF _ Cardinals starting cornerback Tommy Knight thought
he was over the injury problems of his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   Then he suffered a potentially serious shoulder injury in
Thursday's morning practice, the latest blow to an already thin
secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how bad it is,'' Coach Vince Tobin said. ``He
will (miss) more than two or three days.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight will miss Saturday's scrimmage at Walkup Skydome and
undergo a magnetic resonance imaging on his left shoulder Monday in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely frustrating,'' said Knight, who was slowed by
shoulder and knee injuries his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   Knight's backup, J.J. McCleskey, has been starting at strong
safety because Tommy Bennett suffered a hamstring and hip flexor
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to decide whether to move (McCleskey) to corner or
leave him at safety,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   McCleskey said he has no preference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care where I play,'' McCleskey said. ``I just want to
make sure we have the four best (defensive backs) out there and
that we win some games.''
</P>
<P>
   Also ailing is No. 3 cornerback Ty Howard, who is slowed by
arthritis in his left knee. That left Dell McGee, who missed all of
last season with a shoulder injury, as the starting right
cornerback in Thursday afternoon's practice.
</P>
<P>
   If McCleskey is moved back to corner, the starting strong safety
would be second-year pro Kenny Harris or rookie Corey Chavous, a
second-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Pat Tillman, a seventh-round draft pick from Arizona
State, also could be moved there. He is playing free safety. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
