</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARTERS ON LINE HUNGRY  
 ASU DEFENSIVE COACH TOUTS TALENT, DEPTH 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-DEFENSIVE LINE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If drinking milkshakes at 3 a.m. makes Quincy Yancy a better
player, well, bring 'em on.
</P>
<P>
   With Yancy the likely starter at strong-side defense end this
season, the 6-foot-8 Arizona State sophomore hit the weight room _
and the kitchen _ often. He's up to 255 pounds, 10 more than last
season, thanks, in part, to some strange late-night eating
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milk at 2 a.m., milkshakes at 3,'' he said. ``I'd eat a
minimum of four times a day. It gets expensive, but if that's what
you have to do . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Although defensive coordinator Phil Snow says the line may have
some of the best talent and depth on the team, he also knows it may
take half the season to surface.
</P>
<P>
   Only senior left tackle Albrey Battle is assured a starting job.
Battle, who posted 44 total tackles and three sacks last season,
will miss his running mate, Jeremy Staat, who has moved on to the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The top returning player for the other spot is junior Ryan
Reilly, who the coaches agree probably has made more strides than
anyone in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be a lot like (former Sun Devil) Shawn Swayda by
the end of his career,'' Snow said. ``He really understands the
game. He plays blockers well. He's strong, and he's getting better
at rushing the passer.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's biggest challenge will come from Junior Ioane, a
transfer from Snow College in Utah who recorded 11 sacks last
season. Ioane, along with defensive end Erik Flowers, a transfer
from Trinity Valley Community College in Texas, reported to the
team this week. Both have been surrounded by their fair share of
hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fairness to them, the Derrick Rodgers of the world are far
and few between,'' Snow said. ``We know both guys are athletic, but
I don't think we can expect too much too soon. I think by
midseason, both will be good football players for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Both played last year under coaches who were in Division I
programs the previous season and may improve quicker that most
junior college transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers is expected to contend at weak-side end.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short time he's been here, he's already showed his
skills on the field,'' Yancy said. ``He's ready to go and is in
solid shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Ford also will try to win the job at Camp Tontozona. He
has been in the program for four years but has played sporadically,
never quite showing the consistency the coaches want.
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing player in the end mix is redshirt freshman
Levi Jones, a walk-on from Eloy who weighs 270 and impressed the
staff last season.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Malchi Crawford won't be back because his petition
for an extra season of eligibility because of injuries was denied
by the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every season there's been a different set of faces, and every
season those faces stepped up and did their jobs,'' Yancy said.
``Last year, people thought we wouldn't be as good, but people
stepped up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can do it this year, too.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
