A1679 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     07-31 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTH IS, DODGERS DEAL WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ You couldn't make this up, not even on eve of the
major-league trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Before the sixth inning of Thursday's 3-1 victory over
Philadelphia at Veterans Stadium, Dodgers general manager Tom
Lasorda left his box and walked into the dugout. An inning later,
second baseman Wilton Guerrero left the game.
</P>
<P>
   Within 10 minutes, there were wire reports that Guerrero had
been traded to the Montreal Expos for left-hander Carlos Perez and
shortstop Mark Grudzielanek as part of a three-way deal that would
bring Seattle's Randy Johnson to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Only problem. There was no trade.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda went to the dugout to use the bathroom. Guerrero left
the game with a tender left leg. But with the zany climate of
tonight's trading deadline, everything has gotten blurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does this stuff get started?'' said Lasorda, who did speak
to the Expos on Thursday about Perez. ``There is no trade. We never
talked about Grudzielanek or Guerrero.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lasorda is trying to put Antonio Osuna into a deal for
Perez, and the Expos don't want him.
</P>
<P>
   Expos officials would not confirm the three-way deal, saying
only the team that loses out on Johnson would go after Perez.
</P>
<P>
   The night was strange enough with the team heading to New York
to face former Dodgers Mike Piazza and Hideo Nomo in a four-game
weekend series.
</P>
<P>
   And after playing horribly Wednesday night, the Dodgers (56-52)
came back with a solid defensive game and moved into a tie with
Philadelphia in the National League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   But Raul Mondesi, who was 4 for 9 in the first two games of the
series, left Thursday's game after straining his lower back.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, who struck out each of his two at-bats, will be
re-evaluated before tonight's game. But he is not expected to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good right now,'' said Mondesi, who was taken to New
York by limousine instead of the team bus. ``They say it's day to
day, but we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing that appeared status quo was the
performance of Chan Ho Park, who limited the Phillies to two hits
and one run in eight innings to win his 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Shaw pitched a perfect ninth for his 31st save overall and
eighth as a Dodger.
</P>
<P>
   Park (10-5) has five victories and two no-decisions in his past
seven starts. He has a 1.10 ERA during that span.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was his best outing of the year,'' manager Glenn Hoffman
said. ``He has been great for the last six weeks. With all that's
going on, we really need him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scored twice in the second inning. Matt Beech (3-7)
struck out 10 but also walked five and threw a wild pitch that
enabled Charles Johnson to score the Dodgers' first run.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers added an insurance run in the sixth, when Gary
Sheffield singled and Eric Karros doubled him home.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Park cruised through the Phillies' order. His only
real problem came in the fourth, when Doug Glanville and Gregg
Jefferies opened with singles.
</P>
<P>
   Trenidad Hubbard, who took over for Mondesi in center, fielded
Jefferies hit and threw to third, enabling Jefferies to take
second.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Rolen was hit by a pitch to load the bases and Rico Brogna
hit a drive to the gap in right-center that could have been
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But Hubbard ran it down for the out. He threw back to the
infield and could have started a double play, but Guerrero held the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Karros screamed at Guerrero, but all was forgotten when Kevin
Jordan grounded into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero's mental lapses on the field have become more glaring
recently. Wednesday night, he tried to score standing up after
being faked by Phillies catcher Bobby Estalella.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero's older brother, Vladimir, plays for the Expos. But
Montreal manager Felipe Alou is not a Wilton Guerrero fan.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna is earning $450,000 this season but will make $1.05 next
season. The cost-conscious Expos already have locked in closer
Ugueth Urbina to a three-year, $15 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos want Double-A center fielder Peter Bergeron, who is
batting .316 for San Antonio and is considered a top prospect. He
is from Massachusetts, but the Expos also like his French last
name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
