r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-DIAMONDBACKS     07-31 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-DIAMONDBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAAL `V' FOR VICTORY  
 PITCHER BLANKS CUBS WITH COMPLETE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The way Omar Daal has performed since the Diamondbacks placed
him in the rotation, it's almost a wonder other clubs didn't do the
same with the young Venezuelan left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   At just 26, Daal, who is pictured in the club's media guide with
a disallowed goatee, is on his way to cementing himself quite a
future with the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best pitcher on the staff,'' Brian Anderson said.
``No doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Daal delivered a masterful complete game shutout victory, the
first in the brief franchise history, as the Diamondbacks beat the
Chicago Cubs, 4-0, Thursday afternoon in front of a near sellout
crowd at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Jorge Fabregas, who called a brilliant game behind the
plate, received high praise from Manager Buck Showalter and Daal,
who said Fabregas played a big role in the victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was arguably the best single-game performance by a
Diamondbacks pitcher this season. Daal (5-5, 2.84 ERA) manhandled
the heart of the Cubs' batting order, getting Mark Grace, Sammy
Sosa and Glenallen Hill to combine for two singles in 12 plate
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daal was the whole game,'' Chicago Manager Jim Riggleman said.
``He was outstanding. We didn't get him. Recently, he's been as
sharp as anyone on their staff. Our advance reports indicated that,
and they weren't wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The three dangerous hitters in the middle of the Cubs' lineup
combined to strike out five times, quite an achievement considering
Daal struck out seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole key is to get those guys with no one on base,'' Daal
said. ``That way you get them to swing at your pitches, not the
other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Daal faced the minimum three batters in an inning six times,
including in the ninth when he went out having already thrown 114
pitches. But Daal got Sosa, Hill and Kevin Orie in order, the last
two on strikeouts, to close out the Diamondbacks' 39th victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks must win 24 of their remaining 55 games in
order to avoid losing 100 games. With Daal scheduled to start
another 11 times, the club's chances of winning the necessary 63
games suddenly don't seem so far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, he can flat-out pitch,'' fellow starter Willie
Blair said. ``He's fun to watch because he knows what he's doing.
He watches the game and studies it. Since he's been in the
rotation, he's been better than anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Daal did the little things so well on this day. He fielded his
position looking an awful lot like Greg Maddux, a multiple Gold
Glove winner who is generally considered the best fielding pitcher
in the game today.
</P>
<P>
   With Sosa on second in the second inning, Daal caught a drive up
the middle and got Sosa into a rundown between second and third
that was basically a textbook example. He also picked off Lance
Johnson off first base later.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Omar and some of our pitchers and some of the
things they do,'' Showalter said. ``They hold runners, play their
position, throw strikes and work quickly. If you do those four
things, you don't always have to have a 95 mile-per-hour
fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   Daal got all the offensive support he wound up needing in the
second inning when Fabregas and Danny Klassen, who entered the game
a combined 0 for 29, had back-to-back two-out RBI hits.
</P>
<P>
   Devon White, who may have played his last home game as a
Diamondback, added a solo home run and an RBI single to close out
Arizona's scoring. White has been the club's de facto cleanup
hitter since injuries took out Travis Lee and Matt Williams. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
