r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-BRICKYAR-D-QUALIF     07-31 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRICKYAR-D-QUALIFYING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVAN WEATHERS RAIN, TAKES BRICKYARD POLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ This is going to hurt, Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   It never got higher than about 65 degrees Thursday at
Indianapolis Motor Speedway, nippy enough to send some shivering
race fans and unprepared media scrambling to souvenir stands for
unplanned purchases of overpriced sweat shirts.
</P>
<P>
   But the chilly day, which included a near four-hour rain delay,
helped Ernie Irvan grab the Brickyard 400 pole position with a
record-scorching lap clocked at 179.394 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan, who broke the former mark (177.736 mph) he set a year
ago, was the first driver to qualify after the 2.5-mile oval
finally dried.
</P>
<P>
   He set a standard none could equal. But some gave it a valiant
try, including NASCAR Winston Cup Series points leader Jeff Gordon,
the 47th of 51 drivers to make an attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon could only muster a lap of 178.324 mph from his Rick
Hendrick-owned Chevrolet Monte Carlo. That put stock-car racing's
poster boy on the inside of the second row. Dale Jarrett (178.596
mph) will start alongside Irvan on the front row.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan had to wait longer than anyone for the final results,
first weathering a lengthy delay, then having to wait in the wings
for another 90 minutes while the remainder of the field qualified.
</P>
<P>
   Was it worth it?
</P>
<P>
   Uh, does it rain in Indianapolis in the summertime?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how I could have gotten a better lap,'' said
Irvan, who has no top-five finishes, one pole position and is No.
16 in the driver's standings in his first season driving the
Skittles Pontiac. ``We did everything we could do. It handled as
good as it has since we've been here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to the motorhome (after qualifying) and just sat there
listening to the radio and biting our fingernails. We tried to
figure out who was going to beat us and who wasn't going to beat
us. Obviously, there were some heavy hitters still out there. The
one we were so nervous about was (Gordon).
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we've got to figure out a way to win this race.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvan was one of four Pontiac drivers to crack the top 10
starting positions, equaling the Chevy contingent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an incredible lap Ernie put up there, especially
being the first car out,'' Jarrett said. ``He gets around here
good, and he'll be a guy to contend with here on Saturday. But
we've got a good race car, too. I think we've proved the last three
years we know how to get around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett won two years ago and finished third in 1995 and last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon also knows one of the shortcuts to the winner's circle,
having won in 1994 and finishing fourth last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took our best shot at the pole,'' Gordon said. ``The car
was on the edge, and I didn't see any point in pushing it harder
and taking a chance on wrecking.''
</P>
<P>
   Notable absentees among the top 25 qualifiers were defending
champion Ricky Rudd (27th), Dale Earnhardt (28th) and Jeff Burton
(34th).
</P>
<P>
   Another qualifying session is scheduled today, which will
determine the 43 starters.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan admitted he was a likely beneficiary of the weather
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, when the racetrack is real green and all the
rubber is washed off, is when it sticks best,'' Irvan said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
