</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEWAY-SHOOTERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST FREEWAY SHOOTING MAY BE HAVE BEEN RANDOM ACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ALEX ROTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the latest in a rash of recent Southern
California freeway shootings, a man driving to work on the Golden
State Freeway near Griffith Park was wounded in what police suspect
was a random attack.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say they see no pattern to the four shootings in
the past two weeks, which in itself is troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no method to this madness,'' said Detective Bob Lopez
of the Los Angeles Police Department's Northeast Division.
</P>
<P>
   The latest shooting victim, 21-year-old Raul Corona, was driving
to work at 5:23 a.m. Thursday when gunshots from another car hit
him in the torso and shoulder, police said. The Los Angeles man was
listed in critical condition Thursday at Los Angeles County/USC
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if this is just a road-rage incident or who
knows,'' Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the shots were fired from a green Honda Civic
carrying three Latinos with shaved heads. Both cars were heading
north near the Colorado Boulevard off-ramp when the shooting
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just said he was driving on the freeway and all of a sudden
shots rang out,'' Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   He said police don't believe Corona is a gang member and aren't
aware of any connection between the victim and his assailants.
Corona works at a sales job in the Glendale-Burbank area, Lopez
said.
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting, Corona struggled to drive off the freeway
but his car crashed into a guardrail, at which point he stumbled
out of the car before calling for help, police said. He was
conscious at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Police interviewed Corona on Thursday, but he was heavily
medicated and difficult to understand, Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   California Highway Patrol Sgt. Ernie Sanchez said investigators
don't see any pattern to the recent shootings.
</P>
<P>
   According to CHP statistics, there were 10 cases last year in
which someone was arrested or convicted for shooting at an occupied
vehicle. That is the average for the past 14 years, from a low of
three such shootings in 1988 to a high of 18 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting comes five days after a man was shot and killed
while changing a tire on the southbound Golden Gate Freeway. Don
Terrell Berry, 29, was shot to death by a gunman who got out of his
truck to fire the shots. Police still have no motive and no
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   On July 16, a 3-year-old boy was shot in the head on the Pomona
Freeway in Monterey Park. His father, Thomas Simental, 23, also was
wounded. On Thursday, police investigating the shooting arrested
five people on various weapons and narcotics violations.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Thursday whether any of them would be charged in
connection with the boy's shooting, said sheriff's Deputy Joan
Raber.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-year-old boy narrowly missed being hit by bullets fired
Wednesday by 20-year-old Jesus Orozco and a 17-year-old boy
shooting at cars from their Garden Grove back yard. The two were
arrested for investigation of illegal discharge of a firearm, said
Garden Grove police Lt. John Woods.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 0121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
