<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SANCTIONS-DEBATE (Washington) _ Congress and the Clinton
administration are rethinking the use of economic sanctions, a
foreign policy tool of choice for decades, as the penalties
increasingly prove ineffective or backfire. But it'll be hard: More
than 75 countries are now under sanctions or the threat of
penalties. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ECON (Mexico City) _ Mexico's banking bailout needs a
bailout, but the opposition party is pulling out all the stops to
embarrass President Zedillo. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-HMO-REACT (Piqua, Ohio) _ For the elderly and disabled
people of this city, Anthem Blue Cross and Blue Shield's Medicare
HMO provided exactly the kind of aggressive, benefit-laden and
prevention-oriented care that Congress envisioned when they decided
to open up the 33-year-old Medicare program to HMOs. But Anthem got
over-extended as it hustled to lock up the Medicare market and
recently announced it was discontinuing its Medicare HMO in 19 Ohio
counties. The anger, dislocation and confusion among its elderly
beneficiaries says a lot about the dangers to come as more and more
managed care companies break into the Medicare market. By Peter T.
Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HOW-LIFE-BEGAN (Undated) _ The idea that life on Earth began
in the furnace-like temperatures of a volcanic environment has
received support from an experiment designed to reconstruct the
chemical events that may have led to the first living cells. By
Nicholas D. Wade.
</P>
<P>
   POWERBALL (Westerville, Ohio) _ On the trail of the winners of
the big jackpot. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-BUFFALOBOB-SMITH (Undated) _ Buffalo Bob Smith, a singing
piano player and chatty radio disk jockey who created Howdy Doody
and then teamed up with the puppet on one of early television's
most enduring children's shows, died Thursday of cancer at age 80.
By Richard Severo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LEFTHANDED-DNA (Undated) _ One of the mysteries of DNA is
why it is always ``lefthanded.'' Now scientists are ready to link
that explanation to the way dust clouds are polarized in the same
direction. By Malcolm Browne.
</P>
<P>
   BRAWLEY-JURY (Poughkeepsie, N.Y.) _ Talking to jurors: What it
was like to be in the middle of the Brawley defamation suit
maelstrom.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HAMPTONS (Undated) _ The Hamptons on Long Island gear up
for the arrival of a battle-scarred Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-TEARDOWNS (Beverly Hills, Calif.) _ The big Tudor house on
the corner wasn't exactly the old Granville place in ``It's a
Wonderful Life,'' and the man who lived there for nearly 50 years
until he died last summer was named James Stewart, not George
Bailey. But 918 N. Roxbury Drive, with its towering trees, wide
lawn and walled English garden, was a landmark on a leafy street
where the neighbors included Lucille Ball, Jack Benny and Ira
Gershwin. Now the house, which was sold in the spring for $5.6
million, is gone, demolished over the last three weeks by its new
owner to make way for an Italian-style villa twice as big, and all
that remains is a hole in the ground. It is just one of the latest
casualties in that affluent Tinseltown tradition, the ``teardown.''
By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS _ Congress dodges the Lewinsky matter, for now.
By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-COSTS (Undated) _ Despite signs that economic growth is
slowing sharply, wages and benefits are climbing a bit faster than
a year ago. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT grpahics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ How low can it go? The stock of
Oxford Health Plans, the troubled managed-care company, was already
down and out, having fallen sharply last year when the company told
investors to expect an enormous loss. But the stock has lost about
half of its value in just the last few weeks. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Bob Jeffrey describes himself as
someone who ``loves challenges.'' He has certainly come to the
right place. Jeffrey is the new president of the flagship New York
office of J. Walter Thompson USA. Jeffrey's mission is formidable:
to help Thompson New York wipe away the tarnish put on its
reputation by almost two years of turnover in accounts and turmoil
in the top executive ranks. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOLISM-DRUG (Undated) _ A drug widely available in Europe
that may reduce the urge to drink is being tested in the United
States, which has 13.7 million alcoholics. Its French maker hopes
to have it on the U.S. market in 2000. Many experts on dependency
say the drug _ acamprosate, which would be sold in the United
States as Campral _ is badly needed. Only two other medications can
treat alcoholism, and both can have unpleasant or potentially
dangerous side effects. But others in the medical community argue
that alcoholics should be treated with counseling alone. By David
J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BAKER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Russell Baker skeptically looks at some
news events.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENTHAL-COLUMN (Undated) _ A.M. Rosenthal comment on the
Lewinsky inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEN-BERKOW-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on
tennis great Rod Laver who has suffered a stroke. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MET-UNICORN (New York) _ The branch of the Metropolitan Museum
known as the Cloisters is, in every sense, one of the high points
of art in New York City. An impressive jumble of Romanesque scraps
and American prewar masonry, and a monument to American
philanthropy, it sits atop a rocky outcrop over the Hudson near the
upper tip of Manhattan. If location is one of the Cloisters'
outstanding attractions, the magnificent trove of medieval art it
houses is another. Burgundian carvings, illuminated manuscripts and
one of the greatest of all early Netherlandish paintings are among
the treasures. But surely the most famous work is the set of
tapestries long known as ``The Hunt of the Unicorn.'' By Holland
Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-SHAKERS (Undated) _ The peninsula encompassing the
downtown area of Portland, Maine., is a pleasantly compact place,
with neighborhoods that invite strolling and a harbor full of
islands reached by a ferry ride that can feel like a vacation in
itself. The chance to visit such a manageable maritime city and do
a little exploring along the coast nearby lured my wife, Margaret,
and me on a recent weekend. But we also went out of curiosity about
a living link to an unusual chapter in American religious history.
For more than two centuries, a Shaker community has made its home
on a farmstead less than an hour's drive away from Portland, and
the six believers living there now are the last remnant of this
sect in the United States. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-OUTDOOR-DANCE (New York) _ A young girl dressed in a
scalloped tunic and kerchief jumps awkwardly on a makeshift outdoor
stage beneath the Queensborough Bridge in the late 1960s. Seven
shambling young avant-gardists spread the 1970s gospel of
fashionably untutored and untheatrical dance performance on a city
sidewalk. Ballroom dancers spin and fly through countless nights in
the parks of New York City in the 1940s and '50s. Charming
photographs from ``Stepping Out: A Century of Dance in New York
City Parks,'' an exhibition at the Central Park Arsenal Building,
suggest that outdoor dance performances have long been with us. But
those performances have changed a great deal, to judge by the
attractions offered by festivals this summer in the city and
beyond. By Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
