<HEADLINE>
RAIN MAKES WAIT TOUGH ON ROOKIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Hometown favorite  &UR; Kenny Irwin Jr. nearly scaled
the Brickyard 400 mountain Thursday, qualifying fourth-fastest at
178.260 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, who leads all rookies in the drivers standings, almost
was too nervous to brave an attempt after sitting through a long
rain delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 20 minutes before I had to go out, I guess I was holding
my breath,'' Irwin said. ``It's such a big deal for me to come to
Indy. It's awesome. It's what you work for your whole career, to
get to a point like this. It's really neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin will start Saturday's race from outside Row 2, one
position ahead of surprising  &UR; Jeff
 &UR; Green.
</P>
<P>
   Green, making only his 10th start of the season, is No. 42 in
the drivers standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to come to a place like this and be this fast,''
Green said. ``It's pretty cool to be able to see the front no
matter where you are.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Hey, cabbie &QL;  &QL; 
 &UR; Dale Earnhardt has a cameo role in the movie ``BASEketball,'' which
premieres today. Earnhardt plays himself and is featured as a
washed-up race car driver now driving a taxicab for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the scene was filmed one week after Earnhardt ended
a long losing streak by winning February's Daytona 500. &QL;  &QL; 
Tickets, please &QL;  &QL; 
Of the 12 International Race of Champions drivers, road racing star
 &UR; Tommy Kendall has the least experience at Indianapolis Motor
Speedway. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
