<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1689 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-MERCURY-AZR &LR;      07-31 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-MERCURY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LA'S WOES POSE TEST FOR MERCURY  
 WOOLRIDGE LIKELY TO COACH SPARKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the second time in five days, the Mercury face
the prospect of ending its losing streak against a team debuting
under a new coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Sparks fired Julie Rousseau on Thursday night,
team President Johnny Buss told the ``Los Angeles Times,'' and is
expected to name Sparks assistant and former Laker Orlando
Woolridge as interim coach for the final third of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix (12-8), trying to snap a four-game losing streak that
includes a 70-68 defeat here eight days ago, will meet the Sparks
(7-13) under the same circumstance it faced in Salt Lake City on
Monday. That night, the Utah Starzz debuted under new Coach Frank
Layden, a former NBA Coach of the Year, and beat the Mercury,
90-80.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I was saying after Utah, what a firing really does is
gets the players' attention because the onus really falls on their
shoulders,'' Mercury assistant coach Kathy Anderson said. ``They
don't have that excuse (for losing) any more. It makes the players
accountable and focused and excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistake we made with Utah was things were easy for us at
the beginning, and we wanted it to be that way the rest of the
game. When Utah woke up, we didn't respond. That's not unique to
the Utah game.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Phoenix led Los Angeles, 43-27, with 17:38 remaining on
July 23 and 6-foot-5 Lisa Leslie, the WNBA's leading rebounder and
third leading scorer, in street clothes because of injury. But the
Mercury played like the trailing team, rushing its offense and
being burned in transition defense by guards Tamecka Dixon and
Penny Toler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't make the adjustment well to how they would play
without Lisa,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie returned Monday in an 83-67 loss at Cleveland, getting in
early foul trouble and finishing with only 12 points in 24 minutes.
She had 13 points and 13 rebounds, her league-high 11th
double-double of the season, in a 77-68 win over expansion
Washington on Wednesday that could not save Rousseau.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks are making their second coaching change in less than
two seasons and the 10-team league's fifth. Rousseau was promoted
from assistant July 16, 1997, when Linda Sharp was fired and was
retained this season on only high school head coaching experience.
Her WNBA record is 17-20.
</P>
<P>
   Woolridge, 38, played 13 years in the NBA, including 1988-90
with the Lakers. His comments after a 75-66 Sparks win at the Great
Western Forum late last season were taken as disparaging by Mercury
Coach Cheryl Miller and used as motivation by Phoenix in a
season-ending 73-68 overtime win that clinched the Western
Conference title.
</P>
<P>
   Despite dropping five of its past six games, the Mercury remains
a half-game ahead of Cleveland and New York (both 12-9) for the top
wild card playoff berth. The Rockers lost Thursday to Charlotte,
79-64. A Cleveland win would have knocked Phoenix, which won its
first three games and six of its first seven, to its lowest playoff
standing of the season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
