<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS IN A `SELLING MODE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Diamondbacks do make a trade before tonight's 9 p.m.
(Arizona time) trading deadline, it most likely will be a
last-minute situation, General Manager  &UR; Joe Garagiola Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot of bobbing and weaving going on today,''
Garagiola said. ``We've been in contact with a lot of people. It's
important (baseball) people know we're still in there and in a
selling mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``But why would somebody make their best offer Thursday when
they have until Friday night?''
</P>
<P>
   Once again Garagiola indicated any deal the Diamondbacks will
make also would have to include a minor league prospect and not be
a simple trade of major league level players. &QL; 
Roster move &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks on Thursday sent starter  &UR; Bob Wolcott, &UR; the
winning pitcher in Tuesday's 7-5 win over the Cubs, back to Tucson
to make room for reliever  &UR; Felix Rodriguez, &UR; who was activated from
the disabled list after missing 31 games with a right hip flexor
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for Walcott's departure is that southpaw  &UR; Brian
Anderson, &UR; who missed his last scheduled start Tuesday with a sore
elbow on his throwing arm, got through his first hard workout
Thursday with no problems and should make his next scheduled start
Sunday in Milwaukee. &QL; 
Williams delayed &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The return to action of third baseman  &UR; Matt Williams, &UR; who's
missed 13 games with a micro-stress fracture of his left foot, has
been pushed back to Monday when the Diamondbacks open a three-game
set in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was expected to rejoin the team in Milwaukee on Sunday
but will play Friday and Saturday nights with the Tucson
Sidewinders and travel on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who worked out with the team Thursday in batting
practice, isn't especially looking forward to his two games in the
minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you just don't have the same adrenaline going,''
Williams said. ``But as long as you know your purpose, it's OK.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Extra bases &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks' reliever  &UR; Alan Embree uses an abnormally small
glove for a pitcher but says he's going to retire it in favor of a
bigger model.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . I'm throwing my split-finger change-up more, and I can
conceal the grip better in a bigger glove.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering into Thursday's series finale against the Cubs,
Diamondbacks reliever
 &UR; Willie Banks had retired 23 of the past 24 men he has faced after
being drilled in a couple appearances earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Andy Benes, &UR; today's starter in Milwaukee, flew to brew town a
day earlier Thursday and missed Thursday's game so he would be
rested and ready. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
