<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CORRUPTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PARTY CHIEF IN BEIJING GETS 16 YEARS IN PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In a resolution of China's highest-profile case of
political prosecution, state media reported on Friday morning that
a Beijing court sentenced Chen Xitong, a former mayor and party
boss of Beijing, to 16 years in prison for corruption and
dereliction of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, 68, is the most senior Chinese leader to be jailed since
the show trials of the Gang of Four, the leftists who were ousted
from power 20 years ago. Earlier reports had accused Chen of
embezzling state funds, taking bribes and abusing power to support
``a corrupt and decadent life.''
</P>
<P>
   In China today, a vast panorama of corruption has grown out of
flourishing businesses controlled by officials with broad influence
and few checks or balances. Even so, Chen's demise is an
eye-opening tale of seemingly invincible power, spectacular excess
and sudden fall.
</P>
<P>
   As the top man in Beijing's city government, and the man with
final say over building permits during a construction boom in the
early 1990s, Chen personally amassed a fund of $24 million, as well
as an extensive collection of private homes where he had a taste
for entertaining young female television presenters, according to
an internal report on his activities that emerged last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he was implicated in a series of far larger financial
schemes that may have totaled as much as $2 billion, although the
sophistication with which officials shield their activities and the
secrecy that guards senior leaders makes an accurate total
impossible to ascertain.
</P>
<P>
   Known for boasting that his power was beyond anyone's reach,
Chen funneled millions of dollars to various acquaintances to start
business ventures. Last year's report said he also gave a
girlfriend and her family a total of nine apartments around
Beijing, at a time when housing was still very tight.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's personal empire only crumbled after a financial scandal
in 1995 implicated one of his closest aides, a deputy mayor named
Wang Baosen, who was soon found on the side of a hill outside
Beijing with a bullet hole in his head. It was officially deemed a
suicide, but secrecy about the exact circumstances of his death
inevitably stirred speculation about its true cause.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's principal mistress was apparently tipped off about Chen's
impending demise by his son and accomplice, and she fled overseas
with an undisclosed amount of money. Another deputy mayor, Zhang
Baifa, said publicly last year that her whereabouts are still
unknown to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's son, Chen Xiaotong, president of a hotel in Beijing, was
sentenced last year to 12 years in prison for taking bribes and
misusing public funds. The senior Chen's personal secretary, Chen
Jian, is serving a 15-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Chen himself was forced to resign in April, 1995. He
has been held under tight security ever since, while party
officials debated his fate in secret.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 0139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
