<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1742 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI &LR;      07-31 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAWED DRUG POLICY LED TO TOUR DE FRANCE DEBACLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Fascinating as is the season-long Mariner
deconstruction, it is, in a larger view, a trifle compared to the
virtual instant collapse of an entire sport.
</P>
<P>
   While professional cycling's premier event, the Tour de France,
is not something that foams the latte of the average slug-hugging
Seattleite, a recent trip to England and its extensive media
coverage of the race was an eye-opener to the uninitiated.
</P>
<P>
   Now that most of the field has been investigated, searched,
arrested, jailed or deported, and the remainder has protested, quit
or is holding its breath in a corner of the Alps, the Tour
qualifies as perhaps the most self-destructive event in modern
sports history.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't kept up, the convulsions began July 17 when a
masseur for a prominent team, Festina, was busted for having
illegal performance-enhancing substances in his car. The guy
subsequently confessed, as did several racers, the team was thrown
out and hell was shaken loose.
</P>
<P>
   Police began multiple investigations, TV crews sifted racers'
garbage, cyclists staged sit-downs and slow-downs, and hysteria
turned the Continent into one giant Jerry Springer show.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most remarkable developments of the scandal is that
racers are being busted almost daily, despite the intense scrutiny
and legal carnage. The first thing learned by most American college
kids is that when a hard knock is heard on the door, rush headlong
to the head to make a watery deposit of any substances that might
be confused with, uh, performance enhancers.
</P>
<P>
   But most cyclists have so long used these goodies, which have
become a big part of many international endurance sports, that they
can't imagine going on without them. The familiarity makes them
oblivious to the most startling image of the controversy from the
outside:
</P>
<P>
   The angry athletes virtually shut down their Super Bowl because
their own rules and rulemakers are attempting to stop them from
continuing to break the law.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shame, no embarrassment. They know they've been
ignoring sports law _ and in some cases criminal law _ but have
been willing to throw away France's biggest athletic event if they
aren't allowed to continue.
</P>
<P>
   However, the departure from most known conventions of civilized
behavior isn't quite as naked as it seems. The heart of the scandal
is not actually a drug, but a natural hormone called erythropoetin,
or EPO, which is viewed by athletes and some doctors as far less
sinister than steroids, speed and other provocative juices of an
earlier generation of athletes.
</P>
<P>
   EPO is produced naturally by the kidneys to promote production
of red blood cells, which are crucial in carrying oxygen throughout
the body. Since 1983, EPO has been produced in labs to fight anemia
for victims of kidney failure and HIV.
</P>
<P>
   In athletes, EPO increases aerobic endurance and helps recovery.
Although there is some medical evidence suggesting abuse leads to
high blood pressure, seizures, diarrhea and nausea, the Tour racers
have so institutionalized its use that they claim to have managed
away the risk.
</P>
<P>
   After his arrest and confession, the Festina team manager said,
``The objective was to maximize the riders' performance under
strict medical control to prevent them from obtaining drugs for
themselves in ways that could seriously affect their health.''
</P>
<P>
   The argument resonated this week in another way, when
International Olympic Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch
called for a reduction in the list of banned substances at the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   This departure from the usual Olympic rhetoric of
test-and-arrest-for-everything is not just an acknowledgment that
the users are so far ahead of the detectives that justice is
improbable. It's also a recognition that naturally occurring
substances such as EPO, over-the-counter nutritional supplements
such as creatine, and ordinary medications such as antihistamines,
may not be harmful in controlled use.
</P>
<P>
   While they may help performances, the natural stuff is generally
undetectable by urine testing. Blood testing can work, but it is an
invasive, occasionally troublesome procedure. Most athletes tend to
be fussy about giving up valuable fluids before or after races.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, stopping doping with the conventional morality
and methods is flat impossible. Something must change, as the Tour
implosion fairly screams.
</P>
<P>
   The growing sentiment is towards acceptance instead of
enforcement. And the likeliest way is the creation of two classes
of international sport _ pure and open.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, competitors in the pure division must submit to
blood, urine and other tests to prove their chemical virginity. The
open competitors can drop the pretenses in exchange for listing
enhancers and subjecting themselves to monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   The logistics would be a mess, but the new deal at least would
have the virtue of honesty, informed choice and public disclosure
that is utterly absent from the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, no mystery prevails as to which division would
get all the media coverage, sponsorship and prize money. But at
least the quibbling over what sport is would end, and we would be
down to arguing price.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 0205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1743 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETHINK-OFFICE-BLDGS-     07-31 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETHINK-OFFICE-BLDGS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEARING DOWN THE WALLS OF TRADITIONAL OFFICES  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 700-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 1 August 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
