<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SEAHAWKS, IMPACT OF ALLEN'S LARGESSE SHOULD BE EVIDENT VS.
DALLAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Friday night's preseason opener provides a first chance
to see what an offseason shaped by Paul Allen's money and Randy
Mueller's moxie has done for the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   There's the new-look offense, with five-time Pro Bowl back Ricky
Watters, signed as a free agent, running behind a line that has
been bolstered by free-agent additions Brian Habib at guard and
Kevin Glover at center.
</P>
<P>
   There also has been a needed infusion of speed at linebacker,
with free agent Darrin Smith stepping into the starting lineup and
draft choices Anthony Simmons and DeShone Myles expected to improve
what were the NFL's worst special teams last season.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller, the vice president of football operations, sold those
players on playing for the Seahawks or selected them in the draft _
using the billionaire-deep pockets of Allen, still in his first
year as owner.
</P>
<P>
   But strong safety Jay Bellamy has another suggestion for
must-see TV when the Seahawks meet the Dallas Cowboys at Texas
Stadium at 6 p.m. PDT.
</P>
<P>
   ``Check the rookies' eyes after the opening kickoff,'' said
Bellamy, who made the club as a rookie free agent in 1994 because
of his special-teams efforts and is now a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be this big,'' he said, forming a circle in front of
his face with the index fingers and thumbs of both hands. ``The
rookies don't know what they're about to experience. They don't
realize how fast this game is played at this level, just the tempo
and explosiveness in a game as compared to practice or the college
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in for a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another reason to watch the opening kickoff, and each
special-teams play that follows on a field where the temperature is
expected to reach 120 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change on a Seahawks team that has been in constant
change since Dennis Erickson became the coach in 1995 is the
emphasis being placed on the kicking game.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Rodriguez, considered the best special-teams coach in the
league, was hired from the Washington Redskins to right the units
that did so much wrong in costing the Seahawks at least four
victories during last year's late-season slide to an 8-8 record.
</P>
<P>
   He's not just coaching the special teams; Rodriguez is teaching
the players how to play special teams.
</P>
<P>
   The speed of running back Ahman Green, a third-round pick, will
be used on kickoff returns. The speed and tackling prowess of
Simmons, the first-round pick, and Myles, a fourth-rounder, will
come into play on punt and kickoff coverage. Wide receiver Joey
Galloway and cornerback Shawn Springs, both starters, will return
punts. Free safety Darryl Williams, a Pro Bowl selection last
season, and linebacker Chad Brown, a Pro Bowl selection the year
before, also will be key players in the kicking game.
</P>
<P>
   Drastic moves were made where drastic change was needed.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Rodriguez isn't expecting a lot just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I want to do is make sure we get 11 guys on
the field for every special-teams play,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   As the circle of reporters standing around Rodriguez laughed, he
responded with an I'm-not-kidding glance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You laugh, but that really is my No. 1 goal,'' Rodriguez said.
``With 80 guys on the sideline, it's chaos. Some guys are only
going to play a short time before they're standing there without
their pads on. So guys who aren't used to going in are going to
have to go in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, it's chaos.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
