<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-MOON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS REFUSE TO BUDGE ON OFFER TO WARREN MOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Warren Moon can threaten to retire, but the veteran
quarterback can't force the Seahawks to budge from their position
on renegotiating his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a report that Moon said he will retire if the Seahawks
do not increase their one-year, $2 million offer, club vice
president Randy Mueller said Thursday it is up to Moon to either
accept the deal or settle on another option _ such as continuing
his holdout or ending his 20-year professional career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be too bad if he retired, but that's always been an
option for him,'' Mueller said. ``Does this change our position at
all? No.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks are holding to their offer that includes a $1.3
million raise from the $550,000 base salary Moon was scheduled to
make, plus a $150,000 roster bonus he already has been paid. The
club also is offering $1.6 million in incentives that Moon and his
agent, Leigh Steinberg, consider laughable because they would be
difficult to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've given it a lot of thought, and if the situation doesn't
change, I'll retire,'' Moon told the Houston Chronicle in a story
published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Moon said he was not even thinking about retiring and
Steinberg said it was ridiculous to consider retirement an option
for Moon, who will be 42 in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, I'd ask for my release, but I don't think they'd give
it to me,'' Moon said in the Chronicle. ``Then, yes, I'll just
retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Mueller said the club will not release Moon, who signed a
two-year contract last year to be the backup to John Friesz but
became the starter when Friesz suffered an injury in the season
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Moon, who has returned to his offseason home in Houston, could
not be reached for comment Thursday and Steinberg was not at his
Newport Beach, Calif., office.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller has not talked with Moon's agents since July 19. The
last time they communicated was early last week, when Mueller and
Steinberg exchanged faxed letters that restated their positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without having talked to Warren, I don't know what I can say
about it,'' Mueller said, just before boarding a bus at the team's
Eastern Washington University training camp in Cheney, the first
leg of the club's trip to Dallas for Friday night's preseason
opener against the Dallas Cowboys. ``I don't know where he's coming
from or what their posturing is on this. I don't know what Warren
is thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon's holdout reached 12 days Thursday. His teammates had a
45-minute walk-through at their training camp before flying to
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him here. I don't want him to retire. I think he's a
real key for us,'' coach Dennis Erickson said. ``But if he decides
to retire we go with either of the Johns (John Friesz or Jon
Kitna), and I'm happy with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon mentioned Wednesday settling for the same two-year deal
that he first raised in interviews with Seattle-area reporters last
week, a deal that would pay him $3.5 million to $4.5 million this
year as part of a $7-8 million package.
</P>
<P>
   But the only proposal the club has is Moon's original request
for a three-year, $15 million deal that includes a $6 million
signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they don't want to give me a two-year deal because
they're afraid I won't play next year,'' Moon said. ``They're
afraid I'll retire after one season and they'll have that portion
of my prorated signing bonus count against the 1999 (salary) cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon considered retiring after last season because of the
uncertainty over who might be coaching the team. But he reiterated
to the Chronicle that he is willing to sign an agreement that he'll
play the second year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
