<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRISTINA-BOOK-EXCERPT-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``CRISTINA!: MY LIFE AS A BLONDE'' -- EXCERPTS FROM CRISTINA
SARALEGUI'S SIZZLING AUTOBIOGRAPHY
</HEADLINE>
  North American English-language print rights. 
 By CRISTINA SARALEGUI  
<TEXT>
<P>
   She is the host of the most-watched TV program in the
world--Cristina Saralegui, the Cuban refugee who worked her way to
the top of the publishing world, then switched to television to
create the ``El Show de Cristina,'' viewed daily by 100 million
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Bilingual, Cristina became well-known to English-speakers when
she began broadcasting her show for CBS in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Her story, told in three 1200-word parts, will inspire anyone to
do more with what they have. Born into wealth and ease, Cristina
lost it all when her family fled to Miami during Castro's
revolution. She defeated racism and poverty with an undaunted will
to work and to believe in her own dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Her mission in this book is to show her readers how to do the
same.
</P>
<P>
   THE SERIES IS ALSO AVAILABLE IN SPANISH, slugged
BC-CRISTINA-SPANISH-BOOK-EXCERPT-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Part 1, Cristina tells of the family's flight to Miami and
how hardships in this country transformed her from a little rich
girl to a compassionate and supremely confidant businesswoman. She
lays down rules of disciplined goal-setting and shows her readers
how to follow them to success.
</P>
<P>
   In Part 2, Cristina recounts the romance of meeting Marcos Avila
of Miami Sound Machine, of how they overcame her family's
resistance to her marrying a rock star 11 years her junior, and
finally of how he led her to become more successful than even she
had dreamed.
</P>
<P>
   In Part 3, Cristina describes her new life in TV, the longs and
grueling pace, the seductions of fame and influence. She also
counters her critics who say the show is too sexy, and tells for
the first time why she chose not to renew her English-language deal
with CBS.
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-CRISTINA-BOOK-EXCERPT-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (To publish one or more parts of this book excerpt, they must be
purchased -- the rate is not prohibitive -- from one of these New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
</P>
<P>
   (--Mexico, Central America, South America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los
Angeles, 310-996-0075; fax, 310-996-0089.
</P>
