<HEADER>
A1989 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRISTINA-BOOK-EXCERPT     07-31 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRISTINA-BOOK-EXCERPT-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``CRISTINA!: MY LIFE AS A BLONDE'' -- EXCERPTS FROM CRISTINA
SARALEGUI'S SIZZLING AUTOBIOGRAPHY
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS.: Spanish translation available 
 North American English-language print rights. 
 By CRISTINA SARALEGUI  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keeping my head above water in the world of television wasn't
easy. First of all I had to shed my old body, face, hair--my entire
appearance--along with everything I had grown used to during the
past 20 years of my life.
</P>
<P>
   I had been a writer and magazine editor; I worked at a desk like
a slave. When I took a break, I wolfed down anything I could find
in the vending machines.
</P>
<P>
   Today, when I look at the videos from the first year of ``El
Show de Cristina,'' I'm horrified. I see myself as ridiculous,
strident. I look like a prize pony at auction, draped in scarves,
chains, bracelets, three-tier earrings, everything dangling and
clanking against the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually we polished my image and paid attention to audience
reaction. I worked really hard to find my own personal style. Now I
keep my hair at shoulder length, and I like my makeup light and
wear simple clothes.
</P>
<P>
   I learned to eat low carbohydrates, low fat and low sugar, and
to eat small quantities of protein every three hours in order to
maintain a stable energy level to function better all day.
</P>
<P>
   The result was that for the first time, I looked great on
television, and again for the first time in my life, I understood
what it was to be an attractive woman, because when I arrived
somewhere, people turned to look at me even if they didn't know who
I was. That had never happened to me before, and I was 41 years
old!
</P>
<P>
   Another factor about my appearance was that I am fair-skinned,
blond and blue-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   When the show first aired, letters poured in from my Hispanic
brothers and sisters all across the United States, in which they
wrote that I was ``too white,'' too ``guera'' (the Mexican word for
blonde) to represent Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Those viewers had to understand that what they were doing to me
was as racist as what Anglos were doing to them. The acceptance
took six months of letters from the public telling me I should wear
more blush!
</P>
<P>
   Once an older woman came up to me and chided, ``Cristina, all
you talk about is sex.''
</P>
<P>
   My response: ``No, senora, I talk about everything! From flying
saucers to breast cancer. You only remember the programs about
sex.''
</P>
<P>
   I air themes on sex because apart from the enormous need for
information on that subject, every time I include a segment on a
sexual topic, the ratings go off the charts, and numbers outweigh
hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of calling a radio station to complain about a program
or writing incensed letters, why not just turn off the set when the
topic comes on? But no--ooo! Just the opposite. More and more sets
are turned on.
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious that many people don't have the least idea what
human sexuality is, and someone must offer them the truth. Their
parents certainly haven't assumed that responsibility, despite the
fact that the duty for the sexual and moral education of our
children rests squarely on us parents.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1992, with ``Cristina'' established as No. 1 in its
category in Spanish-language television, I took a shot at the
coveted crossover into English.
</P>
<P>
   It was simply titled the ``Cristina Show,'' and I was delighted
at the challenge, it goes without saying. But for CBS to hire a
communicator with a Latin accent was nothing short of
revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   At first there were the usual comparisons, and reporters asked
if I was trying to knock off Oprah. ``Are you kidding?'' I'd ask
jokingly. ``Oprah is like a supersonic transport. I'm a fly
requesting permission to land.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept of the program was to feature topics that
demonstrated the pluralism of U.S. society, emphasizing the
immigrant roots shared by all of us, even the oldest North American
families, whose ancestors also emigrated from other countries.
</P>
<P>
   We chose themes that reflected that concept in all its
ramifications. For example, on one program we called ``White Like
Me,'' several plastic surgeons explained the operations people of
different races--Asian, African American or Hispanic--underwent to
alter their features to make them look ``white.''
</P>
<P>
   We discussed prejudice against black peoples. We presented black
Haitians, immigrants into the United States, who complained that
black Americans discriminated against them because of their
nationality and their accent.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 11 weeks, the average ratings augured a nearly
guaranteed success. Some years later, Jonathan Rodgers (president
of the group of CBS stations that gave me the chance to work in
English) explained to us that the program had obtained a higher
average rating than any other beginning program since that time.
</P>
<P>
   But when we began to negotiate, the CBS management offered us a
budget we didn't consider adequate. Just the opposite; the amount
was lower than the current budget of our program in Spanish, when
equivalent formats in English spend two or three times that sum and
more.
</P>
<P>
   So Marcos and I decided not to renew.
</P>
<P>
   What I never understood, though, and what I never will
understand, is how it was reported in the trade publications again
and again that our show had failed and that we were canceled
because of poor ratings.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who may believe that, let me tell you: Ratings in the
United States are public property. If the reporters had verified
the facts, as was their responsibility, they would have realized
that what they were writing was not true.
</P>
<P>
   I had to pay for all that. I'm still paying, in the sense that
every time someone mentions our 1992 venture into the
English-language market, the invariable comment is that we
``failed'' and that we were ``canceled.'' That's still
inconceivable to me.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever told me that a woman looks young until suddenly,
when she approaches the decade between 45 and 55, she runs out of
estrogen and the years suddenly show. Her hands (and her vagina)
begin to dry up, and all you can think about is your little-girl
hands that are gone forever.
</P>
<P>
   Thank God, everything my mother didn't warn me about I found in
a book titled ``Silent Passage'' by Gail Sheehy, which become my
bible. Until I read it, I not only didn't recognize the stage I was
going through in my life but also didn't know what had to do to
survive it and to continue succeeding, without allowing that series
of hurdles to slow down my life.
</P>
<P>
   How do I feel as I approach 50? What am I like in this stage of
my Iife? Vigorous, curious, sensual, sexual, in good physical
condition, flexible and creative.
</P>
<P>
   I define myself as an adult woman who has struggled very hard to
be able to determine the destiny of her own life. I think that one
can achieve everything she sets out to, although not always all at
once. That is the secret.
</P>
<P>
   I completed a cycle of comfort, of working for 22 years for the
company that formed me professionally. I was I able to have my
children, to stay home, to marry twice, to cook for my parents....
</P>
<P>
   I did all these things! I completed those cycles.
</P>
<P>
   We're told we can't have everything in life. That's not true! We
can have it all (or enough), as long as we know how to choose. Life
is nothing more than an endless rosary of choices and lessons, one
after the other.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   Reprinted from CRISTINA! MY LIFE AS A BLONDE by Cristina
Saralegui
</P>
<P>
   Copyright 1998 by Cristina Saralegui enterprises Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Published by arangement with Warnre BOoks, Inc., New York USA
</P>
<P>
   All rights reserved
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
