<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1992 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRBORN-LASER01-COX     07-31 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRBORN-LASER01-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Laser equipped battleships to combat nukes
</P>
<P>
   By Dick Stanley
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ High-flying laser ``battleships'' could be America's
best means of stopping a regional nuclear war before it started,
the chief technical advisor to Secretary of Defense says.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Mark, also a former chancellor for the University of Texas
System, said an early 21st-century fleet of the Boeing 747-400s
armed with high-power lasers that can shoot down nuclear-tipped
missiles could help stop regional nuclear wars and prevent others
from happening.
</P>
<P>
   Mark, who the U.S. Senate confirmed in June as the chief
technical advisor to Defense Secretary William Cohen, revealed the
Airborne Laser strategy while he was in Austin this week. The jet
could become a key part of the Clinton administration's plans to
deal with the spread of nuclear weapons as nations such as India
and Pakistan, which have fought each other in the past, acquire and
test them.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Air Force plans call for the first Airborne Laser, at an
estimated cost of $1.1 billion, to be delivered in 2003, followed
by a publicized shoot-down of a missile over the Pacific Ocean off
the coast of California. If Congress approves, the service hopes to
acquire six more of the planes by 2006. The planes are not intended
to combat intercontinental ballistic missiles, the subject of the
controversial, Reagan-era Star Wars missile defense program. Those
missiles rise into the fringes of space before plunging back to
their targets. The Airborne Laser would only engage
intermediate-range and cruise missiles in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would be similar to the AWACS (Airborne Warning and
Control System radar surveillance planes) and deployable in very
critical situations,'' Mark said. ``AWACS is there to manage the
air battle. The Airborne Laser will be there to handle the missile
threat over a large area.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark said the Airborne Laser, under development for more than 20
years, would be a deterrent to a nuclear war by threatening
destruction of the country that tried to start one. Circling about
200 miles away from, say, a warring Iran and Iraq, the
steel-cutting laser could cripple nuclear-tipped missiles soon
enough in their flights for the warheads to fall back on the
country that launched them.
</P>
<P>
   Mark, 69, who still lives in Austin and commutes to the
Pentagon, was at his old office at UT briefly this week enroute to
California to watch the latest test of the new laser the jets would
carry. He has been on a leave of absence from his UT professorship
in aerospace engineering since May, when President Clinton
nominated him for the defense post, director of Defense Research
and Engineering.
</P>
<P>
   He said he took the defense job to offer his 40 years of
defense-related technology research, in government and
universities, to help combat the spread of nuclear arms, as well as
chemical and biological weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   A former secretary of the Air Force (1979-81) and former deputy
director of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
(1981-84), Mark said he hopes to diminish the need for the Airborne
Laser by helping find new, classified technical means of
discovering a country's nuclear weapon preparations, as the U.S.
did with Iraq, before the warheads are ready for use.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the means would be continued reliance on spy
satellites, the latest generations of which carry radars capable of
seeing through clouds, soil, sand and snow. As director of the
then-secret National Reconnaissance Office in the late 1970s, Mark
presided over some changes to the satellites that are still in use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology is classified but the fact that we're using it
is not,'' Mark said. ``We really want to know what the North
Koreans and the Iranians are doing when they test a rocket capable
of carrying a nuclear weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   Controversial new prohibitions on the export of computers and
other technologies that could be useful for the development of
nuclear, chemical or biological weapons also may be needed, Mark
said, as well as tighter controls over the distribution of
plutonium and other nuclear materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our principal job is to flag the things that ought to be
examined,'' Mark said. ``But this is clearly an issue over which
men of goodwill might differ.'' Mark is convinced, however, of the
Airborne Laser's ability to protect civilian populations and
military assets.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was introduced to the concept, which nuclear
physicist Edward Teller dubbed the ``aerial battleship,'' in 1967
when Mark became a member of the Air Force Scientific Advisory
Board. He has been following its progress ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Low-power lasers are commonly used in hospitals and clinics for
surgery and other medical procedures. The chemical oxygen-iodine
laser the 747s would carry is suitable for industrial applications.
Its concentrated beam, focused with the aid of telescope mirrors,
can cut stainless steel, titanium and other metals and is being
considered for such civilian uses as mining and drilling for oil.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, the laser and its targeting optics are being
developed by the Air Force in cooperation with Boeing, TRW and
Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   An Air Force scenario for the planes calls for their crews to
detect and track missiles in less than two minutes and focus their
lasers on them for the five seconds it would take to disable them.
One problem the Air Force still is working on is gathering
worldwide data on air turbulence, which affects the laser's ability
to focus on a target.
</P>
<P>
   Mark said his job is to use his expertise to tell the defense
secretary what will work and what won't. And one thing he is
convinced will not work, in its present form, is the 1996
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. President Clinton signed the treaty,
which was drawn up by the United Nations, but the Senate has balked
at ratification.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty should be revised, Mark said, to allow the U.S. to
conduct at least one or two underground nuclear tests each year to
ensure the workability of its nuclear arsenal, after completion of
the ongoing drawdown by treaty with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Without such testing, Mark said, America's enemies, such as
Libya's Moammar Kadafi, would know that its remaining nuclear arms
were suspect, since the radioactive components of nuclear weapons
have a limited shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a tragedy for the world,'' Mark said, ``if Kadafi
had (working) nuclear weapons and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-31-98 0022E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
