<HEADER>
A1994 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMIC-CARRINGTON01-CO     07-31 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMIC-CARRINGTON01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Raunchy comic Carrington `bad boy of Nashville'
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HBO wants to talk about a sitcom. Album sales are climbing.
Comedy club gigs have him rolling in the dough.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Carrington can feel it. He's on the verge of something
big.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can feel a rumble,'' says Carrington. ``I just need that one
big thing to push me over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a plan,'' he says with a mischievous smirk. ``I want a
million people to like me and pay me $10 a year for the rest of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so he probably won't get paradise in an installment plan.
But it might not take that much for Carrington to be comedy's next
big thing.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years of touring have built a loyal following for the
28-year-old married father of two boys from Tulsa, Okla. Comedy
club audiences are now shouting requests for their favorite bits of
his raunchy brand of guitar-slingin', good ol' boy humor. Millions
have heard him perform songs during regular spots on radio's
syndicated Bob and Tom Show. He's done segments on A&AMP;E's Evening at
the Improv and NBC's Friday Night Videos. And his new album,
Hangin' With Rodney, has sold almost 20,000 copies in less than two
months _ impressive numbers for any debut comedy album that doesn't
have a huge promotional campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad, since at least half of his best material is strictly
for adults. Jokes about bodily functions, anatomically correct
snowmen, sexually transmitted diseases. That sort of thing. This
ain't your father's Jeff Foxworthy or Jerry Clower album. Think
instead of a raw, countryfied Redd Foxx in a cowboy hat and a Texas
accent.
</P>
<P>
   Carrington does have less raunchy material, but even then it
tends to be hilariously scatological. Such as this bit about his
infrequent churchgoing:
</P>
<P>
   ``The trouble with going to church once a year is you got all
those righteous people who go every day lookin' at you like, `What
are you doing here? Feeling guilty about something? You can't just
make it up in one day!' Get off my case, lady, I'm just here for
the wine and bread, for god sakes. And the preacher, he always
wants to point you out, don't he? (As the preacher) `WE GOT SOME
NEW PEOPLE HERE TODAY WITH US!' We ain't new, mister, we were here
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a little dismayed about the parental advisory sticker on
the front of the CD. The way he figures it, the stuff he talks
about is the way most people think but rarely speak of in mixed
company. You can hear audible gasps on the album at the beginning,
before audience members buy into the concept. He dutifully chides
them: ``Comedy club, chuckle chuckle, y'all. Don't get all bent out
of shape!'' It helps break the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you don't offend people in some shape or form, you
haven't really done your job or your aren't doing it right,''
Carrington said. ``I like a little shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nashville never had an album with a (parental advisory)
sticker on it,'' Carrington says. ``Country music and Nashville are
about family values, but behind the scenes those people are as
regular as I am. My humor is what makes me laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there have been those who have advised Carrington to tone
it down in order to make the big push into TV and widespread
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to clean it up,'' he said. ``I want to do what it
is that I do. If I become known as the bad boy of comedy in
Nashville, well, I'm not sure I want that, but if so, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-30-98 1641E
</P>
