A1996 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOE-ELY01-COX     07-31 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOE-ELY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ely's coming: Texan bringing his spicy blues mix to Kravis
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 25 years on the road, Joe Ely has performed his rich blend of
Tex-Mex country music at plenty of weird gigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played a biker bar in Norway once, inside the Arctic
Circle,'' the 51-year-old native of Amarillo, Texas, remembered.
``By the second song, everyone had their clothes off and were
making love on the floor. The guys in the band were looking at
their instruments and saying, like, `Hey, don't mind us.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me started about weird gigs . . . Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, Joe. Whatever you say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played another show, another biker gig where everyone had a
gun sticking out of the front of their pants. We were out in the
field on a cotton farm in the middle of west Texas, about 300
people. There was this big feud between two rival groups. Sort of
the opposite from the Norway thing. Maybe we should have told them
to just take off their guns and make love, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, cheap stunts won't be necessary to entertain his
audience. All Ely needs is to peel open his song book from more
than a dozen albums and let the menagerie of characters romp
through his gritty landscape. It's a place where gamblers, cowboys,
murderous women and rowdy diners feel nice and comfy. A place where
Christmas lights stay up all year, and desperadoes ride high on the
ridge.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of his latest album, ``Twistin' in the Wind.''
Released in May, the dozen tracks, all written or co-written by
Ely, feature such tales as the waitress who takes no guff from a
band of thirsty cowboys in ``Nacho Mama'' or a heartbroken
Louisiana gravel-pit worker in ``Workin' for the Man.'' Then,
there's the raucous and funny ``If I Could Teach My Chihuahua to
Sing,'' in which a destitute hombre brainstorms about how to make a
little dinero:
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could teach my chihuahua to sing/What a wonderful world
it would be/I could take her to the border/And teach her how to
order/margaritas and fajitas, senoritas would bring.
</P>
<P>
   Such songs have been his style since his solo debut album in
1977. A spicy mix of folk, rock, country and Texas blues has
flavored his tales of busted dreams, romantic woe and more than a
few rough characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always fashioned a song around how it feels, not around a
certain style,'' Ely said Monday from his hotel room in Myrtle
Beach, S.C., where he was playing a gig. ``All the musicians on the
album have a pretty wide palette of instruments, from flamenco to
steel guitar, and I trust them to know what to do. The song itself
tells me how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   His past few albums have leaned heavily on a cross between
country and flamenco flavors, a style Ely wryly dubs as
``flamenco-billy.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Ely, it's a sound that Nashville and country
radio treat like the plague, a style heard only in watered-down
tones in an occasional George Strait song.
</P>
<P>
   His most high-profile effort of late was his reunion with
longtime pals Jimmie Dale Gilmore and Butch Hancock for the song
``South Wind of Summer'' on ``The Horse Whisperer'' soundtrack. The
three musicians formed the core of the Flatlanders, a legendary
group that released only one album on eight-track in 1972, but
which influenced many of the groups that emerged out of the Austin,
Texas, club scene.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of commercial acceptance of his solo efforts is a
reality Ely accepts. Huge album sales have never been part of his
career, although critics have praised his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's either been a good thing or bad thing that I never really
listened to country throughout my life,'' he said. ``I know how
Nashville works and how everyone jumps on the bandwagon of what
works. That's something I can't do. I wouldn't know what to do with
a lot of success.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ely has a fondness for the ``soul of country music and
the tradition of telling stories'' fostered by such artists as Lyle
Lovett, Steve Earle, Willie Nelson and Waylon Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom T. Hall told me one time that some people go around the
world and don't see a thing, while some go around the block and see
the whole world,'' he said. ``I like to think I fit in the latter
category.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
