<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain riding high off first top 40 hit
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't let the title of his current album fool you: There's
nothing misguided about Edwin McCain's career these days.
</P>
<P>
   After years of working his way through the Southeastern club
circuit and seeing his debut album, ``Honor Among Thieves,'' sell a
respectable but hardly earth-shattering 400,000 copies, the South
Carolina singer-songwriter seemed destined for a life of modest
success. A slow initial response to his second album, ``Misguided
Roses,'' released in July 1997, confirmed the forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the producers of the TV teen sensation ``Dawson's Creek''
took notice of one of ``Misguided's'' cuts, a tortured romantic
ballad called ``I'll Be.'' It aired on the series' season finale on
May 19. Within weeks, McCain, who will appear at the Carefree
Theatre in West Palm Beach, Fla., on Aug. 2, had a breakthrough hit
_ with the song still holding onto the No. 9 spot on Billboard's
Adult Top 40 charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an incredible feeling of relief,'' McCain, 28, says of
his recent good fortune, speaking by phone during a tour break. ``A
sense of `Whew. . . . I don't have to get my pizza (delivery) job
back.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As for the song, already a staple at summer weddings, McCain
says there's more to it than the heartbreak on the surface. ``It is
a love song, and it was written for someone, but the content is not
romantically charged,'' he explains. ``The metaphor of a
relationship is there, but this song is more of a
pull-myself-up-by-my-bootstraps situation, where I was really
burned out after the first record and a little disillusioned and
jaded.''
</P>
<P>
   That McCain should have had such a tough road is a mystery,
given his potent combination of earthy vocals and sensitive
songmanship: Think James Taylor with a few beers under his belt.
McCain also had the benefit of being part of the Southeast's
band-rich scene: Hootie and the Blowfish's Darius Rucker even did a
guest solo on his first album.
</P>
<P>
   Not that McCain sees much of a musical link among the region's
many acts. ``I don't think it's necessarily a defined sound as it
is more about good songwriting,'' he says. ``Whether it's Matchbox
20 writing good alternative songs or me and the Hootie guys writing
good pop songs or folk songs or whatever you want to call them.''
</P>
<P>
   If McCain seems a little confused about his musical identity,
it's only because ``I'll Be'' has crossed so many radio formats.
``All of a sudden, I'm in pop land, playing next to Shania Twain
and the Backstreet Boys,'' he kids.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is no stranger to Palm Beach County, having come here
with his band for a SunFest gig a few years ago. He returned to the
festival this past spring, when he sang lead vocals with Frogwings,
an all-star jam band put together by Allman Brothers Band drummer
(and Jupiter resident) Butch Trucks. ``Butch is such a big brother
and friend to me . . . he worries about me and my career,'' McCain
says.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's own band hardly fits the jam mold _ and he makes no
apologies for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not into 20-minute improvisations,'' he concludes.
``We're about songs.''
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-30-98 1834E
</P>
