<HEADER>
A1998 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD01-COX     07-31 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WOODWORKING COLUMN:
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's always good to see people who jump right into a woodworking
project, but the frustrations that can result are often sad.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a couple of woeful plaints off the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to make a frame for my record album, and since I
can't find a perfect square frame, I have to make my own. I'm using
four equal pieces of quarter molding for the sides. So, I've
routered everything, sanded, etc. But when I try to nail two pieces
together at the corners with a congrouvated nail (is that the right
word?), the pieces move, because the underside is round. I get
someone to hold the pieces in a right-angled box for support, but
when I hammer the metal in, it still slips. Does anyone know how to
fix this? Thanks! Brandon B.''
</P>
<P>
   Pardon me for not fixing the ``congrouvated nail,'' but it's too
priceless to tamper with. Brandon's chief problem, of course, is
that it's virtually impossible to put together a frame without a
frame clamp of some sort.
</P>
<P>
   One assumes, although he doesn't say, that he's mitering the
ends of the frame pieces. This has to be done with great accuracy.
Then, to do a really nice job, the ends ought to be covered with
glue _ not too much _ and the glue allowed to seep into the end
grain and dry. Then the ends should be glued again and the whole
thing placed in a frame clamp.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of different frame clamps on the market, but
since it appears that Brandon wants to make just one frame, a
fabric band clamp may be his cheapest solution. The type with hard
corners that run on threaded rods is better, but the last time I
looked, one of those runs about $20.
</P>
<P>
   With the fabric band clamp, you have to make sure the frame is
square before the glue sets. To do this, take two small sticks,
hold them together side by side, put them inside the frame, then
expand them until one end of each meets in an opposite corner of
the frame. Holding this position firmly so their combined length
doesn't change, pull them out and put them back in the frame the
other way, touching the other two opposing corners. If the sticks
are too long to go in that way, or if they fit poorly, nudge the
pieces around a little. When the same stick length fits perfectly
both ways, the frame is square. People who build lots of frames
generally build a permanent jig like this to test their frames.
</P>
<P>
   When the glue is dry, take the frame out of the frame clamp.
Using bar clamps or C-clamps, secure one corner to a work surface
and with a wire bit, drill a starter hole for a brad of the
appropriate length at a 90-degree angle on the outside of one side
of the corner. Tap the brad into place. There are inexpensive
devices made for seating these brads without hammering if you're
going to make more than one frame. Do this on each corner.
</P>
<P>
   That should be sufficient for the average frame, if it isn't
going to hold anything especially heavy. One does have to wonder,
however, where Brandon has been looking for ready-made frames.
</P>
<P>
   Next, from someone who doesn't sign a name, comes this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Is cedar difficult to resaw? I've cut fir, pine and mahogany
with perfect results using a Suffolk blade(in a bandsaw), but cedar
cuts with a bow in it top to bottom and jams the saw.''
</P>
<P>
   What this individual has never cut before, obviously, is wet
wood. Cedar is an extremely soft wood and when dry it will cut like
butter. However, any wood when thick and wet will close up on a
bandsaw blade and hold it in a death grip. I've had to cut several
blades off my bandsaw and throw them _ and the piece of wood _ into
the trash, with many a good-natured laugh and a merry whistle.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to avoid a disaster like this is to immediately jam
something like a screwdriver blade into the kerf before the binding
starts. If the cut is a long one, that may not suffice, either.
Unless Anonymous is a woodturner, he'll do well to let his cedar
dry before he resaws it. If he's a turner, best to use a chain saw.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   We want to hear from you but are unable to acknowledge every
message.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
