<SLUG> BC-CANCER-STAMP01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stamp helps stamp out breast cancer
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What better way to help stamp out breast cancer than a breast
cancer stamp?
</P>
<P>
   A new first-class stamp that will provide money for breast
cancer research went on sale Thursday, July 30, in the Miami Valley
and across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The stamp, which sells for 40 cents, costs 8 cents more than a
first-class letter stamp. The additional 8 cents will be divided 70
percent-30 percent between the National Institutes of Health and
the Department of Defense's Medical Research Program for breast
cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time the U.S. Postal Service has issued a
``semipostal,'' a first-class stamp with added cost. About 200
million of the stamps will be printed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful,'' says Judy Frost, 54, a five-year
breast cancer survivor from Kettering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect them to find a cure in my lifetime and I believe
research is very important,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Jones, a postal clerk in downtown Dayton, says
customers began asking for the stamp Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   She believes many Americans will be willing to spend the
additional 8 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women for sure, and some men that have wives or relatives or
friends (who've had breast cancer) and know what they've gone
through,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The stamp, in green, blue, yellow and orange, features a drawing
of a woman with the slogan ``Fund the Fight, Find A Cure.'' It was
designed by cancer survivor Ethel Kessler of Bethesda, Md., and
illustrated by Whitney Sherman of Baltimore. CONTACT Meredith Moss
at 225-2440 or by e-mail at meredith_mosscoxohio.co
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
