<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2002 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMUGGLERS01-COX     07-31 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLERS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smugglers used elaborate scheme, law officers say
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ It began with a few stolen pickup trucks and Chevrolet
Suburbans along Interstate 35 in North Austin last year.
</P>
<P>
   A few soon became a few hundred. And when some of the same
stolen Austin trucks began showing up abandoned by the border near
Eagle Pass, detectives launched an investigation that would uncover
an elaborate illegal- immigrant smuggling ring involving 200 stolen
vehicles and thousands of undocumented immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Working together under the Austin Violent Crime Task Force, the
FBI and Austin police uncovered a scheme that used the stolen
vehicles to smuggle illegal immigrants into the United States.
After being brought to Austin, the immigrants were sometimes held
against their will in apartments until they paid their captors an
$800 ``transport'' fee.
</P>
<P>
   Officials believe the smugglers may also be responsible for the
deaths of four immigrants who drowned attempting to cross a swollen
Rio Grande, said Stan Knee, Austin police chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people were dealing in human misery,'' Knee said
Thursday in announcing the results of the yearlong investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, FBI agents and police officers have arrested
22 men and one woman in ``Operation Coyote,'' named because coyote
is a common nickname for immigrant smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck McCormick, FBI supervisory special agent, said these kinds
of smuggling schemes are common and becoming moreso. ``It's
something we can expect to see more of in the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The crime ring's scheme was relatively straightforward, said
Nancy Wright Hohengarten, assistant district attorney for Travis
County. The smugglers paid Austin gang members to steal pickups and
Suburbans, offering about $200 to $300 a vehicle. The smugglers
would drive the stolen trucks to Eagle Pass, where they crammed
undocumented immigrants, sometimes by the dozens, into the truck
beds and onto the Suburban seats.
</P>
<P>
   Once in Austin, the smugglers would demand the $800 transport
fee. Those who paid were set free. Those who couldn't were kept
locked in several Austin apartments until relatives or friends
could send money, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the investigation is continuing and several crime ring
suspects remain at large, officials were not releasing the location
of the apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Hohengarten said several immigrants escaped their captors, and
more than 40 of the immigrants were caught and deported by the
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   Hohengarten said the smugglers avoided being caught at various
checkpoints along the highway to Austin by using separate rental
cars as decoys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (rental cars) would travel in front or behind the stolen
truck, and if the police pulled over the truck, then the car would
do something like speed or distract the officer long enough for the
truck to drive away,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officers recovered a third of the stolen pickups
and Suburbans, or about $600,000 worth of the $2 million in stolen
vehicles used in the smuggling scheme. Some were recovered in Eagle
Pass, where they were parked awaiting drivers or passengers,
according to officials. Others were recovered on the road to Eagle
Pass, while some were recovered in Austin, where they were
abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 people were connected to the ring _ many of them
Austin gang members recruited by the smugglers to steal cars. Six
of the suspects, including the alleged ring leader, Cesar Labra
Gonzalez, 36, remained at large with warrants out for their arrest,
authorities said. The other five at-large suspects were identified
in court records as Jacinto Benitez, 35; Manuel Dominguez, 26;
Mario Perez, 32; Juan Gabriel Domingue, 22; and Leudi Sanchez, 26.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the people suspected of being in the ring were indicted
this month on federal charges related to alien smuggling. The rest
face state charges of conspiracy to commit auto theft of more than
$200,000, which carries penalties ranging from five to 99 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Coyote is the latest in several collaborations
involving federal and local law enforcement officials and other
agencies since the joint task force was formed in 1995. In January,
the task force arrested 15 members of one of Austin's most violent
gangs, Big Dawg, in a continuing effort to curb gang activity in
Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Involving federal agents and prosecuting criminals under federal
laws often lead to tougher sentences for convicted criminals
without the possibility of parole.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
