<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2005 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYMONS01-COX     07-31 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMONS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report: Church did nothing about bishop's sex abuse
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ Catholic church officials removed J. Keith
Symons as bishop of the Palm Beach diocese in June and said their
swift, decisive action was evidence of a new attitude toward sexual
abusers.
</P>
<P>
   After all, only a few weeks were needed to force Symons to
resign after he admitted molesting altar boys during the 1950s and
'60s, church leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lynch, the St. Petersburg bishop who replaced Symons,
praised Pope John Paul II's quick approval of the resignation,
citing it as further proof the church was policing itself better.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, records released by the Pinellas-Pasco State
Attorney's Office told a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators' reports show that one of Symons' victims
complained about him to a Pensacola bishop four years ago, and the
church did nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Symons admitted being a molester then but was allowed to remain
in office until the 53-year-old victim came forward a second time
and complained more vocally to church officials last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch released a statement Thursday saying he first heard of the
man's original complaint a few days before Symons' departure. He
said he has approached a retired judge in Palm Beach County and
asked him to investigate how the church handled the initial
disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge agreed to perform the investigation if the state's
attorney agreed,'' Lynch said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Palm Beach County State Attorney's Office nor Lynch
would identify the judge or comment on the likelihood of his
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still hope that the judge will be able to conduct a thorough
investigation of the 1995 meeting, and make recommendations for the
future which I will share with the Holy See and with other
bishops,'' Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pinellas-Pasco state attorney began investigating
allegations against Symons, 65, after he admitted molesting five
altar boys decades before and stepped down. Prosecutors determined
too much time had passed to file criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators' records show that the 53-year-old victim who
ultimately forced Symons' ouster went to John M. Smith, then-bishop
of the Diocese of Pensacola-Tallahassee, after telling his
counselor and wife of the abuse, which began when he was a
13-year-old altar boy. The man, whose name has been withheld by
investigators, said Smith arranged for him to meet with Symons and
Smith in Pensacola.
</P>
<P>
   Symons admitted at that meeting that he had molested the man but
claimed he had stopped his abusive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Symons) admitted and stated that (the victim) was the only
one he had ever touched, and there had been no once since,'' the
investigators' report says. ``The meeting ended with Symons
agreeing to get counseling but to remain in his present position as
bishop of (the) Palm Beach area.''
</P>
<P>
   But a few months ago, troubled by a well-publicized sexual abuse
case involving another priest, the victim complained to Smith's
successor, Bishop John H. Ricard.
</P>
<P>
   ``After speaking with Bishop Ricard,'' the report said, ``Ricard
told him he would make sure Symons was removed from his office.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, now a bishop in Trenton, N.J., would not comment about
whether he told anyone else in the church about the first
complaint. But he released this statement:
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995, I was asked by a gentleman in his early 50s to set up
a meeting between himself and Bishop Symons to effect a spiritual
reconciliation relating to a sexual abuse matter in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Responding to his request, I arranged for such a face-to-face
meeting. The gentleman was satisfied with the meeting and was
grateful to me for bringing the parties together. I do not think it
is appropriate for me to comment any further because this was a
pastoral outreach for healing and reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   The victim became outraged when another case involving sexual
molestation by a priest became public and a church official called
it ``an isolated incident,'' according to the investigators'
report. The victim, who is undergoing counseling at the church's
expense, then asked to meet with Ricard and told him about Symons.
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney's file contained statements from another
unidentified man, now 52, who said Symons also molested him in the
late 1950s and early 1960s. He never reported the abuse to the
church.
</P>
<P>
   Both victims told similar stories. The 53-year-old said Symons
began to molest him when he was a 13-year-old altar boy. He said
Symons, then a young priest, took him to dinners after Mass and
then on overnight trips and stays in motel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The man said he recalled waking up and finding Symons in bed
with him, lying on top of him, fondling him or trying to rape him.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old victim told investigators the first person he
told about the molestation was his wife in 1980. He later
confronted his father, believing he had knowledge of the abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says his father just looked at the ground and would not
answer him,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Symons served in each of the state's seven dioceses, with more
than half of his 40-year career spent in the St. Petersburg area.
The church says he is undergoing psychiatric treatment at an
undisclosed site.
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-30-98 2305E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
