<P>
   These columns for release the weekend of Saturday, August 1,
1998, are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ The initial phase of the telecom technology
upgrade, known as local number portability (LNP), should be in
place in the nation's top 100 markets by the end of the year. In
due course, number portability should expand from current
capabilities _ to keep a number when you change local providers _
to span services in any of the 50 states. (Glass, Cox News Service)
MOVED 7/30.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Even after the Capitol shootings, Congress does
not wonder whether it might knit up a seamless system to care for,
and about, the mentally ill. And it insists upon a slovenliness in
firearms management that makes it no trick for a man who has been
delusional for years to pick up a gun and go hunting his devils.
(Teepen, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ When the states, citing reform, washed
their hands of responsibility for the mental health system, the
federal government declined to step in. Those decisions caught up
with us the other day at the Capitol when two cops were gunned down
by an abuse posing as a reform. A grateful Congress is naming a
door for the cops. (Rosenfeld, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ A recent New York Times review of the Richard
Ellis book ``Imagining Atlantis'' caught my attention. What the
author and reviewer fail to recognize, in their literary efforts to
be academically correct, is that Atlantis does exist in the minds
of every adventurer and dreamer who ever lived. (Kleinberg, Cox
News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ Editor's Note: Cox News Service columnist Joe
Murray is on assignment. Here is one of his favorite columns from
his archives. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ The Internet is a treasure trove of bad puns
and one liners, most of which seem to end up in my e-mailbox,
courtesy of far-off friends who obviously don't have enough to do
at work. Here are a few selections I've culled over the past few
weeks: (list of really bad jokes follows). (Borders, Nacogdoches
Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CSIBLEY-COLUMN _ One of my grandsons is getting married to a
darling, dark-haired, bookish young girl, and I've brooded over how
to help with the celebration and what to give them. (Sibley,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 7/30.
</P>
