<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ``I'm trying to make a frame for my record
album, and since I can't find a perfect square frame, I have to
make my own. I'm using four equal pieces of quarter molding for the
sides. So, I've routered everything, sanded, etc. But when I try to
nail two pieces together at the corners with a congrouvated nail
(is that the right word?), the pieces move, because the underside
is round. I get someone to hold the pieces in a right-angled box
for support, but when I hammer the metal in, it still slips. Does
anyone know how to fix this? Thanks! Brandon B.'' Pardon me for not
fixing the ``congrouvated nail,'' but it's too priceless to tamper
with. Brandon's chief problem, of course, is that it's virtually
impossible to put together a frame withrame clamp of some
sort. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   LILITH-FAIR _ Lilith Fair, the big tour of women singers reaches
Austin Friday. A live review/feature is planned. (Riemenschneider,
Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN _ Don't let the title of his current album fool you:
There's nothing misguided about Edwin McCain's career these days.
After years of working his way through the Southeastern club
circuit and seeing his debut album, ``Honor Among Thieves,'' sell a
respectable but hardly earth-shattering 400,000 copies, the South
Carolina singer-songwriter seemed destined for a life of modest
success. A slow initial response to his second album, ``Misguided
Roses,'' released in July 1997, confirmed the forecast. (Passy,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOE-ELY _ In 25 years on the road, Joe Ely has performed his
rich blend of Tex-Mex country music at plenty of weird gigs. ``I
played a biker bar in Norway once, inside the Arctic Circle,'' the
51-year-old native of Amarillo, Texas, remembered. ``By the second
song, everyone had their clothes off and were making love on the
floor. The guys in the band were looking at their instruments and
saying, like, `Hey, don't mind us.' ``Don't get me started about
weird gigs . . . Wow.'' (Houck, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COMIC-CARRINGTON _ HBO wants to talk about a sitcom. Album sales
are climbing. Comedy club gigs have him rolling in the dough.
Rodney Carrington can feel it. He's on the verge of something big.
(Houck, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-STAMP _ What better way to help stamp out breast cancer
than a breast cancer stamp? A new first-class stamp that will
provide money for breast cancer research went on sale Thursday,
July 30, in the Miami Valley and across the country. The stamp,
which sells for 40 cents, costs 8 cents more than a first-class
letter stamp. The additional 8 cents will be divided 70 percent-30
percent between the National Institutes of Health and the
Department of Defense's Medical Research Program for breast cancer
research. (Moss, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   AIRBORN-LASER _ AUSTIN _ High-flying laser ``battleships'' could
be America's best means of stopping a regional nuclear war before
it started, Hans Mark, the chief technical advisor to Secretary of
Defense says. Mark, who the U.S. Senate confirmed in June as the
chief technical advisor to Defense Secretary William Cohen,
revealed the Airborne Laser strategy while he was in Austin this
week (week of July 27). The jet could become a key part of the
Clinton administration's plans to deal with the spread of nuclear
weapons as nations such as India and Pakistan, which have fought
each other in the past, acquire and test them. (Stanley, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   Eds: The stories with the BELIEF prefix below are part of a
final package of stories by the Atlanta Journal-C onstitution on
What Southerners Believe. Pages, photos and iluustrations with the
package are posted in the Religion folder.
</P>
<P>
   BELIEF-DEVIL _ Southerners look to God and organized religion
for help in explaining many of life's mysteries. And their beliefs
are not lightly held; they run deep. Much more than in other parts
of the country, Southerners believe there is a God (88%) and that
God answers prayers (90%). In Dixie, people may be less likely to
buy into alien visitation, UFO's or psychic healing, but they
absolutely believe in devil possession, and that some souls go to
heaven while others go to Hell. (White, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WITH BELIEF-BOXES _ Topic by topic, we do a short text block
(3'') with a smallish chart about the traditional belief questions
and about who does and doesn't buy in, ie. question on devil
possession might note that minorities in the South are far more
likely than any other demographic subset to believe in devil
possession. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BELIEF-LIFEFORCE _ A small but noteworthy portion of the people
we polled would not say they believed in God, but affirmed their
belief in a ``life force.'' Nearly 10 percent of Souterhners and 17
percent of non-Southerners fell into this category. We talk to some
of them about what they mean and how a life force is different than
a traditional Jewish-Muslim-Christian view of God. We look at the
possible Eastern influences. And, for the 87 percent of Southerners
who believe in God (compared to 68 percent of non-South), we
discuss how they view him/her as judge, redeemer, etc. (White,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BELIEF-DATING _ Men and women have been looking for ways to meet
one another since that first moment when Adam spotted Eve. Tired of
the singles scene, many people are falling back on the Church to
help them find the perfect match. In recent years, dating services
with a decidely religious character have entered the market and
joined Jewish matchmakers as alternative ways for people to meet
others with similar values. (BLAKE, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   SYMONS _ WEST PALM BEACH _ Catholic church officials removed J.
Keith Symons as bishop of the Palm Beach diocese in June and said
their swift, decisive action was evidence of a new attitude toward
sexual abusers. But recently, records released by the
Pinellas-Pasco State Attorney's Office told a different story.
Investigators' reports show that one of Symons' victims complained
about him to a Pensacola bishop four years ago, and the church did
nothing. (Moffett, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
