<HEADER>
A2049 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-SPACE-$ADV02-     07-31 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-SPACE-$ADV02-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN HELP SCAN THE SKIES FOR THREATENING ROCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As no doubt you know, astronomers are worried about run-amok
asteroids striking the Earth and wiping out civilization, to say
nothing of the new TV season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (And I intend to say nothing about the new TV season, except
that the list of shows I'm determined never to see grows longer
every day.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows exactly how many asteroids, comets, minor planets
and other space objects are dancing around in the cosmos, thinking
about smacking Earth upside the head. But the Planetary Society in
Pasadena, Calif., which purports to know a lot about this subject,
says there may be 100 million of them larger than 100 meters
across. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I myself am not quite two meters tall, and if you took 50 of me
you'd, uh, be a lot braver than my sisters, who can barely stand
one of me. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So far only about 300 of these dangerous space things have been
discovered. Which means there's a lot of discovery work yet to be
done. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Planetary Society, which calls these things Near-Earth
Objects, is so worried about Earth getting whacked by an NEO that
it's offering to pay even amateur observers to look for them and,
when one is found, to shout ``Eureka!!'' or some such. (What do we
do once warned? Cry, perhaps?) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Planetary Society paid out more than $35,000 for
this work, which seems paltry compared with what the Pentagon
spends on hammers and toilet seats. But no doubt the money helped
keep food on the tables of several amateur astronomers who, like
amateur columnists, tend to get so wrapped up in their work they
forget to earn grocery money. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although no exact amount of money has been designated for the
NEO-hunt project this year, a Planetary Society official says it
probably will be about the same as last year. But you won't get
even a penny of it if you don't submit an application. And the
deadline is Aug. 15, which, speaking of spacey things, is the
anniversary of the 1969 opening of the Woodstock Music and Art Fair
on Max Yasgur's farm in Bethel, N.Y., where, as far as I know, no
asteroid has ever landed. (Though who in 1969 would have noticed?) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To get an application, go the this Web site _
http:/planetary.org _ or ask for one by e-mail at
tps.br &LR; mars.planetary.org. And if you don't know what any of that
means you probably shouldn't be outside watching for falling
objects anyway. Or, for that matter, inside playing with sharp
objects. Just go lie down and wait for help to come. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I certainly don't wish to alarm you about the possibility of not
making it through this week without an asteroid blowing up Earth.
Movies such as ``Deep Impact'' and ``Armageddon'' already have done
that work for me. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Louis Friedman, executive director of the Planetary
Society, complains that ``we spend far more on entertainment about
dangerous near-Earth objects than we spend on actually locating
them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But you may recall that this past March we were treated to a
scary false alarm. One day astronomers said there was a strong
possibility that at 12:30 p.m. (CST) on Oct. 26, 2028, a mile-wide
asteroid known as 1997 XF11 would plow into Earth at 17,000 mph and
pretty much make the whole planet look like downtown Detroit. The
next day, after some recalculation, they said never mind. The thing
would miss us by enough that we didn't need to worry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Has Earth ever been hit by any of these things? Oh, you bet.
Scientists say the huge crater off the Yucatan coast was created by
a meteor 65 million years ago and that the impact may have led to
the extinction of the dinosaurs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, to give us all enough warning to tell our friends farewell,
you need to help find these NEOs. Well, unless they're simply small
TV-studio-seeking NEOs. In which case just let them come. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
