<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, July 31, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   POLL-CALIF (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Written off as unknown and too
little funded to secure his party's nomination, GOP candidate Matt
Fong is whittling incumbent Barbara Boxer's once-healthy lead in
the U.S. Senate race, a new San Francisco Examiner poll shows.
Boxer gets 43 percent compared with 40 percent for state Treasurer
Fong _ a statistical dead heat. By ROB ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   CROCODILE (San Francisco) _ Look out, Florida: San Francisco is
getting its own reputation as a reptile resort. Nearly two years
after an alligator in a local lake grabbed headlines nationwide,
its evil twin has been captured in the Mission District here. Well,
not exactly. This one's a crocodile. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   PRIEST-SEXCHARGE (San Antonio) _ Monsignor Joseph Deane
discusses the sex charge against him that prosecutors dropped last
year. The woman who made the charge sued him and he countersued.
Then they agreed to drop the suits, but the Archdiocese of San
Antonio remains a defendant in the case. By SUZANNE HOHOLIK.
</P>
<P>
   PRISONS-AIDS (Oakland, Calif.) _ California's prisons are
accused of hastening the death of inmates with AIDS. By ROBERT
SELNA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ OK, I've heard some horror stories
about Windows 98, but after checking it out, well, it's not all
bad. In fact, about three fourths of readers who wrote to me said
the installation went smoothly, with only minor problems if any.
The remainder of the respondents, though, were in dire straits. By
DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader wants to know what to
look for when buying a PC monitor. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ In their zeal to cut costs, some
companies have zeroed in on absenteeism. And many have instituted
strict sick leave policies that leave workers yelling for mercy. By
putting so much pressure on employees not to take the sick leave
they've earned, workers are pushed to lie about themselves. By L.M.
SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TANG-FASHION (San Francisco) _ In the midst of tony Madison
Avenue in New York, among the Versaces and Pradas and Ralphs and
Calvins there is now a Tang. Shanghai Tang. At the fashion and gift
emporium, you'll find traditional Chinese clothing with a modern
spin by designer Gemma Choi. By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ART-MUSEUM (Berkeley, Calif.) _ At a time when the admission of
African American freshmen has plummeted as a result of the end of
affirmative action programs at the University of California at
Berkeley, it is ironic that the university's museum is showing two
African American artists purely on the basis of their merit as
artists. By DAVID BONETTI.
</P>
<P>
   AUGUST-BOOKS (Undated) _ The dog days of August may be upon us,
but in the world of mysteries and thrillers, it looks like a mighty
interesting month. Some hot new titles include Richard North
Patterson's ``No Safe Place,'' a book about presidential politics.
By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   SF-BLUES (San Francisco) _ The first San Francisco Blues
Festival was held in 1973 in a gym. Johnny Fuller was a headliner,
along with Charlie Musselwhite, Jimmy McCracklin, Luther Tucker and
L.C. ``Good Rockin''' Robinson. This September the festival will
celebrate its 26th time around. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   SHOWTIME (Undated) _ This weekend is Showtime's coming out
party. Yes, the network has been in business for years but if you
wanted to pick a time when it really tried to define itself, you
couldn't pick two better days than Saturday and Sunday. That's when
Showtime begins to not only give HBO a run for its
original-programming money, but the networks as well. By TIM
GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SESAME (San Francisco) _ A traveling Sesame Street art
exhibition has arrived in San Francisco, with contributions from
various celebrities detailing what the long-runing educational
program has meant to them. By CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-CABIRIA (San Francisco) _ ``Nights of Cabiria,''
Federico Fellini's 1957 Oscar winner, is the latest classic movie
to receive a careful and extensive restoration and re-release, part
of a very pleasing recent trend in the movie business By WALTER
ADDIEGO.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MARIUS (San Francisco) _ A warm-hearted and humane
examination of love between a pair of mature, working-class adults,
``Marius and Jeannette'' tells a simple story with good humor and
somber overtones. By WALTER ADDIEGO.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-RELEASES (San Francisco) _ The recent flood of George
Gershwin's music heralds the composer's centennial. But other new
releases represent the acme and nadir of the current market. By
ALLAN ULRICH.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Until this week week Rep. Frank
Riggs, R-Calif., was known as a big supporter of swabbing pepper
spray in the eyes of chained young women. Now Riggs has become
known as the guy who wants to stick it in the eye of San Francisco.
He tacked an amendment on a spending bill that would prevent the
city from using federal housing money because it requires
contractors to provide benefits for domestic partners. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   BOOZE (San Francisco) _ After two sports stars died within a
week of each other a decade ago from cocaine overdoses, the
president of the United States declared ``war'' on illegal drugs.
In contrast, in the wake of seven publicized college binge-drinking
deaths last year, Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala
didn't declare war on booze. Instead, she asked for voluntary
restrictions on college alcohol advertising. By HILARY ABRAMSON.
</P>
