<SLUG> BC-ICELAND-PRESIDENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICELAND'S OPEN-DOOR PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DICK LEHR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REYKJAVIK, Iceland _ The approach to the president's house is an
easy one, taking you along an open and uncrowded road, through a
bird sanctuary and right up to the entrance of the gleaming white
house with its red-tiled roof.
</P>
<P>
   The housekeeper opens the front door and standing right inside,
at the entry to his office, is the welcoming president, Olafur
Ragnar Grimsson. Just the housekeeper and the president _ no
security checks, no bodyguards, no handlers. The tall, white-haired
leader smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see ... there is no security, and it's a very true
reflection of how open and truly democratic Iceland is,'' says
Grimmson, 55, who two years ago was elected the country's fifth
president since it gained independence from Denmark in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sometimes say to my foreign friends that perhaps one of the
great contributions Iceland can make to the world is that we are a
living demonstration that the theories of an open, democratic
society can work. You have a functioning society which has this
peaceful tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. The tiny island nation of about 270,000 people, located
just below the Arctic Circle, is virtually crime free. It has no
army. The nation's economy, built largely around a flourishing
fishing industry, is robust. With few natural recources, most goods
are imported and the cost of living is therefore high, but
Icelanders enjoy universal health care and publicly financed
education through college.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the century we were a nation of poor
farmers and fishermen,'' Grimsson said during an interview at his
home last week. ``Now at the end of the century we can show the
world almost a laboratory case of what an actual, prosperous
society looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   This time of year is Iceland's summer, featuring nearly 22 hours
of daylight and a kind of lightness of being, as increasing numbers
of tourists come to mingle in the sophisticated capital city that
is home to a majority of the nation's population. Or they venture
out into the wide open, mostly treeless country, with active
volcanoes alongside glaciers and geysers, with grassy lowlands
along the southern coastline and, inland, vast deserts of black
sand.
</P>
<P>
   The president's house, built in the 12th century and elegantly
restored, sits at the tip of a peninsula on the outskirts of
Reykjavik and features a sweeping view of the city skyline and,
beyond it, the peaks of a faraway mountain range. The air is crisp,
with temperatures reaching into the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsson is a veteran of Icelandic politics, a former member of
Parliament and the country's finance minister from 1988 to 1991.
Previously a professor of political science, he studied at
Britain's Manchester University and is regarded as an
internationalist.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he succeeded the world's first popularly elected
female head of state, Vigdis Finnbogadottir, who served four terms.
In an interview, the erect and bespectacled Grimsson comes off more
like a political philosopher than a hard-boiled politician, talking
about the time he spends pondering ``the core question of what it
means to be an Icelander in this changing global world.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of what it means to be an Icelander is that they give great
summits. This is the Reykjavik that was made famous for hosting the
summit between President Reagan and Russian leader Mikhail
Gorbachev in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly enough, says Grimsson, some of the key
participants say that the lack of security apparatus that usually
accompanies such summits _ the guards were Icelandic Boy Scouts _
affected the mindsets of Reagan and Gorbachev.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reagan has said he never felt more secure in all his
presidency as he did here,'' said Grimsson. ``The atmosphere of the
country, its openness, contributed to the openness that suddenly
took place. For the first time in 30 years, the leaders of America
and the Soviet Union started to speak to each other like ordinary
human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Though this is the country's season of light, for Grimsson and
his wife and twin daughters the year has been a difficult one. His
wife, Gudrun Katrin Thorbergsdottir, was diagnosed with leukemia
and this summer she underwent a bone marrow transplant. Grimsson
has been spending most of his time with her in Seattle, where she
had the transplant in July, and he returned to Iceland recently for
a few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult journey,'' Grimsson said about his
wife's illness and treatment before turning the discussion away
from the personal back to the national.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsson preferred to stress ``the special kinship'' between his
country and the United States. Noting that Viking explorer Leif
Ericson, who was born in west Iceland, sailed to America in 1000,
Grimsson said, ``our two countries share a unique historical
heritage of discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Icelanders admire Americans in many ways, because I think we
sense, basically, that America, like Iceland, is a nation created
by settlers,'' he says. But there is much about the United States _
the violence and crime rates, for example _ that Icelanders find
puzzling. ``We find it disappointing, maybe a little bit tragic,
that this splendid democratic nation, America, is burdened with all
these problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean why cannot America, in its entirety today, be more
civilized?'' asks Grimsson. ``But, on the other hand, we recognize
the great creativity that does takes place.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimsson last year traveled to the United States and met with
President Clinton, and the two agreed to develop plans to jointly
celebrate the millennium, not just to look back to celebrate the
past, the 1,000 years since Ericson's trip to America, but also to
look ahead ``to extend the importance of the culture of discovery
into the 21st Century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can stress our shared Viking heritage to impress young
people, to train them, in the mindset of the culture of discovery
and exploration, and the willingness to go into unknown
territories,'' says Grimsson.
</P>
<P>
   Plans are underway to reenact Viking voyages to America. ``I
think this is very important for America, because it shows in a
very dramatic way that the American history is perhaps much older
than the official emphasis on the past 350 years or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suddenly extends the history of America, and it brings to
life the fact that America _ 1,000 years ago _ was an integral part
of a democratic culture of discovery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
