<HEADLINE>
SHOWTIME'S `RUDE' IS JUST NASTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
RUDE AWAKENING 
Starring: Sherilynn Fenn, Lynn Redgrave, Richard Lewis 
Created by: Claudia Lonow 
On: Showtime 
Time: Saturday at 11 p.m. 
Rated: TVMA 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Connoisseurs of dreck need no longer rummage around in
``Veronica's Closet'' for squalid, witless humor, because an even
worse sitcom premieres Saturday: howtime's ``Rude Awakening.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a show so wretched that its stars should pray that no
one will watch it, because their careers might never recover. Then
again, that might be fit punishment for all involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rude Awakening'' tries to wring laughs from the travails of
Billie Frank, an alcoholic played by Sherilyn Fenn of ``Twin
Peaks'' semi-fame. Billie's career and her life have bottomed out,
and all she really wants is another drink.
</P>
<P>
   This is actually more promising sitcom terrain than it might
appear; remember the edgily brilliant ``John Larroquette Show,''
featuring a recovering drunk who ran a bus station in St. Louis?
</P>
<P>
   Well, take away the bus station and the wit, replace them with
an utterly unlikable lead character and the most noxious supporting
cast in recent memory, and you're left with ``Rude Awakening.''
</P>
<P>
   In chronicling Billie's days of whine and poses, ``Rude
Awakening'' aims for dark humor, but it's dark to the point of
invisibility.
</P>
<P>
   Once the star of a nighttime soap opera, Billie now has bottomed
out so abjectly that she's working as a secretary to a scuzzy
B-movie producer (Richard Lewis) who keeps putting the moves on
her. Even worse, she keeps getting so drunk that she falls into bed
with guys whose names she can't remember in the morning. ``Bad
genitals! Bad!'' she admonishes her private parts after one such
amorous encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Get the idea of the comedy heights we're scaling here? This is a
show whose idea of yuks is to have Billie tell a guy that she was
voted ``girl most likely to vomit'' in high school. Other gems: ``I
would love to change my mind, but they won't take it back.'' ``In
my culture, throwing up is a sign of great happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   For a show that is chiefly notable for its own emetic qualities,
is it really wise to keep harping on this subject?
</P>
<P>
   Billie can't decide whether she really wants to stop drinking.
Given the repellent family and friends who surround her, including
Lynn Redgrave as her mother, it's hard to blame Billie for
constantly falling off the wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime has scheduled this loser for the late-night hour of 11
p.m. Note to Showtime programmers: When it comes to ``Rude
Awakening,'' better never than late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
