<SLUG> BC-TANG-FASHION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST MEETS WEST ON FASHION STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the midst of tony Madison Avenue in New York,
among the Versaces and Pradas and Ralphs and Calvins there is now a
Tang.
</P>
<P>
   Shanghai Tang.
</P>
<P>
   If you've been to Hong Kong, you already know about David Tang's
fashion and gift emporium, where traditional Chinese clothing is
given a modern spin by designer Gemma Choi. You like Mandarin
collars? They'll give you Mandarin collars that will make your neck
look improbably long. You think the traditional cheung sam or
``Suzi Wong'' dress is a sexy look? You can have one made to order
out of fabric the likes of which you've never seen.
</P>
<P>
   If you go for color, as I do, you'll flip for the vivacity of
traditional Chinese hues like fuchsia, lime, scarlet and orange.
</P>
<P>
   Choi was a featured designer recently during the S.F. Design
Center's Summer Market. Her clothing and her company were part of
``Under the Spell: The Fusion of East/West Design'' program that
included American-born architect Gordon Deere and interior designer
Barbara Allen (a Kansan with a Japanese mother and an American
father, married to a British banker and residing in Kuala Lumpur,
Malaysia), who decorates the palaces of the Sultan of Brunei. Talk
about your East-West fusion.
</P>
<P>
   Choi's clothing, shown very briefly, is colorful, body-conscious
and arrestingly bright.
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration for the designer comes from provincial Chinese
decorative arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be impossible,'' she says, ``to exhaust the sources
for my designs.''
</P>
<P>
   The embroidered, light-as-a-feather silk brocades are done in
elaborate patterns using traditional Chinese elements like the
chrysanthemum, dragon and lotus. Color combinations are festive: A
navy ground with gold, silver, red and green; oranges, fuchsias,
pinks and golds woven together in a blaze of iridescence.
</P>
<P>
   Choi has worked her brocade fabrics into modern Western designs
like the flat-front skinny pant and the sleeveless, Mao-necked
architectural top cropped to show some tummy. A staple of her work
is the chi pao, which Westerners have come to know as the cheung
sam (the difference: Chi pao is Mandarin; cheung sam is Cantonese
for the same garment). Her show opened with short, form-fitting
satin versions worked up in lime and fuchsia.
</P>
<P>
   For men: The traditional Chinese robe rendered in breathtaking
velvets and gilt-woven satins and brocades in a rusty imperial
gold. In addition, ``New York men are wearing my velvet jacket
instead of tuxedos,'' she says of the traditional men's cheung sam,
a boxy jacket with frog-closings down the front and a low Mao
collar designed to show the white silk brocade shirt underneath.
The extra-long sleeves are designed to roll back to reveal the
lining of the coat, usually in a contrasting color.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Shanghai Tang head to the West Coast, probably Los
Angeles first. ``They understand color down there,'' laughs Choi.
Short of running to Hong Kong (where the store is in the Pedder
Building, 12 Pedder St., phone: 011-852-2525-7333), you can stroll
Madison Avenue and pick up a T-shirt or two or have something
gorgeous made to order. Prices for ready-to-wear from $300 up;
custom work starts at $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Madison Avenue: The Vera Wang wedding gown boutique,
which grew out of designer Wang's frustration when she married
nearly 10 years ago at the age of 40. She found that everything on
the market looked like sugar confection. The frou-frou bride at the
top of the wedding cake. Too much lace; too many beads; too many
layers, buttons, textures and weight. So when she opened her
boutique in 1991, her gowns were simple in the extreme.
</P>
<P>
   They still are simply beautiful, but there is modernity in the
simplicity. While the bouffant skirts hark back to the mythic
Bianchi gowns of the late '50s, the dropped waists and
skin-revealing tops (also a reference to the Sabrina necklines of
Givenchy for Audrey Hepburn) are at once daring (very low backs on
some gowns), yet tasteful, feminine and youthful.
</P>
<P>
   When you consider that a majority of brides are in the
20-to-30-something age group when their bodies are great and their
hopes are the highest, Wang's gowns suit the pared-down eye of the
practical modern woman. Celeb clients who have floated down the
aisle in a Wang creation include Uma Thurman (very preggers),
Sharon Stone, Karina Gore (the veep's daughter) and Chynna
Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Wang's wedding gowns do not come cheap. While the Luxe line
(which is made to order with more fine detail) prices out at $5,000
to $10,000, most of the less decorated gowns run between $2,500 and
$3,500.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Real glamour is also at the heart of Lily Samii evening wear.
Unforgiving styles like the slip dress are called ageist and
bodyist by Lily Samii's resident designer, Jacques Pantazes, who
designed for the French couture house of Jean Patou. ``Nobody who
isn't perfect should wear it. If they're not a size 2 and 20 years
old, I try to talk my clients out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pantazes's fall line for Samii is architectural, structured and
elegant, particularly a strapless stunner created from Ziberline, a
complex-woven silk and wool with a spring in it. Color-blocked
vertically in deep red and black, the dress has a stand-away top
over a black velvet bustier with nipped waist. The skirt has some
heft and falls in graceful cloverleafs. It's a major ball gown at a
competitive price ($2,595).
</P>
<P>
   Samii's atelier at 260 Stockton St., fourth floor, in San
Francisco is full of mother-of-the-bride clothes that tend to be
more conservative. But there is nothing stuffy or dated about the
six or seven ensembles created for the opera crowd, particularly a
sculptural black gown with beaded lingerie straps and a sweetheart
decolletage (lined inside with saffron silk charmeuse) worn with a
major saffron charmeuse and black organza shawl trimmed with jet
beads. Gorgeous and sexy, they have an extra fillip: Each piece is
created like couture, right on the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sizes don't matter here,'' Jacques says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
