<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2201 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATIN-LEAGUE-ART-BOS &LR;      07-31 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-LEAGUE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL GREEK _ AND LATIN _ TO THESE STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, Mass. _ To the teachers, the success of this week's
Junior Classics League convention, the largest in 30 years, was its
``synergy'' _ a Greek-derived word, of course.
</P>
<P>
   And most of the 1,700 junior high and high school students here
could probably easily cite the roots of that word: ``syn,'' Greek
for ``together,'' and ``ergon,'' meaning ``to work.''
</P>
<P>
   While the national gathering of students of Greek and Latin
included language exams, contests, and workshops, just as important
to the students was their chance to be part of a 1990s-style
bacchanalia, although a tame one: making outrageous costumes,
attending dances, staying up all night, and ordering pizza with new
friends. Thursday, they strolled around in togas accessorized with
sunglasses, eyebrow rings, and Adidas flip-flops.
</P>
<P>
   The week was a triumph for the Classics League, which drew more
students to the annual convention than at any time since 1968, when
classical studies by young people started a steep decline,
organizers say. Student interest in Latin and Greek has been
steadily on the rise in the 1990s, say league students and
teachers. And the crowds of rowdy and enthusiastic students who
gathered at UMass-Amherst, including about 130 from Massachusetts,
appeared proof that, even in the computer age, interest in the
ancient remains.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``We don't have enough teachers for all the jobs out there,''
said Sherwin Little, a Latin teacher from Cincinnati who is an
adviser at the convention. ``There are lots of cutesy books out now
that tell you how to insult someone in Latin, or how to ask for a
date. The kids think it's hysterical. And we believe in whatever
works.''
</P>
<P>
   If you ask these teenagers, ancient and modern definitely work
together.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen-year-old David Wilson of Amarillo, Texas, said sure,
he's a dedicated student of Latin but what he really wants to do at
the convention, which ends today, is make a statement about the
Lone Star State.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Texas kids have better costumes, he insisted Thursday, which
was designated a ``day in old Rome.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, in a tunic, was armed with a plastic sword and
inflatable spiked iron ball. On his cowboy hat was the button,
``oscula me'' _ ``kiss me'' in Latin.
</P>
<P>
   The cutthroat state-against-state competition that is part of
the gathering includes traditional tests, Jeopardy-style games,
``Olympika'' sports events, and an art contest. Most of the winners
were to be announced late last night. Boston Latin Academy, the
Massachusetts Latin champions in state competition, did not make
the finals of the Certamen language and history competition here.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not dampen the enthusiasm of the Massachusetts
delegation in the biggest event, the daily ``spirit'' contest, in
which each state tries to outdo the others with costumes and chants
such as, ``We're number one. You're number two. We'll kick the
Latin right out of you!''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have spirit, you're not going to want to win,''
said Amanda Marcellino, 14, of Boston Latin Academy, explaining how
screaming, shouting, and waving banners is tied to sober study.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the levity, students conceded that learning classics makes
them better readers and writers. They also say it boosts scores on
standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always enjoyed Latin, but I'm just starting to appreciate
it,'' said Sarah Ramer, 17, of Wayne, N.J. ``When we read `Paradise
Lost' in English, I understood the long, complicated sentences
because they were just like Latin. And I got the references _ so I
didn't even need to read the footnotes.''
</P>
<P>
   High school Latin teacher Robin Boots-Ebenfield of New Jersey
said enthusiasm by students for the classics must be almost
entirely cultivated by good teachers: ``The successful teachers are
the salesmen and the `rah-rah' types.''
</P>
<P>
   However, even charismatic teachers may not be able to mainstream
the classics with teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At our school, all the weirdos take Latin,'' said Cynthia
Keeler of Aurora, Col. ``But that's OK. They're interesting, and
they have a lot of spirit for Latin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
