<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KARMA CHAMELEON'S NEXT LIFE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boy George has grown up. Yes, that is not a misprint. The
singer, flamboyant personality, and outre leader of '80s British
band Culture Club has been through a post-breakup malaise, drugs,
therapy, and various other side trips to emerge a thoughtful, still
outspoken, '90s revival story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually had a very easy time in Culture Club,'' George says
today. ``In terms of career, it took off really quickly. I made a
lot of money and I didn't really have to do much for myself. So,
when you come out the other end of that, you're pretty (messed up).
You have to start thinking for yourself and being a bit more
grown-up. And I guess that's what I've been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The reunited Culture Club _ with George, Roy Hay, Mikey Craig,
and Jon Moss (all the original members) _ is headlining an '80s
package tour this summer with Human League and Howard Jones. George
&AMP; Co. reprise ``Karma Chameleon,'' ``Do You Really Want to Hurt
Me,'' ``I'll Tumble 4 Ya,'' and other hits. These appear on a new
double CD _ one a ``Greatest Hits'' record, the other an excellent
live disc taken from a recent ``Storytellers'' show on cable
station VH1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how you can discover your own music years
later,'' says George (born George Dowd 37 years ago), adding that
many of the tunes were not the sugary ditties they were thought to
be at that teen-idol time, but were really ``personal stories''
connected to his now-defunct love affair with drummer Moss.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the relationship problems, the drugs, and whatever, now
give a real edge, because people know that the songs were about
something,'' says George. ``They were kind of the soundtrack of my
despair, if you like. And I think singing them now, and not being
involved with Jon, is very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Culture Club broke up in 1986. George was in the midst of a
raging, three-year heroin addiction, which he kicked in 1987. Since
then, he's released three solo albums (which have been far more
successful overseas than in America), been a dance club DJ, run a
record label, and for the last few years, written a weekly
newspaper column in London's Sunday Express. What about? ``Gay
politics and a bit of bitching about this or that person,'' says
George. ``But mainly issues that affect gay people.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the other members: Moss, his former lover, is now married
with a child and has had a home studio and done some live gigs; Hay
is living in Los Angeles and working on soundtracks with Grammy
nominee Hans Zimmer; and Craig is raising five children and has
been involved in a London dance club.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for a Culture Club reunion came from VH1, George says.
``I thought, yeah, that could be interesting. It wasn't like I sat
down and said, OK, I got nothing else going on in my life, what
next? It wasn't a desperate move. It was more like the idea came up
and I thought, why not? It scared me a bit, which is a good thing.
Because I think if anything frightens you, even in a small way, it
represents a kind of challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   However, don't expect the Culture Club members to unburden
themselves to one another like new age converts. This is not the
Fleetwood Mac reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we sat down and had a heart-to-heart talk about
what went on in the past,'' says George. ``People joke about it and
references are made constantly, but it's really not the British way
to sit down and analyze things. In that respect, I'm not typically
a British person, because I do analyze things. I also accept that I
come from a culture that doesn't do that, so it's a bit like
there's a rhinoceros in the room but nobody mentions it. Everyone
gets on very well, but maybe we'll have one night on tour where we
get really drunk and it all turns into a `Cat on a Hot Tin Roof.'
That could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Culture Club attempted a reunion in 1990 and
even started to make a new album, but George found it to be
``old-fashioned'' and bowed out. ``I'd been dabbling in dance music
and gone off in a totally different direction, yet there we were
making almost an '80s pastiche album. It just wasn't interesting to
me, so I caused a scene and left.''
</P>
<P>
   George realizes that this summer's return is a ``nostalgia
tour,'' but believes Culture Club will make a progressive new album
within the next year. ``To be honest with you, I really wouldn't be
doing this if there wasn't something else to come from it. What we
do next is the interesting bit, because I'm not interested in being
Gerry &AMP; the Pacemakers. For me, this tour is a means to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   The new double CD has one new single, ``I Just Want to Be
Loved,'' which sounds like a traditional, roots-reggae tune.
``Everybody says that, but I think that's a good sign,'' says
George. ``But it is an original song.''
</P>
<P>
   Culture Club recently kicked off its tour by playing three
nights in Monte Carlo. ``That was very laid-back. It was
millionaires and their very young girlfriends,'' says George. ``But
it's going to be nice when we get out to play for real people _
people that know your songs.''
</P>
<P>
   George is excited about the triple bill with Human League and
Howard Jones. ``Originally it was going to be Duran Duran and
UB40,'' he says. ``But Duran Duran aren't speaking anymore; and
UB40, I don't think they could do it. So we just went for a list of
different bands. I love the Human League, so that was one of the
early choices. At the end of the day, it's got to work _ and I
think this is a very good lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Before George goes, he's asked to comment on the current state
of gay entertainers in this country. As expected, he has a quick
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even people I know that are intelligent will say, `I think
this gay thing has gotten out of hand.' I'll say, `What the heck to
you mean?' They'll say, `You know, it's just gotten out of hand.'
And I'll go, `Oh, I see. We're allowed to exist, but we should just
keep our mouths shut.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, my theory is that the world hasn't changed that much
in terms of gay issues or racism,'' says George. ``I think what
happens is that you change. I think the gay community, like the
black community, has gotten stronger. They have a sense of their
own power. They have a sense of pride. And they kind of orchestrate
the changes, just because of their own attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   He's still not pleased, however, with the way gay artists are
portrayed on TV or the movies. ``I think it's always cliched. We're
always the kind of eyeliner on the one-liner. You're either
inoffensive, or you're a dork character. And I find that
frustrating. But then, I think that's true of all minorities. You
know, you have black guys who are the villains, South Americans who
are the thieves, and fat people who are funny. I just think it's
true of all minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the end of the day, it's about you. That's the one
thing that I've learned in the last few years. It's that you change
the attitude to yourself. Therefore, other people change their
attitude to you. Not all people, but enough of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
