<HEADLINE>
A HEARTY JOKE, NOT QUITE IN FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
POLISH WEDDING 
Directed and written by: Theresa Connelly 
Starring: Claire Danes, Lena Olin, Gabriel Byrne, Adam Trese, Mili
Avital, Daniel LaPaine, Rade Serbedzkija 
Running time: 101 minutes 
Rated: PG-13  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How do you make a film called ``Polish Wedding'' and not have it
turn into a Polish joke? That's the question facing first-time
writer-director Theresa Connelly, who knows the territory _
specifically, Hamtramck, the Polish-American enclave surrounded by
Detroit _ but hasn't the finesse to avoid having her film crumble
into self-conscious clunkiness as it overpitches the personality
clashes among its family named Pzoniak. It's dominated by that
earthiest of earth mothers, Lena Olin, as Jadzia, who declares
herself queen of her unruly clan _ a claim nobody is inclined to
dispute, especially her long-suffering husband, dour Bolek, a baker
who, as played by Gabriel Byrne, is submerged in denial as he
shuffles between hearth and home.
</P>
<P>
   Olin's smoldering matriarch seeks extramarital satisfaction in
the office building where she works as part of the cleaning crew.
What nobody seems to notice is that her DNA is very much present in
her daughter, Claire Danes, who hits a sympathetic level of edgy
agitation as she drives the neighborhood guys nuts. All that keeps
the locals away except for one smitten young cop (Adam Trese) are
the protective noises made by her strapping brothers, who crash
around the house like pieces of heavy construction equipment and
seem almost relieved to have their lives filled with purpose when
their mother orders them to get to work painting the outside and
washing the windows.
</P>
<P>
   But Olin and Danes and the others can carry the one-note
material only so far. Connelly does capture the sense of place
she's after, and the heartiness pervading the Pzoniak household,
seething with dissatisfaction though it is, feels like the real
thing. It can have been no easy feat to get a Hamtramck-based film
greenlit. But the fact that the richly textured flavor of life
there has never been adequately captured on film makes one wish
Connelly had done a few more rewrites and carried the Pzoniaks past
stereotype and sitcom hyperactivity and served up their cheatin' _
and vigorously beatin' _ hearts with more insight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
