<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATING WRIGHT AND WRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Granted, Ben Wright was never convicted of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   His mistake occurred in 1995, when the Wilmington News Journal
quoted the television golf analyst explaining his views on the
LPGA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lesbians in the sport hurt women's golf,'' Wright said. Women
golfers, he added, ``are handicapped by having boobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite naturally, as Mr. Sensitive told Sports Illustrated,
unnamed CBS officials told him to deny making the statements. So
Wright said he was misquoted, and CBS in turn stood by its
prize-winning guy, re-signing him to a four-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after the ink had dried on the deal, CBS suspended
the Briton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so bloody stupid; stupid, naive, and weak,'' Wright told
Sports Illustrated. ``The most stupid thing I did was remain
silent. I should have come out and said, `Hey, I said all these
dumb things, and they were wrong ...'''
</P>
<P>
   Wright is now 65 years old, and he is probably really sorry
about making those statements.
</P>
<P>
   But what is particularly disgusting about the television
industry these days is the use of disgraced announcers to boost
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Charles, executive producer of T.J. Sports Television, is
the latest fraud. He decided to bring Wright back to do commentary
for a syndicated show.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to what Charles told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for all the publicity I can get on this show _
good, bad, or indifferent,'' he said. ``My personal opinion was
that Ben got a raw deal. But we'd still have gone after him because
he's the best.''
</P>
<P>
   The name of the show is unimportant; it's lame, anyway, largely
because shameless hucksters like Charles are willing to do anything
to get a speck of a rating.
</P>
<P>
   Madison Square Garden Network president Dave Checketts pulled
the same stunt with Marv Albert.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year after pleading guilty to a misdeamenor charge
of assault, Albert was hired back to do radio play-by-play for the
New York Knicks and to host a 30-minute sports news show on cable
television.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy the Greek never had it so good.
</P>
<P>
   Curiosities sell. No telling what Marv might do or Wright might
say.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that Wright will not be on live. His two-minute
segments are taped.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CBS out of race
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TNN will air the NASCAR Winston Cup Pepsi 400 Oct. 17. CBS was
scheduled to show the race July 4, but fires near Daytona
International Speedway forced a cancellation of what would have
been the first live network telecast of a night race. CBS Sports
was unable to fit the race into its October programming, so it was
shifted to TNN Motorsports, which CBS owns. CBS plans to air the
race in 1999 ... On Sunday, TNN will show the NASCAR Pennzoil/VIP
Discount Auto Center 200 Craftsman Truck series race live from New
Hampshire International Speedway in Loudon ... ESPN2 plans to
televise as many as five US games at the World Basketball
Championships in Athens. If the US makes it past the first round,
ESPN2 will air two second-round games _ Monday at midight and
Tuesday at 9 p.m. The remaining telecasts would be next Friday at 4
p.m. (quarterfinal), Aug. 8 at 5 (semifinal), and Aug. 9 at 1
(championship) ... HBO's ``Boxing After Dark'' will televise the
Goodwill Games boxing semifinals and final. The broadcasts air
tonight and tomorrow nights at 11, with Jim Lampley, Larry
Merchant, and Roy Jones Jr. calling the action from ringside ...
CBS has announced its NFL broadcast teams for the upcoming season.
Greg Gumbel, Phil Simms, and Armen Keteyian will be the No. 1 team,
followed by Verne Lundquist, Randy Cross, and Michele Tafoya; Kevin
Harlan and Sam Wyche; Gus Johnson and Steve Tasker; Ian Eagle and
Mark May; Don Criqui and Beasley Reece; and Craig Bolerjack or Bill
Macatee and John Dockery. The ``NFL Today'' team is composed of Jim
Nantz, Marcus Allen, Brent Jones, and George Seifert.
</P>
