<HEADER>
A2217 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WAR-CIVILIZATION-B     07-31 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WAR-CIVILIZATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PENETRATING WAR OF THE WORLDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
WAR AND CIVILIZATION 
Produced by: Bruce Eadie 
Directed by: Tony Bulley 
On: TLC (The Learning Channel) 
Date: Sunday-Wednesday, 9-11 p.m.begins august 2 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given that there's no human record of a century without war,
what does the future hold, especially now that civilization has
perfected means to annihilate itself?
</P>
<P>
   That's the dreadful question hovering over the ambitious ``War
and Civilization,'' an eight-hour, eight-episode survey of warfare
through the ages produced for the Learning Channel. Two aging
eminences _ Walter Cronkite, who narrates, and John Keegan, whose
acclaimed work in military studies informs the documentary _
provide intellectual ballast and an air of gravity. If it all
sounds a bit leaden, well, it's not, at least based on the four
episodes I saw, including the engaging introductory hour and the
concluding episode, which is the most opinionated.
</P>
<P>
   ``War and Civilization'' is quite right to ask large
philosophical questions, although Keegan's answers are simplistic
and sometimes contradictory. For example, he submits that actions
like those by the United States in the Gulf War are ``absolutely
necessary'' to restrain rogue states. Then he goes on to speculate
that wars have perhaps become too humanly and materially costly to
prosecute at all.
</P>
<P>
   But Keegan's large-caliber ideas aren't vital to the overall
success of ``War and Civilization,'' which is enlivened and
distinguished by fascinating details. This well-researched
information is often embedded in exciting mini-chronicles of
pivotal battles and campaigns that keep one's attention glued to
the program. (Two episodes air nightly, Sunday through Wednesday, 9
to 11 and again midnight to 2 a.m.)
</P>
<P>
   The Western way of war was born 3,000 years ago, we learn in the
first episode, with Greek warriors known as Hoplites deployed in
phalanx formations bristling with long spears. Their aim was that
of subsequent armies, to act quickly and decisively. They bore 70
pounds of armor and weapons, just as today's US infantry soldiers
carry roughly 70 pounds of gear. The more things change, the more,
intriguingly, they stay the same.
</P>
<P>
   What has changed radically, of course, is mankind's killing
efficiency and power. Some 3.5 million troops were involved at
Stalingrad during World War II, the biggest battle in history, in
which 1.1 million Soviet soldiers were killed. More than 100
million people have perished in 20th-century warfare, more than all
the lives lost in the previous history of warfare, according to the
final hour, ``The Price of War.'' Rules governing warfare
essentially vanished in the mid-20th century, just as the atom bomb
made its horrifying impact.
</P>
<P>
   Facts and such staggering figures as these rarely are divorced
from a rich context that often relates warfare to other human
endeavors. For example, we see the ways war tears economies apart:
Many European cities went bankrupt building a new wave of
fortifications designed to withstand cannon fire. As another
example, we learn that the advent of gunpowder ushered in medical
advances as physicians began treating the complex internal wounds
inflicted by gunshot.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in ``War and Civilization'' is more curious than another
story related in episode 4,``Gunpowder.'' Although Japanese
warlords fought with guns in the late 16th century, these weapons
soon vanished from the island nation because of its ancient
reverence for the sword. For 250 years, the Japanese confined
themselves to the sacred blade in combat. The sharpness of
lovingly, painstakingly crafted new swords was tested, by the way,
on the corpses of executed criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Among the important actions ``War and Civilization'' skillfully
and grippingly distills are the battles at Salamis between Greek
and Persian vessels; of the Battle of Crecy, where English longbows
overwhelmed the French; and of Waterloo, where 190,000 troops
clashed on a tiny battlefield and 40,000 men were left dead or
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The production hardly moves at the pace of MTV, but the series'
well-staged reenactments, crisp editing, and canny use of sound
effects invigorates the battle scenes, helping the viewer sense the
horror and, sometimes, the strange pageantry of mortal combat.
</P>
<P>
   If Keegan's overarching ideas aren't original, some of his
geopolitical hypotheses seem fresh, and certainly provocative.
Take, for instance, his notion that although the United States was
finally driven out of Vietnam by a cause-inspired enemy, our long
and aggressive presence there was ``decisive'' in bringing an end
to the Cold War because of the impression it left on the USSR.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, flaws and peculiarities in a production
this broad and ambitious. One little oddity it's impossible to
forget are long shots of historian Keegan filmed, it appears,
leaning on a bridge in London, and looking like he's from another
century wearing formal white gloves.
</P>
<P>
   The episodes I saw vary considerably in their narrative
coherence, but all are well-written and have a great deal to offer,
as I strongly suspect the others do, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
