<SLUG> BC-CHEERS-FADES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHEERS' FADES AFTER LANDMARK ENTERS RERUNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It is a lonely sight in the Prudential Center: stacks
of T-shirts bearing the golden ``Cheers'' emblem, a television
blaring an episode from 1984, shoppers strolling indifferently past
images of the prudish waitress with winged hair.
</P>
<P>
   One man glances at the vending cart, then moves on. A salesman
from St. Louis ponders a coffee cup and two mugs. The vendor says
business is usually better, but five years after the last episode
of the sitcom, even she prays for the fate of Boston's most famous
fictional bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one girl come and buy a T-shirt, and then she said,
`What is Cheers?''' said Tracy Wright, 24. ``Somebody else asked me
if Cheers was a kind of beer.''
</P>
<P>
   It is still, to some outsiders, a symbol of this city. Tourists
still buy Cheers keychains, though vendors say sales are dropping;
commercial ``Cheers bars'' now pepper airports around the globe,
though even the logo seems as antiquated as flowery Coca-Cola
script. In Boston, the Bull &AMP; Finch pub, credited with inspiring
the Hollywood set, sticks name tags on diners _ still making it, as
the theme song goes, the bar where ``everybody knows your name.''
</P>
<P>
   But the question now is: who will remember it?
</P>
<P>
   Off the air except for reruns since the famous ``Last Call''
episode in 1993, ``Cheers'' appears, understandably, to have lost
its luster among tourists. And Boston seems to be drifting away
from one important part of its past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not as hot as it was in its heyday, but I think there
still will be a curiosity factor,'' said Peggy Davis-Mullen,
chairwoman of the City Council's committee on tourism. ``That will
change as we all get older. My generation, we're the same age as
some of those folks, so we could identify. But as the viewing
audience gets older and as the hip stuff gets younger, then you'll
see an even greater impact.''
</P>
<P>
   There is the tangible evidence: Attendance at the Bull &AMP; Finch,
the Beacon Hill watering hole that became the model for the Cheers
bar, dropped by 200,000 in the first year after the show went off
the air, according to a survey by the Boston Business Journal. More
than half a dozen local concierges say requests for directions are
now infrequent. Even Stan Novack, vice president of Host Marriott,
which runs the restaurant chain, says merchandise sales have
dropped off over the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the anecdotal evidence, the stories from local
tourism experts that suggest the television show no longer
symbolizes Boston to the rest of the nation _ and that Cheers
character Diane Chambers now has a rival as the female icon of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get an Ally McBeal bar,'' Davis-Mullen said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that the Cheers logo has become its own
nationwide tourist phenomenon, akin to Planet Hollywood or the Hard
Rock Cafe. Just last week, a new Cheers bar opened in Omaha; last
month, another debuted in Kuala Lumpur, Novack said. But the
approximately $30 million revenue the food chain brings in each
year is related more to the convenience of the restaurant than the
television show or its home port, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken on a life of its own,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas A. Kershaw, owner of the original Bull &AMP; Finch, insists
the same is true in Boston. But unlike an interview in 1994, when
he boasted $4.5 million in merchandise revenue alone, Kershaw last
week refused to divulge the revenues or even number of guests over
the last four years because it is a ``privately held company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm saying is that business is still good,'' he said. ``If
I gave numbers at one point, that's terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Concierges at local hotels tell a different story, one that
centers on classic Boston institutions along the Freedom Trail.
While there are some requests for directions to ``the Cheers
place'' _ and even fewer for the two Cheers bars at Logan airport _
the television lure hardly compares to the two longtime favorites:
Faneuil Hall and the USS Constitution, concierges said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a place people ask for,'' said Alain Morel, concierge
at the Ritz-Carlton on Arlington Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, they don't know about it. We recommend it
anyway,'' said Betty Salemme, of the Seaport Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   And of the tourists interviewed last week, more than a few
admitted to having left Cheers off their lists. Adam Jacobs, 32,
and Carri Martino, 27, of San Francisco, happened by the Beacon
Street bar ``by mistake'' and kept walking because it is
``touristy.'' Erin Keane, 15, of New Jersey, made it to the Freedom
Trail, the Aquarium, Quincy Market, the Titanic show, the USS
Constitution, and the Museum of Fine Arts gift shop. But not the
Bull &AMP; Finch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to,'' she shrugged. ``But we didn't get to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
