<SLUG> BC-PROBE-WHITEHOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE WEST WING, ALL REMAINS QUIET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seven times during a daily briefing with reporters
this week, White House press secretary Michael McCurry pleaded
ignorance to questions on the Monica S. Lewinsky case and the
president's strategy in addressing the allegations. And that was
just in the first two minutes of the briefing.
</P>
<P>
   His professed ignorance has become routine around the West Wing,
where the most senior, most trusted political aides say they have
no input in or knowledge of Clinton's legal maneuvers and the
decisions that could affect the course of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, prominent Clinton allies outside the White
House now say that the president's failure to publicly address the
charges and his inability to adopt a coherent public relations
strategy has created the impression _ rightly or wrongly _ of an
administration in utter disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is the ``war room'' mentality that carried Clinton through
allegations of marital infidelity in New Hampshire in 1992, the
campaign-finance charges in 1997, and the first weeks of the
Lewinsky investigation earlier this year. It has been replaced,
according to one administration official, by an ``exhaustion
mentality,'' with weary officials either tendering their
resignations, as McCurry has done, or actively seeking to know as
little as possible about Clinton's plight for fear of being
subpoenaed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disquieting, discomforting part of all this is that
ignorance is bliss,'' said one administration official. ``People in
the White House just don't want to know anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The result: public relations disasters, like the weekend refusal
by White House officials to even acknowledge the fact that Clinton
received a subpoena from independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr _ a
first for a president. In private, McCurry seemed angered by the
lack of communication between Clinton's lawyers and policy
advisers. The White House still did not even acknowledge that it
had received the subpoena until Starr withdrew it in a deal for
Clinton's testimony on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that Clinton has remained engaged in his policy
agenda, and has maintained his public schedule. He was in North
Carolina Thursday for an environmental event and is heading to the
Hamptons on Long Island, N.Y., this weekend for a round of fund
raising with some of the party's biggest contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked in to see the president this morning, and he looked
up and said, `We should be saying more about technology,''' Ann
Lewis, the White House communications director, said of a midweek
encounter. Lewis said the president then began adding things to a
speech on education, and described him as ``focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, other aides privately told of a distracted president
spending an increasing amount of time behind closed doors with
lawyers Robert Bennett, David Kendall, Mickey Kantor, and White
House counsel Charles Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   They also reported growing frustrations with a policy agenda
that appeared to stall the day the Lewinsky story splashed across
the front page of the Washington Post in January.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning and evening, White House political strategists
like Doug Sosnik, a Clinton counselor, and Rahm Emanuel, Clinton's
chief adviser, gather in Ruff's office to discuss the day's news.
At each meeting, Ruff tells the rest of the staff virtually nothing
about the legal matters Clinton faces, and faces a dwindling number
of questions from a staff beaten down by a lack of answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned about the state of the White House,''
said one adviser with intimate knowledge. ``There is a tremendous
amount of disarray and lack of a message. There was that silliness
of not confirming the serving of a subpoena, the lack of any
message team. There is literally a total vacuum of political and
press strategy in the White House. Everyone has taken a pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Many White House aides were buoyed by news reports that Lewinsky
told Starr's prosecutors that she herself had typed up the
``talking points'' document given to her former friend Linda R.
Tripp. McCurry scolded reporters for printing and broadcasting
stories that insinuated Clinton confidant and White House Deputy
Counsel Bruce Lindsey was the author. But even that victory seemed
to fade away in the other news of the week, the arrangements made
by Lewinsky and Clinton to testify.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the case is resolved, many in the West Wing expect
to no longer be part of the Clinton circle. McCurry has announced
he will depart in October. Chief of staff Erskine Bowles has sent
strong signals that he will leave by year's end. Thursday, he
uncharacteristically gave two speeches during a Clinton trip to
North Carolina, in what appeared to be a dry run for a possible
gubernatorial bid. And Emanuel has long been rumored to be leaving
the White House for his native Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
