<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TUATARA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUATARA'S ECLECTIC SOUND FLOWS FROM ITS DIVERSITY OF MUSICAL
TALENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Named for a reptile once common in New Zealand, Seattle band
Tuatara sounds ancient yet modern.
</P>
<P>
   Formed by drummer-percussionist Barrett Martin of Screaming
Trees, bassist Justin Harwood of Luna, saxophonist Skerik of
Critters Buggin' and guitarist, mandolinist Peter Buck of R.E.M.,
Tuatara is a collaborative group that has grown to about 10
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Its first album, ``Breaking the Ethers'' (Epic Records), offered
a rhythmic, exotic blend of musical styles played on sitar,
saxophone, steel drums, marimba, vibraphone, acoustic bass,
didgeridoo and other instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trading With the Enemy,'' the group's follow-up album (also on
Epic), released last month, was recorded in Seattle at the Ironwood
and Jupiter studios. It's more accessible than the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first album was more ambient and atmospheric, whereas the
second has more songs, more compositions,'' said Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Though Martin and Harwood are listed as co-producers, everyone
contributed to the new album's creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think because Barrett and I are founding members and it's
sort of our project conceptually, everyone looks to us for a nod,''
Harwood said. ``But that's about as far as it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Martin, Harwood, Skerik and Buck, Tuatara currently
includes saxophonist Steve Berlin of Los Lobos, guitarist Scott
McCaughey of The Minus 5 and the Young Fresh Fellows, percussionist
Elizabeth Pupo-Walker, multi-instrumentalist Mike Stone and horn
players Christopher Littlefield and Craig Flory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can get much bigger,'' Harwood said. ``We've
got most of the bases covered.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuatara's sound evolved over many jam sessions, where shared
ideas were massaged into songs. Martin's collection of hundreds of
instruments from around the world insured that each session would
be unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bring an instrument into the studio and put it over in the
corner and someone will always go over and try it,'' Harwood said.
``And within five minutes, they've come up with a riff _ maybe the
only one they've been able to play on it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the first to admit that you're not going to master an
instrument that's not indigenous to your culture,'' Martin added.
``That's best left to the masters. But if you can get a cool sound
out of it, it's worth the effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The songs on the new album are diverse. ``Smuggler's Cove,''
which Stone contributed, has a film noir feel. ``Koto Song,''
written by McCaughey, recalls the Polynesia-inspired vintage lounge
music of Martin Denny.
</P>
<P>
   The atmospheric ``Wormwood'' was written late at night, using
vibraphone and upright bass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the only time when I've actually turned the
lights down in order to get a vibe going,'' Harwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Buck provided the basic riffs for the tongue-in-cheek
``L'Espionage Pomme de Terre'' (Espionage of the Potato), based on
incident in which Buck was arrested while on an African safari for
taking photos at an airport. The airport, situated in a town named
for the local potato, turned out to be a military base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
