<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWERBALL'S `LUCKY' 13? DON'T BET ON IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What intrigued America most this week was not anything bubbling
out of the swamp in D.C.: Out here, we're talking Powerball, the
fantasy of striking it fabulously rich with a one-dollar pass
through a lottery terminal.
</P>
<P>
   And terminal, alas, are the hopes of millions of us who tossed
greenbacks onto the bonfire of illusory dreams. Psychiatrists warn
of post-Powerball withdrawal, triggering depression or worse among
vulnerable bettors who shoved too much of their already fragile
self-esteem into the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   You're more likely to be hit by lightning than to beat the
one-in-80-million lottery odds. Let's hear it for the winners, 13
people from an Ohio machine shop who sent to Indiana for the
fateful purchase. That gang will split up a pre-tax lump sum of
$160-odd million, the fattest prize anywhere, ever. We wish them
well.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a downside to winning. Not that fear of winning
prevented me from handing a ten-spot to my friend who put a little
pool together. Winning fantastic wealth means you solve a bunch of
your existing problems _ and inherit a swath of new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Say you're one of the Lucky 13 from the machine shop, and you
get a one-13th share of the lump sum, $12.4 million before taxes,
$9 million after. You now have a whole new set of problems. People
think you are filthy rich, and so they treat you differently.
Everyone close to you knows your bottom line just improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Learn to say `no,''' was the advice of the new lawyer for the
Ohio 13. You'll get a lot of practice using the ``N'' word. At
home, at work, if you continue to work, in church, everyone will
have their hand out.
</P>
<P>
   You are doomed to a lifetime of either overtipping or being
called a cheapskate behind your back. You will not be able to enter
your neighborhood coffee shop, convenience store, or gas station
without someone hollering out unsolicited advice or making some
kind of snide crack. You'll develop a sinking sensation that your
life has changed, permanently, in ways you never anticipated, and
do not welcome.
</P>
<P>
   You'll become shyer around strangers, waiting for a flicker of
recognition, some double-take, some acknowledgment of your
perceived good luck, and their same-old-same-old bad luck. And that
will get tiresome.
</P>
<P>
   Like Michael Jordan or Leonardo DiCaprio, you'll be unable to
eat out without waiting for someone to clap you on the shoulder
while your fork is just passing under your nose. I once sat at a
fancy dinner next to a stunningly beautiful movie star. She had no
problem sticking to her diet, because persistently intrusive fans
kept interrupting her for a hello, a snapshot, an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   Most lottery winners drift back into anonymity with the general
public _ but not with their immediate circle. Quitting your job,
swapping friendly colleagues for beady-eyed money managers who bill
you by the minute, becoming suspicious of every approach, wary that
every Little Leaguer high school yearbook salesman is waiting to
pounce; all this is not fun.
</P>
<P>
   Like most people, I long assumed that with just ten grand more a
year, everything would be fine. But there's never enough money.
It's always ten more, and ten more on top of that ten. A pal who
calls himself ``the old Southie sage'' listens to the laments of
the retired gents who hang out around Castle Island. ``What do you
do tomorrow? Nothing? Nothing is hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Think about all the people in our society who achieve the
highest prizes and the grief they frequently encounter. Bill
Clinton? His privacy is destroyed, his conduct widely questioned,
his personal morality impugned, his enemies in full cry. Would you
swap places with Bill? Or with, say, Mike Tyson? A psychological
basket case, unable to control himself, a cartoonish parody of a
self-confident heavyweight champ.
</P>
<P>
   Princess Diana? Was she lucky? Pick one of dozens of movie
stars, rock musicians, athletic icons, weigh what you know of their
lives, and ask: Was what they gained worth what they lost? Jack
Kennedy? Marilyn Monroe? Do you see a pattern here? Achieving a
goal means ending a dream. And then you need a new dream to replace
the old one that brought you as far as you already got.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the ranks of the newly rich can be jarring. ``Let me
tell you about the very rich,'' wrote F. Scott Fitzgerald. ``They
are different from you and me ... They think, deep in their hearts,
that they are better than we are. They are different.''
</P>
<P>
   Half of all rich people inherited their money. The top one
percent of American households was worth an average of about $8
million three years ago, economist Edward Wolff told the Christian
Science Monitor. The rich are getting younger, and their ranks
include more Asians, Hispanics, and other minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The richest 10 percent of Americans own 88 percent of all stocks
and mutual funds. So they've been getting richer. But happier?
That's another story. Ten years from now, I'll bet some of those 13
Ohio machine shop winners will wish their number had never come up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2236 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-BASEKETBALL-BOS     07-31 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BASEKETBALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUDE `BASEKETBALL' FAILS TO SCORE LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Baseketball is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
BASEKETBALL 
Directed by: David Zucker 
Written by: David Zucker and Robert LoCash 
Starring: Matt Stone, Trey Parker, Yasmine Bleeth, Jenny McCarthy,
Robert Vaughn, Dian Bachar 
Running time: 104 minutes 
Rated: R (If it's objectionable or offensive, you'll find it here) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trey Parker and Matt Stone are the guys who made anal probes and
talking excrement funny.
</P>
<P>
   They are the creators of Comedy Central's ``South Park,'' the
``It'' show of the moment, a devastatingly crude animated series
which suggests how the ``Peanuts'' gang might have turned out if
they'd feasted on a steady diet of Quentin Tarantino, Marilyn
Manson, and the Playboy Channel.
</P>
<P>
   But as anyone who has ever watched the TV-M rated foibles of
Cartman, Stan, Kyle, and Kenny in their fictional Colorado town
knows, a little dab of ``South Park'' will do you just fine for a
good long time, unless you have a serious jones for bodily fluids
and gross-out humor.
</P>
<P>
   In which case, ``Baseketball,'' may be the film for you.
</P>
<P>
   Lowbrow doesn't even begin to explain this comedy, which stars
Parker and Stone as lifelong friends and losers who hit it big when
they create a new sport, a combination of baseball and basketball.
If it's offensive or objectionable, director David Zucker of
``Airplane'' and ``Naked Gun'' fame, who co-wrote the script with
Robert LoCash, finds a way to get it in the movie:
</P>
<P>
   A 10-year-old liver patient doing tequila shots? Yup!
</P>
<P>
   A man saying ``Got Milk,'' then squirting the aforementioned
liquid from his nipples? Check!
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Borgnine doing a strip tease and singing Right Said
Fred's ``I'm Too Sexy''? You betcha!
</P>
<P>
   This film is crass, coarse, vulgar, and uncouth. But its biggest
sin is that it's rarely funny. Crude and rude is fine, but the
point should be to make 'em laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, the film has its moments. It gets off to a
great start when young Joe Cooper, sitting in Yankee Stadium,
catches the third home run hit by Reggie Jackson in the deciding
game of the 1977 World Series, It is a pure spiritual sports
moment, but ever since professional sports have been corrupted, a
narrator tells us. Athletes are more interested in end zone dances
than sportsmanship, evidenced by a ``Riverdance''-style celebration
after a football team scores.
</P>
<P>
   Teams test the loyalty of fans by moving from one locale to the
next. Says the narrator, ``The Minnesota Lakers moved to Los
Angeles where there are no lakes; The Houston Oilers moved to
Tennesee where there is no oil. The New Orleans Jazz moved to Utah
where they don't allow music.'' Endless expansion has watered down
the talent pool, forcing teams to recruit players from ``prisons,
mental institutions, and Texas.'' The incessant commercialization
of sports has given rise to such facilities as Preparation H Arena
and Maxi Tampon Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   This is the film's prologue, and it's very funny because it
smacks of truth. But nothing else even comes close once Cooper
(Parker) and his best friend, Doug Remer (Stone) grow up to be
bums, who stumble upon the game which goes from backyard curiosity
to national obsession. There are vague plotlines about Coop's
desire to keep the game free of commercialism, Remer's easy nod
toward the temptation of clothing contracts and such, and Coop's
budding romance with a shapely young thing, Jenna (Yasmine Bleeth)
who runs the Dream Come True foundation.
</P>
<P>
   In between there's dominatrix cheerleaders, gay jokes, lots of
mangled animals, gay jokes, snaps on Robert Downey Jr. and
Christian Slater, gay jokes, and prosthetic devices which would
have made Mark Wahlberg weep in ``Boogie Nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and did I mention there are gay jokes?
</P>
<P>
   Parker and Stone are OK, but they shouldn't quit those day jobs.
Then again, Konstantin Stanislavsky couldn't have done much with a
script which asked him to pretend to sip a bag of fat sucked out of
Marlon Brando's hindparts. There are also appearances by real
sportscasters, Bob Costas, Al Michaels, Dan Patrick, and Kenny
Mayne.
</P>
<P>
   This being a Zucker project, he employs his usual
everything-but-the-kitchen-sink style _ if you don't laugh at one
gag, wait a split second, there's another on the way. It's not a
comedy, it's an endless drive-by with Uzis, except most of the
shots are misfires.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker and company should have taken a few cues from ``There's
Something About Mary,'' the summer's other crude and rude comedy.
There are just as many body fluids a-flowin', but the laughs are
rich and plentiful. ``Baseketball'' plays like a rookie who has a
great April, only to fizzle in the dog days of the pennant race.
Come back, Chris Farley. All is forgiven!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
