A2239 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-CHIMNEY-BOS &LR;      07-31 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CHIMNEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW VINE NOVEL HAS ALL THE HALLMARKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE CHIMNEY SWEEPER'S BOY 
By Barbara Vine 
Harmony Books, 344 pp., $24 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After best-selling novelist Gerald Candless dies at age 71 of a
heart attack, his browbeaten wife Ursula and their two smug
daughters, Hope and Sarah, try to piece together the facts of his
life. He was a difficult man, especially to his wife, whom he
bullied in life and cruelly mocked in his novels. But he smothered
his daughters with love and they adored him.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah, who teaches women's studies at the University of London,
decides to write her father's biography and soon discovers that his
life was a carefully constructed lie, that Gerald Candless wasn't
even Gerald Candless. He'd stolen his name from a dead child.
</P>
<P>
   This is the eighth non-mystery novel by the acclaimed and
prolific mystery writer Ruth Rendell, writing under the name
Barbara Vine. Fans of any or all of the seven previous books will
recognize in this novel many of the elements that make the Vine
books so engrossing. In ``The Chimney Sweeper's Boy,'' the past
haunts the present, neuroses abound, obsession flourishes, shameful
secrets unfold, suspense hovers overs the plot like the mist that
rolls over the Candlesses' isolated home on a cliff high above the
sea. There is a creepy, claustrophobic feel to this novel,
symbolized by an image from Candless's recurring dream, in which
he's trapped alone inside a tube of stone deep inside the earth,
its ends sealed with cement ``covered with fan-shaped prints where
hard hands had pressed it in _ from the inside.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chimney Sweeper's Boy'' explores the uncertain territory
that separates a writer's life from his fiction. The truth about
Gerald Candless lies in his books. He mined his own life for
material and wove his secrets into his plots. Sarah doggedly sets
about analyzing her father's work and interviewing people from his
past.
</P>
<P>
   One important clue to the mystery of Candless's identity turns
out to be a particular moth he chose as the logo for his books, one
with the Latin name Epichnopterix plumella, commonly known as the
chimney sweeper's boy, a small insect unusual in that it abstains
from sexual activity. Sarah is reminded that in Greek mythology the
butterfly or moth symbolized ``the spirit of man liberated from the
impurities of the flesh.'' By the time the moth wings its way into
the plot, and maybe even before, readers will have guessed that
Candless was homosexual, but that's only part of the secret that
compelled him to re-invent himself so elaborately.
</P>
<P>
   As Sarah digs into her father's past, Ursula mulls over her
memories of a long, unhappy marriage to a man who despised her. As
she recalls various incidents she begins to accept the truth about
her late husband, a truth that would have been obvious had she not
been blinded, at first by love, later by an indifference born of
pain. Candless has left his mark on his daughters, too. His
crushing, controlling love gave them strength to succeed in the
world, but crippled them emotionally. Both daughters are heavy
drinkers who have difficult relationships with men. There's plenty
of angst and suffering in this novel before it reaches its
not-exactly-happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah's relentless investigating brings her to the brink of the
truth, but the big question remains: ``What she didn't know is why
... he had taken on that new identity.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be unfair to reveal the answer, or the circumstances
under which the answer comes to light, and anyway, the revelation
is a bit of a disappointment. The real surprise of the book is that
Candless, who's portrayed as a perfectly awful human being, turns
out to have had a secret streak of kindness and decency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chimney Sweeper's Boy'' is about the process of writing
fiction, among other things. It's interesting to see Rendell
writing as Vine writing about a novelist who assumes another
identity, although just what it revels about Rendell, if anything,
remains a mystery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
