<HEADLINE>
SYMPATHETIC SKETCH OF FRENCH `FAMILLE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
UN AIR DE FAMILLE 
Directed by: Cedric Klapisch 
Screenplay by: Agnes Jaoui, Jean-Pierre Bacri, Klapisch 
Starring: Jaoui, Bacri, Jean-Pierre Daroussin, Catherine Frot,
Claire Maurier, Wladimir Yordanoff 
Running time: 107 minutes; subtitles 
Rating: Unrated 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bittersweet dramas about family dysfunction either get more
bitter or more sweet as they unload their recrimination-filled
baggage. Cedric Klapisch's ``Un Air de Famille'' moves in the
direction of sweetness. Not, however, sentimentally or with any
intention of providing any glib resolutions. Rather, as Klapisch
trains his camera on the unhappy members of a French brood gathered
for an after-hours birthday celebration in the family-owned
restaurant, the film moves to embrace its characters. They're
messed up in the usual ways, but Klapisch never makes the mistake
of letting himself or his film slide into contempt for the banality
of their shortcomings. ``Un Air de Famille'' likes its characters
and you will, too.
</P>
<P>
   You can sense the film's origin as a one-set play, although
Klapisch boldly fights claustrophobia by employing Cinemascope,
which means the characters always share the frame with something
else in the down-at-heels cafe _ a window, a jukebox, each other.
The family _ overbearing mom, rebel daughter, favorite son,
scapegoat son, and their respective spouses _ has lived in a state
of uneasy coexistence for years and you just know the fragile truce
is about to be shattered when they gather to celebrate the birthday
of the successful son's sweet but bullied wife.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the place is Le Pere Tranquille, a piece of black
humor since the clan's father is dead. He was regarded as an
amiable loser by his ambitious wife, who left him. But as seen in
flashback romping with the kids in bed after they pour into their
parents' bedroom, you can easily believe that the heart went out of
the family when the modestly regarded tranquil dad did. Although no
world-beater, he obviously made a go of the restaurant and
generated a degree of family happiness that has been harder and
harder to come by since the kids have grown older. Klapisch plays
the warm-hearted dad in flashback, and he becomes a character, too,
whose absence is felt.
</P>
<P>
   Claire Maurier's matriarch, callous and cruel, bludgeons
everybody into line and has guaranteed bad blood between her sons
by favoring one and downgrading the other. Wladimir Yordanoff's
Philippe is the businessman who works for a computer company, but
only, as his wife keeps reminding him, as the number four man in
the pecking order. He has just appeared on local television and
makes the mistake of fishing for compliments. It's a misstep for
which he pays quickly as his sister observes that he stuttered once
and his mother finds fault with his choice in neckties.
</P>
<P>
   His mother's lifelong favoritism has turned him into an
egocentric monster, whose sweet wife is only able to enjoy herself
on the rare occasions when she has a drink. Tonight is one such
occasion, and Catherine Frot expertly lets us imagine her life of
benign incarceration by the way she comes to life for a few minutes
when the waiter dances with her when her husband will not. He at
least still has his wife, which is more than Jean-Pierre Bacri's
glum proprietor can say. None of them are exactly bursting with
people skills, including Agnes Jaoui's sister. She tries to make
her lack of prospects at the age of 30 seem a triumphant rejection
of bourgeois shallowness, but she comes off as more lonely and
worried than she cares to show.
</P>
<P>
   The leads _ including Jean-Pierre Darroussin's clear-eyed
waiter, the whistle-blower on excess _ played their roles on stage
many times. Jaoui and Bacri wrote the play and have worked out with
Klapisch exactly how to reveal the corrosive family dynamic without
getting too explicit. The important things here are revealed in
facial expressions or small behavioral gestures, never in clumsily
expository dialogue. Klapisch's decision not to open up the drama
in the ways films usually open up plays was the right one. In the
end, the members of this neurotic family seem boxed in not by the
film's stage origins, but by their own but ironclad patterns. ``Un
Air de Famille'' is affecting because it seems wise and rueful, yet
compassionate and hopeful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
