<HEADLINE>
FAR RIGHT USING GAYS FOR TARGET PRACTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Until this week Rep. Frank Riggs, R-Calif., was
known nationally as a big supporter of swabbing pepper spray in the
eyes of chained young women.
</P>
<P>
   I call that very, very kinky for a guy who claims to be a
defender of morals and an enemy of coercion. The women were chained
to a stump in his office as part of a protest against his
pro-logging policies. Riggs said it was ``probably an appropriate
use of force.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Riggs has become known as the guy who wants to stick it in
the eye of San Francisco. He tacked an amendment on a Housing and
Urban Development spending bill that would prevent San Francisco
from using federal housing money in requiring contractors to
provide benefits for domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   I call that very, very perverted for a Republican who claims to
believe in local autonomy and decreasing the power of the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, there is one principle that overrides the Republican
belief in small government: Bash gays in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   If Democrats crafted a bill aimed specifically at punishing a
Republican district, they'd never hear the end of outrage from an
alleged small-government Gingrichite like Riggs. Riggs represents a
swath of Northern California that includes Mendocino, Sonoma and
Napa counties. If Democrats in the House wanted to make a surgical
strike on his district alone, they could ban federal funding
supporting the cloning of grapevines.
</P>
<P>
   It might pass. The sheeplike public hates cloning.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, we'd lose the wines that help us get through the
political news. Cloned vines resist the phylloxera that has ravaged
vineyards. We'd be cutting off our nose and bouquet to spite our
face.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Riggs is leaving California when his term runs out in
November. This anti-gay amendment is his way of saying goodbye,
like a finger waved from a U-Haul.
</P>
<P>
   Riggs will live in Virginia, where he already has a house. Rumor
has it that he wants to be a lobbyist, but after attacking
America's favorite city (according to three surveys this year)
he'll have to be a lobbyist for the pepper spray industry.
</P>
<P>
   When the House aims legislation at a specific city, it's usually
to give it some goodies, like nuclear submarine contracts to New
London, Conn. When it's intended to take something away from a
city, it's usually aimed at Mayor Marion Barry of Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But then Congress has a traditional role as ruler of Washington.
Now Congress is going to tell San Francisco what to do? We don't
listen to Washington politicians. They listen to us if they want to
raise money here.
</P>
<P>
   The state of California can't even tell San Francisco what to do
when it comes to marijuana, bilingual education and affirmative
action. Gov. Pete Wilson and Attorney General Dan Lungren, both
Republicans, aren't even allowed across the bridges without white
flags.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Supervisor Mark Leno thinks the Riggs provision
can be removed before the HUD bill passes the Senate, but he still
finds it unsettling, and not just because San Francisco could lose
up to $200 million in housing funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is part of a coordinated effort,'' he said. ``We're
at war. The target once again is us.''
</P>
<P>
   Leno means gays, and everyone from Trent Lott to Reggie White to
Frank Riggs has been taking shots. It's a pretty transparent effort
to mobilize hard-core right-wing voters for the November election,
so the Republicans can keep their majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
   It's not democracy in action. It's demonization in action.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago Bill Clinton's advisers kept saying, ``It's the
economy, stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the economy is pretty good, and someone seems to be telling
Republicans, ``It's the gays, stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Scapegoats have been useful in politics in the past, but at the
cost of hurting a lot of people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a good time to have a Democratic president with a
partners problem of his own. Riggs said Americans ``want leaders
who respect and support, rather than dishonor, the sanctity of
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   It's likely he wasn't just attacking gay marriages, but had one
particular heterosexual marriage in mind, too.
</P>
<P>
   As Leno says, ``It's all a big chess game. They make one move on
this side of the board, and then a move on the other side of the
board.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Starr side of the board is reaching endgame, but the
Republicans aren't doing quite as well on the side of the board
where gays are being used as pawns.
</P>
<P>
   You know, Riggs is a total amateur when it comes to crafting
legislation aimed at a specific city. The master is right here in
San Francisco's City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   When Mayor Willie Brown was speaker of the California Assembly
he was always figuring out ways to tailor bills so benefits only
went to cities that were also counties _ meaning one city, San
Francisco. Those were the days.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he can invent a special tax for Republican congressmen
coming here on vacation. He could call it a user's fee.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Riggs and his ilk are doing right now. They're using
us.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
