<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-EVER-AFTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EVER AFTER': A TOUGHER, BRAVER CINDERELLA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
EVER AFTER 
Directed by: Andy Tennant 
Screenplay by: Susannah Grant, Tennant, Rick Parks 
Starring: Drew Barrymore, Anjelica Huston, Dougray Scott, Patrick
Godfrey, Megan Dodds, Melanie Lynskey, Timothy West, Judy Parfitt,
Jeroen Krabbe, Lee Ingleby, Jeanne Moreau 
Running time: 122 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (momentary strong language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't let the fairytale look of ``Ever After'' fool you. Beneath
its 16th century costumes and medieval walled chateau shimmering in
the Dordogne, there's a decidedly modern sensibility to this
richly-textured but tough-minded retelling of the Cinderella story.
Soft, pure and beautiful as Drew Barrymore looks beneath her pale
soot-covered skin, she's no passive victim. Part of the fun of
watching the tongue-in-cheek modernity comes from watching her
rescue the prince who comes to rescue her, then handily take on the
job of extricating herself from danger a second time as he arrives
breathless on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   The ingredients of the myth are there, and so is the romance,
but they've been rejiggered and rearranged around the feminist
spirit of Barrymore's Danielle, as the girl behind the legend is
called. Although she has been relegated to servant status after he
father dies and her upwardly mobile stepmother takes over, she's no
docile drudge. She was educated by her lordly and loving father
(Jeroen Krabbe), who literally dies with his boots on shortly after
introducing Danielle to her new stepmother and stepsisters, but not
before teaching her swordsmanship and giving her the run of his
library. At a key juncture, she quotes nimbly _ and appropriately _
from Thomas More's ``Utopia.''
</P>
<P>
   Dougray Scott's prince, meanwhile, is a bit of a rebel himself,
and is attracted to the spunky Danielle _ who beans him with an
apple when she catches him stealing a horse from her family's
stable as he flees an arranged marriage. Not that things go that
swimmingly for them. If the French countrified Cinderella can do
with a status makeover, the prince, hobbled by a few snobbish bad
habits, needs a soul makeover. Nor does Barrymore's do-it-yourself
Cinderella rely on magic dispensed by a fairy godmother. This a
real-world Cinderella _ or at least as realistic as a glossy
Hollywood feminist costume romance can get.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while not operating from much of a power base, Danielle
is not without allies. She gets aid and sympathy from an amusing
addition to the legend, Leonardo da Vinci (Patrick Godfrey), who
knows quality when he sees it, previews the Mona Lisa for the
prince, comes close to literally walking on water, then springs
Danielle from a dungeon. The final piece of the picture, brightly
put in place under Andy Tennant's direction, involves Anjelica
Huston's gratifyingly faceted stepmother, rescued from campy
cliche. The stepsisters _ Megan Dodd's icy-hearted, beautiful,
spoiled favorite and Melanie Lynskey's chunkier, kinder,
second-class-citizen sibling are another plus. ``Ever After'' is
fresh and surprising and sympathetic, even in places you don't
expect it to be. In a formula-laden summer, its gorgeousness and,
even more important, its rethinkings, are a delight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
