<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY AND MADNESS FILL `THE WELL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE WELL 
Directed by: Samantha Lang 
Screenplay by: Laura Jones (novel: Elizabeth Jolley) 
Starring: Miranda Otto, Pamela Rabe, Paul Chubb, Frank Wilson,
Steve Jacobs, Genevieve Lemon 
Running time: 102 minutes 
Rated: Unrated 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Psychosexual and geographical eeriness intersect seductively and
intriguingly in ``The Well,'' a highly charged debut film from
Australia's Samantha Lang. It's a steadily involving pas de deux
between a gaunt spinster played by Pamela Rabe and a nymphet played
by Miranda Otto. Each woman is needy, each is intense. The playing
out of their gravitational attraction against the dislocating
effects of a remote Australian outback setting is expressed in a
remarkable combination of the spare, the rugged, and the
otherworldly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; if,,.333l &LR;  Pale and contained, Otto's Katherine doesn't look
like much as she slinks into the isolated farm to which she has
been sent from the latest of a long string of correctional
institutions. But she's not as passive and retrograde as she seems.
She's just being cautious. It doesn't take her long to notice that
she has freed something long repressed in Rabe's lonely middle-aged
woman living with her difficult aged father. After hiring
Katherine, Rabe's Hester takes a shine to her and decides she wants
her around permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Bribing Katherine with gifts, and not seeming to notice or care
that the housework goes increasingly undone, Hester sells the farm
for cash after her father dies, moves them into a small house on
the edge of the property, and plans trips to Europe and New York.
She's again oblivious to the shifts in Katherine's moods and
expressions as the younger woman shuttles between naivete and
cunning and the onset of power plays designed to see just how much
she can get from Hester.
</P>
<P>
   After Katherine insists on some breathing room and the chance to
pursue some social life away from Hester, an accident involving a
stranger changes things. Katherine and Hester move from sharing a
concealed relationship to harboring a secret that could plunge them
both into serious trouble. What had been the onset of erotic
stirrings becomes colored by new complications and pressures. The
mood turns from playful and enticingly suggestive to something
darker as their haven suddenly seems less safe and stable than it
did.
</P>
<P>
   Having been drawn together, the women draw apart, retreat into
separate realities. Simple seduction is replaced by manipulation
and desperation. The atmosphere becomes threatening. Shimmer is
replaced by harshness, the line between mystery and madness blurs
as the film takes the metaphorical plunge suggested by its title.
The film's taut contours and subliminal rumblings will invoke
comparisons to early Jane Campion, but Lang is a gifted and
immensely promising filmmaker who can stand on her own as she
tightens the screws and draws us into the febrile duet between two
riveting actresses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
