<HEADER>
A2259 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-31 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUID PRO QUO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Massachusetts' legislative session rushes to its close,
housing activist Thomas Callahan checks daily on the status of the
insurance tax cut bill. On every visit, he bumps into industry
lobbyists doing the same thing: ``It was scary. It was really
scary,'' he says of the lobbyists' constant presence.
</P>
<P>
   It may be even scarier for the lobbyists to keep running into
Callahan. Because of the tenacity of activists like him, state
legislators appear on the verge of approving a law requiring
insurance companies to make a significant contribution to a
community reinvestment fund in exchange for significant tax relief.
The law is believed to be precedent-setting nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday around noon, conference committee members shook hands
on this deal: To get some $50 million in tax relief, life insurance
firms, as well as property and casualty firms, must invest a total
of $200 million _ or $100 million from each industry sector _ in
direct loans for affordable housing in low- and moderate-income
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Senate Ways and Means Chairman Stanley C. Rosenberg,
(D-Amherst), who participated in conference committee
deliberations, said he is optimistic the agreement would become
law.
</P>
<P>
   However, state Representative Peter Larkin (D-Pittsfield), who
cochairs the joint legislative Taxation Committee and also took
part in the conference committee, was more cautious, saying ``there
are still bumps in the road.'' The conference committee reconvened
to smooth them out.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the House worked to lower the dollar amount of
the industry commitment. The activists got as far as they did
because the Senate was on their side.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Rosenberg, that includes Senate President Thomas
Birmingham; state Senator Warren Tolman (D-Watertown), who cochairs
the joint legislative Taxation Committee; and state Senator Dianne
Wilkerson (D-Boston), who chaired the Insurance Committee until she
was removed from her leadership position after pleading guilty last
year to failure to file tax returns. (Despite personal problems,
Wilkerson hung in to support the community investment piece of the
bill.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is, the insurance companies are making a significant
investment in communities across Massachusetts. In return, we'll be
levelling the playing field for in-state and out-of-state
insurers,'' says Tolman.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 20 years, Massachusetts-based insurance companies
have been angling for a tax cut. Finally, their turn at bat came
up.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the industry wanted to pony up community investment
money in return for a tax cut. But after shrewdly calculating the
politics, John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. chairman Stephen
L. Brown decided to play ball with activists like Callahan.
</P>
<P>
   That created a rift with the property and casualty firms, which
wanted to bully past the community folks. But ultimately, Brown's
willingness to apply finesse, not muscle, seems to have paved the
way for the long-awaited industry tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Hancock is not acting on pure altruism. On the
national front, there have been rumblings about bringing other
financial services, besides banks, into the community reinvestment
realm.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry wants no part of a law that might link
any company acquisitions to community reinvestment requirements.
So, working out a deal with local community activists became the
preferred scenario.
</P>
<P>
   The community investment commitment makes business sense, as
well as social policy sense. The insurance companies know how to
make pooled investments. This way, they are all in it together.
When the fine print of the bill's final version is analyzed, some
companies could be bigger winners than others.
</P>
<P>
   But as Callahan sees it: ``If this bill passes with at least a
couple hundred million dollars in new investment, this will be the
beginning of a new relationship between community organizations in
this state and the insurance industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, it would signal the start of a relationship,
(itals)period(unitals). And that is win-win for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Joan Vennochi is a columnist with the Globe Business section.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
