A2267 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEKETBALL-SOUTH-PAR     07-31 2246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEKETBALL-SOUTH-PARK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BASEKETBALL' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 IN THE POST-POLITICALLY CORRECT ZONE WITH `SOUTH PARK' and &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JONATHAN VAN METER  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    Long before ``South Park'' became the national phenomenon that
it is today, David Zucker had approached its creators _ Trey Parker
and Matt Stone _ with ``Baseketball,'' the first film he had
written in seven years.
 &HT;    Back in 1980, Zucker and his brother Jerry, outsiders in
Hollywood, had become something of a sensation with their first
movie, ``Airplane!'' _ a classic, with its memorably offensive
one-liners and ridiculous sight gags.
 &HT;    Over the years since, Zucker had grown frustrated by a climate
that seemed increasingly afraid of the outrageous, taboo-busting
humor that made ``Airplane!'' so fresh and funny. He sat out much
of the '90s before finally writing ``Baseketball,'' a goofy comedy
that aspired to be a satire about our national sports culture.
 &HT;    ``I think the best thing that happened to me,'' Zucker says,
``was to have Matt and Trey come along and say, `Well, you know,
``Baseketball'' is a great idea for a movie, but it's tame.' I just
went bananas. I was so embarrassed.''
 &HT;    ``We went to a couple of read-throughs,'' Stone says, ``and we
peppered a few lines with our humor, and it would get a big laugh.
We felt we had nothing to lose, so Trey and I started going off:
`This is a guy's movie. It's a sports parody. This is what every
guy lives through _ the whole sports, buddy, triumph-glory bull _
and we're making fun of a lot of that, and this is the way guys
talk.''
 &HT;    Zucker, who was a fan of Parker and Stone's student films and
had worked with them on a couple of shorts, had originally wanted
Parker to direct ``Baseketball,'' but he turned it down because he
was in the midst of starting work on ``South Park.''
 &HT;    One day, when Zucker and a producer were casting the film _
looking through a pile of head shots _ the producer said, ``What
about Trey Parker?'' Zucker thought it was an inspired idea, not
realizing that the producer meant the other Trey Parker _ a
modestly successful character actor. No matter. The mixup had
turned on a light: Zucker could hire Parker and Stone to play the
two buddies around whom the film turns and, for the same price,
exploit the spontaneous shenanigans that lie at the heart of the
Parker-Stone bond.
 &HT;    Because the two know each other and their idiosyncrasies so
well, Parker, 28, and Stone, 27, suggested things that no one else
could have thought of, things that predictably racheted up the
gross-and-shocking quotient. In one scene, for example, the two of
them are talking in the dugout and Parker is chewing a chaw of
tobacco. It was his idea to give it to Stone, who puts the tobacco
in his mouth and keeps right on chewing.
 &HT;    Jenny McCarthy, the former star of MTV's ``Singled Out,'' plays
a sort of young Zsa Zsa Gabor in ``Baseketball.'' No stranger to
grossness herself, McCarthy once posed for a shoe ad sitting on the
toilet reading a newspaper. ``They're kind of like any guy next
door _ just with a whole lot of talent,'' she says. ``We try to
battle each other to see who can talk the most disgusting. They're
so in line with my kind of humor, which is where I hope comedy is
going. They did a lot of improv in 'Baseketball.' It has a lot of
'South Park' touches to it.''
 &HT;    If ``Baseketball,'' which opens July 31, is a hit, it will be in
no small part because of Parker and Stone, who are in the odd,
perhaps unprecedented, position of being famous unknowns.
 &HT;    ``They come to it with the aura of their success,'' Zucker says.
``They have all that cachet because they're the authors of `South
Park.' People are already set to cheer for them. But they're
behind-the-scenes guys.''
 &HT;    Shortly before the release of `Baseketball,' I ask Stone if he's
looking forward to becoming a movie star. ``I'm totally
unprepared,'' he says. ``I hate the fact that I can't walk down the
street already without people looking at me. I went to this cheesy
bar last night and no 21-year-old Hollywood person was coming up
and going: `Heeey! Matt Stone!' I had the best time just sinking
into obscurity again, which is especially hard to do in LA.'' He
heaves a big sigh. ``We're going to Las Vegas this weekend, and I
know it's just going to be awful, walking around with everyone
yelling: `Hey! South Park! Can we get a picture?'''
 &HT;    No one could ever have guessed that ``South Park'' _ a crude,
funny, disturbing, adorable, obnoxious little cartoon on a cable
channel that millions of Americans still can't get _ would become
so huge so fast. What made the success of ``South Park'' different
from that of other adult animated series like ``The Simpsons'' and
``Beavis and Butthead'' is that it happened all at once.
 &HT;    The show made its debut last August and by December it was the
highest-rated show ever, by far, on Comedy Central _ as well as the
inspiration for the top-selling T-shirt in America. Parker and
Stone employ scatological humor fairly regularly; last year's
Christmas special, for example, featured a piece of talking,
singing feces named Mr. Hankey the Christmas Poo.
 &HT;    The most striking thing about ``South Park,'' which centers on a
group of boys in third grade, however, is its ability to pluck the
strings of fear and hatred in a surprisingly serious way. The show
plays with phobias in lines such as, ``Your mom's a Jew,'' ``Could
we get rid of all the Mexicans?'' and ``Asian culture has plagued
our fragile earth for many years. We must end it.''
 &HT;    These lines _ usually spoken by Parker and Stone and coming out
of the mouths of cartoon children _ are truly subversive. And yet,
nestled amid all the carnage (the same character dies a bloody
death in every episode) and hate speech, there is always a moral _
often of the touchy-feely, can't-we-all-just-get-along variety.
 &HT;    One of their best shows _ and Parker and Stone's favorite _ is
titled ''Big Gay Al's Big Gay Boat Ride,'' and features the
exaggerated, lisping character known as Big Gay Al. Stan, one of
the third-grade characters on the show, finds out that his dog is
gay and suffers endless mortification at the hands of his friends,
who shout, ``Stan's dog's a homo!''
 &HT;    Eventually, Stan learns about tolerance from Big Gay Al, and in
the end, all is well in South Park. What often keeps the show from
being offensive is this kind of sweetness _ and that it's funny.
 &HT;    In a recent, dicier episode, the four main characters travel to
China for a dodge-ball tournament. The Chinese announcers are drawn
in what can only be described as cartoon yellowface, while their
voices mock Asians speaking bad English. The twist is that the
Chinese announcers are making fun of American accents and ``big
eyes.'' It's a tricky game Parker and Stone are playing, and it
doesn't always work. ``That was a deep one,'' Stone says.
 &HT;    ``It's totally offensive. But we did it in a way to make a
point: turning it around. So it's us doing Chinese accents, making
fun of the Chinese, who are doing accents making fun of Americans.
It's just to say, `Who cares?'''
 &HT;    Good question, though a more precise inquiry might be: Does
everyone get it? Are some of the ``South Park'' fans simply
laughing at Jew jokes or goofy Chinese accents or gay stereotypes,
without the layers of irony that exist at the point of creation?
Probably. As with all comedy that dares to articulate the things
that people don't for fear of sounding mean or hateful, there's
always a chance that it might be dangerously misinterpreted _ or
misused.
 &HT;    Or, as they say, What about the children? Stone, who is Jewish,
says that people do get it, especially children _ who technically
aren't supposed to be watching. (The show comes on at 10 p.m.) He
cites, for example, a child who wrote to him that when he and his
classmates reenacted the Rosa Parks story in school, they imagined
the bus driver to be Cartman, the character on the show who says
the most horrible things.
 &HT;    Point: Kids know that Cartman is not be emulated, even though
repeating Cartman's offensive lines for laughs in school the next
day has become an adolescent pastime.
 &HT;    In some ways, it's like the Howard Stern debate of a few years
back: If Howard Stern is a good guy _ not the racist, sexist
homophobe his radio character so often is _ isn't it OK for him to
pretend that he's a terrible person? Just for laughs? The
difference, Parker and Stone would argue, is that their jokes have
context, where Stern's don't.
 &HT;    ``It comes back to telling a story,'' Stone says. ``The
combination of sweetness and real emotion and this totally bizarre
post-politically correct kind of brutality. Without one, you can't
have the other. That's how you suck people in _ with character and
story and emotion. We take a totally weird idea and try to mold it
into an afterschool-special kind of story.''
 &HT;    He mentions a scene that takes place at a football game. ``We
had the announcer say, 'Oh, I haven't seen a Jew run like that
since 1938.' Just a horrible thing to say. But there's a history of
sports announcers getting busted for things like that. The other
announcer says: `Dude! You can't say that! That's not cool!' If you
did that in the wrong way it would be very offensive. But I think
it's obvious when you watch `South Park' that we're saying we know
this is a stereotype and we're messing with that. When you don't
wink at the audience you really are guilty of perpetrating
something.''
 &HT;    One reason it is hard to be offended by the Parker-Stone
sensibility is that they are so earnest.
 &HT;    ``As bizarre as it is,'' says Parker of the show, ``there's this
overlying sweetness to it all. Like: `Hey, you know what? The
world's all right.' And I think that's because Matt and I are
really very happy and optimistic. It wouldn't work if we were
really dark, coffee-drinking, leather-jacket-wearing guys. It would
just be us making all these crass remarks about the world and it
would get old.''
 &HT;    Because ``Baseketball'' is the first Parker-Stone enterprise to
hit the street since ``South Park,'' there is intense excitement
among the show's legion of fans.
 &HT;    ``I haven't laughed that hard (intentionally) during a movie
since I saw `Airplane!' for the first time,'' wrote one young
critic on the Internet who saw an early test screening in
California. ``The movie was not (expletive) P.C.!!!!!! . . . This
movie is incredibly offensive. Many will hate it and will want it
banned.''
 &HT;    Part of what appeals about Parker and Stone is their spirit of
youthful rebellion, their desire, as Stone puts it, ``to flip off
the Man.''
 &HT;    Doug Herzog, the president and CEO of Comedy Central and the
person responsible for putting the show on the air, has given this
a lot of thought.
 &HT;    ``One of my late-night theories,'' he says, ``is that Matt and
Trey grew up on MTV, David Letterman - they're cool. But they've
been programmed to be cool. What they've never really had, because
their coolness is sort of marketed to them, is something to rebel
against. They don't get it in their rock music. I think you could
probably make the argument that `South Park' is rebellious. It's
something that your parents might not understand.''
 &HT;    Parker and Stone are members of a group of enlightened young
white guys who grew up being sensitive as a matter of course. Part
of what it means to be a New Young White Guy is to be assiduously
not racist, sexist or homophobic _ which is why Parker and Stone
give themselves permission to make insensitive jokes: They know
they're kidding. What they're rebelling against is being told to be
sensitive.
 &HT;    But where Herzog sees healthy rebellion, many critics see
immaturity. And while there is an undeniable intelligence at work,
the most disturbing thing about ``South Park'' isn't so much the
show itself as the horse it rode in on, what you might call Creep
Culture.
 &HT;    ``The Howard Stern Show,'' ''Beavis and Butthead,'' ``Dumb and
Dumber'' and ``South Park'' are all populated by jerks who say mean
things and treat people badly. You get the sense that the creative
minds behind these ventures were all picked on as children and _
deep down _ learned to identify with their tormentors. Only now, as
adults, hidden behind the characters they invent, can they get back
at the bully.
 &HT;    What pushes ``South Park'' above the fray is that the characters
Parker and Stone have invented are third-grade boys _ a group for
whom such obnoxious behavior is to be expected, perhaps even
forgiven.
 &HT;     c.1998 Jonathan Van Meter  
