<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND WIN FOR ARNOLD VW ADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In May, critics converge on the south of France to salute the
year's best movies at the famous Cannes Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   In late June and early July, it's the advertising industry's
turn, and this year, one of the judges at the 45th International
Advertising Festival was Ron Lawner, a managing partner and chief
creative officer at Arnold Communications of Boston, New England's
largest ad agency.
</P>
<P>
   As one of 23 judges, and the only American on the panel, it was
Lawner's job to sort through 7,000 entries. The goal was to honor
the best print advertising in the world.
</P>
<P>
   (A separate panel of judges reviewed TV ads.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was gruelling work at first,'' says Lawner, who conceded
that he later relieved the stresses of judging by tooling along the
Riviera in a rented Porsche.
</P>
<P>
   For several days, though, Lawner sat in a room by himself as he
sifted through large bound portfolios of ads.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the thousands of ads was marked with a bar code, much
like a box of Cheerios at a supermarket, and Lawner was equipped
with a scanner.
</P>
<P>
   Lawner would review each ad, sweep over the page with his
scanner, and then punch in a score from 1 to 9.
</P>
<P>
   After several days of working alone, the judges were brought
together to compare notes and pick finalists in such categories as
car, clothing, and computer ads.
</P>
<P>
   In reviewing thousands of print ads, Lawner noted several
trends. In a global economy, the sight gag has become the Esperanto
of marketing, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of words and text, the lingua franca of the pitch is
fast becoming a visual vernacular _ a simple, humorous image that
can be instantly understood whether viewed in Hong Kong, Hollywood,
or Holliston.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get the message right away,'' Lawner says.
</P>
<P>
   One of his favorite ads was for Jaguar, the British luxury car.
The company is promoting a new model with a souped-up V-8 engine,
and a print ad from Ogilvy &AMP; Mather shows an enlarged photo of the
silver jaguar that serves as the car's hood ornament; in the ad,
the jaguar is straining at a chain leash.
</P>
<P>
   An ad for Burger King's ``fiery fries'' that ran in Singapore
also got high marks from the judges.
</P>
<P>
   Devised by Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, a graphic shows a french fry
standing vertically with one end daubed in ketchup. The effect is
to evoke the image of a match catching fire.
</P>
<P>
   ```Keep it simple' should absolutely be the first rule of
advertising,'' Lawner says.
</P>
<P>
   Lawner applied that rule when he helped create print ads to
launch the new version of the Volkswagen Beetle this spring.
</P>
<P>
   One ad shows a yellow Beetle and the message, ``If you sold your
soul in the '80s, here's your chance to buy it back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Less flower, more power,'' says another Beetle ad.
</P>
<P>
   These ads were among those reviewed by the Cannes judges, though
Lawner recused himself from voting on his own work.
</P>
<P>
   Over several days, thousands of ads were winnowed to two
finalists for a Grand Prix, the festival's award for the finest
print advertising of the year. (A Grand Prix was also awarded to
the best TV ad campaign.)
</P>
<P>
   In print, the finalists were Arnold's ads for VW and ads for
Apple Computer Inc. Created by TBWA Chiat/Day of California, the
Apple ads feature photos of celebrities such as Picasso, Gandhi,
and Bob Dylan. The tag line: ``Think different.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first face off between Arnold and Chiat/Day.
Not long ago, the agencies were the two finalists in the
competition for Apple's advertising account.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lawner, Arnold was Apple's choice until Apple
founder Steve Jobs stepped in, overruled the decision of his aides,
and gave the business to Chiat/Day.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, Chiat/Day created a Super Bowl ad for Apple
that is widely regarded as one of the best TV ads ever, and perhaps
Jobs gave the account to Chiat/Day out of loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   (In that old Apple ad, the ambiance is heavy with sinister
conformity and 1984 menace. As drones watch, a Big Brother figure
intones his new world order over a huge TV screen. A woman athlete
revolts and in a blow for individualism, she hurls a hammer,
shattering the TV screen and Big Brother's world.)
</P>
<P>
   Given the recent rivalry between the two agencies, Lawner says
of the Grand Prix showdown at Cannes, ``I sure didn't want to lose
to Chiat/Day.''
</P>
<P>
   He needn't have worried. The Grand Prix now sits near the door
of his office.
</P>
<P>
   Of his summer vacation in Cannes, Lawner says it would be hard
to top his experience: ``First-time festival. First-time judge.
First-time Grand Prix. I'm not going back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
