<HEADER>
A2280 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FLOYD-BOS &LR;      07-31 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FLOYD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TIM FLOYD, LOOKS ARE DECEIVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The older man sat to the left of the dais, nodding his
approval as Tim Floyd gave his first United Center press
conference. Camera flashes lit the room like fireworks. There was
plenty of noise: turning notebook pages, clicking minirecorders,
and the constant murmur of a whispering crowd. And then you looked
at the older man, Don Haskins. He was watching and, most important,
listening.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd is a complex man, certainly. But if you could give themes
to humans as if they were feature films, the essence of Floyd's
story would be: how to trust what you hear over what you see.
</P>
<P>
   Haskins learned that lesson in 1977. While many have scoffed at
the idea of Floyd _ a career college coach _ taking over for Phil
Jackson as coach of the six-time NBA champion Bulls, Haskins coolly
leaned back at last week's press conference _ where Floyd was
introduced as the Bulls' director of basketball operations and,
assuming Jackson sticks to his retirement plans, next coach _ and
heard Floyd thank him for ``giving me a chance when I probably
wasn't ready.''
</P>
<P>
   A 22-year-old Floyd certainly wasn't ready to be teaching any
courses on legibility. He had just finished his career at Louisiana
Tech. He was looking for a job as a graduate assistant, so he wrote
the legendary Haskins at the University of Texas-El Paso. When he
was 12, Floyd's father told him that Haskins was someone to follow
if he ever wanted to know how to coach. Floyd wrote Haskins at
UTEP. Haskins saw the letter and nearly crumpled it so he could
dunk it in a trash can. The handwriting was terrible, so bad that
Haskins would say later he thought Floyd was a little, well, dim
intellectually. But the coach read what the young man had to say,
and it made sense. He also noticed that Tim Floyd was the son of
the late Lee Floyd, former coach at Southern Mississippi. A chance
was given. For the next nine seasons, UTEP basketball would not be
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Trust what you hear over what you see. And not how you hear it,
either. Floyd has a thick accent, shaped by Hattiesburg, Miss., and
refined by Louisiana, Texas, Idaho, and Iowa. He may talk ball with
a drawl, but don't let his quirky dialect fool you. He knows his
subject. The Celtics know that better than most teams, many of them
skeptical of this 44-year-old man who is known to be a fishing
buddy of Bulls general manager Jerry Krause.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to evaluating college players and evaluating
them for the NBA, I find that he's one of the best guys to talk
to,'' Celtics general manager Chris Wallace said. ``He's always on
the mark when I ask him about players. I can't think of a time when
he hasn't come up with an accurate assessment of a guy. I think he
is a very bright person, and not just in the sense of basketball
and the strategic points of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe his travels have something to do with that. Wallace calls
him a ``by-the-bootstraps guy.'' That's because Floyd quickly
became Haskins's top recruiter at a place where drawing local
talent is not always easy. ``Kids are not going to be in the local
barber shop talking about how they want to play at UTEP,'' Wallace
said. Floyd realized that, too. So he hit the road, tapping into
Los Angeles and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   After nine years of being Haskins's top man at UTEP _ Tim
Hardaway and Greg Foster passed through town while he was there _
Floyd moved on to Idaho for two seasons as head coach. And the
University of New Orleans after that.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, it should be clear that Floyd never fell into the
path illuminated by television lights and automatic exposure. While
he was in New Orleans, word had traveled around campus that he was
looking for players. One day a lanky kid who had been packing
groceries showed up at his office. The name: Ervin Johnson. The
history (abridged version): He went from a novice at New Orleans to
a millionaire with the Milwaukee Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year,'' Krause said of Floyd, ``I watched his team win
even though he didn't have a player over 6-5.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Floyd got to Iowa State, his reputation had grown
among college coaches. He was good, the new guy in Ames. How good?
They would find out later when his Iowa State Cyclones won the
school's first postseason tournament title. You know that the
Celtics wanted to hire Kansas coach Roy Williams when they thought
Rick Pitino wasn't interested in the job. What you may not know is
that many observers of the Big Eight and later the Big 12 thought
Floyd was the best coach in that league.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Floyd and Haskins and Krause and Wallace all have to know
that the critics will have a ``but ...'' for this. Ames, Iowa, is
not Chicago. There's a big difference at shooting guard between
former Cyclone Fred Hoiberg and current Bull Michael Jordan _ who
has said he will play for no one other than Jackson. Floyd has been
annoyed with television and newspapers in Iowa; wait until he feels
the heat of two major dailies in Chicago, a couple of all-sports
radio stations, and a crowd of TV and radio outlets as well as
suburban publications. And, really, will Jordan play for him? If
not, Floyd may have to deal with a different theme in 1998-99: How
to replace a legend?
</P>
<P>
   ``If all their players don't come back, he's really not dealing
with the champion Chicago Bulls,'' Pitino said. ``If they don't
come back, he's like any other coach coming in to rebuild a
program. I know Tim Floyd and I respect him. He is a very good
judge of talent. He has to come in and carve his own niche.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe David Stern doesn't want to hear this, but there is a
chance Jordan liked what he heard about and/or from Floyd. Teams
are not supposed to communicate with their players during the
lockout, but Bulls chairman Jerry Reinsdorf was seen leaving
Jordan's Chicago office the day before Floyd was hired. There's a
chance Reinsdorf spoke to Jordan about Floyd's positives and that
Jordan listened. Listening. A very important part of Floyd's next
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to Kentucky, it was different because I was the
Knick coach going to Kentucky,'' Pitino said. ``This is the coach
at Iowa State coming to the Bulls. He has already done a good thing
by saying he didn't want to change that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino was referring to Floyd's assertion that he would like to
employ the triangle offense. Defense? Not a problem. In a land of
88-79 NBA scores, Floyd will fit in. A Haskins disciple is always
taught defense first.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs from day one that some were willing to give
Floyd a chance. He was speaking late in his press conference when a
reporter identified herself as a proud Iowa Hawkeye, the antithesis
of an Iowa State Cyclone. Floyd said he wouldn't hold her alma
mater against her and then cracked, ``But I may have to speak a
little slower for you.'' Laughter all around. The older man was
chuckling, too. This was progress, because a room full of people
were simply responding to what they heard, not what they saw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
