A2281 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     07-31 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF GROWS MAINE BANK FAR FROM THE BIG CITY'S GLARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big city doesn't do much for banker Bill Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan has quietly built Peoples Heritage Financial Group into New
England's fourth-largest banking company, growing business in the
region's suburban and rural areas and striking very friendly merger
deals.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples, based in Portland, Maine, has grown to become a big
fish in smaller New England banking ponds: Maine and New Hampshire.
When it hit Massachusetts two years ago, the point of entry was
Haverhill.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples made one of its biggest deals of all this month,
acquiring Springfield Institution for Savings for $428 million to
spread into Western Massachusetts. The acquisition will boost
Peoples's assets, just $4.3 billion at the end of 1996, to about
$12 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've done this well in that people view us as a bank
that cares about being a community bank,'' said Ryan, who left a
quickly deteriorating Bank of New England in 1989 to become the
heir apparent at Peoples.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't make Peoples any threat to Fleet Financial Group or
BankBoston Corp. Even the $20 billion of assets at number three
Citizens Financial Group would cast a large shadow over the
company. But People's has managed to grow quickly in part by posing
as the hometown banking alternative in a lot of places.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples touts its community bank sensibilities as the big
competitive advantage in rural and small city markets. But it's
mergers that has given the company its real bulk. Before its deal
in Springfield, Peoples had bought CFX Corp. of Keene, N.H., for
$627 million in April. It acquired Maine's largest insurance agency
and another Portland bank last year. In 1996, it acquired Family
Bancorp in Haverhill and Bank of New Hampshire Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan has been a persuasive buyer because he can pay in the hot
currency of Peoples stock and allows the sellers to keep their
institution's name and local presence. Better than that, top
executives keep their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception on the part of the borrower is that they are
doing business with a local bank,'' said analyst Tucker Anthony
analyst James Ackor, based in Portland, Maine. ``They've eaten
Fleet's and Keycorp's lunch up here because they are the local
bank.''
</P>
<P>
   But all that local presence and executive employment means
Peoples can't cover takeover premiums by slashing so deeply into
the expenses of newly acquired banks. The typical cost savings in a
Peoples deal is targeted at 25 percent, well below reductions of up
to 40 percent or more in the most brutal consoldiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to consolidate back office operations but we always
leave the face-to-face customer people intact,'' said Ryan. Chief
executives almost always count as customer people.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of optimum cost savings, Peoples pushes its ability to
quickly push more business through its newly acquired franchises.
Usually Peoples can add some services such as trust offerings,
business lending and third-party auto credit.
</P>
<P>
   It can be a risky propostion, pushing hard to increase business
in a hot economy. But Ryan insists the products and services being
pushed are low- or no-risk compared to the commercial real estate
loans that came crashing down around similar ``earn-out''
strategies in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said there are no blanket expectations for fast ``revenue
enhancements'' and did not dislose targets for individual banks he
had purchased.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said Peoples has estimated it can boost business in
Springfield by $2.3 million after taxes next year and by $4.7
million in 2000. The target at CFX is $5.1 million, after taxes,
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples may own a big piece of the northern New England banking
market today, but it was just another little struggling thrift in
the early 1990s. Peoples stock, which finished Thursday at 23 1/16,
traded as low as a split-adjusted 1 1/8 in the depths of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   It recovered slowly and later got into other business lines. The
development of small business commercial lending helped diversify
business and commanded higher loan interest rates than consumer
products.
</P>
<P>
   In part, Peoples had a chance to expand aggressively throughout
the small cities and rural areas of the north because a larger and
more powerful bank that had been following exactly that strategy
did an about-face.
</P>
<P>
   Keycorp of Albany, N.Y., took a big-bank tact and merged with
Society Corp. of Cleveland, where the combined institution is now
headquartered.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said he has no particular merger ambitions today, but few
people expect him to sit still. The best possible merger fits may
be one of two Vermont banks, Chittenden Corp. or BankNorth Group
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Both banks are based in Burlington but have branches in central
Massachusetts, an area between Springfield and Haverhill that
Peoples would eventually need to cover.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect to see him near Boston. Analysts, competitors and
Ryan himself agree the People's plan won't do nearly as well in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan insists he doesn't have any end-game plan in mind to sell
Peoples. But a moment later he leaves the door wide open to
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the strategy of community banking will still have a
niche in the near future,'' he said. ``But with all the
consoldiation in banking, only time will tell. If a giant bank from
somewhere consolidates the rest of New England, will there sitll be
a need for community banking. I think it's an unanswered
question.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
