<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLONS NOT STARTING TO TAKE JOB FOR GRANTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ One of Pete Carroll's assets as a coach is
his ability to convince veterans like Ferric Collons that they're
in a dogfight for a job.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they might not be.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want guys getting complacent and comfortable with
what's going on,'' said the Patriots coach. ``I wouldn't mind them
not knowing what's going on. What I'm pleased with is that we're
creating great competition. You see it everywhere on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   He's getting it at receiver, where Vincent Brisby and Shawn
Jefferson are battling for the spot opposite Terry Glenn. He's
getting it further down on the receiver depth chart, where Anthony
Ladd, Tony Simmons, and Tony Gaiter are all battling for a spot.
</P>
<P>
   He's getting it at fullback, where Tony Carter, who had been on
the sidelines with a sprained left foot, came back to practice
because rookie Chris Floyd was looking so good on film.
</P>
<P>
   He's getting it at running back, where Sedrick Shaw and Robert
Edwards are battling for the No. 1 job and Harold Shaw is in a
fight with Derrick Cullors and Robert Green for work as the
third-down back.
</P>
<P>
   He's getting it at cornerback, where Tebucky Jones, Chris Canty,
and Mark Tate are all trying to put their best foot forward.
</P>
<P>
   He's also getting it at defensive tackle, where Chad Eaton is
battling Mark Wheeler and Henry Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   And now he says he's getting it at defensive end, where Boston
College's Chris Sullivan is battling Collons for the starting left
slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ferric is starting in this game (the exhibition opener at San
Francisco Sunday) and he comes into the camp as a starter having
lost out through injury,'' said Carroll. ``But Chris has worked
with the first unit a lot in the past couple of days. We'll let
that competition play out. Nobody likes somebody looking over their
shoulder and being right behind, and that's what Chris is doing
right now, so I hope it means we're seeing the best of both guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Collons understands this perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris Sullivan stepped in last year and he played his ass
off,'' said Collons. ``That's put me in a tough position because
now you have basically two starters. I got hurt and I was gone. If
it didn't happen that way ... we could speculate a thousand times,
but it did. And you can't say there was a drop-off. In fact, they
played so well at the end of the year that I'm fighting for my
job.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-7-inch, 300-pound Collons is the Patriots' biggest
starting lineman. On a team that lacks size up front, Collons is a
big presence who is considered an excellent run-stopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't worry about things I can't control,'' said Collons, a
University of California product. ``I let the chips fall where they
fall. I don't think being a professional, you need anything to
motivate you. You just line up and play. That's motivation enough.
But there's definitely a competition. There's no two ways about it.
You have two guys who started for this team in the same season.
It's kind of a weird situation, but that's the way it went down.''
</P>
<P>
   Collons tore his left pectoral muscle in a freak accident during
drills following the Patriots' humiliating loss to the Denver
Broncos in 1997. He underwent surgery and was out for the season.
At first, the Patriots missed his run-stopping ability, but
Sullivan came on and filled a big void.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tough break for Collons, who had signed a two-year deal
after the Patriots decided to match a two-year, $3 million offer
sheet by the Philadelphia Eagles when he was a restricted free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute I signed that contract, it left my mind,'' said
Collons. ``I didn't think about it twice. All that concerns me is
the New England Patriots.''
</P>
<P>
   Collons left his offseason healing in the hands of team
physician Bert Zarins and trainer Ron O'Neil, even though his wife
is an orthopedic surgeon at San Francisco General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 100 percent,'' said Collons. ``Dr. Z and Ronnie O did a
great job briging me along slow and steady. We never really pushed
it. It was absolutely miserable during the healing process. Now I
don't even feel it. The only reminder is this scar on my
shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Collons didn't take part in the strength and conditioning
program two years ago because of family commitments. But he never
left Foxborough after his injury, knowing he not only needed to get
healthy but also stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to give myself the best possible chance to play
football,'' said Collons. ``The rehab was an ongoing process. Now I
just want to stay healthy, compete, play first and second down ...
whatever it is I can do, I want to do it. That's the great thing
about our group _ we have a very eclectic group of guys on the
D-line. There's not a mold for this unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Collons
</P>
<P>
   moved around a lot early in his career. In 1995, he played for
four teams. He was signed by the Los Angeles Raiders as a rookie
free agent in 1992 and spent time on their practice squad. After
being released by LA, he was one of the first 10 players signed by
the Jacksonville Jaguars when they entered the NFL in '95, then was
claimed on waivers by the Atlanta Falcons, who in turn traded him
to Green Bay. The Packers traded him to New England April 18, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Collons doesn't want to be moving again, and the likelihood is
he won't be. Carroll just wants to light little fires in hopes
there'll be a big one at the end of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
