<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV02-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTOMOTIVE TRANSPORTION: TWO SIDES OF A COIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, August 02, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week, we consider automotive transportation sublime and
ridiculous, sublime as in the pricey Jaguar XK8 Convertible, an
automobile that offers style, luxury, performance _ and a touch of
the ridiculous if you think of it as family transport. For
ridiculous, consider the Kia Sportage, an alleged sport/utility
which at first glance would seem virtuous in that a well-equipped
4WD version is available for under $20,000, almost a budget car
these days. It may well be competent traversing a mudhole, but for
everyday driving, it's no bargain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The XK8 is sublime revisited, and it hasn't changed since our
last visit in October 1997; it is still a vision of luxury with
leather and expensive wood inside, and this time around something
akin to plum coloring on the outside _ nice, I thought. But, then,
what do I know, being color-perception impaired?
</P>
<P>
   The radio controls still need work, the air conditioning still
accommodates those of us who like deep chill behind the wheel or
milder interior climes _ but both at once is pushing it. At a base
sticker of $70,480 delivered, I still think the buyer deserves a
top that disappears completely under a body panel rather than one
that, after a magnificent mechanical ballet, merely falls limp
behind the back seat like a dancer exhausted after the performance.
And, as far as this columnist is concerned, the stylish boot that
snaps in place over it can stay in the trunk _ or home in the
closet, if it were mine.
</P>
<P>
   The 290-horsepower V-8 offers very quick, quiet acceleration,
whisper-quiet touring at any speed, and the Jaguar's handling and
road manners equal or surpass in grace its elegant styling. Tooling
along at turnpike speeds, one may still hold a normal conversation
or listen to the radio. Mileage this time around was 19.73 miles
per gallon overall on an abbreviated tour. I would have kept it
longer had there been significant change _ so many cars, so little
time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And now for something completely different. That phrase, you may
recall, was a standard exclamation on televsion's ``Monty Python
Show.'' The Kia Sportage, I think, would have been right at home
with the Python posse.
</P>
<P>
   This was my third encounter with the Sportage, this after a
meeting with a platoon of Kia people assuring me that the car was
``much improved'' _ they said ``you'll love it.'' Love? This isn't
even close to ``like.''
</P>
<P>
   The first two encounters were at Pocono Raceway in the eastern
mountains of Pennsylvania under the auspices of the International
Motor Press Association and its annual test day at the track. On
the track, the Sportage was the pits; on the off-road course
provided, it wasn't much better. Since then, Kia has been fighting
to survive in bankruptcy and playing ``Lets Make a Deal'' with
customers _ you want a Kia, call the company and haggle. But why
would you want a Sportage when for less money you could have much
better, a Honda CR-V or a Toyota RAV4?
</P>
<P>
   For openers, the interior of the tested model, a 4WD EX with
4-speed manual gearbox that lists for $18,495 plus $450 delivery,
was not exactly a welcome wagon. The emergency brake handle between
the front seats is partially blocked by an annoying sliding armrest
that covers a small bin. The radio controls are the worst thing
since the Hummer's, which was designed, I'm sure, in Hell.
Match-head-sized buttons, little rockers, all marked with quaint
codes, make tuning an aggravating chore.
</P>
<P>
   Once tuned, the FM snappedd, crackled, and popped persistently;
the AM simply faded out at every bridge, dip in the road, or overly
large tree.
</P>
<P>
   The 4WD tranfer case control lever is on the floor, close to
your leg _ not exactly convenient. Small glove box, door bins, coin
holder, and bin to the left of the wheel make up the front interior
storage.
</P>
<P>
   In the rear, entry is tight _ smallish door with large
wheel-well intrusion. Once aboard, you haven't much room for your
knees.
</P>
<P>
   It gets worse. On the road, the Sportage feels like a rollover
looking for a place to happen. The body leans, sways _ this may be
a safety feature. Maybe the Koreans did this to make us slow down
on the turns, to give us a physical warning of impending doom. And
maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they really believe Americans use these things in the
boonies and designed a lot of travel into the suspension for
maximum benefit on the Rubicon Trail. And maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe _ my take on it _ it's an inferior car with a sloppy
suspension, sloppy handling. The nominal 2.0-liter, four-cylinder
engine (1.998 liters, to be exact) is somewhat anemic, given to
poor acceleration, a bit noisy. The five-speed manual was so-so,
and you had to work the poor thing to a frazzle to keep the engine
revving at a level where you might wrest anything like reasonable
performance from it.
</P>
<P>
   The Kia starts as a four-door, 2WD model for around $15,000 and
offers eight variations in steps up to the 4WD EX with automatic
for around $20,000. Fuel mileage amounted to 20.3 miles per gallon,
but that's not based on protracted experience. I got out of Kia
rather quickly; I found it a thoroughly unlikable vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   If you must buy Korean, try Daewoo for reasonable transport at
reasonable prices.
</P>
<P>
   For what you get, KIa Sportage is overpriced. And, frankly, it's
not a car I'd want to see in the hands of new or inexperienced
drivers. Thumbs down!
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
