<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2288 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV02     07-31 1489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV02-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALANCE IMPORTANT IN BUILDING FIXED-INCOME PORTFOLIO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 02, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. You recently recommend a portfolio of three bond funds --
Vanguard Short-Term Bond, Vanguard GNMA, and Vanguard High-Yield
Corporate Bond funds, estimating an annual yield of about 7.1
percent. What are your thoughts about replacing the Short-Term Bond
fund in this portfolio with Vanguard's Long-Term Treasury of
perhaps Vanguard Intermediate-Term Treasury funds? Based on some of
my old Vanguard information, these funds have higher average annual
total returns than the Short-Term fund. This year I will be 69 and
my wife 67. Our portfolio at this point is entirely within the
Vanguard family, consisting of $596,341, of which $362,642 is in
fixed-income funds and the balance spread between Windsor II and
Primecap As you know, those two stock funds have not kept pace
lately. Should we make a change?
</P>
<P>
   J.J., Atlantic Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The selection of the fixed-income portfolios in the previous
column was designed with as much regard to risk as yield. The idea
was to balance the high-risk Vanguard High-Yield Bond fund with the
conservative Vanguard Short-Term Bond fund. Certainly you could get
a higher-yield by eliminating the conservative Short-Term Bond fund
in favor of a bolder fund, but the at this point you can't do it
with one of Vanguard's Treasury funds -- all of them now have lower
yields than the Short-Term fund. The Short-Term fund has a 30-day
yield of 5.93 percent as this is written, according to Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   The best-yielding of the Treasury funds is 5.64 percent for the
Long-Term U.S. Treasury fund, and the others spiral downward. You
could look to Vanguard's Long-Term Corporate Bond fund, with a
yield of 6.31 percent, or to its Long-Term Bond Index, with a 6.07
percent yield, but neither produces a very significant margin of
improved yield.
</P>
<P>
   But when you go from a short-term fund to a long-term one, you
add a significant amount of risk. To demonstrate this, I'll go back
to 1994, the current benchmark as a headache year for bond fund
owners. That year Vanguard's Short-Term Bond fund had a negative
total return of .08 percent; Vanguard Intermediate-Term U.S.
Treasury fund lost 4.33 percent, and the Long-Term U. S. Treasury
lost 7.04 percent. See why I wanted the conservative end of the
portfolio?
</P>
<P>
   Now, the market usually compensates investors in long-term bonds
handsomely, providing a significantly higher yield. But I don't
think the current difference in yields is sufficient to warrant the
risk -- you get 38 basis points higher yield for holding the Long-
Term Corporate fund's portfolio of 20-year maturity bonds, compared
to an average weighted maturity of one to three years for the
Short-Term fund.
</P>
<P>
   So my feeling is that if you wanted to sweeten the yield on the
portfolio I suggested, you could do it better by reducing the
Short-Term position and adding to either the GNMA or High-Yield
Corporate holdings, depending on how much you're willing to crank
up the risk. But remember the basic adage: when you go for higher
yield, higher risk is going to come along with the package.
</P>
<P>
   As for your own portfolio, I calculate 60.8 percent is in
fixed-income holdings, which means you are holding a little bit
more stock than most people your age chose to. But I think you're
being a little unfair to the Windsor II fund. Perhaps you're not
taking the nature of the beast into consideration. This is a
value-oriented fund, and while it hasn't come anywhere near beating
the growth-oriented funds in the current bull market, it's still
near the head of the class among its peers, and has done very
nicely on any basis. So far this year its 13.3 percent total return
puts it in the top quartile of its peer group, where the average
return was 8.8 percent. Over a longer term, Windsor II's three-year
average annual total return of 28.9 percent compares to a 22.7
percent peer-group average.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Primecap hasn't done particularly well, even
among its large-cap blend peers. Its 11.9 percent year-to-date
total return of 11.9 percent compares to a peer average of 16.2
percent, and the three-year record also trails the average, 23.7
percent to 25.7 percent. You might decide to move some of this
money to Vanguard's Index 500 fund, and perhaps, depending on how
happy you are with the current market and how content you are to
have nearly 41 percent of your money in stocks, moving a little of
the Primecap money onto the fixed-income side, perhaps reducing
stocks to 35 percent of the total portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I plan to invest $1,000 for my grandchild for his education
or to help him when he is 21 years old. I just received a package
from the Stein Roe Young Investors Fund, and I am thinking of
investing $1,000 there. I also plan to invest a further $1,000 in a
conservative fund. Is Stein Roe Young Investor a good fund, and
where should I put the other $1,000? My grandchild is one year old.
</P>
<P>
   H.A., Ramona, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Stein Roe Young Investor's fund is an excellent offering,
building a top-flight record in less than five years of existence.
True, it's a growth fund, and accordingly it offers a portfolio
that will be vulnerable to market reversals. But whether your
grandchild uses the money for education in about 17 years or waits
until he's 21 years old, this is a long-term investment, and during
those many years the market's gains should far outweigh the
inevitable market corrections.
</P>
<P>
   A second plus for this fund, as you probably know from the
information they sent you, is that it caters its portfolio to
companies that can be readily understood by youngsters, and in
addition to the boilerplate reports required by the SEC, it also
sends admirable reports designed to be read and understood by
investors of tender years. And although the fund normally has a
$2,500 minimum initial investment, it is reduced to $1,000 for
uniform gift to minors accounts.
</P>
<P>
   My first instinct was to suggest you stick the entire $2,000 in
this fund -- figuring that the long investment time period should
outweigh the risk. But if you're convinced you want another
offering with a less aggressive approach, I suggest Vanguard's
Balanced Index fund, which holds 60 percent of its assets in stocks
and the rest in bonds. If you wanted to simplify paperwork by
operating within a single fund family, you could look at Stein
Roe's Balanced and Asset Allocation funds -- but when you're
looking you'll probably notice that the Vanguard offering has
significantly better returns and thus should be worth the extra
paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   But I'd still rather see you put the entire $2,000 in Stein Roe
Young Investors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have an elderly relative in a nursing home and I have his
power of attorney. His cash has run out, and we are now selling his
home and expect to receive about $365,000 from the sale. My
question is this: how best to invest this money to maximize income
with minimum risk? What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   P.J., Rockport, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. My first instinct was to suggest the kind of investment
portfolio I usually urge for people needing a steady income stream
-- dominated by a steady Ginnie Mae fund.
</P>
<P>
   But there are two problems here. Ginnie Mae funds work best for
people who are in for the long ride, and whose withdrawals will be
more or less in line with the actual yield of the fund. In the case
of your elderly relative, his money is probably going to run out at
some point between seven and eight years from now -- no matter what
you do. Moreover, since his withdrawals would represent more than
twice the actual yield, an investment in such a fund would put him
prey to the bumpy near-term market course that's common among such
funds. Finally, since the sequence of withdrawals will be so
substantial, in the long run the question of one conservative
investment over another is fairly unimportant. For that reason, I
suggest you put $100,000 of the money in a five-year CD, on which
the best rates are currently running at slightly better than 6.30
percent, and the balance in a sequence of shorter CDs, putting
about $130,000 in a two-year CD, on which the best yields are in
excess of 6 percent, $60,000 in a one-year CD, $30,000 in a
six-month CD, and the final $30,000 in a mutual fund money market
account. (Don't use a bank money market account, which usually
yields about half of what mutual fund money markets offer.) It's
not a particularly sexy portfolio, but it's one you won't have to
worry about, and there's no way you can invest this money
conservatively that will make a great deal of difference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
