<SLUG> BC-AUGUST-BOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLERS, THRILLERS FOR AUGUST READING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dog days of August may be upon us, but in the world of
mysteries and thrillers, it looks like a mighty interesting month.
</P>
<P>
   Following is a sampling of new titles being published in August:
</P>
<P>
   Richard North Patterson dives into presidential politics in ``No
Safe Place.'' Twelve years after his brother was assassinated in
California during his presidential campaign, Sen. Kerry Kilcannon
enters the race for the White House and becomes the target of an
anti-abortionist.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Hillerman reunites Navajo Tribal Police acting Lt. Chee and
retired Joe Leaphorn, who investigate the murder of a tribal police
officer, the disappearance of a biologist and an outbreak of
bubonic plague in ``The First Eagle.''
</P>
<P>
   In William Marshall's ``To the End,'' Detective Chief Inspector
Harry Feiffer of Hong Kong's Yellowthread Street Precinct tries to
find out if a murdered janitor was the intended victim as fellow
detectives believe they have encountered the Curse of the Mummy's
Tomb.
</P>
<P>
   Repairman Jack is back in F. Paul Wilson's ``Legacies.'' Jack,
who fixes situations, now must discover the secrets of a house
inherited by Dr. Alicia Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas Detective Sgt. Romulus Poe investigates the murder of
a showgirl, whose mutilated body was dumped in the desert in Faye
Kellerman's ``Moon Music.''
</P>
<P>
   In John S. Powell's ``The Nostradamus Prophecy,'' a nuclear
warhead is detonated in New York's Financial District. Friar Clark,
head of the Nuclear Emergency Search Team, must track down four
more warheads planted by a cartel of Chechen Mafia, militant
Muslims and North Korean military.
</P>
<P>
   Boston private investigators Patrick Kenzie and Angela Gennaro
are hired to investigate the year-old disappearance of a 6-year-old
girl. Hindering the investigation is an indifferent mother, a
pedophile couple, a group of homeless parents and a shadowy police
unit in Dennis Lehane's ``Gone Baby Gone.''
</P>
<P>
   In Victoria Gotti's ``I'll Be Watching You,'' best-selling
mystery writer Rose Miller is being stalked by someone who leaves
red roses with threatening notes that hint of her mysterious past.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Austen investigates the serial murders of women with links
to the Church of St. Agnes, where Cat's brother is the priest in
Jane Rubino's ``Cheat the Devil.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigating the collapse of a house, El Paso Police Detective
David Alvarez finds the bodies of the homeowner and an unidentified
person in a concealed basement room in Aileen Schumacher's
``Framework for Death.''
</P>
<P>
   Three beautiful women are suspected of committing a series of
murders in Sidney Sheldon's ``Tell Me Your Dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   When Simone Hollingsworth fails to show up for bell-ringing
practice, no one is concerned until her husband starts acting
strangely and a body is discovered in ``Faithful Unto Death _ a
Chief Inspector Barnaby Mystery'' by Caroline Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurateur Jan Lawless thinks she has found the perfect tenant
when she rents out her third-floor apartment to Elliot Beauman, a
children's book author and psychic. Then an old friend of her
father's begins investigating a string of murders linked to Beauman
and his family in Ellen Hart's ``Wicked Games.''
</P>
<P>
   In John Ridley's ``Love Is a Racket,'' would-be scriptwriter
Jeffty Kittridge's life is on the skids. Then he meets a beautiful
young homeless woman who inspires what might be the perfect con.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Chief Inspector Colin Harpur is the first police
officer to arrive at a brutal murder scene at a train station
outside London. To his horror, the victim is his wife in Bill
James' ``Roses, Roses.''
</P>
<P>
   While FBI Agent Mark Beaumont investigates the cult Church of
the Evolution, the granddaughter of the cult's leader is kidnapped
by a woman who plans to take over the cult's funds in ``Storming
Heaven'' by Kyle Mills.
</P>
<P>
   In Les Standiford's ``Presidential Deal,'' building contractor
John Deal rescues 19 Cuban women and children who have been dumped
overboard by smugglers. During a ceremony where he is to receive
the National Medal of Honor, Deal and the first lady are kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   Kit Deleeuw investigates a suburban New Jersey nursing home run
by a powerful politician in ``Death Row'' by Jon Katz.
</P>
<P>
   Private Investigator Cecil Younger is asked to investigate the
doctor aboard an Alaskan cruise ship in John Straley's ``The Angels
Will Not Care.''
</P>
<P>
   In H. Paul Jeffers' ``Corpus Corpus,'' underworld lawyer
Theodore Janus goes to New York to attend the annual dinner of the
Wolfe Pack, fans of Rex Stout's fictional detective. While in the
Big Apple, Janus is murdered after he is implicated in the murder
of a Mafia turncoat. It's up to Sgt. John Bogdanovic to solve the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper columnist and radio personality Alexander Brass is
asked to look into the disappearance of Two-Headed Mary, a swindler
and fixture on the Great White Way during the Depression in Michael
Kurland's ``The Girls in the High-Heeled Shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kay Mitchell's ``A Rage of Innocents,'' Chief Inspector
Morrissey checks out the alarming crime rate in Malminister _ the
body of a pregnant woman is found in a ditch, a gang of kids stabs
a man to death and a housewife is raped.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA's anti-terrorist force, Mongoose, has to stop Bobbie
Pearl from his next threatened mass murder in Nicholas van Pelt's
``The Mongoose Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Luther Little asks his old friend, Seattle P.I. Thomas Black, to
track down his daughter Belinda, a junkie who has disappeared in
Earl Emmerson's ``Catfish Cafe.''
</P>
<P>
   School boys go a murderous rampage in an English village in
Margaret Yorke's ``Act of Violence.''
</P>
<P>
   A bloodstained and naked man found running on a motorway is
admitted to a psychiatric ward. Two armed guards assigned to
protect him are killed, he abducts his psychiatrist and the chase
is on in Katherine John's ``By Any Other Name.''
</P>
<P>
   Europol, the European Union's FBI, assigns British psychological
profiler Claudine Carter to track down a serial killer who has left
dismembered bodies in 15 countries in Brian Freemantle's ``Mind
Reader.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lane hunts down a missing high-tech Russian submarine and
comes face to face with his nemesis, ex-KGB Agent Valeri Yernin in
Sean Flannery's ``Achilles Heel.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. Now go find a favorite reading spot and
enjoy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
