<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of SATURDAY, Aug. 1:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in Kenneth Starr's
investigation of the president.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NY (Dateline to kum) _ The president leaves for a
weekend of fundraising in the Hamptons on New York's Long Island.
By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-SHOOTING (Washington) _ Funeral for slain Capitol Police
officer Chestnut. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-RUSSIA (Washington) _ An IBM unit is to plead guilty in
federal court here to illegally shipping 17 computers to Russian
nuclear weapons lab and to pay $8.5 million fine. It is apparently
the first conviction in IBM's history and the result of diplomatic
misunderstandings and commercial zeal. By Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-WARMING-U.S. (Washington) _ The administration releases
its economic analysis of the costs of complying with Kyoto protocol
on climate change. Debate is over how much of the U.S. commitment
to reduce greenhouse gas emissions can come from trading of credits
with other countries. By John H. Cushman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ The House votes on more
amendments as the long-running battle approaches a conclusion
Monday. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-STATEHOOD (Washington) _ Developments on Puerto Rico
statehood referendum issue. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-ID (Washington) _ The Clinton administration says it
wants to delay plans to assign every American a health-care ID
number until privacy legislation is passed. But privacy experts are
attacking the current privacy legislation, which Republicans
recently attached to the bill that would create a patients' ``bill
of rights.'' By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TEAMSTERS-LEEHAM (Charlotte, N.C.) _ On the campaign trail with
Tom Leedham, the underdog candidate for Teamsters president. By
Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly Religion Column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   CORMORANT-SLAYING (Dateline to kum, N.Y.) _ Developments in the
report of a mass slaying of 1,000 protected cormorants on Lake
Ontario. The birds were reportedly killed because they had been
eating too many of the wide-mouthed bass that sport fisherman are
also after. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO (Dateline to kum) _ Despite declarations that the
offensive against ethnic Albanian separatists in Kosovo is over,
the shelling continues; interviews with refugees. By Mike O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   UKRAINE-IMF (Kiev) _ An International Monetary Fund team
announces that will recommend a $2.2 billion loan to cash-strapped
Ukraine, a country the United States has showered with assistance
for much of this decade but where the economy remains crippled by
corruption and lack of reform. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-ELECT (Phnom Penh) _ Scores of villagers who supported
opposition parties in Sunday's election are fleeing to Phnom Penh
in fear of reprisals. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-OBUCHI (Tokyo) _ In his first full day of work as Japan's
new prime minister, Keizo Obuchi, who has been described as dull,
ox-like and plodding, embarks on an all-out charm offensive, wooing
the international markets and the media that will carry his message
to them. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Washington) _ The economy grew faster than expected
in the second quarter as strong consumer demand, fueled by low
inflation and an abundance of jobs, helped offset fallout from the
Asian crisis and the GM strike. Gross domestic product expanded at
a 1.4 percent annual rate. Although that was well below the first
quarter's pace of 5.5 percent, it was considerably above the gain
of only 0.2 percent expected by analysts. Consumer spending rose at
a 5.8 percent annual rate. Industrial production stalled, though,
as businesses trimmed their inventories. The price deflator, a
closely watched measure of price increases, grew at a rate of 0.9
percent. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-RANK (Undated) _ Folo on reports in Britain that the
Blackstone Group and Kohlberg Kravis Roberts are considering
takeover bids for the Rank Group, which could be valued at nearly
$5 billion. By Peter Truell.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-AVIATION (Rome) _ If Lockheed Martin's abandonment last
month of its bid for Northrop Grumman marked the end of mergers in
America's military industry, France's decision to undertake the
privatization of its aerospace giant, Aerospatiale, showed just how
alive the process is of sorting out Europe's aviation and defense
industries. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-THOMSON (Rome) _ Looking at Thomson Multimedia, in
which Microsoft is buying a 7.5 percent stake. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock market developments: The Dow Jones
Industrial Average was down 50 points at 1:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Frank Rich's ``Journal'' and Tom Friedman's ``Foreign Affairs'';
details to come.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports, and
special section stories will move by 3:00 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER _ A list of stories being considered by
New York Times editors for Page 1 will move at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ Stories scheduled for Page 1 will be
listed by 7 p.m.
</P>
