<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-BLUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO BLUES FEST STILL WAILING AFTER 26 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The first San Francisco Blues Festival was held
in 1973 in a gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Fuller was a headliner, along with Charlie Musselwhite,
Jimmy McCracklin, Luther Tucker and L.C. ``Good Rockin''' Robinson.
This September the festival will celebrate its 26th time around,
each new program put together by producer Tom Mazzolini in a dream
of strum and holler.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first year, thousands of people showed up. Thousands,''
Mazzolini said. ``We had to put speakers up outside. It was
absolutely chaotic, but two things came into focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``One, that all the blues musicians in the Bay Area were ready
for something like this, and second, the response for the festival
was overwhelming. ... We could definitely do No.2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little did I know that years later we would be at No. 26,''
said Mazzolini, putting the final touches on this year's festival,
to be held at the Great Meadow at Fort Mason Sept. 19-20.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 version will be headlined by the Robert Cray Band;
Mavis Staples; Taj Mahal; Ramblin' Jack Elliott; the trio of Irma
Thomas, Marcia Ball and Tracy Nelson; and, coming full circle, the
Jimmy McCracklin Revue.
</P>
<P>
   The festival also will boast Shana Morrison, daughter of Van
Morrison; Sugar Pie DeSanto, who has shared top billing with Etta
James; Roy Rogers and the Delta Rhythm Kings; the Fedora Blues
Allstars; local blues kingpin Tommy Castro; Magic Slim and the
Teardrops; and Steve Lucky and the Rhumba Bums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each festival has its own unique quality,'' Mazzolini said.
``You never know what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazzolini is looking forward to seeing Morrison, Rogers and
Ramblin' Jack this year, along with the Nelson, Bell, Thomas trio
belting out tunes from the CD, ``Sing It!'' He expects close to a
full house, but even after a quarter of a century, Mazzolini isn't
sure what kind of blues will draw what kind of crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always up to the gods,'' he said. ``The high-water mark
for us was in 1991, with B.B. King. We sold out in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   A sell-out at Great Meadow is 9,000 tickets, and if the
weather's fine _ as it has been more often than not _ the Blues
Festival could make a run at a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzolini will have a better idea of what kind of response to
expect when the Charmaine Neville Band plays at the annual free
kickoff concert on Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup for Sept. 19 includes acoustic blues artist Barbara
Dane, the Fedora Blues Allstars, the Jimmy McCracklin Revue with
DeSanto and Jesse James, the Mississippi Delta Blues Caravan, the
Steel Guitar Explosion with Sonny Rhodes and Freddie Roulette,
Little Charlie and the Nightcats, Staples and the Robert Cray Band.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday will see the True Spirit Gospel Singers; the Elmer Lee
Thomas Blues Revue; Lucky and the Rhumba Bums; the Delta Rhythm
Kings with Rogers, Elliott, Morrison and Tom Rigney; Wolfman
Washington and the Roadmasters; Magic Slim; Castro; the
Thomas-Ball-Nelson trio; and Taj Mahal and the Phantom Blues Band.
</P>
<P>
   One-day tickets are $20 in advance, $25 at the door. A $35
two-day pass is available only in advance. Tickets are on sale
without service charge at Streetlight Records in San Francisco,
Down Home Music in El Cerrito and Village Music in Mill Valley.
They can be purchased with reduced service charges through BASS
tickets at Tower or Wherehouse stores or by calling (415) 979-BASS,
(510) 762-BASS, (408) 998-BASS or 1-800-225-BASS out of state.
Tickets can also be purchased on-line at www.ticketweb.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
