<HEADLINE>
`SESAME STREET' EXHIBITION INCLUDES WORKS BY CELEBRITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CRAIG MARINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A traveling ``Sesame Street'' art exhibition,
now in San Francisco, features contributions from various
celebrities detailing what the long-runing educational program has
meant to them.
</P>
<P>
   And Lisa Sherman-Cohen, publicist for the Children's Television
Workshop, admits that there are certain advantages to getting
celebrities to contribute to a ``Sesame Street'' celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, who doesn't like `Sesame Street'?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As the program celebrates its 30th year on public television,
people were asked to donate a little something for a traveling
tribute, which will culminate in New York next spring with an
auction to benefit three charities: the Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric
AIDS Foundation, Reading is Fundamental and the National Black
Child Development Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, people starting sending in paintings,
collages, sculptures and just about everything else. The exhibit
runs through Aug. 16 at the International Children's Art Museum at
the World Trade Center in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Among those making contributions were singer Carly Simon, actor
Dennis Franz, talk show hostesses Katie Couric, Rosie O'Donnell and
Sally Jessy Raphael, musicians Wynton Marsalis and Mary Chapin
Carpenter, and former first lady Barbara Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sent in a drawing of herself reading her book about her dog
to a group of children as Big Bird and a giant furry purple
creature looked on.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the efforts were more professional than others, but all
seemed to come from the heart. Simon sent a detailed oil painting
of a piece of fruit with the caption ``P is for Pear.'' Comedienne
Ruth Buzzi's painting of various ``Sesame Street'' characters
lazing beneath a tree showed some real art training, while Franz's
cartoon self-portrait with letters floating through his brain was
charming, though he should clearly not consider a change of
careers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the contributors seemed a bit old to have their own
personal Sesame experiences, except through their childrens' eyes.
But two of the people at the museum Thursday fit the perfect
demographic.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's Educational Director, Julie Wolfe, 30, said,
```Sesame Street' made me feel special. I loved it when the number
of the day was my age or the letter was in my name. And I loved
Grover.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jana Johnson, who is traveling with the exhibit, is 29. But
her tale is a bit sadder.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents never let me watch television before dinner,'' she
said, maintaining a professional smile despite the obvious pain
inflicted upon her inner child. ``I do feel a bit neglected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
