<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SHOWTIME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S SHOWTIME, AT LAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This weekend is Showtime's coming out party.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the network has been in business for years but if you
wanted to pick a time when it really tried to define itself, you
couldn't pick two better days than Saturday and Sunday. That's when
Showtime begins to not only give HBO a run for its
original-programming money, but the networks as well.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Showtime unveils two new sitcoms in ``Linc's,'' which
looks at all aspects of the African-American experience, and ``Rude
Awakenings,'' which destroys the notion of safe, predictable
premises for comedies.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Sunday the channel airs the controversial ``Lolita.''
While airing ``Lolita'' is really business as usual for Showtime,
the two sitcoms represent an expanding line up of original drama
and comedy series. There are some flaws in each of the two shows,
but they shine brightly in a field of bland, unoriginal network
programming that is about to assault television sets in September.
</P>
<P>
   When Tim Reid was asked why the networks couldn't make a sitcom
like ``Linc's,'' he just started laughing. It really is that
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   First, cable doesn't hesitate to break new ground or do
something edgy or different. In ``Linc's'' (check local listings)
Showtime found a sitcom _ some might say dramedy _ with an
African-American cast that doesn't need a laugh track and doesn't
go over that tired, stereotypical ground that forces all
African-American comedies to look and sound the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linc's'' breaks out of that box by being political, harsh,
funny and touching all at the same time. Reid, who created the
short-lived but acclaimed ``Frank's Place'' and also starred years
ago in ``WKRP In Cincinnati,'' is executive producer and co-creator
along with Susan Fales-Hill (``A Different World''), two of the
more powerful African-American producers in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   They clearly had a plan. That a black show didn't have to be any
different than a white show as far as content, and the limitations
of comedies would have to be smashed. Thus we get Steven Williams
(``The X-Files'') as Linc, owner of a bar in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Russell Lincoln _ and Republican as Abraham,'' says
Williams in the one-hour pilot. He opens the show by walking around
the Capitol, commenting. ``Washington, D.C. _ a city laid out by a
black mathematician now run by a black ex-con.''
</P>
<P>
   And later: ``You can always tell when white folks are moving
into the neighborhood when a Starbucks opens up.''
</P>
<P>
   People have tried to paint this show as a black ``Cheers,'' but
it isn't. ``Linc's'' is much more political and socially charged,
less interested in the quick one-liner. Regulars at Linc's bar and
grill include Pam Grier as Eleanor, a children's rights activist
who is as liberal as Linc is Republican. Grier, who has started her
red-hot comeback, is wonderful in this series. She gets to go
toe-to-toe with Georg Sanford Brown as Johnnie, another lobbyist
who has few morals and calls her ``juggs for justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Other regulars are Tisha Campbell as Rosalee, Linc's military
daughter leaning toward lesbianism; Joe Inscoe, the lone white
actor who plays Harlan, chief of staff for a leathery old senator
and longtime supporter of Linc's bar; Golden Brooks as CeCe the
sassy waitress; Eartha, the aging call girl; and Winston, the
sex-starved Nigerian cab driver who also knows all the political
dirt on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a show that is clearly in the dramedy category since real
issues are dissected with a sometimes humorous bent.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Rude Awakenings'' (check local listings), creator Claudia
Lonow didn't laugh when asked why the networks didn't gobble this
gem up. The real joke is that they were interested in the concept,
just not the script as it was, and certainly not in the version
that Showtime ultimately made. Talk about groundbreaking and
envelope pushing. Lonow says flat out this is a show about an
alcoholic slut trying to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Fox would touch that concept. But on ``Showtime'' it's
hilariously good and very adult _ and that's the targeted audience.
</P>
<P>
   Sherilyn Fenn plays Billie Frank, a fading soap star given over
to Irish coffees light on the coffee. Whenever she hits the local
bar, she usually drags somebody back with her. Now she's a
secretary, and her boss _ Richard Lewis _ disdains her drinking but
lusts after her. When she hangs out with her mom, played by Lynn
Redgrave, she can see herself in the future. Redgrave plays her mom
as a functional alcoholic who has a haughty manner and a wicked
tongue (she calls her daughter-in-law ``the vagina'' throughout the
show).
</P>
<P>
   Credit Fenn with pulling off this high-wire act. She's both
funny and sad at the same time, an enormously difficult emotional
trick that the networks wouldn't try in 10 million years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rude Awakenings'' manages to be raunchy, funny and even
slightly touching.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime is truly blossoming as a pay cable outlet, and it
proves it's more than a worthy rival for HBO. What this weekend's
coming-out party suggests is that discerning viewers searching for
originality and quality just may have to pay to get it these days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 1431EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
