r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-CABIRIA-H     07-31 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CABIRIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTORED `CABIRIA' SHOWS FELLINI AT HIS EARLY BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WALTER ADDIEGO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Nights of Cabiria,'' Federico Fellini's 1957 Oscar winner, is
the latest classic movie to receive a careful and extensive
restoration and re-release, part of a very pleasing recent trend in
the movie business that's brought us vastly improved prints of
pictures like ``Lawrence of Arabia'' and ``Vertigo.''
</P>
<P>
   A prime example of the golden age of ``art cinema,'' ``Cabiria''
was the culmination of Fellini's realist period, which included the
extraordinary pictures ``I Vitelloni'' and ``La Strada'' (also an
Academy Award winner). By the time he made his next movie, ``La
Dolce Vita'' (1960), he was internationally famed and working with
higher budgets, and his interests had veered toward the
autobiographical and fantastical.
</P>
<P>
   Before his death in 1993 he made other remarkable movies, but
``Cabiria'' represents the director in top early form.
</P>
<P>
   The film was the second of three major pictures Fellini made
starring his wife, Giulietta Masina. (She was also the victimized
waif in ``La Strada'' and the abandoned housewife of ``Juliet of
the Spirits.'')
</P>
<P>
   Masina had a wondrously expressive face and a comedic talent
that earned her comparisons to Chaplin. Fellini wrote that she had
``a gift for evoking a kind of waking dream quite spontaneously, as
if it were taking place quite outside her own consciousness. With
her clown-like gift for mimicry, she embodies in our relationship
my nostalgia for innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   Cabiria (Masina) is a Roman prostitute whose hope for a better
life is doomed because of her naivete. As the film opens, she is
humiliated when her ``boyfriend'' grabs her purse and pushes her
into the river. This shouldn't be funny, but Cabiria's innocent and
romantic nature, combined with her bantam's anger at being duped,
makes it a superb comic sequence, summing up Cabiria's nature:
She's a bit ridiculous, maybe, but still a suffering human being.
</P>
<P>
   Later, she decides to try her luck on the ritzy Via Veneto,
though she's completely out of place with her ratty fake fur jacket
and ankle socks. She's picked up by a famous movie star (Amedeo
Nazzari) who's had a fight with his girlfriend and taken to his
absurdly extravagant mansion, only to wind up locked in the
bathroom for the night. She joins a group of prostitutes and pimps
for a pilgrimage to a religious shrine, but finds no relief there,
either.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes for Cabiria until she meets Oscar (Francois Perier),
a young man who speaks to her kindly and asks nothing about her
past. She cashes in her bank account, says goodbye to her friend
and fellow streetwalker Wanda (Franca Marzi), and sets out to join
Oscar to celebrate their engagement.
</P>
<P>
   She's giddy, imagining her luck has finally changed. It hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, ``Cabiria'' was available only in extremely poor
prints. The restored version is a pleasure to look at, and is
greatly enhanced with newly and more accurately translated
subtitles. Some of the script, incidentally, was written by Pier
Paolo Pasolini, at the time known only as a poet and novelist, who
was hired to make the prostitutes' dialogue more authentically
gritty.
</P>
<P>
   The restorers are also proud of having found and included a
``missing'' sequence (known as the Man with the Sack episode) about
a mysterious figure who dispenses charity, and which was rumored to
have been cut from the film because it offended the Roman Catholic
Church.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
