<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MARIUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARIUS' A WARM TALE OF WORKING-CLASS LIFE AND LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WALTER ADDIEGO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A warm-hearted and humane examination of love between a pair of
mature, working-class adults, ``Marius and Jeannette'' tells a
simple story with both good humor and somber overtones.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the romantic tale, director Robert Guediguian recounts
the life of a neighborhood, a congested section of Marseille where
the inhabitants still talk to each other and share a sense of
community. The filmmaker's other pictures have been set in the same
city, and he clearly relishes the milieu and its residents.
</P>
<P>
   Jeannette (Ariane Ascaride) is struggling to raise a pair of
children from two different, absent fathers. Her fiery temper and
anti-capitalist views soon cost her her job at a supermarket.
Marius (Gerard Meylan) is a quiet, burly man who works as a guard
at an abandoned cement factory, where he catches Jeannette trying
to steal a few buckets of paint to freshen up her rundown
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Tough times have made Jeannette a pretty brassy woman. When
Marius decides to give her a break and not call the police, she
tries to badger him into letting her have the paint anyway. No
sale, but she's obviously made an impression. If the trepidations
and inertia of middle-age can be overcome, these two could be
headed for something nice.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe somewhere else this would be Marius and Jeannette's
concern and nobody else's, but in the courtyard where her neighbors
meet, argue and chat, it's everybody's business. Marius eventually
moves in with Jeannette, then abruptly disappears. The neighbors _
her friends, really _ believe it's their duty to reunite the couple
if possible.
</P>
<P>
   Life in Jeannette's quarter is hard, but has its compensations _
companionship and a shared, generally leftist viewpoint. A laborer
(Jean-Pierre Darroussin) is endlessly upbraided by his wife for
having once voted for the right-wing National Front. A retired
teacher (Jacques Boudet) starts a liaison with a single woman
(Pascale Roberts) of a certain age after a row over fava beans.
There's a camaraderie of griping, like that of military lifers.
</P>
<P>
   Guediguian has a sentimental streak and takes no pains to hide
it, but the tone is offset to a degree by the acerbic notes in the
fine performance of Ascaride (his wife, who has appeared in all his
films). As Jeannette, she shows the kind of toughness women develop
working alone to feed and clothe their children, and uses it to
give spine to the role.
</P>
<P>
   Ascaride has extensive film and television credits in France,
and her work here earned her a Cesar award _ the French Oscar _ for
best actress.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker tells his story in a manner as unembellished as
the tale itself, which he refers to simply as ``a love story
amongst the poor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 1445EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
