<HEADER>
A2398 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-AMERICA-$ADV0     07-31 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-AMERICA-$ADV03-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COAST TO COAST TO ALMOST-COAST _ WHAT A COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1997 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ America is way too big. Worse, it's a
pasted-together country that could _ and maybe should _ be divided
into fourths or fifths or sixths without hurting much of anything. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I know all this because, for good and sufficient reasons, I've
spent much of the summer pinballing around America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even now I might be somewhere other than where you think I am,
if you think about my being any place at all. Which, for your sake,
I hope you don't. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I began the summer innocently enough, going to Illinois for a
family reunion. I have more relatives in Illinois than elsewhere
because I grew up there, as did my parents. A lot of my relatives
got so deeply rooted in the Land of Lincoln, it turns out, that
they think of Ohio as the East Coast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Illinois is like Indiana, only more so. And like Wisconsin, only
less so. Along with those three, you could throw in a few other
states _ Iowa comes to mind _ and you'd have a pretty homogeneous
country that could export enough corn and soybeans to feed all of
California, which is where I went after I got done hanging around
Illinois. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   California should be at least two countries, south and north. I
first spent time in San Diego, which is terribly proud of itself
for being smart enough to be located in San Diego, which has some
pretty lovely weather and a slick zoo. Then I went up to Berkeley,
itself a semi-slick zoo that has weather more to my perverse liking
_ cool, misty, foggy and whatnot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean to suggest that weather is the only difference
between southern and northern California. Nosiree. People in San
Diego, for instance, spend lots of time being glad they don't live
in nearby Tijuana, Mexico, which seems to them, I gather, like a
dirt-poor cousin you hope never shows up at your lawn parties. By
comparison, many people in Berkeley would be just as happy selling
leather goods in a Tijuana street market _ and wouldn't notice much
difference in their lives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I am, of course, being unfair to huge numbers of San Diegans,
but given the vast wealth there they could bear up under the strain
of my insults, if they chose, by declaring La Jolla, say, a
separate, gated nation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When I was just a kid, I went to La Jolla with my family to
visit friends, who had managed to slip into town before there was
an asset minimum for residents. I remember these sweet people
talking about how many millionaires already lived there, though I
don't recall the specific number. I knew, however, that if I were
ever reduced to going door-to-door to raise funds for my next meal,
people behind the doors in La Jolla could afford to share. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are rich people in Berkeley, too, of course, but their
assets are mostly tied up in what, almost anywhere else, would be
cheap housing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, after I got done with California and had stopped at home
long enough to throw away the junk mail and feed the dog, I headed
to Vermont. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Summer weather in Vermont can be like summer weather in San
Diego, only without the sea gulls and beach bums. My wife grew up
in Vermont. And it's a lovely state, too, except that if you take a
wrong turn you end up in New Hampshire or Massachusetts or some
other state that, if life worked right, would all be mooshed
together into a new country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after returning from Vermont I went to beautiful New
Mexico, which ought to be combined with Arizona, Oklahoma, Utah,
Nevada and parts of Texas to become a country called, say, Nuevo
del Norte Rio Grande Chihuahua del Pecos Bill. A complicated name
like that might keep folks in La Jolla from thinking of such a
country as closet space and attempting a hostile takeover. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which would lead to a too-big, pasted-together country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
