<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-WASTE-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SENATE DELAYS NUCLEAR WASTE COMPACT
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 31 -- Opponents of a deal to store Maine and
Vermont's low-level nuclear waste in Texas won a reprieve Friday
when the Senate put off a final vote on the issue until after its
August recess.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Maine-Vermont-Texas compact, which the House
approved 305-116 Wednesday, had been pushing Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott to schedule a vote this week, just before the Senate
leaves town for a month.
</P>
<P>
   But the compact's main blocker, Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn.,
threatened a filibuster and other delay tactics, prompting Lott to
pull the bill rather than use up what little time he had left
before the vacation on the contentious issue of storing nuclear
waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately though, it will be impossible to prevent a final
vote on this matter,'' Wellstone said. ``But it was very important
to stop it now. This is a time for organizing and mobilizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone does not object to the two New England states sending
their waste to Texas, but to the decision to dump the waste in a
poor, predominantly Hispanic town in west Texas, 15 miles from the
Mexican border. He believes the site will be environmentally
dangerous, and that its selection was based on the town's inability
to marshal political opposition to the compact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important fight for an environmental justice,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The compact has the support of the governors -- an independent,
a Republican and a Democrat -- as well as the state legislatures
and all six senators from the three states, and Maine voters
approved the deal by a three-to-one margin in a 1993 referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Congress must approve the deal because it involves inter-state
commerce, something that has been done with nine other nuclear
waste compacts that covered 41 states. Supporters of the compact,
including Maine's Republican senators, Olympia Snowe and Susan
Collins, and Reps. John Baldacci, D-Bangor, and Tom Allen,
D-Portland, say that it will be environmentally sound and that
Wellstone's arguments ``simply don't hold water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Had he not objected, we would have been able to dispense with
it this week,'' said Dave Lackey, Snowe's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, Maine and Vermont will pay $25 million each for the
construction of the site, which will house low-level waste
predominantly from private nuclear reactors such as the defunct
Maine Yankee. Lott agreed to hold a debate and vote on the compact
Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, we'll have a vote on it, and we'll be
able to pass it,'' Lackey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 1457EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2423 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-RELEASES-HNS &LR;      07-31 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-RELEASES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE VOCAL MUSIC, A LOT OF GERSHWIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALLAN ULRICH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Consider the following releases as previews of
events upcoming events. The recent flood of George Gershwin music
heralds the composer's centennial. But, first, the acme and nadir
of current vocal releases:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Songs by Beethoven, Strauss, Schumann and Liszt. Ben Heppner,
tenor; Craig Rutenberg, piano. RCA Red Seal 09026-63104.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is possible for tenors with enormous voices whose last
name is not Vickers to both dominate the opera stage and to perform
Lieder with uncommon sensitivity. The peripatetic Heppner, who
gives his first local recital at the University of California at
Berkeley in January, is one of those rare artists.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, during this Toronto-taped compact disc, you can
feel the Canadian singer restraining himself. Yet he is savvy about
deploying his liquid tone to the needs of the concert hall without
slighting the emotional substance of Beethoven's ``Adelaide'' and
``An die ferne Geliebte,'' Strauss' Op. 27 (including ``Morgen''
and ``Ruhe, meine Seele''), seven of Schumann's ``Myrthen'' and
Liszt's ``Tre sonetti di Petrarca.''
</P>
<P>
   Heppner projects the texts with thrilling clarity. And, as we
(and a growing host of singers) know from his local appearances,
Rutenberg is among the most caring and supple of today's
accompanists.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arias by Strauss and Mozart. Jane Eaglen, soprano; Israel
Philharmonic conducted by Zubin Mehta. Sony Classical SK 60042.
</P>
<P>
   RCA is using its contract with Heppner to record him in suitable
and engaging repertoire. In contrast, Sony Classical's philosophy
for Eaglen amounts to starting the tape and letting her rip.
</P>
<P>
   That she does. The English soprano, who will be Brunnhilde in
three of the San Francisco Opera's four ``Ring of the Nibelung''
cycles next June, certainly possesses monumental volume and weight
in all the material she undertakes. Yet this recital consistently
overpowers without convincing.
</P>
<P>
   The final scene of ``Salome'' rides the orchestral onslaught
impressively, but the absence of inflection suggests a limited
interpretive intelligence. Eaglen lacks the solidity in the bottom
register for an adequate rendering of Ariadne's monologue. And the
charm of ``Arabella'' completely eludes this singer.
</P>
<P>
   The Mozart fares even worse. Eaglen simply doesn't have the
technical security to spit out the staccati in Donna Anna's honor
aria and Elettra's vengeful exit scene. Mehta and his Israelis are
no help at all to her.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Sony should have left this CD in the can.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin: ``Porgy and Bess'' (selections); ``Blue Monday.''
Marquita Lister, Harolyn Blackwell, sopranos; Gregg Baker,
baritone; Central State University Chorus; Cincinnati Pops
Orchestra conducted by Erich Kunzel. Telarc CD-80434.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody searching for a one-disc helping of the Gershwins'
great, if problematic opera, might find this an appealing
proposition. Of musicological interest, Kunzel includes 10 newly
orchestrated minutes of Act III that were previously suppressed
because of the length of the work. Of sentimental interest is the
late Cab Calloway's pungent, idiosyncratic delivery of Sportin'
Life's ``It Ain't Necessarily So.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, the premiere recording of Will Vodery's original
orchestration of the promising, if ultimately unsuccessful 1922
chamber opera, ``Blue Monday,'' vastly improves upon previous
renderings; this one feels right.
</P>
<P>
   Lister, as she demonstrated in a touring production a few years
ago, is a vibrant Bess. Blackwell contributes an ethereal
``Summertime.'' Baker, who has been a memorable Crown, moves up to
Porgy here and takes on Jake for good measure. Kunzel conducts with
verve.
</P>
<P>
   Note, however, that Sony Heritage has just published for the
first time on CD its famed 1951 studio recording of ``Porgy and
Bess'' on mid-priced MH2K-63322 (two CDs). This was the initial
attempt to record the opera (virtually) complete, and it is still a
heroic undertaking, thanks to the performances of Lawrence Winters,
Camilla Williams and Avon Long and the theatrically oriented
conducting of Lehman Engel.
</P>
<P>
   Sumptuous packaging and a complete libretto for a change.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin: Fantasy for Violin and Orchestra on ``Porgy and
Bess''; Three Preludes; Songs for Violin and Orchestra. Joshua
Bell, violin; John Williams, piano; London Symphony Orchestra
conducted by John Williams. Sony Classical SK 60659.
</P>
<P>
   You can, if you so desire, dismiss Bell's first CD under his new
Sony contract as a mere crossover venture (one often wonders about
his company these days). But the playing is so opulent, fervent,
witty and tasteful that much can be forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   The Fantasy consists of a 20-minute medley by Alexander Courage
(he composed the original ``Star Trek'' theme) of nine numbers from
the opera. Bell delivers the preludes in Jascha Heifetz's
time-tested transcriptions and those contemporary deans among
arrangers, William D. Brohn and Jonathan Tunick, went to town on
seven Gershwin standards.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight is ``Sweet and Low Down.'' Bell starts by quoting
``Carnival of the Animals''; then he plays against an accompaniment
of Gershwin's original piano roll of the song. It's classy and
irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We Got Rhythm'': A Gershwin Songbook. Andre Previn, piano;
David Finck, double-bass. Deutsche Grammophon 289 453 493.
</P>
<P>
   This CD adds up to a preview of the jazz concert these musicians
will play Sept. 27 at the Gershwin Theater, a benefit for the San
Francisco AIDS Foundation and Classical Action. Previn and Finck
finesse their way through 14 Gershwin tunes, and the air of
sophisticated improvisation is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Previn sounds like an exceptional jazz pianist. Sometimes, his
treatment takes you by surprise; ``They All Laughed'' is positively
ferocious in its chordal assault. And occasionally, he teases you
for a small eternity with the melody, which he finally delivers in
small doses. Still, for all its erudition, this Gershwin collection
swings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
