 ART ADV.: Photos with LATIN-LEAGUE and CHEERS-FADES are being
transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ICELAND-PRESIDENT (Reykyavik) -- Interviewing the president of
Icleand is a no-brainer. Just knock on the door and see if he's
home. Life and times in a country that's virtually crime-free, with
no army, universal health care and free education for all through
college. By Dick Lehr. 100 pix.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PROBE-WHITEHOUSE (Washington) -- Seven times in his daily
briefing, press secretary Michael McCurry pleads ignorance about
the Lewinsky case and the president's strategy. And that was just
in the first two minutes. By Brian McGrory.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHEERS-FADES (Boston) -- For a decade, ``Cheers'' defined Boston
for the nation. Tourists flocked to the pub that inspired the
beloved sitcom. Now the excitement is gone and other attractions
lure tourists. By Anne E. Kornblut. 900 words. (a and e
coding) &UR;  &LR; PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-LEAGUE (Amherst, Mass.) -- While the national gathering of
1,700 students of Greek and Latin included language exams,
contests, and workshops, just as important to the students was
their chance to be part of a 1990s-style bacchanalia, although a
tame one. By Marcella Bombardieri. 750 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NYHAN-COLUMN (Undated) -- What intrigued America most this week
was not anything bubbling out of the swamp in DC. Out here, we're
talking Powerball. By David Nyhan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BEAM-COLUMN (Undated) -- Alex Beam is on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-WAR-CIVILIZATION (Undated) -- ``War and Civilization'' is
quite right to ask large philosophical questions, although its
answers are simplistic and sometimes contradictory. By John Koch.
</P>
<P>
   TV-RUDE (Undated) -- Connoisseurs of dreck need no longer
rummage around in ``Veronica's Closet'' for squalid, witless humor,
because an even worse sitcom, Showtime's ``Rude Awakening,''
premieres Saturday. By Don Aucoin.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-BEST-YEARS (Undated) -- How Harold Russell got the role
in ``Best Years of Our Lives'' is a story that says a lot about a
happy man who can shake hooks with the best of them. By M.R.
Montgomery. 1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-BASEKETBALL (Undated) _ Lowbrow doesn't even begin to
explain ``Baseketball.'' By Renee Graham.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-EVER-AFTER (Undated) _ Don't let ``Ever After'' fool you.
Beneath its 16th century costumes and medieval walled chateau
there's a decidedly modern sensibility. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-FAMILLE (Undated) -- Cedric Klapisch's ``Un Air de
Famille'' moves in the direction of sweetness. Not, however, with
any intention of providing glib resolutions. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-POLISH (Undated) -- How do you make ``Polish Wedding''
without it becoming a Polish joke? No problem for Theresa Connelly,
who knows the territory. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-WELL (Undated) -- Psychosexual and geographical eeriness
intersect seductively and intriguingly in ``The Well,'' a debut
film from Australia's Samantha Lang. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-BOY (Undated) _ Sober and out, Boy George is ready for
Culture Club's reunion. By Steve Morse.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-ROCK (Undated) _ Emmylou Harris had thought of taking time
off to write some new songs. But now she's traveling with Lilith
Fair. By Steve Morse.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-CHIMNEY (Undated) _ In ``The Chimney Sweeper's Boy,'' the
past haunts the present, neuroses abound, obsession flourishes,
shameful secrets unfold. By Diane White.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-HOMELESS (Tokyo) -- A dirty secret in a rich country that
prides itself in caring for the weak is Japan's homeless problem,
exacerbated by the economic crisis. By Indira A.R. Lakshmanan. 800
words. (f and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   ONADVERTISING-COLUMN (Undated) -- Judge at the recent Cannes
International Advertising Festival discusses advertising trends _
and the joy of winning a top prize for his VW Beetle ads. By Chris
Reidy.
</P>
<P>
   VENNOCHI-COLUMN (Undated) -- Massachusetts seems about to
approve a first-in-the nation law requiring insurance companies to
contribute to community investment funds in exchange for tax
relief. By Joan Vennochi.
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ People's Heritage Financial bulds
the fourth-largest bank in New England by working the
suburban/rural marketplace and striking very friendly merger deals.
By Steven Syre and Steve Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;   &UR; (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKN-FLOYD (Undated) -- If you could give themes to humans as if
they were feature-length films, the essence of Tim Floyd's story
would be: How to trust what you hear over what you see. By Michael
Holley. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS (Smithfield, R.I.) -- Pete Carroll's success may
very well be that he's been able to convince veterans like Ferric
Collons they're in a dogfight for a starting job. Even though they
might not be. By Nick Cafardo.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SPORTS-COLUMN (Undated) -- What is particularly disgusting
about the TV industry these days is the use of disgraced announcers
to boost ratings. By Howard Manly.
</P>
