<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSOCIATION WILL HELP SUICIDE SURVIVORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Where can I contact the group Survivors of Suicide? _ M.R.,
Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: One way to find Survivors of Suicide or a similar group in
your area is to call the American Association of Suicidology at
(202) 237-2280.
</P>
<P>
   The association maintains a directory of support groups, which
can be purchased for $10 from 4201 Connecticut Ave., N.W., Suite
310, Washington, DC 20008.
</P>
<P>
   More than 31,000 people committed suicide in the United States
in 1995, according to Alan Berman, the association's executive
director. The group also can refer callers to the nearest suicide
crisis hot line.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If my son says the word ``moron'' one more time I'm going to
scream. Where did this word come from? _ J.G., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: It originated in a 1910 classification scheme for
developmentally disabled people proposed by the American
Association on Mental Deficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme grouped people into three categories depending on
their impaired level of mental development: idiot, imbecile and
moron. A moron was a person with an IQ range of 50-75 or a
potential mental age of 7-12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Moron comes from the Greek ``moros,'' meaning ``foolish or
stupid.'' By 1959, the widespread use of the three terms as
all-purpose insults prompted the medical community to create a new
classification scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why was the Will Rogers Coliseum named for the entertainer
when he was from Oklahoma? _ M.G., Euless, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The name was a popularly supported suggestion of longtime
friend Amon G. Carter Sr. The coliseum and auditorium were built in
1936, not long after Rogers' death on Aug. 15, 1935.
</P>
<P>
   The friendship between Carter and Rogers was described during
the Nov. 4, 1997, rededication of two artworks that Carter donated
to the memorial center.
</P>
<P>
   The works are an Electra Waggoner statue of Rogers riding his
horse, Soapsuds, and a life-size portrait of the entertainer by
Seymour Stone.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
