<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Managing editors, weekend editors)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following religion features.
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, where indicated, have been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEWS AND FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-FLYJESUS-COX (West Palm Beach, FLa.) _ Harold Martin
wants to be a missionary, but he says he can't preach. So, the Hobe
Sound resident plans to be a bush pilot for God. Martin, 23, dreams
of flying small, single-engine planes to nearly inaccessible areas
in forgotten parts of the world to serve Christ. By Steve Gushee.
Moved 7-30.
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-SHAKERS-NYT (Undated) _ A vistor's look at a living link
to an unusual chapter in American religious history: for more than
two centuries, a Shaker community has made its home on a farmstead
less than an hour's drive away from Portland, and the six believers
living there now are the last remnant of this sect in the U.S. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-CAMP-BOS (Weston, Mass.) _ It looks like just another
summer camp _ field trips, pizza parties, and pickup basketball
games. But for the young Christian activists and local Catholic
Church leaders behind it, the three-week program at Regis College
here is part of a new strategy to reach at-risk youth in American
cities. By Diego Ribadeneira. Moved 7-30.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-JEWS-COX (Havana) _ The Cuban Jewish community's long
isolation may be nearing an end. Recently, a delegation of 32 Jews
from South Florida, including Cuban Americans, will travel to Cuba
on a six-day reconciliation mission with their Jewish brethren. The
visit is the first trip to Cuba organized by the Greater Miami
Jewish Federation in nearly four decades, according to an official
with the American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee in New York.
By Bill Douthat. Moved 7-28.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDRENOFGOD-COX (Rutledge, Ga.) _ A look at a reunion of
people who have left a controversial religious group that began as
the Jesus freaks of the hippie era. Now called the Family, it is
known more for its almost-anything-goes attitude toward sex
(including, former members say, sex with children) than for its
end-times theology. By Gayle White. Moved 7-24.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-GRAHAM-COX (Undated) _ Interview with Franklin Graham,
46, founder of the international relief organization Samaritan's
Purse and recognized successor to his father, evangelist Billy
Graham. He told the story of his own life in his first book,
``Rebel With a Cause.'' Now, in ``Living Beyond the Limits,'' he
recounts the stories of other people who have made an impression on
him. He lives with his wife and children in Boone, N.C. By Gayle
White. Moved 7-24.
</P>
<P>
   NC-BAPTISTS-WOMEN-NYT (Raleigh, N.C.) _ The influential
186-year-old First Baptist Church, a mainstream Baptist church but
one that has historically included women in leadership roles, is
expected to vote in the next few months to break from the Southern
Baptist Convention. If the 1,300-member church votes, as expected,
to leave the Convention, it would be the first large,
long-established church to do so over the submission declaration,
which asks husbands to lead their families and wives to serve as
gracious, uncomplaining helpers. By Rick Bragg. Moved 7-24.
</P>
<P>
   REPORTINGONRELIGION-TEX (Rome) _ The Information Age meets the
Age of Faith. The new millennium, less than two years away, will
usher in one of the most religious centuries. And religious and
media leaders, who are often at odds over news coverage of
religion, must forge closer ties in interpreting the new wave of
spirituality sweeping a troubled world. By Jim Jones. Moved 7-24.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-CONSUMERISM-TEX (Dallas) _ What would Jesus do? It has
become a million-dollar question. Literally. Abbreviated as WWJD,
it has helped sell more than 17 million bracelets and countless
coffee mugs, key chains and calendars. And more products are on the
way. By Matthew Brady. Moved 7-24.
</P>
<P>
   LUTHERAN-KIDS-COX (Atlanta)- Keeping the faith while having fun:
a look at the 30,000-strong National Lutheran Church-Missouri Synod
Youth Gathering meeting here. By Gayle White. Moved 7-27.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT (New York) _ People have been turning to the
Paraclete Bookstore for years as a source of serious books on
Christian, especially Roman Catholic, theology and history. Now the
store faces an uncertain future. Moved 7-24. By Peter Steinfels.
Moved 7-24.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-MUSIC25-COX (Undated) _ Maire Brennan's haunting voice,
heard through the music of Clannad, the Irish band that helped kick
off the Celtic craze in the U.S., is now heard on ``Perfect Time,''
in which she has ventured into the world of Christian music for the
first time. By John Blake. Moved 7-24.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS (Plainville, Mass.) _ On a community farm,
nuns happily reap what they sow. Crystal Springs, a 40-acre spread
that three nuns have turned into a sacred celebration of the earth
and its bounties, was created out of the nuns' belief that earth is
the primary revelation of the divine. And food the land provides is
what binds people and the earth. By Diego Ribadeneira. Moved 7-29.
</P>
</TEXT>
