A2443 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-MIYAZAWA-HNS &LR;      07-31 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-MIYAZAWA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIYAZAWA'S TASK OF SAVING JAPAN IS ENORMOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ This week's appointment of Kiichi Miyazawa, one of the
grand old men of Japan's 1980s economic boom, to be finance
minister shows the nation is relying on a revered figure of the
past to forestall a new financial crisis with possible global
repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   But Miyazawa's selection was greeted with some misgivings. A
former prime minister as well as previously a holder of the
financial post, he is 78 and was himself reluctant to take on such
an arduous task _ nothing less than restoring the country to
even-keel.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he is widely seen as the only one with a genuine chance of
succeeding because he alone among Japanese politicians has the
prestige to deal on equal terms with the senior civil servants who
really run things.
</P>
<P>
   He immediately announced he would stop supporting the weak yen
and trying to bolster the floundering Tokyo stock exchange. He thus
provided a major challenge to the policy of intervention that has
long dominated in official circles.
</P>
<P>
   The new prime minister, Keizo Obuchi, has been using all the
right language about restructuring the banking system, which is
nearing collapse, and reforming the economy in general in order to
introduce more competition, especially from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   But these are changes that the top civil servants have resisted
in the past because they represent a challenge to their own power.
These officials have been in charge for too long not to offer
tenacious resistance to a real overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, far-reaching reforms would have been attempted in the
early 1990s when the economy first began to skid.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi isn't the first prime minister to talk tough. Nearly all
have failed to fulfill their promises, and some have failed even to
try. The civil servants are well-practiced in the strategy of
appearing to retreat while holding onto the essentials of their
position.
</P>
<P>
   They were doing so 50 years ago when Gen. Douglas MacArthur
ruled Japan as U.S. supreme commander. The civil servants often
undermined the political and economic reforms he demanded.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi was the most important figure in the preceding government
nominally led by Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto. His power didn't
stem from his job as foreign minister but from his status as chief
of the leading faction in the Liberal Democratic Party, which has
held power almost solidly for nearly 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   As a junior member of Obuchi's group, Hashimoto was little more
than a front man for his boss. If he had wanted to, Obuchi could
have become head of the government at any time during the past two
or three years. Exactly why he decided to put himself in the line
of fire now is something of a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The LDP has traditionally been much more concerned with
factional infighting among its own warring clans than with
governing, one of the reasons the senior civil servants gained
ascendancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LDP politicians are obsessed by the trappings of power _
the jobs and perks _ not with power itself,'' according to
historian Robert Rintoul, a specialist on Japan at the National
Research Council, a leading think tank here. ``Maneuvering within
the party is wholly separate from policymaking for the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that Miyazawa, old as he is, may be ready to break
the mold and act in decisive political fashion. Admittedly, the
odds are against him. Yet unless he does, Japan is likely to
stumble into yet a worse economic quagmire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 1514EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
