<HEADER>
A2447 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-MINES01-COX     07-31 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MINES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRITAIN'S MILITARY BARS USE, SALE OF LAND MINES
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON Jr.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Supporting a cause championed by the late Princess
Diana, the British government Friday banned the manufacture, sale
and use by its military of land mines.
</P>
<P>
   The government had been working for months to implement the ban
before the Aug. 31 anniversary of Diana's death in a Paris car
crash. The princess had campaigned energetically and publicly for a
worldwide ban on mines, which kill 25,000 people a year and injure
many more.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary George Robertson said Britain's government was
trying to set an example for other countries that are not
participating in the Ottawa Convention, an initiative to rid the
world of the anti-personnel weapons. More than 120 countries have
signed the convention, and Britain's action Friday came at the same
time it formally ratified the pact.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Russia and China have not signed the accord.
The Clinton administration has explained that the U.S. military has
no practical alternative.
</P>
<P>
   However, Robertson told BBC Radio that eliminating land mines
would not diminish his country's military capability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most professional army in the world now has said this is
not a system that is morally correct or militarily useful,'' he
said. ``I believe we now have the moral authority to ask other
countries to join us and make sure that these weapon systems are
outlawed everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He praised the late princess for bringing attention to the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a big impact on an international campaign that has
been for the good of the world,'' Robertson said. ``As we approach
the first anniversary of her death, I think it is a fitting legacy
that we should by that time have the 40 countries required
ratifying the treaty to bring it into force.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain, which had allowed only limited use of the bans, has
destroyed about half its stock of 500,000 mines. As the anniversary
of Diana's death approaches, official plans are being made to honor
the woman dubbed ``the People's Princess'' by Prime Minister Tony
Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Elizabeth has ordered that flags be flown at half-staff on
Aug. 31, and a royal memorial service is planned at Crathie Church,
just outside the grounds of Balmoral Castle in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles and his and Diana's sons, William and Harry, are
expected to attend the private ceremony. Blair and his wife,
Cherie, also are scheduled to attend.
</P>
<P>
   William and Harry were on vacation from school at Balmoral last
year when Charles informed them of their mother's death. The two
boys held a 50th birthday celebration _ planned as a surprise party
until it was leaked to the press here _ for their father Friday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
