<HEADLINE>
`LINC'S' SHOWS MUCH PROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
LINC'S 
Starring: Pam Grier, Steven Williams, Georg Stanford Brown 
Created by: Tim Reid and Susan Fales-Hill 
On: Showtime 
Time: Saturday at 10 p.m. 
Rated: TVMA 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It's a rare TV comedy that makes politics the fulcrum of its
humor, and a rarer one still that doesn't shy away from the subject
of race.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to ``Linc's,'' an extremely promising new Showtime
sitcom that blends the barroom bonhomie of ``Cheers'' with the
Beltway buzz of ``Murphy Brown'' and ``Lateline.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that at the Washington tavern known as Linc's,
the owner and most of the patrons are black. The creators and cast
of ``Linc's'' (who include the one and only Pam Grier) do not waste
the opportunity this presents for a fresh perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Make that perspectives. Among the distinctive things about
``Linc's'' is that, without sacrificing any humor, it showcases the
political, cultural, and economic diversity of black Americans.
This is a show whose characters range from high-powered lawyers to
immigrant cab drivers, from waitresses to pinstriped lobbyists,
from rock-ribbed Republicans to diehard liberal Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   As befits the Washington setting, the characters are wised-up.
At ``Linc's,'' everybody knows your name, and also your foibles,
and sometimes your price.
</P>
<P>
   At one pole of the ``Linc's'' world stands proprietor Russell
Lincoln (Steven Williams), a widower who wears his political
incorrectness with defiant pride and boasts that he is ``as
Republican as Abraham.''
</P>
<P>
   In a blunt soliloquy on pop culture, Linc takes hip-hop to task:
``And who is backing this so-called music? Liberal white boys who
show they're `down with the community' by wearing their caps
backward and making classic films like `Booty Call.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the other pole stands Grier's Eleanor Winthrop, a liberal
attorney and children's rights activist locked in a dismal
marriage. The ideological spats between Linc and Eleanor do a poor
job of concealing their attraction to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, talking politics and sex, with topical references
to Linda Tripp, Eddie Murphy, and Ellen DeGeneres, stands an
engaging roster of regulars.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among them is amoral lobbyist Johnnie B. Goode (Georg
Stanford Brown), who can't understand why Winthrop and her
political allies are pushing a bill to penalize the tobacco
companies he represents. ``Doesn't anyone realize they've employed
more people than they've killed?'' Goode asks plaintively.
</P>
<P>
   The frequent target of Johnnie's blandishments is Harlan Hubbard
IV (Joe Inscoe), the reprobate chief of staff for a right-wing US
senator from Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the ensemble is Cece Jennings (Golden Brooks), a
tart-tongued waitress and single mother whose appraisals of men are
as scathing as anything Carla Tortelli &UR;  &LR; came up with; Winston Iwelu
(Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje), a cab driver from Nigeria who fancies
himself the ``Prime Minister of Love''; and a high-priced callgirl
named Eartha (Daphne Maxwell-Reid).
</P>
<P>
   Their verbal roughhouse is no-holds-barred. Winston derides
Johnnie as ``you assimilated `Amistad' baby.'' Cece responds to
Winston's boasting about the glories of Africa with: ``Didn't you
people bring us Ebola?''
</P>
<P>
   It is Linc's daughter Rosalee (Tisha Campbell), an Army
lieutenant, who catalyzes tonight's premiere when she returns home
and informs her father that she believes she is gay. Linc doesn't
take it well; he prefers to see her as ``heterosexually
challenged,'' a condition he thinks he can reverse by finding the
right man for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let you watch `Lethal Weapon' far too many times,'' he
laments.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such one-liners, Linc is not a caricature of a
conservative. Williams endows him with a strength and humanity that
makes viewers confident that his love for his daughter will
eventually triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Grier, however, does not appear to have fully settled into her
role as Eleanor. The legendary star of ``Foxy Brown'' and the
recent ``Jackie Brown'' is a bit subdued, suggesting she is still
trying to find the character.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the cast is already hitting on all cylinders,
though. Their light touch will be needed, since upcoming episodes
will involve such heavy issues as gun control, religion, and
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Reid, who created ``Linc's'' along with Susan Fales-Hill,
was the force behind ``Frank's Place,'' a fine show set in an urban
restaurant that offered a look at black culture but was canceled
after one season in the mid 1980s. Here's hoping ``Linc's'' stays
open a lot longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
