<HEADLINE>
UN MONITORS ENVIRONMENT IN PARKS WORLDWIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have read that Al Gore gave the United Nations control of
46 national parks, including Yellowstone. Is this true? _ O.H.,
Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: This misapprehension comes from U.S. participation in a
U.N.-monitored effort to protect Yellowstone, the Grand Canyon and
many other historic and natural places around the world.
</P>
<P>
   These designated ``World Heritage'' or ``Biosphere Reserve''
sites are monitored by a U.N. group for compliance with
international environmental agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Host countries control their own lands but face a U.N. rebuke if
they fall out of compliance. In 1996, Yellowstone was declared a
``World Heritage Site in danger'' because of plans to reopen a mine
a few miles from the park's borders.
</P>
<P>
   Idaho Rep. Helen Chenoweth and others argue that the effort can
lead to ``unconstitutional restrictions on private property.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration sees it differently. ``This
administration has no intention of ceding sovereignty over U.S.
lands to international organizations,'' assistant Interior
Secretary George Frampton told Gannett News Service in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you allowed to visit the cemetery where Jean Harlow is
buried? _ R.J., Waco, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Public visits are allowed from 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. weekdays at
the Forest Lawn Cemetery in Glendale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Harlow and many other legendary performers are buried there,
including George Burns, Sammy Davis Jr., Clark Gable, Jimmy Stewart
and Spencer Tracy.
</P>
<P>
   Harlow's place of interment is the Great Mausoleum, which is in
a part of the cemetery that allows only family members after 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of celebrity burial sites are described at the World
Wide Web site www.findagrave.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What kind of car was featured in the movie ``Christine?'' _
M.S., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Christine was a ``Ford red'' 1958 Plymouth Fury, a model
that's a collector's item in real life because only 2,000 were
made.
</P>
<P>
   In Stephen King's book, Christine had four doors, but it was
changed to a two-door for the film because no four-door 1958 Furys
were ever built.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen 1958 Furys were destroyed in the making of the
film, according to the Internet Movie Database.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
