<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM BLINKED, AND THE STRIKE IS SETTLED _ FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   General Motors blinked this week, returning the controversial
dies to the plant from which they had been abducted, thus
triggering a lengthy, costly strike. By now, the agreement has been
signed and GM is slowly cranking up production of new models. There
was no victory in the agreement, only the postponement of
confrontation. GM did not learn to love or even live with its work
force, and the union still feels it has leverage with a company
that looks upon its labor as a commodity that's available much
cheaper elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   There are some mysteries left for us to ponder. For openers, how
much did the General actually lose? For more than a month, the
figure held at $1.2 billion in the media reports, although the
reporters every day told us the losses continued to climb.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, this week, it was reported to be a $2 billion loss; on
Thursday the New York Times said $3 billion. Yet, it was also
reported with some frequency that the losses amounted to some $80
million a day. Considering the duration of the strike, at that rate
the loss is more than $4.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street is content that profits are merely down for the
quarter _ does that mean the General made money during the strike?
</P>
<P>
   Note that during the discussion of losses, it was primarily
company losses that were discussed. The losses to the labor force
were mentionerd now and again. Never, however, in all of the
discussion of loss were you likely to hear about loss to the
nation, loss to the national industrial base.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who remember the mobilization of World War II and
recall that it was the automobile industry that virtually overnight
turned from building cars to building military might unparalleled
in history sense another kind of loss _ a much greater loss to the
nation. As the manufacturing base shifts to foreign shores, we lose
a means of creating national wealth and defending the national
existence.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another mystery of the GM-UAW confrontation to consider.
Why, with auto stocks dwindling and dealers in a position to
auction off that dwindling inventory to the highest bidder, was GM
still offering rebates on virtually everything it offers for sale?
If a company is losing money so fast during a labor dispute that it
must shut off the utilities and cancel executive travel, does it
make sense to pay someone $1,000 to buy a car?
</P>
<P>
   The big question: Where was Chairman Jack, the current Smith in
charge? Where has he been during all this labor strife? In the
bunker? GM has suffered a plague of Smiths _ Roger the Magnificent
Spender who squandered billions while losing market share steadily,
and Jack the Silent who sits mute while the sales attrition
continues.
</P>
<P>
   And what next?
</P>
<P>
   The GM board meets Monday; expect an announcement Tuesday. Don't
expect an announcement of a love-in with blue-collar labor. Do
expect a reorganization and more job cuts.
</P>
<P>
   I'm betting you'll see the demise of a couple of models, perhaps
a couple of divisions. And a shift of even more production outside
the United States borders. The way American trade law currently
stands, you can forge a widget in China, polish it in Canada, put
it in a sedan here, and count it as domestic content _ meaning
American made.
</P>
<P>
   What do we do when the Chinese and the Mexicans go on strike?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a cheerier note, August in New England offers the opportunity
to buy an antique car at auction, take up the congenial sport of
road rallying, or, if you own a V-12-powered automobile and have
around $3,500 in spare change rattling in your jeans, to sign up
for a 1,000-mile vintage autumn road rally designed for the
automotive sybarites among us.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Aug. 22, is the auction opportunity, at Owls Head
Transportation Museum where, as of this writing, some 66 vehicles
covering 1924 to the current year have been consigned for the
annual fund-raiser, New England Auction of Antique, Classic and
Special Interest Autos. A couple of Ford Model Ts, 1928
International truck, early Chevys, LaSalle, Packard, Marmon, Riley,
Jaguar, and Hudson are among the more interesting marques offered.
And there is the 1952 MG TD Mark II.
</P>
<P>
   The auction catalog, describing all the vehicles offered, is to
be available at $40 a copy, which includes two seats in the
reserved bidding section. For details on the auction, telephone the
museum at 207-594-4418 (fax 207-594-4410) or write to Owls Head
Transportation Museum, PO Box 277, Owls Head, ME 04854. For the
electronic set, e-mail address is ohtm(at)midcoats.com, and the
Internet site is http://www.ohtm.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rally opportunity comes Saturday, Aug. 29, in Connecticut as
the Sports Car Club of New England Road Rally Championship series
offers Hurdle '98. It is a 180-mile event begining and ending in
Southington, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   An SCCA rally is a competition, but it is not a race; the rally
is a time/distance/speed exercise in precision driving in several
classes, depending upon your experience. This one, in addition to
Novice Class for the neophytes, offers an F Class for first-time
rallyists.
</P>
<P>
   Registration and a rally school begin Friday evening, Aug. 28,
and registration continues from 7:30 a.m. until 8:30 a.m. Saturday.
First car is off the line at 8:31, and the last car is scheduled
across the finish at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Entries and questions should be directed to rallymasters Jon and
Kelli Lamkins, 77 Johanna Circle, Southington, CT 06489, or
telephone 860-747-9514. Or e-mail john.lamkins(AT)snet.net. All
that's needed are two people (one to drive, one to navigate), a
street-legal automobile and the entry fee _ $30 per car for SCCA
members, $35 nonmember. A copy of NER/SCCA rally regulations is
available at $4 per each.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Forza Mille V-12 is scheduled Oct. 4-9 through New England's
northern tier _ northern Maine, New Hampshire, and Vermont, with
stops at such fancy resorts as Samoset, Grand Summit, and The
Balsams, and Owls Head, Oxford Speedway and a lot of scenic byways
in the midst of autumn color.
</P>
<P>
   For details, write to Forze Mille V-12, c/o Rich and Jean
Taylor, Jackson Hill Road, Sharon, CT 06069, or telephone
800-645-6069. The $3,495 entry fee covers meals, lodging,
logistical support, security, and trained mechanics in attendance.
It's a benefit event that raises funds for a number of New England
charities. It's also fun on a grand scale.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
