<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-HOMELESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAIN OF JAPAN'S RECESSION FOUND IN TENTS, LEAN-TOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.  R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ For anyone familiar with Japan's glistening, seemingly
uniform prosperity, or with the care this rich nation pays to
promoting income equality, it is hard to believe the encampments of
the homeless along the Sumida River exist.
</P>
<P>
   But as countless unwitting commuters whizz along the elevated
Capital Highway, hundreds of destitute people live almost invisibly
underneath, in neatly lined-up cardboard boxes wrapped in
waterproof blue tarpaulins. Their numbers are echoed by thousands
more _ mostly older, jobless men _ scattered imperceptibly in a
handful of Tokyo's train stations, underpasses, and parks.
</P>
<P>
   The homeless problem is not new here, but it is growing and
claiming some unexpected victims. The homeless in Tokyo doubled in
the first half of this decade with the fizzling of Japan's
``bubble'' economy, to an estimated 10,000, and their ranks are
growing faster now as unemployment hits post-war records.
</P>
<P>
   These are the most extreme victims of Japan's worst recession in
23 years, and because of the huge value this society places on work
and group belonging, the suffering they endure can be as much
psychological as it is physical.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers have recently found a few ``salarymen'' still wearing
their company pins camped out on park benches. But most of the
homeless are blue-collar workers over age 50 who came here years
ago when jobs were plentiful. In the 1990s, manual work dried up,
and what is left is being offered to younger men.
</P>
<P>
   The plight of Tokyo's homeless is a window into two serious
problems underlying Japan's current economic malaise: the decline
of its once-dominant construction and manufacturing industries and
the rapid graying of its population. Unless the country is able to
restructure flailing industries while at the same time finding
resources to better serve its laid-off and elderly, it could face
mounting homelessness and other Western-style social problems that
it has long prided itself on avoiding.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is perhaps nowhere more evident than along a grim,
gray stretch of the Sumida riverbank, across from a gas refinery
and nondescript warehouses, in the Sanya district of Tokyo once
famous for day labor opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, welfare workers say, there was no cardboard community
here; today, an estimated 500 refrigerator cartons, lean-to tarps,
and plywood cubes serve as homes. To a Western eye, they may be
striking in their orderliness; brooms, umbrellas and clean
undershirts hang from clotheslines, water bottles for drinking and
washing are tied to the tarps, single-burner gas cookers are
common, and shoes are left outside boxes so as not to sully
mattresses inside.
</P>
<P>
   The occupants are mostly clean-shaven and polite men, such as
Kazuo Yamada, 56, who said he was laid off without a pension last
year from a job making car bodies for Mitsubishi. He has lived in a
blue nylon tent between two men in cartons for seven months, ever
since he ran out of money to pay rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be frank, this is the first time I've been unemployed,''
confided Yamada. ``I can't find anything. That's why I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   Yamada's story is not surprising given that Japan lost 630,000
manufacturing jobs from 1990 to 1997, and retraining is not highly
developed here.
</P>
<P>
   Government policy toward the displaced has been spotty at best.
Starting in 1993, the government spent millions of dollars to build
temporary apartments for the homeless to get them off the streets
in winter but tore down the buildings in spring because no
community wanted a year-round shelter.
</P>
<P>
   There are places, such as the government-run Johoku Fukushi
Social Welfare Center in Sanya, that give out vouchers for cheap
motels. But director Kunio Nozaki says the vouchers are a band-aid;
jobs are the only long-term solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if this recession ends, these people won't be able to get
jobs because of their age and lack of other skills,'' said a
dispirited Nozaki.
</P>
<P>
   At the peak of the bubble economy in 1988-89, the welfare center
had three times as many daily construction jobs on offer as
applicants. Since 1991, with the drop in property prices, building
has dropped off and machines have replaced people at work sites.
The center has seen a 20 percent jump in jobseekers this year but
will have only 11,000 jobs for 90,000 hopefuls in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Nozaki wants the government to create more jobs for the
displaced, such as cleaning up parks and cemeteries. But he
realizes that will not solve the underlying problem of an economy
in the doldrums. Since 1991, 110,000 small firms have shut down,
and many of their castoffs have settled here too.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most of the jobless do not apply for assistance. Single
mothers and children get cash benefits, but single laborers do not,
and many never worked at one place long enough to qualify for
national health or social security. Meanwhile, public and private
pensions are running out of funds; last year alone, 14 private
pension plans went broke.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 1 percent of Japanese are on welfare, Nozaki says.
Most men in Sanya ``are still hoping they can get a job. They still
have pride.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that almost half of Sanya's residents are now
working fewer than 10 days a month. Nozaki gestures out the window
at several old men sleeping on the pavement or weaving down the
alley, drunk on cheap rice wine, or ``sake,'' that is sold from
streetside vending machines. ``They have given up. This feeling
permeates everything here,'' he said. ``They're lonely, they have
no jobs, and they are getting desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Police Agency, unemployment and
bankruptcy are the causes of one in three suicides.
</P>
<P>
   For now, homelessness affects only a fraction of the population
and is isolated to a few areas. It is still nearly impossible to
find a panhandler in Tokyo. But these streets that were once noisy
with construction trucks begging for day laborers are now bereft of
activity. Sanya appears to be populated solely by slow-moving old
men.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's population is rapidly aging and birth rates are so low
that it is unclear who will support the elderly. Today, 21 percent
of Japan's population is over the age of 60. By 2020, that figure
is expected to jump to nearly one in three, versus 19 percent in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Most Japanese families have more elderly to care for than
children, and with the fracturing of extended families, more senior
citizens are finding themselves alone. In Tokyo, 14,000 people are
on waiting lists for public nursing homes. Others, like Sanya's
homeless, aren't even seeking help.
</P>
<P>
   A clean-cut, 65-year-old homeless man named Nakayama who was too
embarrassed to give his first name survives on food he scavenges
from the garbage. ``I go to the jobs center and I look on the
street for jobs, but I can't get any because of my age. I have a
dream of getting a job, but I don't think that dream will come
true.''
</P>
<P>
   Nakayama, who owned his own construction company before it went
bankrupt several years ago, has been living for 2 1/2 years in a
plywood shack. Carefully stacked on shelves he built are bread
loaves from volunteers, fruit and books rescued from a Dumpster and
cheap cooking pots. His tiny area reeks of rotting garbage, but he
keeps it clean with scouring powder and steel wool.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other men here, Nakayama has no interest in the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party choice for the new prime minister, Foreign
Minister Keizo Obuchi, because he can't see how it will affect his
life. ``Japanese politicians never do anything good for us, so I
don't care anymore,'' he said. ``Even with a new prime minister,
nothing will change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
