u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV02-B     07-31 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV02-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR BLACKS TO BRING CLARENCE THOMAS IN FROM THE COLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 02, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most remarkable political speeches in recent memory
sprang Wednesday from the lips of Clarence Thomas, the Supreme
Court justice who has been ostracized by a large and influential
faction of America's black leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pains me deeply,'' he told the largest convention of black
lawyers in Memphis, ``more deeply than any of you can imagine, to
be perceived by so many members of my race as being a harm.''
</P>
<P>
   A dozen people in his audience walked out, he was denounced from
the podium before he began his talk, and a number of prominent
blacks went out of their way to make clear they do not forgive his
apostasy.
</P>
<P>
   In the seven years since President Bush nominated him to replace
the revered and widely respected Thurgood Marshall, Thomas has
voted and written against some of the positions Marshall espoused.
</P>
<P>
   He is the most visible, and most powerful (with his one-ninth of
the highest court's clout) of the conservative black Americans who
were raised up in the Reagan years in an attempt by the GOP to
blunt the 10-1 advantage Democrats typically enjoy among black
voters.
</P>
<P>
   What made Thomas's speech at the National Bar Association so
poignant to me, as it was so painful to him, was the manner in
which he felt he had to beseech his own people for the most
elementary standards of acceptance, respect, and compassion. I have
never been a Thomas advocate. But the manner in which he has been
shunned by so many of his own race is disquieting and disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   Because America is such a broad and diverse land, we have
learned that it is dangerous to hold others hostage to our own
narrow views. Because of the distances and numbers involved, our
land cannot afford the narrow and brutal ultimatums that make much
smaller places like Northern Ireland, the Middle East, or the
Balkans such killing fields. It is in the Congress and the courts,
as well as in our national elections, where we thrash out the
differences, regional and racial, that would otherwise divide us at
our peril.
</P>
<P>
   It was race and class that were at the root of the civil war we
are still trying to get over. And it is race and class that still
bedevil us. By selecting Thomas, a little-known and unheralded
black conservative, George Bush did not do the country nor Thomas
any favors. His confirmation hearings were anguished, angry, and
abrasive. Anita Hill's tales of sexual exploitation made the Senate
Judiciary Committee squirm. I have talked with members of that
panel who still feel reputations were wrecked, and professional
lives were destroyed, as a result of those televised accusations
and denials.
</P>
<P>
   Not until this year's steamy Lewinsky business has the American
political process been so drenched in so much sordid sexual
sheepdip. The Thomas-Hill confrontation, which further divided
feminists (``I believe Anita'' was their bumper sticker) from
conservatives, was never adequately resolved, though he was
eventually confirmed. While his court colleagues accept him without
reservation, the public and blacks of influence are deeply divided.
</P>
<P>
   At the root of antipathy to Thomas is his resolute dismissal of
affirmative action as a legitimate tool to defuse centuries of
ingrained racial prejudice. He is still viewed by many as the
blackfaced tool by which clever white manipulators maneuver to
maintain a discredited antebellum status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Such a gross oversimplification, it goes without saying, does
credit to neither side in the querulous debate. But a large number
of black professionals made it out of the working class into the
middle class by being singled out young and early for the kinds of
extra push that affirmative action was invented for. And many of
those same successful blacks denounce Thomas as a traitor to his
race because of his philosophical objections to the way affirmative
action is implemented.
</P>
<P>
   For him to bow to the black majority view, Thomas argued
eloquently, would make him no more than ``an intellectual slave.''
His critics seem to want to deny him his ``humanity,'' he asserted,
to humbly ``follow the prescription asigned to blacks.'' It is that
very stereotype of the black slave bowing to superior force that
Thomas vows to reject, no matter what the personal cost.
</P>
<P>
   But he is clearly anguished over the personal rejections and
slights which have marred his career. ``All the sacrifice, all the
long hours studying, were to help, not to hurt,'' he pleaded.
``Despite some of the nonsense that has been said about me by those
who should know better ... the psycho-silliness ... I am a man, a
black man, an American.'' He all but begged for some sort of end to
his banishment from the salons of black acceptance. ``Isn't it time
to realize that being angry with me solves no problems?''
</P>
<P>
   He took a calculated risk in laying bare his heart, and some of
the most influential blacks in America still refuse to offer their
hand. In one 1996 survey of American blacks, he was viewed
negatively by 44 percent, positively by only 32. His harsh
criticism of black studies programs, and his hewing to
law-and-order positions that blacks think fall unduly on the
darker-hued, keep him out of the black mainstream. He once
denounced some black leaders as professional whiners who ``bitch,
bitch, moan and moan, whine and whine.''
</P>
<P>
   I think it's high time the black leadership relents, and invites
Clarence Thomas in from the cold. I would think more of them for
doing that, even as I continue to feel he is not my kind of Supreme
Court voter. That court and this country are big enough to tolerate
Thomas. Are the black leaders?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
