<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2477 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV02-B     07-31 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV02-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 02, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are feeling a little guilty that you are not lugging to
the beach a big serious book about political economy _ David
Landes' ``Wealth and Poverty of Nations,'' say, or ``The Commanding
Heights'' by Daniel Yergin and Joseph Stanislaw _ then I have a
suggestion. Read this column and relax.
</P>
<P>
   Herewith a list of 10 books that are at once weightier and less
fun. (With a single exception, they are university press books.) In
a more virtuous life, or in the fall perhaps, you might enjoy
reading any one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Each was written for a specialized audience. But each has
something to say bordering on news about a topic of general
interest. So they are digested here.
</P>
<P>
   Skim what you're missing, then go for a walk with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   (BOX)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Money Interest and The Public Interest,'' by Perry G.
Mehrling (Harvard University Press). This warm and humane biography
of three monetary economists whose careers spanned the last 100
years _ Allyn Young, Alvin Hansen, and Edward Shaw _ has a great
deal to say about action away from the ball. In this case it is the
efforts of three practical men to construe and fashion monetary
policy during the ``revolution'' and ``counterrevolution'' of John
Maynard Keynes and Milton Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technopols: Freeing Politics and Markets in Latin America in
the 1980s,'' edited by Jorge Dominguez (Penn State University
Press). It is early yet to expect anyone, even a journalist, to
pull together the similar yet different experiences of Argentina,
Mexico, Brazil, and Chile during their market-oriented
transformations. So editor Dominguez, professor of government at
Harvard University, has done the next best thing, coralling experts
to write engaging profiles of the technically skilled, politically
savvy leaders (``technopols'') who made them: Domingo Cavallo,
Pedro Aspe, Fernando Henrique Cardoso, Evelyn Matthei, and
Alejandro Foxley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dumaine's Amoskeag: Let the Record Speak,'' by Arthur M.
Kenison (St. Anselm College Press). The twinkly-eyed portrait of
Frederick C. (``Buck'') Dumaine is the key to this reinterpretation
of the career of New England's legendary asset stripper. The book
conveys admirably the feel of old New Hampshire. But even the most
sympathetic treatment can't turn Dumaine into a latter-day Aaron
Feurstein. In the depression of 1921 he tried to cut the hourly
wage at Amoskeag Mills by 35 percent while incresing the work week
to 54 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vietnam Military Lore: Legends, Shadows and Heroes,'' by Ray
Bows (Bows and Sons Publishing, Hanover, Mass.). This grand
adventure in self-publishing has a remarkable secret: in 53 war
stories and hundreds of photographs sprawling over 1,200 pages,
retired Special Forces master sergeant Bows has tracked down, often
in the unlikliest places, the stories of the fallen heroes for whom
American camps and airfields in Vietnam were named: an annotated
Wall of Remembrance for the home. What's the connection with
business? Same as anything having to do with America in Vietnam:
it's a vivid reminder of growing up in a certain way in the 1960s
at a key fork in the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demanding Medical Excellence: Doctors and Accountability in
the Information Age,'' by Michael L. Millenson (University of
Chicago Press). A former newspaper reporter tracks the revolution
in quality management and medical measurement, thereby providing a
highly readable and persuasive account of the reasons for the turn
to managed health care in the 1990s. It's more than your doctor is
likely to tell you about why he/she does what he/she does.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mutual Fund Business,'' by Robert C. Pozen (MIT Press).
What do you get when you ask Fidelity Management and Research Co.'s
top lawyer to teach a course on mutual funds? This combination
textbook and reader, designed to display the mutual fund industry
and many of its controversies, makes a good introduction and
reference book. It has a fair amount to say as well about Dreyfus
Corp., Vanguard Group, Putnam Cos., T. Rowe Price Associates, and
other giants of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Government in the Tropics,'' by Judith Tendler (The Johns
Hopkins University Press). It's a commonplace in mainstream
development thinking that the closer you get to the equator, the
worse governments are likely to be. Massachusetts Institute of
Technology professor Tendler argues the opposite _ that there is no
necessary connection and that the remarkable performance of the
small state Ceara in northeast Brazil demonstrates how a government
whose servants are thought to be slightly better than the rest _ as
civil service bureaucrats are thought to be in France or Japan _
can work well in a poor region, as long as the sense of chosenness
cuts across all categories of workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty Years in a Red House: A Memoir of Childhood and Youth
in Communist China,'' by Zhu Xiao Di (University of Massachusetts
Press). Ross Terrill says in his foreward, ``Sometimes one person's
story, like a single ray that bursts from a mirror as a powerful
wave of light, illuminates the life of an epoch and a nation.'' Zhu
Xiao Di was born in 1958. This matter-of-fact account of his
family's travails, especially during the Cultural Revolution (his
father was a prominent Communist official) is a splendid lesson in
20th century Chinese history, the next best thing to having had a
family friend all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Population Spike and After: Reflections on the 21st
Century,'' by W.W. Rostow (Oxford University Press). There is no
more ardent devotee of the Big Picture than Rostow, professor
emeritus of political economy at the University of Texas at Austin.
The great spike he discerns is in populatiuon growth rates: having
greatly speeded up during the past two centuries, they are about to
decelerate even more quickly. The earth's population will level off
at 10 billion by about 2050 as the birthrate drops, he expects;
thereafter, the global problem of an aging population dependent to
a smaller work force will make American, German, and Japanese
Boomers' problems with soicial security today look like kid stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Stream of Windows: Unsettling Reflections on Trade,
Immigration, and Democracy,'' by Jagdish Bhagwati (MIT Press).
Along with Paul Krugman and Alan Blinder, Bhagwati is at the top of
the class of smoothwriting economists. This collection of his
articles is an excellent tour d'horizon of trade and immigration
issues from the perspective of a former economic policy adviser to
the director general of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
