<HEADER>
A2505 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     07-31 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMRY? LEXUS? ONLY THE STICKER TELLS YOU FOR SURE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CARS-GLANCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it a Camry or a Lexus?
</P>
<P>
   Only a look at the nameplate _ or the sticker _ can tell you for
sure.
</P>
<P>
   Lexus, the upscale division of Japan's Toyota, rolled out an
all-new version of its entry-level ES 300 sedan in mid-1996 as an
early 1997 model.
</P>
<P>
   This bigger and better ES 300, with a 200-horsepower V-6 engine
and roomier interior, set the stage for a more important event for
Toyota: the introduction of the all-new midsize Camry sedan.
</P>
<P>
   That vehicle, which debuted in fall 1996 as a '97 model, took
the market by storm, giving the Camry its first win as the
best-selling car in the United States. It beat the Ford Taurus and
Honda Accord, whose sales had held first or second place most of
the previous decade.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the main reason the Camry finally beat the Taurus and
the Accord is that people who saw it and drove it came away knowing
that it was a Lexus in Toyota clothing.
</P>
<P>
   This trend of automakers cloning their niche-market upscale
brands to provide vehicles for their mass-market nameplates is
quite common. I mentioned a similar arrangement recently with the
Audi A4 and this year's new Volkswagen Passat, two vehicles that
share a chassis and drivetrain.
</P>
<P>
   As with the Audi and Passat, the Camry and ES 300 have some
differences. But other than the ritzy appeal of the Lexus
nameplate, there is little difference between a high-end Camry XLE
model ($24,868) and the ES 300 ($30,790) except the price. Add the
popular extras, such as leather interior and sun roof, and the
Lexus costs at least $5,000 more than a comparably equipped Camry.
</P>
<P>
   For value-conscious buyers, the choice is clear: Toyota wins
easily. The Camry is also a better bet for people who routinely
carry five adults; despite their nearly identical designs, the ES
300 has slightly less room in the rear than the Camry. That means
two adults can sit comfortably in the back seat of the Lexus, but
three is a tight fit.
</P>
<P>
   There's a difference in the trunk, too: 13 cubic feet of space
in the ES 300 vs. 14.1 cubic feet in the Camry.
</P>
<P>
   You don't even have to buy the most expensive Camry to get a car
that's very Lexuslike. We tested a midlevel, four-cylinder Camry LE
(base price $20,218) back-to-back with an ES 300, and found the
Camry to be an exceptionally good buy.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the four-cylinder engine _ with 133 horsepower and 147
foot-pounds of torque _ isn't quite up to the speed of the V-6
engine that is standard in the Lexus and optional in Camry. But the
extra power really isn't necessary; stick with the four-cylinder if
price is a consideration. Just to upgrade to the V-6 in the Camry
LE costs an additional $2,340.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the low price of the LE four-cylinder, you get the same
four-speed automatic transmission of the Lexus, as well as power
windows and door locks, cruise control, power dual outside mirrors,
air-conditioning and lots more.
</P>
<P>
   Leather is optional on the Lexus ($1,650) and the Camry LE
($1,100).
</P>
<P>
   Now, with all of that in mind, why bother buying the Lexus? If
you have the extra bucks, the ES 300 is a good buy even though it's
basically the same car.
</P>
<P>
   First, it will have a better resale value because of the Lexus
name. Second, it has a lot more standard or available extras, such
as automatic air-conditioning, side-impact air bags (new for 1998),
and a great stereo-system upgrade: a 215-watt Nakamichi
AM/FM/cassette unit with a remote-control six-disc CD changer
conveniently mounted in the glove box. That unit costs $1,600 and
comes with seven speakers, including a subwoofer. But even the base
Pioneer AM/FM/cassette in the Lexus is better than the stereo in
the Camry. (You can add a six-disc changer for $1,050 in the Lexus
or $650 in the Camry).
</P>
<P>
   The side-impact air bags are optional on all Camry models, but
standard in the Lexus.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could tell you that the ride in the Lexus is quieter
than the Camry's, but I couldn't tell a difference. Both are so
quiet even at highway speeds that you can carry on a conversation
at whisper level. These are two of the quietest vehicles on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the rides in both cars are cushy. But Lexus offers an
uplevel variable-suspension system ($600) that has four
driver-adjustable modes: soft, normal, sport or hard. The soft
setting is comparable to the Camry's ride; the firmer settings
allow for better cornering and more road feel.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel is also a consideration. The four-cylinder Camry is rated
at 23 miles per gallon in the city and 30 mpg on the highway, and
it burns regular unleaded gasoline. The V-6 in the Camry and the ES
300 is EPA rated at 19 mpg in the city and 26 on the highway, and
premium fuel is recommended. (Both come with an 18.5-gallon tank).
</P>
<P>
   My advice is to buy the Lexus if price is no object and you
don't need the bigger back seat and trunk of the Camry. But if you
want to save money, try a Camry equipped to the level your budget
can handle, and enjoy an almost-Lexus for a lot less money.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, you can't go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're having trouble making up your mind, check out the
full-size Toyota Avalon, which we also recently tested. It's built
on the same chassis as the Camry and ES 300, although it's
stretched a bit.
</P>
<P>
   This is the most luxurious Toyota available; it sells for
$24,278 to about $30,000, and has more room than the Camry or the
ES 300.
</P>
<P>
   A HYBRID TOYOTA: The Prius, a Corolla-size Toyota that uses an
electric motor and a 1.5-liter gasoline engine, will go on sale in
the United States in fall 2000, the automaker announced last week.
</P>
<P>
   The car operates on zero-emissions electric power under 30 miles
per hour, perfect for crowded city streets, but switches to
gasoline power at higher speeds _ usually on less-busy (and
less-polluted) highways.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota will initially earmark 20,000 of these vehicles a year
for North America and Europe. It has been on sale in Japan since
December at a reasonable price of about $15,500. (The biggest
problem with electric vehicles, other than their limited range on
battery power, has been their prohibitive cost).
</P>
<P>
   The Prius doesn't have to be plugged into an electrical outlet
to be recharged; its batteries charge while the gasoline engine is
running. That means that you're not stuck if the batteries run
down; just fire up the gas engine and keep going.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota claims fuel economy of up to 66 miles per gallon with a
combination of both power sources.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned: I will test-drive the Prius this month when Toyota
brings it to Fort Worth-Dallas for a media program.
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Check out his Wheelin' new-car review column
weekly on the Internet at
ww.netarrant.net/today/news/opinions/necol.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
