r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PREVIEW-OF-EARTH'S-DE     07-31 0332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREVIEW-OF-EARTH'S-DESTRUCTION-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EARTH COULD BE IN FOR AN ELECTRIFYING TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By HAZEL MUIR  
 Copyright 1998 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A star in the constellation Draco may be giving us a glimpse of
the Earth's future 4.5 billion years hence, when the Sun swells up
into a red giant, say astrophysicists in Canberra.
</P>
<P>
   If the Sun grows large enough, the Earth's atmosphere and
surface will be stripped away. But its iron and nickel core might
survive, as the Sun shrinks back to become a white dwarf star the
size of Venus.
</P>
<P>
   Jianke Li, Lilia Ferrario and Dayal Wickramasinghe of the
Australian National University, think a white dwarf called GD356,
65 light years away, has gone down a similar path. White dwarfs
sometimes have powerful magnetic fields, and Li says these would
induce huge electrical currents in the metal core of any planet
circling the star. The currents would flow between the star and the
planet, carried by the ionized gases surrounding the star.
</P>
<P>
   The team's calculations, due to appear in Astrophysical Journal
Letters, show that such electrical currents could excite hydrogen
atoms in the poles of GD356 to emit frequencies of light which
would be polarized by the star's magnetic fields. Until now the
polarized light emitted by the star has defied explanation.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is intriguing, says James Liebert of the University of
Arizona in Tucson, who has studied GD356 since its discovery in the
1980s. ``I have seen no viable alternative idea proposed to explain
this unique star.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
