<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUYER BEWARE: HANSON LETTERS INSIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I am going to sell two of my computers. I want
to make sure absolutely none of my files are accessible or
retrievable. Someone told me that formatting the hard drive will
erase everything permanently. Is this correct?
</P>
<P>
   _Privacy Please
</P>
<P>
   DEAR PRIVACY: Afraid someone's going to stumble across those fan
letters to Hanson? You have every right to be worried.
</P>
<P>
   Formatting the drive is generally enough to discourage most
normal people. However, you can bet the FBI has a whole room full
of guys dressed like the Blues Brothers who have ways of
resurrecting all your embarrassing secrets. If you're worried about
things like that, you can use these procedures I found at the Naval
Surface Warfare Center's Web site while looking for nuclear secrets
to sell to Third World tinhorn dictators. Maybe I shouldn't have
told you that last part.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, here's how the Navy would do it, because you never can
tell when Saddam Hussein will show up at the surplus store. First,
make yourself an MS-DOS bootable diskette on an unclassified
system. Your mom's computer will do. Then copy Fdisk.exe and
Format.exe from the DOS directory to the diskette. If you have a
SCSI hard drive, you'll need the low-level format program that came
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Now go find a copy of Norton Utilities (version 8 for DOS _ yes,
DOS _ or earlier) and copy Wipeinfo.exe, Wipeinfo.hlp, Nlib200.rtl,
Nusetup.cfg and Diskedit.exe to the floppy and write-protect it by
sliding the little black tab so that the square holes on either
side of the disk are open. Oh, go look at a diskette to see what I
mean.
</P>
<P>
   I'll skip the Windows NT stuff the swabbies go through since it
probably doesn't apply to you. Boot with the floppy, then run
Fdisk. Follow the on-screen menu to delete all disk partitions and
drives. When they're all gone, create a new partition _ or more
than one if your drive is bigger than 2 GB _ and run Format.exe on
it. If you have a SCSI, use its format program instead.
</P>
<P>
   Now make Saddam really have to work for it by typing in Wipeinfo
/gov:c, which overwrites the drive with twice as much meaningless,
random garble as the Navy actually requires, making it the ideal
speech generator for Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure for Macs is pretty much the same: reformat, then
run the Mac version of Wipeinfo.
</P>
<P>
   If you're still worried, use Diskedit to randomly verify that
sectors have been overwritten. As long as you're doing it the Navy
way, make sure to document the procedure in triplicate. The yellow
copy goes to CINCPAC, the blue to ECOMCON and the pink to that
suspicious-looking yeoman with the Iraqi accent.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and you should probably take the ``Hanson Rules'' bumper
sticker off the computer while you're at it.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: How can I eliminate the sign-on that comes up
every time I boot Windows 95? There is no reason we would ever want
it in our household.
</P>
<P>
   _ Too Many Keystrokes
</P>
<P>
   DEAR TOO: It's refreshing to see a family that has no secrets,
with a relationship built on trust and mutual respect. So how did
you manage to get your letter through that rift in the space-time
continuum all the way from the '50s?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, go to Network in the Control Panel and make sure your
primary log-on is set to Windows Logon. Then go to the Password
icon to change your Windows password. Leave the blanks empty, even
when you have to verify the password, and you shouldn't be bothered
again. Is that homemade apple pie I smell?
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
