<HEADER>
A2579 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-31 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READERS RELATE THEIR TALES OF WINDOWS 98 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Recent issues of online and computer trade publications are
brimming with horror stories about Windows 98 upgrades gone bad. A
check of Usenet news groups and other discussion forums devoted to
Microsoft Corp.'s new consumer operating system also reveal cries
of pain.
</P>
<P>
   However, Microsoft insists that everything is peachy in
Windowsland. The company says it's getting a third fewer requests
for technical support than it did with Windows 95. That's despite
the fact that Windows 98 is selling at about the same pace as
Windows 95 in its early days.
</P>
<P>
   So what's going on here? Is Windows 98 a flawed upgrade, or are
we merely hearing a small percentage of squeaky wheels demanding
grease?
</P>
<P>
   Usually, when there are problems with an operating system
upgrade, I'll hear about it from readers via e-mail. But in the
days and weeks that followed the release of Windows 98, I received
not a single complaint. The silence, as they say, was deafening.
Either those who'd tried Windows 98 were completely happy, or their
computers were so messed up that they couldn't send e-mail and were
too depressed to call me on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to get to the bottom of this, I asked readers to tell
me about their experiences upgrading to Windows 98, whether good or
bad. I received about 50 e-mail and fax responses.
</P>
<P>
   About three-fourths said the installation went smoothly, with
only minor problems if any. Those users seemed fairly happy with
the upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   An Austin, Texas, woman's ebullient response was typical. ``I've
installed Windows 98 on several machines now, and each one has been
a breeze. I had a minor problem, which turned out to be due to old
drivers I was using for specific hardware. Once I downloaded the
newer drivers, ''voila!`` I'm looking forward to upgrading many
more! I've been telling all my friends to make the change. In a
nutshell, Windows 98 rocks!!''
</P>
<P>
   Whether a problem was minor depended on the sophistication of
the user. While this woman saw a modem-driver issue as a stroll in
the park, others considered the same problem as a barefoot marathon
over broken glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me two days to get Windows 98 to set up my US Robotics
Sportster Winmodem,'' wrote one man. ``It was a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the respondents, though, were in dire straits.
Windows 98 caused major problems for them, ranging from completely
hosed installations to systems that crashed with regularity. In
many cases, this group beat a hasty retreat to their original
Windows 95 installations.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most common problems in this category involved
Windows 98 stopping dead in its tracks in the middle of the
installation process. This left users in a kind of operating system
limbo, stuck between Windows 95 and 98 and often unable to fully
boot their systems.
</P>
<P>
   Often, these people tried getting through to Microsoft's
technical support via phone, and found themselves on hold for
extended periods of time and eventually giving up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Installing the upgrade was definitely a nightmare,'' wrote a
Bellville, Texas, man. ``It was on a Compaq Presario 1620 notebook.
The first part went smoothly, but 19 percent of the way through
copying files it just stopped copying files. After 30 minutes of no
activity, I called Microsoft support. Ironically, a screen touting
`More reliable than ever,' or something to that effect, was frozen
on the monitor.''
</P>
<P>
   One man, who was trying to install Windows 98 on several
computers at work, didn't set his expectations too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our experience with the upgrade from 95 to 98 went as
anticipated,'' he wrote. ``It didn't work, and we couldn't get
through to Microsoft for support.''
</P>
<P>
   There were two specific problems that seemed to crop up
repeatedly in mail from readers and in online forums. The first
involves modems _ Windows 98 seems to be having a hard time in
general recognizing modems properly. This is surprising because
Windows 95 was pretty good at it.
</P>
<P>
   The other, and more serious, involves lockups during
installation. In many cases, the only solution was to reinstall
Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   I ran these problems by Microsoft spokesman Ryan James, and he
came back with information that might help users who plan to
upgrade to Windows 98. James pointed me to articles in the
Microsoft Knowledge Base, the same database of issues that
Microsoft's tech support uses. It's available online at
support.microsoft.com.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Windows 98 may incorrectly detect a modem if the
driver on your system is used for several different kinds of
modems. The solution is to get a Windows 98-specific driver from
the modem's manufacturer, or manually detect the modem instead of
letting Windows 98 do it for you. (Use the Modems module in the
Control Panel, and choose the ``Don't detect my modem ...''
option.)
</P>
<P>
   The problem of lockups during installation may be caused by a
virus checker left running, either via the AUTOEXEC.BAT file or
from Windows itself. Virus checkers and all programs that run in
the background should be disabled before installing any operating
system upgrade. It's a good idea to get down to the simplest system
configuration possible, then re-enable your bells and whistles once
everything is working properly.
</P>
<P>
   However, even if users are diligent, there may be a hidden trap
waiting to trip them up. It seems that some computers have a
rudimentary form of virus-checking built into their hardware that
prevents Windows 95 and 98 from configuring the hard drive. Before
installing Windows 98, check the BIOS settings (you can find out
how to get into them by reading your computer's manual) and disable
virus-checking if it's turned on.
</P>
<P>
   The Knowledge Base includes a general page that links to
specific Windows 98 troubleshooting tips. The page can be found
atsupport.microsoft.com/support/kb/articles/q187/6/02.asp.
</P>
<P>
   If you're considering upgrading to Windows 98, you also might
want to read a column I wrote on strategies for a successful
upgrade at
www.chron.com/content/chronicle/tech/98/06/26/compute.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
