voted repeatedly Friday to shield a bipartisan campaign finance
bill from a final onslaught of amendments, making it all but
certain that the measure will win final House passage. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-RUSSIA (Washington) _ An IBM subsidiary plead guilty Friday
to illegally exporting 17 advanced computers to a Russian nuclear
weapons laboratory and agreed to pay a $8.5 million fine, in what
is believed to be the first criminal conviction against the
corporate giant. By Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ President Clinton, commenting
publicly for the first time about the Aug. 17 testimony his lawyers
fought to avoid, said he will ``completely and truthfully'' answer
prosecutors' questions about Monica Lewinsky. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL-SHOOTING (Washington) _ Officer Jacob Chestnut of the
Capitol Police was laid to rest in Arlington National Cemetery
under skies streaked with gray following an emotion-drenched
funeral during which hundreds of police officers laughed and wept
alongside dozens of members of Congress. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-ID (Washington) _ The Clinton administration temporarily
backed away from its plan to assign every American a computerized
code that would be used to track medical records from birth to
death, saying the ``unique health identifier'' would be put on hold
until Congress passes comprehensive legislation to protect patient
privacy. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CORMORANT-SLAYING (Dateline to kum, N.Y.) _ In the largest
mass-killing of a federally protected species, 1,000 cormorants
were shot in Lake Ontario near Watertown, N.Y., apparently because
they had been eating too many of the wide-mouthed bass that
fisherman also crave. Masses of dead and dying birds _ almost all
of them fledgling young that were not able to fly were discovered
on Wednesday on Little Galloo Island by two New York state
biologists. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
