<HEADLINE>
LOOK AT THE DOT PITCH, RESOLUTION WHEN SHOPPING FOR PC MONITOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I'm in the market for a new computer monitor, and I've been
shopping around. I understand about screen resolution and dot
pitch, but I get the feeling there are other things to pay
attention to. What other specs matter?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm glad you're taking the time to understand about monitors.
Unfortunately, most people who buy a PC approach a monitor as an
afterthought. Or, even worse, they see it as a category in which
they can cut costs by buying cheap.
</P>
<P>
   However, a monitor is one of four key components through which
users interact with a PC, including the keyboard, mouse and
speakers. Cheap out on the monitor, and the result is eyestrain and
headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Dot pitch (the distance between the tiny dots that make up an
image on a screen) and resolution (the number of dots, or pixels,
expressed both horizontally and vertically) are indeed important.
As you've read on these pages many times before, a smaller dot
pitch is better _ look for a maximum of a .28 dot pitch (or a .25
stripe pitch, if you are considering a monitor that uses a Sony
Trinitron tube). For resolution, you want a screen that will handle
at least 1,280-by-1,024 pixels. The bigger the resolution, the more
space you'll have on your screen for multiple applications.
However, as you increase the resolution, objects, such as icons and
text, will get smaller.
</P>
<P>
   When shopping for a monitor, see what it looks like at a variety
of resolutions, ranging from 640-by-480 to 800-by-600 to
1,024-by-768. On larger monitors, such as 19 inches and higher,
check out 1,152-by-864 and up.
</P>
<P>
   You should also look at the refresh rate _ how fast the screen
is redrawn _ which is expressed in hertz. You want as high a
refresh rate as possible for the highest resolution the monitor can
handle. Look for a refresh rate across all resolutions of at least
72 hertz, which is the point at which the human eye no longer sees
that annoying onscreen flickering. Some monitors can handle refresh
rates of 120 hertz and higher, but you should be happy in the 75-85
hertz range.
</P>
<P>
   Another aspect to consider is convergence _ how well the red,
green and blue electron guns in a monitor are able to focus on one
pixel. If these guns don't converge well on that single point, you
end up with a fuzzy image and pixels that aren't quite true white.
</P>
<P>
   Check out how text appears on the edge of the monitor, and avoid
those with text that appears fuzzy.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to play with a monitor's controls. Most monitors now
have onscreen menus that guide you through tweaking and resizing
the image. Poorly designed menus can drive you nuts, so make sure
you inspect the way they are laid out.
</P>
<P>
   The level of brightness and contrast is often a matter of
personal choice, so make sure you are comfortable with these
settings.
</P>
<P>
   Also, be aware that the stated size of the monitor includes part
of the screen covered by the bezel around the edges of the cathode
ray tube. So, a 17-inch monitor usually has a viewing area in the
15.5-inch range.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I had a hard drive crash last week and am in the process of
restoring it all. But I have a nagging problem under dial-up
networking. A little black window pops up asking for log in and
password info. The window is ``post dial terminal screen.'' Had
this problem once before but cannot find the fix for it.
</P>
<P>
   A: Look in the Dial Up Networking folder for the connection icon
that's giving you problems, right-click on it and choose
Properties. The bottom half of the box that appears shows the kind
of modem you're using _ click on the Configure button. Then, click
on the Options tab. One of the options you'll find is ``Bring up
terminal window after dialing.'' Uncheck that box, and you should
be fine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
