<HEADLINE>
DESPITE `ALL THE GOLD,' GATLIN SAVED BY FAITH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry Gatlin, the Grammy Award-winning country music singer,
already had hit records such as ``Broken Lady'' and ``All the Gold
in California,'' when drugs and alcohol began taking him down a
disastrous path.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a mess, wasn't I?'' Gatlin said in an interview this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Gatlin tells about it in a new book, ``All the Gold in
California,'' named after the song, released by Thomas Nelson
Publishing. It's a story, fortunately, with a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of his faith, family and loyal friends, the singer
recovered in time to save both his marriage and his career.
</P>
<P>
   He got help along the way from former University of Texas
football coach Darrell Royal and television personality Kathie Lee
Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just like Lou Gehrig,'' said Gatlin, quoting Gehrig when
the baseball legend knew he was dying of a rare muscle disease. ``I
consider myself the luckiest man on the face of the Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Gatlin is a West Texan, born in Seminole, northwest of Fort
Worth, and reared in Abilene, Olney and Odessa. He went to the
University of Houston on a football scholarship and was headed for
law school. But he had been singing in public since childhood and
was destined for an entertainment career.
</P>
<P>
   He began as a gospel singer and was trying out as a singer with
the Imperials when he met the late Dottie West. She hired him as a
songwriter in Nashville while he was working as a janitor. The
Gatlin Brothers burst on the scene with a series of hit records in
the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   And cocaine and alcohol became a part of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting high in places all over the world was fun,'' he said
this week. ``It's very alluring. But all of a sudden the drugs stop
working, the alcohol stops working and it finally becomes a hellish
experience of having to have it every day.''
</P>
<P>
   He found himself at his lowest point in 1984 after he performed
in Dallas and then began bingeing on alcohol and cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was crawling around on my hands and knees looking for little
pieces of cocaine,'' Gatlin says in his book. ``I crawled into the
bathroom and caught a glimpse of the devil in the mirror. Surely
this reflection in the glass was not Larry Wayne Gatlin, good
Christian boy from good Christian parents.''
</P>
<P>
   He got on his knees and prayed, ``God, if you don't help me, I'm
going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Gatlin said God did help him. He somehow got packed, made his
way to a cab and asked to be taken to Dallas/Fort Worth Airport so
he could fly home to Nashville. But he had no money to pay the
fare.
</P>
<P>
   Finally the driver, who didn't recognize Gatlin at first, gave
him credit after Gatlin sang a line from ``All the Gold in
California.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, with gentle persuasion from Royal, Gatlin agreed to
go to a drug treatment center in California. He credits prayer with
ending his desire for cocaine and alcohol. After becoming free of
drugs and alcohol, he continued his career, starring in ``The Will
Rogers Follies'' on Broadway and appearing in the movie ``The
Dottie West Story.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his brother retired from the road five years ago and have
a theater in Myrtle Beach, S.C. Larry Gatlin, who lives in Austin
and attends the Riverbend Church where the Rev. Gerald Mann is
pastor, has a new gospel album. He has written a musical, ``Texas
Flyer,'' based on his childhood memories. It had a nine-week run in
Houston, and he hopes it eventually will be seen on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Gatlin's autobiography, which has a foreword by singer Johnny
Cash, is an attempt to help others who get caught in the snare of
drug addiction, Gatlin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want this book to tell people _ no matter who they are or
what condition they are in _ that it is never too late to turn to
your heavenly Father.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
