<HEADLINE>
1999 SAAB 9-3: A SOLID BREAKAWAY FROM THE COOKIE CUTTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2)  
 (af)  
 By FRED BROCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Saab introduced its redesigned 900 in 1994, cheers quickly
turned to groans among many die-hard fans of the Swedish icon. They
thought that the car didn't seem as tough or as durable as its
predecessor; they complained that it lacked the traditional solid
feel of a Saab.
</P>
<P>
   Since General Motors acquired 50 percent of the company four
years earlier, many of the traditionalists concluded that Saab,
which had maintained a distinctive character in a sea of generic
look-alikes, had succumbed to Americanization.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for its 1999 model year, Saab has tweaked the 900 in an
effort to counter those concerns. The car, which went on sale in
May, even has a new name _ the 9-3. It's part of a one-two punch by
Saab to revive its lagging sales and re-establish itself as a
leader in auto technology.
</P>
<P>
   In April, it introduced the 9-5, a new high-end model that
replaces the 9000 and competes with luxury sedans like the BMW
5-Series.
</P>
<P>
   But while the 9-5 is impressive to drive, if not daringly
styled, Saab is clearly counting on the 9-3 to put it back in the
good graces of its loyal customer base. It just might work: while
the 9-3 looks much the same as the 900, Saab has made a number of
technical modifications that add up to an impressive overall
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The car comes with an array of standard equipment and its
pricing is fairly aggressive. Including destination charges, the
suggested retail price ranges from $26,050 for the three-door
hatchback to $32,050 for the five-door hatchback SE.
</P>
<P>
   The two convertible models are $37,050 and $42,050. After taking
into account equipment that is standard on the new models but was
optional on the 900, all but the three-door hatchback are less
expensive _ the five-door hatchback by nearly 9 percent. Prices of
the other models are down by around 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   All 9-3s come with a 185-horsepower, 2-liter turbo-charged
four-cylinder engine previously available only on the 900 SE. While
the flagship 9-5 features a smoothly integrated and very civilized
light-pressure turbo-charger, the 9-3 has the kick of a full-boost
turbo.
</P>
<P>
   This maintains Saab's hallmark of maximum torque at low engine
revolutions, making the car fast off the mark. The 9-3 hits its
maximum torque of 194 foot-pounds at just 2,100 rpm with a
five-speed manual transmission; with a four-speed automatic, the
maximum is 170 foot-pounds at 2,000 rpm. The 9-3 manual accelerates
from zero to 60 miles an hour in about 7 seconds; the automatic,
according to Saab's data, takes 8 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The interior maintains the previous, clean design, with
logically placed switches and controls. The driver's area has the
look and feel of an airplane cockpit. The front seats are wider and
have longer bottom cushions, and they are extremely comfortable,
providing just the right amount of firmness without being
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I found the 9-3s seats to be more comfortable than the
bigger, more expensive seats in the 9-5. The rear seats have ample
leg and head room.
</P>
<P>
   But I had a couple of nits about the interior. The optional
compact-disk player is just $100 extra. At that price, why not just
include it so a buyer is not left with a nickeled-and-dimed
feeling? My guess is that the CD player will become a dealer
giveaway to clinch sales.
</P>
<P>
   The other involves cup holders, or the lack thereof. Europeans
can like it or not, but these gadgets are important to many
American commuters. And Saab just doesn't seem to get it: The 9-3
has a cup holder between the front seats that only the rear
passengers can use easily.
</P>
<P>
   (At least the 9-5 has a cleverly designed holder that pops out
of the dash and is convenient for the driver.)
</P>
<P>
   But these irritations melted away as I eased a 9-3 SE with a
manual transmission onto Route 3 in New Jersey and headed east for
the 12-mile drive to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The car zipped and maneuvered effortlessly through traffic.
Unlike the light-pressure turbo on the 9-5, the full-boost version
on the 9-3 was more forceful but produced a ``turbo lag'' _ that
split-second delay between when you kick the accelerator and when
the turbo-charger fully kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a little getting used to, and the only way to avoid it
is to keep the engine revved up above 2,000 rpm _ not a very
practical or economical solution.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, once you're accustomed to the lag it becomes part of the
driving experience, and a lot of turbo enthusiasts actually like
it.
</P>
<P>
   For those Saab owners, myself included, who were disappointed
with the redesigned 900 of 1994, the 9-3 is a welcome return to
better days. Changes in the chassis, steering, struts, springs and
shock absorbers have eliminated the last 900's light feeling and
helped restore the car's traditional solid demeanor without
sacrificing a smooth ride.
</P>
<P>
   Steering improvements are especially noticeable, a result of
altering the steering ratio for quicker and more precise response.
And longer-travel front struts help make the car less choppy over
bumps.
</P>
<P>
   The car climbs hills like a champ, and the manual transmission's
five speeds have a very wide range. The hydraulically operated
clutch and four-wheel antilock disk brakes do their jobs without
effort or complaint.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Saab's safety features are outstanding. The 9-3 has
front and side air bags, and its crashworthiness has been further
refined to direct the forces of a crash downward to the floor and
away from passengers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, both the 9-3 and the 9-5 include Saab's new
``active'' head restraints to help protect against whiplash: if the
car is hit from the rear, the front headrests pop up and forward to
cradle the heads of the driver and passenger.
</P>
<P>
   And the side-view mirror on the passenger side is ``split'' in
such a way as to provide a 30 percent wider field of view,
eliminating a common blind spot for drivers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: For once, past performance really does guarantee
future returns. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
