<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILL-CONCEIVED RULES REGARDING SICK DAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A craftsman who works for one of Houston's biggest
companies said he is pressured to take a day of vacation when he
calls in sick.
</P>
<P>
   Companies claim they're family-friendly, he said, asking not to
be identified, yet they want you to use a day you'd normally spend
with your family when you're really sick.
</P>
<P>
   In their zeal to cut costs, some companies have zeroed in on
absenteeism. And many have instituted strict sick leave policies
that leave workers yelling for mercy.
</P>
<P>
   The craftsman said he and his co-workers are frightened of
layoffs and worry that the amount of sick time an employee uses
will be a major factor as to who stays and who goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our foremen have become doctors now,'' the craftsman said.
They diagnose illnesses, deciding whether an employee's malady is
enough to get a day off.
</P>
<P>
   By putting so much pressure on employees not to take the sick
leave they've earned, workers are pushed to lie about themselves,
said Daryl Koehn, director of the Center for Business Ethics
Studies at the University of St. Thomas in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   They are sick, but they are telling the world they are ``on
vacation,'' Koehn said. Businesses are sending out a double signal:
They complain about people lying on their resumes, but now they
want their employees to lie on their time sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Many managers get a bonus for good attendance in their
departments, prompting some companies to design programs that put
subtle pressure on employees.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, for example, give an annual banquet or pass out
$50 bonuses if employees meet attendance goals, said E. Dale
Wortham, assistant business manager for the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers Local 716.
</P>
<P>
   Employees like the perks, so if Joe Blow gets pneumonia, all of
a sudden he's the black sheep of the family, Wortham said. That way
the company doesn't have to be the bad guy _ it has all the
employees enforcing the goals.
</P>
<P>
   Wortham said that many of the programs he sees that discourage
employees from using their sick leave usually come from human
resource managers who're trying to improve productivity. And they
often backfire.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies require an employee to be off for two days before
he is paid for any sick leave. That just encourages the two-day
flu, Wortham said, because employees stay out both days to get
paid.
</P>
<P>
   That's true, said Chuck Niederhofer, director of human resources
for Williams Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Union-represented employees are not paid for the first day
they're sick, so they tend to stay out a second day because they're
annoyed, said Niederhofer. He said the program was designed by a
previous administration to reduce absenteeism.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a lot of pressure on school teachers not to call
in sick, said Gayle Fallon, president of the Houston Federation of
Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, because of a handful of ``anal retentive principals,''
who were trying to reduce absenteeism, teachers were told they
could no longer report their illness to an automated system, said
Fallon, who represents about 5,000 teachers in the Houston
Independent School District. The system was great, she said,
because teachers could chose a substitute and leave detailed lesson
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Now, teachers must call in to the school and talk to a
secretary, who relays the message, Fallon said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the teachers dislike the new system _ now it's the
principal's or secretary's job to find a substitute and explain the
lesson plan _ and it never dawned on HISD that they have to pay
overtime for the secretaries to take all the sick calls, she said.
</P>
<P>
   HISD press secretary Terry Abbott said it's more difficult to
fake an illness if a teacher actually talks to a principal or
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   At the city of Houston's public works and engineering
department, employees must notify their supervisor 24 hours in
advance if they plan to be sick to avoid an ``occurrence,'' said
Faye Cole, executive director of the American Federation of State,
County and Municipal Workers Local 1550 in Houston. Too many
``occurrences'' and an employee is fired, she said.
</P>
<P>
   To fight back, Cole told the employees she represents to notify
their supervisor each day that they planned to be sick the
following day. That way, if an employee took sick, he'd be covered.
Cole said the department threatened to cite the union for ``abusive
sick leave'' but there was one catch: No one actually called in
sick.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Vara, human resources director for the city, said he
believes the 24-hour notice, if true, is overstepping reasonable
bounds and he is looking into the situation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
