<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2646 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON01-COX     07-31 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHITE HOUSE TO STAY MUM ON LEWINSKY UNTIL CLINTON TESTIFIES
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vowing to testify ''completely and truthfully''
about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, President Clinton on
Friday ruled out any other comment on the matter until he faces
questions from federal prosecutors Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision to button up and hunker down over the next
two weeks was aimed at tamping down the media clamor for demands
for comment on the latest developments in independent counsel
Kenneth Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is probing allegations that Clinton had an Oval Office
affair with Lewinsky then later urged her to lie about it _ charges
the president has denied.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one wants to get this matter behind us more than I do _
except maybe all the rest of the American people,'' Clinton told
reporters in the White House Rose Garden, after making brief
remarks about the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am looking forward to the opportunity in the next few days
of testifying. I will do so completely and truthfully. I am anxious
to do it,'' Clinton said, ignoring questions shouted at him about
the issue. ''But I hope you can understand why, in the interim, I
can and should have no further comment on these matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Clinton's remarks, presidential spokesman Michael
McCurry told reporters gathered around his desk that the White
House press office would also go dark on the Lewinsky matter until
Clinton's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not in a position to answer any Lewinsky questions. I
don't have any information,'' said McCurry. ''I don't expect to
have any information before Aug. 17.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry told reporters he was leaving Friday for a two-week
vacation _ ''I'll be so far in the deep hollows of South Carolina
you won't be able to find me,'' he said _ and urged journalists to
do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's not much that's going to happen on this matter in the
next 10 days to two weeks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks might have been as much wishful thinking as
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the White House has sought to respond only minimally
to questions about the Lewinsky matter, trying instead to interest
reporters in a diverse menu of policy themes ranging from Social
Security to efforts to shoo away the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
   As Starr's investigation kicked into a finishing sprint this
week, however, the issue of Clinton's defense, and possibly even
his survival, eclipsed all other concerns for the White House press
corps.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Clinton tried to turn the lights out on the story
Friday, Starr's office was awaiting lab tests to determine whether
a dress Lewinsky turned over to prosecutors contained physical
evidence of an intimate encounter with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was also expected to decide by Monday whether to
appeal to the Supreme Court a federal appeals court decision
requiring deputy White House counsel and Clinton confidant Bruce
Lindsey to go before the grand jury to answer questions about the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey has appeared several times before the grand jury, but
has declined to answer key questions, claiming that to respond
would violate the confidentiality of his attorney-client
relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court rejected that argument in a Monday ruling,
saying essentially that Lindsey was a public official first and a
presidential confidant second.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has been investigating the Lewinsky matter since January
and is expected to compile a lengthy report of his findings for
submission to Congress as early as mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   It would then be up to the House to decide whether there was
evidence of criminal wrongdoing by Clinton that might support
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has stated in sworn testimony that he never had a sexual
relationship with Lewinsky, who has also denied such a relationship
under oath.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, however, Lewinsky exchanged her Fifth Amendment
right to remain silent in exchange for blanket immunity from
prosecution. She is expected to change her testimony and outline
the details of an Oval Office liaison with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
