<HEADER>
A2657 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAMGRIER-RETURNS-TEX     07-31 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMART AS A FOX AND BACK WITH A VENGEANCE
</HEADLINE>
 GRIER-RETURNS-TEX PASADENA, Calif: black action films. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But ask about script availability, and she says, ``Every script
that comes to you there's a jewel of a scene, jewel of a character
in it, and you can work all the time,'' instead of hearing
something about a Hollywood in which women and people of color are
merely afterthoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no such thing to me as a small role. I don't care if
I'm in two scenes that say something about my humanity, that say
something about challenging my craft, challenging myself as a
person. I'm a character actor. I want to be different in everything
I do. I haven't played Pam yet. Most people don't know who Pam
really is. And maybe that's the way it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier is the daughter of an Air Force mechanic' she grew up on
military bases, mostly in Denver. She was a student at Metropolitan
State College there when spotted at a beauty pageant by an agent
who persuaded her to make a dash for Hollywood. After small parts
in campy Roger Corman films like ``The Big Doll House'' in 1971,
she landed the starring role in ``Coffy,'' and her cult-figure
status began.
</P>
<P>
   The formula Grier film featured colorful characters, thumping
music, nudity and violence. She portrayed women proficient with
their brains and certainly their bodies _ despite the films'
posturing about women's liberation, Grier often appeared in various
stages of undress either in bed or battle. In ``Coffy,'' she was a
nurse who singlehandedly brought down a drug-dealing empire as
revenge for its destruction of her young sister.
</P>
<P>
   Grier doesn't make excuses for the films and rather wonders if
we pulled the plug too soon, as do many whose livelihoods were cut
short when groups like the NAACP and Urban League protested about
``negative black images'' in films that depicted the lives of
pimps, pushers and prostitutes. She says, ``You have to crawl
before you walk, and we were crawling and ready to walk. Look what
happened after that. We had nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier certainly didn't. She would appear in films like ``Greased
Lightning'' with then-boyfriend Richard Pryor and log screen time
as Philip Michael Thomas' girlfriend on ``Miami Vice.'' There was
the homicidal hooker in ``Fort Apache, the Bronx;'' Steven Seagal's
bantering police partner in ``Above the Law;'' and a lucky survivor
in ``Mars Attacks!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie Brown'' broke a two-decade drought for Grier as leading
lady, although her stature was, strangely, resurrecting. Grier had
wooed the rap community as the head-bopping girlfriend of Dr. Dre
in the video of Snoop Doggy Dogg's ``It's a Doggy Dogg World,'' and
whether it was '70s nostalgia or not, the name ``Pam Grier'' was
being batted about.
</P>
<P>
   Scripts are now coming in, more than she'd ever seen before, but
you'd never know it by Grier's response. ``Movements are cyclical;
if I've learned anything in this business, I've learned that,'' she
says. ``I mean, people like to reminisce. There's a comfort zone
about that time that was interesting. It had everything, the '70s
did. It had this incredible energy and creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Grier understands her lot. Someone asked her the other
day whether her career will now take off like John Travolta's after
his ``Pulp Fiction'' rebirth, and she replied that, no, she's not
an attractive, white, male actor who can dance.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Grier is diversifying, looking to write and direct. In
the meantime?
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to explore characters,'' she says. ``We're all so
uniquely different, with unique thoughts. There's a vast psyche to
explore. I feel like I'm just getting started.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
