<HEADER>
A2661 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAMGRIER-RETURNS-TEX     07-31 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMART AS A FOX AND BACK WITH A VENGEANCE
</HEADLINE>
 GRIER-RETURNS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ ``There is no frustration level,'' Pam Grier
says quickly. ``You don't deal with it. It's acceptance.'' Grier is
discussing Hollywood and scripts, fame and perception, downfalls
and comebacks. The way she sucks in questions and spits out
answers, you'd think she either prepped herself magnificently or
simply switched to autopilot.
</P>
<P>
   Bet on the latter. She answers swiftly and softly, concisely and
precisely, sounding like a polished team player concerned about
image _ and a radical, restless sistergirl from around the way at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   This changeable rat-ta-tat-tat appears easy for Grier, who
certainly has been around long enough to adjust the controls, to go
both street and sophisticated, to know the players and their whims,
to have heard it before it gets to her, to know that survival is
based on inner strength and reserve, and that you can't possibly
retain sanity without a concrete plan of attack.
</P>
<P>
   Ask about her disappearance from film and she launches into the
state of Hollywood and the craft of acting, saying that one never
goes anywhere, they merely redirect and reload.
</P>
<P>
   Ask about her sex symbol status, and she gently turns the
tables, drilling you about sexist ideals of women in Hollywood and
mentioning that she has never once called herself a sex symbol.
``So why should you?''
</P>
<P>
   Ask about the 1970s blaxploitation films, in which her largest
body of work is represented, and she questions what would have
happened had black film been allowed to mature.
</P>
<P>
   Ask about her comeback, and she smiles sheepishly, only to say
that, Uh, sweetie, I ain't been nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the 1970s _ when Grier was the queen of a string of
films featuring black performers in mostly street dramas like
``Coffy'' and ``Foxy Brown'' and ``Sheba Baby'' _ has she been in
such demand. Grier is taking it in stride, with the grace of a
veteran who has the battle scars to prove that patience and time
are things earned. Who better to understand the fickle ways of
Hollywood, how quickly it all can be snatched out from under you?
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie Brown,'' the Quentin Tarantino film in which Grier
played a down-on-her-luck flight attendant drawn into a sting
operation with federal agents and a cast of sociopaths and
druggies, launched her back into the public eye. But television, a
medium somewhat foreign to her and just as unwelcoming to black
women, is where she could become a household name again.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday is the premiere of ``Linc's,'' the first black-cast
situation comedy developed by Showtime and one of the few conceived
under the creative notion of separate-but-equal programming.
Created by Tim Reid and featuring a strong cast that includes Georg
Stanford Brown, Steven Williams and Tisha Campbell, the show's
selling point is, by and large, Grier.
</P>
<P>
   She plays a Washington, D.C., lobbyist who's married but having
trouble. She hangs out at a bar (Linc's) where she's surrounded by
an eccentric mix of characters designed to spark a whole bunch of
political and social and racial tension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks are calling it a black `Cheers,' '' says Reid. ``And
while I'd love to have the kind of success they had in terms of
years and becoming woven into the pop and cultural fabric, I don't
see this as a black anything. It's just a well-written, funny
series about a group of people who frequent this bar.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Linc's,'' Grier's character is firm but fair, soft around
sharp edges. ``She's da bomb, basically, the funk, the acting
diva,'' Campbell says. ``As soon as I learned that Pam was cast, I
knew this would be a quality project. I mean, the woman is such a
survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   The survivor is sitting cross-legged on the end of her hotel
bed. Having just endured a 23-hour flight from Australia the night
before, she claims fatigue but looks energized. She claims to be a
loner and recluse who'd rather be on her Colorado ranch with her
fiance, 36-year-old RCA Records executive Kevin Evans, but when we
meet, she's warm and personable.
</P>
<P>
   She talks a lot about the metaphysical, of taking care of body
and soul and mind, how such a routine keeps her, at an age
reportedly somewhere between 44 and 50, (she says 49) looking more
like 35, tops.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be true to yourself, got to give to yourself,''
Grier says. ``It helps me stay centered in this crazy business, to
keep focused on my craft.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier seems incredibly focused; words spray from her lips in a
rapid-fire succession and she rarely forgets what she's been asked,
even if she takes a roundabout way of getting there.
</P>
<P>
   You have to ask how Grier has remained so centered, so at peace,
figuring that her world had to be turned upside down when the movie
industry turned its back on black action films. MORE &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
