<HEADER>
A2664 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IAN-MUSIC-LADN     07-31 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IAN-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC FROM A NIGHT TO REMEMBER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Los Angeles is burning up, but the transplanted
Brit looks cool. Relaxed. As if the Huntington Library's shady
outdoor cafe were Ian Whitcomb's natural habitat and he'd been
reared in this desert inferno instead of in mild, moist Surrey,
England.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Whitcomb has had nearly 30 years to adapt to Southern
California's endless summers, ever since a boyhood infatuation with
comic books, Hollywood movies and rock 'n' roll first lured him to
America.
</P>
<P>
   In between, the well-spoken Altadena resident has been a
journalist; a KROQ, KCRW and KPCC radio host; a sometime film and
TV character actor; an author of a dozen books about American music
and popular culture; and a ukulele/accordion player with some 200
recordings under his belt. He even had a Top 10 rock novelty hit _
surely you remember ``You Turn Me On'' from the summer of '65?
</P>
<P>
   His latest project, however, has transported Whitcomb halfway
back across the Atlantic Ocean, to a night that made history 86
years ago and endures as the most unsinkable of legends.
</P>
<P>
   When the R.M.S. Titanic struck an iceberg on April 14, 1912, the
eight members of the ship's White Star Orchestra picked up their
instruments and started to play. Warding off bitter cold, they
performed song after song as they moved up the ship's sloping
stern, doing their best to keep the doomed passengers from
panicking.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra's leader, violinist Wallace Hartley, and his seven
bandmates were among the 1,500 people who drowned that night.
Hartley was found with his violin case strapped to his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Whitcomb decided to honor the brave musicians' spirit with a
1997 CD release, ``Titanic _ Music as Heard on the Fateful Voyage''
(Rhino). Performed by Whitcomb and his six-man band, the
compilation includes such fin de siecle parlor favorites as ``The
Mosquito's Parade'' and ``Lily of Laguna,'' both dating from the
1890s, along with pre-World War I pop standards including Irving
Berlin's ``Alexander's Ragtime Band,'' ``Shine on Harvest Moon''
and ``Oh, You Beautiful Doll.''
</P>
<P>
   In putting the collection together, Whitcomb had access to the
White Star Line's company music book, a total of about 350 tunes
that its bands could play on request. Additional research was
carried out at the Huntington Library, Art Collections and
Botanical Gardens in San Marino, where Whitcomb has been a kind of
unofficial scholar-in-residence for some years.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The CD) was not done as a commercial venture, it really was
done as a labor of love,'' Whitcomb says, wincing slightly for fear
his sentiment might sound trite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to expose the world to some of this beautiful and
neglected music from the turn of the century,'' Whitcomb proceeds,
more confidently. ``We're getting near the millennium, and it's
about time we looked back on a wonderful century of American
music.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Whitcomb and his band the Bungalow Boys will launch
another salvage operation today with a 2 p.m. concert of music from
the ``Titanic'' CD at Glendale's Alex Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first of four concerts at the Alex dedicated to
early-20th-century American music. Coming up Oct. 25 is ``Treasures
of Tin Pan Alley,'' followed by ``Songs of the Ragtime Era'' (Nov.
15) and ``Songs of the Jazz Age'' (Dec. 6). Whitcomb's vocalist
wife, Regina, will accompany the band at each concert, and couples
will re-create dances from the period.
</P>
<P>
   Having served as a musical consultant on James Cameron's
blockbuster movie, Whitcomb knew it would be a smart marketing move
to open the series with the ``Titanic'' concert. But other
historical reasons dictated this concert be first, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around the time the ship went down, America was receiving the
first bite of ragtime, the first bite of American popular culture,
and jazz was soon to follow. It was the first invasion of American
popular culture in the world. It's the earliest form of lounge
music, but much better than what we call lounge music.''
</P>
<P>
   Hauling up musical relics from the past is Whitcomb's grand
passion. While his teen-idol status has long since faded, his
stature as an authoritative advocate of American popular music
continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Whitcomb began developing his wide-open musical tastes in youth,
when he was the class cutup at a posh British prep school. Never a
fan of traditional British culture _ he considers Shakespeare
``vastly overrated'' _ Whitcomb fell in love with New Orleans jazz,
Texas boogie-woogie and gangster movie slang. In those days, he
says, ``I didn't know you weren't supposed to like Pat Boone
because he'd ripped off Little Richard.'' He also preferred Sam the
Sham to Bob Dylan because ``I can get a sermon from a pulpit and a
lecture from a schoolmaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitcomb describes the Titanic era of music as ``very
democratic.'' Radio stations and record labels hadn't yet seized
control of the music industry, so it wasn't unusual for an average
listener to have a working knowledge of everything from classical
to ragtime.
</P>
<P>
   Whitcomb says he's been a Titanic buff since reading Walter
Lord's ``A Night to Remember'' when he was 14. He was even close to
getting cast as bandleader Hartley in Cameron's film but didn't get
the part _ ``quite rightly, because Wallace Hartley was 34 when he
died, and I'm not 34.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitcomb's only objection to Cameron's depiction of the original
orchestra was in having its final song be the pious ``Nearer My God
to Thee.'' In reality, the band went down playing the melancholy
``Songe d'Automne'' (``Dream of Autumn'').
</P>
<P>
   Whitcomb says he'd have been proud to stand on that deck,
playing great music on his way to the hereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was one good thing that came out of that night, it
was what that band did,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't want to go down yet. I think I've still got some
songs to sing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
