A2669 &Cx1f; taf-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPROVED-DIGITAL-IMAG     07-31 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPROVED-DIGITAL-IMAGING-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TECHNIQUE IMPROVES DIGITAL IMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By BARRY FOX  
 Copyright 1998 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Police will soon be more confident about using digital images as
evidence in criminal trials, thanks to a new watermarking system.
Using digital pictures as evidence has been a problem until now,
because they are so easy to alter.
</P>
<P>
   But the British firm Signum Technologies, based in Cheltenham,
England, has come up with a device that makes digital images more
secure. At least one British police force is keen to test it.
</P>
<P>
   Police forces are already trying out digital cameras to collect
evidence of driving offenses on motorways in Leicester and Devon,
and around London. But they are concerned that this evidence could
be challenged in court. Police would also like to use digital
cameras for more than just motoring offenses. They want to use them
to take pictures of the scene of a crime. The advantage of a
digital camera is that the photographer can preview the scene
through a screen that shows the final image.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Crown Prosecution Service warned the House of Lords
Science and Technology Committee late last year that ``some form of
data protection and encryption is needed to exclude external
interference and rebut claims that images have been tampered
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Digital images are built up from several hundred thousand
individual picture points or pixels, each represented by a
numerical value. If the camera uses 8-bit code, each pixel can have
any one of 256 values. Signum's system, called VeriData, breaks
down the picture into an unpredictable jigsaw of small blocks of
various sizes, each containing around a thousand pixels.
</P>
<P>
   The value of selected points within each block is slightly
altered, usually by plus or minus 1. The pattern of these changes
is dictated by a mathematical key, which is specific to the user.
</P>
<P>
   The changes to the picture are too small to be noticeable to the
human eye, but analysis software that has access to the key is able
to check the pattern in each block, and between blocks. If all the
blocks check out correctly, the picture is validated. If the sums
in any block come out wrong, the software marks it with
crosshatching to warn that it has been tampered with. If the
picture has been cropped to remove an object from the scene of a
crime, the picture shows hatching around the altered edges.
</P>
<P>
   The VeriData software works in conjunction with standard image
software on an ordinary PC. Processing is virtually instant. But
Signum recognizes that for the system to be tamperproof, the image
has to be coded inside the camera. The company is working with the
photographic film maker Agfa on real-time coding.
</P>
<P>
   Signum is also working with Hammersmith Hospital in London on a
similar system to encode medical images, such as X-rays, as they
are created. ``The medical area is now full of litigation,''
explains Signum's Alan Bartlett. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2683 &Cx1f; taf-z
s a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIZER-EDUC-ART-3TAKES     07-31 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIZER-EDUC-ART-3TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEODORE SIZER: EDUCATIONAL THEORIST AS CHARTER SCHOOL PRINCIPAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (from `Education Life' special section)  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 2)  
 (ART ADV: Photo of Theodore Sizer is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By JAMES TRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARVARD, Mass. _ Toward the end of this last school year,
Theodore Sizer, the author and strategist of school reform, was
sitting at a long table in the windowless office of the Francis W.
Parker Charter Essential School here.
</P>
<P>
   Sizer is a largish, shambling fellow with shaggy brows and merry
little eyes, an ironist with a deft sense of human folly. At that
moment, however, he had lost his sense of humor. He and his wife,
Nancy, had just agreed to become co-principals of Parker, a
three-year-old junior and senior high school founded on the
progressive principles with which he is associated.
</P>
<P>
   The school does not believe in tracking, grade levels,
multiple-choice tests or letter grades. And now the Sizers were
getting a dose of school reality: For the previous two weeks,
Parker had been forced to yank half its students out of class to
take a battery of exams that represents the Commonwealth of
Massachusetts' very different idea of school reform. Classes had
virtually ground to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole notion that a small group of unelected people could
decide the ideas that everyone is going to be held accountable for
to me is outrageous,'' Sizer said, fuming. ``Outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of standardized tests, and of statewide curriculum, is
not quite so outrageous as all that, but Sizer's idea of a good
school is far from conventional. As head of the Coalition of
Essential Schools until his retirement this spring, Sizer, 66, has
been remarkably effective in attracting teachers, administrators
and even policy makers to his vision of school as an autonomous
community devoted to sophisticated intellectual inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent book, ``Horace's Hope: What Works for the
American High School'' (Houghton Mifflin, 1996) _ Horace, a
world-wise high school teacher, is a fictional alter ego _ Sizer
offers stirring vignettes of just such schools. But the stirring
vignette is, he knows, the opiate of school reform. He openly
concedes his continuing dismay at the resistance the system puts up
in the face of change. ``The system carries on,'' he writes, ``even
when the carrying on is irrational.''
</P>
<P>
   Sizer the freshly minted principal couldn't have been surprised
at what Sizer the author already knew; after almost 45 years in
education, he's not subject to many illusions. Still, he soldiers
on. He spoke over coffee at a former officers' club. (Parker is
located on a decommissioned military base.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I take real satisfaction with the extent to which some of the
ideas which in the mid-'80s appeared far out are now in the
mainstream,'' he said, citing the notion that children move ahead
based on their performance, not their age. ``In my optimistic
moments,'' he added, ``I think we've changed the agenda of the
national conversation about secondary schools.''
</P>
<P>
   School innovators tend to be either former teachers or
academicians; Sizer is a teacher who became an academic. When he
left the Army in 1955 _ he was briefly stationed at the
intelligence center that now serves, coincidentally, as Parker's
massive and forbidding home _ he taught English at the Roxbury
Latin School in West Roxbury, Mass., and then at a boys grammar
school in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   He got his Ph.D. in education and history at Harvard; taught in
the education school and then served as dean, and in 1974 became
headmaster of the Phillips Academy at Andover.
</P>
<P>
   Sizer had become increasingly interested in why schools seemed
to be doing such a poor job. In 1981, backed by Carnegie and
several other foundations, he left Andover and spent a year
traveling in the land of high schools. The result was a personal,
intentionally unsystematic narrative called ``Horace's
Compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   In it, Sizer described an academically sterile world governed by
a bargain he called the ``conspiracy of the least'' _ you promise
to behave if I promise to ask little or nothing of you. He found
superintendents who prided themselves on their efficiency as they
presided over well-behaved, lifeless schools. But unlike the
authors of the famously alarmist 1983 presidential report ``A
Nation at Risk,'' he did not blame the lassitude of the '60s and
did not propose a return to tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``High schools,'' he wrote, ``should respect adolescents more
and patronize them less'' _ the kind of plain-spoken, appealing
aphorism that helped make ``Horace's Compromise'' perhaps the most
discussed school reform book of its time.
</P>
<P>
   Sizer contended that students had to be actively engaged in
their own learning, allowing schools to set the bar of expectations
much higher. In effect, he linked the progressives' faith in the
capacities of the child with the conservatives' criticism of school
standards.
</P>
<P>
   He ultimately elaborated nine principles that would guide the
kind of alternative school he had in mind, including the doctrine
that teaching be personalized and entail coaching rather than
imparting; that teachers and principals be able to make important
educational decisions for themselves; that the curriculum focus on
essential skills _ reading, writing, oral presentation,
mathematical problem-solving, scientific investigation _ rather
than broadly cover facts; and that students demonstrate ``mastery''
of a subject in so-called exhibitions, in which students give an
oral presentation of a paper or project, rather than merely passing
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Some elements remain controversial to this day. Many educational
psychologists, as well as more traditionally minded educators,
believe that skills like ``critical thinking'' cannot be taught
directly.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Professor E. D. Hirsch of the University of Virginia, for
example, promotes the idea that teachers should impart, and
students master, a specific body of information; students become
effective learners, he asserts, as their knowledge expands. Sizer,
however, contends that children will not make sense of information
unless they know why they are learning it, and unless they care
about the reason. This debate continues to divide the progressives
from the traditionalists.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Sizer established the Coalition of Essential Schools at
Brown University, where he also taught. More than 1,000 schools are
now associated with the coalition; 253 that have substantially
restructured along the coalition's lines are considered ``essential
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Sizer also started an initiative called Re:Learning in
which governors and state education commissioners agreed to try to
foster statewide school restructuring. So far, the governors of 12
states have pledged to join the endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   Sizer's ideas have achieved a level of acceptance he never
dreamed of when he was articulating them. And yet he concedes that
much of the change has been superficial or transitory. For example,
at Wilmington High School in Delaware, he recalled, ``a wonderful
team of five teachers created a school within a school. These five
teachers kept riding it out, but without support from above, they
couldn't sustain it, and they finally quit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hierarchical bureaucracies are brutally difficult to change,''
he concluded, ``particularly when the political establishment
doesn't care about them.'' Even when the establishment had
committed itself, through the Re: Learning project, Sizer conceded,
``a lot of it was just talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the essential schools have turned out to be essential in
name only. A recent study of four restructured schools in Illinois,
one of the Re:Learning states, concluded that over time the
essential-school changes ``had a tendency to become
indistinguishable from what other district schools were doing and
what the superintendent wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, written by Nora Prestine, a professor of education at
the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, found that while
the less controversial changes _ learning in teams or the use of
longer class periods _ survived, the ones that more deeply violated
conventional practice, like requiring exhibitions rather than tests
or the pedagogy of a narrower, deeper curriculum, did not.
Moreover, the effort of rethinking everything in a school turned
out to be exhausting; without constant stoking of the fires,
efforts ultimately went cold.
</P>
<P>
   Change was never institutionalized enough to survive the
departure of prime movers. ``Elaborate schemes for dramatic and
systemwide change,'' Ms. Prestine concluded, ``may provide high
melodrama but little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Sizer does not dispute the study's discouraging conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's driving the debate is the basics,'' he said. ``If you
think that an educated person is a question-asker of a respectful
sort, a lot of people just don't want that.''
</P>
<P>
   The essential schools movement is encountering not only inertia
but an opposing tide of change _ toward prescribed curricula,
mastery of content and standardized testing. Indeed, the same 1993
Massachusetts law that established a mechanism for charter schools
like Parker also led to the creation of subject-by-subject
frameworks, and to the tests that Sizer deplores.
</P>
<P>
   Sizer strongly objects to the current effort in New York state
to raise standards by requiring all students to take
college-preparatory Regents courses. ``The kind of serious
intellectual activity which is in the marrow of the bones of the
kids will be replaced by a narrow test,'' he said. ``They'll kill
the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Sizer has been one of the most cogent critics of what he
considers a mushy curriculum spooned out at high schools, it is
surprising to hear him oppose efforts for a more rigorous course of
study. His position is that the wrong kind of reform is making the
right kind impossible.
</P>
<P>
   One clear implication of both Ms. Prestine's research and
Sizer's own reflections _ and, for that matter, organizational
dynamics theory _ is that schools will embrace a radical new model
only if they start from zero, and will remain true to their
principles only if they are independent from central authority.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary public schools can satisfy the first criterion _
thousands of wholly new schools have started up in recent years _
but not the second. Charter schools, however, do both. Charter
schools are public schools that operate autonomously and are held
accountable to goals set out in their initiating charter. Thirty-
two states now have charter statutes. A law for New York state
failed in the last legislative session. But Massachusetts, which
passed one of the first laws, has 24 charter schools. The movement
represents the best hope for essential schools, and for all such
ambitious programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Parker charter school was founded by a group of local
parents and educators in 1995 with 122 seventh and eighth graders;
the Sizers agreed to serve on the board. Like many such schools,
Parker has offered an object lesson in the limits of pure
democracy. The school was originally directed by one of its
teachers. That system didn't provide much guidance to the eager and
largely inexperienced teaching staff, and the school's format
seemed to change every two weeks. For year two, the board hired
someone to serve as both teacher and administrator.
</P>
<P>
   But there was still a vacuum of authority. ``We were a bit naive
about power,'' Nancy Sizer said gently. By this past year it had
become clear that the school needed a full-time principal. The
Sizers, who had long had a second home in Harvard, a bucolic spot
in central Massachusetts, and who had decided to move there after
Sizer had retired from the coalition, agreed to take the job
without pay until a permanent principal could be found. It was the
first real school job Ted Sizer had had in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   After three years, Parker now has about 250 children in what
would be grades 7 through 10 if the school had grades. Instead, the
children are grouped in one of three divisions. They gateway
(essential schools are virtual factories of neologisms) from one
division to the next when they have demonstrated mastery in one of
the two domains, Arts and Humanities or Math, Science and
Technology. (You can simultaneously be in Division 1 in one domain,
and Division 2 in another.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The traditionalist criticism of essential schools is that
students are held to squishy, unverifiable standards. But the
standards for promotion at Parker appear to be high. To demonstrate
excellence in reading, for example, students exiting Division 1 are
expected to identify an author's purpose and point of view; analyze
the positions taken in a text and the evidence offered in their
support; evaluate writing strategies and elements of the author's
craft, and so on, down through 20 criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Parker answers almost perfectly to the popular conception of a
progressive school. It is an extremely friendly, unbuttoned sort of
place where students eat lunch in any empty space, where teachers
hold counseling sessions on ancient sprung couches at one side of
their classrooms, where everyone knows everyone and last names
barely exist. Students sit in clusters rather than rows, and they
spend time in class not so much learning things as using their
knowledge in a setting that supposedly makes that knowledge
meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   Everything at Parker is a project. In one class, students were
preparing for a mock trial of the early 20th century anarchist Emma
Goldman, some serving as defense lawyers and others as witnesses.
In another, they were learning how to write ballads to prepare for
writing one of their own about a historical figure (a marginalized
or oppressed figure, of course).
</P>
<P>
   Is this a better way? ``It's different,'' said Leah Tyo, a
Division 2 student. ``I can't tell you all the battles of the Civil
War, but I can tell you what it felt like to be a slave.''
Substituting this kind of emotional identification for hard
knowledge is just the kind of thing that drives people like E.D.
Hirsch crazy. Leah also said, ``In my old school, I was getting A's
and B's in science, and I didn't remember a thing. Now, when we did
a segment on eclipses, I had to think up a mathematical equation to
demonstrate which planets could have eclipses.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether students are, in fact, gaining a deeper understanding of
a narrower range of knowledge is the $64,000 question of the
essential schools movement. (Parker's test results will not be
available until October.)
</P>
<P>
   Every year, the Massachusetts Department of Education sends out
a team to evaluate each of the charter schools. Ed Kirby, the
department's assistant for charter schools, said that on his recent
visit he was impressed by the school's intellectual atmosphere, by
the students' engagement and by the faculty's commitment to
Parker's founding principles.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, the team identified a number of
tensions inherent in Parker's design. The school has to figure out,
for example, how to deal with students who don't take
responsibility for their own learning. It has to remain
personalized even as it almost doubles to a projected 400 students.
Most of all, Kirby said, Parker has to find a way of adapting to
the reality of the statewide curriculum standards, and the
accompanying tests. Like it or not, he added, people will look at
those results and draw comparisons with other schools.
</P>
<P>
   Sizer doesn't like it, but he is too much the realist to dispute
it.
</P>
<P>
   He and his staff worry about the test results, and they worry
about the consequence of not giving out conventional grades. They
are hoping to persuade colleges to look instead to the students'
portfolios and their teachers' detailed comments on them, which is
likely to be an uphill struggle. Sizer also has to worry about
money. State aid, he says, leaves Parker 10 percent shy of the
irreducible minimum the school needs for its daily operations.
</P>
<P>
   But he is determined not to accept the kind of compromises to
which his mythical teacher, Horace, has grown wearily accustomed.
When Sizer is asked what he is going to be thinking about this
summer, he doesn't talk about money or tests; he mentions the
intellectual challenge of devising a curriculum for students now
reaching Division 3.
</P>
<P>
   The danger of slipping into a good conventional thing instead of
a super-good unconventional thing is high, he said. And he
characterized the school's culture as very positive, quite
undisciplined and often, albeit unintentionally, rude. A good
school, he said, has a strong sense of collective responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   That is, in fact, a great deal to ask of a school; but then, it
is Sizer's school. He may have recognized that he cannot change the
world but he can, at least, cultivate his own little patch of
earth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
