<HEADLINE>
FREELANDER TESTS THE BIG MARKET  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-1243 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By RICHARD FEAST   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOLIHULL, England _ Reversing itself, Land Rover now plans to
sell its new Freelander sport utility vehicle in North America.
Only eight months ago, senior company officials at the headquarters
here declared the demise of a project to re-engineer the Freelander
to meet United States emissions and safety regulations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle will arrive in the United States in late 2000, three
years after going on sale in Europe and elsewhere. American
versions will have a 2.5-liter gasoline-powered V6 and five-speed
automatic transmission, in contrast to the four-cylinder gas and
diesel engines and manual transmissions currently available. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Freelander costs $27,250 to $32,350 in Britain, where it is
priced well below Land Rover's Discovery model and about half as
much as its Range Rover. The price tag includes the value-added tax
required by the European Union, so the Freelander is certain to be
less expensive in the highly competitive American market.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is available in Europe as a conservative five-door
wagon or as a more youthful three-door with a convertible softop or
removable hardtop, only the five-door will be exported to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike all previous Land Rovers, which use separate steel-girder
chassis and light alloy bodies, the Freelander has a unit body
structure like that of a conventional car.
</P>
<P>
   As such, it will be an obvious competitor to the hot-selling
Mercedes-Benz M-class _ a model that now outsells all Land Rovers
in the United States more than 2 to 1. Rover Group, owned by
Mercedes's archrival, BMW, could not ignore such a showroom
performance by its old adversary.
</P>
<P>
   Freelander will be one element in the counteroffensive. The
other will be the BMW E53 _ the so-called sports activity vehicle _
which goes into production in South Carolina next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a wide spread of dealers ready to introduce the
new model to a broader public,'' said Walter Hasselkus, chairman of
Rover. ``The timing is right for Freelander to enter the American
market'' _ the largest for sport utility vehicles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
