<HEADLINE>
HOT ITEMS: AIR TRAVELER'S MOISTURIZER; MARS/VENUS BOARD GAME;
FASHIONS FOR FULL-FIGURED TEENS; GOGGLES AS STREET WEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Aug. 2) 
(Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the humidity in planes typically under 10 percent, the air
is drier than the Mojave. That may be why supermodels on the
Concorde spritz Evian on their skin. Now Skinceuticals is proposing
a different approach. Its Hydrating B5 Gel contains hyaluronic
acid, which attracts water and boosts the effect of any
moisturizer, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   The gel was introduced to counter the drying tendencies of
Skinceuticals products that are used to prevent wrinkles. But
customers used it to prevent the flaking that jet travel can
produce.
</P>
<P>
   Why use Hydrating B5 Gel, at $55 an ounce, rather than an
inexpensive drugstore product? ``If someone has normal skin, any
moisturizer will do the job,'' Dr. Patricia Wexler, a
dermatologist, said. ``But if someone has aging or sun-damaged
skin, there is a clinical difference between something like the B5
Hydrating Gel and the less expensive generic moisturizers.''
</P>
<P>
   The gel is available through dermatologists and Bliss Spa in the
SoHo section of New York, or from (800) 811-1660.
</P>
<P>
   _ ELENA KORNBLUTH
</P>
<P>
   Board Game from the Mars/Venus Author
</P>
<P>
   The universe of ``Men Are From Mars, Women Are From Venus''
keeps expanding. John Gray's 1992 self-help manual has sold 6.5
million copies and has generated audiotapes and videotapes, a CD of
love songs, a Broadway show and now a board game. (Sample question:
``Bigger is a) better; b) not better; c) who cares?'')
</P>
<P>
   ``You constantly want more from him,'' said Pattie Smith, a
former drug counselor who owns the book, videos and board game.
``The material is like vitamins or nutrients.''
</P>
<P>
   She credits the Mars/Venus philosophy _ which holds that men and
women must understand the differences in how the sexes communicate
_ with saving her marriage. After training at the Mars and Venus
Institute in Mill Valley, Calif., she became one of 200 workshop
leaders teaching the techniques.
</P>
<P>
   During one of the telephone interviews he schedules on a ``media
day'' every two weeks, Gray, a psychologist, said, ``People call
this an overnight success, but they forget I was in practice for
close to 20 years before I wrote the book.''
</P>
<P>
   _ KIMBERLY STEVENS
</P>
<P>
   Fashions for Full-Figured Teens
</P>
<P>
   For years, clothing for queen-size women was often dowdy and
unstylish, and Lane Bryant, the national chain store for women size
14 and up, was not exactly fashion-forward. But the company is
introducing a new label, Venezia Jeans Clothing, with an emphasis
on stylish looks for amply proportioned young women.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes are being modeled by full-figured young spokeswomen,
including Mia Tyler, an actress; Abbie Kearses, a television
reporter, and Kym Hampton of the Women's National Basketball
Association. They will take part in a photo shoot and fashion show
at Chelsea Piers in New York on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lane Bryant said it developed the line in response to a study
showing that the fastest-growing market for such clothing was among
women 17 to 25. No doubt they crave stylish clothes as much as
anyone, but one might wonder about the message in the company's
news release that ``it's phat to be fat.'' The number of overweight
adolescents has more than doubled since 1965, according to the
Centers for Disease Control, and doctors link obesity to health
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beauty comes in all different packages,'' insisted Ms. Tyler,
19, the sister of the actress Liv Tyler. ``You can't put a size on
it. If you're a size 12, then you're not any less beautiful than a
size 4.''
</P>
<P>
   What does her father _ Steven Tyler, the whippet-thin lead
singer of Aerosmith _ think of her work as a ``phat'' spokeswoman?
``He loves it and he's proud of me, and it keeps me out of the
house,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Goggles as Street Wear
</P>
<P>
   Once found only under water, goggles are making a splash on the
street, sold alongside sunglasses and baseball caps by sidewalk
peddlers.
</P>
<P>
   Rappers like Busta Rhymes, DMX, Cam'Ron and Big Pun have
popularized goggles as the latest hip-hop accessory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having them strapped across your forehead is an important
aspect of the look,'' said Emil Wilbekin, the fashion director of
Vibe magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Cam'Ron sports a pair on the cover of ``Confessions of Fire,''
his latest CD, which is currently the No. 2 seller at the Virgin
Megastore in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The trend started about four years ago when a rapper named Super
Natural, who based his image on an amphibian, wore swimming
goggles. Then ski goggles by the likes of Oakley and Bolle were
adopted as street wear.
</P>
<P>
   Wilbekin said goggles made sense as street wear for the same
reason as North Face anoraks and Patagonia fleece _ protection
against the extremes of inner-city life.
</P>
<P>
   _ KIMBERLY STEVENS
</P>
