<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2707 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-CO-CEOs-$ADV02     07-31 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-CO-CEOs-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDLY DEALS CLOUD LEADERSHIP ROLES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (Eds: Please note sub slugline)  
 (af)  
 By ADAM BRYANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is hard enough for investors to tell whether many of the
recent corporate mergers make sense. But figuring out whether the
power-sharing agreements made by top executives of the merged
companies will work is nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Even the executives who negotiate these arrangements can find
them confusing. Charles R. Lee, chairman of GTE, stumbled last week
while trying to explain his arrangement with Ivan G. Seidenberg,
chief executive of Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be chairman and chief executive officer of the merged
company,'' he said at a news conference, ``and Ivan will be
president and co-chief executive officer of the company. I'm a
co-chief executive, he's a `co' _ I think I goofed that up. We're
partners, we're two `cos.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lee can be forgiven his tied tongue. After all, such marriages
of convenience are still a bit new for corporate America. Among the
biggest merger deals, hostile takeovers are giving way to so-called
mergers of equals, in which the chief executives of the merged
companies must, by definition, maintain equal status after their
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that old-fashioned command-and-control hierarchies
still drive the action at corporate headquarters. These days,
sharing is a fashionable term, and chief executives besides Lee and
Seidenberg are using it often.
</P>
<P>
   John R. Stafford, chief executive of American Home Products, and
Robert B. Shapiro, chief executive of Monsanto, for example,
announced such an arrangement in June. And Sanford I. Weill, the
chairman of Travelers Group, and John S. Reed, the chairman of
Citicorp, agreed to share power in their new company, Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   But what are the chances that these modern marriages will work?
</P>
<P>
   Consider, as a baseline, that close to half of all real
marriages end in divorce _ and most of them do not start off as
marriages of convenience.
</P>
<P>
   In corporate weddings of chief executives, the power-sharing
agreements are typically just a side effect of getting the deal
done, not a result of two executives' seeking each other out
because their strengths are complementary.
</P>
<P>
   Executives may have any number of reasons to want to retain the
title of chief executive in the new company: protecting their
lieutenants in the merged company, making more money or avoiding
being seen as a loser in a power struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to solve a social problem,'' said Herbert M.
Sandler, the co-chief executive of the Golden West Financial Corp.,
the Oakland, Calif.-based parent of World Savings Bank. ``They're
not saying, `That's a guy I'd really like to team up with.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sandler can speak with some authority on the subject. He has
shared the title of chief executive with his wife, Marion O.
Sandler, since they bought Golden West in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Sandler said that for co-chief arrangements to work, the
executives must trust and respect each other, and, most important,
have no hidden agendas. ``If it's being driven by other factors,
then you're making real compromises, and then there is a high risk
that it's not going to work,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Some executives have said they do not think such relationships
can work, period. When CUC International merged with HFS Inc. last
December, CUC's chairman, Walter A. Forbes, entered into an unusual
agreement with Henry R. Silverman, the HFS chairman. Until the year
2000, Forbes would be chairman of the merged company, the Cendant
Corp., and Silverman would be chief executive; after that they
would switch jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Although Forbes resigned this week over accounting
irregularities at the company, he said in an interview earlier this
month that they chose the job-trading structure because it would
have been unwieldy to have two chief executives making decisions at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just felt that co-anything is difficult,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee of GTE and Seidenberg declined to be interviewed. But Dennis
C. Carey, vice chairman for the United States practice of Spencer
Stuart, an executive search firm that has often worked for GTE,
said he believed Lee and Seidenberg would develop a productive
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, he said, has long made a habit of sharing decision-making
with his top managers at GTE.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt that Chuck will find this power-sharing
arrangement very comfortable,'' Carey said. ``It's part of his
approach to conducting business.''
</P>
<P>
   And Seidenberg, who will become the sole chief executive of the
merged company in July 2002 and will replace Lee as chairman two
years later, has already shown that he can wait patiently. He was
chairman of Nynex when it merged with Bell Atlantic and agreed then
to take a back seat until Raymond W. Smith, the chairman of Bell
Atlantic, stepped aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a radical departure from what Ivan had already
adapted to,'' Carey said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, marriages of convenience do work out. Robin H.H.
Wilson and Glenn R. Zander were co-chief executives of Trans World
Airlines during most of 1993, as it was working its way out of
Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection. They were thrown together because
they represented two important parties in the bankruptcy _ Wilson
the airline's employees, and Zander the creditors.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, their skills fit together nicely: Wilson had
expertise in airline operations and Zander in finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this particular circumstance, this was the right
solution,'' Wilson, who is now managing director of SH&AMP;E Inc., a
consulting firm, said last week. ``But it does create some
particular pressures on individuals to acquire a certain
compatibility.''
</P>
<P>
   As successful as the executives were in helping TWA emerge from
bankruptcy, Wilson said he would probably not have chosen a
co-chief role if he had the chance to do it all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``A more traditional model would be preferable,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 1714EDT &QL; 
