<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2709 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRAWSTRING-PANTS-$ADV     07-31 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAWSTRING-PANTS-$ADV02-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JUST-WOKE-UP LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 2)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID COLMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What if you went to work in your pajamas?
</P>
<P>
   Fashion has crossed many a line in the sand in the name of
creativity and publicity, but the latest taboo to be broken seems
to have been thought up before designers had showered and shaved in
the morning.
</P>
<P>
   If the styles coming down men's runways over the past weeks in
Milan, Paris and New York are any indication, slouchy drawstring
pants, reminiscent of pajamas, are going to be big in spring 1999.
Calvin Klein even showed drawstring pants as the bottom half of a
tailored suit.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for more casual men's clothes has boomed over the
last few years. But are drawstring pants, made of cotton or nylon
for spring, or of heavier cotton or wool for fall, pushing the
casual envelope too far? These humble pants, beloved of surfers,
yogis and good-for-nothing bums, might seem to be out of their
depth when made of luxury fabrics, with price tags to match.
</P>
<P>
   But designers are arguing strongly that men should add them to
their wardrobes. ``They're sexy,'' Cynthia Rowley said, watching as
her own midweight plaid wool drawstring pants were modeled by her
husband, Bill Keenan, an artist, last week at her showroom.
``There's something a little gritty about them, like you just
rolled out of bed. And they make you seem kind of creative, like a
free spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who wore drawstring pants to a law office or on Wall
Street might quickly find himself a very free spirit. But for those
who need not dress in a uniform in or out of the workplace, there
is a good variety of drawstring pants already in stores. At
Bloomingdale's, DKNY's version in cashmere and wool knit is $150;
in black cotton ($130), also by DKNY, the pants have a sort of
paratrooper flair.
</P>
<P>
   For the truly flush, Yohji Yamamoto's black drawstring
karate-style wool pants are $530 at Barneys New York. Ms. Rowley's
drawstring pants are $180 at her store at 112 Wooster St. (Prince
Street) in SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   Lower-priced versions are more in keeping with drawstring
trousers' shiftless chic. Wearmart, a new store in NoLIta, just
east of SoHo at 229 Elizabeth St. (Prince Street), sells
medical-scrub-style cotton drawstring pants for $68. At Paragon
Sporting Goods, 867 Broadway (18th Street), a pair of Gramicci
light cotton twill walking pants is $40.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, at OK Uniform, at 368 Broadway (Prince Street),
cotton drawstring pants for the medical trade come in a rainbow of
colors, from white and gray to ruby, midnight blue, pink and green.
If you're unsure if you're a drawstring-pants kind of man, OK
Uniform is a good place to start, since its versions cost only $12.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the year-round activities for which drawstring pants
work well, like drinking coffee, smoking cigarettes and throwing
away unpaid bills, they are perfect for the one time of year when
everyone's ambition is to be a beachcomber. That is, right now.
</P>
<P>
   See you in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
