A2720 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-BIZ-PLANNERS-N     07-31 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-BIZ-PLANNERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL PLANNERS FUME AT THE TAKING OF A TITLE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the investment advisers, accountants, stockbrokers,
insurance agents and other consultants who bill themselves as
financial planners, there is a one-word answer to Shakespeare's
question, ``What's in a name?''
</P>
<P>
   It's money. And lately there has been plenty of it as more and
more investors are willing to pay for financial advice.
</P>
<P>
   So no wonder that these advisers are in high dudgeon that some
New York City welfare workers are now being called financial
planners, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not call these people doctors, or astronauts or nuclear
physicists?'' asked Valerie Lasher-Adelman, a certified financial
planner who is also president of the New York chapter of the
Institute of Certified Financial Planners, which has 12,800
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've yet to find a financial planner who works on career
counseling, let alone job placement,'' she said. ``To call a
financial planner a caseworker would be just as inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   What has her so upset is the city's decision to use the title
``financial planner'' for caseworkers at its 30 welfare offices who
screen welfare applicants in hourlong interviews. The offices are
being renamed ``job centers'' as part of the national effort to
overhaul welfare policy _ and to freshen welfare's image.
</P>
<P>
   But the people who were already calling themselves financial
planners say the name is being misappropriated. ``Financial
planning is much more than giving people budgeting advice,'' said
Rosilyn Overton, a certified financial planner and New York chapter
president of the International Association for Financial Planning,
which represents 36,000 planners. ``It's about investments, estate
planning and using the financial planning process, which is very
disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   The Family Independence Administration in New York City (that's
what used to be the welfare department) argues that financial
planning is a key to getting people off welfare, regardless of how
those who like to call their clients ``high net worth individuals''
feel about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to look at what the particular concerns are, but
frankly, we're now asking our staff to engage in discussion that
involves a certain level of financial detail,'' said Debra Sproles,
a spokeswoman for the city Human Resources Administration, which
oversees the welfare system.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sproles said that because welfare benefits now carry a
lifetime limit of five years, the workers sometimes go to great
lengths discussing topics like cash flow, credit information and
the potential benefits _ like Medicaid _ that might keep applicants
out of the welfare system altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is to get people thinking about financial
self-management,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The city's move would appear to be perfectly legal, even if it
flies in the face of efforts by more traditional financial planners
to become recognized as a profession, for no one holds the rights
to the ``financial planner'' label.
</P>
<P>
   Certified financial planners, however, are not only protected by
a federally registered trademark, but they must also pass a test
administered by their trade group's board of standards.
</P>
<P>
   In early July, that board sent a letter to Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani, protesting the title change. It also offered to work with
welfare officials to find a more appropriate name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if 5 percent of what caseworkers offer might legitimately
be called financial advice, I still think it's a misnomer,'' said
Robert P. Goss, president of the Certified Financial Planner Board
of Standards.
</P>
<P>
   In defense of the usage, Bill Waldman, president of the American
Public Health Services Association, which represents state and
local welfare agencies, noted that these days caseworkers are
called upon to help people ``move from their entry-level jobs and
out of poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about estate planning, or tax shelters,'' he
said. ``But financial independence does involve a lot of
planning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
