<HEADER>
A2750 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIEST-SEXCHARGE-HNS &LR;      07-31 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIEST-SEXCHARGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIEST, ACCUSED OF SEXUAL ADVANCE, PLANS TO LEAVE PARISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUZANNE HOHOLIK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Sitting in the office he has used at St. Cecilia's
Catholic Church for 12 years, Monsignor Joseph Deane takes a deep
breath and exhales. He is bracing to discuss the worst experience
of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1997, Shirley Willis accused Deane of making sexual
advances toward her. She said in court documents that when she
refused his wishes, she was fired as principal of a San Antonio
school affiliated with the church.
</P>
<P>
   Deane, 63, is not uncomfortable talking about the allegations,
but he is quick to state his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do it,'' said Deane, who has spent his 39-year career
in San Antonio. ``As a priest, I expected a cross. I didn't expect
this, but I'll hang on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the ordeal, he vehemently denied the allegations, and
in September, criminal charges filed against him were dropped.
Willis filed a civil lawsuit asking for court costs, back pay and
punitive damages. Deane countersued.
</P>
<P>
   He also rejected repeated attempts to settle that suit, even for
$2,500, saying he would never admit to something he had not done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't settle,'' Deane said. ``I had no reason to settle,
for that little amount was the same as the half million I was sued
for. It was admitting something I didn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, Deane and Willis agreed to drop the lawsuits against
each other. A lawsuit against the church over her dismissal
remains.
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor Lawrence Stuebben, vicar general and director of
administration for the archdiocese, said settling with Willis is
not an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not willing to pay a penny,'' Stuebben said, adding that
he did not believe the case would ever go to court.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Petty, Willis' attorney, would not comment on the case
until she had spoken with her client. Willis reportedly was out of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Parishioners at St. Cecilia's rallied to the priest's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Reyes, a member for 30 years, said she never doubted
Deane's innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people behind him. A lot of his
ex-parishioners would come to our church and support him,'' Reyes
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alice R. Trevio, Deane's housekeeper for 11 years, said the
allegations took a toll on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just crucified, persecuted. He was down, just down,''
she said. ``He was just in prayer all the time for one year. He was
hurting real bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the charges against him, Deane remained on the job he
loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has always been my source of strength _ ministering to
people, preparing people for baptism, preparing people for
marriage,'' he said. ``It's been a test of my priesthood. It made
me appreciate my parish staff and parish.''
</P>
<P>
   But Deane will return to his home in Ireland for a three-month
sabbatical, saying ``I will not, more than likely, be back in San
Antonio.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very happy here. It's a very responsive congregation,
good school and responsible staff,'' he said. ``I'm just putting
this behind me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
