<HEADER>
A2758 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     07-31 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVASION OF THE CAT PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Aug. 3)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was an interesting story in the Arizona Republic about how
there are two kinds of people in the world: cat people and dog
people.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking here is that cats and dogs have opposite
personalities and philosophies of life. Cats, for example, are
independent, devious, untrustworthy things that, as soon as you let
your guard down, leap at your neck and sink their claws into your
carotid. Kenneth Starr is an example of a cat person. So are
religious evangelists.
</P>
<P>
   Dog people, on the other hand, are loyal, obedient optimists who
are unburdened by false modesty, mood swings or dreams of world
conquest. Forrest Gump was a dog person. So are most vice
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   You will notice that I had to use a fictional character as an
example of a dog person. That is because, in my opinion, there are
a lot more cat people these days than dog people, which is sad but
perhaps inevitable given the wily nature of cats and the fact that
dogs would much rather chase their tails or sniff each other's
butts than waste time worrying about the shifting balance of power.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to me that the world would be a better place if more of
us behaved like dogs, excluding the butt-sniffing part, of course.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, despite his recent acquisition of a Labrador
retriever, is a cat person down to his last corpuscle. While this
may account for his success as a politician, it does not win him a
lot of points in the ``character'' department. (It is typical of
cat people that we would entrust Clinton with our nuclear arsenal
yet would not feel comfortable allowing him to chaperone our
teen-age daughter to the prom.)
</P>
<P>
   Most of our recent presidents have been cat people, which could
explain why we haven't had a chief executive worth a hoot since
Harry Truman, the last, great dog president.
</P>
<P>
   Just because a president is a dog does not guarantee that he's
worth a hoot, of course. Gerald Ford was a dog president in the
sense that he was clumsy and also because he pardoned Richard
Nixon, the ultimate cat president. (Dogs are nothing if not
forgiving, which is why dog people have no chance against cat
people, whose idea of forgiveness is to drag your barely breathing
carcass into the living room so they can bat you with their paws
and chew on you for a few days until you die of blood loss or
starvation, whichever comes first.)
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan might have seemed like a dog president because he
was so friendly and good-natured, but he was really a cat president
in dog's clothing. Reagan liked nothing more than a good, long nap
(a classic cat trait) and, when awake, seemed uninterested in just
about everything that did not pertain directly to him. Since it is
considered unseemly, even in Washington, for a president to drag
the near-lifeless carcasses of his tormentors onto the Oval Office
carpet and gnaw on them slowly over the course of several days,
Reagan simply adopted the strategy of ``not remembering'' anything
that happened during his administration that was remotely
unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Since there were a great many unpleasant things that happened
during Reagan's administration (Ollie North and James Watt come
immediately to mind), Reagan spent almost his entire eight years in
office either sleeping or not remembering, a perfect cat's life by
almost any definition.
</P>
<P>
   It goes without saying that dog people do not understand cat
people, whereas cat people understand dog people perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   All of which suggests that men may not be from Mars, nor women
from Venus, but that all of us merely arrived from different
kennels. It is an idea worthy of further exploration, just as soon
as I finish my nap.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Sarasota (Fla.)
Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
