<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2767 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERFUME-FUTURIST-$ADV     07-31 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERFUME-FUTURIST-$ADV02-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATCHING A WHIFF OF THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 2)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By PENELOPE GREEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a hot summer morning, Lori Smith, a trend
forecaster at Givaudan Roure, one of the world's largest makers of
perfume, was in a taxi on her way to a pastry shop in the East
Village, looking, she said, for new ways to express creaminess.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been searching for the new warmth, for a new kind of
luxury,'' she said. ``One of our perfumers had this idea that
luxury had a texture _ a creaminess, but not like cream-cheese
creaminess. Something fluffier. Maybe something with a berry on
top. D'you know?''
</P>
<P>
   So it was that Ms. Smith found herself nibbling macaroons and
biscotti in Veniero's on East 11th Street under the amused gaze of
the counterwoman, and talking excitedly of what the future might
smell like.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olfactive epiphanies, new kinds of olfactive communication,
that's what I look for,'' said Ms. Smith, whose job is to translate
what is percolating on the street, in fashion and in the culture
generally for perfumers, so that they can distill her insights into
marketable products. She often speaks in epigrams like ``Coffee
smells like dating to the generation that grew up in Starbucks'' or
``Purity is sexuality today.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith, who has the neat movements and compact physiognomy of
an athlete _ a tennis player, say, or a surfer _ calls her
fieldwork ``trend trekking,'' and it can take her to the top of
Killington Mountain in Vermont, among the snowboarders, or, as on
this day, around lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   She had begun her morning with a quick stop at the Mercer Hotel
in SoHo. Like a radioactive hot spot, the lobby emitted faint
signals, and she pricked up her ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought us this tiny glass of water in the middle of an
enormous silver tray,'' she said. ``And it was sort of galling but
sort of special, too. D'you know, these little intimate hotels are
like a very `for you' cologne. It's like going up and smelling
someone's neck. And that's where it's at now. Not unisex, but sexy.
Not Calvin Klein but Tom Ford. The beautiful bodies getting dressed
up again!''
</P>
<P>
   How insights and exclamations like these make their way into a
bottle of perfume is the latest chapter in the story of the
fragrance business. Makers of products from sneakers to soft drinks
have consulted trend forecasters and self-styled futurists at least
since Faith Popcorn, in a feverish display of self-marketing, began
``brailling the culture'' some 20-odd years ago. But the more
conservative fragrance industry has until recently eschewed such
practices.
</P>
<P>
   That is changing, as more than 1,100 perfumes crowd the
marketplace and companies fight for new customers in a $5 billion
industry. ``Gurus, prognosticators, trend spotters, whatever you
want to call them, help companies look at where the business is
going,'' said Ann Gottlieb, an industry consultant, whose clients
range from Calvin Klein to Christian Dior.
</P>
<P>
   A wake-up call was the surprise success in 1995 of CK One, the
unisex fragrance from Calvin Klein for urban 20-somethings. It was
a market that had been largely untapped. ``I was like, Hello, young
people!'' said Kathleen Montrose, vice president of marketing for
Firmenich, another fragrance company. ``That whole tribe thing was
very on target sociodemographically.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith recently prodded her own employer, Givaudan Roure, to
develop a fragrance for teen-age surfer girls, or at least girls
who would like to be surfers, and to find a retail client to market
it.
</P>
<P>
   Thus was born Hula Scent from Roxy Quiksilver, due in stores
this fall. It smells, she said, a little like a beach, a little
woody (like an old wooden long board) and a little like the ocean
breeze off California. ``Which is sort of citrusy,'' Ms. Smith
added, ``and it's there because when I asked surfers what they
thought about when they were waiting for the next wave, they
described this smell.''
</P>
<P>
   The youth market is a moving target, notoriously difficult to
get a fix on, but Ms. Smith _ even though she is 36 and a graduate
of the Wharton School of Business _ is an expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lori told us that the New Age consumer _ Generation Y or
whatever you want to call it _ is very comfortable with chemicals,
which is a complete switch from the Gen X
unbleached-linen-botanicals thing,'' Geoffrey Webster, president
and general manager of Givaudan Roure, said. ``So maybe now a
perfume has a silicone base instead of a natural one. Total
reversal! But these are the kids we have to bring in. Because once
you get a group to experience the joy of personal fragrance, they
don't ever go back.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the forthcoming Roxy scent, Ms. Smith has
contributed to fragrances like Michael Jordan's cologne and Polo
Extreme. ``What I do is bring the outside world in,'' she said. If
perfumers are the noses of the fragrance business, trend
forecasters are its eyes and ears.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes her field reports affect a perfume's scent, like Polo
Extreme, which contains a pepper note that is a perfumer's response
to Ms. Smith's suggestion that the fragrance be ``spiky and peaky,
like an adrenaline rush, the thing that links people involved in
extreme sports,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes her reports affect the way a perfume is sold, or where
it is sold (surf shops, in the case of Roxy). And sometimes, said
Webster, her boss, her reports have no overt effect at all.
``Except that they affect the way we all think about the changing
culture, and that affects the perfumers in the mid- and
long-term,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the industry were skeptical about the value of
futurists, trend-forecasters and assorted cool-hunters. ``If people
really knew how to predict things that are sensory, there would be
no failures,'' said Allan Mottus, publisher of The Informationist,
a fragrance-industry newsletter. ``Great successes are usually
initiated by intuition, not trend forecasting. Of course, what
happens is that when there's a huge success, like a CK One,
everybody goes running backward and tries to spin around it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A word on how the business works. The companies that stamp their
names and images on fragrances _ the Estee Lauders and Ralph
Laurens _ don't actually make the juice in the bottles, although
they collaborate. Almost every major scent is concocted by one of
four specialized companies, a group that includes Givaudan Roure,
International Flavors and Fragrances, Quest International and
Firmenich.
</P>
<P>
   Perfumers at the fragrance companies blend together fragrances
from personal collections of scents they've created in response to
a variety of things that may or may not include cultural trends, as
well as intuition _ how the creaminess of a macaroon may signal a
new sort of luxury, and what that may smell like.
</P>
<P>
   Wiping the crumbs from her mouth, Ms. Smith darted out of
Veniero's and race-walked south on First Avenue. A homeless man
careened into her. ``Peach,'' he whispered, and stumbled away.
``Did he really say that? Wow!'' Ms. Smith said. ``Fruit is so big
now. We had a grapefruit meeting the other day, and we're all like,
`Oh, man, this is the best part, or that is.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the future?'' she asked out loud. ``That biscuit we
smelled and ate. The smell of a supernatural color. A super
grapefruit. Something crazy in the mix, like disco lemonade,'' she
sang.
</P>
<P>
   Like designers trying to anticipate what hemlines or colors will
appeal a year from now, Ms. Smith and her colleagues have their
eyes fixed over the horizon of what is currently in stores. If
Mount Everest was yesterday's destination, its aroma may be
tomorrow's perfume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fragrance has left the realm of what it was originally, an
expression of character, and entered the realms of fashion and
experience and beyond,'' said Paul Austin, business development
manager and trend forecaster at Quest, the fragrance company.
</P>
<P>
   Once a forecaster nails a trend, a perfumer has a host of ways
of responding to it. One is to use head-space technology _
essentially sampling the air around a flower, or the breeze off the
Pacific Ocean, and reproducing the aroma in a laboratory. Givaudan
Roure has developed a machine called ScentTrek; nestled in hot-air
balloons the company has sent whizzing over the top of rain
forests, it forages for new smells.
</P>
<P>
   International Flavors and Fragrances used a similar technology
for its client Rei Kawakubo, the designer of Comme des Garcons,
whose new perfume, Odeur 53, contains notes of burnt rubber, sand
dunes and plastic baby dolls. So much for the language of flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Joffe, managing director of Comme des Garcons and Ms.
Kawakubo's husband, said Odeur 53 was not a perfume but ``a
sequence of smells and associations.'' The company is advertising
it as an ``anti-perfume.''
</P>
<P>
   Through extensive polling, the folks at Quest can tell what
ingredients smell like peace or sex or clean laundry to the
majority of the population. Forecasters like Austin graze the
culture for trends, match them up with the database of stored
associations-as-smells and hope that a perfume star is born.
</P>
<P>
   Both Austin and Ms. Smith like to give the trends they spot
snappy names. Austin has identified 38, including ones called
Master of Time and High-Tech Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's First Aid. ``It's the whole idea of looking to the
pharmacy for inspiration, looking for something that's clinically
pure and perhaps anti-nature,'' he said. ``It's a mini-millennial
concept that also incorporates the notion of white. We saw a lot of
white gauzes in the fashion collections, and then there were those
Helmut Lang slashes, those wounds. A friend of mine said we're all
licking our wounds from being fashion victims. So we're exploring
smells that would create a germ-free aura.''
</P>
<P>
   At Broadway and Prince Street, Ms. Smith flourished a tiny paper
blotter like a little gift. ``Snap Green Bean! Can you feel the
snap?'' she asked. ``Can you hear it? This came from a trend we
called Veggie Values _ which arose from the fact that kids will
identify themselves as vegetarian even if they're not. It's like a
badge of identification for them.''
</P>
<P>
   At Dean &AMP; Deluca she stopped to sample some sorbets made by a
company called Out of a Flower _ Grapefruit Tarragon, Tequila
Cilantro _ because they reminded her of a DJ mixing different
sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith reached into her handbag and brought out little pots
of powder. Touch Lycra, Air, Velvet the labels read. ``We
challenged the perfumers to create millennial materials, to mix up
the form,'' she said. ``I talked about things like lily of the
valley in a pill. And this is what came back.'' The powder felt
soft and shone on the back of a hand. It smelled terrific.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks south, in a clothing store called Yellow Rat
Bastard, Ms. Smith fondled a pair of cargo pants. Yellow Rat
Bastard spoke to Ms. Smith because ``it's about having all your
stuff on you,'' she said. ``Just look at all those pockets and
flaps and things,'' she added, pointing to the pants.
``Pro-function, that's big.''
</P>
<P>
   With its reggae soundtrack and plastic fruit displays, the store
also makes a brave show of surf culture, an environment _ nay, a
movement _ Ms. Smith is staunchly behind. ``A few months ago, I got
hit in the head by a freaking surfboard in Paris,'' she said.
``Paris. And then I'm in London a week later and there's one on top
of a car. I'm like, whoa! The beach is about peace, and everybody
wants some of that. It's about smelling the beach on the street,
and we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another little blotter appeared. ``We were in Costa Rica,'' she
said, ``and we found this beach _ here it is.'' The blotter smelled
like air, and the foam on the waves, and something else _ something
indefinable. It cut right through the sickly sweet smell from a
peanut stand on the corner. Perhaps it was the smell of the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
