s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARN-ELEVATORS-2TAKES     07-31 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARN-ELEVATORS-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ELEVATOR AS CIRCUS, AND CONFESSIONAL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Pa., Calif., R.I., Conn.)   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)Office-building elevators may provide a relatively
short ride to work, but they go a long way toward contributing to
the human comedy. Some passengers have nothing to do but listen;
others take the opportunity to have some fun with all those people
pretending they are unaware of their fellow passengers. And
sometimes a ride on a elevator can be a journey toward
enlightenment.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an elevator in a tall office building on Park Avenue, two
young Citicorp executives were talking one day in the early 1980s
when they were overheard by Paige Churchman of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   One of them said, ``I used to have a ... ''
</P>
<P>
   There was a pause while the car descended at least half a floor.
</P>
<P>
   Then it came to him.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... photographic memory.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susan Carrier of Los Angeles and an office acquaintance use
their elevator time to catch up on personal news.
</P>
<P>
   One day, her friend asked, ``Do you have any children yet?''
</P>
<P>
   And Mrs. Carrier, whose husband, George, is a lawyer, replied,
``No, not yet, but we'd love to start a family.''
</P>
<P>
   To which the acquaintance responded, ``And is your husband still
practicing?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carrier, astonished that the woman would ask such a personal
question in a crowded elevator, retorted, ``Yes, he's still
practicing, and one of these days he's going to get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   And her friend said, ``I meant practicing (italics)law.''(end
italics)
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd broke into laughter, Ms. Carrier says she made a
quick escape _ to the wrong floor. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Talk, they say, is cheap. But those who say it may want to
reconsider after listening to the story of James M. Marsh of
Rosemont, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, Marsh was based in Philadelphia and
assigned by the Army to renegotiate military contracts on which
excessive profits were being made.
</P>
<P>
   One day, Marsh, a chief warrant officer, was in an elevator
downtown with his commanding officer. They found themselves in the
presence of two well-dressed men.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you doing?'' one said to the other.
</P>
<P>
   And the reply came: ``We're making so much money it scares me.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsh's commander recognized the second speaker as the president
of a wire manufacturing company. When they returned to their
office, Marsh was ordered to send the man's company a notice of
renegotiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're making wire today, the Signal Corps is paying for
it,'' the colonel said.
</P>
<P>
   The company responded to the order, reported for a discussion of
its pricing and agreed to refund the government $250,000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They didn't call Mark Vasconcellos jigoku-mimi for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Here, he says, is how it happened:
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade ago, Vasconcellos, as a lending officer at a
major Japanese bank in Manhattan, was in the habit of having lunch
with his best friend, who was working in the treasurer's office of
a major New York bank with headquarters just up the street. They
met in its cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   One day, as Vasconcellos entered the elevator to return to his
office, two Japanese employees of the friend's bank were discussing
a multibillion-dollar deal, which happened to be one that
Vasconcellos was asked to bid on.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that he didn't understand Japanese, they were comparing
notes on their absolute rock-bottom bid.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, Vasconcellos did understand Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to return to my office and undercut their bid by
less than one penny,'' he writes. ``My bank got the business, and I
was thenceforth nicknamed jigoku-mimi by my colleagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you knew the translation all along: hell ears. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
