<HEADER>
A2780 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-LMAY01-COX     07-31 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-LMAY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: How should we act when insects drop in?
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   McCaysville, Ga. _ Strange, but Ben Whitaker and I found
ourselves talking about whether to kill or not to kill. The Georgia
representative and I were agreeing how it gets tougher and tougher
to smash an insect _ even as it invades the house.
</P>
<P>
   And this has been a summer for invasions. In some ways, indoors
looks much like outdoors, as various critters, seeking refuge from
the bitter heat, take up residence from floor to ceiling, living
among the houseplants just as comfortably as if they were camping
in trees and shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   What to do _ reach for the insecticide? The swatter?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten to the point when I see a spider or a cricket, I
pick it up and take it outside,'' said Whitaker, a Republican from
Ellijay. ``Everything's put here for a purpose. I weigh 210 pounds.
Why should I snuff out the life of a little insect?''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, sensibility. Our conversation reminded me of a passage from
the 18th-century novel ``Tristram Shandy'' by Laurence Sterne: The
gentle character ``my uncle Toby'' says to ``the fly which buzz'd
about his nose all dinner time _ `Go _ go poor devil ... get thee
gone _ why should I hurt thee? This world is surely wide enough to
hold both thee and me.'''
</P>
<P>
   In real life today, most of us do not shoo flies (and certainly
not mosquitoes) with such compassion. To be sure, neither Whitaker
nor I raised the question of what we do when they buzz our dining
rooms and porches. Usually, I find it a tossup between herding them
out or putting them out of my misery with a swatter or folded
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, we did not talk about regular rats or those cute,
bushy-tailed ones _ squirrels _ and what un-Tobylike behavior they
might inspire.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, certain insects seem more acceptable in the house
than do others. And insects in general seem more acceptable than,
say, snakes.
</P>
<P>
   That said, I do marvel at what change that represents _ just in
my lifetime. I have lived in houses where both sky and ground were
visible from every room in the house _ an open invitation to just
about anything that could fit through the cracks. Dirt daubers
seemed comfortably tame and at home, as did worms and wasps.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, I can only imagine what it must have been like in
earlier times, surviving in dugouts on the Plains or in hovels on
Southern plantations.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with all manner of creatures coming in from the heat, I
am again getting a taste of life close to nature. Faced with armies
of insects and a lizard here and there (no cracks, but they're
clever), I'm less likely than before to jump up and look for a way
to eradicate them. Instead, I want to know what their intent might
be.
</P>
<P>
   If the wasp immediately flies to the ceiling, seeking a new
place to build a nest, well, it's all right for it to look around _
until I get around to showing it to the door.
</P>
<P>
   And the lizard _ what harm can it do, really? Its greatest
danger may be to itself. One found its way into a bowl sitting on
the floor. Black with blue markings, it made a beautiful sight
against the white porcelain. Forgotten, it must have stayed in the
bowl for more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing. Stiff, gone, it looked just like itself, perfectly
preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, poor ants. Harmless harbingers of peony blooms in the
garden, their armies are despised in some homes almost as much as
roaches or mice. But not by Toby.
</P>
<P>
   As for Whitaker and me, our sensibilities are growing, but we've
still got a ways to go.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
