<HEADER>
A2782 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARN-ELEVATORS-2NDTAK     07-31 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARN-ELEVATORS-2NDTAKE-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: hell ears.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early one morning, Wilma Davidson, a communications consultant
from East Greenwich, R.I., and her husband, Stephen, a corporate
vice president, were side by side in a packed elevator in a Chicago
hotel, headed for different floors. He was on his way to a business
meeting and she was to deliver a seminar. All of the elevator's
passengers were silent and aloof.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for my husband,'' Ms. Davidson writes. ``As the doors
to his floor opened, he quickly grabbed me around the waist
tightly, pulling me to him for a quick and passionate kiss. But
that's not all.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he jumped out, he turned back to me (and everyone else in
the elevator) and said in a clear voice, just as the doors
reclosed, `Now remember, not a word to my wife.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davidson says she has since forgiven him. But it was the
last time she accompanied him on a business trip. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not just men who practice mischief in elevators. Robert
Ross of Queens remembers the time that he and a co-worker, a woman,
found themselves in a prestigious midtown Manhattan hotel after
work, on their way to have a drink with a former business
colleague.
</P>
<P>
   The elevator was almost full when Ross and his companion
entered.
</P>
<P>
   As it glided up, she turned to him and, in a clear, innocent
voice asked, ``Are you sure you will marry me afterward?'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early in his long business career, Ronald J. Rakowski of Bethel,
Conn., worked in an office building in Washington in which one
floor was leased to the United States Information Agency. He had
read enough about the agency to have a favorable impression of it.
</P>
<P>
   One day, however, the press was full of accounts about a new
book that linked it to the Central Intelligence Agency and even
identified the building where Rakowski worked as a place where the
USIA conducted some covert activities.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Rakowski and his boss were in an elevator with
a third passenger when the car stopped at the floor occupied by the
agency. The doors opened slowly, then closed slowly, with no one
getting on or off.
</P>
<P>
   After a few moments, the fellow passenger, his eyes wide and his
voice filled with awe, turned to Rakowski and his boss and said,
``Talk about cover; you couldn't even see that son of a gun!'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Evening in Manhattan. At the end of a long workday inside 30
Rockefeller Plaza, an Art Deco elevator, crowded with women in
gowns and men in black tie, soared toward the Rainbow Room on the
65th floor. Lynne Hawes of Mount Kisco, N.Y., was among them, with
a dashing fellow as her escort.
</P>
<P>
   In a setting that presages a night of glamour above the
twinkling lights of the city, he was overcome with a need to
concoct some mischief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a phone,'' he announced. ``I forgot to call my parole
officer.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Hawes recalls it, ``The captive audience, equally divided
in disbelief and horror, began to edge toward the door to get off
as soon as the elevator stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   As for herself, she writes, ``I simply turned bright purple.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Donald A. Duffy of Washington had some friends who took great
delight in telling bizarre tales when ascending in crowded
office-building elevators and then exiting at the first stop _ thus
leaving their stories unfinished and their fellow passengers agape,
spellbound and hanging in suspense.
</P>
<P>
   One morning, Duffy arranged their comeuppance. He planted an
accomplice on the elevator. When the two jokers exited as planned,
the accomplice shouted: ``Wait a minute! I want to hear the end of
this.'' And he left with them.
</P>
<P>
   The accomplice told Duffy later that the tale teller had been
rendered utterly, and satisfyingly, speechless. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a tough day in the elevators, some people come home
absolutely exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   One evening, just after Marc Ungar had moved into an apartment
building on Manhattan's East Side, he got a lesson in urban living
from a young professional couple who followed him into the
elevator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm too tired for takeout,'' the woman announced. ``Let's just
have dinner delivered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
