<HEADER>
A2784 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELIEF-LIFEFORCE-COX     07-31 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELIEF-LIFEFORCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some turn to 'spirit' instead of God
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is something in the universe larger than the sum of its
parts, but not everyone is willing to say flatly that there is a
God.
</P>
<P>
   While a vast majority of people questioned in a recent Southern
Focus Poll said they believe in God, about one in 10 Southerners
and 17 percent of non-Southerners described their belief as in a
``spirit or life force.''
</P>
<P>
   Among weekly Southern churchgoers, 99 percent said they believe
in God, while 1 percent defined their belief as in a ``spirit or
life force.'' Of Southerners who said they never go to church, 27
percent expressed belief in a spiritual force, while 60 percent
said they believed in God. The poll, conducted by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution and the University of North Carolina, showed
that Southerners who describe themselves as politically liberal are
more likely than self-described conservatives (18 percent to 6
percent) to describe their belief as in a ``life force'' rather
than in ``God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to believe everything was created by accident
or by chance and is going nowhere,'' said poll respondent John
Reagan, 54, of St. Charles, Ill. ``I don't think that seems
reasonable. But I'm not sure the Christian concept is reasonable
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan, an electrical engineer who was raised Catholic, said he
is troubled by the church's idea of eternal punishment for sins and
exclusion of non-Christians from God's grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of believe man created religion so he could find a way
of obtaining immortal life because he wanted to,'' said Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Faison, 74, of Charlotte, has similar views.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to pick a word to describe it, I'm an agnostic,'' she
said. ``I do believe there's something that holds all of us
together _ I've just never been convinced of what that is.''
</P>
<P>
   Faison, a retired stenographer who was raised Methodist, said
she no longer attends church.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year between October 1992 and fall of 1993, her son,
mother and daughter all died, and she found herself crying out for
divine support.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my direst moments, I find myself calling for help or
assistance or acknowledgment,'' she said. ``I don't remember any
response. I don't know that I've ever received any
acknowledgment.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward personal spirituality is growing, said Dan
Liss, 48, founding editor of Aquarius, an alternative newspaper in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who do believe there is a divine
force in the universe, whether they call it creator, goddess or
power,'' he said, ``but they're fed up with church politics. Should
women be ministers? Should gays be married in church? People want
to be connected to a higher power, but they don't want to be caught
up in all those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people are also dissatisfied with religious hierarchies, he
said. ``There's the same resistance to top-down management styles
you see in
</P>
<P>
   business.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Liss' readers are developing their own ``eclectic belief
systems,'' he said. ``They may be part of a Buddhist meditation
group. They may also do a `full moon circle' with a women's group
and study the kabbalah.''
</P>
<P>
   He compares the trend in religion to one he sees in medicine.
Some people go to doctors, but they still try herbal medicine and
massage therapy, he said. ``They want to pick out the parts that
work for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Eiesland, an assistant professor of sociology of religion
at Emory University, talks about an ``amazing fertility'' of
spiritual beliefs in a culture where there is no state religion.
</P>
<P>
   She relates the trend toward belief in a ``life force'' to the
flourishing self-improvement movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tapping into a spiritual source,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Chase Melver, 24, a greenskeeper from Ash, N.C.,
describes that spiritual force as ``the driving energy that makes
the stars burn, which gives us light which makes the grass grow so
the cows can eat the grass and we can eat the cows and drink their
milk. ...''
</P>
<P>
   But Melver, who attended a Baptist church as a small child, said
he does not attribute to that force any morality or standards of
value. ``It sets the stage for us to make our own decisions,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He looks at humankind as part of the giant food chain, with
responsibility for keeping the planet healthy. Melver said he has
talked at length to friends and read the New Testament, the Koran
and ``The Celestine Prophecy'' as part of his spiritual quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dream about it,'' he said. ``You can drive yourself nuts
thinking about this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
