<HEADER>
A2785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-PORCHES-COX     07-31 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PORCHES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Porches: Homeowners expand the cozy, sit-a-spell comfort of the
indoors
 &HT;    FREELANCE STORY. TO BE USED BY COX PAPERS ONLY. NOT TO BE USED
BY NY TIMES WIRE.
 &HT;    By Lisa Mowry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Porches offer the best of both worlds. When you're swaying in a
swing, enjoying the hum of outdoors, you're not sealed off from the
world like you are inside on the sofa. Yet you're partially
protected from the elements.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why homeowners of all ages and lifestyles are
clamoring to add a porch or just dress one up.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we're seeking nostalgia, a chance to re-create a Norman
Rockwell setting where pitchers of lemonade and churns of ice cream
provide wholesome refreshment, where Grandma's wicker settee and an
old creaky rocker are the furnishings of choice.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Andy and Aunt Bee entertained Mayberry folks on a
front porch _ not in a slick media room. With today's houses
buzzing, beeping and clicking from all the high-tech gadgetry, a
quiet porch is a gracious addition to our lives _ and an
opportunity to enjoy the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   When Audrey Newsome was growing up in Hawkinsville, friends and
neighbors gathered on her family's wide, open-air porch for
conversation and summer breezes. The 18-foot-by-30-foot porch she
recently added to her Atlanta area house serves the same purpose,
becoming party central for wedding brunches, holiday soirees or
smaller gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   At 1,100 square feet, the interior designer's house is compact,
so the porch became a necessity. ``With small houses, you need an
open place like this to breathe,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   A friend's gift of a white wicker porch swing inspired Newsome
to collect other old wicker. She arranged three seating areas,
which somehow make the space seem larger, but more intimate, she
says. The furniture upholstery was a bargain _ yards of a
discontinued fabric she chose for its woven pattern (which shows
less dirt, she says) and soft shades of mint-greens and blues.
Using colors in nature draws in the surroundings. ``This way, the
eye picks up the greens, then continues into the wooded back
yard,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Newsome didn't hesitate to use wooden pieces, such as a teak
armoire and mahogany sideboard, or an oil painting outside, though
she chose tile-topped tables for ease in cleanup. ``I just hose the
tables off if they get dirty, and once a week I use a blower on the
cushions to get the dirt off,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In suburban Gwinnett County(Ga.), Newsome's friend and client,
Carole Kendall, spends entire weekends on the porch with husband
Dave. ``We both work inside all week, so whenever possible we want
to be outside,'' Kendall says. Their charming, open-air porch has a
touch of Charleston about it, which is appropriate; the Kendalls
have a second home there and are naturally drawn to Lowcountry
architecture. White-pine floors and columns help set the tone for
leisurely evenings and the occasional party.
</P>
<P>
   It was a get-together several years ago that inspired the porch.
When heavy rain ruined what was to be an outdoor party on their
rear deck, the couple decided they needed a roofed structure. David
Kendall wanted a barn, while his wife leaned toward a porch. Their
lofty structure _ designed by Atlanta architect Scott Zanardo _
offers the best of each, with its vaulted ceiling and dormer
windows. ``With the ceiling so high, you don't feel like you're in
a room, and the sunlight can filter in,'' Carole Kendall says.
</P>
<P>
   (Depending on the features, Zanardo says the cost of adding a
covered porch can range from about $20 to $45 per square foot.)
</P>
<P>
   If the Kendalls' architecture is farmhouse-meets-Charleston, the
decor has roots in Mexico. While vacationing there, Kendall picked
up a colorful, primitive fabric square and asked Newsome to
incorporate it into furnishings for her new porch. The setting now
radiates with vibrant greens, yellows and reds, a welcome change to
the soft pastel upholsteries typically paired with antique wicker.
</P>
<P>
   The porch is part living room, part dining area, part den. An
armoire hides a television set, allowing the Kendalls to experience
the unlikely combination of De Niro and a summer breeze. And in
nice weather, the Kendalls are known to eat three meals a day
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've thought about putting a bed out on the porch,'' she
says. ``Then we wouldn't have to come inside at all.''
</P>
<P>
   PORCH PLANNERS: M A K I N G T H E M O V E O U T S I D E
</P>
<P>
   Before building a porch, ask yourself these questions: Where is
the best location for exposure? Can the entry be created from an
existing door or window? Should the porch be open or screened?
</P>
<P>
   Visit as many porches as possible before designing your own, and
for best results consult a professional.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   -- High ceilings and skylights allow natural light to filter in.
Add ceiling fans and electricity for lighting.
</P>
<P>
   -- Floors can be just about anything, preferably natural
materials such as old pine, Mexican tile or even cork tile.
Painting floors (with an oil-based paint) adds an old-fashioned
touch.
</P>
<P>
   -- While many prefer traditional outdoor seating made of wrought
iron or aluminum frames, others opt for a living room look. For the
latter, think aged wicker, painted wooden benches, sisal or cotton
rugs, round tablecloths, lamps and flea market finds such as picnic
baskets filled with magazines or collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   -- Use common sense about exposure. Recent refinements in
weather-resistant fabrics allow more choices in porch pillows than
in the past, but plan on replacing them every few years.
</P>
<P>
   -- A covered porch can be a great canvas for a gardener's
creativity, so long as you stick to shade or partial-shade plants.
Depending on the amount of light, container plantings can include
caladiums, hostas, ferns and even coleus and geraniums, says Teena
Barnes of Lost Mountain Nursery in west Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to get a lot of splashy color in that sort of
environment, so you need to depend on the different tones of leaves
and textures of plants to add interest,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
