<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-WATCH-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER PROTESTS, A MERGER IS SCUTTLED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Ill.)   (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two closed-end funds _ the Scudder Spain and Portugal fund and
the Growth Fund of Spain _ said their boards had voted to end a
controversial merger agreement. Instead, the two funds, which trade
at steep discounts to their net asset values, are taking steps to
allow shareholders to cash out at net asset value.
</P>
<P>
   But the two funds, both managed by Scudder Kemper Investments,
are taking different tacks. The board of the Growth Fund of Spain
approved a plan to convert to an open-end fund. It expects
shareholders to vote on the proposal in October and, if approved by
a two-thirds majority of shares outstanding, to complete the
conversion by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   A 2 percent fee will be charged on the redemption of shares not
held for at least one year, and the fund said it retained the right
to pay the proceeds of large redemptions ``in kind,'' or with stock
instead of cash.
</P>
<P>
   The Scudder Spain and Portugal fund, by contrast, will remain a
closed-end fund but will offer shareholders in-kind redemption of
their shares as soon as is practical.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellation of the merger comes after a bitter public
battle with shareholder activists who objected to several
provisions of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows how the boards of directors and the managers are
being responsive to their shareholders out of necessity,' said
David Schachter, a vice president of Thomas J. Herzfeld Advisors, a
closed-end fund specialist in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike open-end funds, which issue and redeem shares at net
asset value, closed-end funds offer a fixed number shares that
trade on stock markets. As such, they may trade at a premium to
their net asset value but far more often trade at a discount,
sometimes in the double digit percentage.
</P>
<P>
   As of July 24, the Scudder Spain and Portugal fund traded at a
discount to its net asset value of TK percent, while the the Growth
Fund of Spain traded at a discount of 10.1 percent. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Van Kampen American Capital has changed its name to Van Kampen
Investments, and the names of the funds that it runs will soon
follow suit. The company's 36 Van Kampen American Capital funds and
its 13 Morgan Stanley funds will begin using the Van Kampen name
starting on Aug. 31. The Morgan Stanley funds are administered and
distributed by Van Kampen.
</P>
<P>
   Similar changes are in the works for the company's 38 Van Kampen
American Capital closed-end funds. The 13 closed-end funds run by
Morgan Stanley will not be affected by the name changes.
</P>
<P>
   The new names are part of a corporate-wide rebranding process,
said Eileen Davis, a company spokeswoman. The changes do not affect
the management or operations of the funds.
</P>
<P>
   Van Kampen, based in Oakbrook Terrace, Ill., is a unit of Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. It took on its former name through the
acquisition of American Capital Management and Research Inc. in
1994. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blackrock Funds announced that it would close its Small Cap
Growth Equity fund to new investors on Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, with $1.5 billion in assets, returned 16.8 percent,
annualized, for the three years through July 24, versus an average
of 12.7 percent for its small-cap growth peers. It returned 5.8
percent for the 12 months through July 24, versus 6.8 percent for
its group, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial
publisher
</P>
<P>
   Blackrock has started the Micro-Cap Equity Portfolio, which is
managed by William Wykle and the same management team that runs
Small Cap Growth Equity. The new fund will invest in American
growth companies that have market capitalizations of less than $300
million. It will close when assets reach $250 million, the company
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
