<SLUG> BC-BUFFALO-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUFFALO' ROAMS FROM HATE TO LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - First-time filmmaker Vincent Gallo takes a tremendous
risk in ``Buffalo '66.'' He gives us a despicable hero and then
cajoles us into liking him.
</P>
<P>
   It's a neat trick, for Billy Brown (Gallo) is no ``lovable
rogue,'' such as we are used to from Hollywood. No, he is a
thoroughly thuggish ex-con, bristling with skull-thudding violence
and emotional emptiness. He has no redeeming qualities.
</P>
<P>
   But then we meet his parents, and suddenly we know why and begin
to feel sorry for him. His parents (Anjelica Huston, Ben Gazzara)
are monsters. She cruelly tells Billy she is sorry he was born
because his birth made her miss an important football game. In a
flashback, we learn that when Billy was young, his bullying father
killed his pet dog to punish him. The two are self-centered,
mindless, negligent troglodytes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for some reason, Billy wants to impress them.
</P>
<P>
   Billy has just gotten out of prison, although his parents don't
know it. He has told them he was away for five years doing secret
government work. He lies and tells them he has a wife. They want to
meet her.
</P>
<P>
   So Billy kidnaps Layla (Christina Ricci), a young tap-dancing
student, and threatens to beat her brains out unless she goes along
and pretends to be his wife when he meets his parents.
</P>
<P>
   But she takes on the charade with such gusto that we soon come
to realize that Layla is as unnervingly peculiar as any woman we
have seen in the cinema since Tuesday Weld in ``Pretty Poison.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is filled with hilarious details. When Billy grabs
Layla and drags her to the parking lot, she winds up having to
drive the getaway car because Billy can't handle a manual
transmission.
</P>
<P>
   He tells her just how to act around his parents: ``You'll adore
me, you'll love me, you'll cherish me. Jesus Christ, you can't live
without me.'' And what is more, they will be like a couple who have
``spanned time together.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``time spanning'' is repeated and repeated until you have to
belly-laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffalo '66'' is a tremendous movie, funny at times, touching
at others, just when you don't expect it. But always there is the
threat of bloody death behind it, making it all just a little more
on its toes than you expect.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, Gallo makes Billy oddly sympathetic. He has, as
Gallo said in an interview, ``incredible shame and guilt,
resentment and insecurity, disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all there in Gallo's incredible performance. We not only
care about him, we wish him _ and Layla _ well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffalo '66'' is rated R for violence, nudity, sexual
situations and language. 4 stars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
