<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2803 &Cx1f; taf-z
s a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUND-RAISING-EDUC-ART     07-31 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUND-RAISING-EDUC-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ECONOMIST ASKS, DOES HARVARD REALLY NEED $15 BILLION? 
</HEADLINE>
   (from `Education Life' special section)  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 2)  
 (ART ADV: Photo of Henry Hansmann is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its last five-year campaign, Yale University raised $1.7
billion, helping to push its endowment close to $6 billion.
Harvard, with a $12.8 billion endowment, is in the midst of raising
$2.1 billion more.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when a large endowment is a measure of prestige among
top universities, few have questioned the wisdom of accumulating
such huge nest eggs.
</P>
<P>
   One who has is Henry Hansmann, a professor at Yale's School of
Law and an expert on the economics and law of nonprofit
institutions. Hansmann is not against university fund raising. But
he says that students, universities and society would be better off
if universities spent most of their money now, rather than
investing it indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in his office, Hansmann spoke about the merits
and drawbacks of his ideas _ and why so few institutions seem ready
to embrace them.
</P>
<P>
   Saving has long been held up as a virtue. Why shouldn't we
applaud Harvard and Yale for what they have accomplished?
</P>
<P>
   Saving is worthwhile only if you have a better use for the money
in the future than you do now. With universities, there is no
particular reason to believe that there will be a better use in the
future and every reason to believe the reverse is true. At any
moment, boards of trustees should be asking whether a dollar is
better off going into an endowment or being invested in a young
student's mind or in research.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it better to spend the money now rather than later?
</P>
<P>
   Building an endowment means spending less on educating scholars
today and, instead, saving the money to give to scholars in the
future. Yet there is every reason to believe that incomes in the
future will be higher than they are today. That has been the case
for 350 years. So what we are doing is taking from the poor and
giving to the rich. Also, in terms of productivity of physics
experiments and other research, there is no reason to think they
will be more productive in the future than today.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that the leading universities receive more income
each year than they can usefully spend, and that therefore it is a
good thing that they are piling up some of it in an investment
account. At least there it is being used to finance productive
industries and yields at least the same rate of return that
publicly traded companies produce on average.
</P>
<P>
   But if that is true _ if universities are taking in today more
income than they can productively spend _ why do they continue to
conduct major capital campaigns to raise more, as most major
universities have in recent years?
</P>
<P>
   Many universities say they need a big endowment to insure that
there is a steady stream of money to support students and research
_ that they can't count on tuition, grants and gifts year after
year. Are they wrong?
</P>
<P>
   There is an argument that universities should be risk-averse
since they have long-term commitments and there is no easy way to
expand and contract. They have heavy investments in a physical
plant that they can't just rent out for other purposes if they have
a bad year. Tenured faculty also represent a long-term commitment.
</P>
<P>
   But if you look back over the past century, has Harvard,
Princeton, Yale or Swarthmore _ or any university _ really used its
endowment as a buffer against adversity? When times are tight, they
cut educational expenditures so they can get over the hard times
and maintain the endowment's value.
</P>
<P>
   A stranger from Mars who looks at private universities would
probably say they are institutions whose business is to manage
large pools of investment assets and that they run educational
institutions on the side that can expand and contract to act as
buffers for the investment pools.
</P>
<P>
   Is it really harmful to operate universities this way?
</P>
<P>
   The endowment makes a university riskier because when the stock
market moves down, spending goes down with it. That is probably the
very time when it is harder to get students to pay tuition and the
university is in tighter straits. What's more, the endowment tends
to be an overall net drain on most universities. They actually
spend less out of their endowments _ typically about 5 percent
annually of their endowment's current capital value _ than they put
into them each year.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the money in endowments isn't being wasted. It's
being invested in productive assets via the securities markets. It
just isn't being invested in education.
</P>
<P>
   If it makes so little sense, why are so many universities trying
so hard to build their endowments?
</P>
<P>
   They fell into it by habit. When these universities began, many
were state funded. They began raising endowments in the 19th
century, when the states cut their support. At that time, the flow
of gifts tended to be lumpy. There would be decades between
fund-raising campaigns. They couldn't afford to spend it all
immediately, or they wouldn't have had anything left after a couple
of years.
</P>
<P>
   So in the 19th century, having an endowment made a lot of sense.
Now financial gift flows are much smoother, so the need to have a
big endowment to smooth out the bulkiness of financial gifts is no
longer so apparent. But the habit remains.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for endowments is that donors prefer to make
gifts that way, to fund something over a long period of time. If
they feel they are contributing to a perpetual fund, they feel they
are buying a bit of immortality _ just as when they pay for
construction of a building. Whether it is the most efficient way to
fund a university or not, it is sometimes the only way the money
can be raised.
</P>
<P>
   Why isn't there more debate about how endowments are maintained?
</P>
<P>
   Almost no one who has the power to raise the issue has the
incentive. Giving for endowments is an attractive thing. It's a
motivator. It's very quantifiable. With these patterns of giving,
no responsible educational administrator is going to go out and
announce the end of the endowment.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any chance, then, that behavior will change?
</P>
<P>
   Once the economics of endowments are better understood, maybe
that understanding will seep into conventional wisdom. Then
universities may begin to adopt creative investment policies that
are more thoughtfully geared to the real tradeoffs between
investing in financial assets and investing in other assets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
