<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2806 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-HOSPITAL-DISPUTE     07-31 1722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOSPITAL-DISPUTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vatican orders Texas hospital to eliminate reproductive services
 &HT;    (An Austin story that moved previously, recast for a national
audience. For immediate release.)
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Vatican has twice instructed the Roman
Catholic Bishop of Austin to end contraceptive programs and
sterilizations at a church-managed city hospital, setting up a
dispute among the church, the bishop and community members.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic bishops nationwide are watching the dispute, which
involves Brackenridge Hospital, leased from the city by the
Catholic-owned Seton Healthcare Network. Seton's lease with the
city requires it to offer such reproductive services, and McCarthy,
considered one of the more moderate bishops in the country, said he
intends to stick by the terms of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Seton is owned by the religious order Daughters of Charity but
operates under the purview of the bishop, who is responsible for
ensuring that Catholic moral teachings are upheld in his diocese.
Seton had to and did receive the bishop's approval before entering
into the lease agreement; McCarthy was not required to have the
Vatican approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But an anonymous group of conservative Catholics in Austin had
complaints about the lease agreement sent to the Vatican's most
powerful office, the Congregation for the Doctrine of Faith. The
Congregation ensures that church laws are obeyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (conservative Catholics) don't listen to their bishop and
think they can overpower him, and that's what makes it more of a
problem than it needs to be,'' said the Rev. Kevin O'Rourke,
director of the Catholic Center for Health Care Ethics at St. Louis
University and one of several ethicists who reviewed the lease
agreement for the diocese.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican's response could affect future mergers, acquisitions
and management operating agreements between Catholic and
non-Catholic hospitals and medical centers throughout the country.
Last year, the Vatican stopped one merger in New Jersey, and some
bishops have stepped in to halt others. The Seton-Brackenridge
agreement began in 1995, the year the pope issued an encyclical
that warned administrators of Catholic health facilities that if
they bend the church rules on reproductive services, their
institutions could lose Catholic sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   In June, McCarthy met in Rome with Pope John Paul II and
Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, who heads the Congregation for the
Doctrine of Faith.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy confirmed that the 30-year lease agreement was
discussed but would not disclose details of his meetings, other
than to say the talks were amicable.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict could have major repercussions for Austin, McCarthy
and Seton. The Vatican could order McCarthy to tell the Daughters
of Charity to stop sterilizations and contraceptive measures at
Brackenridge or face disciplinary action, including disavowing
Seton as a Catholic institution. If McCarthy failed to follow a
Vatican directive, disciplinary measures could range from a
reprimand to removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when the city was considering turning over the
management of debt-ridden Brackenridge to Seton, controversy
erupted in the community over what would happen to reproductive
services.
</P>
<P>
   The city promised organizations such as Planned Parenthood and
the National Organization for Women that it would not turn the
hospital over to a private entity without ensuring that
reproductive services would be available. Seton vowed not to break
church laws, which prohibit abortion, sterilization, fertility
treatments and contraceptives. Both sides were optimistic that they
could work out a deal, and they did.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was not a perfect fit, McCarthy said, but it does
not violate any church laws because Seton does not directly provide
the reproductive services.
</P>
<P>
   Five Catholic ethicists approved the agreement and the City
Council unanimously approved it. The lease requires Seton to allow
reproductive services on site at Brackenridge; abortions are not
provided.
</P>
<P>
   Seton also is required to give space in the hospital for the
Austin/Travis County Health and Human Services Department to offer
reproductive services information and counseling, including
information on abortions and contraceptives. To offset the cost of
providing this service, the City of Austin required Seton pay an
additional $81,721 a year for the lease, bringing the total annual
payment to more than $2.1 million. The contract includes a possible
$10 million fine if Seton breaks the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   According to the agreement, sterilizations and contraceptives
are private matters between patients and physicians. Seton
contracts with nurses from another health-care company for nursing
services during tubal ligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The woman and her physician determine what services are
provided,'' said Ed Berger, Seton's vice president of advocacy and
public policy. ``There is not a hospital policy about that. The key
words are that Seton policies 'allow' these to take place... as
opposed to 'will provide' or 'do it' or whatever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fastiggi, an associate professor of religious studies at
St. Edward's University, has openly criticized the lease agreement,
saying he respects the bishop but thinks that the agreement
violates Catholic Church laws. He aired that opinion in 1995 during
a diocesan meeting where the agreement was explained.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, the Rev. William Broussard, ethicist for the
Austin diocese and a Seton board member, sent Fastiggi a letter
saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob you were described by those who witnessed your questions
as 'frantic,' 'emotional,' 'angry' and 'disturbed.' ''The letter
later said: ``Either you presented yourself years ago with the
skill of an actor hiding a split personality, or Bob, you are
deteriorating right in front of our eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Fastiggi also received a letter of reprimand from Patricia
Hayes, then president of St. Edward's and now executive vice
president and chief operating officer of Seton. Hayes warned
Fastiggi that his ``judgmental'' style of presenting information on
the Seton agreement and another issue needed to stop. Also, Hayes
said that her letter would become ``a part of your formal annual
evaluation as a faculty member at St. Edward's.''
</P>
<P>
   In May 1995, at the request of some Austin Catholics who didn't
want to be identified, the Saint Joseph Foundation, a San
Antonio-based conservative Catholic group, notified Rome of the
proposed lease agreement between Seton and Brackenridge,
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the concerns expressed at the time is if the identities
of all those were known, the bishop could be harsh and take
retribution against them,'' said Chuck Wilson, the Saint Joseph
Foundation executive director. ``Everything that has happened since
then has been strictly between the Congregation and McCarthy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Congregation for the Doctrine of Faith wrote McCarthy asking
for details of the agreement. He responded in early June 1995. The
Vatican sent back a letter of opposition. In July, McCarthy
notified the Vatican that a new agreement for sterilizations and
reproductive service delivery had been reached that created a
``wall of separation'' between Seton and the services the church
considers sinful.
</P>
<P>
   That letter didn't reach the Congregation for the Doctrine of
Faith office until December. In March 1996, the Vatican sent
another letter telling McCarthy not to allow the agreement to go
through until Vatican officials could fully review it. McCarthy
replied that a 30-year agreement had been signed Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Vatican has written two letters, the more recent
in December, telling McCarthy to instruct Seton to immediately stop
sterilizations and contraceptive programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clash of beliefs
</P>
<P>
   William May, an ethicist at the John Paul II Institute for
Studies on Marriage and Family in Washington, D.C., called the
Seton agreement ``fishy.''
</P>
<P>
   May, who until last year was one of 30 theologians on the
International Theological Commission, an arm of the doctrinal
congregation, added:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great difficulty reconciling this as what a Catholic
hospital should be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Theological disputes such as this one, he went on, ``are decided
by a higher authority, and the higher authority would be ... the
Congregation for the Doctrine of Faith.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy said he will continue to communicate with the Vatican
but has no plans to interfere with the Daughters of Charity
hospital operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm completely supportive of what the Daughters of Charity are
doing here,'' McCarthy said. He said they are delivering health
care to thousands of poor people who otherwise might not get needed
medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   Helping the poor, he pointed out, is one of the cornerstones of
the Catholic faith.
</P>
<P>
   In its last fiscal year that ended June 30, Seton delivered $47
million in charity health-care services. Next year, the amount is
expected to reach $50 million, Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   Seton will never break the lease, Hayes said. There are at least
15 dioceses in the country where Catholic hospitals have agreements
to offer reproductive services, O'Rourke said.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics for Free Choice, an independent group that believes
Catholics should be able to make their own decisions on
reproduction, reports that 84 Catholic hospitals have merged with
non-Catholic institutions since 1990. Twenty more mergers are
pending. It is expected that 15 of the new institutions will not
provide reproductive services.
</P>
<P>
   Provisions for such services are an economic necessity for many
Catholic hospitals. Without the availability of reproductive
services, Catholic hospitals risk losing contracts with managed
health-care providers, the bread and butter of any health system,
O'Rourke said.
</P>
<P>
   The mission of a Catholic hospital system is to provide health
care to the poor, but it must have income from insured patients to
pay for its work with the less fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not trying to expand our hospital empire ... we don't
think of health care as a business,'' McCarthy said. ``We are
trying to protect health care for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
