<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton pledged Friday to
testify ``completely and truthfully'' before independent counsel
Ken Starr's grand jury Aug. 17, but served notice that neither he
nor his spokesmen would have any further comment on the Monica
Lewinsky matter before then. In fact, press secretary Mike McCurry
announced that he was taking a two-week vacation. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   TECH-LOBBYING _ WASHINGTON _ Last fall, the high-tech industry
lost a legislative skirmish in its multi-year battle with the FBI
and U.S. spy agencies over who will control encryption of messages
on the Internet. Scared and enraged by a loss that threatened the
growth of their industry's profits, high-tech rivals stopped
dissing each other long enough to chip in more than $5 million to
form a lobbying coaltion called Americans for Computer Privacy and
convince a lot of their customers, suppliers and sympathizers to
sign up. Launched in March, the $5 million lobbying alliance of
more than 90 companies and 40 associations already has won some
early rounds in its fight against the FBI and U.S. spy agencies. A
look at who formed Americans for Computer Privacy, why, how they
grew it, how they run it, and what it does. (Mollison, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TECH-ENCRYPTION _ WASHINGTON _ What the coalition wants and why
its foes don't want to give it to them. With art and data for a
graphic showing the founding, inner circle and rank-and-file
companies and associations in the coalition, together with lobbying
and political expenditures. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SCHIZOPHRENIA _ WASHINGTON _ Scientists are coming up with a
deeper understanding and new treatments for schizophrenia.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moved Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-MINES _ LONDON _ To honor a cause dear to Princess
Diana's heart, the British army on Friday pledged to end the use of
land mines before the anniversary of the princess's death late this
month. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTIONS _ OAXACA, Mexico _ Mexico continues to test its
transition to peaceful and pluralistic elections this Sunday, Aug.
2. Jubilant from its first gubernatorial victory in Zacatecas state
in July, Mexico's left-center Party of the Democratic Revolution
(PRD) has another strong candidate running in Oaxaca state on Aug.
2. In many ways, Oaxaca's election is more meaningful for the PRD
than Zacatecas': In Zacatecas, the PRD's candidate was a recent
convert from the dominant Revolutionary Institutional Party (the
PRI), who took votes with him because he was popular. In Oaxaca,
the PRD's Hector Sanchez is a true party man, and a popular
grass-roots activist who speaks Zapotec, an Indian language, and
whose political experience includes fighting for peasant and Indian
rights. His victory -- or even a close second place showing_ would
represent an electoral break through for Mexico's Indian and left
activists, who are often targets of assassination attempts and
arbitrary arrests in this impoverished, politically violent state.
On Aug. 2, governors will also be chosen in the Mexican states of
Aguascalientes and Veracruz. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CADET _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ The first woman ever
admitted to Russia's vaunted naval academy, founded by Peter the
Great, has just finished her first hellish year. Similar to her
American counterparts at military academies like Annapolis and West
Point, she has tales to tell of difficult days ina mostly-male
dominion. But Lyudmilla Yolshina is alone, a female class of one in
a first-year class of 60. She won't quit, she says, but she's not
sure she'd recommended it to other women. (Holmes, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-HUSSEIN _ AMMAN, Jordan _ The soveriegn of this small
country for 45 years, King Hussein is the emblem of his nation and
its guarantor of stability and security. Even among those who feel
he has been dictatorial and let his country languish in an economic
recession, Jordainians breathed a sigh of relief to see him
apparently in control of his recently found lymphoma cancer. ``This
is not the time for the king to be sick, you know,'' said car parts
retalier George Naber, after watching the King on television
Tuesday nigh. ``The situation in this country is very bad. He is
the only one who can control everything.'' The King's illness calls
into question the future of a small country that plays a huge role
in protecting the stability of the Middle East. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Thursday, July 30
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TUSKEEGEE _ On Sunday, a street in the Dobbins Air Reserve Base
compound will be named after the Tuskeegee Airmen of World War II.
(Payne, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   POPE-HOSPITAL _AUSTIN, Texas _ The Vatican has twice instructed
the Roman Catholic Bishop of Austin to end contraceptive programs
and sterilizations at a church-managed city hospital, setting up a
dispute among the church, the bishop and community members.
Catholic bishops nationwide are watching the dispute, which
involves Brackenridge Hospital, leased from the city by the
Catholic-owned Seton Healthcare Network. Seton's lease with the
city requires it to offer such reproductive services, and McCarthy,
considered one of the more moderate bishops in the country, said he
intends to stick by the terms of the agreement. (Perkes. Austin
American-Statesmen)
</P>
<P>
   SMUGGLERS _ AUSTIN _ It began with a few stolen pickups and
Chevrolet Suburbans along Interstate 35 in North Austin last year.
A few soon became a few hundred. And when some of the same stolen
Austin trucks began showing up abandoned by the border near Eagle
Pass, detectives launched an investigation that would uncover an
elaborate illegal- immigrant smuggling ring involving 200 stolen
vehicles and thousands of undocumented immigrants. (Tanamachi,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PBP-REYNOLDS (DEVELOPING) _ Creditors have accepted Burt
Reynolds' bankruptcy plan. This is the final stumbling block to
Burt actually getting his plan going and getting out of bankruptcy.
(Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   PREDATOR _ DAYTON, Ohio _ In late June, 20-year-old Louis B.
Hauff, a man classified as a sexual predator, returned to town
after serving a year in prison for corruption of a minor. In most
places in Ohio, deputies would have notified Hauff's neighbors
about his criminal record. They also would have informed nearby
schools, day-care centers, and children's services agencies. But
that didn't happen here.The Court of Appeals that governs Shelby
County and the rest of northwest Ohio has ruled that parts of the
sexual predator law are unconstitutional. (Keilman, Dayton Daily
News). 20.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   Eds: The stories with the BELIEF prefix below are part of a
final package of stories by the Atlanta Journal-Constitution on
What Southerners Believe.
</P>
<P>
   BELIEF-DEVIL _ Southerners look to God and organized religion
for help in explaining many of life's mysteries. And their beliefs
are not lightly held; they run deep. Much more than in other parts
of the country, Southerners believe there is a God (88%) and that
God answers prayers (90%). In Dixie, people may be less likely to
buy into alien visitation, UFO's or psychic healing, but they
absolutely believe in devil possession, and that some souls go to
heaven while others go to Hell. (White, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BELIEF-LIFEFORCE _ A small but noteworthy portion of the people
we polled would not say they believed in God, but affirmed their
belief in a ``life force.'' Nearly 10 percent of Souterhners and 17
percent of non-Southerners fell into this category. We talk to some
of them about what they mean and how a life force is different than
a traditional Jewish-Muslim-Christian view of God. We look at the
possible Eastern influences. And, for the 87 percent of Southerners
who believe in God (compared to 68 percent of non-South), we
discuss how they view him/her as judge, redeemer, etc. (White,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
