<HEADLINE>
A PINCH OF GARDEN WHIMSY: ANNUAL GRASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 2)  
(lb) 
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grass is usually thought of in two ways: the green kind that has
to be mowed frequently in the summer, and the stately ornamental
kind that helps make the garden look decent in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   There's another kind: annual grass for the flower garden.
</P>
<P>
   Turf grass and most ornamental grasses are permanent landscaping
features that should be planted with some thought to their
placement, and given maintenance care. Annual grasses can be
planted on a whim _ in a garden or a tub or wherever you think
their flower stalks and seed heads would look good.
</P>
<P>
   Clumps of grasses like red switch grass and fountain grass are
good in the perennial garden, where they can fill spaces left by
Oriental poppies and other plants that go dormant after blooming.
Hare's-tail grass and canary grass look terrific in the annual
garden, mixed with bedding plants like dwarf cockscomb and globe
amaranth.
</P>
<P>
   In the cutting garden, quaking grass and Job's-tears provide
abundant material for fresh and dried arrangements. Biennial
grasses like wheat can be planted in autumn with the cornflowers
and larkspur, and will be ready for cutting early the following
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Annual and biennial grasses belong to the family Gramineae,
which encompasses everything from the front-yard fescue to bamboo,
as well as most important food grains, like wheat, barley, oats and
corn.
</P>
<P>
   Common grains are often attractive in their own right. (The
volunteer oats that sprout from the straw mulch in the cutting
garden save me the trouble of planting them.) But some grain
varieties can be selected especially for their beauty. Red and
black broomcorn (Sorghum vulgare) is striking as a screen or tall
background plant. Decorative wheat (Triticum aestivum) may be
silver, black or buff, and is usually bearded _ that is, with
slender bristles, or awns, extending from the seed.
</P>
<P>
   In a pinch, you could eat the decorative wheat, and any wildlife
visiting your garden certainly will. Birds are especially fond of
foxtail millet (Setaria macrocheata), which blends beautifully with
native flowers in wild gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Some annual grasses are grown for their seed heads. Job's-tears
(Coix Lacryma-Jobi) produce hard seeds, white to bluish-gray and
about the size of a pea, on 3-foot stalks. The seeds, which smell
like popcorn, are used as beads for necklaces and rosaries in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Canary grass (Phalaris canariensis) has tight seed heads that
look a bit like plumed cockscomb. As the name implies, it is grown
commercially for bird food. Quaking grass (Briza maxima) has
dangling, heart-shaped seed heads that dance in a breeze. The seed
heads of animated oats (Avena sterilis) have awns that twist and
untwist when laid on a moist surface, a habit that makes them
useful as fly-fishing lures.
</P>
<P>
   But most decorative annual grasses are grown for their flower
stalks, which don't really look like flowers but more like feathery
or fluffy plumes. If you intend to use them as fresh or dried
flowers, you should cut them before the color starts to fade and
seeds develop. They dry quickly hanging upside down in bunches in a
dark, well-ventilated place.
</P>
<P>
   Hare's-tail grass (Lagurus ovatus) produces white puffs at the
ends of foot-tall stems. The dark rose plumes of champagne grass
(Rhynchelytrum repens) are about 2 feet long and are produced
continuously from June until autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Fountain grass (Pennisetum setaceum) grows to 2 feet, with
lavender-purple plumes. Feathertop (Pennisetum vilosum) produces
white, woolly plumes that look like small versions of pampas grass.
Red switch grass (Panicum violaceum) and prairie switch grass (P.
virgatum) are on the tall side, at 4 to 6 feet, but the purple-red
plumes are so delicate and airy that the plant doesn't look
overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Switch grass is a perennial, and fountain grass will overwinter
in mild climates. Both bloom the first year from seed, and can be
grown as annuals, although you'll have to pull up the switch grass
to keep it from coming back the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Growing annual grasses is easy. Most can be sowed directly into
the garden in early spring, several weeks before the last frost. A
few, like Job's-tears, germinate better if started indoors under
warmer conditions. If you intend to grow grasses among your annual
flowers, you might want to start them indoors so they can be set
out with the flowering plants. Wherever you start them, a pinch of
seeds _ five or six _ is enough to produce a clump.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't necessary to thin the seedlings. If there are too many,
the strongest plants will crowd out the weaker ones.
</P>
<P>
   Most annual grasses will produce flower plumes 12 to 15 weeks
from seeding, so a clump of fountain grass planted in early April
will be in bloom just in time to rescue the flower garden from the
dog days of late summer.
</P>
<P>
   Seed heads of annual grasses do not persist through the winter
as well as those of perennial ornamental grasses, so you may want
to remove the plants after they have bloomed and replace them with
something like fall-blooming chrysanthemums or pansies.
</P>
<P>
   Annual grasses also need to be planted every year, as they do
not reliably seed themselves. That's really no disadvantage. If the
grasses seeded themselves, either they would become a nuisance or
the flower garden would become another lawn.
</P>
<P>
   A lawn, you'll remember, consists of that green stuff you have
to mow frequently.
</P>
</TEXT>
