<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Washington) _ A powerful array of forces at home
and abroad slowed the economy to a modest but healthy pace during
the second quarter, defying widespread predictions of a sharper
downturn, the government said Friday. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ President Clinton, commenting
publicly for the first time about the Aug. 17 testimony his lawyers
fought to avoid, said he will ``completely and truthfully'' answer
prosecutors' questions about Monica Lewinsky. By John M. Broder.
(Summary from wires.)
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO (Sedlare, Serbia) _ Out of sight of the diplomats,
foreign monitors and aid workers in the Serbian province of Kosovo
there were thousands of new refugees Friday, fleeing a military
offensive the government decreed was over a day ago. By Mike
O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ A steady majority of the House
voted repeatedly Friday to shield a bipartisan campaign finance
bill from a final onslaught of amendments, making it all but
certain that the measure will win final House passage. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-RUSSIA (Washington) _ An IBM subsidiary plead guilty Friday
to illegally exporting 17 advanced computers to a Russian nuclear
weapons laboratory and agreed to pay a $8.5 million fine, in what
is believed to be the first criminal conviction against the
corporate giant. By Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   CORMORANT-SLAYING (Undated) _ In the largest mass-killing of a
federally protected species, 1,000 cormorants were shot in Lake
Ontario near Watertown, N.Y., apparently because they had been
eating too many of the wide-mouthed bass that fisherman also crave.
Masses of dead and dying birds _ almost all of them fledgling young
that were not able to fly were discovered on Wednesday on Little
Galloo Island by two New York state biologists. By Andrew C.
Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-GAMES (Undated) _ The Gay Games, founded 16 years ago as way
to bring together through sports competition people who were being
excluded from mainstream life, has found itself on the eve of the
fifth ``Gay Olympiad'' in Amsterdam being accused of the very thing
it was created to fight: sexual discrimination. By Kirk Johnson.
</P>
