<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Aug. 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fourth consecutive weekend with low humidity and dry
conditions is expected across much of the Northeast. Sprawling high
pressure will circulate seasonable air into New England with
cumulus clouds developing during the afternoon over the hilly
terrain. It will be mainly sunny from the Northeast Coast to the
Middle Atlantic states and westward through the Ohio Valley and
southern Great Lakes. With light winds and low humidity, there will
be large variations in temperature both from day to night and
between urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   The push of Canadian air will reach into the Southeast with
considerable clouds and clusters of showers and thunderstorms
mostly concentrated along the leading edge of the cooler air mass.
Meanwhile, high pressure over the Gulf of Mexico will sponsor
continued hot, dry conditions over Texas and Louisiana. As sultry
air advances into the Plains, a large cluster of thunderstorms will
be generated over Kansas and western Nebraska. Farther north, humid
air streaming into the Dakotas and eastern Rockies will join with a
jet stream disturbance, triggering more thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the West will be sunny and warmer. High pressure
building along the Washington Coast will direct very warm air
toward the northern California shores. Marine air that has been
banked to the west of the Cascades will yield to drier, warmer
weather from the interior. A few thunderstorms will dampen the
southern Rockies, where the uneven heating of mountains and valleys
generates rising currents of moist air.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Island of Dryness
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Waterloo, Iowa, was on the verge of setting an
all-time record for July, having received only 0.35 inches of rain.
Waterloo's long-standing record for July dryness was set in the
Dust-Bowl year of 1936, when only 0.40 inches fell. This comparison
does not suggest that July should put in the same category as a
Dust Bowl year. The Dust Bowl drought was widespread and
protracted, spanning several years across much of the Plains. In
contrast, Waterloo received over 10 inches of rain in June, marking
its second wettest June. Moreover, most of Iowa was wetter than
average in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
