<HEADER>
A2842 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMD-PROFITS31-COX     07-31 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMD-PROFITS31-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   AMD reduces prices on K6-2 processors
</P>
<P>
   By Omar L. Gallaga
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ AMD Inc. has cut prices on desktop computer processors
it makes in Austin to keep up with cuts by rival Intel Corp. The
move could make profits more elusive for AMD.
</P>
<P>
   The reductions on the K6-2 processors will keep its prices 25
percent lower than Intel's for comparable chips.
</P>
<P>
   When AMD Chief Executive Jerry Sanders introduced the K6 in
April 1997, he pledged prices would be 25 percent less than
Intel's. The K6 has been AMD's strongest challenger to Intel chips,
with companies such as Compaq Computer Corp. and IBM Corp. using it
in lower-cost PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said this week that it would cut prices by 18 percent to
31 percent on nearly all of the Pentium II and Celeron processors
it makes for PCs.
</P>
<P>
   AMD had said that it expected to post a profit in the second
half of this year after two years of losses. It would do that, the
company said in its earnings report earlier this month, by selling
3.5 million K6 and K6-2 processors in the third quarter and 4.5
million in the fourth quarter for a total of 12 million for the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just putting more pressure on them,'' said
Michael Bernstein, an analyst with Semico Research. ``I think
they're going to be very challenged (to make a profit).''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AMD slipped in trading on the New York Stock Exchange
on Wednesday, falling 81 1/4 cents to $15.68 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   The price cuts come even as a worldwide slowdown in the
semiconductor industry has eroded profits from companies, including
Intel and AMD.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, AMD announced it lost $64.6 million despite
increased sales of its K6 processors.
</P>
<P>
   AMD will be further challenged when PC makers begin introducing
systems using Intel's new Mendocino processor, designed to compete
with AMD in the low-end PC market. Those systems are expected to
begin shipping late next month. So far, AMD won't say how it will
price its own processors in comparison to Mendocino chips.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to ship faster K6-2 processors at 350 MHz in
the third quarter and 400 MHz by the end of the year. The company
also expects to begin producing its follow-up product, the K6-3, by
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, AMD will begin work on producing the next-generation
K7 in Austin, with production at a new facility in Dresden,
Germany, to begin in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   AMD is not offering a 25 percent discount against Intel's
Celeron processors.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, AMD is matching prices on those processors, insisting
that its K6, while running at the same clock speed, offers better
performance and enhanced graphic capabilities missing in the
Celeron.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
