<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2843 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN01-C     07-31 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: NASCAR fastest growing spectator sport in country
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Sitting several hours in Thursday's rain, staring
at an empty race track and the bundled hulks of Winston Cup cars
hidden under heavy tarpaulins, was nothing for Tom and Diane
McDonald, their 12-year-old son T.J. and his buddy, Matt Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the McDonalds left their Gondert Avenue home in
Dayton for the Brickyard 400 qualifying and got as far as the
outskirts of Indianapolis when the transmission fell out of their
van.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just left it on the side of the interstate and started
walking 'til we got to an exit,'' McDonald said. ``We walked into a
motel and made two phone calls. One was to get the van towed back
to Dayton and the other was to get a taxi so we could get to the
track. The ride cost $40, but there was no way we were gonna miss
the Brickyard.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald, huddled under a small brown umbrella in his Dale
Earnhardt tank top, cap and wristwatch, felt the same Thursday as
he sat in the middle of Section 25 in the uncovered grandstands at
Indianapolis Motor Speedway. His wife wore a rain parka and the two
ingenious kids were encased, barrel-like, in the blue and gold
plastic skirts that had been wrapped around the track's 55-gallon
trash cans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sold one for $5 to some guy who wanted to protect his
wife,'' Matt said incredulously. ``I could have sold more, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots more, since tens of thousands of other fans waited almost
four hours until the track dried enough for qualifying and Ernie
Irvan won the pole. That kind of not-so-dry devotion tells you a
lot about why NASCAR is the fastest growing spectator sport in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of increasing cynicism with pro sports, this is a love
affair that's heating up the turnstiles and the till. According to
a report by IEG, a Chicago-based consulting firm, NASCAR will
generate $1.1 billion in sponsorship revenue this year. That's more
than the NFL, NBA, NHL and Major League Baseball _ COMBINED.
</P>
<P>
   Auto racing, according to Nielsen Media Research, is the only
professional sport that has increased its TV audience each year
since 1990. Over the past five years, network ratings show NASCAR
with a 20.8 percent increase as compared to the NBA with an 8.9
increase, the NHL with a plus 5.6 percent, the NFL with a 6.9
decrease and Major League Baseball down 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a record 6.1 million people attended Winston Cup
races _ an average of 190,000 per event. Those numbers will
continue to jump as tracks are being built across the country _
including Kansas City, Chicago, Denver, Atlantic City and now Jerry
Carroll's speedway in Northern Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already on his mailing list,'' said Mike and Tami
Cunningham of Cincinnati as they sat huddled beneath a
9-foot-by-12-foot sheet of plastic. ``We're waiting with an open
check book. We want tickets to the Kentucky track.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom McDonald felt the same: ``I'll be first in line for tickets,
even if it means camping out down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup racing has become the nation's motor sport of
choice, especially since the IndyCar circuit continues to dilute
its product with a nasty civil war. Even in Thursday's rain, there
was more excitement around Indianapolis than there was this past
May. Unlike with the 1998-version of the Indianapolis 500, the
hotels and restaurants here are full, the best drivers in the
business are all gathered and sponsors are clamoring to get their
names on the cars.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon, who grew up 20 miles from the Speedway in Pittsboro
and who won the inaugural Brickyard 400 in 1994, senses the
pendulum swing: ``What always made the Indianapolis Motor Speedway
and the Indy 500 is that the best of the best were in one series.
That's what I think we hold right now. We've got the best of the
best in stock car racing. And now that we're here, I'd love seeing
it be the top event here.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it already?
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Brickyard 400 winner Ricky Rudd wouldn't commit:
``Man, I hate to touch that one. I'm still a fan of the Indy 500,
but I don't think they did the race justice when they split the
sport. It's hurt the recognition. But it wouldn't be fair for me to
say stock cars are bigger than IndyCars.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have to _ the numbers say it for him. This past May
the Indy 500 drew a 5.6 TV rating - down 33 percent from 1995, the
last year CART drivers were in the race. Meanwhile, this year's
Daytona 500 drew an 8.6 audience. Even lesser NASCAR races have
drawn Indy 500 numbers. Saturday's Brickyard will do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Daytona 500 overtook the Brickyard in total purse
money this year, the crowd here _ annually at 300,000 _ is bigger.
And there would be an even larger gathering _ possibly eclipsing
the Indy 500 _ if the speedway would put more tickets on sale.
</P>
<P>
   If there are restraints on the gate here, there are none on
sponsorships. The top 10 national advertisers all market products
in NASCAR and IEG has found NASCAR alone will account for 10
percent of all the money spent this year on sports sponsorships by
U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   As Bruton Smith, who owns the Charlotte, Atlanta and Texas
speedways, said: ``When you see Fortune 500 companies getting
involved, what are they getting? Number one, they get exposure for
their product. We find our fans are intensely loyal to their
product. If there's a product on one of these cars and a product on
the shelf next to it, our fans will pick up the product that's on
that car.''
</P>
<P>
   Why is there such loyalty?
</P>
<P>
   ``These drivers don't go on strike or refuse to report,''
McDonald said. ``They appreciate the fans. The stars here walk past
and they give autographs. You don't see that with a lot of pro
football and basketball guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunnigham agreed: ``There aren't prima donnas here. These guys
are like you and me. When Harry Gant was driving, he put on roofs
during the week, then got in his stock car on the weekend. There's
something that draws you to guys like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even football and basketball players feel the stock car pull.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Washington, the former San Francisco 49ers running back who
now fields a NASCAR Grand National team with former basketball
great Julius Erving, talked about the allure of NASCAR:
</P>
<P>
   ``After you attend one of these events, there's no way for you
not to be a fan. If there's a NASCAR event on TV, there's no way I
can walk past. It's as if Lawrence Taylor jumped in front of me and
tackled me. I stop dead. I've got to take it in.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the same mindset Tom McDonald showed when he loaded his
family into a taxi to get to the track two years ago, the same
mindset Mike Cunningham and his wife had beneath that plastic
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing could have got me out of here, today,'' Mike said.
``Well . . . almost nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to a hole melted in the plastic. ``I tried to smoke a
cigar underneath here. I burned the plastic and ruined the cigar.''
</P>
<P>
   Tami laughed: ``Yeah, but he brought two more big plastic sheets
along, too. It could rain all weekend. We'd still be here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
