<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLPHINS-CAMP01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Avery in doghouse
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ This is the definition of an optimist. You are an
NFL rookie. Training camp is 10 days old and you are in the coach's
doghouse. In fact, you figure you have ``the biggest chain in the
whole doghouse'' strapped to your neck.
</P>
<P>
   And you see this as a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   This is Miami Dolphins running back John Avery's view of the
saga that has unfolded ever since he strained his right hamstring
Sunday during an intrasquad scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   He has since been the target of criticism from Dolphins coach
Jimmy Johnson for missing two days (and counting) of practices, for
showing up 15 minutes before a walk-through and for joking with
healthy teammates during practice.
</P>
<P>
   Avery's reaction?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he has taken Johnson's words to heart. Yes, he wants to
please the boss. Yes, he wants to work hard to get healthy as
quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But, no, he is not sitting in his room at night, frantically
calling his mother or his agent to complain about how the man who
just last week was covering him with praise is now blasting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach wants me back out there,'' Avery said. ``That's the way
I look at it. Not that coach dislikes me. I'm looking at it as he
knows I can contribute to the offense and I need to be out there.
That does more for my confidence than anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking at the negative things. I'm looking at the
positive things. I'm looking at getting well, getting back out
there and getting out of the doghouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' he says, ``boy, I got the biggest chain in the
doghouse around my neck.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows that the only way to remove that chain is to get back
on the field and start making the kind of runs the Dolphins
envisioned when they made him their first-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try some things to see how far to go,'' he said.
``I don't want to reinjure it and be back and forth between the
field and the training room throughout camp. I'm going to work
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no need to ask whether there is pressure to work
through it even when there is pain.
</P>
<P>
   All one has to do is wander through the locker room. Stop by
linebacker Derrick Rodger's locker. Look at the sign taped to one
side that says, ``I feel pain, but it doesn't control me.'' Check
out the one on the other side that says, in part, ``when the tough
get going, they don't say my leg is hurting or my feet are sore.''
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the talk. Just a few lockers away from Avery,
linebacker Anthony Harris is describing having his finger
dislocated Tuesday ... the bone popped through the skin ... it was
pointing this way ... it was throbbing like a second heart.
</P>
<P>
   Harris missed one practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just one of those war injuries,'' he says. ``Got to tape it up
and go.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the NFL. Avery knew it would be like this. His first day
of training camp he looked over and saw rookie fullback Landon
Smith vomiting. Smith did not stop playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different than in college,'' Avery said that day. ``When
you're in college, if you're the star and you get sick, 30 trainers
come running out. They wipe your mouth for you and say, `Are you
OK?' Here you've got to suck it up and keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Little did Avery know that three days later he would feel
something in his right hamstring. He didn't say much about it then.
It wasn't until the scrimmage _ after he carried the ball six times
in eight plays and crumpled to the ground _ that the injury jumped
into the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even after the injury, Avery says his biggest task in
training camp isn't physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest part is going to be how well I get through it
mentally,'' he said. ``Physically, I'm going to get well, I'm going
to get better, I'm going to get back out there. The mental aspects
are going to be the hardest.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Trying the real thing: The Dolphins usually use college
officials for their practices. Thursday, though, three NFL
officials _ Dale Hammer, Tom White and Jim Quirk _ were on the
field. They also will work today's practice and Saturday's
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really helps us, especially working on some new techniques
and things we're doing in the secondary, just to see how they're
going to call pass interference,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   By training camp standards, it was an easy day. One practice.
Shorts. No hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got quite a few guys banged up,'' Johnson said.
``Nothing serious, but I wanted to pull back a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
