<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   He said, she said, not about sex
</P>
<P>
   By Rowland Nethaway
</P>
<P>
   c: 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Now that Monica Lewinsky has made a deal to
testify that she had a sexual relationship with President Clinton,
the American
</P>
<P>
   people have a choice.
</P>
<P>
   Americans now can either believe a man of such rectitude that he
never inhaled when he smoked marijuana or they can believe a lying,
little tramp.
</P>
<P>
   Put that way, a lot of Americans would choose to believe
Clinton, particularly if the economy remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   However he puts it, Clinton's well-honed modus operandi is to
trash the reputations of his accusers who can't otherwise be
deflected.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's M.O. is to deflect potential accusers either with a
reward, such as the cushy government job he obtained for Gennifer
Flowers, or
</P>
<P>
   with a smear campaign, such as the one his investigators and
spin doctors did on Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Some accusers, such as Flowers and Kathleen Willey, get
Clinton's double-barreled treatment. Now that Lewinsky has grasped
the idea that
</P>
<P>
   people who lie under oath can go to prison, she should prepare
herself for Clinton's second barrel _ his ``dark side,'' according
to Leon Panetta.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton (or some nice person who works for him) helped land
Lewinsky a job in the Pentagon complete with a security clearance,
which is a
</P>
<P>
   classic example of Clinton's first-step damage control strategy.
But with subpoenas, affidavits and rumors clogging the air at the
White House, Vernon Jordan, Clinton's fixer, got several nice
out-of-town jobs lined up for Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan did much the same for Clinton's Arkansas buddy and
Whitewater insider Webster L. Hubbell just before the big guy went
down for the count for felonious fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the American ambassador to the United Nations met
at his home to discuss a U.N. job for Clinton's former intern
friend, who also
</P>
<P>
   could testify against him, is in keeping with Clinton's
time-tested M.O. for bimbo eruptions and scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's dirt diggers, Investigative Group International, has
reportedly armed Clinton with every speck of dirt in Lewinsky's
background. These investigators performed a similar service for
Clinton in the Paula Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   If Lewinsky testifies that she had a sexual relationship with
Clinton, then someone is lying under oath, which, as everyone
knows, is a crime.
</P>
<P>
   This investigation is not about sex, which is a deflection
tactic used by Clinton's spin doctors . It is about high crimes and
misdemeanors. It is about the crimes of lying under oath,
obstruction of justice and subornation of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has testified under oath that he did not have sex with
Lewinsky. He also looked right in the television camera and told
the American people that he did not have sex with the young woman
to whom he gave special gifts.
</P>
<P>
   If Lewinsky does change her testimony under oath to say that she
and Clinton had a sexual relationship, then Clinton must shift the
criminal
</P>
<P>
   perjury blame back to Lewinsky by arguing that she told the
truth the first time she was questioned but lied the second time.
</P>
<P>
   Without any other evidence, all prosectors and the American
people will know is that either Clinton or Lewinsky is guilty of
criminal perjury.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a classic ``he-said, she-said'' dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's dirt diggers may be able to produce evidence and
anecdotes that Lewinsky told lies in the past and therefore she
should not be
</P>
<P>
   believed now.
</P>
<P>
   But that would be a tough sell because Clinton has been lying,
bending the truth, shading the truth and denying the truth since
before Lewinsky was born. Remember his lies and deception about how
he avoided military service? He's not called Slick Willie for
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: RNeth(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
