<SLUG> BC-SENSUS-DRUG31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin's Sensus Drug hopes to raise $46 million in initial
public offering
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Sensus Drug Development Corp. of Austin is planning to
raise up to $46 million by selling shares of stock to the public.
</P>
<P>
   That would make it the first Austin-based biotechnology company
to make an initial public offering. Others in Austin's small
community of biotech companies are publicly traded, but they were
based elsewhere when they went public.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-year-old company is attempting to commercialize a drug
called Trovert that may be useful in treating a rare disease that
stems from excessive pituitary gland activity.
</P>
<P>
   Called acromegaly, the disease can result in abnormal growth in
the hands, feet and other parts of the body. It can lead to heart
disease and cancer. Andre the Giant, the late professional
wrestler, suffered from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Sensus estimates about 40,000 people are now receiving another
drug therapy for acromegaly.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hawkins, who previously had founded a drug-testing
company, formed Sensus with Dr. John Scarlett in 1994 to work in
partnership with researchers to speed development of drugs for
niche markets.
</P>
<P>
   Trovert is the company's first drug candidate and is ready for
the last phase of clinical tests. The company intends to seek
approval from U.S. and European drug regulators in the second half
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins founded Pharmaco Dynamics Research Inc. in the mid-1980s
as an Austin-based clinical drug testing company. He sold the
company in 1992 to Applied Bioscience International for $95 million
in stock.
</P>
<P>
   According to the registration statement filed with the
Securities and Exchange Commission, Sensus would raise up to $46
million by selling up to 5 million shares of common stock. The
company, in four years of operation, has accumulated losses of
$32.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon for drug companies to post heavy losses as
they develop drugs. The goal is to recoup investment and add profit
by selling drugs with high margins while they are protected by
patents.
</P>
<P>
   Existing shareholders own just over 23 million shares of stock.
Principal shareholders include: Ross Financial Corp. of Grand
Cayman Island, British West Indies, 8 million shares, 34.8 percent;
Richard Hawkins, 2.98 million shares, 12.9 percent; Dr. Nona Niland
of Austin, 2.98 million shares, 12.9 percent; Genentech Inc., 1.66
million shares, 7.2 percent; Chief Executive Officer Dr. John
Scarlett, 1.38 million shares, 6 percent; Goldman Sachs Group, 1.19
million shares, 5.2 percent; and Corporate Director Lyle Hohnke,
922,381 shares, 4.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to use the funds raised in the offering to pay
for further drug testing for Trovert, for repayment of $1.6 million
in debt, and for establishing a sales and marketing organization
for the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Underwriters for the offering are Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.;
NationsBanc Montgomery Securities; and BankAmerica Robertson
Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-30-98 0046E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
