<P>
   PBP-GOLF-TIPS (With photos) _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Second
installment of six-part series to help you improve your golf game.
This week's topic is irons. (Franquet, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   EVANDR _ The Evander Holyfield camp has lowered its demands for
a financial pledge from Atlanta businesses to help pay for a bout
at the Georgia Dome. This came on the heels of ``four or five''
buisnesses phoning Holyfield's attorney today as a result of
today's story that the city didn't want his fight here. (Schultz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AMD-PROFITS _ AUSTIN _ AMD Inc. has cut prices on desktop
computer processors it makes in Austin to keep up with cuts by
rival Intel Corp. The move could make profits more elusive for AMD.
The reductions on the K6-2 processors will keep its prices 25
percent lower than Intel's for comparable chips. When AMD Chief
Executive Jerry Sanders introduced the K6 in April 1997, he pledged
prices would be 25 percent less than Intel's. The K6 has been AMD's
strongest challenger to Intel chips, with companies such as Compaq
Computer Corp. and IBM Corp. using it in lower-cost PCs. (Gallaga,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SENSUS-DRUG _ AUSTIN _ Sensus Drug Development Corp. of Austin
is planning to raise up to $46 million by selling shares of stock
to the public. That would make it the first Austin-based
biotechnology company to make an initial public offering. Others in
Austin's small community of biotech companies are publicly traded,
but they were based elsewhere when they went public. The 4-year-old
company is attempting to commercialize a drug called Trovert that
may be useful in treating a rare disease that stems from excessive
pituitary gland activity. (Ladendorf, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PRATT-MOVES _ As many as 2,000 Pratt &AMP; Whitney employees from
the company's campus in northwestern Palm Beach County could be
moved to Pratt's operations in Connecticut within three years,
according to a Connecticut newspaper. The move would be part of the
company's restructuring, the Manchester Journal-Inquirer said
recently. Pratt Senior Vice President Ed Crow held meetings with
engineers in both states, the newspaper said. (Pounds, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HIWAY _ BOCA RATON _ Colorado-based Internet service company
Verio Inc. will acquire buy Hiway Technologies in a stock and cash
deal worth $352.4 million, the companies announced. The transaction
is made up of $101 million in cash and 8.67 million shares of Verio
common stock, with Hiway shareholders owning about 19 percent of
the combined company on a fully diluted basis after the deal. Hiway
also gets to appoint one member to Verio's board of directors.
(Pounds, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
