<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUTCH TEAM PULLS OUT OF TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUTUN, France _ Another day, another defection. Friday it was
the Dutch TVM team that pulled out of the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   The five remaining riders on the team did not join the race that
started in Switzerland, where it finished Thursday, and headed back
to France. They would not even set foot back in the country, their
director said, but instead would leave Switzerland and make their
way back to the Netherlands via Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Four members of the team were taken away by police after
Tuesday's race and asked to give blood, urine, and hair samples as
part of the drug investigation that has shadowed the Tour since
just before its start. TVM did not drop out the next day, but three
other teams did, angered by what they consider harassment. The
remaining riders staged a slowdown, and the stage was nullified.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Thursday, TVM's team leader, Jeroen Blijlevens, quit the
race, and the rest of the team followed suit that night.
</P>
<P>
   The race that began July 11 with 189 riders is now down to 96,
with two days of racing to go. Some of those dropouts are the
results of crashes or fatigue, but most have withdrawn in defiance
amid the ongoing drug investigations by French police.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, authorities placed Italian rider Rodolfo Massi under
investigation, one step short of charging him, the first such
action against a cyclist. Dr. Nicolas Terrados Cepada of the
Spanish team ONCE also was placed under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh, there was a race Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The riders left Switzerland and headed west for a 150-mile ride
to this city of 16,000 near Dijon in central France. A group of 14
riders that included Pascal Derame and Frankie Andreu of the US
Postal Service team took off after just 15 minutes and opened a gap
of 15 minutes on the pack.
</P>
<P>
   But since no one in the lead group was top-ranked, the others
felt safe to let them go, since whoever won wouldn't affect the
overall standings.
</P>
<P>
   With about 5 miles left, a group of four bolted ahead to battle
it out on the flat sprint finish, and even though Derame appeared
in position to take it, he was edged by Swede Magnus Backstedt.
Andreu finished with a group just 25 seconds behind, and most of
the pack cruised in 16 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Backstedt, a former downhill skier, is the first Swede to win a
stage in the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   The overall standings remain the same, with Italian Marco
Pantani in first place, followed by Bobby Julich of Glenwood
Springs, Colo., and Jan Ullrich of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But in Saturday's time trial, all eyes will no doubt be on Tyler
Hamilton of Brookline, Mass., who surprised everyone with his
second-place finish in the time trial two weeks ago. ``Well, more
eyes will be on me than last time,'' he said Friday. ``Most people
were saying, `Who's this guy?' and going through their files to
figure out who I am and where I'd come from.''
</P>
<P>
   But he seemed calm about the race as he relaxed before the stage
Friday, drinking coffee, eating a piece of apple pie, and talking
on a cell phone to his fiancee, Haven Parchinski, in Boston (at 4
a.m. EST).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the race (today) is a lot like the last one, with a
lot of ups and downs, ups and downs, so I think that's good for
me,'' Hamilton said. ``But this is after about three weeks of
racing, so hopefully, my body will be able to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who was ranked fifth overall after that first time
trial, is now in 53d place. It's a disappointment, he said, but not
surprising, considering he suffered heat stroke one day last week
and almost pulled out of the race. ``My goal before the race was to
be in the top 20 or 25, but I lost an hour and 6 minutes in two
days last week,'' he said. ``But that's all right. You learn from
things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The two riders who have the most at stake today are Julich and
Ullrich. They are separated by only 14 seconds and could easily
swap positions today.
</P>
<P>
   While Julich finished fourth in the last time trial, Ullrich won
the race and was 1 minute 18 seconds ahead of the US cyclist. If he
rides that way again, Ullrich wili probably leapfrog over Julich.
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday's race, Julich pedaled away from reporters,
saying, ``I have to get to the podium.''
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about the podium at the staging area where riders
sign in for the day's race, but by tomorrow, he might be talking
about a very different podium. That's the one in Paris, on the
Champs Elysees. And whether he's in second or third place, it's a
safe bet that Julich will be standing there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material Press was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
