<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2859 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-31 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOOD TRAVELS TO THE US TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ David Wood tells the story on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was with the Rockets, Hakeem Olajuwon told (general
manager) Ray Patterson, `You should have more players on this team
like David Wood.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty impressive, huh?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' continues Wood. ``He said, `We need more
players making $300,000 so you have more money to pay me.'''
</P>
<P>
   That's assuming David Wood has ever made $300,000 in one shot.
Maybe he has, but it's more likely that the Ultimate Handyman has
always settled for the minimum. He has, after all, played a total
of 412 NBA games for eight NBA teams. Throw in time spent in Italy,
Spain, and what we might call Denny's America (i.e., the CBA) and
you've got one of the great Marco Polo hoop resumes of our time.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's representing Uncle Sam. Look what The Lockout hath
wrought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wouldn't a guy like me want to play for this team?'' he
says. ``This is a great opportunity. If I win a gold medal, it will
be the highlight of my basketball career.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Tomjanovich has made Wood a starting forward on his US team
here at the World Basketball Championships. He was in quick foul
trouble in the opener against Brazil. He was more conspicuous in
the loss to Lithuania (including a 3-pointer during a near-miss
comeback). And he was very efficient in Friday's 88-62 dispatch of
South Korea, shooting 4 for 5 from the floor while picking up two
rebounds and two assists.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA players who chose to stiff USA Basketball and the world
championships are almost all cradle-to-grave spoiled athletic pups.
They were stars in high school. They schlepped around as AAU
princes. They were big deals in college. They were high draft
picks. They can afford to tip in large denominations.
</P>
<P>
   David Wood represents the flip side of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 6-1 and 124 pounds as a sophomore in high school,'' he
reports. ``I got cut by the JVs.''
</P>
<P>
   He arrived at Nevada-Reno via Skagit Junior College. He didn't
put up big numbers in Reno, either (12 points and 9 rebounds a game
as a senior). But what impressed NBA scouts was the same thing that
always seems to keep this 6-foot-7-inch forward employed. ``I
defend. I get offensive rebounds. I'm a 3-point shooter. I play
hard all the time,'' he explains. ``If you're looking for a guy
like that to come off your bench, then I'm your man.''
</P>
<P>
   And he is available. One of the reasons he was eager to get on
this team was the audition factor. ``I think there are as many as
seven or eight guys on the team who might wind up with NBA offers
if they play well in this tournament,'' he reasons. He figures he's
one of them.
</P>
<P>
   He was last seen in the NBA during the 1996-97 season
(Milwaukee). He split last season between Unicaja Malaga in the
Spanish League and the Rockford Lightning of the CBA. ``It's one
thing being a bench player in the NBA and it's another thing
playing in Europe and the CBA,'' he explains. ``I've played five
years as a role player in the NBA. In Europe and the CBA, I can
score. I averaged a double-double in Rockford. After you play there
for a while, you start to get your offensive aggressiveness back.''
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old journeyman _ if he isn't, then just who is? _ is
the complete team guy, so he is still smarting from the 84-82 loss
to Lithuania that keeps the US from getting a No. 1 seed in the
next round of this tournament. ``What happened, in my opinion, is
that we heard the game plan the coaches gave us, but it went in one
ear and out the other,'' he says. ``We did not rotate properly on
defense at all.''
</P>
<P>
   He still isn't sure how good this team is, although he
definitely knows how good it isn't. That realization became clear
when the US barely defeated middle-of-the-road Italy in an
exhibition game last Saturday night in Rome. ``My anxiety level
went up after that game,'' he admits. ``I realized then it won't be
a cakewalk for us here. We're good enough to win, but it depends on
a lot of factors. We'll have to play smart.''
</P>
<P>
   He pretty much implies that if the US doesn't bring home the
gold, it won't be the fault of the coaches. ``This might be the
best coaching I've ever had in my career,'' he says. ``Rudy, Del
(Harris), and Lon (Kruger) are all great communicators. The game
plans are superb. I know it sounds like I'm kissing some butt here,
but that's really the way I feel about it.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's one thing David Wood knows something about, it's
coaches. In the NBA alone, he's had them in Chicago, Houston, San
Antonio, Detroit, Golden State, Phoenix, Dallas, and Milwaukee.
While in Houston, he came across Rudy T, then an assistant to Don
Chaney. Rudy already knew what made Wood tick, so it isn't so
surprising that he not only made this team but has wound up as a
starter.
</P>
<P>
   Wood is well aware that he isn't playing for a Dream Team.
``We're looking for any motivation we can find,'' he says, ``but
some of the stuff that's been written and said is pretty hurtful.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst?
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone in a Greek paper compared us to the lint at the bottom
of a washing machine,'' he replies. ``We had that translated for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood never gets too up or too down. ``Basketball is important,''
he says, ``but spiritual things are more important. I'm a follower
of Jesus Christ. I don't push my beliefs on anyone, but if someone
wants to find God, I'm there to share. Sometimes I think that's why
I've bounced around so much. He wants me to come in contact with
people.''
</P>
<P>
   If someone out there thinks he has bounced around more than
Wood, let him or her speak now or forever remain silent. ``Most
guys like me spend a couple of years somewhere,'' he says. ``The
longest I've ever been anywhere is with Golden State for a year and
a half, and that was counting two different stints.''
</P>
<P>
   He was planning a normal summer. There was the matter of a
basketball camp, and there was a planned family vacation to Mexico.
Then one day, the phone rang and the voice on the other end asked
if he were interested in this US team. ``I talked to A.C. Green,
Armon Gilliam, and Chuck Person about it,'' Wood says, ``and they
said I should grab the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a childhood dream of mine, to play for the country.
When I was younger, you had to be an All-American. Now you've got
to be one of the top 30 players in the world. For me, this is huge.
It's a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   There couldn't possibly be any more to say.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
