<HEADER>
A2880 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CLINTON-NOMINEES     07-31 0331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-NOMINEES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSE SOMEONE WORTHY OF SERVING, BILL  
 (THIS EDITORIAL IS APPEARING THE AUG. 1 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a thought:
</P>
<P>
   If President Bill Clinton is interested in filling job vacancies
in the federal government, how about filling them with qualified
people?
</P>
<P>
   What a concept.
</P>
<P>
   You might recall Clinton's selection of Zoe Baird for attorney
general, Lani Guinier for a Justice Department position and Judge
Frederica Massiah-Jackson to serve on the U.S. District Court in
Philadelphia never got off the ground. It wasn't going to happen,
thanks to the excess baggage attached to the nominees'
controversial careers.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton still hasn't learned his lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, the Senate Armed Services Committee killed
Clinton's nomination of Daryl Jones to be Air Force secretary. The
president should have seen this coming and spared all concerned an
unpleasant battle.
</P>
<P>
   Even before his nomination last fall, Jones had difficulty _
indeed, different stories _ in answering several charges against
him. He boasted he had 2,000 hours of flying time, while official
records showed he had far fewer hours in the air. Jones apparently
accepted supplemental Air Force flight pay that continued for 3{
years even though he was no longer flying and an Air Force enlisted
man told investigators Jones had sought to sell Amway products to
him.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Securities and Exchange Commission investigated
a Miami airport bond deal that involved lobbying by Jones on behalf
of a financial company, though no wrongdoing has been established.
</P>
<P>
   These lingering doubts led to the inevitable failure of the
Jones nomination, a bitter setback for the president who invested
long hours on the phone with skeptical senators. In the end,
Clinton _ again _ has no one to blame but himself. Next time, Bill,
pick someone who has unimpeachable credentials. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2881 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GANG-INJUNCTION-HNS &LR;      07-31 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANG-INJUNCTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS JUDGE APPLIES CALIFORNIA-STYLE `GANG INJUNCTION' AGAINST 5
SUSPECTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Using a California-style ``gang injunction'' for
the first time in Texas, a judge Friday ordered five suspected gang
members not to associate and banned them from a seven-block area
where Austin police said they openly dealt illegal drugs and
intimidated merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring the five young men to be public nuisances, state
District Judge Wilford Flowers issued a temporary injunction that
authorizes police to arrest them if they violate any of numerous
restrictions, including a ban on their using certain pay phones and
carrying beepers.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers called the restrictions unjustified and
unconstitutional. They contend existing drug laws and criminal
trespass sanctions are the appropriate remedies to discourage
unwelcome visitors.
</P>
<P>
   One cited testimony indicating that prosecutors in Houston and
other Texas cities are watching the Austin case with hopes of
adding the ``gang injunction'' to their arsenal of anti-drug
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers are planning to appeal Flowers' decision to the 3rd
Court of Appeals. A jury trial will be held later to determine if
the temporary injunction should be made permanent.
</P>
<P>
   The judge had issued a temporary restraining order against the
five men about three weeks ago. He strengthened it Friday after
conducting a four-day hearing that included testimony from police
and concerned neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors said the injunction is the hard-earned prize of
the Windsor Park neighborhood, whose crime-weary citizens withstood
threats and bureaucratic frustrations to address their problem. The
neighborhood, just north of Robert Mueller Municipal Airport, is a
collection of modestly priced homes dissected by a bustling
commercial corridor along Cameron Road.
</P>
<P>
   The court order bars the five men from gathering along certain
blocks of Cameron Road and specifically bars them from the premises
of two convenience stores and two nearby apartment complexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story here is how people in the neighborhood got behind
business owners and really lent their support to get these folks
off their property and to quit using their property to sell dope,''
said Assistant District Attorney Bryan Case of Travis County.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do not have a right to get together to commit crimes.
They just flat don't have it,'' said Case, who overcame arguments
that the injunction trampled the five men's civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers claim the civil injunction violates the
defendants' rights of association and assembly and say it was based
on flimsy evidence that would not have been admitted in a criminal
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good example of how we can set a precedent with
very measly facts,'' said attorney Francis Williams Montenegro, who
represents Percy Prejean, 19.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro said prosecutors failed to prove that the defendants
were engaged in organized criminal activity to deliver cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``At most, the evidence showed that some of the defendants
possessed cocaine,'' Montenegro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's lawmaking by the judge. It's very vague, and it gives to
police the power to decide what is abusive language or intimidating
behavior,'' he complained.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro noted that during the hearing before Flowers, an
Austin policeman testified that a mere smile from a gang member can
be construed as intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called it `showing your grill.' So, if my client smiles in
that four-block area, he's going to be arrested,'' Montenegro said.
``Anything that he does, whether it's going to get an ice cream or
smiling or bending down, is suspect behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro acknowledged there was police testimony that the five
defendants are affiliated with a ``subset'' of the Crips gang, but
he insists they are not an ``organized criminal enterprise'' as the
state alleged.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are a criminal organization, the term is used
pathetically loosely,'' Montenegro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are kids who aren't organized, don't have a hierarchy or
even a subculture. They're kids in the neighborhood who don't have
anything to do but hang out. And the very fact that they have a
place as their socializing square is suspect to people.''
</P>
<P>
   But Case said testimony showed the ``hanging out'' was far from
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had business owners and civilians who had seen these
defendants make hand-to-hand deliveries of things into cars, short
exchanges of 5 to 10 seconds, repeatedly,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put on testimony that four of the individuals have been
previously arrested for possession of a controlled substance. One
of them was on tape selling an undercover officer a controlled
substance in Operation Crackdown,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that started happening, four of these defendants really
began to feel the squeeze and began intimidating owners and
residents with threats like `I'll kill your ass,' or `I'll burn
your place down,' or `I'll kick your ass.'''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor said the injunction is similar to a 2-year-old
concept applied _ and legally upheld _ in California.
</P>
<P>
   While the tactic may be popular in some segments of the public,
Case said seeking and enforcing such an injunction is
labor-intensive and ``not very practical.'' He suspects the
injunctions will be sought only rarely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
