<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2891 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LILITH-FAIR-$ADV02-AR     07-31 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILITH-FAIR-$ADV02-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WAY A FISH NEEDS A BICYCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 2)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By JEFF MacGREGOR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I am surrounded by women. Tall, short, fat, thin,
tank top, crop top, flattop, bobbed, blunt cut, dreadlocks,
Goldilocks, hair the color of wheat, whisky, midnight, creme de
menthe; they're young, old, sweet, weird, pierced, plucked,
smoothed, branded, braided, bald; with pants too big, pants too
small, kilts, culottes, khaki. Black, lots of black. Pajama pants.
Flannel. Latex. Cashmere. Tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   I am a man alone at Lilith Fair. A single man. Crossing the
parking lot, I can hear music fading and gaining against the
afternoon breeze. The music spools out and brushes between the cars
even a quarter of a mile from the gate. There is salt in the air,
and sisterhood, and I am here to answer the only honest question
any man ever had about Lilith Fair: Is it a good place to meet
women?
</P>
<P>
   Lilith Fair, of course, is the wildly popular amalgam of
all-female headliners, grrrl power and gender equity
fun-in-the-sun. Even in its second year, when the once-stunning
idea of an all-women's concert tour has worn off, it is still the
summer's hottest ticket. When it landed in New York not long ago, I
headed straight for the Jones Beach Theater to fulfill my destiny
as a romantic anthropologist.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't quite the bosky maypole dance/fertility rite/feminist
barn-raising I'd been expecting. More like a self-actualized county
fair with music. Camped at the distant reaches of the Big Baked
Apple, the layout, the vibe and the footwear are all decidedly
suburban.
</P>
<P>
   In line for the alcoholic-beverage shakedown at the door, it
comes to me slowly that I'm virtually the only unaccompanied male.
The one other single guy I see is a shirtless bodybuilder
pretending to wait for someone while he eyeballs the crowd. Guys
like this make us all look bad, I decide. Predatory. He's sporting
Oakley wraparounds and a rattail Montana militia fade. He probably
told his friends that if you want to chat up the dollies, then go
where the dollies go.
</P>
<P>
   A sound strategy: The math of the place is all in our favor. And
I know that in a crowd like this, what plays is the
consumptive-poet look. Since I'm not nearly gaunt enough, I carry a
little notebook, the better to look tortured and potentially
lyrical.
</P>
<P>
   I see Mr. Flex several times later that night. He is always by
himself, the loneliness and want coming off him like cartoon stink
waves. Is this how we all look when left unsupervised? Do I look
like this? In a show of manly revulsion, I make a point of not
sucking in my gut the rest of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice that rock doesn't just have to be crazy men,'' says
Paula, 21, who's from Clifton, N.J. She's the first woman I speak
to. We chat about the music and the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   I'm trying to get a read on the curious nature of man-woman
interaction under such circumstances, but it's as if I'm being
watched. As if our conversation is being assessed by passers-by for
any inappropriate sexual content. My motives feel all too obvious,
so I flourish my notebook as a sign of my good intentions. Still, I
feel oddly carnivorous and ashamed.
</P>
<P>
   While I'm thinking all this, Paula has continued speaking. I
catch the phrase ``Women are on the rise.'' I avert my eyes,
scribble the quote and scuttle off without really thanking her.
This won't be as easy as I thought.
</P>
<P>
   The other men I see, most of them coupled up with wives or
girlfriends, or cruising in large, mixed teen-age groups, seem as
baffled by the whole thing as I am, chastened at being so
completely outnumbered.
</P>
<P>
   While not specifically marketed as such, Lilith is for women _
thousands of them, in packs, in couples, alone _ and they revel in
the relaxed unity of their majority. By sunset most of the men, me
included, will be overstimulated and cranky. We'll have about us
the panicked, wanton look of kids caught in a burning candy store.
</P>
<P>
   I try again, with Nicole. Just some civil conversation, no
notebook. She's down from Westchester County. ``It's cool because
everyone's so comfortable,'' she says. Not me. We are sitting
behind the greasy cart that cooks up the Fried Dough and Bloomin'
Onions. I feel like an escaped convict. ``I came down to see the
bands,'' Nicole says. ``I didn't know they had all these little
booths.'' She and her friend Pam seem really nice. I feel like
Saddam Hussein at a VFW mixer. I excuse myself.
</P>
<P>
   I take my seat in the amphitheater. Missy Elliott is on stage
working ``Supa Dupa Fly.'' She and her backup singers are the only
ones dancing. There is plenty of reflective, supportive swaying
from the audience. I've never thought of hip-hop as being
particularly nurturing, but there's solidarity on the wind tonight.
I slump down, an outlander, while hundreds of adolescent girls from
Scarsdale flick gang signs at Ms. Elliott as if they had tape stuck
to their fingers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Back outside to the bazaar. The slickest booths and tents are
those of the big-name brands: Kodak, Levi's, Tower Records.
Shoehorned between them are the smaller outfits _ the craft
sellers, with their complicated hemp jewelry, vague ceramics and
pastel canvas bags. I pretend to shop. There are plenty of
cosmetics and therapeutics on display, nail polish running a
distant third behind skin care and aromatic oils.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Biore introduced its pore strips at Lilith and shook
the world of rhino-epidermal hygiene to its very foundations. This
year it's giving away self-heating facial masks, whose purpose
eludes me, but they get darned hot when you rub them on. (I tried
it. You could heat a ski lodge with these things.) Isn't that
enough in a too-complicated world?
</P>
<P>
   I give the grrrrl in the booth the big eye, the sideshow barker
smile; she's pretty and I'm alone, after all. Too loudly I say,
``How's business?'' She looks at me with perfect contempt. The
rolling of her eyes is almost audible.
</P>
<P>
   I now feel profoundly single. Maybe Starbucks, with its long
lines of over-mellowed folk-rockers trying to down enough caffeine
to jump-start their dance glands, is the place to exchange some
enlightened neo-postfeminist badinage with a member of the opposite
sex.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks provides the evening's comic relief by setting up two
Magnetic Poetry boards, at which anyone can arrange a few couplets
while waiting for the significant other to sprinkle cinnamon on a
$4 iced latte.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that rotten poetry is indeed portable, the fragments I
see run the gamut from bad to extra-bad to bleeding-from-the-ears
bad. One suggests that I ``recall the caramel dazzle,'' another
that I ruminate on the ``dark water juice of evening.'' The word
``shards'' gets a real workout. Others take a more declarative
approach: ``It is evening'' and ``We were getting coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to concerts where people take drugs and throw
bottles and shout obscenities and get hauled off by the cops?
</P>
<P>
   I lose my stomach for the whole enterprise _ throw in the towel
on my woeful efforts as a would-be sensitive heartbreaker. Maybe
it's the poetry. What is happening to me? How have women lived for
thousands upon thousands of years under this kind of constant, arch
scrutiny? The pressure is too much.
</P>
<P>
   Around this time I discover a place of sepulchral peace. Cool
and silent, ringingly empty: the men's room. The Lourdes of men's
rooms. A porcelain blizzard of tile and light and immaculate
stainless steel. Forty-eight perfect urinals stretch to the
horizon, two dozen on each wall, mirroring one another across a
glacier top of otherworldly white. I am alone here. I am healed. It
is like finding Superman's Fortress of Solitude.
</P>
<P>
   Next door the women wait in lines 20 minutes long. But here all
is quiet and safety. Other men begin to straggle in, haggard and
undone by the day. They pause for a moment, reverent, and sigh,
relief passing across their faces like that of a downed World War
II flier finding sanctuary in the nave of an abandoned church.
</P>
<P>
   More of us limp in, and more, still more, smiling at one
another, nodding to the next and the next as we arrive, knowing
that this is as good as tonight may ever get.
</P>
<P>
   I turn to leave. Mr. Flex arrives, still shirtless, still
single.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' he says, scanning the brilliant room from behind his
sinister wraparounds, ``do you work out?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2900 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWER-SUMMER-2NDTAKE-     07-31 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-SUMMER-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ of its customers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Natural gas utilities can pass on the wholesale costs of gas to
their customers. But except in some instances when interruptible
customers want to continue receiving power, electric utilities can
charge only what state regulators previously have approved.
Utilities and their shareholders have to absorb the extra cost. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not saying we don't want to play by the rules. We're
saying let's make them fair to everybody,'' Philipp said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One possibility, she said, is a circuit breaker, which would
allow wholesale prices to go up only so far before taking a
breather. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even utilities that weren't on the brink of blackouts were
scrambling to meet the demand caused by the high temperatures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Power &AMP; Light, for example, knew that on July 20 it
was going to be hectic because of the hot weather. The demand for
electricity that day set a company record. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the utility's major generating units was down for
repairs, but it was brought back on line to help supply the
afternoon's peak demand. Some smaller units that kick in to meet
peak loads also were put into operation, and the utility was able
to use a new gas turbine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Expecting demand to soar, the utility notified its interruptible
customers that they would be affected. In addition, KCP&AMP;L purchased
200 megawatts from other utilities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the price was $500 a megawatt. That's 12 times this summer's
cheapest price, about $40. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it all worked. The utility could say it had met the
demand from its residential, small-business and other customers who
weren't on interruptible contracts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fortunate,'' said Frank Branca, vice president of
wholesale and transmission services at KCP&AMP;L. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the margin for error has dwindled over the last few years as
demand has caught up with the capacity to generate electricity. In
Missouri and Kansas, the last major power plant to be built was the
Wolf Creek nuclear plant in 1985. KCP&AMP;L and Western are the
owners. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This (summer) is going to focus people on the issue of new
capacity,'' Branca said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L now has total capacity of 3,586 megawatts and can service
a peak hourly demand of 3,139 megawatts, for a reserve of more than
14 percent. Of that total, about 3,000 megawatts can be generated
by KCP&AMP;L; the rest is from contracts for power from other
utilities, which are typically less volatile than the spot market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In part, the wholesale supplies were tight and prices higher
because this summer's hot weather has been so widespread, from the
Rocky Mountains to the Ohio Valley. The situation was aggravated by
a higher-than-normal number of power plants off line because of
repairs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, the region's utilities have not had as much
power to sell to others. In a more-normal summer, a utility in an
area with moderate weather would have plenty of surplus power to
sell to a utility in an area with hot weather. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But other possibilities also have been suggested. Steel Dynamics
Inc., a company in Indiana, is accusing the utility American
Electric Power Corp. of not generating more electricity so it could
manipulate the market and sell some high-priced power on the
wholesale market. American Electric had denied the allegations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason for the shortages and price swings, the role
of wholesale markets will be scrutinized in the coming months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charles Linderman, director of fossil fuels and renewable-energy
programs for the Edison Electric Institute, said utilities had come
to rely too heavily on the wholesale market _ making them subject
to its whims. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The solution, he said, is to build more plants. In some areas of
the country, entrepreneurs already are building plants that
generate power to sell to several utilities. The prices, however,
generally are higher. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing whether capacity should be increased and how to do it
now is sure to get more attention. Utilities across the region are
at least considering how to increase capacity because of the
growing demand and the behavior of the wholesale markets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Western already has plans to bring a plant out of mothballs, a
decision it made before this summer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Larry Holloway, chief of energy operations for the Kansas
Corporation Commission, said, ``Simply put, demand has grown faster
than most people thought possible.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
