A2905 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWER-SUMMER-2TAKES-K     07-31 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-SUMMER-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT OF SUMMER REVEALS PROBLEMS WITH WHOLESALE ELECTRICITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The call came in late June, just as the
summer heat wave began building, to the oil refinery owned by
Farmland Industries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KG&AMP;E, the electric and gas utility, said it would have to cut
the refinery's supply of electricity unless Farmland paid a sharply
higher price. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On July 6, the call came again. And again last week, when high
temperatures caused the demand for electricity to soar. Farmland,
unwilling to shut down the Coffeyville, Kan., plant, agreed to pay
up to 84 times what it normally paid for power. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Farmland asked for an explanation, but the utility never
answered, the farm-products cooperative said. So it filed a
complaint with the Kansas Corporation Commission. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to know why they didn't have enough (electricity),''
said Sherlyn Manson, a Farmland spokeswoman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Western Resources, the owner of KG&AMP;E, said there was no mystery
here. Farmland and many other large customers have interruptible
contracts that permit cutoffs during periods of high demand, and
they are given explanations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The effect on Farmland was unavoidable, said Michel' Philipp, a
spokeswoman for Western. A convergence of events, including the
widespread heat wave and an unusual number of malfunctioning power
plants in the region, put a strain on the capacity of many
utilities and caused wholesale prices to gyrate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We take our responsibilities seriously,'' Philipp said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1998, the living isn't easy for electric
utilities. Utilities throughout the country, including Kansas City
Power &AMP; Light, have been put to the test. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Utilities say they are used to the hectic demands of summer,
when air conditioning pushes demand to the highest of the year. But
this time things are a bit different. Wholesale prices for
electricity, which utilities pay to supplement their own supplies,
have soared as much as 200 times their normal levels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New rules governing the transmission of power over the country's
electric grid and a dwindling cushion of surplus power nationwide
have contributed to the tightening of supplies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, say utility executives, regulators and
analysts, this summer's events will be fodder for debating big
issues that lie ahead for electric utilities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a wake-up call,'' said Bill Washburn, manager of the
electric department for the Missouri Public Service Commission. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So far, large commercial customers such as Farmland have been
most affected. Those large customers have interruptible contracts,
but they benefit the rest of the year by paying cheaper rates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the interruptions can be avoided by paying a
higher rate. Farmland's refinery continued to receive power by
paying a rate roughly tied to the wholesale price, which recently
has been up substantially. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Western Resources, which owns the utility supplying Farmland's
refinery, declined to comment on the specifics of Farmland's
complaint but noted that it had no control over wholesale prices
and that other interruptible customers at other utilities also were
affected. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most other customers, including residential users, haven't been
affected because they don't have interruptible contracts. However,
in Colorado, the state's largest utility had to implement a rolling
blackout for a few hours that included residential customers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere there have been close calls. The Chicago area was
recently on the verge of blackouts. Last week Western's KPL and
KG&AMP;E warned customers that if they didn't reduce their consumption,
rolling blackouts were possible. Customers responded and the
blackouts were avoided. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In its situation, Farmland questions whether it was necessary to
interrupt its service, noting that Western has a generating
capacity of 5,300 megawatts and the recent peak demand of KG&AMP;E and
KPL combined was 4,300 megawatts. A megawatt powers 500 homes for
an hour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Western executives say, however, that the 5,300 figure is
misleading. The utility is required to keep some capacity in
reserve, and that reduces the capacity available to just over 4,600
megawatts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was also a generator off line _ the Lawrence 5 unit _ and
the need to keep its electrical grid from becoming overloaded. The
utility also had long-term commitments to sell about 400 megawatts
of electricity to other utilities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have is an interruptible customer that didn't want to
be interrupted,'' Philipp said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Western, for its part, has pushed federal regulators to
investigate the wholesale market, including the recent price
spikes. New rules to prevent overloading of transmission lines also
made receiving electricity purchased on the wholesale market more
difficult. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wholesale electricity is power that a utility has available to
sell to other utilities. And on the spot market, prices can
fluctuate wildly because wholesale electricity has been deregulated
since the mid-1990s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Western was one of several utilities that pushed federal
regulators to investigate the wholesale market after prices spiked
about $40 to as high as $7,500 a megawatt in late June. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of Western's grievances is that while the wholesale market
is deregulated, the price the utility can charge is controlled for
most of its customers. &QL; 
MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
