tremendous risk in ``Buffalo '66.`` He gives us a despicable hero
and then cajoles us into liking him. It's a neat trick, for Billy
Brown (Gallo) is no ``lovable rogue,'' such as we are used to from
Hollywood. No, he is a thoroughly thuggish ex-con, bristling with
skull-thudding violence and emotional emptiness. He has no
redeeming qualities. But then we meet his parents, and suddenly we
know why and begin to feel sorry for him. By RICHARD NILSEN. Story
moved in the ``E`` category. &QL; 
