A2910 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-31 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUYING ROYALS INVOLVES GIVING TO COMMUNITY, ACCEPTING FINANCIAL
LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Is there an economic justification for paying
the asking price of $75 million for the Kansas City Royals? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but it involves a Catch-22. Given the Royals' inability to
turn a profit in their relatively small market, they probably are a
worthwhile investment only if the franchise can be moved to a more
lucrative locale. The terms of the sale, however, will preclude any
such move for the time being. Meanwhile, the transitional directors
are obligated to ensure that the purchasing partnership includes
adequate local representation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This means the Royals must find prospective buyers willing to
look beyond the economics of the deal and buy the franchise more or
less as a gift to the community. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the community, nobody seems willing to step
forth and fill the civic leadership void created when Royals owner
Ewing M. Kauffman died. Kauffman's legacy was an ingenious plan to
create a bonanza for charities from the proceeds of a Royals sale
that would keep the club in Kansas City. The success of the plan,
though, turned on finding just the right buyer willing to pay a
premium for an enterprise more geared to producing psychic rewards
than attractive investment returns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So far, the quest for the dream buyer has become increasingly
frustrating, which raises the question of whether this is a problem
of local leadership shortcomings, daunting financial challenges or
just plain old bad luck. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The answer is yes, yes and yes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman was unique. Kansas City never again will have a citizen
combining his high level of dedication to the good of his community
with the financial wherewithal and willingness to spend what it
takes to translate his lofty dreams for his community into
reality. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart magnate David Glass might have become a dedicated
keeper of the Kauffman flame as far as the Royals destiny is
concerned. His pockets and his love of baseball are both deep. He
may not be a Kansas Citian, but his devotion to local civic
interests also seemed deep when he came to head the Royals interim
stewardship team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the line, though, Glass apparently thought
better of assuming a permanent role as Kauffman's dream keeper.
It's hard to read a guy's mind at long distance but, given the
downside of the role, who could blame him? After he took the knocks
from the media that come with the territory, he probably decided
the cost to his psyche wasn't worth the benefit of being a
continuing part of major league baseball in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What probably hurt worst was having his motives impugned when
all he was trying to do was keep the faith with a dead friend, do
right by his late friend's community and enjoy being part of a game
he loves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another thing that has hurt the Royals marketability is the
residual bad vibes from the strike that shut down baseball a few
years back. Some who might have been bidders before the strike
probably came to see major league baseball as damaged goods. Now
the basketball lockout has come along to reinforce the notion that
big-league sports is a sinkhole and there are better places to put
your money. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for bad luck, the Lamar Hunt-Western Resources Inc. bid seems
jeopardized by an arcane tax rule that diminishes the Royals'
investment value for its purposes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that if this deal does everything for Kansas
City that Kauffman wanted, it, too, will prove unique. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
