<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2920 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-POLMONEY01-COX     07-31 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-POLMONEY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE REJECTS CHALLENGES TO CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORMS
 &HT;    By MARK SHERMAN AND ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted overwhelmingly Friday to reject the
final attempts to add crippling amendments to the main bipartisan
bill for overhauling federal campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to pass the House,'' predicted Rep. Martin Meehan,
D-Mass., after he and Rep. Chris Shays, R-Conn., kept almost all
Democrats and a healthy chunk of the Republicans united in
opposition to the parliamentary ``land mines'' planted by the House
Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Shays said the sponsors accepted some ``harmless'' amendments,
but managed to avoid all 15 of the GOP amendments, including five
defeated Friday, that ``would have torn off limbs (or) blown us
apart.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill would close loopholes under which parties
have been able to accept ``soft money'' from people giving more
than the legal contribution limits or from the treasuries of unions
or corporations. It would also apply the existing disclosure and
financial rules for campaign ads to any TV or radio ads that
mention a federal candidate in the weeks leading up to an election.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the Shays-Meehan itself will be be held Monday
evening, said Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas. Votes on
substitute bills, and possibly on amendments to those substitutes,
are also possible. The House plans to send the bill with the most
votes to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Armey repeated his promise that the leadership would end months
of foot-dragging and let the House send the bill to the Senate
before members leave for their month-long summer vacation, probably
Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``It weighs heavy on my heart,'' Armey said. ``I don't know how,
but we will have completed this by the time we leave town on
Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors called the five amendments that were defeated Friday
``poison pills,'' because each of them would have made the bill
unacceptable to some of its existing supporters.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a 218-vote majority to amend a bill in the 435-member
House. But Speaker Newt Gingrich of Georgia and other GOP leaders
were unable to round up more than 200 votes for any of the 15
bill-scuttling amendments offered during weeks of sporadic debate.
</P>
<P>
   One defeated Friday was an effort by Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., to
prohibit election officials from publishing voting materials in
languages other than English. With 74 Republicans joining 186
Democrats and one independent in voting against it, Barr's plan
obtained only 142 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Another proposal, defeated 253-160 after it was offered by Rep.
Clay Shaw, R-Fla., would have required congressional candidates to
raise at least half their campaign funds within their own state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I overheard a couple of (opponents) say, 'We failed to put
enough weight on this ship to sink it,' `` chuckled Rep. Sander
Levin, D-Mich., who supports the bipartisan bill.
</P>
<P>
   However, supporters are keeping their eyes peeled for more of
the ``savvy maneuvers'' already used by GOP leaders to delay action
on a bill originally scheduled for consideration in March, said
Rep. Zach Wamp, R-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have grown very wary though this process,'' Wamp said.
</P>
<P>
   If any bill does emerge from the House next week, it would then
face resistance in the Senate, where GOP filibusters have blocked
action on similar legislation twice during the past year.
</P>
<P>
   But Levin, who has a brother in the Senate, said he expects
sympathetic senators to find a way to force consideration of the
measure after the Senate reconvenes in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll see it brought up and brought up and brought
up,'' Levin said. ``I think it will have a fighting chance.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
