<HEADER>
A2923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROUNDABOUT-THEATER-64     07-31 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROUNDABOUT-THEATER-640(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLE IS NOTHING NEW TO THE ROUNDABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sometimes a dose of neurotic energy and a
manic-depressive business history can have their blessings.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the case at the Roundabout Theater, where the
latest turn of the roller coaster _ going from Broadway's hottest
theater to Broadway's most beleaguered in the space of two weeks _
has a certain familiar, dark logic.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Roundabout had Broadway's most-desired ticket
in ``Cabaret,'' record overall sales and the appearance of a
theater juggernaut. Since then the construction accident in Times
Square has shut down ``Cabaret'' indefinitely and the Roundabout's
two other shows for a week, and the theater is one target of a
sweeping investigation of ticket scalping in the entertainment
business.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Haimes, the company's artistic director, bustles about the
Roundabout's Criterion Theater these days with a slightly rattled
``what next?'' look. But he said that everything in his nature and
the company's history taught him not to expect the empyrean moments
to last, so this feels more like one more turn of the wheel than a
startling fall from comfortably lofty heights.
</P>
<P>
   Since its beginnings in 1966 in the renovated basement of a
supermarket on West 26th Street, the theater has declared
bankruptcy (in 1978), voted to close (in 1983), moved twice and in
the process grown to become the United States' second-biggest
nonprofit theater, after Lincoln Center. So shifts of fate are
nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``First by dint of my own personality and my own neurosis, and
second by dint of having been in this business long enough to go
through ups and downs and ups and downs, I never felt I was on top
of the world,'' said Haimes, who joined the company in 1983, only
to see the theater run out of money and face closure two weeks
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying it's healthy or good, but I always assume that
disaster is around the corner. I just didn't think a building would
fall down on top of `Cabaret.' That's a level of disaster that's
new. That's a new gold standard for my half-empty-vs.-half-full
neurosis.''
</P>
<P>
   At the top of Haimes' agenda is figuring out what, if anything,
to do about ``Cabaret,'' the critical and box office blockbuster,
whose Kit Kat Klub still sits empty on the closed-off part of 43rd
Street beneath the construction accident at the Conde Naste
Building. No start-up date has been set, but he said his best guess
was that the theater might reopen in about two weeks. Customers
with tickets for performances while the show was closed can get
refunds or exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the anxiety level is the investigation by the New York
attorney general's office of ticket scalping and ``ice,'' the
practice of box offices' overcharging ticket brokers for desirable
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   An article in Variety on Monday said ``The Roundabout'' was one
target of the investigation. Officials with the attorney general's
office say the Roundabout is one of more than a dozen major venues
asked to turn over information, and say the investigation covers
ticket and box-office practices at virtually all of the biggest
entertainment names in New York.
</P>
<P>
   David Corvette, a spokesman for the attorney general's office,
said the investigation focused only on box offices, not on
productions or theaters over all. Haimes said he knew of no
improper practices at the Roundabout and suspected that
``Cabaret's'' status as the most desirable ticket in town made it
the obvious magnet for any investigation of ticket scalping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time your tickets are selling for above the ticket prices
by anyone, it's horrible,'' he said. ``I know the Roundabout is
only charging the ticket price, but people on the outside don't
necessarily know it. I can't help but feel there is a little bit of
kicking us while we're down, but then I'm probably in the
feeling-sorry-for-myself mode.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Cabaret'' is losing about $280,000 in box-office receipts each
week and is still paying most of the $200,000-a-week costs of
mounting Cabaret. Since the accident on July 21, Haimes and the
show's artistic leaders have been scrambling to find an alternative
site. They are still looking. But given how much it would cost and
how long it would take to replicate the show's unique
configuration, which calls for building a seedy Berlin nightclub
and a stage, Haimes is not optimistic. Because of the costs, any
move would have to be permanent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still investigating any alternative we can think of,''
he said. ``But we are not going to move it unless we feel we can
replicate the artistic experience, and that's very hard to do. It's
not like taking over a Broadway theater and taking out the first
three rows, so our options are pretty limited.''
</P>
<P>
   One site that has been mentioned is the old Studio 54 location,
but it is not air-conditioned and the costs of renovating it may be
prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   The other two shows, ``Side Man'' and ``You Never Can Tell,''
reopened after a few days. But the total financial loss will be
considerable. Haimes said that because the accident was so unusual,
it is not clear whether it will be covered by insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Even if insurance and damages from the developer or construction
company eventually compensate for much of the loss, for now the
financial costs are substantial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will probably turn a profitable year into a not-for-profit
one,'' Haimes said in his office with its klieg lights hanging
overhead. ``If you're a commercial company and something, God
forbid, doesn't work out, you can close the company and move onto
something else. In a not-for profit like ours, when you have
problems you live with them forever. So if we lose $700,000,
$800,000, $900,000, that's a lot of money for us. Especially when
it happens to `Cabaret,' which is the kind of hit an institution
like ours has once in a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout's annual operating budget is $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   But for all his gloom, the Roundabout is still seeing record
ticket sales and subscriptions _ 5,000 above its pace last year _
and is ready to begin rehearsing two new productions, ``Little Me''
with Martin Short, and Beth Henley's ``Impossible Marriage'' with
Holly Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   And for some cast members the delay isn't all bad.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Jason Leigh, who is making her Broadway debut replacing
Tony-award-winning Natasha Richardson, said she felt terrible about
the disruption. But the delay has given her more time to rehearse
than the two-and-a-half weeks she had expected and more free time
to explore New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cast really misses doing the show,'' said Ms. Leigh, who
is from Los Angeles, ``but it's kind of a luxury for me to have
more time to rehearse and get up to speed. And I'm really enjoying
New York. I've fallen in love with the subways. They seem so fast
and cool and anonymous. Everyone tells me this is a love affair
that will quickly pass, but for now I'm kind of enthralled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
