<SLUG> BC-STRATUS-ASCEND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRATUS, ASCEND SAID TO BE IN MERGER TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stratus Computer Inc. of Marlborough, Mass. is negotiating to be
acquired by California-based Ascend Communications Inc. for between
$800 million and $1 billion, according to a source familiar with
the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   While the talks could still break off over the weekend, a deal
is expected to be announced as early as Monday, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation that the two companies were discussing a buyout has
been rampant since mid-week, fueling a 30 percent jump in Stratus
stock. The company makes failure-proof computer systems that run
non-stop for such customers as telephone carriers, banks, and
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, however, Wall Street seemed to have soured on the
deal. Investors dumped shares of Ascend, which makes networking
equipment for phone companies and Internet service providers, amid
concern that buying Stratus was a bad idea _ both financially and
strategically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it makes economic sense for Ascend to buy
Stratus,'' Steven Frenkel, an analyst at investment banking firm
Paragon Capital, told CNet, an Internet news service. ``It is like
buying a farm to get a haystack.''
</P>
<P>
   Ascend's stock fell 7 1/32 _ a 14 percent slide _ to 44 15/32.
More than 25.2 million shares were traded, making it the most
active stock in US markets. Stratus shares, meanwhile, rose 7/8 to
28 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said investors are worried that Stratus,
which has struggled lately, will drag down Ascend just as the
Alameda, Calif.-based company is recovering from its last
acquisition: the $3.7 billion buyout of Westford-based Cascade
Communications in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling through most of last year, Ascend has beaten
Wall Street's earnings estimates for three quarters in a row,
fueled by strong sales of its powerful switching equipment, which
allows telecommunications companies to move data traffic over phone
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Stratus, meanwhile, lost $10 million in the most recent quarter
and saw its sales fall 20 percent. Last week, the company said it
would cut 350 jobs _ 15 percent of its work &UR;  &LR; force _ and take a $20
million charge against earnings because of slackening demand in
Asia that shows no signs of improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Ascend may be attracted to Stratus because of its
capabilities in Signaling System 7, or SS7 _ an industry-standard
technology that is vital to allowing telephone carriers to offer
value-added services like caller ID, call-waiting, or
call-forwarding over data networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``With SS7 from Stratus, Ascend's data switching products become
more attractive to carriers,'' said Maribel Lopez,
telecommunications analyst at Cambridge-based Forrester Research.
``Ascend can start to offer voice and data switching in a single
box.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted that Cisco Systems Inc., the biggest data networking
firm, recently acquired a company called Lightspeed &UR;  &LR; International
Inc. of Sterling, Va., for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   Stratus's SS7 expertise has been hotly purused by Ascend rivals.
In late March, Ascend rival Bay Networks Inc. of Santa Clara signed
a technology agreement with Stratus to jointly develop new products
based on Stratus's SS7 equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Cristinziano, an analyst with Gerard Klauer Mattison
in New York, noted that SS7 applications are a small part of
Stratus' business. Most of its revenues come from selling powerful
computer servers _ a business that is far afield from Ascend's
networking expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Ascend would be better off forming a strategic alliance with
Stratus, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real value is the services themselves, not the hardware
underlying it,'' he said. ``You can get some of these strategic
benefits without buying the whole company.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Matthew Barzowskas of First Albany Corp. in Boston,
agreed. ``There's a lot of stratus that Ascend doesn't need.''
</P>
<P>
   There's another reason that analysts frown on a deal between
Ascend and Stratus.
</P>
<P>
   Many on Wall Street have speculated that Ascend would make a
good acquisition target itself _ most likly, by Lucent Technologies
Inc. Lucent is the former equipment arm of AT&AMP;T Corp., which also
recently spun off NCR Corp., its computer division.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ascend would blow $800 million on Stratus, it makes them
less attractive,'' said Cristinziano. ``Lucent already got rid of
NCR. Why would they another computer company?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ronald Rosenberg of the Globe staff contribted to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
