<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE INITIATES DRIVE TO PREVENT MEDICAL ERRORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Mass. _ Massachusetts health officials unveiled
Friday what they say is America's most ambitious drive to prevent
medical errors, a move made partly in response to the fact that
several of America's highest-profile and most tragic recent medical
errors occurred at Massachusetts hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition of state officials, hospital executives, doctors
and other health leaders who announced their existence and mission
Friday actually has been meeting privately for more than a year.
But given the sensitivity of their misson, members said they wanted
to ensure they could work together before going public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't as though we were trying to keep the media away,''
Dr. John Noble, who helped get the group going and chairs it,
explained at a briefing for three reporters at the headquarters of
the Massachusetts Hospital Association. ``We felt we had to get our
act together before we'd have anything to share . . . We're now at
a point where we think we can start to play a kind of ball.''
</P>
<P>
   And while coalition members acknowledged that the credibility of
health care providers and hospitals has been damaged by recent
mishaps here, they insisted their intent is to eliminate errors
rather than polish images. ``If someone at this table honestly
thought this was about spin control we'd have been out of here in
two seconds,'' said Dr. Randolph Peto, head of quality improvement
at a subsidiary of the Massachusetts Medical Society.
</P>
<P>
   Errors have always been a worry at health facilities here and
elsewhere, but the problem came into intense focus three years ago
when Betsy A. Lehman, a Boston Globe health columnist being treated
at the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, was killed by a massive
overdose of a powerful anticancer drug.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Quincy Hospital was under the spotlight after
three elderly surgical patients died and another had the wrong
kidney removed; last year the state uncovered serious deficiencies
at Newton-Wellesley Hospital surrounding several maternal deaths,
and recently complaints of negligence have been leveled against
Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   While all those incidents were distinct, so many happening
within such a short time convinced state officials that not enough
was being done to root out errors, said Nancy Ridley, the assistant
commissioner of public health who oversees investigations of
troubles like those.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Ridley added, several patterns became clear: While
human errors were involved, the underlying problems were with
quality-control systems. While each hospital fashioned its own
solutions, those solutions weren't applied as fast as they could
have been at other hospitals. And while studies have documented
easy-to-apply ways of preventing medical errors, there's no system
for ensuring everyone knows about and institutes such ``best
practice'' approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Noble shared those frustrations in his role as a commissoner of
the Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations,
which inspects hospitals nationwide. So 18 months ago he approached
Bay State officials about assembling health experts here to come up
with solutions, and 15 months ago a letter was sent to every
hospital inviting it to join.
</P>
<P>
   The group's first target is medication-related errors of the
kind that killed Lehman. One approach will be to highlight the fact
that such errors most often involve 10 common drugs. Coalition
members also will zero in on the ease with which errors arise in
prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Before any statewide changes are recommended, however, a
consensus will have to be reached among hospital executives,
doctors, nurses and other hands-on providers who will review the
proposals. ``If we're going to have interventions that really work
they've got to come from groups that are representative of
hospitals and other health care organizations,'' said Noble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
