<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-BIAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US PROBES RACE BIAS WITHIN MASSACHUSETTS POLICE DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Springfield, Mass. police department, stung by allegations
of racism and reeling from a $2 million jury verdict two months ago
to the family of an unarmed black motorist shot to death by a white
police officer, is cooperating with federal authorities
investigating racism in the department.
</P>
<P>
   A US Justice Department spokesman in Washington Friday confirmed
that the department is conducting an ``administrative
investigation'' into alleged racial discrimination by police
officers and will send civil rights investigators to the city for
two days early this month.
</P>
<P>
   The probe, sparked by complaints from the city's minority
residents, has been ongoing for at least two years, but many view
it with more urgency in the wake of the June verdict against the
city and patrolman Donald Brown.
</P>
<P>
   After less than seven hours of deliberation, a jury in US
District Court in Springfield found that Brown had used excessive
force when he shot and killed 20-year-old Benjamin Schoolfield in
1994. The jury also found that the city was negligent in providing
inadequate training to officers.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict was widely viewed as vindication in a black
community that has long complained about the treatment blacks
receive at the hands of white police officers.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1996, police officer Joseph Bradley was fired after
phoning a black minister and mocking the burning of black churches
in the South. That same month police allegedly used Mace to arrest
a 78-year-old black woman and in October of that year allegations
of police brutality were leveled when local and state police
tangled with hundreds of minority teenagers outside a local
athletic club.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict in the Schoolfield case came two years after federal
authorities refused to bring criminal charges against Springfield
officers in Schoolfield's death. US Attorney Donald K. Stern closed
the federal inquiry in April 1996, saying investigators found
insufficient evidence of any civil rights violations. A Hampden
County grand jury earlier had found that Schoolfield was shot
accidentally as Brown approached Schoolfield's van with his gun
drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that he ran up to the van, which falsely had been
reported stolen, at a traffic light. He said he accidentally broke
the side window with the gun and as he tried to dislodge his arm
the van started rolling backwards. The gun fired, he said, as he
tried to free his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Justice Department spokesman Christine DiBartolo
confirmed that the inquiry was ongoing but refused to say who
requested it or when it might be concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Under such an investigation, which does not involve the courts,
the Justice Department tries to work cooperatively with the party
under investigation. The probe, DiBartolo said, will determine
whether the Springfield police department discriminated on the
basis of race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working very cooperatively with the police department,''
she said. ``We hope to come to a voluntary resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Springfield Mayor Michael J. Albano said he first became aware
of the investigation before he became mayor in January 1996. ``Even
before I took office they were knocking on my door,'' he said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Albano said he's pleased with the progress the police department
has made since then, including the appointment of a new police
chief, Paula Meara, the first woman to head a big city police
department in New England, a new police commission and enhanced
sensitivity training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved the internal investigation unit outside the police
department,'' added Albano. ``We've done a number of things on our
own that will satisfy their concerns. I'm very comfortable with the
progress the city has made in the last two years, particularly in
the minority community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
