<SLUG> BC-MORALES-HOUSE-$ADV-2-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAME DUCK MORALES BUYS $775,000 HOUSE IN SCENIC AUSTIN HILLS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 2) 
 
By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Not many state employees _ not even agency heads
_ live in $800,000 houses. But Attorney General Dan Morales is
already sampling the uppercrust lifestyle he expects as an
investment banker after he leaves office in January.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the recent controversy over lawyer fees in the
tobacco case, Morales quietly purchased and moved his new family
into a 5,059-square-foot house in the scenic hills west of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The property carries an $835,000 appraisal and a $615,000
mortgage, way off the normal lending charts for someone with a
$92,217 state salary. But Morales, who arranged financing through
the previous owner, is betting on much higher earnings when he
enters the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Property records show Morales purchased the house, located in a
gated neighborhood above Lake Austin, in March for $775,000 from
Tanya Hill of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   His spokesman Ron Dusek said the attorney general spent $150,000
he had made from the sale of a previous home last year on the down
payment. He said Morales is paying Hill, who holds the $615,000
note on the property, $4,300 a month, based on an interest rate of
7 1/2 percent for a 30-year loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, on his salary, he cannot get a (conventional) loan
for that amount,'' Dusek said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to sit down after he leaves office and
renegotiate the terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Dusek said there were no co-signers on the note other than
Morales' wife, Christine. He said the sale was arranged through a
real estate agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``She (Hill) had no idea who he (Morales) was,'' said Dusek.
</P>
<P>
   Property records indicate Hill had paid $775,000 cash for the
house in June 1997. Dusek said she never lived there.
</P>
<P>
   The only source of income Morales listed on his most recent
public financial disclosure statement, which covers 1997, was his
state salary.
</P>
<P>
   He did not report income from any investments, not even interest
on bank accounts. State officeholders are supposed to report any
interest income of more than $500 a year, according to the Texas
Ethics Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Dusek said Morales held the $150,000 he made from the February
1997 sale of a house on the Pedernales River outside Austin in a
noninterest bearing bank account.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't know how soon he was going to be using it,'' the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, 42, shocked the Texas political world last December
when he announced he would not seek re-election to a third term as
the state's top lawyer. He said he wanted to spend more time with
his wife, whom he married last year, and her two children.
</P>
<P>
   He has said he plans to enter the financial investment business
after he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of Morales' public career occurred this year when
he negotiated a $17.3 billion settlement of a lawsuit against the
tobacco industry over public health care costs associated with
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   He became embroiled in a nasty political fight with Gov. George
W. Bush and seven state legislators over $2.3 billion in legal fees
that a federal judge awarded a group of private lawyers Morales
retained to represent the state in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general and his detractors finally agreed to
separate the controversy over lawyers' payments from the body of
the settlement, which allowed the judge to give final approval to
the tobacco deal last month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
