<HEADER>
A2963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-THOMSON-NYT     07-31 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-THOMSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE'S THOMSON MULTIMEDIA COMPLETES A REMARKABLE TURNAROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mexico, France, Ind.)  (js) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ For years, Thomson Multimedia was known mostly for two
things: color television sets and losses.
</P>
<P>
   With Microsoft and the DirecTV unit of Hughes Electronics, which
is part of General Motors; NEC of Japan; and Alcatel SA of France
lining up to buy shares in Thomson, the French government is
betting this will end.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement announced on Thursday, each of the four
partners will be allowed to buy 7.5 percent of Thomson Multimedia.
The amount the four will pay for their shares will not be set
before the fall. With this deal, Thomson Multimedia gets commercial
connections and partners to help push it into new fields of digital
television.
</P>
<P>
   The deal represents a remarkable turnaround for Thomson
Multimedia. For years, French industrial policy had it that if
Europe surrendered the consumer electronics business to Japan
without a struggle, it risked not only the loss of engineering and
factory jobs, but ultimately important industries like
semiconductors, too.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, when Paris nationalized France's leading consumer
electronics group, Thomson Multimedia, it named as chairman a tough
former paratrooper, Alain Gomez, and ordered him to stop the
Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, a cigar-puffing manager who drove motorcycles to work,
began by acquiring television manufacturers. He bought Telefunken
of Germany, and the Ferguson television division of Thorn EMI of
Britain and, in 1987, Thomson Multimedia acquired the consumer
electronics businesses of General Electric Co. and its RCA
subsidiary, which make RCA, GE and Proscan televisions.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Thomson Multimedia grew into the world's
fourth-biggest consumer electronics group, after Matsushita and
Sony of Japan and Royal Philips Electronics of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Though few Americans heard of the quiet French giant, by the
mid-1990s Thomson Multimedia and its American arm, Thomson Consumer
Electronics Inc., had become a global power. In the United States,
the world's biggest consumer electronics market, it led the
television market, with a 25 percent share. Indeed, by 1997, North
America generated two-thirds of Thomson Multimedia's $6.3 billion
of revenue. (In Europe, with a 10 percent share, the company was
No. 3, after Philips and Sony.)
</P>
<P>
   But size did not bring profitability. The spending spree piled
up debt; Thomson Multimedia's manufacturing base was outmoded, and
poor logistics tied up cash in unmoved stock. Losses mounted.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1990s, successive French governments were selling
nationalized assets. Debating the company's future in Parliament in
1996, conservative prime minister Alain Juppe complained that $2.55
billion of debt made Thomson Multimedia, ``under the circumstances,
worth nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   A plan to sell Thomson SA, the nationalized holding company that
groups Thomson Multimedia with the military electronics company,
Thomson CSF, to the French Groupe Lagardere, was reversed after
Lagardere sought to dump Thomson Multimedia, by selling it for 1
French franc, or about 16 cents, to Daewoo of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a group of French companies led by the electronics
group Alcatel Alsthom took control of Thomson CSF, and Paris
ordered an overhaul of Thomson Multimedia. In the United States,
big factories like one for television sets in Bloomington, Ind.,
the world's largest, were shut, and production shifted to a new
$150 million plant in Juarez, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   To wipe out debt, Juppe's successor, Socialist Lionel Jospin,
poured $2 billion into Thomson in 1997, agreeing in return to
European Union demands that Thomson Multimedia limit its European
market share and seek industrial partners.
</P>
<P>
   To find them, the government named as chairman Thierry Breton,
an owlish 43-year-old former computer science professor who had
earlier turned around the unprofitable state-owned computer
company, Groupe Bull, in which Paris sold shares to IBM, Motorola
and NEC, in exchange for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financially, Thomson has been improving rapidly, and the
fundamentals of the company are better than has been said,'' said
Elie Cohen, director of research at the National Center for
Scientific Research in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   For Microsoft, Thomson becomes an important manufacturing and
distributing ally in digital television, but also in its struggle
against Sun Microsystems over a programming language for what is
called distributed computing, which promises to endow consumer
appliances, from televisions and telephones to kitchen appliances
and cars, with intelligence by connecting them to a computer
network.
</P>
<P>
   Alcatel, moreover, is among the cellular telephone companies
that deploy the kinds of networks that are at the heart of this
evolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The partners are interested in Thomson for the markets RCA
provides,'' Cohen said. ``It is important for them to have Thomson
at their side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
