<HEADLINE>
`LINC'S': BAD MEN, FEISTY WOMEN AT THE LOCAL BAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lb) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Linc's,'' a new Showtime comedy series, all the men are bad
and all the women are good. Linc himself (Steven Williams), a
50-ish Washington bar owner, is a narrow-minded Republican who,
upon learning that his daughter has had a lesbian relationship,
asks a priest, ``How well do these exorcisms work?''
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie (Georg Stanford Brown) is an evil lobbyist who wants
only the best for the tobacco industry. Harlan (Joe Inscoe) is a
Southern white racist who keeps telling his young black waitress
about ``our old cook Bessie.''
</P>
<P>
   And Winston (Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje) is a cabdriver with an
inflated notion of his appeal to women. In the first episode, one
black man tells another to go back to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, CeCe (Golden Brooks) is just a hard-working
waitress and single mom; Eartha (Daphne Maxwell-Reid) is just a
hard-working prostitute, and Eleanor (Pam Grier, sexy and strong as
ever) is the head of something called the National Organization for
Children and works as a lobbyist only to do good, like pushing
through a free-school-lunch bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linc's,'' which has its premiere Saturday, has such a fine
pedigree _ created by Tim Reid, who did ``Frank's Place,'' and
Susan Fales-Hill, who worked on ``The Cosby Show'' _ that it's
particularly embarrassing to see its first episode include condom
jokes and the gratuitous use of vulgarities. Maybe it's impossible
for a show set in a bar not to have a hooker, but does everyone
have to refer to her work in such blunt terms?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the dialogue is obvious as well. ``Women are not fit
for combat; they're too weak,'' Johnnie tells Rosalee (Tisha
Campbell), Linc's 23-year-old daughter, who is an Army lieutenant.
And early in the first episode, a customer asks Linc, ``When are
you two going to stop doing the Texas two-step _ and tango?'' He is
referring to Linc and Evelyn, who is, unfortunately, a married
woman (but her husband cheats, so who could blame her?).
</P>
<P>
   The show is intelligent and very political, with jokes about
subjects from Linda Tripp to the coming-out episode of ``Ellen.''
Maybe if the characters start showing a little complexity and
become less fixated on sex, ``Linc's'' will have a chance to be as
good as its premise.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LINC'S'
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Saturday on Showtime
</P>
<P>
   Tim Reid and Susan Fales-Hill, creators and executive producers;
Adriana Trigiani, supervising producer; Charles Randolph-Wright,
executive story editor; Debbie Allen, director of the premiere
episode of ``Linc's.''
</P>
<P>
   With: Pam Grier (Eleanor), Steven Williams (Russell A. Lincoln),
Georg Stanford Brown (Johnnie), Tisha Campbell (Rosalee), Joe
Inscoe (Harlan), Golden Brooks (CeCe), Daphne Maxwell-Reid (Eartha)
and Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje (Winston).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
