</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AWAKENING-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RUDE AWAKENING': NOT AS CLEVER AS IT THINKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lb) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the opening credits of ``Rude Awakening,'' the beautiful
Billie Frank (Sherilyn Fenn) wakes up in her big brass bed,
handcuffed to the headboard, with no memory of how she got there.
In the first episode of this new half-hour sitcom, Billie throws up
the morning after a drunken one-night stand, goes to work
(apparently as a B-film producer's receptionist), gets in trouble
for sleeping with a client, crashes her car into a fire hydrant and
is ordered by the court to join Addictions Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of thing probably happened to Sam Malone and Murphy
Brown all the time before they quit drinking, but we never saw it
on ``Cheers'' or Murphy's series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rude Awakening'' thinks it's cleverer than it really is and
could use an injection of real wit, but the cast is appealing. Lynn
Redgrave is charmingly haughty as Billie's mother, who missed her
daughter's pre-12-step intervention because she was having a bikini
wax.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Penner is likable as Dave, the handsome coffee shop
owner and fellow AA member who turns down Billie's almost immediate
offer of sex because under the circumstances it wouldn't be right.
(Now there's a novel reason for keeping the sexual tension in a
series going.)
</P>
<P>
   The self-consciously wacky characters also include a lesbian
recovering heroin addict and alcoholic (Rain Pryor, daughter of
Richard) and a born-again-Christian sister-in-law (Corinne Bohrer).
</P>
<P>
   Now if only some screenwriter will make them smart. Being able
to use four-letter words because it's cable doesn't make a
character sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `RUDE AWAKENING'
</P>
<P>
   11 p.m. ET Saturday on Showtime
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
