<SLUG> BC-NETSCAPE-WEB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETSCAPE PUTS CLAMP ON EMPLOYEES' WEB SITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Netscape Communications Corp. temporarily shut down Web sites
Friday belonging to dozens of its employees, after one of them
posted a parody that linked Apple Computer Inc. with several
notorious mass murderers.
</P>
<P>
   The site made fun of Apple's well-known ``Think Different'' ad
campaign, which features photos of famous artists, scholars and
human rights activists. The parody site attached the Apple logo and
slogan to photos of serial killers like John Wayne Gacy and
Theodore Bundy, as well as Cambodian dictator Pol Pot, who murdered
as many as a million of his countrymen during the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape encourages its employees to create their own Web pages,
which are hosted on Netscape's own computers. The company has a
policy forbidding the publication of ``derogatory or demeaning
language or pictures'' on these pages.
</P>
<P>
   A Web site devoted to users of Apple's Macintosh computers
published news of the offensive Web site Friday. But officials at
Netscape were unaware of it until they were contacted by The Boston
Globe. Within minutes, Netscape shut down all its employee Web
pages pending an investigation of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the majority of the sites don't contain
anything like this,'' said Margie Mader, director of human
resources. ``But we've got to be sure.'' Mader said that the
company would contact the employee whose page contained the
offensive materials, but declined to say what action might be
taken.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
