</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-RUSSIA-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM UNIT ADMITS ILLEGAL SALE OF COMPUTERS TO RUSSIAN NUCLEAR LAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An IBM subsidiary pleaded guilty Friday to
exporting illegally 17 advanced computers to a Russian nuclear
weapons laboratory and agreed to pay an $8.5 million fine, in what
is believed to be the first criminal conviction against the
corporate giant.
</P>
<P>
   Russia secretly bought the computers in late 1996 and early 1997
in the mistaken belief that Washington would approve the purchase
after Moscow signed a total ban on nuclear tests, long advocated by
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The computers can improve Russia's ability to simulate nuclear
weapons testing. The sale of any computer to a Russian nuclear
weapons facility requires federal approval, which IBM never
received.
</P>
<P>
   After an 18-month investigation, IBM's Moscow-based subsidiary,
IBM East Europe/Asia Ltd., pleaded guilty to 17 felony violations
of the export control laws in U.S. District Court in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   There was no evidence that IBM's American executives were aware
of the illegal shipments, which involved a series of Russian
middleman and circuitous shipping arrangements in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``IBM acted in a highly responsible manner'' by cooperating with
the government, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Eric Dubelier, who
prosecuted the case.
</P>
<P>
   IBM spokesman Rob Wilson said: ``We regret the involvement of
our Russian subsidiary in this case. IBM will not tolerate any
violation of its standards of business conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, the Clinton administration has
unsuccessfully tried to persuade Russia to return the computers or
move them to a civilian location, administration officials said.
Those efforts included a request by Vice President Al Gore when he
was in Moscow recently.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the Moscow-based subsidiary entered the plea,
Dubelier complained that the Russians ``have refused to assist us
in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the United States does not know the location of the most
powerful computer but believed the other 16 are at a facility in
Arzamas-16, a closed city where the Soviet Union designed its
hydrogen bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the case illustrates the difficulties of adhering
to U.S. legal standards in markets like Russia, where the full rule
of law has yet to be established. IBM is believed to have no
previous criminal record, according to Mark Menefee, the Commerce
Department's top export investigator.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The IBM case, which was investigated by the Commerce Department
and the Customs Service, ``confirms that the export control system
of the United States works,'' Menefee said.
</P>
<P>
   But if a Russian official had not boasted that he had acquired
some advanced American computers from Silicon Graphics and IBM, the
United States might never have found out about the unlawfully
shipped computers.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1997, the head of Russia's Ministry of Atomic Energy,
which oversees nuclear weapon laboratories, told reporters of the
purchase, and federal investigators began an inquiry into why none
of the Russian computer sales had been licensed.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Graphics has denied any wrongdoing. Its dealings with
Russia are the subject of a separate federal investigation in
California which, investigators said, has found less incriminating
evidence than the IBM inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Congress also reacted to the Russian admission, out of concern
that President Clinton had gone too far in 1996 when he relaxed
controls over the export of some advanced computers. Despite
opposition from the White House and lobbying by IBM's senior
executives, Congress replaced the tighter controls over some
computer exports last year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when U.S. negotiators were pressing skeptical Russian
officials to join a nuclear test ban, officials in Moscow said they
were enticed with hints that they could later buy high performance
computers from the United States. U.S. officials deny any such
offer.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of testing, computer simulations help determine
if nuclear weapons work as designed.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's desire to obtain such computers was well known inside
IBM's Moscow office. The office sales manager was a Russian
national who previously worked at a government physics institute.
</P>
<P>
   And selling computers to Arzamas-16 was seen as a stepping stone
to the lucrative Russian market.
</P>
<P>
   ``IBM was very pushy,'' said Yevgeny Shablygin, head of the
Moscow computer dealer that arranged the purchase of 16 IBM
computers. ``They thought Arzamas could be like Los Alamos, a very
prestigious customer. That's what this job was all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of IBM's Moscow subsidiary knew that Arzamas-16 was
responsible for nuclear weapons research before they installed 16
computers there in November 1996, according to the ``factual
proffer'' submitted Friday by Dubelier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that one of America's leading corporations has been
undermining national security because it was willing to take risks
in entering the Russian market,'' said Gary Milhollin, director of
the Wisconsin Project on Nuclear Arms Control.
</P>
<P>
   The guilty plea by the Moscow-based subsidiary was entered by
Bruce Baird, a lawyer with the Washington firm of Covington &AMP;
Burling. U.S. District Court Judge Norma Holloway Johnson accepted
the 17-count criminal information and the fine of $8.5 million, the
maximum available under the export control laws.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Russian company will separately pay a civil
fine of $171,000 levied by the Commerce Department. The company
also agreed to accept Commerce Department restrictions on some of
its computer sales in Russia for the next two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
