<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran to expand presence at Hartsfield
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- AirTran will base more of its pilots and flight
attendants in Atlanta as part of a plan to expand service from
Hartsfield International Airport this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier announced this week it is adding service to some
cities and cutting back service to others. By October, it will have
more than 260 daily flights between Atlanta and 30 cities. The
company now has 120 daily departures from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The changes will allow AirTran to set up a more traditional hub
system at Hartsfield and operate more like larger competitors.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the changes, AirTran is eliminating most of its 14
nonstop flights to Atlanta from Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier, which was created by the merger of AirTran Airways
and Atlanta-based ValuJet, also will restart flights next month to
Miami. It will be the first time AirTran has flown directly to
Miami from Atlanta since the 1996 crash of Flight 592 that killed
all 110 aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Flights also will begin from Atlanta to Quad Cities/Moline,
Ill., in September, and to Newark, N.J., in October. AirTran said
it is also adding service to Buffalo, N.Y., Washington's Dulles
airport and Orlando. But the carrier will discontinue flights to
Allentown, Pa.; West Palm Beach, Fla.; Des Moines, Iowa; and Islip
and Syracuse, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran is the second-largest carrier serving Atlanta after
Delta Air Lines, which provides 80 percent of the flights. Last
month, Delta announced expanded service from Orlando through its
Delta Express flights, which do not come to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran said 165 pilots and flight attendants, mainly in
Orlando, will join 125 others already based in Atlanta. Spokeswoman
Cara Maruskin said the carrier will hire additional workers,
especially flight attendants, in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The airline will use its existing 18 gates at Hartsfield to
accommodate the expanded service. ``We'd like more and have made a
formal request for more gates,'' Maruskin said.
</P>
<P>
   She said funneling all its flights through Atlanta will allow
AirTran to tap into more stable year-round markets, allowing it to
maintain the profitability it has restored for the first time since
the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found that the Orlando market was primarily seasonal and
leisure-based, so that's really why we're going to the bigger
Atlanta base,'' Maruskin said. She added AirTran customers will
still be able to reach all the airline's destinations, just not
directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not stopping service,'' she said. ``We're just using
Atlanta (more).''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
