<SLUG> BC-CDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Banks sometimes share data with brokerage units
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Banks are pushing into the stock brokerage and
insurance businesses, enabling brokers and agents to poke into your
banking business.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank, First Union, Wachovia, SunTrust Banks and others
routinely share customer information with their investment
subsidiaries. So if your certificate of deposit is about to mature,
you could get a call from a stockbroker proposing alternative
investments.
</P>
<P>
   It's been perfectly legal since 1997 under an amendment to the
Fair Credit Reporting Act, as long as you give an OK. You probably
did that without knowing it, according to consumer groups, which
consider the sharing of such information an invasion of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer groups and the Federal Trade Commission are doing
what we can to repeal that law. But it's a tough battle,'' said
Edmund Mierzwinski of the U.S. Public Interest Research Group in
Washington. He termed the amendment ``a successful anti-consumer
lobbying effort by the banking industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The banks don't see a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no programs and systems in place that automatically
send referrals,'' said SunTrust Banks spokesman Hugh Suhr.
``Ideally a referral would be made from a relationship approach to
banking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While it's acceptable to share that information (about CDs)
between the bank and the broker dealer, it really does not happen
with a great deal of frequency within Wachovia. Our counselors are
not preying on CD lists as a way of doing business,'' said Forrest
C. Childers, senior vice president and managing director of
Wachovia Investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a customer privacy document that's posted on our
Internet site (http://wachovia.com)'', Childers said. ``Basically,
anything we're going to do with customer information is specified
in the guidelines of that policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fair Credit Reporting Act requires your permission for
information sharing, but in practice, said Mierzwinski, ``that's
buried in fine print.'' Notification of your rights along with a
means of requesting that your data not be shared _ an option that
you have to pursue _ is all that's required. The law does not
provide for a way to stop information sharing, according to the
Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   You should have received notice from your bank in one form or
another.
</P>
<P>
   Most commonly, the notice about information sharing is in your
customer agreement with the bank, according to Pierce Nelson,
spokesman for the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you'd find many people who thought they'd given
permission for that,'' said Jean Ann Fox of the Washington-based
Consumer Federation of America.
</P>
<P>
   She noted states could prohibit information sharing. Georgia has
no such law, according to Steve Bridges, commissioner of banking
and finance.
</P>
<P>
   Banking companies desiring to convert CDs into more profitable
securities have a large market to pursue. Insured savings
institutions have about $1.15 trillion in time deposits such as
CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
