<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield gives Atlanta business comunnity another round
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Sudden interest from some Atlanta businesses has led
Evander Holyfield's representatives to give the community another
week to make a significant financial commitment for a potential
Holyfield fight in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thomas, the heavyweight champion's attorney, said he
received phone calls from ``four or five major businesses'' on
Friday after Holyfield and Thomas expressed disappointment in the
community for not supporting a proposed bout against Vaughn Bean on
Sept. 19. Their comments appeared in Friday's editions of The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting calls now from people saying, 'What do you mean
there's no support? What can we do?' `` Thomas said. ``There's no
concrete decision, but we're going to try to make this work.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said the change has led Holyfield, promoter Don King and
the Showtime cable network to lower the amount of guarantees they
are seeking from the city's businesses. They originally cited a
figure of $2 million to $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to take more risk and make more of a
sacrifice,'' Thomas said. ``We're willing to take a chance on
people buying tickets and the business support being there.''
</P>
<P>
   King's alternate plan, if the Atlanta fight doesn't come off, is
for Holyfield to fight Bean or Henry Akinwande in October in Las
Vegas or Atlantic City. Holyfield, whose scheduled June 6 fight in
New York City against Akinwande was canceled because the challenger
tested positive for hepatitis B, has not fought since a November
win over Michael Moorer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
