<SLUG> BC-UPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Nothing's really changed,' UPS employees complain
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- A year after the bruising strike at United Parcel
Service, Teamsters again took up their posts outside the company's
distribution hubs Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This time they were handing out flyers, not striking. Workers
are voicing complaints remarkably similar to those that led to the
paralyzing walkout last August. UPS and Teamsters continue to
wrangle over the company's heavy reliance on part-time workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's really changed,'' says Scott McKee, a part-time
package sorter who picked up a union flier outside the company's
Doraville center.
</P>
<P>
   McKee, 43, is in his ninth year as a part-timer at UPS, despite
repeated requests to go full-time. His pay was bumped up after the
strike _ he now makes close to $30,000 a year for working 40 to 50
hours a week. But like many part-timers working full-time weeks, he
gets less pay, and reduced vacation time and pension terms compared
to full timers.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal that ended last year's strike, UPS committed to
shift part-timers into 2,000 new full-time jobs this year. But
under the agreement, the company doesn't have to add the jobs if
reduced package volume has led to layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it has cut part-time jobs through attrition and
laid off some full-time drivers because its load of daily U.S.
package deliveries has dropped 4 percent in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials dispute the company's conclusions, accuse UPS of
cutting back on its service in rural areas and point out company
profits are up.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials are seeking arbitration to resolve the
dispute, according to spokesman Robert Godlewski. Donald Scott, the
statewide president for the Teamsters' local 728, says he doubts
the disagreements will grow into another crippling showdown between
the company and the union.
</P>
<P>
   McKee, the part-time sorter, agrees. ``Nobody wants that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
