<HEADLINE>
US RESORTS FAVORED BY CANADIANS FEELING LONELY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLD ORCHARD BEACH, Maine _ Once, this was considered the summer
resort town of choice for Quebecers. But the 8,000-person town _ at
a five-hour drive, the closest ocean beach to Montreal -- has seen
a decline in Canadian tourists as the strong US dollar pushes down
Canadians' buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a few,'' says Phyllis Kilfoil, owner of the 18-room
Millbrook Motel, which has had fewer than half a dozen Canadian
guests each week this summer. ``The numbers are low, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this is high tourist season in the Old Orchard Beach
area, with up to 140,000 people streaming into town on a crowded
Saturday, hotel owners say the Canadians are either staying away or
making shorter trips to Maine. And those Canadians who do come
often try to use the plummeting exchange rate to wring sympathy out
of businesspeople.
</P>
<P>
   ``They try to use it as bargaining power to get the rate down,''
says Mitchell M. Wood, who owns the Americana Motel, right across
the street from the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, once they've decided to shell out expensive American
dollars for a hotel room, Canadian tourists frequently spend less
on extra amenities, local businespeople say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a little more frugal,'' says James E. Harmon,
executive director of the Old Orchard Beach Chamber of Commerce.
``Instead of dining out, they might cook in their room. They go to
matinees instead of evening movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Old Orchard Beach has tried to capitalize on the strong US
economy by refurbishing the nearly 350-year-old town, adding
fountains and trees and renovating the roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really made an investment into the town about six or seven
years ago trying to bring back the American family,'' says Harmon.
``Where we've slacked off in Canadian tourists the Americans have
filled the void.''
</P>
<P>
   And the tourist void is not yet bottomless in Maine. Their
numbers may be shrinking, but Canadians continue to visit the
state. Border crossings into Maine were up in June, according to
the Maine Office of Tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some local hotel owners say Maine is a deal, compared to
steep vacation prices in Canada's Maritime Provinces. ``The motel
rates up there, they're double my rates,'' says Rousseau.
</P>
<P>
   And for some Canadians, the exchange rate may be more a favorite
complaint than a vacation-killer. ``They've been talking about it
for 10 years,'' Rousseau says. ``It gives them some means of
conversation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
