<SLUG> BC-MA-INSURANCE-TAXCUTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATORS AGREE TO $50M TAX CUT FOR INSURANCE COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Reaching agreement on what is believed to be the first
law of its kind, the Massachusetts Legislature was expected Friday
night to pass a long-awaited tax break for insurance companies in
return for contributions to a community reinvestment fund.
</P>
<P>
   After racing to craft a compromise between House and Senate
versions, conferees Friday said they had agreed to a bill that
would give insurance companies up to $50 million in tax relief over
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, companies would contribute $200 million _ $100
million each from life insurance companies and property and
casualty companies _ to a pool to fund housing in poor areas of the
state as well as minority- and women-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The full Legislature was expected to adopt the measure before
adjourning for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody involved with this is very pleased,'' said Sen.
Warren Tolman, chairman of the Senate Joint Committee on Taxation.
``The insurance companies are happy. The community groups are
happy. Some people up here have been working on this for 15 years.
We finally did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts insurance companies for years have lobbied for
lower taxes, which are higher in the state than the nationwide
average of 2 percent. Because of a peculiarity in insurance tax
laws, companies pay the rate of their home state wherever they do
business, meaning Massachusetts companies' tax bills are
significantly higher than their counterparts in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, community groups have long lobbied for laws
encouraging the insurance industry to contribute to development in
poor communities in the same manner community reinvestment laws
compel banks to make loans in underdeveloped areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good bill and a very good start to what we hope
will be a long and beneficial relationship with the insurance
industry,'' said Marc Draisen, president of the Insurance Community
Reinvestment Coalition. ``The insurance industry is one the
nation's largest controllers of capital. With this as a start, we
feel that in four or five years, insurance companies will be eager
to invest in low- and moderate-income areas.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to creating the $200 million pool of money, the bill
also infuses $100 million into the Massachusetts Capital Resources
Co., created in 1977 to promote community investment by the
insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   The bill scraps the 14 percent net investment tax now paid by
Massachusetts life insurers and eliminates two smaller but costly
taxes paid by property and casualty insurers based
</P>
<P>
   here. It also grants a 1.5 percent tax credit on the amount
invested by any insurer working in Massachusetts in community
projects and gives community advocates more say in how insurers
fund lower-income projects.
</P>
<P>
   Companies who choose not to give to the fund, won't receive tax
breaks under the terms of the bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
