<SLUG> BC-NY-MEN'S-FASHION-$ADV02-980&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOS AND DON'TS OF RUNWAY SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 2)  
(lb) 
 By FRANK DeCARO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To get to Day for Night, a stylish space on fashion's
new frontier in the westernmost reaches of Chelsea, you need to
take a slow-moving, living-room-size,
don't-touch-the-walls-they're-filthy freight elevator up to the
18th floor. Including waiting time, air kisses and loading-dock
chitchat of the ``Love your Prada man-purse'' variety, it takes
maybe 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Nautica show for spring 1999, held there last Monday, was
over in maybe eight.
</P>
<P>
   The 32 outfits on display went by in a flash of sleeveless
T-shirts and neoprene pants, leaving the audience wanting more _ a
full-fledged sampling of David Chu's latest collection, perhaps _
or less, that is, no show at all.
</P>
<P>
   In its brevity, the Nautica show was the soul of folly. All that
expense and for what? Cotton jams and a couple of suits.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Farhi, the British sportswear designer, used the term
``focused collection'' in the notes for her menswear show at the
New York Public Library last Tuesday. In that phrase, she hit upon
the essence of any good fashion show. It can't be too long or too
short, too boring or too radical, too somber or too cute. It must
be focused, but fulfilling.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's men's shows in New York _ officially known as
General Motors Fashion Week _ offered plenty of lessons in how to
show fashion and how not to. The proceedings proved that not every
designer is up to the task of showing on a runway and that it takes
a particular confluence of ingredients to get it just right.
</P>
<P>
   What are those ingredients?
</P>
<P>
   Location, location, location. It is one of the unspoken rules of
fashion. If a show is held in a convenient place, it doesn't have
to set the world on fire. The Public Library's Celeste Bartos
Forum, where many shows were presented, is nondescript but
efficient. The Hugo Boss show was perfectly suited to it. If it's
hard to get to a show, however, it had better be good.
</P>
<P>
   John Bartlett can show on 10th Avenue. His mix of Army surplus
and Lilly Pulitzer _ what he called a ``dizzying world of
come-hither hybrids'' in the show notes _ was as cocksure and
cockamamie as always, and completely worth the trip. Few jaunts to
the far West Side were as fruitful, however.
</P>
<P>
   An air of exclusivity is important, too. Marc Jacobs showed his
collection of Old Navy Deluxe in a tiny space on Mercer Street with
Billy Zane's cueball head front row center. It felt as if you were
in for something, although after the show there was considerable
debate on the merits of cashmere fatigues.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Hilfiger took exclusivity to the extreme at his show on
Tuesday morning. Once his bouncers closed the doors of the Dia
Center for the Arts on West 22nd Street, they didn't want to open
them. Sean Combs (known as Puffy), who arrived 25 minutes late just
as the show was beginning, almost didn't get in but was given
access as the lights were dimming. LaVelle Olexa, Lord &AMP; Taylor's
top fashion merchandiser, wasn't so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get in, a runway full of the right models can do
wonders to help you forget the surliness of the bouncers. A
celebrity in the room helps if he is as unexpected as Dharma &AMP;
Greg's Thomas Gibson at Hilfiger or, better yet, as cool as Samuel
L. Jackson, the star of ``The Negotiator,'' at Hugo Boss.
</P>
<P>
   The most endearing presence on the runways last week, however,
was not a celebrity at all. It was the model Colin Egglesfield, a
looker in the Tom Cruise vein with a killer smile. Although he has
modeled for two years _ doing print campaigns for Calvin Klein and
Versace _ he seemed just the tiniest bit embarrassed by the
attention his gym-sculptured body was receiving.
</P>
<P>
   At Cynthia Rowley's rooftop showing, high above an entrance to
the Lincoln Tunnel on Wednesday, he was made to model a striped
Speedo-style bikini. His ear-to-ear grin seemed to say, ``I'm
nearly naked, and you're all staring at me!'' He covered his face
as he approached the outstretched lenses of the photographers,
which, of course, made him even more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   As much as the right models, giveaways are a good thing at any
fashion show. Ms. Rowley knows that parting gifts can't make a
presentation _ usually _ but they leave the audience feeling better
than it might without them. Believing that only too much is enough,
she plied her guests with enough gear for a day at the beach _ a
striped towel, lip balm, aloe vera gel and a good book.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at Hugo Boss handed out metal-frame sunglasses in
black bags. Jacobs gave away plain white T-shirts with his name
writ tiny and silk-screened in white on white on the back between
the shoulders. There were note pads from Nautica.
</P>
<P>
   Of all fashion-show ingredients, cool music is among the most
important. It focuses opinion and sometimes explains a designer's
impetus. You hear ``Planet Claire'' by the B-52s, and you imagine
Bartlett in a new wave state of mind. At Kenneth Cole's show last
Monday, it was a disco remake of ``Dreams'' by Fleetwood Mac that
lent the collection its hipness.
</P>
<P>
   As the audience entered Gene Meyer's show on Wednesday at the
Public Library, it heard ``It's My Turn,'' then ``I've Never Been
to Me.'' At the finale, it was ``Xanadu'' by Olivia Newton-John.
The cheery schmaltz was irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, a designer whose colorful neckties and boxer shorts have
been spicing up even the drabbest men's wardrobes for years,
suggested that his latest collection was the result of ``designing
under the influence of St. John's wort.''
</P>
<P>
   The allusion to the trendy mood enhancer _ a sort of herbal
Prozac _ made it clear that he is aware of a world beyond the pages
of W. It added validity to the idea of sequined shirts worn with
chinos and reminded his audience how completely necessary it is for
a designer to pick up a thread of popular culture and weave it into
something of his own. The best shows last week did just that.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Years ago, before ``zeitgeist'' became the most overused word in
fashion and television coverage of runway shows became ubiquitous,
menswear week as we know it didn't exist. Twice a year, journalists
would travel to the Westchester County suburb of Rye Brook for a
weekend at the Hilton organized by a trade organization known as
the Men's Fashion Association. Those who attended called it Fashion
Camp, and it was, in all senses of the word.
</P>
<P>
   By today's standards, the runway presentations were strictly
Paramus Park: catalog models in commentated shows. But as cheesy as
it all was, the focus was always on the clothes. In retrospect,
that wasn't such a bad thing. Jhane Barnes in a hotel ballroom
wasn't nearly as glamorous as seeing Jackson, the movie star, on
the runway at the Public Library, but it had its merits.
</P>
<P>
   If the clothes are really good, not much more is needed. Ralph
Lauren didn't even attend his menswear still-life presentation last
Thursday _ he was on vacation at his ranch, his hands said _ but it
didn't matter. The clothes looked just fine without him. Likewise,
Donna Karan's showroom walk-through of DKNY Men later that day was
a winner because the clothes looked so good. The hors d'oeuvres
didn't hurt, however.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
