<SLUG> BC-ADDISON-LAYOFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADDISON WESLEY TO LAY OFF 375 WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Publisher Addison Wesley Longman will lay off about 375
corporate-services employees from its Reading, Mass. headquarters
next March when parent company Pearson PLC completes its
acquisition of Simon &AMP; Schuster's educational publishing business
from Viacom Inc., Addison Wesley officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The combined Simon &AMP; Schuster/Addison Wesley educational
division, to be renamed Pearson Education, will be the largest
educational publishing company in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson Education will be headquartered at Simon &AMP; Schuster's
475,000-square-foot facility in Upper Saddle River, N.J. All
Addison Wesley business divisions, including human resources,
orders, and finance, will move to New Jersey, while editorial
positions will remain in the company's Reading and Stoneham
offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Reading headquarters' 730 employees were told of the layoffs
Friday morning. The remaining jobs will be transferred to New
Jersey by April 1999, except for the information services division,
which will move later that year, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson plans to give laid-off workers severance pay and help
them look for jobs elsewhere in the company's publishing empire,
company spokeswoman Susan Stockman said.
</P>
<P>
   London-based Pearson bought Addison Wesley, which controls 14
percent of the US educational market, in 1988 for $283 million.
</P>
<P>
   The British media conglomerate, which also owns The Financial
Times, The Economist, and several TV operations, agreed to acquire
Simon &AMP; Schuster in May as part of a wave of publishing industry
mergers. After a planned sale of some Simon &AMP; Schuster assets to
Hicks, Must, Tate &AMP; Furst, the transaction is expected to bring in
$3.6 billion for Pearson.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is awaiting US regulatory approval; Addison
Wesley &UR;  &LR; chairman and chief executive Peter Jovanovich &UR;  &LR; said he
expects the sale to be finalized later this year. The company has
received requests for more information for an ``expected'' second
round of Department of Justice scrutiny and is cooperating,
according to Pearson spokesman Roy Winnick.
</P>
<P>
   Addison Wesley, founded in 1942 in Cambridge, Mass., moved to
its Reading location in the 1960s. The company has no plans to
abandon its Boston-area locations entirely, according to
Jovanovich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
