<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3006 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-BOS &LR;      07-31 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POISON PILLS' EXCISED FROM CAMPAIGN REFINANCE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House reached the threshold of what one
lawmaker called ``the promised land'' of a new campaign finance
system Friday as supporters of a landmark overhaul bill defeated
the last of more than 60 amendments aimed at gutting the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The overhaul plan, considered a hopeless cause only months ago
amid stern opposition from House Speaker Newt Gingrich, faces a
final vote Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   If the bill passes, it will mark one of the most remarkable
rescues of apparently doomed legislation in the House in recent
years. No major proposal to improve the nation's campaign finance
system has become law in more than a generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extraordinary accomplishment to have gotten through
this process, which was set up by the Republican leaders to defeat
the bill,'' said Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts
Democrat, who is sponsoring the measure with Representative
Christopher Shays, a Connecticut Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were rebuffed,'' Meehan said of the GOP leaders, ``and we
are headed toward a showdown on Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the measure would face another uphill battle in the
Senate, where a similar plan died earlier this year when backers
could not muster enough votes to end a Republican filibuster,
supporters hope the plan passes the House by a margin substantial
enough to provide fresh momentum in the Senate. President Clinton
has said he would sign the bill into law if it reaches the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Shays said he expects more than 230 members of the 435-member
House to vote for the overhaul plan, just months after he and
Meehan struggled to find enough colleagues to sign a petition that
forced Gingrich to permit a debate on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   However, Meehan remained cautious. ``We're in a strong
position,'' he said. ``But we need to work over the weekend to make
sure members don't get cold feet, which sometimes happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure would ban the unlimited, unregulated contributions
known as ``soft money,'' which were at the center of the most
serious campaign finance abuses in the 1996 elections. Both major
parties are continuing to raise soft money for the 1998 and 2000
elections at a rapid clip.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the plan would prohibit independent advertising by
special interest groups before elections unless the organizations
disclosed who provided the money for the ads.
</P>
<P>
   In votes Friday, the Shays-Meehan coalition defeated five
amendments that were seen as ``poison pills,'' measures so divisive
they would break apart the coalition supporting the overall
package.
</P>
<P>
   Notable among them was an amendment by Representative Clay Shaw,
a Florida Republican, that would have required House candidates to
raise at least 50 percent of their contributions within their home
states.
</P>
<P>
   Shays-Meehan supporters said that proposal would hurt candidates
in some low-income and minority districts. The measure was
defeated, 253-168.
</P>
<P>
   In another key vote, the House rejected a plan that Shays-Meehan
backers said would have rolled back the so-called ``motor voter''
law by eliminating mail-in registration and requiring prospective
voters to provide proof of citizenship, photo identification, and
Social Security numbers. The measure failed, 260-165.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the most difficult challenge facing Shays and Meehan
before the vote on Monday is maintaning the support of most black
and Hispanic House members in their coalition. The minority members
are under intense pressure from 65 groups opposed to an amendment
to Shays-Meehan that would ban contributions from noncitizens who
are legal residents of the United States. The amendment passed
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Shays-Meehan bill shuts legal immigrants out of a crucial
part of the political process,'' the groups stated in a letter sent
Thursday to House members.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Shays-Meehan plan is backed by a broad coalition of
groups such as Common Cause and the League of Women Voters, the
measure also has been assailed by organizations such as the
American Civil Liberties Union and the National Rifle Association
as an assault on free-speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   If the bill becomes law, the National Right to Life Committee
plans court challenges to several provisions that would regulate
advocacy aimed at influencing federal elections.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the controversy, Shays and Meehan have made numerous
concessions to hold together their coalition. As a consequence, the
final product has left some supporters craving more than the final
bill contains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The passage of Shays-Meehan addresses loopholes in the
system,'' said Ellen Miller, executive director of Public Campaign,
which favors publicly financed elections. ``But it doesn't touch
the underlying concerns the public has about the role of special
interest money and how it dominates candidate fund-raising.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Shays-Meehan supporters described the package as a solid
compromise. ``It's the best we could do under the circumstances,''
said Representative Steve Horn, a California Republican. ``It's a
major step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Most rank-and-file Republicans have backed Gingrich's efforts to
scuttle the bill, including a rare procedure that created a
legislative free-for-all among every House coalition trying to
improve the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   Under the process, known as ``Queen of the Hill,'' 12
alternative plans, including Shays-Meehan, were to be voted on,
with the measure receiving the most votes prevailing.
</P>
<P>
   However, the sponsors of several alternatives have said they
will withdraw their plans if Shays-Meehan passes. The greatest
remaining threat to Shays-Meehan would be a compromise plan by
House freshmen, but even some of the bill's freshmen sponsors have
said they will not cast a vote that kills the Shays-Meehan plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
