<SLUG> BC-BIZWEEK-ART-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2)  
 (af)  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRIKES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GM and UAW Settle &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After nearly eight weeks that are expected to cost General
Motors $3 billion in after-tax losses, the auto maker and the
United Automobile Workers union settled strikes at two auto parts
factories in Flint, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes had shut down GM assembly plants across North
America, rippled through to suppliers, pushed hundreds of thousands
of workers into temporary unemployment and slowed the nation's
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   One worker, Matthew Purzycki, and his wife, Amy, embraced in joy
at the settlement. But it is less labor peace than rapprochement _
it does not directly address issues that the union had declared
were driving the strike, like GM's push to open new factories
overseas or its effort to shrink its American work force through
attrition. Still, the two sides agreed to meet regularly in an
effort to avert future strikes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE ECONOMY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Creeping Wage Inflation &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In one of the tightest peacetime labor markets in memory, wage
inflation is rising. But it is creeping, not galloping. The Labor
Department's employment cost index _ a broad gauge that is closely
watched by the Federal Reserve chairman, Alan Greenspan, and other
policy makers _ rose 0.9 percent this spring, slightly more than
the winter's 0.7 percent increase. ... The gross domestic product
increased at a modest 1.4 percent annual rate in the second
quarter, the Commerce Department said.
</P>
<P>
   The slackening after a 5.5 percent rate in the first three
months was attributed to losing trade with crisis-ridden Asian
nations and to the prolonged GM strike. ... Sales of new homes
climbed 3.8 percent in June, to an annual rate of 935,000 units,
the fastest pace since record-keeping began in 1963, the Commerce
Department said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bouncing Back &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices snapped out of their slump toward the end of the
week, as the Dow Jones industrial average climbed back above 9,000.
But on Friday the skid resumed, with the average ending the week at
8,883.29, down 54.07 points, and more than 450 below its high of
9,337.97, set on July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Concern over earnings, the Asian crisis and the White House sex
scandal was cited ... Despite the market's recent choppy
conditions, new and additional issues of stock so far this year are
running high, Securities Data reported. Some 600 common-stock deals
in the first seven months of 1998 brought in domestic proceeds of
about $66.7 billion, surpassed only by the $69.6 billion of
offerings in the comparable period of 1996. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Fed Chief Dies &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   William McChesney Martin Jr., who steered an independent course
during 19 years as chairman of the Federal Reserve, died at 91. He
had won the respect of five administrations, from that of Harry S.
Truman to Richard M. Nixon. ... Walter A. Forbes, chairman of the
beleaguered Cendant Corp., a direct marketer and franchiser,
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   The board immediately elected Henry R. Silverman, the company's
chief executive, to the additional post of chairman. ... Ron Carey,
the Teamster president who once seemed destined to clean up one of
the nation's largest but most corrupt unions, was expelled from the
union by a court-appointed review board. It said he failed to stop
an illegal scheme that siphoned more than $750,000 in union money
into his 1996 re-election campaign. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   TELECOMMUNICATIONS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Merger Frenzy &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, which dominates local telephone business from
Maine to Virginia, agreed to acquire the GTE Corp., the nation's
largest independent local and long-distance company, for $52.9
billion in stock. But stock traders made the deal look more like
the pin that burst the telecommunications stock bubble than a
megamerger.
</P>
<P>
   Most telephone stocks declined, and investors who had bought GTE
shares hoping that they would rise in a takeover saw their price
slide, too. GTE ended the week at $54.44, or $1.32 below Monday's
close of $55.75, while Bell Atlantic fell $45.44. ... AT&AMP;T and
British Telecommunications agreed to merge most of their
international operations into a jointly owned company that would
have $10 billion in revenue. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OTHER DEALS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Multinational Multimedia &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The French government agreed to sell 30 percent of its
money-losing Thomson Multimedia, one of Europe's largest consumer
electronics makers, to four companies including Microsoft, which is
expected to expand its push into delivering Internet services via
television. The other buyers are the DirecTV unit of Hughes
Electronics, NEC of Japan and Alcatel Alsthom of France. ...
American International Group said it would invest $1.35 billion in
the Blackstone Group, a private New York merchant bank. ... Paul
Allen, the billionaire investor, agreed to buy more than 90 percent
of Charter Communications, the nation's 10th-largest cable
operator, for $4.5 billion. ... Swiss Reinsurance agreed to acquire
Life Re for $1.8 billion cash.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Letter Bomb by E-Mail? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Popular e-mail programs from Microsoft and Netscape
Communications have a serious security flaw that could permit a
malicious person to send a virus-laden message that could crash a
computer and destroy or even steal data when an attachment was
opened. Although there is no evidence yet of any virus that
exploits this vulnerability, security tests have shown that the
flaw exists in three popular e-mail programs, used by perhaps tens
of millions of people around the world: Microsoft's Outlook Express
and Outlook 98 and Netscape Mail. The flaw is said to result from
programmers' use of the programming languages C and C(plusplus).
(Eds: plusplus should be replaced by symbol). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Ink Thickens &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Japan's banking crisis is far worse than Tokyo has publicly
acknowledged, American officials and private financial experts have
concluded, with bad debts approaching roughly $1 trillion, or
nearly twice the official estimate. Japanese banks have used
accounting tricks to hide unpaid debts, the foreign experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, who has been a fixture in
American-Japanese relations for four decades, agreed to become
Finance Minister, thus landing in the center of the financial
storm. The new estimates suggest that bailing out the Japanese
banks could cost Japanese taxpayers far more than the $214 billion
that Tokyo has set aside. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER MADNESS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Roar of the Crowd &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hoping for one of the 500 free pairs of jeans being offered,
hundreds of people swarmed a new Old Navy store in the heart of
Chicago's loop on Thursday, clogging streets and creating a street
festival-type atmosphere during the midday rush hour until three
police officers on horseback herded them to the sidewalk. ``This is
all just for a store opening,'' one officer said. ``Unbelievable.''
. ... Unbelievable? He should have seen the crowds in Connecticut,
above. But there the stakes were higher: $292 million in a
Powerball lottery. Thousands of out-of-state ticket buyers swarmed
into elegant Greenwich, creating a spectacle that local residents
found decidedly declasse. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anger Over a Phone Deal &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the one of the largest privatizations ever, Brazil sold
control of most of its telephone system, Telebras, for about $19
billion to MCI and Spanish and Portuguese telephone companies. But
many Brazilians were angry, contending that foreigners were paying
far too little for Telebras securities being sold at the Rio de
Janeiro stock exchange. Protesters in downtown Rio lined up behind
a barricade during a clash with Brazilian riot police.
</P>
</TEXT>
