<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-MINIMUM-WAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTEMPT TO RAISE MINIMUM WAGE DIES IN LEGISLATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A proposal to raise Massachusetts' minimum wage by this
year died a remarkable death Friday night despite broadbased
support after House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran refused to allow the
measure to come up for a vote on the last day of the legislative
session.
</P>
<P>
   Both branches of the Democratic-controlled Legislature have
widely supported the idea. Even Acting Governor Paul Cellucci
conceded on the issue, saying working people deserve a break in the
booming economy of an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in spite of all that, the bill boost the rate by 90 cents
per hour remained stuck in committee just as Finneran, the only
outspoken critic to the proposal outside of the business community,
had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups, as well as Finneran, have said raising the
minimum wage could cause inflation and drive low-cost jobs
out-of-state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said all along we don't think increasing the minimum
wage is a good idea at this time,'' said Rick Lord, executive vice
president for legislative policy at the Associated Industries of
Massachusetts. ``We're certainly pleased the Speaker has decided to
hold the line on those issues and we sincerely do believe there are
other alternatives that should be looked at'' such as increasing
the earned income tax credit to help poor people, Lord said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cellucci has been opposed to hiking the minimum wage,
he filed legislation in May to raise it from $5.25 an hour to $6.15
over the next two years, saying the increase was a much-needed
reward for working people.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, meanwhile, had its own plan to boost the wage to
$6.75 an hour over three years. That plan, tacked onto the budget,
got sliced on the cutting room floor by negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   And Cellucci's proposal, the only one left, has been stuck in
House Ways and Means where it remained right up until the stroke of
midnight when the session ended.
</P>
<P>
   Now the only chance for residents of Massachusetts getting an
increase is to rely on a raise at the federal level, which will set
the floor for wages across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The federal minimum wage is now at $5.15 an hour, but US Senator
Edward M. Kennedy has proposed increasing that to $6.15 an hour
over two years.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he urged Finneran to let minimum wage come up for
a vote, knowing that House members would pass the measure, as would
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran -- who was not available for comment -- has been clear
in his opposition recently, saying Massachusetts should not stick
its neck out and increase the wage, leaving cheaper labor just
beyond the borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to the Speaker of the House several times on that. I
told him I think it's important,'' Cellucci said. ``He talked about
his concern that we act alone. The fact of the matter is
Connecticut has just adopted an increase in the minimum wage that
has the exact same figures as the bill I filed. So when you put
Massachusetts and Connecticut together, that's a pretty big piece
of the regional economy of New England,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut increased its minimum wage this year with little
acrimony after years of partisan clashes on the issue. The base pay
there will inch up from $5.18 per hour to $5.65 on Jan. 1. The
second of the two-stage increase will be an additional 50 cents per
hour in the year 2000, pushing the minimum wage to $6.15 per hour
or about $12,000 annually for a 40-hour work week. That state has
the country's highest per-capita income and only about 4 percent of
the work force is paid minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bluestone, professor of political economy at the
University of Massachusetts at Boston, sharply disagreed with the
Speaker's argument for staying pat on the issue, especially in a
state with such a high cost of living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Finneran's wrong and I'm surprised that a Democrat is
opposing a rise in the minimum wage. The fact is that part of the
reason why we've had a growing economy over the last two-and-a-half
years nationwide is due to the fact that we raised the minimum
wage, which put more money in people's pockets and they went out
and spent it,'' Bluestone said. ``All of the new evidence on the
minimum wage suggests that there is, at most, a very small to no
negative employment effect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
