<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-CHEAP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN GO NORTH TO CASH IN ON CANDIAN DOLLAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i, f and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ The swoon of the Canadian dollar has put
a sizzle into the wallets of Americans venturing north of the
border, especially those seeking vacation bargains in
accommodations, entertainment, and souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listening to the radio on the drive up, it seemed as though
the Canadian dollar was hitting another record low with every news
update,'' said Paul Dow of Georgetown, Mass., on a camping trip
with his wife, Maureen, through Prince Edward Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty hard news for the poor Canadians, I'd guess, but
it meant our vacation was getting cheaper by the hour,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The loonie _ nickname of the Canadian dollar because of the
national bird, the common loon, depicted on the country's $1 coin _
is in free fall, plummeting to all-time lows against the greenback.
Right now, the Canadian dollar is worth about .66 cents US, its
lowest level in history. The value is eroding so inexorably that
prognosticators say there is no way of telling where the loonie
will finally flutter to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't pick a bottom,'' said Sal Guatieri, senior economist
with the Bank of Montreal. ``The near-term picture is not very
rosy.''
</P>
<P>
   One often-heard joke asks what do you call Canada's $2 coin?
Answer: An American dollar. But the yucks are sounding hollow as
headlines proclaiming yet another precipitous drop have become
routine front page fare _ another day, another drop. In July, the
loonie closed at seven all-time lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's relentless, it's unhealthy,'' said Sherry Cooper,
economist at Nesbitt Burns Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Canada is the victim of Asia's economic woes.
Desperate times in once-booming Pacific Rim nations from Japan to
Indonesia means a drastically shriveled market for natural
resources and other exports on which the Canadian economy is so
reliant. Meanwhile, the economic tremors in Asia have investors
scrambling to put their money into the strongest and safest
currency in the world _ the US dollar _ and selling off secondary
currencies, such as Canada's.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other factors, as well, including long-running
fear that restless Quebec may yet vote to secede from the country
before the end of the century. Additionally, high unemployment
continues to dog most of the 10 provinces despite overall
strengthening of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   However, the news is not all bad for Canada. Exporters benefit
from cheaper Canadian products, for example. Meanwhile, the
country's tourism industry is booming on the back of the drooping
loonie as Americans flock to Canada in search of bargains _ and
Canadians, less and less able to afford vacations in Maine or
California, settle for holidays in their own backyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd really prefer to spend a week in Vermont and another week
on Cape Cod, as we usually do,'' said Mary Chan of Toronto,
vacationing in Nova Scotia with her husband and two children. ``But
the weak loonie makes New England just too painfully expensive to
enjoy. Even a family lunch break at McDonald's is going to run us
$45'' in equivalent Canadian money.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, tourist officials say the most startling change brought
by the plunging Canadian dollar is not so much the arrival of more
Americans _ although the numbers of Yanks are up almost everywhere
_ but the hordes of Canadians who feel financially obliged to
vacation in their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Canadian visitor totals are up enormously, and that more
reflects the devalued dollar than the arrivals of more Americans,''
said Sharon Martin, manager of inquiries and research for Nova
Scotia's Department of Economic Development and Tourism. ``A lot of
Canadians are choosing Canadian vacations primarily because our
dollar is so weak down in the states. But I think it's rather rare
for an American to say, `Hey, the Canadian dollar is low _ let's
go!' It's more like they find the stronger'' US dollar ``just an
added bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   That notion was echoed by most of more than a dozen vacationing
New Englanders interviewed in the Maritime Provinces and Quebec in
recent days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came looking for natural beauty, not bargains,'' said
Robert Wilson of Uxbridge, Mass., vacationing in the Maritime
Provinces with wife Elaine. ``It's nice that the our dollar
stretches farther, and some of the savings are a real surprise, but
currency was not a deciding factor. We were just looking for a
lovely place and a relaxed pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the shrunken dollar, Canada is not an across-the-board
shopper's paradise. Nearly all manufactured consumer goods, whether
cameras or chain saws, still cost considerably more in Canada than
in the United States. Gasoline is also more expensive, as is a
bottle of wine or trip to the supermarket. Taxes are stupefying,
with combined federal and provincial sales taxes ranging from 15 to
19 percent. Even taxes are taxed, as in the case of postage.
</P>
<P>
   But the weak Canadian dollar has transformed many of the things
tourists seek into remarkable deals, whether motel rooms, museum
fees, restaurant meals, high-quality handicrafts, or kitschy
souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in US dollars, a ticket for a musical at a Prince
Edward Island theater costs $6 while a room at one of
Charlottetown's better hotels can be had for $50. Cheaper but
perfectly decent motel rooms can easily be found for $25 a night.
Luxury hotel rooms in Toronto, Montreal or Halifax can be found for
$120 a night, about half the cost of New York or Boston. It's
possible to play 18 holes of golf at an oceanside course for $20.
Souvenir T-shirts can run as low as $5, while exquisite handmade
quilts can be bought for $250 or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same quality of quilt in Pennsylvania would be $500,
easily,'' said Maureen Dow.
</P>
<P>
   Even gambling is cheaper because, hey, if you drop $100 at the
casino in Montreal or Halifax at today's rates it's only a loss of
$66.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian dollar has been slipping for decades. The last time
one Canadian dollar trade for one US dollar was 1976. But it wasn't
until this year that the loonie plunged below the so-called
``psychological barrier'' of US 68 cents, hitherto the lowest level
in history.
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa has made no effort to ride to the rescue, at least so
far. Indeed, Prime Minister Jean Chretien enraged many citizens
earlier this month when he shrugged off the dollar's decline as
just ``a reality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Monetary policy is now powerless in Canada,'' Jeoffrey Hall,
market analyst for Boston's Thomson Global Markets, told the Ottawa
Citizen. ``Stick a fork in the Canadian dollar, it's done.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Americans, Canada's grim reality is cause to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Peterson, a recently graduated law student from Bristol,
Rhode Island, said she and her husband had originally planned to
travel across the US this summer to celebrate their recent
marriage. But a look at the exchange rate changed their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figure we'll have basically the same
across-the-prairies-and-over-the-Rockies experience for two-thirds
the cost,'' she said while sipping Moosehead beer at an outdoor
cafe in Montreal's Old City. ``And we're hoping it'll be just as
romantic to stroll beside Vancouver's bay as San Francisco's.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
