<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-AVIATION-600&AMP;A     07-31 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-AVIATION-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR EUROPE'S MILITARY INDUSTRY, THE MERGERS ARE JUST BEGINNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Military industry mergers may be history in the United
States, but in Europe they are very much alive.
</P>
<P>
   France's decision last week to privatize its aerospace giant,
Aerospatiale, shows that the process of sorting out European
aviation and military industries is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   American military companies, by contrast, have evolved into a
few giants, concentrated to the point that Lockheed Martin scrapped
its bid for Northrop Grumman a few weeks ago. The Pentagon said the
merged company would be too powerful, sending the message that
further combinations were not likely.
</P>
<P>
   European military companies, unlike their American counterparts,
remain highly fragmented, with hundreds of small competitors
struggling to pay for expensive research and development, even as
national defense budgets have shrunk.
</P>
<P>
   After the fall of communism, European governments slashed
military budgets so much that they collectively equal only about
half the Pentagon's $270-billion allocation.
</P>
<P>
   This is the main reason why Europe wants its aviation and
military industries to group into an enormous conglomerate,
tentatively named the European Aerospace and Defense Company, with
divisions that would include Airbus Industrie, the commercial
aircraft manufacturer, as well as space and defense activities like
military aircraft, missiles and weapons systems.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Airbus has been a resounding success, getting half
the worldwide orders this year for new jetliners despite bitter
competition from its rival, Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Manfred Bischoff, chief executive of Daimler-Benz
Aerospace, said that Airbus, which until now operated as a loose
consortium of four European aircraft manufacturers, would be ready
to start operating as a single company, probably a corporation
under French law, by the first half of next year. The challenge now
is building the rest of the new European aviation and military
conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem,'' said Nick Cunningham, aerospace analyst at
Salomon Smith Barney in London, ``is putting the monster
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The obstacles to such an undertaking are large. British
Aerospace, privatized in 1981, is one of the most efficient and
profitable companies, while Aerospatiale has a history of
government largess and bureaucratic management.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as industries are merged and duplication eliminated,
jobs will disappear. Deciding who remains employed will be
particularly difficult because Europe's unemployment rate is
roughly double that of the United States'.
</P>
<P>
   For Airbus, the chance to extend its newfound momentum by
tapping financial markets and financing new products, like a
planned jet for more than 500 passengers, depends on its ability to
operate as a single company, with its own management and
bookkeeping. European governments agree. This spring, Bonn warned
Airbus there would be no German government money for the superjet
until Airbus became a unified corporation.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea for a unified aerospace and military company goes
beyond the plans for Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   Under a grand design proposed earlier this year by Germany,
France and Britain, the big new company would be effectively owned
by the present Airbus partners _ Aerospatiale, Germany's
Daimler-Benz Aerospace, British Aerospace and Spain's
Construcciones Aeronauticas SA _ plus private investors. Run by a
single management, the company would consist not only of Airbus as
its commercial aircraft arm, but other units for space technology,
military aircraft and helicopters, missiles and weapons systems.
Italy and Sweden, though not part of the Airbus consortium, support
the plan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The reasoning is that Europe's military contractors, without the
influence of such a huge group, would wilt against the powerful
American companies like Lockheed Martin, Boeing and Raytheon that
emerged from five years of consolidation in the U.S.military
industry. Earlier this year, the largest European companies _
British Aerospace, the market leader; Aerospatiale, the No. 2.; and
the No. 3, Daimler-Benz _ ratified the plan.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that plan, the French government of Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin agreed last week to push the government stake in
Aerospatiale under 50 percent, bring in the big defense and
publishing group, Lagardere, as a private shareholder, and give the
government a ``golden share'' to assure national security
interests.
</P>
<P>
   The carousel of mergers and acquisitions is now expected to
begin in earnest to form the clusters that will ultimately be the
planned European company's divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Daimler-Benz announced that by year-end it will merge
its space activities into Matra Marconi Space, a joint venture
formed last year by Britain's General Electric Co. and Lagardere.
The resulting space contractor, with $2.5 billion of revenues, will
be the world's third largest, after Lockheed Martin and
Boeing-Rockwell. At the same time, Spain announced it would put 25
percent of its national aerospace group, the Airbus partner
Construcciones Aeronauticas, on the block for private investors,
and British Aerospace immediately said it would acquire a stake.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is no assurance that the proposed new aerospace
and defense group will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even as Daimler and British Aerospace officials praised
the French, they said they were continuing to talk with each other
_ about first choices, like the shape of the new European company,
but also about fallback positions, such as a possible merger of
their own. ``We're always talking with each other,'' said Simon
Raynes, the British Aerospace spokesman. ``All this talking is
really about seeking solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   But reports of discussions between the British and the Germans
have raised fears in Paris of a special British-German deal
designed to cut out the French.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Daimler's planned takeover of Chrysler Corp. has
contributed to speculation in France of Daimler's possible
withdrawal from the aerospace business, to focus on automobiles.
Daimler officials have denied that and said earlier this week that
Chrysler could even create aerospace opportunities for Daimler in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
