<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3028 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-500&AMP;A     07-31 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMY SLOWS, BUT GROWTH IS STILL HEALTHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV.: a graphic for use with this story is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(HLW)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A powerful array of forces at home and abroad
slowed the economy to a modest but still healthy pace during the
second quarter, the government said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department said that the nation's gross domestic
product grew at a 1.4 percent annual rate during April, May and
June. It was the most sluggish quarter in three years, and it
marked a substantial slowdown from the blistering pace of growth in
the first quarter, which the department on Friday revised upward to
5.5 percent from its earlier estimate of 5.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown rattled Wall Street, where investors have become
increasingly nervous about the ability of companies to sustain
strong earnings growth. The Dow Jones industrial average fell
143.66 points to close at 8,883.29. It has fallen more than 450
points or nearly 5 percent since hitting a new high two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But growth in the second quarter was considerably stronger than
had been projected by economists. Many had expected no growth or
even a slight contraction in the nation's total output.
</P>
<P>
   Although considerable uncertainties remain, not least among them
the continued effects of Asia's financial crisis on the United
States, the consensus among analysts is that growth for the rest of
the year should be 2 percent to 3 percent, considered respectable.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the details of Friday's report suggested that the
economy had so far weathered the Asia crisis _ plus the effects of
the now-settled strike against General Motors and a decision by
industry to prune excessively large stockpiles of unsold goods _
without much fundamental damage or any serious risk of recession.
</P>
<P>
   While export-oriented manufacturers and farmers are suffering
from Asia's problems, many of the forces that have driven the
nation's seven-year expansion remained very much intact, especially
strong growth in spending by consumers and businesses within the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The report showed that domestic final sales, an indicator of
domestic demand, surged 6.3 percent in the second quarter, compared
with a 6.6 percent gain in the first quarter, as consumers
continued to spend freely and businesses continued to invest in new
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Personal consumption increased 5.8 percent in the quarter, down
just slightly from 6.1 percent in the first three months of the
year. Capital spending by businesses rose 17.8 percent, roughly
half the rate of the previous quarter but still a vibrant pace.
</P>
<P>
   The report also suggested that inflation remains dormant, with
the main price index rising 0.8 percent in the second quarter, down
from 0.9 percent in the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy has taken a lot and come through it well,'' said
Richard D. Rippe, an economist at Prudential Securities in New
York.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like many economists, Rippe said it is still unclear how strong
growth will be for the rest of the year, and that much depends on
whether the situation in Asia stabilizes. So far, there are some
``very impressive'' signs in the third quarter of continued strong
demand, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still have a clash between weakness in trade and
inventories and on the other hand very vibrant domestic demand,''
Rippe said. ``That clash is likely to continue in the second half
of the year and how it turns out will determine how much momentum
the economy has.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's report was a preliminary estimate by the Commerce
Department, and it will almost certainly be revised as new data
come in, although it is impossible to say whether up or down.
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials at the White House expressed relief that the
economy, the cornerstone of President Clinton's political support,
continued to show considerable resilience.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in the Rose Garden, Clinton said that while
``growth in the second quarter of 1998 was more moderate than the
truly remarkable first quarter, it shows that our economy continues
to enjoy steady growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying that the downturn in growth reflected ``the discernible
effects'' of Asia's crisis, Clinton pressed Japan's new government
to act quickly to deal with its faltering banking system and
invigorate its economy. He also renewed his calls to Congress to
provide new financing to the International Monetary Fund to help
keep the problems in Asia and much of the rest of the developing
world from more deeply wounding the American economy.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown seems unlikely to have any immediate effect on the
Federal Reserve's interest rate policy, economists said. The
central bank's most aggressive inflation fighters will continue to
focus on the combination of low unemployment and strong demand,
while another contingent, including Alan Greenspan, the Fed's
chairman, seems willing to keep rates unchanged as long as there
are no clear signs of broad-based increases in wages and prices.
</P>
<P>
   The second quarter's 1.4 percent growth rate followed six
consecutive quarters in which growth was 3 percent or higher, a
streak that was accompanied by falling unemployment and little or
no inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the slowdown was caused by temporary factors that
are unlikely to persist. Commerce Department economists estimated
that the strike that crippled General Motors subtracted about 1
percentage point from gross domestic product during the second
quarter. Because the strike was not settled until this week, it
will also depress third quarter growth somewhat, but economists
said GM will likely try to make up for lost production, helping to
strengthen growth by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp downturn in exports to Asia and increased competition
from imports took another 2 to 2.5 percentage points off second
quarter growth rates, economists said. Decisions by companies to
reduce production to work off some of the big inventories they had
amassed in the first quarter also reduced growth by around 2
percentage points, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts say the inventory adjustment is now largely
complete, removing one impediment to more robust growth. With the
GM strike settled, the big question remains how much of a drag Asia
will have on exports for the rest of the year, with some economists
saying the worst is past and others saying the deterioration will
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts also think there could be a downturn coming in
consumer demand, which has been fed by the strong stock market, low
unemployment and high levels of consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department report showed that the personal savings
rate plummeted in the second quarter to 0.6 percent from 1.2
percent in the first quarter and 3.5 percent in 1994. Economists at
Chase Securities in New York said in a report on Friday that the
low savings rate could leave many consumers with little financial
cushion if the stock market were to plummet.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's report from the Commerce Department also included
revisions to economic growth statistics for each of the last three
years, showing that growth from 1995 through 1997 was slightly
higher than previously reported. For 1997, growth was revised up to
3.9 percent from 3.8 percent; for 1996, the revision was to 3.4
percent from 2.8 percent, and for 1995 the change was to 2.3
percent from 2.0 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
