<HEADER>
A3032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARTHA-STEWART-STUDIE     07-31 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTHA-STEWART-STUDIES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MARTHA 101, EVEN CLASS ANXIETIES GET IRONED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.)  
 (bl)  
 By MARGALIT FOX   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Martha Stewart a colonialist tool? An American populist? Or
is she merely a flyspeck on the damask tablecloth of history?
</P>
<P>
   No longer simply a taste maker to millions, a successful
entrepreneur or the subject of chronic parody, Martha Stewart has
become a Text.
</P>
<P>
   Like Madonna a decade ago, Ms. Stewart is today a piping hot
offering on the cultural studies smorgasbord. In the last few
years, about two dozen scholars across the United States and Canada
have trained their gaze on the woman often described as the doyenne
of domesticity. Now, in rigorously footnoted pages, descriptions of
lavender-scented linens rub elbows with Foucault, Lacan and
Gramsci. Proposals for at least three books are making the rounds
of academic publishers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's such a wonderful clay to work with,'' said Kyla Wazana,
who recently completed a master's degree in English at the
University of Toronto and is an editor of a planned anthology, ``No
Place Like Home: Cultural Anxiety, Nostalgia and Martha Stewart
Living.'' ``She's open to so many readings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stewart scholars (nearly all women, many of them graduate
students) argue that Ms. Stewart's sheer ubiquity _ her 22 glossy
books on entertaining, gardening and decorating; her magazine,
Martha Stewart Living, with its more than 2 million readers; her
television program; her syndicated newspaper column and daily radio
spot; her Web site; her weekly segment on ``CBS This Morning''; her
line of home furnishings, and her signature catch phrase, ``It's a
good thing'' _ has lodged her in the North American consciousness
too firmly for the academy to ignore. And like taste makers
throughout history, they say, Ms. Stewart is a brilliant mirror of
the longings and anxieties of her age.
</P>
<P>
   Among more traditional academics, the emerging discipline has
provoked predictable dismissals. But the new scholars say that Ms.
Stewart carries more historical weight than meets the eye: a modern
custodian of social norms, she is the latest in a line of
professional household advisers that began with the authors of
women's domestic manuals in the 18th and 19th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known of these early advisers was Mrs. Beeton, whose
book ``Household Management,'' published in England in 1861,
offered such homely advice as ``Menus for a Servants' Hall Dinner
for 12'' and ``How to Select a Wet Nurse.'' In this country,
Catharine Beecher, a sister of Harriet Beecher Stowe, set household
duties within the larger framework of Christian moral obligation,
providing, in ``American Woman's Home'' (1869), chapters on ``Good
Temper in the Housekeeper'' and ``Care of the Homeless, the
Helpless and the Vicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides defining women's roles in terms of domestic virtue,
books like these served a larger social function: they helped
foster a collective identity for the newly emerging middle class,
defining its members as distinct from working people. One
19th-century American manual, for instance, offered suggestions for
teaching servants to read, along with the usual cooking and laundry
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not only advice books for those uninitiated in the
arts of the home, the table and decoration; they're prescriptive
texts about social distance,'' said Ann Laura Stoler, a professor
of anthropology, English and women's studies at the University of
Michigan who has written extensively on domestic manuals. ``They
map out cultural distinctions, but they also mark class, gender
and, very importantly, racial differences.''
</P>
<P>
   If the early taste makers helped construct bourgeois identity,
Ms. Stewart (nee Kostyra), the daughter of lower-middle-class
Polish-American parents, is helping to maintain it in today's
anxious age, where social roles are more ambiguous than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``She represents the parvenu class entering the leisure class,''
said Linda Robertson, a co-director of the media and society
program at Hobart and William Smith Colleges and the editor of
another proposed anthology on Ms. Stewart. ``She's teaching people
who have a desire to emulate or to enter a particular class, not
people who are already confident of their status in that class.''
</P>
<P>
   But just how to interpret Ms. Stewart's cultural prescriptions
is open to vigorous debate. In the introductory essay to their
anthology, ``Martha Stewart's Living: History, Fragmentation and
Late Capitalism's (A)esthetician,'' Ms. Wazana and her co-editor,
Zoe Newman, explore parallels between Ms. Stewart's work and the
psychology of colonialism. Through repeated rituals that center on
cleanliness, nostalgia and setting boundaries, they argue, both Ms.
Stewart and colonialists strive to create a safe haven in a hostile
world, demarcating the imperial ``us'' from the menacing ``other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You leave Mother England and you go into the bush and you try
to carve out a place that reflects upper-class English
sensibilities,'' said Ms. Newman, a graduate student in sociology
at the University of Toronto. ``You eat your picnic off china and
crystal in the middle of the desert.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A similar ethos is at work in Ms. Stewart's advice, which holds
out the promise of security through grace, beauty and meticulous
order. An essay in the Newman-Wazana anthology, ``A Look at Linen
Closets: Liminality, Structure and Anti-Structure in Martha Stewart
Living,'' examines Ms. Stewart's rage for organization as
represented in an instructional article in her magazine on
arranging sheets and towels. The author, Ashley Prentice Anderson,
argues that linens are fraught with messy, primitive associations,
which trigger in Ms. Stewart _ and in everyone else _ an urgent
need for control. ``You're born on a sheet and you die on a
sheet,'' said Ms. Anderson, a graduate student in English at New
York University.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Newman also cited recurrent images of fences, hedges and
garden walls as well as an article in the magazine on organizing
basements that portrayed the nether region of the house as a place
of foreboding and disorder. ``I connect that to a need to regulate,
a fear of transgression and the need for clear boundaries,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   By imposing such boundaries, these scholars say, Ms. Stewart
serves to stem unease about race, class and sexuality. ``It's
people of color, it's working-class people'' who are being put at a
distance, said Ms. Newman, who stressed that she was not accusing
the literal, flesh-and-blood Ms. Stewart of racism but rather
examining her work as a symptom of the larger culture.
</P>
<P>
   Other scholars see Ms. Stewart's role as more benign. To Lynda
Goldstein and Virginia Smith, the authors of a planned book,
``Reading Martha Stewart: It's a Good Thing,'' their subject
upholds a tradition of American self-reliance that harks back to
Jefferson and Franklin. ``One of the ways in this country that we
have defined class for 150 years is, `Who does their own
housework?,''' said Ms. Smith, a lecturer in American studies and
English at the Pennsylvania State University.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stewart does, at least in her public incarnation. Although
viewed as purveying the blue-blood good life, she does not disdain
manual labor, these scholars observe. In a given week she might be
seen on television gathering eggs from her henhouse, mucking around
in a compost heap or banging together a trellis. As a result, Ms.
Smith said, her social role is more complex than it first appears.
``There's a real working-class background and a real manual
dexterity that she's not afraid to weave into her clearly
upper-class presentation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And under Ms. Stewart, the sexual politics of domestic
instruction have been markedly altered, Ms. Robertson said. ``I
don't think she's building her advice about bourgeois taste around
issues of family, or around a woman's role within patriarchy,'' she
said. Instead, she noted, Ms. Stewart focuses on the esthetics of
objects.
</P>
<P>
   There is one point, however, on which Ms. Stewart's diverse
analysts agree: they would never have undertaken their subject if
it weren't also a labor of love. ``We're interacting with her as
consumers as well as critically,'' Ms. Wazana said. ``I made her
avocado soup last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart scholars have already weathered their share of ribbing
in the intellectual press, and a proposal by Ms. Newman and Ms.
Wazana for a special session on Ms. Stewart at the Modern Language
Association's year-end convention was recently turned down. ``It
wasn't well enough focused,'' Phyllis Franklin, the executive
director of the MLA, said in a recent interview. ``There was some
question about what you would learn from it.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least one person thinks Martha Stewart scholarship is a
good thing. ``I sighed a little sigh of relief that finally
someone, maybe in a kind of overreaction, was taking me a little
seriously,'' Ms. Stewart said recently when asked how it felt to
become an academic discipline. ``Because I fancy myself closer to
that kind of study than to a parody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
