<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3035 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMS-VINEYARD-BOS &LR;      07-31 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-VINEYARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS HOST BIG FUND-RAISING EVENT ON MARTHA'S VINEYARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It sounds like a dream weekend on Martha's
Vineyard: horseback riding, sailing, golfing, dining, tennis, and
an ``after-hours'' party at the Hot Tin Roof.
</P>
<P>
   But this is business as usual for Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   One year after Democratic senators hob-nobbed with senators at a
controversial Nantucket fund-raiser in the midst of the campaign
finance scandal, only the location has changed. About 100 corporate
representatives and other donors are gathering this weekend on
Martha's Vineyard with perhaps a dozen senators, including John F.
Kerry and Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts, in what has become
one of the sought-after and secretive fund-raising events of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Amidst the fun, there are briefings scheduled on politics and
other legislative matters _ though not on the agenda is campaign
finance reform, which died in the Senate this spring though a bill
remains alive in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party officials said the senators were slated to
arrive on the island like most tourists, aboard commercial
aircraft. But party documents obtained by The Globe said that
numerous senators and their families were scheduled to fly aboard
corporate jets supplied by Federal Express, drug company Eli Lilly
and the AFLAC insurance firm _ three companies that have plenty of
business before the US Senate.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Kennedy, one of the Senate leaders on health care
insurance, flew aboard AFLAC's Falcon 50 jet, an aide confirmed.
Robb flew aboard a Gulf Stream II jet supplied by Eli Lilly, a
spokesman said. The Democratic Party reimbursed the companies only
for the equivalent of a first-class commercial ticket, far below
the value of a private flight from Washington. When Democratic
senators last year headed to Nantucket for a nearly identical
event, Kerry actively participated but called it a ``sick'' example
of selling access. But that did not dissuade Kerry from
participating once again this year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of meeting at Nantucket's White Elephant Resort, the
Democrats are taking over the Harbor View Hotel in Martha's
Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats aren't the only ones to put on such exclusive events,
of course. Republicans regularly put on similar extravaganzas. But
for the Democrats, the venue of choice has become a mid-summer
weekend on Nantucket or Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   The public is not invited, unless they happen to be one of a
select group who has given $20,000 a year to the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee. The 100 or so donors, whose names
have not been released, are expected to pay a $5,000 installment
while attending the session.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no public announcement of the event. But several
aides said that senators were heading directly from the funeral of
slain US Capitol Police officer Jacob Chestnut to go to the
Martha's Vineyard bash.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's event on Nantucket drew about 200 people who had
given $20,000 each to the DSCC, making it worth $4 million.
Although Kerry helped organize the event and invited donors to his
Nantucket home, he said, ``I think it is sick. Do people get
access? Yes, and I think it is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry's comments were not well-received by other senators, some
of whom felt he was being hypocritical for helping to arrange the
event and then criticizing it. Kerry did not return a call Friday
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Tucker, a spokesman for the DSCC, said that about a
dozen senators are expected to attend. Aside from Kerry, the
senators include DSCC chairman Robert Kerrey of Nebraska, Senator
Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, Senator Frank Lautenberg, Senator
Mary Landrieu of Washington, Senator Chuck Robb of Virginia and
Senator Barbara Boxer. All advocate some form of campaign finance
reform. Other senators are also expected to attend, as well as some
Democratic candidates for the US Senate.
</P>
<P>
   While political fund-raisers are held practically every day in
Washington and around the country, the Martha's Vineyard event is
extraordinary because it provides so much ``face time'' between
senators and donors. They have two to three days together in a
relaxed, social environment, a far cry from the typical Washington
fund-raiser where donors often can do little more than exchange
pleasantries and sit through speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this entry on the Martha's Vineyard schedule, which
advises senators to leave behind their wing-tip shoes: ``Sailing.
Launches will leave the dock...for sailing at 1 p.m. sharp. A
reminder that shoes are not allowed on the deck of these sail
boats.'' As for the late-night party at the Hot Tin Roof, the
schedule notes that ``the final bus will depart at 12:30 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   The schedule also calls for some senators to give briefings to
the donors on various issues, including the status of Senate races.
``DSCC vice chairman Senator Bob Torricelli will provide a
political overview and briefing to our guests,'' the schedule says.
</P>
<P>
   While the senators enjoy the Vineyard, President Clinton will be
just down the coast, at the Hamptons _ holding a fund-raiser, of
course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
