<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-CHESTNUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND CAPITOL SHOOTING VICTIM IS BURIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. _ Almost one week to the hour after a gunman
stormed into the US Capitol, killing two guards and wounding a
tourist, police officer Jacob J. Chestnut was buried Friday with
full military honors at Arlington National Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   With 4,000 mourners filling every seat in a suburban Maryland
church, Chestnut's daughter, Karen _ one of his five children _
described her father as a private hero before he became a public
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before he was this hero of democracy, before a (Capitol
Building) door was named after him, before he was the first African
American to be lain in state, before he was mourned all over the
world, he was neighbor, friend, husband, and to me, he was Daddy,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Chestnut, in his eulogy, said his older brother ``had a
way of bringing people together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They call him a hero here _ he's always been my hero,'' he
said. ``I'm 50 years old, and he's always been a role model.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, thousands of police officers from
around the country attended a funeral for a slain Capitol Police
guard. Detective John Michael Gibson, 42, a Waltham, Mass. native,
was buried Thursday at Arlington National Cemetery. And in a repeat
Friday, a miles-long funeral procession crept toward the cemetery,
winding past the Capitol, with police cruisers and motorcycles
displaying American flags and blue ribbons from their antennas.
</P>
<P>
   As with Gibson's funeral on Thursday, spectators lined the route
in silent tribute.
</P>
<P>
   At the Capitol, dozens of staff members and police remembered
Chestnut and Gibson with 13 seconds of silence at about 3:35 p.m.,
to remember the length of time the shooting lasted a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   After an honor guard fired shots in salute and two buglers
started playing ``Taps,'' Chestnut's widow, Wen-Ling, began to cry.
Capitol Police Chief Gary Albrecht held her hands and tried to
comfort her as he gave her the folded flag that had been draped
over husband's casket.
</P>
<P>
   In a show of support, the Gibson family attended Friday's
funeral, and Chestnut's family had attended Thursday's services.
Friday, Gibson's wife, Evelyn, embraced Chestnut's widow after the
ceremony, and they cried together.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut, 58, who retired from the Air Force after 20 years and
spent 18 years with the Capitol Police, was buried beneath a cherry
tree in a section the cemetery once known as Freedmen's Village, a
settlement in which freed slaves lived after the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators building a case against the man charged with the
attack, Russell E. Weston Jr., say a security camera captured the
scene of Chestnut's killing near the Document Room door on the East
side of the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The tape shows the attacker's left hand, gun drawn, and then
Chestnut, who was talking to a tourist, crumbling to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The killer, his face hidden by a wide-brimmed hat, then walks
through the metal detector Chestnut manned, and shifts his gun to
his right hand. After a few steps, his body recoils, as if he shot
or was shot at, before the attacker runs out of the picture behind
a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson was mortally wounded in a gunfight just down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Weston, who also was wounded by gunfire, remains hospitalized.
He is charged with killing federal officers, which could result in
the death penalty upon conviction. Weston's family said he has been
diagnosed as a paranoid schizophrenic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
