A3041 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-SMALLCAPS-ART     07-31 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-SMALLCAPS-ART-$ADV02-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE SMALL-CAP STOCKS READY FOR A RALLY? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Kan., N.C., Ariz., Mass., Ill.)  (ART ADV: Graphic showing Russell 20000 vs. the S&AMP;P 500 will be
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2)  
 (af)  
 By ANNE TERGESEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as baseball fans often look at a batter who is in a slump
and say, ``He's due,'' many analysts who follow
small-capitalization stocks are saying they are ready to rise.
</P>
<P>
   The bull market has largely been a blue-chip phenomenon, with
stocks of small companies _ those with market values of less than
$1 billion _ sometimes languishing far behind.
</P>
<P>
   And since late April, the gap between large and small has become
a gulf: The Standard and Poor's 500-stock index of big-company
stocks has fallen by less than 1 percent, while the Russell 2000
index of small-company stocks has fallen 14.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts say, a long-term investor with a stomach for the
gyrations of small-cap stocks may find that now is a good time to
think small. They argue that once the impact of Asia's financial
crisis on American corporate earnings becomes clearer _ Abby Joseph
Cohen, the Goldman, Sachs market guru, said she expected that to
happen in ``the next few months'' _ the stage will be set for small
caps to outperform their larger peers, which are more exposed to
foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   Since the second quarter of 1997, small companies on average
have posted superior earnings gains, and that trend is expected to
continue at least for the rest of the year, according to First
Call, which tracks earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   And small caps are cheaper relative to large stocks than they
have been since the market downturn of 1990, said Satya Pradhuman,
director of small-cap research at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   L. Keith Mullins, equity strategist at Salomon Smith Barney,
said, ``I would buy some now, because small caps are very difficult
to buy when the tide turns.'' Indeed, with trading volumes slim,
prices tend to rocket when demand rises.
</P>
<P>
   But before jumping into the market, consider this: Because small
companies are less experienced, less diversified and less analyzed
than blue chips, they are riskier investments. Moreover, limited
liquidity can make it very difficult to pull out, should disaster
strike.
</P>
<P>
   If you can tolerate the risk, should you be looking at for value
or growth stocks in the small-cap arena? Two factors suggest the
former. First, value stocks tend to offer greater protection during
selloffs _ something to worry about, given the market's overall
high valuations and recent volatility.
</P>
<P>
   Second, small-cap value stocks have achieved twice the
cumulative return of their growth-stock counterparts from 1979
through June 30 of this year, according to Frank Russell &AMP; Co., a
financial consulting firm in Tacoma, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Following are some small-cap holdings of 5 of the 10 best
small-cap value managers, ranked according to their funds'
five-year records by Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial
publisher. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A YOUNG REIT: The top-performing fund, Weitz Hickory, is not
restricted to the small-cap market, but the fund's manager, Richard
F. Lawson, says that is where the bargains are these days.
Specifically, Lawson likes Novastar Financial, a real estate
investment trust in Westwood, Kan., that he says has ``two strikes
against it'' because, as a mortgage REIT and a subprime mortgage
lender, it is in two areas now out of favor with investors.
</P>
<P>
   But with an experienced management team as well as more
conservative accounting standards and lower taxes and costs than
rivals, it should be selling for more than its current nine times
1999 earnings estimates of $2.13 a share, Lawson said.
</P>
<P>
   Because Novastar, just one and a half years old, is still in a
start-up phase, costs are likely to fall and earnings are likely to
climb, he said. And what is the fair value of the stock, now at
$16.3125. At least $30, said Lawson, who is so confident that he
has poured 4.1 percent of his fund's assets of more than $300
million into the company, which has a market capitalization of just
$150 million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A COMPUTER'S PICK: One of the top 10 holdings of the Barr
Rosenberg U.S. Small Cap fund is First Citizens Bankshares, a
regional bank in Raleigh, N.C., that is trading at $100.25 a share,
or 16 times trailing 12-month earnings. First Citizens, whose
market capitalization recently reached $1 billion, was picked by
Barr Rosenberg's computer models, which look for small companies
trading for less than they are worth, predict which companies are
likely to post higher-than-expected profits over the year and
reject those on which the market has soured.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the model compiles a portfolio that mimics the
sector weightings and risk profile of the Russell 2000, but with a
lower average price-to-earnings ratio, said Floyd Coleman, the
portfolio manager. The fund, with 730 stocks, closed to new
investors in February. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A CHOICE IN CHIPS: Bob Perkins now has about 15 percent of his
Berger Small Cap Value fund in an unlikely place: semiconductor,
communication and other growth stocks that have fallen so far they
now resemble value-style investments. One pick is Speedfam
International, a maker of semiconductor manufacturing equipment in
Chandler, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which accounts for 2 percent of the fund's $220
million portfolio, is trading at $16.875, or 24 times earnings
estimates for 1999. More important to Perkins, Speedfam offers
various protections: cash on hand equivalent to $9 a share, profits
and a debt-free balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins said that the Asian crisis had beaten down many stocks
in this sector, but that he was confident that the turmoil would
subside. As a result, he expects the company to trade at up to 20
times the $2 a share he thinks it can earn in 2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RIPE FOR GAINS: In contrast, William B. Gerlach, co-manager of
the $1 billion MAS Small Cap Value Portfolio, offers a more classic
value-style investment: Fresh Del Monte Produce, the
banana-and-pineapple distributor. At $18.75, the stock trades at 11
times its consensus earnings estimate for 1998, a multiple lower
than the company's projected average annualized profit growth of 15
percent this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the rival Dole Food trades at 16 times its 1998
earnings estimates. But Dole's earnings expectations have been
lowered, while estimates for Fresh Del Monte have been raised for
both this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   And Gerlach expects further upward revisions in light of Fresh
Del Monte's announcement on July 22, that it had agreed to acquire
the AIT Group, a company that would add other fruits and vegetables
to Fresh Del Monte's product line. Given Dole's price-to-earnings
ratio, Fresh Del Monte is worth about $23, he added. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLEANED AND PRESSED: These days, Peter Larson, manager of the
$320 million Galaxy Small Cap Value fund, is bullish on Unifirst of
Wilmington, Mass., a renter of uniforms for delivery people,
mechanics and others. At $26.1666, the stock trades for about 14
times 1999 earnings estimates, substantially below the multiple of
37 for the industry leader, Cintas.
</P>
<P>
   With forecasts of 15.6 percent earnings growth in 1999, fueled
by small acquisitions, minor price increases and a new, more
efficient distribution center, Unifirst could hit $35 by year-end,
Larson said. Industry consolidation may also help the stock, which
makes up 1.1 percent of Larson's portfolio. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is no guarantee that either these stocks or
small caps in general will take off. Skeptics note that although a
positive climate has existed for small caps for some time, the
market has not yet rallied.
</P>
<P>
   Still, history suggests that patient investors will be rewarded.
According to Ibbotson Associates, the research firm in Chicago,
small caps have earned compound annual returns of 12.7 percent
since 1926, versus 11 percent for S&AMP;P 500 stocks. That may sound
like a minor difference, but over time, it adds up: $1 invested in
big stocks 72 years ago is now worth $1,828; the same investment in
small stocks would have grown to $5,520.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
