</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COYOTE-ATTACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTE THAT ATTACKED BOY HAD FRACTURED LEG, OFFICIAL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND ABBY FUND  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDWICH, Mass. -- The coyote that mauled a three-year old boy
here was not carrying rabies, but an examination of the animal's
body turned up a possibly important clue as to why the rare attack
occurred, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The coyote's right front leg had been fractured and healed some
time ago, most likely when it was very young. Rob Deblinger, the
state's assistant director for wildlife, said it's possible the
coyote was hit by a car and picked up and nursed back to health by
someone. When a coyote is accustomed to being fed by humans, it is
more likely to attack, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, wildlife specialists confirmed that the number of
coyotes in highly populated areas in eastern Massachusetts is
increasing, and that while attacks are rare, people should avoid
any contact with the animals.
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore the dangers, a pack of coyotes attacked a
dog in Swansea Friday while a neighbor looked on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting for the powerball numbers, when I heard an
agonizing yelp,'' said Gina Roberts of Swansea. ``It was horrible,
so I ran to the window, and they were running thru my yard -- it
was a mother coyote and three pups, and Alby (her neighbor's
schnauzer) was in the mouth of one of the pups.
</P>
<P>
   Alby, brutalized and bloodied, survived.
</P>
<P>
   Coyote attacks on pets by coyotes are now common in
Massachusetts, specialists say, and encounters with humans have
become more menacing, though never violent before Wednesday's
attack on three-year-old Daniel Neal, as he played on his backyard
swing set. Neal was rescued by his mother, who kicked and punched
the coyote until it let her son go.
</P>
<P>
   In Hudson, Deblinger said, a young coyote has been bothering a
day-care center, where children often eat lunch outside. When the
coyote shows up, the children rush inside and the coyote jumps the
fence and eats their lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Bellwood of People for Cats, a Falmouth group that
provides shelter for stray cats and helps people find lost cats,
said coyotes have become so prevalent on the Cape and such a danger
to cats that she would be in favor of an extended hunting season or
even a bounty on coyote pelts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds terrible, I know, but it's a means of population
control,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Coyote hunting season this year will run from November 2 to
Febrary 27, 1999, but state officials say few animals are killed
because no one is interested in the meat or the pelt. Officials say
there are between 3,000 to 4,000 coyotes in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of coyotes in Massachusetts _ and particularly
into its eastern and southern regions _ has been a long time
coming. The animals began migrating to westerm Massachusetts from
the north in the 1940s. The first coyotes were spotted in southern
and eastern Massachusetts in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Langlois, a wildlife biologist with the state Division of
Fisheries and Wildlife, said reports of coyote sightings have been
``steadily increasing,'' with some fluctuations, from 81 in 1990 to
137 in 1996. The slight dip last year, to 105, was due to the fact
that the animals are now so common in some places that people have
stopped reporting them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have people, after their third years of seeing coyotes,
who just don't report it anymore,'' Langlois said.
</P>
<P>
   Cape Cod is the most recent place to attract a large coyote
population, as the animals swam the Cape Cod Canal or walked over
ice floes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Chatham officials hired a federal
sharpshooter to kill two coyotes who had supposedly been plaguing
the town's population of endangered piping plovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only place they don't exist yet is Nantucket and the
Vineyard,'' Langlois said. ``Whatever habitat is available to them,
they'll adapt to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Cocca of the Massachusetts Audubon Society in Lincoln
agrees. ``They're in Concord and Lincoln and Weston,'' Cocca said.
``Not in huge numbers, but I'll occasionally get a call.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes are highly adaptable, and can live off compost piles,
trash bins, or scraps of food left for them by people, wildlife
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Deblinger said his office is hampered in dealing with coyote
complaints because a law passed by voters in 1996 bars the use of
leg-hold traps. He said a trap is much more effective in dealing
with a nuisance coyote than trying to shoot it.
</P>
<P>
   ``To try to hunt them down with a gun, you're never at the right
place at the right time,'' he said. ``So we feel very helpless when
it comes to these sitatutions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
