<HEADLINE>
ELECTION VICTORY FOR PRI SEEMS LIKELY IN VERACRUZ STATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDREW DOWNIE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORIBAZA, Mexico _ Mexico's ruling party, a beleaguered giant
weighed down by its reputation for fraud, corruption and lies, now
seems poised to win a huge vote of confidence in one of the
country's largest states Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The election results from Veracruz state, the hothouse of
Mexican politics, are expected to demonstrate why, for all its
troubles, the PRI, as the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party
is known, is still the most powerful political machine in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 4 million potential voters, the Gulf coast state is
the third most populous region in Mexican politics, after Mexico
City and the surrounding state of Mexico. The party that wins the
Veracruz governor's office will gain a key foothold in the race for
the presidency in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a tight national election, Veracruz can be the place where
the result is resolved,'' Sen. Adolfo Aguilar, a leading opposition
politician, said during a recent visit to the state. ``This is
politically the most important election'' of the 10 gubernatorial
contests this year.
</P>
<P>
   The state has traditionally been a stronghold of the PRI, which
has held Mexico's presidency since 1929. But its power has been
challenged here, as it has across Mexico, by the gradual rise of
the right-wing National Action Party and the leftist Democratic
Revolution Party. Between them, the opposition won control of
Mexico's lower house of Congress and the Mexico City mayor's post
last year while taking nearly all of Veracruz's key cities in
municipal elections.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what has happened here in the months since is a classic
illustration of why Mexico's long-ruling party cannot be counted
out of any election.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the PRI is showing signs of reinvigorating itself,
and opponents charge that the party has returned to some of the
tactics that helped it control Mexican politics for decades _
buying votes and monopolizing the media. It has even called on
well-known entertainers to make campaign pitches at concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the PRI found a way to win the Chihuahua state
governor's race last month _ it conducted its first-ever party
primary to select its candidate and capitalized on his popularity _
the party stamped out the internal fighting in Veracruz that
threatened to scuttle its campaign here.
</P>
<P>
   The party is now firmly behind gubernatorial &UR;  &LR; candidate Miguel
Aleman, and polls show that the multimillionaire businessman and
former senator has built a substantial lead over his nearest rival,
the National Action Party's candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Even before securing the nomination, Aleman and his campaign
strategists worked to unify the state party. In one key move, the
Aleman camp persuaded his toughest PRI rival to drop out of the
race, giving him a lucrative job.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, political analysts said, PRI politicians pressured
state authorities to release a former governor, Dante Delgado, from
jail, thereby nullifying any threat posed by the politician and his
followers.
</P>
<P>
   In another astute stroke, Aleman's lieutenants enlisted the help
of one of the PRI's most influential old-guard politicos to back
their boss, a decision that brought many of Aleman's potential
opponents into his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The party activists in the Aleman camp have cast their lot with
one of the most recognized names in Mexico. In selecting Aleman,
66, the PRI chose not only a politician from one of the nation's
best-known families _ the candidate's father became Mexico's first
civilian president in 1946 _ but also a businessman who has made a
huge fortune through his shareholdings with the Televisa media
empire.
</P>
<P>
   But Aleman owes his success to more than just his name and
fortune. He has shown himself capable of turning around an ailing
state party, a rare skill within the PRI and one that has attracted
the attention of national bosses. Now, many experts and politicians
are mentioning Aleman as a possible presidential candidate in the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He denies any interest in running for the nation's top office
but does say that his experience in uniting the state party may be
useful in bringing the fractured national party together behind the
eventual nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's logical to think that if we can do it in 90 days in a
difficult state that we can do it (nationally),'' Aleman said in an
interview in Orizaba, a small town in the shadow of Mexico's
tallest mountain, Pico de Orizaba. ``If I can help the party, then
I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Aleman's and the PRI's determination to win Veracruz is evident
in a campaign that experts and opponents say is rife with dirty
tricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Veracruz, politics works in the same old way it has always
done,'' said Joel Estuvillo, an analyst with the Mexican Institute
of Political Studies. ``The state party simply wants to win, and
they are going to try to use whatever resources or mechanisms at
their disposal to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Mexico has won international praise during the last few
years for making great strides in reducing unfair campaign
practices and electoral fraud, the race here in Veracruz echoes
with shades of classic old-style politics.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in past campaigns, opponents accuse the PRI of buying
rural votes with money and food and of spending way above the legal
limit.
</P>
<P>
   Aleman's opponents have also accused Televisa of showing a bias
toward him. They say the photogenic campaigner receives favorable
coverage on the country's highest rated TV news show, while his
opponents are all but ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Televisa doesn't come to see me,'' complained National
Action's candidate, Luis Pazos. ``Aleman has eight people following
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Aleman denies the charges, he admits that some of
Mexico's best-known entertainers _ all of them under contract to
Televisa _ have given concerts in the state where ``they speak well
of me on stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Emilio Azcarraga Jean, the son of Aleman's late
business partner, Emilio Azcarraga Milmo, and the current head of
Televisa, attended one of Aleman's campaign rallies. Aleman closed
his campaign at a rally and concert attended by thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say those allegations fortify Veracruz's reputation as a
hotbed of politics and show how desperate the PRI is to retain
control of a state that in national elections has historically
provided them with around 10 percent of their total vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veracruz is the most politicized state in Mexico and if Aleman
wins decisively, he is going to be on everyone's short list for the
presidency,'' said George Grayson, author of a guide to this
weekend's election in Veracruz, Aguascalientes and Oaxaca.
</P>
<P>
   ``So this is going to be an election that has national
significance, not only because of Veracruz's size, but more so
because a thumping victory will give impetus to Aleman's
presidential prospects,'' he said. ``Veracruz is an important state
in terms of the number of votes that are delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys play for keeps.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Andrew Downie is a free-lance journalist based in Mexico City who
wrote this for the Houston Chronicle &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3049 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORELAND-COX     07-31 5341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORELAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A CHILD KILLER IN THE FAMILY
 &HT;    By Charlise Lyles,
 &HT;    Wendy Hundley, Lou Grieco
 &HT;    and Rob Modic
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Regina Moreland wanted 10 children, just like her
mother.
</P>
<P>
   She bore only two.
</P>
<P>
   So over the years, she and husband Phillip filled their house
with other kids _ foster, adopted, a developmentally disabled
grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   Regina also opened her arms to a passel of great-nieces and
nephews who visited the Moreland home at 633 Homewood Ave.
</P>
<P>
   A grandmother at age 39, Regina welcomed all as part of her
abundant and complicated extended family tree _ one that may now be
falling under the weight of its own branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children were her whole wide world,'' said Debbie Marshall,
43, one of Regina's sisters.
</P>
<P>
   But between November and June, four children died while sleeping
at the Moreland home _ three grandchildren, and a great-niece, ages
3 and younger. Montgomery County Coroner James H. Davis has ruled
the deaths homicides by suffocation.
</P>
<P>
   A suspect has emerged, but police have not said who it is.
However, family members say police have told them they are focusing
on a child in the Moreland household. It's a revelation that has
split family loyalties between those who want cooperation with
police and those who reject authorities' suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   If authorities build their case against a child, it would be an
unprecedented example of a young serial killer, according to Robert
K. Ressler, a former FBI profiler who started the bureau's
Behavioral Science Unit.
</P>
<P>
   The case has raised grave public concerns and a host of
difficult questions for medical examiners, police, social workers,
juvenile courts and others. Why did so many children die before
authorities ruled the deaths homicides? Could some of the deaths
have been prevented? Could a child have committed the murders? If
so, under what circumstances? How will the justice system respond
if a child is found to have killed?
</P>
<P>
   And will more children die?
</P>
<P>
   This is a story about a tragedy, a murder mystery and a family,
one that is fighting to remain intact in the face of unspeakable
misfortune. A suicide and a car accident have taken two more family
members this year. Children have been removed from their home.
Whatever happens, this broken family portrait will never be whole
again.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Moreland has fiercely defended the children in her house.
Police say Regina has cooperated very little with detectives and
has enlisted her extended family in a battle to discredit police.
She declined to be interviewed for this story and her lawyer,
Anthony VanNoy, was out of town and couldn't be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Them kids is her babies, regardless of whether they are
adopted or not,'' said Debbie Marshall. ``If they (police) want to
insinuate that (a) child did it, Ginie is going to protect that
child with all her heart and soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Another of Regina's sisters, Tracy Marshall, pinched her nose
shut and covered her mouth to demonstrate the way police showed her
how the children had been suffocated. ``We can't go on what the
police believe,'' said Marshall, 34. ``We are family. We need
facts, some kind of solid proof.''
</P>
<P>
   Police are attempting to make a scapegoat of a child because
``the coroner himself doesn't really know what happened,'' said
Regina's mother, Cecile Marshall, 60.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, investigators say their evidence would be
circumstantial and hard to prove. There is also no clear motive,
making the case even tougher, said Dayton Police Lt. John Huber.
</P>
<P>
   Police continue to seek evidence. At the same time, some experts
question whether a child in the Moreland household could have
killed four toddlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have severe doubts about it,'' said Dr. Linda Norton, a
Dallas forensic pathologist who testified in the Waneta Hoyt case,
in which an upstate New York woman was convicted in 1995 of
murdering her five children _ from 1965 to 1971.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a reporter's query, Norton questioned whether a
child could kill without leaving clear signs of trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Kuehnl, a psychologist in Centerville who is often
called upon to assess young defendants in criminal cases, said the
way the victims were killed _ by stealth at night _ does not seem
like the work of a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would suggest willful planning,'' she said. ``Usually
deaths of this nature occur in the throes of family conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Anchored by Regina and husband Phillip, 42, the Moreland
household appeared stable _ a marriage of 22 years, a network of
aunts, uncles and cousins who seem closer than the typical family.
But domestic violence and financial debt were among the family
travails, police and court records show.
</P>
<P>
   Childrens Services had taken a foster child from the home. And
the Moreland's natural children became teen-age parents. Their son,
Kenyatta Moreland, fathered seven children by age 21.
</P>
<P>
   Police are not saying how they arrived at a suspect, though they
have said they had ruled out Regina and Phillip because they were
not present for some of the deaths. Investigators have not
elaborated on where the couple was or who was actually present.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Regina's will to protect her family has slowed
efforts to solve the case.
</P>
<P>
   While one branch of the family tree steadfastly supports Regina,
another branch that she loved and nurtured may have reached the
breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   Her son, Kenyatta, now 23, said he has grown frustrated with his
mother's attitude toward investigators. Two of his children have
died while visiting her home. He said other extended-family members
have the same suspicions as police. ``But they just ain't said it.
Momma don't accept it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mothers of the dead children also expressed frustration
toward Regina. ``She thinks we're all wrong for thinking this,''
said Paullecia Anderson, whose 3-year-daughter was the third child
to die.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Regina has attended the funerals of six family members
since Nov. 10, when the first child died. Her husband killed
himself on March 6. Days later, her natural daughter, Jamila, 19,
was killed in a car accident. ``She has had no time to grieve,''
her former lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   And authorities have removed her three adopted children, and a
biological granddaughter, to separate foster homes.
</P>
<P>
   A custody hearing is scheduled in Montgomery County Juvenile
Court on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A stout woman whose eyes are puffy and ringed with purplish
circles, Regina has railed before television news cameras and
enlisted the NAACP for support in a tireless effort to dispute
police suspicions that a child in her home has killed.
</P>
<P>
   A close-knit family
</P>
<P>
   Regina Moreland began to expand her family shortly after the
Morelands bought the house at 633 Homewood in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Morelands had two children. Kenyatta was born
in 1975 when Regina was 15 and Phillip 18. Three years later,
Jamila was born.
</P>
<P>
   The house on Homewood is in the Five Oaks neighborhood of
renovated homes. Purchased for $26,900, it was nothing fancy, a
1,984-square-foot two-story with four bedrooms, shutters, a
pillared porch and good-sized backyard where children could play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regina only had two kids naturally and she wanted 10 kids,''
said Debbie Marshall. ``We all said we were going to have 10 kids,
like momma.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, the Morelands adopted one child. By 1991,
when Jamila and Kenyatta were teen-agers, the Morelands became
foster parents and began adopting more children. Also, when
Kenyatta fathered a child at 16, the Morelands took in their
granddaughter, who was developmentally disabled and suffered
seizures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social workers would bring kids in the middle of the night
with nothing, and Ginie would take them,'' said Tracy Marshall,
Regina's sister.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the Moreland household totaled eight: three adopted
children, the granddaughter as well as Jamila and Kenyatta, and
mother Regina and father Phillip.
</P>
<P>
   Regina worked as a nurse's aide at Bethany Lutheran Village, a
nursing home. And Phillip worked two jobs: at GM Moraine Truck and
Assembly Division and at USAirways in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   On Sundays, the Morelands went to separate churches. Regina took
the children to Zebulun Missionary Baptist Church, where her clan,
the Marshalls, proudly makes up most of the congregation. Regina's
uncle, the Rev. Willie Marshall, is pastor. Phillip Moreland
worshipped across town at Maranatha Christian Fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil was fun-loving, caring, dedicated. He would do anything.
If you needed something, he'd do it. He was a very religious man,''
said his brother, Ronald Moreland.
</P>
<P>
   Regina routinely visited her sister, who lives nearby. ``Bigger
families seem to be closer,'' said Debbie Marshall, one of Regina's
nine siblings. ``We're real close. That's all we do is go from each
others' houses. We never went out or nothing _ maybe skating,
wrestling, to the movies. We never been partying people.''
</P>
<P>
   In her extended family and her immediate family, Regina is giver
and taskmaster, a sturdy stalk rooted in nurturing soil, her
siblings said.
</P>
<P>
   Through a divorce that left their mother supporting a large
family on a waitress' wages, the sister whom they affectionately
call ``Ginie'' was there.
</P>
<P>
   When father, Robert Marshall, died in 1989 of a heart attack
brought on by acute cocaine intoxication, Ginie was there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were wrong, she flat out told you,'' said her brother,
Otis Marshall, 33. ``Then she would help you out with your problem.
You know what? She was the strongest one in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   When her son Kenyatta's girlfriends were pregnant with nowhere
to go, Regina let them stay at 633 Homewood, the girlfriends said.
On Saturdays, Regina rose early to shop at garage sales for baby
clothes and blankets, they said.
</P>
<P>
   While living in Regina's home, the girlfriends said they
observed a mother in control of her household. The adopted children
were assigned tasks such as hauling laundry to the basement and
helping to care for the developmentally disabled child who still
wore diapers. When chores were executed poorly, Regina instructed
the children to repeat the task. When toddler-aged grandchildren,
great nieces and nephews visited, the adopted children assisted
with care, said mothers of the dead children.
</P>
<P>
   Officials would later say they observed Regina as a loving and
caring mother, attentive to her children and attuned to their
needs. They say the Morelands practiced appropriate discipline and
raised the children to be well-mannered and polite, to say grace
before meals, and to play together harmoniously.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Ginie, known as the family photographer, captured
frame by frame the faces of her family. Each new leaf of the family
tree. Every infant growth spurt. Every new set of front teeth.
``She camcordered everything,'' said Debbie Marshall. And on the
walls of Regina Moreland's house, those portraits chronicle an
intact family _ a smiling husband and wife, a handsome son, a
shyish daughter, plump-cheeked toddlers in ribbons, bows and polka
dots.
</P>
<P>
   But by the mid-1990s, strain within this private family began to
draw the attention of public agencies and authorities, according to
police reports and court documents:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In 1995, 911 dispatchers received at least 24 calls from 633
Homewood. At least two were calls for seizures. Several others were
for various family problems.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In March 1995, police and Children Services workers came to
the house after a 7-year-old foster boy who lived with the
Morelands told his teacher that bruises and a bump on his arm and
forehead were caused by his foster mother and father paddling him
and his foster father hurling him against a wall. Corporal
punishment involving foster children is against Children Services
Board policy. The child was removed from the home.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  By June 1995, Children Services had investigated several
reports of problems in the home and stopped placing foster children
with the Morelands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some concerns about some of the children in the
home and the care they were receiving,'' spokeswoman Ann Stevens
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  That same month, police responded to Phillip Moreland's call
for help to control daughter Jamila, who had begun to run away from
home.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In July 1996, police were called to 633 Homewood again. Regina
Moreland reported that her husband, Phillip, had punched her right
eye and knocked out her front tooth. Phillip pleaded guilty to
misdemeanor domestic violence and was ordered into counseling.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Between November 1994 and April 1996, police were called by
Moreland family members at least seven times for reported vandalism
to family-owned vehicles, a break-in, and a stolen auto.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of this, Regina's family tree continued to branch
out.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1996, daughter Jamila gave birth to Da'Jainae
Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   And son Kenyatta, whose first child was already in Regina's
care, had begun a pattern of fathering children out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1996, the year he turned 21, Kenyatta had fathered
seven children by five different mothers who were between the ages
of 15 and 18 when they began having his children. Some had been
pregnant simultaneously, their children born within weeks of one
another: Imari Arielle Moreland was born March 3, 1993. Kenyatta
Le'Shay Moreland was born April 14, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Father Kenyatta's name appears on four of his children's birth
certificates, but he warmly acknowledges each one as his child.
Some of the mothers chose names that begin with the letter K or
that rhyme with Kenyatta, such as Danatta (pronounced Day-not-ta).
</P>
<P>
   A Belmont High School dropout who is employed off and on,
Kenyatta is unable to provide consistent financial support for his
kids, according to two of the mothers of his children. One of them
said she receives some public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   In Regina's house, portraits of Kenyatta line the living room
walls and shelves, displaying her affection for the wiry son who
grew into a handsome, broad-shouldered man with a penchant for nice
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, no one in the extended family took issue with the
number of children Kenyatta had produced. ``A lot of kids run in
our family,'' said Debbie Marshall, Regina's sister. ``When one
person is pregnant in our family, five are pregnant. Ain't nobody
pregnant by themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   And one of the mothers offered, ``What he does is his business.
I've no feelings about it at all,'' said Paullecia Anderson, 21.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyatta is currently the defendant in three misdemeanor cases:
two for domestic violence and one for criminal damaging. Gina Reid,
25, alleged that he assaulted her on April 28 and May 26, 1997,
according to court files. She obtained two temporary protection
orders against Kenyatta at Dayton Municipal Court. In the criminal
damaging case, Reid alleges that he broke her car windows on Oct.
4, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, there were two warrants active for Kenyatta's
arrest, for failing to show up at municipal court hearings
involving those cases.
</P>
<P>
   The Moreland's household was also under financial stress.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 and 1997, three companies got judgments against the
Morelands totaling $12,360 after they failed to pay off debt,
according to court records. Regina's weekly paycheck was garnisheed
after she failed to make timely payments on a 40-inch color
television and a stereo she bought in 1996. That same year the
Morelands' car was repossessed.
</P>
<P>
   Husband Phillip was known to be prudent, said his brother Ronald
Moreland. ``Phillip hated debt. He hated it.''
</P>
<P>
   Such were the circumstances in Regina Moreland's household when
children began to die.
</P>
<P>
   Deaths called ``highly suspicious''
</P>
<P>
   In November 1997 Jamila, then 19 and a mother, had settled down
from her days as a runaway to raise her child.
</P>
<P>
   Jamila continued to live with her parents at the house on
Homewood. They were busy caring for their three adopted children
and the developmentally disabled grandchild. But they helped Jamila
and sometimes called on the adopted children to assist with the
baby, family members said.
</P>
<P>
   A slender girl who sometimes sucked her thumb, Jamila was
worried about 1-year-old Da'Jainae Phillips. She had been sick, in
and out of the hospital several months with seizures.
</P>
<P>
   The evening of Monday, Nov. 10, Jamila went upstairs to check
one more time on her sleeping daughter.
</P>
<P>
   She was so still, her chest not rising and falling. She was not
breathing. Jamila screamed, ``My baby,'' and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   Regina, a nurse's aide, applied CPR, attempting to revive the
child. Paramedics took her to Children's Medical Center, where she
was pronounced dead.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Moreland told police that encephalitis, an inflammation
of the brain, had sent his granddaughter to the hospital in recent
months. At one point, he said, doctors induced a coma to stop
seizures.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Stevens, spokeswoman for Montgomery County Children
Services, said the
</P>
<P>
   agency had provided some assistance to the family in the summer
of 1997 because of a sick infant, but could not provide any other
details.
</P>
<P>
   The medical examiner did not suspect foul play in the death.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later on Wednesday, Nov. 13, Da'Jainae's 2-year-old
cousin, Alexus Dashanea Marshall, died at the Moreland house on
Homewood during a family gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Shenica Nicole Marshall, had been visiting Aunt
Regina and Uncle Phillip. Ready to leave, Shenica went upstairs and
tugged a coat on her still-sleeping toddler. After leaving the
house, she discovered that the child in her arms was not breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Later, coroner's officials told the family that the toddler was
likely dead before
</P>
<P>
   her mother left the house.
</P>
<P>
   In the Montgomery County Regional Crime Laboratory, medical
examiners puzzled over two small bodies wrapped in swaddling. ``Our
suspicions were there immediately,'' said Ken Betz, director of the
crime lab. ``We never came out and said these are natural deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Betz assigned an investigator to research the medical histories
of the two children, who both had histories of pulmonary problems.
</P>
<P>
   Police dispatched fire department officials to test the house
for carbon-monoxide leaks. They found none. Combined Health
District inspectors searched the house for contamination. They
found piles of clothing and debris, cockroach infestation, a sewage
overflow in the basement that had not been properly cleaned up and
concentrations of lead in dust around windows, said Mike Phillips
of the health district. Though roaches can contribute to asthmatic
conditions in young children, overall the inspection found nothing
that would have caused death by asphyxiation, Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   And medical examiners asked police questions: Who was in the
house at the time? Where were they? What room was Alexus in?
</P>
<P>
   Shenica, like Jamila, the mother of the first baby to die, was a
young mother barely out of her teens. And, like Jamila, she was
nervous about infant illnesses. Three months before Alexus died,
her 4-month-old brother, Joboury, had been hospitalized at
Children's Medical Center for bleeding pneumonia and pulmonary
hemorrhaging.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip and Regina, grandparents and great uncle and aunt to the
two children who had died, believed the deaths were due to natural
causes, pointing to Da'Jainae's hospitalizations.
</P>
<P>
   The Moreland household tried to return to normal.
</P>
<P>
   Low-key and quiet, Phillip Moreland kept his grief and
puzzlement to himself as he read the Bible in his bedroom. He went
back to what he had done for years _ demanding quiet in the
household while he watched The Three Stooges on television _ and
continued to punch the clock on his two jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths had shaken the children who had apparently found some
stability in the Moreland home, family members said.
</P>
<P>
   The children were noticeably sad. The grandchild babbled barely
coherent inquiries about dead cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas was coming.
</P>
<P>
   But gifts under the Moreland tree would go unwrapped. Then, at
8:45 a.m. on Christmas Eve, death snatched a third child.
</P>
<P>
   After spending the night at 633 Homewood, Regina's
granddaughter, 3-year-old Danatta Moreland, was found not
breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Paullecia Anderson, had known about the other
deaths. But those children were younger and sickly. Danatta was
healthy, known for warbling the latest nursery school tune she had
learned, and calling Kenyatta, ``Dada.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said she knew and trusted the Moreland household, where
she said she had lived during one of her pregnancies. Besides, it
was Christmas Eve. And Anderson's two children by Kenyatta Moreland
had not seen Grandma Regina for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to stay and I went ahead and left them there,''
said Anderson of Danatta and her sister, Kenyatta, 5. ``It was a
last-minute thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Danatta was pronounced dead at Grandview Hospital and Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities acted swiftly. Two deaths could be a tragic
coincidence, but three?
</P>
<P>
   ``Three children don't die like this,'' said Betz of the crime
lab. ``Three children in one house is highly unusual _ highly
suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   The coroner's office deferred ruling on the deaths of Da'Jainae
Phillips, 1, on
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 10; Alexus Marshall, 2, on Nov. 13; and Danatta Moreland,
3, on Dec. 24.
</P>
<P>
   A conclusion of homicide
</P>
<P>
   After receiving the medical and toxicology reports on Da' Jainae
and Alexus, the crime lab sought expert input before ruling on the
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need assistance to make rulings and we don't want to do it
in a vacuum,'' said Betz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Healthy children do not die for no reason, he said. ``The
worst thing we can do is come back to the community and say, 'We
don't know.'''
</P>
<P>
   The expert panel included members of the Child Abuse Response
and Evaluation team, prosecutors, police, medical experts _
including a pediatric neuropathologist _ and social service
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what the medical panel studied, Coroner Davis would say
later, is the absence of evidence that could explain how the
children had died. Nothing in heart, lung or brain tissue. Nothing
in toxicology reports. No wounds, no stabs, cuts, broken bones,
bruises or other signs of external or internal trauma, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas pathologist Norton said she doubted a child could kill
the children ``without leaving other signs of blunt trauma on their
bodies. An adult perpetrator can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   She had no problem with Davis' homicide ruling, adding that the
odds were ``astronomical'' that all the children died in the same
household by natural causes.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether there is clear medical evidence that the children
suffocated, Coroner Davis said, ``There are some pathological
findings that are compatible with suffocation and some conclusions
arrived at by (process of ) elimination, but it's a mix of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Betz: ``I don't think we ever went 'Aha! This is a
homicide.' As the medical investigation unveiled itself and the
fact that we had three healthy individuals who died suddenly and
unexpectedly for no medical reasons, the conclusion is it was
homicide.''
</P>
<P>
   But what other clues did the panel of experts study? Did they
zero in on the consistent presence of one or two members of the
household? Did the panel run into difficulty piecing together who
was present when each death occurred, since the Moreland household
appeared to have frequent visitors _ adults and children?
</P>
<P>
   ``We interviewed as many people as we could find _children and
adults _ who were present in all three of the deaths,'' said Betz,
declining to say more about who was in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Social workers provided information about family history that
might give indicators or clues to look at, Betz said.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 18, Davis ruled the deaths of Da'Jainae, Alexus and
Danatta homicides by asphyxiation or suffocation.
</P>
<P>
   Betz said the three deaths could have been ``gentle homicide,''
done while the children were sleeping. There had been no struggling
and no crying out.
</P>
<P>
   Police announced they would focus their investigation on family
members.''We're looking at everybody, including children,'' said
Lt. John Huber.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Moreland said neither she nor her husband was ever
questioned as a suspect in the deaths of the three children.
</P>
<P>
   Medical examiners summoned the Morelands to the downtown crime
lab to explain their conclusions. ``After the third death, we laid
it all out for them and gave them an opinion as to who we thought
was responsible,'' Betz said.
</P>
<P>
   Regina rejected the expert conclusions. No child had been killed
at 633 Homewood, she said. Illnesses and medical problems could
explain the children's deaths: Da'Jainae had had encephalitis.
Alexus had had lung problems. While playing, one of the older
adopted children had run into Danatta the day she died. The family
told reporters the coroner's office yielded to public pressure,
ruling the deaths
</P>
<P>
   homicides because it could not explain them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just totally disregard it,'' said Cecile Marshall, Regina's
mother.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to disregarding Davis' findings, the Morelands have
done much to stifle the investigations into the deaths by not
cooperating, said Huber, noting that victims' families usually are
a source of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other relatives became afraid to talk,'' Huber said. ``It
pretty much puts the investigation into neutral.'' Bad information
has also been a factor. ``We've had to get through a lot of rumors
and innuendo, and that took a lot of time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the third death in December, Children Services moved
quickly to remove the three adopted children and the biological
grandchild from the Moreland household to foster care.
</P>
<P>
   Regina and Phillip protested.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Juvenile Judge Michael Murphy granted Regina's
mother, Cecile Marshall, temporary custody of the children.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Moreland wanted her children back.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they took those kids, they took her whole wide world,''
said Debbie Marshall, Regina's sister.
</P>
<P>
   On March 4, in another hearing before Murphy, the Morelands won
the right to unrestricted visits with the children at Grandmother
Marshall's home. A victory, though a small one. No one had been
charged in the deaths of the children.
</P>
<P>
   And Regina was ready for the battle to regain full custody of
all four children. Kenyatta said at that time his father, Phillip,
expressed some reservations about one of the children returning to
the Moreland household.
</P>
<P>
   Paullecia Anderson said she discussed her daughter's death with
Phillip. He was known to sit quietly in his bedroom reading the
Bible, newspapers or magazines. He told Anderson he had been
reading up on suffocation, she said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   A suicide
</P>
<P>
   March 5 was a happy day for Regina Moreland. With Judge Murphy's
ruling, she again had at least some access to her adopted children
and grandchild. Regina and Jamila spent the night with relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip was alone at the house on Homewood. Regina later told
police she talked to her husband at about 2 a.m. on March 6, all
was as well as could be expected.
</P>
<P>
   When Regina and Jamila returned home later that morning, they
found Phillip Moreland collapsed in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daddy ain't breathing! ... He's on the couch,'' Jamila
cried to a 911 dispatcher.
</P>
<P>
   On the 911 tape, Regina Moreland also can be heard screaming in
the background. Jamila cried: ``My daddy's dead! ... Mama, get my
daddy up, please. I can't move my daddy. I can't move my daddy.''
Finally, she implored the dispatcher: ``Please help me, please help
me!''
</P>
<P>
   By this time the medical examiner's office was familiar with the
Morelands.
</P>
<P>
   When Betz arrived at 633 Homewood, he came upon a sad sight.
Phillip Moreland dead on the couch, a Christmas tree and unopened
gifts nearby, as if the Moreland's lives had been frozen in time
after the death of the third child.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, the coroner ruled Phillip Moreland's death a
suicide. He had overdosed on his wife's antidepressant pills.
</P>
<P>
   Burly, quiet Phillip had been the rod and the staff of his
family. ``He held that family together,'' said Betz of the crime
lab, one of several authorities who praised Phillip's handling of a
mysterious and tragic family affair. Now, even if the adopted
children were allowed to return home, they had no father.
</P>
<P>
   An accident
</P>
<P>
   When her father died, Jamila was still grieving over the death
of her own child, who had been the first to die in the Moreland
household.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamila was in a shell, a living zombie,'' her Aunt Tracy
Marshall recalled. ``She would look at you, but her mind would be
somewhere else, way off.''
</P>
<P>
   A week after her father's death, Jamila was on her way home
after an evening with friends. Driving her father's Mercury Tracer,
she pulled away from a stop sign on Frytown Road at Ohio 4 in
Jefferson Twp. She failed to yield to a pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   The truck hit the left side of the car and both vehicles
careened off the west edge of the road. Jamila was taken to Miami
Valley Hospital, where she was pronounced dead. Two friends in the
car survived. An autopsy report revealed a small amount of
marijuana in her system, but no alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   In the Moreland household, Jamila could be counted on to cheer
everyone up. She would care for the adoptive children while her
mother worked. In one 911 call, Jamila could be heard urging a
child to bring diapers for another child who was suffering a
seizure.
</P>
<P>
   The suicide and accident were reported in newspapers, radio and
on television. All now were chronicling the Moreland's saga of
misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these seemingly unrelated tragedies have taken their
toll on Regina,'' the family's former lawyer, John Rion, told
reporters after Jamila's death. ``She hasn't had time to grieve.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Too much sorrow
</P>
<P>
   After the deaths of her husband and daughter, Regina went back
one day to the house on Homewood and found herself unable to enter.
Too much sorrow was there. She moved to 4841 Marburn Ave. in
Trotwood with her mother, who had custody of Regina's three adopted
children and a grandchild. Soon after, she moved across the street
from her mother.
</P>
<P>
   The court had granted Regina unrestricted rights to visit the
children at her mother's. But on a hot summer night in June,
several children stayed at Regina's to sleep in the air
conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Her son, Kenyatta, was on good terms again with Gina Reid, the
mother of two of his children. With 2-year-old Kelab in tow, she
came to the house late to return a car Kenyatta had lent to her.
</P>
<P>
   She had not planned to stay, she would say later. But Reid fell
asleep in a living room chair. Kelab slept nearby on the floor,
Reid said. At about 3 a.m. she woke up. She glanced over at Kelab,
then touched him.
</P>
<P>
   He had turned blue.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Children's Services clashed with Juvenile
Judge Murphy over whether the Moreland's adopted children should be
removed. Children Services argued they should be placed in foster
care. Murphy countered that they were much older than the children
who had died and therefore not likely to be victims. This time,
Murphy ordered the children into foster care pending a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Just days after the death of a fourth child in her home, Regina
attended a large NAACP protest against an alleged incident of
police brutality at a local restaurant. Before television cameras
she railed against detectives. They had mistreated her family, she
said. And they were trying to blame the deaths on a child.
</P>
<P>
   At his funeral at the Bibleway Christian Church, Baby Kelab, in
a small, white ruffled coffin stuffed with teddy bears and toys,
looked as if he had fallen happily to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   In sweltering midday heat, a procession of young mothers and
children filed past his casket to say goodbye. Children who had
played with the dimpled boy wailed until adults, unable to bear
their gri
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
