<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3056 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-275&AMP;     07-31 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-275&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE CAMPAIGN FUNDING BILL SURVIVES KILLER AMENDMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., Ariz., Ky., Tenn., Mich.)   (bl)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A steady majority of the House voted repeatedly
Friday to shield a bipartisan campaign finance bill from a final
onslaught of amendments, making it all but certain that the measure
will win final House passage next week.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the long, contentious debate over how to regulate
campaign fund raising now predict that the bill sponsored by Reps.
Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Martin Meehan, D-Mass., has enough
support to emerge the winner from a byzantine voting process that
pit their proposal against 11 competing campaign finance plans and
numerous amendment attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout weeks of grueling night debate, Shays and Meehan have
regularly commanded the support of from 36 to 84 Republicans
despite intense opposition by GOP leaders. The vast majority of
Democrats also back the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The Shays-Meehan bill would effectively ban the unlimited and
unregulated contributions to the political parties _ or soft money
_ which were at the heart of the 1996 campaign abuses. The bill
would also curb issue advocacy commercials by outside groups in
periods before an election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We crossed the minefield,'' Shays said Friday, after holding
off the last of the amendments that he said could have fractured
his coalition. ``We can see the promised land. We're not quite
there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Linder, the chairman of the House Republicans'
re-election effort, who staunchly opposes the bill, conceded that
the defeat of amendment after amendment showed support for
Shays-Meehan ``looking pretty robust.'' But he said the Senate
would kill the legislation. ``I don't think the Senate will bring
it up,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., the leading Senate foe of the bill,
said: ``You're more likely to see Elvis again than to see this bill
pass the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the lead sponsor of the
companion bill in the Senate, sounded doubtful that he would seek
to consider the issue again this year unless he could find the
eight additional votes needed to cut off a filibuster. His own bill
died in the Senate in February when a majority voted for it but
fell short of breaking a filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders and most rank-and-file Republicans have
fiercely resisted the campaign finance overhaul. They argue that it
unconstitutionally abridges free speech and that it would weaken
the political parties by pushing donors to turn to independent
advocacy groups as they looked for a way around the ban on soft
money. The Republicans have also traditionally raised more money
than the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure that the House would not put pressure on the
Senate, House Republican leaders stalled the final vote on the
Shays-Meehan bill until next week, when the Senate will already be
on its August recess.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the House, the effort to cut back on money in politics
still faces a few final hurdles. To make it to final passage, the
measure must not just win a majority vote, it must command more
support than nine other competing proposals still standing.
</P>
<P>
   If the Shays-Meehan bill wins a large majority when it is taken
up for a vote Monday night, some of the remaining proposals are
expected to be withdrawn. But the Republican leaders could still
try to assemble a larger majority behind another measure drafted by
a bipartisan group of freshman which has less stringent
restrictions on use of soft money by state parties. Meehan, however
said flatly that they would not have enough votes to trump his own
bill.
</P>
<P>
   With the House set to begin its August recess next Friday
afternoon, it also remains unclear precisely when the final vote on
the issue will be taken. Under questioning on the House floor,
Majority Leader Dick Armey said, ``I don't know how, but we will
have this completed before we leave town.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the bill's supporters were still wary about the lack of
a firm schedule. ``I'm concerned about delay,'' said Rep. Zach
Wamp, R-Tenn. ``I've just grown too cynical through this entire
process _ maybe I shouldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally House Republican leaders tried to dispense with the
campaign finance issue by holding a debate but never allowing the
Shays-Meehan bill to come to the floor for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   When that backfired politically, they switched gears and allowed
perhaps the fullest debate the House has seen on any issue. Debate
began May 22 and has taken place intermittently ever since, usually
in the post prime-time hours of the night. The opponents admitted
that they were trying to run out the clock or else attach
amendments to the bill that would drive away supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Among the amendments defeated Friday were several designed to
push Hispanic and black Democrats away from the Shays-Meehan bill.
One proposal, defeated 261-142, would have prohibited the use of
bilingual voting materials.
</P>
<P>
   Another, defeated 253-160, would have required candidates to
raise at least 50 percent of their contributions within their home
states. Democrats get more of their money from political action
committees than Republicans do, and this change would have made it
harder for them to rely on PACs.
</P>
<P>
   Other measures that were turned back would have tripled the
current limit on how much individuals can donate to candidates,
altered the restriction on issue advertising contained in the bill,
and made it illegal for any individual to collect contributions
from a number of people and turn them over collectively, a practice
known as ``bundling'' that has been conducted with notable
efficiency by Emily's List, a group that promotes the candidacies
of women Democrats who favor abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   A few amendments did pass with the support of Shays and Meehan,
including one that would soften an amendment that passed earlier
this month to ban contributions by non-citizens who are legal
residents of the United States. The amendment approved Friday would
allow resident aliens serving in the armed forces to make campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've thwarted every poison pill,'' said Rep. Sander Levin,
D-Mich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
