<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3057 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-757300-SPI &LR;      07-31 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-757300-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING PREPARES FOR 1ST FLIGHT OF LONGEST NARROW-BODY COMMERICAL
PLANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. Friday chalked up two more orders for
its new 757-300 as the company prepared for the first flight Sunday
of the world's longest narrow-body commercial airplane.
</P>
<P>
   That maiden flight will be broadcast live on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the first live Internet broadcast of the
inaugural flight of a Boeing airplane,'' said Margaret Nomi, deputy
program manager of the 757-300 program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our 757-300 customers, our suppliers, Boeing employees and
airplane buffs everywhere will be able to watch as it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The jet is to take off from Renton Field to the north over Lake
Washington about 10 a.m., though the time could be pushed back by
adverse weather or last-minute technical glitches. The plane will
fly for about three hours, testing various flight systems, before
landing at Boeing Field, where Boeing President Harry Stonecipher
will greet the two pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want to watch the event live on the Internet will need
to go to Boeing's Web site at http://www.boeing.com. Viewing
instructions will be posted. To view the Internet broadcast,
computer users will need the RealPlayer plug-in installed on their
browser. Those who do not have the software on their computer can
download it free from Boeing's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has set up a hotline to offer up-to-date information
about the flight. The number is 425-234-4083.
</P>
<P>
   The 757-300 is a derivative of the 757-200, which first flew
Feb. 19, 1982. The development project was launched in September
1996 with an order from Condor Flugdienst, a German charter
carrier. The new model is 178.7 feet long, about 23 feet longer
than the 757-200. The extra length allows it to carry about 20
percent more passengers. It is the longest single-aisle commercial
airplane ever built. Twin-aisle widebody jets built by Boeing and
Airbus are longer.
</P>
<P>
   The 757-300 typically seats about 289 passengers and will be
cheaper to operate than the 757-200, Boeing says.
</P>
<P>
   So far, airlines have placed 17 orders for the new plane,
including two Friday from Arkia Israeli Airlines, based in Tel
Aviv. It also took options for two more planes, making the order
worth about $250 million. The list price of the 757-300 ranges from
$68 to $75 million, though customers typically receive big
discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Arkia is the largest charter operator in Israel, and through its
leasing subsidiary owns a fleet of 23 Boeing airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The capabilities offered in the 757s fit directly into our
plan of expanding our borders and offering more international
charter flights,'' said Arkia President and Chief Executive Officer
Israel Borovich. ``The new airplanes will offer our passengers a
new level of service and comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Powered by Rolls-Royce engines, the first airplane is scheduled
for delivery to Arkia in the first quarter of 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
