<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3060 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION     07-31 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VOWS TO TESTIFY `TRUTHFULLY' ABOUT RELATIONSHIP WITH
LEWINSKY  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton promised Friday to testify
``completely and truthfully'' about his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, saying he is eager to put behind him the grand jury
investigation into their alleged affair and cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting publicly for the first time about the Aug. 17
testimony his lawyers tried to avoid, the president said he is
``looking forward'' to the session with independent counsel Kenneth
Starr's prosecutors. The grand jury will be able to watch the
confrontation and ask questions via a closed-circuit television
link.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to get this matter behind us more than I do,
except maybe all the rest of the American people,'' Clinton said.
``I am looking forward to the opportunity, in the next few days, of
testifying. I will do so completely and truthfully.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's agreement to appear before grand jurors did not
quiet his opponents on Capitol Hill, but there was a general
consensus that even a scathing report from Starr would not trigger
impeachment hearings until after the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks about his upcoming testimony came during a
brief Rose Garden appearance, a session carefully staged to allow
him to exit without having to answer questions shouted by
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating the flurry, Clinton held up his hands to the
cacophony. ``Wait, wait, wait, wait! Everybody's got a question.
Let me give you the answer to all of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was ``anxious'' to meet with prosecutors, Clinton made
his vow to tell the truth and finished by saying: ``I hope you can
understand why in the interim I can and should have no further
comment on these matters. Thank you very much.''
</P>
<P>
   The president then walked back to his office as reporters again
shouted questions about reports of DNA testing on Lewinsky's dress
and whether he stands by his earlier denials of a sexual
relationship with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Later, White House aides insisted the president has no plans to
alter his sworn testimony in Paula Jones' sexual harassment
lawsuit, in which he denied any sexual contact with Lewinsky.
Regarding the allegation that he engaged in a cover-up, aides said
Clinton also will be standing by his public denial of ever urging
anyone to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Until Clinton is put under oath by Starr and his deputies Aug.
17, presidential aides said little more about the scandal would be
coming from the White House. ``There's not much on this matter in
the next 10 days or two weeks,'' said White House spokesman Mike
McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said the president already has met with his private
attorney, David Kendall, and they have begun ``mapping out the
quantity and time'' they will need to prepare for the session in
which he will be linked to the grand jury room by closed-circuit
television. While Clinton, who will have his lawyers present, and
prosecutors will be at the White House, the television link will
allow grand jurors to ask their own questions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Tuesday agreed to testify, but only after he had been
served with a subpoena,.
</P>
<P>
   That announcement came a day after Lewinsky struck a deal with
Starr to avoid prosecution in exchange for telling the grand jury
that she and Clinton engaged in sex and discussed ways to keep
their relationship secret.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster that account _ which contradicts her sworn statement
in the Jones' case and Clinton's statements so far _ Lewinsky on
Tuesday delivered to prosecutors a blue cocktail dress that she
reportedly wore during a White House tryst with the president. The
dress was undergoing DNA testing by the FBI, which on Friday
reportedly found a discernible stain on the garment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, opinion surveys this week found that while two-thirds
of Americans still approve of Clinton's performance as president, a
growing number of people believe he is lying when he denies having
a sexual affair with Lewinsky. In January, half did not believe the
president engaged in sex with the former intern. This week,
two-thirds do not believe the president's denials.
</P>
<P>
   And when Lewinsky's word is pitted against the president's, more
people believe her, according to a Fox News poll conducted
Wednesday and Thursday. The survey of 899 registered voters found
42 percent siding with Lewinsky if she says they had sex, and 31
percent willing to believe Clinton if he denies the affair.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a CNN/Time Magazine survey found 69 percent of
Americans willing to call an end to the matter if Clinton
acknowledges having sex with Lewinsky and discussing ways to keep
their affair secret. Fifty-two percent of the Republicans surveyed
by CNN/Time agreed that acknowledgment of wrongdoing by Clinton
should bring a close to the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, one Republican senator with White House
ambitions _ John Ashcroft of Missouri _ announced plans to hold
hearings on whether presidents can be subpoenaed, indicted and
prosecuted for violating the law.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech on the Senate floor, Ashcroft said perjury by the
president in the Jones case is ``clearly offensive to the
Constitution and constitutes an impeachable offense.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, members of the House Judiciary Committee _ the
panel that would hold impeachment hearings _ signaled that they
would not begin work until after the November elections even if
Starr delivers a report in the next few weeks outlining alleged
crimes against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa., who has no election challenge, said he
would be willing to begin studying a report and brief other
lawmakers, but said, ``The real analysis and review would not be
done until after the election.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready for any eventuality,'' said Judiciary Committee
Chairman Henry J. Hyde, R-Ill., whose panel will handle the report
and has already hired extra staff to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Starr announced Friday that he is taking an unpaid
leave of absence from his law firm _ the Washington office of
Chicago-based Kirkland &AMP; Ellis _ to devote his energies to
completing his investigation of the Clinton administration
</P>
<P>
   Starr has been criticized by Democrats for drawing about $1
million in legal fees from private clients while overseeing the
investigation _ which is near the end of its fourth year _ of
Clinton's business dealings in Arkansas, the misuse of FBI files by
White House aides, the death of deputy White House counsel Vince
Foster, and the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
