u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABC-PRESIDENT-360&AMP;ADD     07-31 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABC-PRESIDENT-360&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ABC PRESIDENT WILL BE HIGHEST-RANKING WOMAN IN THE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ABC has named Patricia Fili-Krushel, the president of
the network's daytime division, to the position of president of the
ABC Television Network, and increased the duties of that position
to include oversight of ABC's news and entertainment divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The job will make Mrs. Fili-Krushel, 44, the highest-ranking
woman executive in the television business.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Iger, the president of ABC Inc., announced the
appointment Friday, citing Mrs. Fili-Krushel's background in both
the programming and business sides of the television industry.
</P>
<P>
   She will succeed Preston Padden, who left as ABC president to
take a position as the chief lobbyist in Washington for ABC's
parent, Walt Disney &UR;  &LR; Co. Under Padden, the job of president of the
ABC network was narrowed to include mainly the ABC sales and
affiliate relations divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Those responsibilities will remain under Mrs. Fili-Krushel, but
the heads of ABC's news and entertainment divisions, David Westin
and Stuart Bloomberg, will now also report to her. That had been
the structure at ABC before Padden's appointment.
</P>
<P>
   As president of ABC's daytime division, Mrs. Fili-Krushel helped
the network maintain the leading position among female viewers
between 18 and 49 _ the most important audience for daytime
advertisers. She also introduced the program ``The View,'' with
Barbara Walters, one of the few successful new daytime shows in
recent years. Previously, Mrs. Fili-Krushel had been group vice
president of the Lifetime cable channel, where she introduced such
original series as ``The Life and Times of Molly Dodd,'' as well as
original movies.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Fili-Krushel, however, played down the significance of her
status as the highest-ranking women executive in television in an
interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that at the Lifetime cable network, where she worked
five years, she participated in that network's switch to an
all-women's programming format.
</P>
<P>
   ``I obviously became sensitive to women's issues while I was at
Lifetime,'' she said. ``And I understand there's a responsibility
to be a certain role model for women in a job like this.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the last year, two high-ranking women executives, Kay
Koplovitz, the chairwoman and chief executive of the cable
television company USA Networks &UR;  &LR; Inc., and Geraldine Laybourne,
president of cable television operations for Walt Disney and ABC,
both stepped down from their posts.
</P>
<P>
   Before arriving at Lifetime, Mrs. Fili-Krushel worked at Time
Warner's HBO, where she was a vice president for business affairs
and production.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thrilled that Bob chose to make this a bigger job,'' she
said. ``Programming is what I've done the most and what excites me
the most, but I feel I know both the programming and business sides
and can handle them equally well. I like the combination in this
new job.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Fili-Krushel said ``there are a lot of challenges ahead,''
citing the problems every broadcast network has faced in recent
years just being profitable. ``When you look at the 10 most
profitable networks and see only one of them, NBC, is a broadcast
network, you have to recognize the difficult time this is for
broadcasters. I had experience on the cable side at Lifetime so I
know how effective the economics are there with a dual revenue
stream.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the other big problems Mrs. Fili-Krushel will face in her
new position is dealing with ABC's affiliated stations. The network
has been in tough negotiations with the stations over a proposed
plan to help ABC defray the costs of NFL football games.
</P>
<P>
   A main focus of opposition by the affiliates has been an
experiment ABC is conducting, rerunning several of its daytime soap
operas on cable channels in three test markets around the country.
Mrs. Fili-Krushel has been in charge of that test and acknowledged,
``It's a big bone of contention with affiliates that has to be
worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   She also acknowledged that she had no experience on the news
side of the network business and would give Westin ``compete
autonomy'' in that area.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Fili-Krushel is part of cross-network marriage. Her
husband, Kenneth Krushel, is a senior vice president in charge of
strategic development for NBC, a unit of General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten used to not talking about proprietary things at
home,'' Mrs. Fili-Krushel said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
