<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE EARNINGS, HURT BY ASIA CRISIS, DEPRESS SHARES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Share prices dropped sharply Friday, more than
erasing big gains from the prior day, in a sign that investors
remain troubled by unimpressive corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   After having largely dismissed the Asian economic crisis,
investors are finally awakening to the effects of a slowdown in the
Pacific region, Wall Street analysts say. That slowdown may
diminish the growth in corporate profits at home, and thereby
stifle stocks for the remainder of 1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This prospect has caused several weeks of fluctuating
expectations and volatile trading, pulling the major stock indexes
down from all-time highs set earlier this summer. Many
smaller-company stocks, which have been battered for months, are in
negative territory for the year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This ain't pretty,'' Robert Dickey, a technical analyst at
Dain Rauscher in Minneapolis, said. ``We've been in a correction
since April, but the big blue chips are finally joining the rest of
the market, which has been crumbling for weeks.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 143.66 points, or
1.59 percent, to close at 8,883.29. The sharp drop came a day after
the Dow rallied 111.99 points, or 1.3 percent. For the week, the
average fell 54.07 points, or six-tenths of 1 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Broader indexes were hit harder. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index fell 22.28 points, or 1.95 percent, to 1,120.67, and the
Nasdaq composite fell nearly 2.5 percent to close at 1,872.39,
leaving that index about 7 percent below its all-time high of
2,014.25 set July 20. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The swings in trading and sentiment have more than a few
analysts worried about whether stocks can regain the momentum that
has propelled one of the greatest bull markets in history. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dickey and other analysts say the overriding concern among
investors is corporate earnings. And the growing consensus is that
despite a robust domestic economy, troubles in Asia and rising wage
growth at home are depressing corporate profits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With more than 80 percent of the companies that make up the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 reporting, corporate earnings are up just 1.7
percent from a year ago, according to IBES International, which
tracks earnings estimates. Analysts are lowering their
third-quarter estimates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worries about corporate profits may have been aggravated by a
government report Friday that the nation's gross domestic product
rose at an annual rate of just 1.4 percent in the second quarter.
Although stronger than expected, it was still a sharp slowdown from
the first quarter's 5.5 percent rate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's clearly a lot of nervousness out there right now,''
Philip J. Orlando, chief investment officer at Value Line Asset
Management, said. ``People are worried about Asia's impact on
earnings, and this Asia problem is getting worse.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to stocks Friday, bond prices rose slightly, pushing
the yield on the 30-year Treasury down to 5.71 percent, from 5.72
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Because investors have low inflation expectations, long-term
bond yields have remained in a narrow range for much of the year.
The 30-year bond has hovered between 5.6 percent and 5.8 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
