<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-LOSERS-LADN </SLUG>
 
MANY CALIFORNIA HMOs LOSING MONEY, SURVEY FINDS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- It turns out not all HMOs are the efficient money
machines that members may perceive them to be.
</P>
<P>
   Up to one-third of California HMOs lost money last year,
according to an annual survey released Friday. And even at that
high rate, the state's HMOs fared better than most nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is looking much better than other states, where
it's common to see 55 to 63 percent losing money,'' said Joseph
Coyne, chief executive officer of Healthcare Databank, a
Sonoma-based firm that tracks the health-care industry and
published the report.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs operated by managed-care specialist Foundation Health
Systems Inc. of suburban Woodland Hills emerged at opposite ends of
the spectrum in Healthcare Databank's 1997 report. The company's
Foundation Health HMO was the state's top money-loser -- winding up
$22 million in the red on more than $1 billion in revenue -- while
its Health Net HMO was among the most profitable, the report found.
The two plans were merged earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of challenges in the marketplace right now,''
said Health Net spokesman Ron Yukelson. ``When you look at the cost
of medical services and the cost of delivering care at hospitals,
those are clearly growing. We could wind up running on a 2 percent
profit margin for 1998, which is probably the antithesis of what
consumers and even the medical community think of'' when they
imagine an HMO's finances.
</P>
<P>
   Indications are that 1998 will be another tough year for many
players. Last year Kaiser Permanente, the nation's largest HMO,
lost $270 million overall but eked out a $9 million profit in
California, according to the Healthcare Databank report. Already in
the first two quarters of 1998, Kaiser has lost $136 million in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross of California parent company WellPoint Health
Networks was another top performer in 1998, but earlier this week
reported a second-quarter net loss after writing off losses from
two money-losing ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in for another year of losses at many HMOs,'' Coyne
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, PruCare, Woodland Hills-based Prudential
HealthCare's HMO, lost $5.2 million last year, down from $40
million in 1996, but in the first quarter of 1998 posted a $6.4
million profit, its first in the state in five years. Prudential
achieved that turnaround in part by slashing its PruCare work force
by 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The HMO industry has faced shrinking margins for several years,
stemming largely from intense pricing competition as health plans
have fought for market share. Rising drug and care-provider prices
have also hurt profits. In response, many health plans have said
they will raise their 1999 premiums, in some cases by 12 percent or
more, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
