s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-MASS-TRUST-ART     07-31 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-MASS-TRUST-ART-$ADV02-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 INVESTING WITH JOHN D. LAUPHEIMER Jr. AT MASSACHUSETTS INVESTORS (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.
Graphic showing fund fact box; stock price for Alcatel Alsthom,
Safeway, Washington Mutual will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2)  
 (af)  
 By WILLIAM R. LONG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Guess I'm a little bit of a throwback,'' said John D.
Laupheimer Jr., 41, lead manager of Massachusetts Investors Trust.
``I wear three-button suits and bow ties. I'm a pretty conservative
fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be appropriate, for his mutual fund is the nation's
oldest, having started in 1924.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Laupheimer is the conservator of a tradition that is
palpable at the Boston headquarters of the fund's adviser, MFS
Investment Management. Lining the hall outside his 25th-floor
office are a dozen portraits of past managers of the fund, and
downstairs is a ledger listing its original investments, in
businesses like Nash Motors and the Naumkeag Steam Cotton Co.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Laupheimer what earns a stock a place in the portfolio
today, and his answer, in an age of technical analysis and
quantitative screening, seems something of a throwback, too: its
people. ``The real key to great companies is operating
management,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Testing the savvy of corporate chieftains is just one way that
Laupheimer judges the worthiness of companies as investments for
MIT, as the fund is known. For example, he looks for low-volatility
stocks, a policy that insures that the fund's beta _ a key measure
of volatility _ remains well below that of the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   This means that stocks in the $9.2 billion portfolio tend to
rise and fall less than the market does, a trait appreciated by
conservative investors.
</P>
<P>
   Laupheimer's vigilance has helped MIT remain one of the top
funds in its category since February 1993, when he was named lead
manager. For the five years ended July 24, the fund has returned
22.9 percent, annualized, compared with an average of 19.6 percent
for all large-capitalization blend funds, which buy large-company
stocks that have either value or growth characteristics, according
to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Laupheimer works with two co-managers and the MFS staff of more
than 30 analysts. He manages a subportfolio that currently accounts
for 60 percent of the fund's assets. The two co-managers, Kevin R.
Parke and Mitchell D. Dynan, pick subportfolios that account for 20
percent each of the assets, although they overlap on 60 percent of
their picks.
</P>
<P>
   Early in Laupheimer's tenure, the managers defined a list of
investment disciplines intended to help insure quality and to
control risk.
</P>
<P>
   One is the rule that the portfolio's volatility should always be
lower than that of the S&AMP;P 500. Another is that the dividend yield
of the portfolio must be at least 90 percent of that of the S&AMP;P
500, reflecting Laupheimer's view that low-dividend stocks are
often companies lacking adequate cash flow. But interestingly for a
manager who seeks safety, he also steers away from high-dividend
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're throwing off their cash to shareholders in large
amounts because they can't think of anything better to do with it,
so their internal growth rates tend to be fairly slow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio's ratio of share prices to earnings is generally
about 10 percent below that of the S&AMP;P, which is currently at 27.6.
</P>
<P>
   This caution has helped returns in past market downturns. In the
last bear market, from May through October of 1990, MIT fell 11.63
percent, versus a drop of 14.69 percent in the S&AMP;P, according to
CDA/Wiesenberger, a fund-tracking service based in Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   As for his current choices, Laupheimer says he has found a
first-rate corporate captain in Steven A. Burd, chief executive of
Safeway Inc., the Western supermarket chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk to him, you know that he knows the dynamics of
his business, really almost store by store, certainly region by
region,'' Laupheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining Safeway as chief executive in 1993, Burd has
raised operating profit margins from below 5 percent to nearly 9
percent while reducing merchandise prices, Laupheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Safeway strategy is to expand by buying other supermarket
companies and then to improve their operating margins by applying
Safeway's standards in areas like coupon strategy, cleanliness,
staffing and labor relations, Laupheimer said. He predicted that
earnings would grow 18 percent annually for the next two or three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Over about two years of buying Safeway stock, Laupheimer said,
the fund has paid an average of about $22 a share. The stock now
trades at $44.75; he expects it to hit $50 in 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Laupheimer also likes Washington Mutual, the Seattle-based
savings and loan company with a market capitalization of about $17
billion. He ranks its management, headed by Kerry K. Killinger, the
chief executive, in the same league as Safeway's.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mutual has diversified from a regional institution
and expanded aggressively by buying big savings and loans. And
Killinger achieves big cost savings by consolidating staff and
management after mergers, Laupheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Washington Mutual had great potential as a takeover
target for a national bank but that it also had strong growth
potential on its own. He saw its stock as attractively valued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a company selling for 12 times next year's earnings,
growing their earnings at 13 to 15 percent, and I don't care
whether they get bought out or not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laupheimer said he has been buying the bank's stock for about a
year at an average cost of $42 a share; it now trades at $39.9375.
``I don't see why this can't be a $60 stock in a year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laupheimer said Alcatel Alsthom, the European supplier of
telecommunications equipment, has also flourished under top-notch
leadership. Serge Tchuruk became chairman and chief executive in
1995 after heading European blue chips like Total, the French oil
company, and Rhone-Poulenc, the drug giant.
</P>
<P>
   Laupheimer said the chiefs of French companies were often
disappointing ``because they never manage to get the costs under
control'' but that Tchuruk had succeeded in such efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The European telecommunications equipment business has lagged
behind its American counterpart, which has boomed with increases in
telephone and fax-machine use, data transmission and Internet
traffic. But Laupheimer said he was optimistic about Alcatel
because it was ``just entering the sweet spot of that growth curve
in Europe'' and because ``the management of this company has a real
track record of providing shareholder value.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcatel stock, available as American depository shares, sells
for about 22 times next year's earnings, which Laupheimer sees as
cheap compared with similar American stocks. ``We think it's got a
growth rate of 20 percent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He started buying shares last year; the average cost has been
$31. The stock now trades at $39.375 and Laupheimer estimates that
it will hit $60 in 12 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
