s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-PHONE-Q&AMP;A-ART-     07-31 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-PHONE-Q&AMP;A-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAPPING THE TELECOMMUNICATIONS SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2)  
 (af)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For investors, the tectonic shifts in the telecommunications
industry in recent years have come not from fundamental changes in
the business _ as numerous as they have been _ but from corporate
mergers, alliances and spinoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week was no exception. The biggest phone companies in the
United States and Britain, AT&AMP;T and British Telecommunications,
last Sunday unveiled a $10 billion venture to serve multinational
business customers.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Bell Atlantic the nation's No. 1 local
communications company, announced a $52.9 billion agreement to
merge with GTE, a big local and long-distance carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Mahoney, a big fan of European stocks and wireless
companies, has managed the $1.7 billion AIM Global
Telecommunications fund for more than five years, shared his
insights on the business. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q.(italics)What are the main thoughts that investors should take
away from last week's flurry of telecommunications news,
particularly the merger agreement between Bell Atlantic and
GTE?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Probably the main thing they should look at is the
consolidation that's going on in the industry. We've been talking
about it for a long time. It's finally coming to pass. We're going
to see this continuing at the top tier of telecommunications in the
U.S., and, I think, globally as well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q.(italics)How should investors approach that process?(end
italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The Bell Atlantic-GTE deal showed you don't necessarily make
immediate money in a takeover, but we should also remember that the
structure of the U.S. industry is somewhat inefficient. It's a lot
like the banking industry, where for regulatory reasons, a
historical accident, you end up with a number of organizations
where a smaller number would be more efficient. And that's good for
investors because the industry has a lot of opportunity to increase
efficiencies and reduce costs.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these companies have more corporate overhead than they
need. How many people are on the legal and regulatory staffs of
Bell Atlantic and GTE? I wouldn't be surprised if there are 1,000
highly paid white-collar people working on legal and regulatory
issues. If they're each making $100,000, which is conservative,
that's $100 million. They're talking about $2 billion in cost
synergies for Bell Atlantic and GTE, and that's pretty reasonable.
So you may see quicker earnings growth for the combined company
than you would see from them separately.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q.(italics)More generally, which particular segments of the
telecommunications market are attractive?(end itallics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Our belief is that wireless remains the fastest-growing
engine in the telecom business. I would always be looking at
wireless for both services and equipment. On the wire-line side,
enhanced services, basically data services, are certainly the
fastest-growing. We thought Worldcom's data business would grow by
about 60 percent in the last quarter, and it grew by 75.
</P>
<P>
   Q.(italics)Why is wireless so attractive?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Fundamentally, I believe ultimately that people will cut the
wire. I don't see the reason for wire-line phones for voice
service. If the price was the same, I don't see why anyone would
have a wire-line phone. I think they would just put something in
their pocket and carry it around. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q.(italics)But haven't wireless stocks suffered recently?(end
italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. They have. Part of that is AT&AMP;T's new Digital One Rate plan,
which is aimed at Nextel. But if you take a look at European
wireless, where they have the technical problems worked out and
everyone is on the same system, they have been great.
</P>
<P>
   The ones that come to mind are Telecom Italia Mobile and
Mannesmann, which is our largest single position; Vodafone and
Orange in the U.K., then the Nordic wireless stocks, like Netcom
and Europolitan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q.(italics)In the United States, one of the concerns has been
that with five and six wireless competitors in some markets, it's
hard for anyone to make any money.(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The U.S. has some things to work out. I don't think the U.S.
is as attractive as Europe right now, but I think you'll end up
with three to four stable national carriers here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q.(italics)Over all, what percentage of the fund have you
invested in Europe?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. About 40. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q.(italics)If Germany's Mannesmann is your single best idea,
what do you think is overrated? What do you not own, and why
not?(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't own Sprint. Even though I like the Sprint wireless
business, I think the stock is very aggressively valued now, and
that's partly on takeover speculation. It might happen, but it
might not happen for a long time. One of the companies that people
thought could acquire Sprint was GTE, and that's not going to
happen any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q.(italics)You mentioned advanced data services. Which carriers
are best positioned?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Worldcom-MCI is clearly the best-positioned carrier in the
world right now, but AT&AMP;T-BT is right there with them. The problem
is that AT&AMP;T-BT hasn't been put together yet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q.(italics)What is your concern with that venture?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You have an organization that doesn't have a clear ``buck
stops here.'' I don't believe in dictators, but I believe there has
to be a single person who bears ultimate responsibility. If two
people think they are each running the show, they will start to
focus on battling each other instead of on growing the business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q.(italics)What is your No. 1 idea in terms of
telecommunications equipment stocks?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I would say Nokia is the best place to be and Alcatel just a
bit behind. Nokia, obviously, because of their wireless business;
the reason I like Alcatel is that it's a big restructuring story,
and there is a lot of leverage there going forward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
