<HEADER>
A3112 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-401(K)-$ADV02-     07-31 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-401(K)-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)  
 U.S. WARNING, OR SORTS, ABOUT FEES AND 401(K)s   (af)  
 By ABBY SHULTZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hidden by the dazzling returns of many 401(k)s in recent years
are the costs of running these plans _ everything from investment
management and record-keeping fees to the expense of maintaining a
toll-free phone line for customer questions.
</P>
<P>
   The costs, which can climb to more than 2 percent of assets, can
add up to big dollars in lost retirement savings, but plan
participants are often left in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Labor Department wants to shed light on the subject. It
has begun by releasing a 17-page booklet describing the range of
fees levied on 401(k)s. The booklet also discusses the higher costs
of actively-managed funds, versus passive ones, and tells
participants that ``brand name'' mutual funds that are sold to
individual investors typically charge higher fees than accounts
that are separately managed for an employer's plan.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet, ``A Look at 401(k) Plan Fees,'' is part of a
broader examination of plan fees that the department will conclude
in the fall and that could irk employers and plan providers.
</P>
<P>
   The department is studying whether 401(k) savings are being
eroded by excess or undisclosed fees, whether companies are meeting
their legal responsibilities in choosing and monitoring 401(k)
service providers and whether participants are being informed about
the effect of fees on their investment results, said Meredith
Miller, deputy assistant secretary in the department's Pension and
Welfare Benefits Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there's a lot of competition among service providers,
the market is pretty inefficient,'' Ms. Miller said. ``They are
competing not on the basis of cost.''
</P>
<P>
   But the information provided in the booklet is hardly
groundbreaking. The booklet, for example, advises plan participants
to ``make informed investment decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   And some suggestions are recurrent: Can't calculate your fees?
Ask the plan administrator. Have questions regarding rates of
returns? Ask the plan administrator. More questions about your
401(k)? Ask the plan adminstrator. You get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the 401(k) fees can be confusing. And there is
no doubt that informing people about the role they play in building
wealth over time is worthwile.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the booklet describes two hypothetical people, each
with 35 years until retirement and $25,000 in a 401(k) account.
Each employee averages an investment return of 7 percent a year and
makes no additional contributions to the plan. One person pay fees
and expenses averaging 0.05 percent a year and ends up with
$227,000 at retirement. The second pays fees and expenses averaging
1.5 percent a year and ends up with only $163,000. So a 1 percent
difference in fees adds up to $64,000 by retirement day.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet goes on to explain the different types of fees. Plan
administration fees, like legal costs or daily valuation services,
rise with the number of services offered, and typically are paid by
the company. But the Labor Department has found that companies are
increasingly shifting these costs to employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we thought participants should have an
understanding of it,'' Ms. Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Most fees charged to a 401(k) plan go toward investment
management _ the cost of managing money, whether invested in mutual
funds or separate accounts run by a money manager. These costs are
deducted from the returns of the 401(k) participants and in effect
are an indirect charge against their account.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your net total return is your return after these fees have
been deducted,'' the booklet states. ``For this reason, these fees,
which are not specifically identified on statements of investments,
may not be immediately apparent.''
</P>
<P>
   The booklet does a good job of raising the fee issue, said David
E. Morse, a partner at the law firm of Whitman, Breed, Abbott &AMP;
Morgan in New York, but he believes that most employees will not
understand much of the text. The terminology is too technical and
requires too much prior knowledge of 401(k) plans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A paragraph on ``surrender and transfer charges,'' for example,
describes them as ``fees an insurance company may charge when an
employer terminates a contract (in other words, withdraws the
plan's investment) before the term of the contract expires or if
you withdraw an amount from the contract.'' Huh?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my clients have trouble getting their employees to read
something that's two pages long when they are talking about
investments,'' Morse said. ``To get them to read something this
dense on fees is an impossible task.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 30,000 copies of the booklet have been distributed in the
month since its release, through the Labor Department's Internet
site (www.dol.gov/dol/pwba) and through a toll-free hot line (800
998-7542), Ms. Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   David Castellani, senior vice president for retirement and
investment services at the Cigna Corp., the insurance giant, said
the booklet would at least give administrators of 401(k) plans the
tools to talk about fees with their participants. But he also
thought this first effort fell short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe the average participant has a fair and deep
understanding of what they pay,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That, Ms. Miller said, is the reason for her department's
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a complicated area,'' she said. ``What we did is take
a cut at a simplified explanation. It's our hope workers can get
more concise information from their employers.'' In other words,
ask the plan administrator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
