<HEADER>
A3113 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PREDATOR-COX     07-31 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREDATOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sexual predator returns to Ohio town
 &HT;    By John Keilman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio -- In late June, a 20-year-old Sidney man,
classified by a judge as a sexual predator, returned to town after
serving a year in prison for corruption of a minor.
</P>
<P>
   In most places in Ohio, deputies would have notified neighbors
about his criminal record. They also would have informed nearby
schools, day care centers, and children's services agencies.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't happen in Sidney.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals that governs Shelby County and the rest of
northwest Ohio has ruled that parts of the sexual predator law are
unconstitutional. That means the sheriff's department can't notify
anybody about felons who were convicted before the law took effect
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all got our opinions on the law, but I have to go by
what the prosecutor and courts decide,'' said Sheriff Mark
Schemmel.
</P>
<P>
   The episode illustrates the uncertainty still surrounding the
predator law's authority over incarcerated sex offenders. The
situation is so murky that some criminals, considered predators by
the prison system, may be able to escape the label for good.
</P>
<P>
   When the law took effect at the start of 1997, it pertained not
only to people who would be convicted in the future, but also to
those already incarcerated. Defense attorneys called that
retroactive punishment _ prohibited by Ohio law _ and immediately
challenged the provision in court.
</P>
<P>
   State prisons nonetheless began screening hundreds of inmates,
trying to determine who met the profile of a predator. They
forwarded the names to local judges, who were supposed to hold
hearings and make a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the law was in dispute, most counties started
hearings immediately. Montgomery County, which hired a staffer in
the probation department to do nothing but sexual predator work,
has held more than 130 so far.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami County, though, judges in the Court of Common Pleas
decided to delay hearings until the 2nd District Court of Appeals
ruled on the issue. That didn't occur until March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, at least three men prison officials believed
were predators _ they had sexually abused children in their care _
were released.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe those men will be able to avoid the predator tag
for good. David Berenson, director of Sex Offender Services for the
Ohio Department of Rehabilitation and Correction, said that ``it is
my understanding that if a guy has been released from prison and a
sexual predator hearing hasn't been held, (then) they cannot hold
it.''
</P>
<P>
   That has been backed up by the Court of Appeals in Franklin
County. In March, it erased the predator status of a former
Catholic priest who admitted having sexual contact with an
11-year-old boy. The judges ruled that the man had not received
proper notice of his hearing before he was released from prison.
</P>
<P>
   Miami County Judge Robert J. Lindeman said he would hold the
hearings anyway and let the appeals courts sort it out.
</P>
<P>
   The predator problems are different in Shelby, Logan, Mercer and
Auglaize counties. The appeals court overseeing that area has ruled
the predator law should not apply to those convicted before it took
effect.
</P>
<P>
   That means those counties can't notify anybody about released
convicts who were tried before Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Supreme Court is deliberating on the appellate judges'
decision. It heard arguments in June and could decide at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Until it does, prosecutors such as Mercer County's Paul Howell
must wait. He said the county has three sex offenders who were
jailed before the law began, but none has been released yet.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some counties say they've had a relatively easy time
with the law. Warren County Prosecutor Tim Oliver said his office
handled a glut of inmate hearings just after the ordinance took
effect, paused until the appeals court in Middletown upheld it,
then began again.
</P>
<P>
   The county has held about 45 hearings, he said, and as far as he
knows, no one has slipped through the cracks. 1 Offenders and
predators
</P>
<P>
   While Miami Valley counties have held dozens of sexual predator
hearings, only a few have actually gained that status. All
convicted sex offenders in Ohio must register with local sheriff's
departments when they get out of prison. But those whom judges find
to be predators must have their names, addresses and photographs
distributed to neighbors and nearby schools and day care centers.
</P>
<P>
   Greene County _17 offenders, 1 predator
</P>
<P>
   Miami County _22 offenders, 0 predators
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County _102 offenders, 7 predators
</P>
<P>
   Preble County _ 4 offenders, 0 predators
</P>
<P>
   Shelby County _ 8 offenders, 0 predators
</P>
<P>
   Warren County _ 7 offenders, 0 predators
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
