u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-595&AMP;ADD-     07-31 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S NEW CHIEF VOWS TO ACT ON ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ On his first day as Japan's prime minister, Keizo Obuchi
once again tried to reassure the world that he would move swiftly
to address Japan's economic problems, hiring a new adviser whose
stature as a financial heavyweight rivals those of many in the
West.
</P>
<P>
   With the announcement Friday that the unemployment rate climbed
to a record 4.3 percent in June while the yen hovered at below 144
to the dollar, Obuchi admitted his naivete regarding economic
matters but told reporters that there is no ``superman'' who can
single-handedly pull the country out of its economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tackle this problem boldly and speedily,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He reiterated his pledge to abandon the austere fiscal policy
that many blame for hampering economic recovery, saying he would
finance a $42 billion tax cut to boost spending by issuing
government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   He trotted out his oft-stated hopes of completing a peace treaty
with Moscow and repeated a pledge to put together a $70 million
supplementary budget to pump up the economy.
</P>
<P>
   And a senior official in the prime minister's office said Friday
night that the new government is ready to deal out the tough love
needed to fix the faltering banking system. ``We have to be
prepared to suffer some bankruptcies,'' he said. ``Some bad banks
are going down.''
</P>
<P>
   While Obuchi said little that he has not said before, he
surprised the public by announcing at a news conference that he had
chosen Toyoo Gyohten, a legendary Japanese financier known for
candidness and a tough negotiating style, as special adviser to his
Cabinet, and more specifically, to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi and his advisers are tentatively trying their hand at
spin control, having suffered, among other indignities, an
unscientific television poll that showed his popularity to be
dramatically lower than two rivals for the nation's top job.
</P>
<P>
   A Foreign Ministry official disclosed that he had asked the
Philippine president, Joseph Estrada, a former actor known for
playing a tough guy in B movies, to teach him a few things about
popular appeal when Estrada called to congratulate him.
</P>
<P>
   And Obuchi is considering using Japan's vaunted rail system _
the debts of which will be one of the many headaches he has to deal
with _ to make weekend forays into the heart of the country to hear
what his new spokesman described as ``views, opinions and grief.''
</P>
<P>
   Gyohten's appointment is meant to assure foreign investors and
world leaders that Obuchi, who is regarded as somewhat of a
financial novice, is serious about fixing Japan's sick banking
system and pulling its economy out of the worst slump in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Gyohten earned the respect of luminaries like Paul Volcker, the
Federal Reserve Board chairman during the Reagan administration,
and Karl Otto Poehl, a former Bundesbank president, for holding his
and Japan's own in Western-style negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   He has represented Japan at both the International Monetary Fund
and the Asian Development Bank. And he was a leading participant in
negotiations that led to the 1985 agreement by the Group of Seven
nations to end the dollar's supremacy and boost the value of the
yen. The accord, which was expected to curb the rise of Japanese
economic power, seriously backfired.
</P>
<P>
   But shortly after the accord was signed, Institutional Investor
wrote in a profile of Gyohten that ``for all his storied
internationalism and open-mindedness, Toyoo Gyohten may well be the
most formidable Japanese adversary the West has ever faced in the
financial arena.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In another effort at spin control Friday, Obuchi introduced his
newly named deputy press secretary, Akitaka Saiki.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, Saiki began to do his job, making some surprising
statements and then backtracking on them almost to the point of
contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Obuchi does not intend to stay in power too long,'' Saiki
said at one point. ``That is another indication of his strong will
to do something good for the nation, good for the region and for
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he said he thought that Obuchi would survive in the job
longer than many people believe he will.
</P>
<P>
   Saiki also said Obuchi did not have much time to bail out the
economy before the opposition and the public start calling for his
head.
</P>
<P>
   But he nonetheless cautioned against a quick turnaround in the
country's fortunes. ``We should not be thinking things will be
looking brightly in the next two or three months,'' he said,
speaking English.
</P>
<P>
   Saiki offered another word of caution. ``Of course, it is an LDP
government,'' he said, referring to the governing Liberal
Democratic Party, ``so things aren't going to change that
dramatically.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
