</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-BLINEBURY-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nigerians lament &QL; 
what could've been
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Greece _ No Dream Team.
</P>
<P>
   But still a Dream.
</P>
<P>
   As the muscular, swift, but mostly inept Nigerian national team
ran through its warm-ups at one end of the vast Olympic Stadium
prior to its game against Australia, a tall, familiar figure
emerged from a tunnel entrance and took a seat on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon, for a few hours, at least, was home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good to be around the guys,'' he said. ``I went to
the shootaround this morning and talked to them. I know many of
them because they play college basketball in the States. But this
is a different situation, where the team is all together in an
international competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The rumor circulating through the World Championship of
Basketball had been that Olajuwon was invited to sit on the bench
as an assistant coach for the Nigerian team.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said chuckling. ``I'm not doing any coaching. I don't
need the aggravation. I'm just here for support, to provide some
encouragement.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the floor, filling a section of the stands, a group of
nearly 200 Nigerian fans caught sight of him and erupted with
cheers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hak-eem! Hak-eem! Hak-eem! We still love you! Please remember
us!''
</P>
<P>
   Since he arrived in Houston in 1980, this was the first time
Olajuwon had seen the Nigerian basketball team play in person. And
while his NBA exploits have been a point of pride in his native
land, it has at the same time been a source of frustration for many
fans he left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Dream with Olowokandi
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if we had Olajuwon and (1998 No. 1 NBA draft pick)
Michael Olowokandi playing for the Nigerian team,'' said Suleiman
Habiba, 25, an immigration officer who was leading cheers in the
middle of the section. ``Who would beat us then? Who would touch us
in the world?
</P>
<P>
   ``You could bring on your American NBA stars. Bring your Dream
Team. With Olajuwon and Olowokandi, we would rule the world.
Instead, all we can do is to hope for a miracle and dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Always dance. Always sing. Always move and shake and sway and
chant and do anything to keep the atmosphere in the arena more like
a carnival than a basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   There are rhythmic drums, piercing horn blasts and songs for
virtually every situation. Fans from other countries come wearing
T-shirts. The members of the Nigerian Basketball Supporters Club
wear green-and-white dashikis and hats with pointed horns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh-shay-oh-shay-oh-oh-shay-habba!'' they sing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means `thank you,' or just about anything you want,'' said
Nasiru Isa, 28, who is painted green and white from his chest up,
including his mustache, and has been a virtual dancing machine
going up and down the long flight of stairs almost nonstop
throughout the game. ``This is not just a basketball game. It is a
celebration of our athletes and a way for us to tell them how much
we care.''
</P>
<P>
   Passionate about sports
</P>
<P>
   The sound at a Nigerian game is like listening to a live version
of Paul Simon's Graceland album. It's a cultural experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nigerian fans have always been passionate about their
sports,'' Olajuwon said. ``I remember getting that kind of support
when I was young playing on the junior national team. Did you see
them at the World Cup in France? I don't think any country had a
better time.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly no other fans packed more celebrating into every
minute. They cheered every move, every dribble by Yinka Dare, the
renowned NBA flop with the New Jersey Nets. They hung on every move
of Obinna Ekezie, the young star at the University of Maryland.
This is a nation that produces abundant raw basketball talent.
</P>
<P>
   Isa coaches a team in Lagos, the Gunners Basketball Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, gunners as in shooters,'' he said, giggling. ``We all can
shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   And they all can fantasize about what it might have been like if
Olajuwon had chosen to represent Nigeria in the Olympics instead of
becoming an American citizen and playing for the United States in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   It is still a touchy subject, and it seems every time he
comments, Olajuwon touches off another controversy. He has not been
back to Nigeria to visit in nearly a decade, fearing the political
unrest. But he was traveling this summer to Mecca and to Jordan,
and he didn't want to miss this opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Hakeem regrets not playing for us,'' Habiba said. ``I
know the Americans swindled us and exploited him. That's OK _ we
still love him.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh-shay-oh-shay-oh-oh-shay-habba!
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasn't this fun?'' Olajuwon said.
</P>
<P>
   For a night, at least, he is home again and they can dream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
