<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-31 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SHALL WE DANCE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By FRANK RICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At Leonard Bernstein's memorial service in 1990,
playwright Arthur Laurents brought down the house when he said,
``There were only two things Lenny was afraid of _ God and Jerry
Robbins.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Robbins, the choreographer who died this week at 79, was
not one of the most beloved figures in the theater. The first time
I saw him in action _ when, as a 15-year-old, I sneaked into a
``Fiddler on the Roof'' rehearsal in 1964 _ the show's cast was
snickering with approval as the star, Zero Mostel, made lewd
gestures mocking him behind his back. The Mostel-Robbins feud was
rooted in the McCarthy era _ Robbins had named names during the
witch hunts while Mostel had been blacklisted _ and yet most of the
animosity Robbins aroused was non-ideological. He was greedy about
billing and royalties. He could be monstrous _ the posthumous
euphemism is ``perfectionist'' _ toward performers.
</P>
<P>
   But much as we might wish otherwise, there is no correlation
between the character of an artist and the quality of his art. No
less than Sinatra _ to take the handiest recent example _ Jerome
Robbins was a giant of our culture.
</P>
<P>
   His was a quintessentially American two-track career that
unfolded, simultaneously for a time, in both the slangy show biz of
Broadway and the poetic realm of dance. ``He brought the vitality
and energy of this country into the ballet,'' said Laurents Friday.
I had asked him and Stephen Sondheim _ the last two survivors of
the creative team that changed the theater forever with the
cinematically staged ``West Side Story'' in 1957 _ to put aside
Robbins the man and evaluate his art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's really the only genius I ever met,'' said
Sondheim. ``Genius is a word people sling around, but my
understanding of that word is endless invention _ and Jerry had
that. ... He had style and substance, but he also knew how to turn
it into entertainment, to bridge the gap to the audience. He had a
way of dealing with the high and the low and a way of combining
them. He could even do television revues _ like the Merman-Martin
special _ and did.''
</P>
<P>
   That mixture of high and low is intrinsic to a young, democratic
culture whose signature achievement may well be ``The Adventures of
Huckleberry Finn.'' Robbins' repertory extended from a Mack
Sennett-inspired Keystone Kops ballet (for Broadway's ``High Button
Shoes,'' 1947) to the Noh theatrics of ``Watermill'' (New York City
Ballet, 1972), from witty recreations of burlesque striptease
routines (``Gypsy,'' 1959) to the Bach classicism of
``Brandenburg'' (City Ballet, last year). His recurrent
choreographic vision of a community coming together in a circle and
splintering could be set to ``Tradition'' in ``Fiddler'' or Chopin
in ``Dances at a Gathering'' (City Ballet, 1969). And what more
epitomizes the fusion of high and low than ``West Side Story''
itself, in which Shakespeare's ``Romeo and Juliet'' is re-imagined
for the seething urbanscape of New York?
</P>
<P>
   Like some other American artists of Russian Jewish stock that he
worked with, including most especially Irving Berlin, Robbins at
times defined the way the country pictures itself. The image of the
three sailors on 24-hour shore leave he created in 1944 for his
breakthrough ballet ``Fancy Free'' and its Broadway follow-up ``On
the Town'' are as much a part of World War II iconography as the
Iwo Jima statue. The insouciant pose he created (initially for Mary
Martin) for Peter's flight in the musical ``Peter Pan'' is a
permanent totem of American childhood, much as the panther-like
leap of the Jets in ``West Side Story'' on their way to the rumble
is a staple of the national adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins saw to it that his voluminous work was meticulously
documented; it won't die with him. But his death nonetheless leaves
a vacuum. ``An era hasn't ended,'' says Sondheim, ``but an era of
people I was awed by has ended.'' For myself, I think of the end of
the Robbins ballet paying tribute to Fred Astaire, ``I'm Old
Fashioned.'' After the dancers finish executing Robbins' many
exhilarating variations on an old Astaire duet with Rita Hayworth,
they retreat to the shadows, making way for a huge movie screen
that flies down for a humbling replay of the black-and-white clip
of the dazzling original. The young dancers salute Astaire with a
farewell wave _ but what had been a mood of celebration is now
tinged with loss. As the curtain falls, the realization dawns that
some artists can never be replaced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
