<SLUG> BC-MATISSE-DISPUTE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT OVER PAINTING BY HENRI MATISSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REGINA HACKETT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Heirs of a French art dealer whose collection was
looted by the Nazis sued the Seattle Art Museum Friday, seeking
return of the Henri Matisse painting ``Odalisque.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed in U.S. District Court in Seattle nine months
after the heirs of Paul Rosenberg asked the museum to provide proof
it rightfully owned the painting or to return it.
</P>
<P>
   John Reed, SAM's lawyer, said Friday that consultants for the
museum are still investigating ownership history of the Matisse
during World War II and the years immediately afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Joice, SAM's chief registrar, said the museum was ``willing
to enter mediation with all parties involved.'' But she refused to
comment on the heir's contention the museum sent them a letter June
12 saying it wouldn't return the painting unless ordered to do so
by a court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The museum told us to sue, so we're suing,'' said Camden Hall,
of the Seattle law firm Foster Pepper &AMP; Shefelman, who represents
the Rosenberg heirs. Hall refused to provide a copy of the museum's
June 12 letter, as did Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he doesn't know what the museum wants to mediate.
``The museum needs to give the painting back,'' he said. ``For the
museum, the painting is part of its inventory. For the Rosenbergs,
it's their heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1927-1928 oil painting titled ``Odalisque'' was featured in
a 1995 book by Hector Feliciano titled, ``The Lost Museum: The Nazi
Conspiracy to Steal the World's Greatest Works of Art.'' Originally
published in France, the book was translated into English and
published in this country last year by Basic Books. In the book,
``Odalisque'' (17{ inches high by 21} inches wide) was listed as
``whereabouts unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   The original owner, Paul Rosenberg, was considered Paris' most
important dealer in 19th and 20th century art between the World
Wars.
</P>
<P>
   After the Nazis invaded France in 1940, Rosenberg and his family
fled to New York, leaving more than 300 major paintings in France,
including works by Picasso, Matisse, Bonnard, Ingres, Delacroix,
Courbet and Cezanne. All of Rosenberg's holdings in France
disappeared into Nazi vaults. ``Odalisque'' was one of the
paintings in Rosenberg's personal collection.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, Seattle's Prentice Bloedel bought ``Odalisque'' from
New York's Knoedler Gallery. In 1991, he donated it to SAM, where
it has been frequently on view since.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of two paintings, two prints and a sculpture by the
French artist owned by the museum. Although the museum declines to
put a monetary value on ``Odalisque,'' Christie's auction house in
Los Angeles said a rough approximate value could be as high as $2
million.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, of the Seattle law firm Davis Wright Tremaine, said in a
prepared statement that the museum is still researching the history
of the painting's ownership, a task that has dragged on due to the
complexity of the subject. ``We have assured counsel for the
Rosenbergs that we will share the results of that research once it
has been completed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Rosenberg, widow of Paul Rosenberg's son, Alexandre,
expressed frustration that the museum is forcing her and her
sister-in-law, Rosenberg's daughter Micheline Nanette Sinclair, to
sue.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released through her attorneys, she said there is
``no genuine doubt that `Odalisque' was part of the collection of
Paul Rosenberg that was stolen by the Nazis. There is no
justification for the Seattle Art Museum's forcing the Rosenberg
family to incur the expense and delay of bringing a lawsuit to
recover it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said the family isn't asking for damages at this point.
``My feeling is if we get the painting back quickly without a lot
of spear throwing we'll probably just fade into the sunset, but if
the museum makes us spend a lot of money and engage in a battle
royal, we might be forced to seek damages.''
</P>
<P>
   In the suit, the Rosenbergs allege ``Odalisque'' was sold in
1954 by Galerie Drouant-David in Paris to Knoedler &AMP; Co., which
then sold it to Bloedel.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Knoedler Gallery were not available Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The heirs say they do not know how Galerie Drouant-David
acquired the painting. If Rosenberg himself had recovered it and
sold it to the gallery, the museum would own it legitimately.
</P>
<P>
   The family claims that isn't the case, said Hall, and that
Rosenberg and his family have made diligent efforts to recover his
property.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, the West German government concluded ``Odalisque'' was
illegally seized by the Nazis in 1941 and traded by Hermann Goering
for other art in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to Feliciano's book, Nazi war booty has become a
subject of renewed interest and controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Art Museum Directors formed a task
force this year to ``recognize and deplore the unlawful
confiscation of art that constituted one of the many horrors of the
Holocaust and World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   However, museums in the United States and Europe are proving
reluctant to part with specific artworks or help heirs obtain such
artworks when they are on tour. Mimi Gates, director of the Seattle
Art Museum, is a member of this task force. She was not available
for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said the museum regrets that ownership of ``Odalisque''
could not have been resolved without a lawsuit but is eager for the
matter to be determined so that ``relative rights and obligations
of the parties, including obligations of the Knoedler Gallery, can
be decided in one forum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
