<SLUG> BC-SOFTWARE-EDUC-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EDUCATIONAL SOFTWARE: SO LONG, SCIENCE KITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (from `Education Life' special section)  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 2)  
 (bl)  
 By JOSH BARBANEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drops of sweat were building up on the edge of my neck as I
pored over the instructions that came with the science kit. I stuck
another wire into the tiny clasp on a cardboard circuit board.
Nothing. The eyes of both eager children began to drift away. The
Morse code key would not buzz. Mr. Science was unmasked once again.
</P>
<P>
   Foolish me. That was some months ago. Now I see that I could
have just left the problem of encouraging scientific inquiry in my
children to the educational software publishers. With the shelves
glutted with reading and math software, the industry is turning to
science. Children _ and adults _ can explore light, sound,
electricity, perception and optical illusions right at their
computer screens, without losing a part or breaking a wire.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes this works brilliantly. Children can learn concepts,
play games and engage, perhaps, in a bit of scientific inquiry. And
yet, there is something sad and lacking about exploring nature and
the physical sciences through computer simulations and animations,
and never getting to see, touch or, yes, even break the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   It is like watching 50 episodes of ``Nature'' without once
walking through the woods or visiting a zoo. After watching a child
build a hundred circuits with bells and batteries on a computer
screen, I began to wish the publisher had included a few wires in
the box.
</P>
<P>
   Lasers, Circuits and Bad Jokes
</P>
<P>
   ``Thinkin' Science Series: ZAP!'' by Edmark, which is owned by
IBM, lets children explore color, lenses, sound waves, electrical
gadgets and lasers through a series of computer games _ or
``learning laboratories,'' as Edmark puts it _ grounded in
scientific concepts.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the program, you are told that you have been
selected to be the guest director of a performance by the musical
group ZAP! in a cartoonlike concert hall. Before the concert can
begin, however, you must learn how to repair wiring, laser lights
and the sound system _ because they all have been struck by
lightning.
</P>
<P>
   In the electricity lab, you learn to construct simple electrical
circuits by adding and cutting wires, and attaching bulbs, fans and
bells. The exercises become increasingly complex, covering basic
electrical concepts like current, voltage, resistance and parallel
circuits. You can follow the lesson plan step by step, or putter
around with your own circuits.
</P>
<P>
   The laser lab explores light rays and colors. Mirrors, lenses,
filters, prisms and color-splitters are used to direct beams of
light around obstacles. When the correct beams strike the target _
an egg _ it hatches into a chick that flies across the screen. You
can experiment with the properties of colors, filtering and
reflecting colored beams of light. And when you solve a problem,
the members of ZAP! reward you with bad jokes and puns that only an
8-year-old could enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Edmark says all this activity helps children ``discover science
through inquiry, observation and experimentation _ just like real
scientists.'' For my taste, there is too much simulation and not
enough reality. On the other hand, many scientists spend their days
staring at computer screens, analyzing mounds of statistical
evidence and simulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thinkin' Science Series: ZAP!,'' $29.95, Edmark. (800)
691-2988; www.
</P>
<P>
   edmark. com. Windows 3.1, Windows 95 or later, or Macintosh,
System 7.0.1 or higher. For ages 8 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe You Shouldn't Believe Your Eyes
</P>
<P>
   At the start of ``Scientific American Library: Illusion,'' the
narrator says: ``We put a great deal of trust in what we see. But
how much of that trust is justified?''
</P>
<P>
   This CD-Rom explores how the eye sees: how space, color, light,
motion and form affect how we see the world around us, and how what
we see is shaped by distortion and illusion.
</P>
<P>
   It takes two Scientific American Library Books, ``Perception,''
by Irvin Rock, and ``Eye, Brain and Vision,'' by David H. Hubel,
and brings them to life with animated, interactive illustrations
and exercises that let you explore illusions right before your very
eyes. There are also interviews, text and illustrations, as well as
50 games and 3-D illusions.
</P>
<P>
   You can explore the inner workings of the eye, discovering how
hard it is to put together a jigsaw puzzle when your mouse moves
the way your eye sees objects before they are inverted by the
brain: upside down and backward. You can also see a crate that
looks as if its back legs were intertwined with the front legs,
even after you are shown how the illusion was done. And you can
listen to a psychologist explain how the blind can draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientific American Library: Illusion,'' $29.95, Byron Preiss
Multimedia Company. (800) 945-3155; www.
</P>
<P>
   byronpreiss. com. Windows 95, or Macintosh or Power Macintosh,
System 7.0 or higher; no recommendations on ages.
</P>
<P>
   Has Carmen Finally Lost Her Way?
</P>
<P>
   Why in the world is Carmen Sandiego in a high-tech space-age
mystery? To teach children math. So what does that have to do with
geography?
</P>
<P>
   When Carmen Sandiego was introduced in the mid-1980s, a
generation ago in the life span of the personal computer, it opened
new vistas in interactive learning. ``Where in the World is Carmen
</P>
<P>
   Sandiego?'' was, in its time, a magical tool that allowed
children to explore the world.
</P>
<P>
   A generation later, ``Carmen Sandiego Math Detective'' seeks to
extend the franchise to new territory. But here, there is nothing
magical, or even particularly clever. It is a conventional
math-drill program, and like many such programs the drill is
sugarcoated in the form of a game or of a mystery to solve. (There
is also ``Carmen Sandiego Word Detective'' and a more plausible
``Where in Time is Carmen Sandiego?'')
</P>
<P>
   In ``Math Detective,'' Carmen Sandiego has stolen 12 world
monuments and shrunk them into tiny crystals. Using the
transporter, you visit hideouts and locate codes that can only be
decoded by completing one of five basic sets of math drills. After
you complete a set of drills you can recover one monument. Alas,
far more imaginative thinking went into the concept than into the
drills. Nervous parents can log on and inspect their child's
progress through the game, click for click, and then decide whether
or not they are ready for the Ivy League, without having to wait
for the SATs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carmen Sandiego Math Detective,'' $34.95, Broderbund Software.
(800) 548-1798; www.broderbund.com. Windows 95, or Macintosh,
System 7.5.1 or higher. Ages 8 to 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
