<SLUG> BC-IRS-ABUSE-ART-3TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANGLED TALE OF THE OILMAN VS. THE IRS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Del.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2)  
 (af)  
 By CAROL MARIE CROPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When one of the nation's richest people _ a
headstrong Texas oilman _ is accused along with his family of
bilking the government of more than $100 million in taxes; when his
former accountant says in a court document that one tax dodge
involved claiming a business deduction for a private jet used
mainly to fly to vacation retreats in California and Colorado; when
the oilman agrees in the end to pay millions in back taxes and his
company offers to plead no contest to criminal tax fraud, one might
think there would be little public sympathy for him.
</P>
<P>
   Think again.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, when Republican senators needed taxpayers who had
been outrageously mistreated by the Internal Revenue Service to
trot before a congressional committee considering an IRS overhaul,
W.A. (Tex) Moncrief was front and center.
</P>
<P>
   Moncrief, in his testimony, was duly outraged, accusing the
agency of Gestapo-like tactics in a 1994 raid on his Fort Worth
office building, then of extorting $23 million from his family to
settle the case. He got plenty of sympathy from Republicans on the
Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Moncrief, long a generous supporter of Republican candidates,
was more than happy to help build a case against the current tax
system. Like many members of Congress, Moncrief, still a commanding
presence at 78, wants the income tax abolished and replaced by a
national sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be the fairest of all,'' he said in a recent
interview in the office of his late father, the legendary Texas
wildcatter W.A. (Monty) Moncrief _ although even some backers of
this idea acknowledge that it would shift more of the tax burden to
the poor and middle class.
</P>
<P>
   But is his really a case of IRS agents running wild, or of one
of the super-rich paying his due _ perhaps even getting off easy?
That is far from clear.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain, though, is that this Texas saga provides a
colorful glimpse at the powerful momentum that has built in the
effort to demonize the army of IRS accountants and lawyers charged
with making sure that Americans pay up.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Moncrief did pay $23 million to the IRS, but he did not
admit defeat. He and two of his sons are suing the accountant who
blew the whistle on them, and the lawyers who advised him, saying
they unethically conspired to harm the Moncrief family. And the
criminal plea that one of Moncrief's sons signed for the family
company, Montex Drilling, was, in a controversial move, never filed
by the government.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS, meanwhile, has refused to pay the whistle-blowing
accountant a promised reward, saying he violated his contract with
them by telling Moncrief's nephew, a state senator, about
Moncrief's dealings and allowing the nephew's accountant access to
tax records.
</P>
<P>
   The whistle-blower is suing the government for the millions he
says he is owed while he tries to fend off Moncrief, whose net
worth was estimated at $300 million in 1995 by Forbes magazine.
Moncrief's civil suit against him was scheduled to go to trial
tomorrow in state court but has been delayed while a federal judge
decides whether the accountant should be considered a federal
employee.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS overhaul on behalf of which Moncrief testified was
signed into law by President Clinton in late July. The measure
makes it clear that Congress no longer wants quite so hard-fisted a
tax collector, providing for outside oversight of the agency and
increased taxpayer leverage against property seizures.
</P>
<P>
   The changes will indeed make the agency more customer-friendly,
said John Berthoud, president of the National Taxpayers Union, a
nonprofit organization that lobbies for lower taxes and supports a
House effort to abolish the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a perception,'' Berthoud said, ``that the IRS is
more interested in serving the needs of government than in serving
the needs of the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   But there could be hazards in taming the agency.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sheldon S. Cohen, an IRS commissioner in the 1960s,
any new protections would shield tax dodgers, too. ``And there are
more deadbeats,'' he said, ``than nice taxpayers at that level'' _
the level at which the agency gives up on coaxing and moves to more
onerous methods.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Moncrief, Cohen said: ``It defies my imagination why
the Congress would let him portray himself in a sympathetic way.
Why, he paid $23 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Moncrief's version is that he did nothing wrong but was forced
to pay because ``the IRS told my attorneys that unless they got
some kind of substantial payment from us, they were not going to
leave us alone.'' The $23 million was one of the largest
noncorporate IRS settlements ever, said Doug Gastorf, chief of
criminal investigations for the agency's North Texas district.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had I known then what I know now,'' Moncrief said recently,
``I would not have paid them a penny.''
</P>
<P>
   The tax troubles began in 1993, when Billy W. Jarvis, Moncrief's
in-house accountant, began talking to the IRS about his suspicions
of tax fraud. Jarvis, a Moncrief employee for 14 years, would be
dismissed for unrelated reasons a few months after the first IRS
contact.
</P>
<P>
   In November of that year, Jarvis met with IRS agents and signed
an agreement to provide information in return for a
whistle-blower's reward of up to $25 million, depending on how much
was collected.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis worked with the IRS over the next 22 months. But after
only a few months, in the spring of 1994, perhaps frustrated by the
agency's inaction, he also opened up a new front against his old
employer. He met with Tex Moncrief's nephew Mike Moncrief, the
state senator, and shared information and documents that Jarvis
said would prove that Tex was cheating Mike's side of the family in
dealings involving oil and gas interests they had inherited.
</P>
<P>
   Tex Moncrief says this was a breach of Jarvis' professional
obligations. Jarvis says he came to believe he had a duty to
disclose a possible violation of Moncrief's fiduciary
responsibility to the nephew.
</P>
<P>
   There had long been friction between Tex Moncrief and the three
children of his late brother, Richard B. Moncrief. While Tex and
two of his four sons had followed his father, Monty, into the oil
business, Dick Moncrief had gone his own way. Tex's side now
controlled most of the family fortune.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The IRS raided Tex Moncrief's business on Sept. 1, 1994 _ almost
a year after its first meeting with Jarvis.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, in March 1995, Mike Moncrief, and his siblings
sued their uncle and two of their cousins, contending they had been
cheated in dealings involving oil and gas interests handed down
from their grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   Through testimony and filings in that suit, the IRS soon figured
out that its informant had begun working with someone else.
</P>
<P>
   It also became clear that Jarvis had agreed to split his
informants' reward with lawyers handling the Mike Moncrief suit and
that he was being paid a consultant's fee of $5,000 a month to help
in that litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Tex Moncrief promptly countersued, contending that his nephew
had made false claims against him in an attempt to injure him and
his business. The elder Moncrief also soon learned that it was
Jarvis who had reported him to the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 raid on his three-story, white-marble-and-glass office
building in downtown Fort Worth had made the front page of The Fort
Worth Star-Telegram as well as national headlines. Sixty-four IRS
agents swarmed through his offices, carting away more than a
million pages of company and family documents.
</P>
<P>
   The raid and its aftershocks shut down his business, Moncrief
said, costing at least $100 million _ most of which, he said,
represented a loss to him personally.
</P>
<P>
   Like a Texas longhorn bull poked with a stick, Tex charged.
</P>
<P>
   First he got his relatives to back down, negotiating to suspend
their litigation and extracting an apology from his nephew, a much
more taciturn man with a penchant for donating to the arts and to
social causes like helping AIDS patients and abused women.
</P>
<P>
   Of his nephew, a rare family Democrat, Tex said recently, ``As
far as I know, Mike has never worked a day in his life outside of
being a county judge and a politician,'' adding, for good measure,
that he was an ``ingrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of such comments, Mike Moncrief, now 54, chose not to
respond, citing an agreement not to discuss the settlement _
intended to apply to both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Tex Moncrief then turned his attention to Jarvis and the lawyers
who had worked with him on the case or advised him in his dealings
with the IRS, filing a suit contending that they had conspired
unlawfully to instigate the nephew's lawsuit and the IRS
investigation, thereby damaging Tex Moncrief's family and causing
emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis says that although he has paid hundreds of thousands of
dollars in legal bills and now has only an 1989 Cadillac and his
retirement plan, Moncrief is still chasing him through the state
courts in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tex, as we know right now, is a pretty mean-spirited person,''
Jarvis said in a recent interview at his lawyer's office. ``He's a
person that does not like to be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis, 61, balding with wire-rimmed glasses, said he started
worrying back in 1991 about the way the Moncriefs handled their
personal and business taxes. He said he talked to his brother, Don,
now a rural county judge, and became convinced that he could be
charged with a crime if he did not act. He was also afraid, he
said, that Moncrief would blame him if the tax problems were
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   According to an affidavit recently unsealed in the case, an IRS
criminal investigator swore that after looking into Jarvis'
information, he found ``probable cause'' that Tex Moncrief and
others had conspired to defraud the government and evade taxes. In
the affidavit, used to obtain the warrant to search the Moncrief
offices, the IRS set out five ways it suspected that the Moncriefs
had cheated on their taxes.
</P>
<P>
   They were suspected of deducting as business expenses personal
items like a jet used to fly to Moncrief's Palm Springs homes and
Colorado retreat; salaries for a personal chauffeur, handyman and
other household help and losses from family ranches used primarily
for pleasure. (Tex Moncrief, in an interview, talked of a
15,000-acre Texas ranch where the family keeps zebras and other
exotic animals.)
</P>
<P>
   The IRS also focused on what they suspected was a 1984 bailout
of one of Tex Moncrief's sons, with Tex and other family members
supposedly paying the son $40 million for properties worth only $8
million to $10 million _ essentially giving him a gift without
paying gift taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In another example, the IRS cited an allegation that Tex
Moncrief transferred an interest in a gas property to another son
without paying gift taxes.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth allegation was that Tex Moncrief diverted money that
should have gone to his elderly mother by keeping her portion of an
$80 million court settlement involving a gas property. This, the
agency said, allowed her $40 million share to pass to Tex and his
sons without payment of gift or estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   And in a possible tax dodge that could have saved the family the
most money, the IRS said it suspected that oil and gas properties
worth up to $190 million and belonging to his mother were
undervalued by Tex Moncrief before her death and sold to her seven
grandchildren for around $12.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Moncrief called the allegations a ``figment of Bill Jarvis'
imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   The plane, he said, was used only for business, and the
properties bought from his son were purchased for less than the
value the banks had placed on them.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the $40 million the IRS said should have gone to his
mother, that was totally his, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the IRS itself had agreed to the value of the oil
and gas properties sold by his mother to the grandchildren, he
said, citing a valuation made after the death of his father two
years before the sale.
</P>
<P>
   For such defensible items, Moncrief said at the congressional
hearing, the government initially wanted him to pay $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   Reconciling Jarvis' contentions and the IRS affidavit with
Moncrief's assertion that he never cheated is hard, since the
matter never resulted in criminal charges or went to trial.
</P>
<P>
   The coming civil trial in the Moncriefs' suit against Jarvis,
however, may shed light on the story.
</P>
<P>
   What is known from the court record in that lawsuit is that
sometime in October 1995, Tex's son and business partner, Charles
B. Moncrief, and the family's high-powered lawyers agreed to enter
a no-contest plea to tax fraud for Montex Drilling.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Among the Moncriefs' lawyers were Robert S. Bennett, better
known for representing President Clinton in the Paula Jones case;
James A. Bruton III, former acting chief of the Justice
Department's tax division, and Dee J. Kelly, an influential lawyer
in North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   According to the signed criminal plea agreement, Montex had
shifted $900,000 in business expenses to Tex Moncrief, which he
then improperly deducted on his 1990 federal return.
</P>
<P>
   No other allegations were addressed in the plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   After being negotiated by the United States Attorney's office in
Dallas, the plea bargain was sent to the tax division of the
Justice Department for approval, according to Gastorf, the district
IRS official, and two other government officials.
</P>
<P>
   There, said the two officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity because of the confidential nature of tax cases, the plea
was killed. Gastorf would say only, ``We thought it would be
accepted when we sent it up there,'' referring other questions to
Loretta C. Argrett, the assistant attorney general responsible for
the tax division.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Argrett, through a spokeswoman, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   However, the spokeswoman, Obern Rainey, said that while
decisions are made case by case, the policy is to oppose no-contest
pleas in all cases; she pointed out a written Justice Department
policy to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   No criminal action was taken. On Jan. 4, 1996, Tex Moncrief's
family settled the IRS case by agreeing to pay $23 million ``for
deficiencies in income, excise, and gift taxes for taxable periods
from Jan. 1, 1989, through Aug. 31, 1994.''
</P>
<P>
   In explaining why no criminal action was taken, Paul E. Coggins,
the United States attorney in Dallas, said: ``You're looking at a
bunch of factors. One was the amount of resources the case was
burning in your district. One was clearly, obviously, you know, the
age of one of the subjects. And then, of course, any issues you
have with the informant is another factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Mason, an IRS inspector called in last year to investigate
complaints by Moncrief about the way the case was handled, said in
a deposition that the agency was able to confirm some of the
allegations raised by Jarvis, as well as ``things that the
investigators were able to get on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said Jarvis' actions compromised the investigation,
stopping it prematurely. The IRS wound up investigating Jarvis
himself, Mason said, and considered filing charges against him for
providing Mike Moncrief's accountant with access to Tex Moncrief's
tax returns, but in the end decided he had not violated federal
law.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Jarvis call many of the complaints ``red herrings.''
Other witnesses could have verified Jarvis' account, they say, and
the government had documentation to substantiate the allegations
after its raid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious to me that there's some political overtones to
the case,'' said Jarvis, citing the only reason he could think of
for the way the case was handled. ``As you know, the Moncriefs are
well-heeled and perfectly capable of wielding a lot of influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Tex Moncrief's lawyers, meanwhile, said they signed the plea
agreement only because they knew it would not be accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attorney said it was a very innocuous situation and it
never came to fruit anyway,'' Moncrief said of the never-filed
criminal plea. ``I didn't pay any more attention to that than I've
paid to you in the last half-second,'' he told a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Moncrief, who said the government extracted the $23 million from
him ``to save face'' after its well-publicized raid, vows to keep
speaking out against the agency and to keep pursuing those who
conspired to break him. ``I couldn't eat, I couldn't sleep. I
couldn't conduct business,'' Moncrief said. ``It was the worst
thing that's ever happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Tex Moncrief's lawsuit against him and the fact that he
hasn't been paid his reward, Jarvis said he would go to the IRS
again if he could do things over. ``I was witness to what I
believed were illegalities,'' he said. ``I didn't have a choice as
to what I had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the truth of this case might depend on your
perspective. ``You get criticized for being too tough on Tex,'' one
government official said. ``Then, on the other hand, you can say
Tex bought his way out. There's no way you can win.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one thing is certain: the government will not be sued.
The United States attorney's office included a clause in its $23
million settlement protecting it from litigation by Tex Moncrief.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William V. Roth Jr., R-Del., chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, said his office did a preliminary check of the Moncrief
situation to establish the facts as best it could but saw no reason
to present the IRS's side at the hearing. ``We had agreed that the
purpose of these hearings was not to retry these cases,'' he said.
The committee has received thousands of complaints about IRS
practices since last year, when it announced its investigation, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, the former IRS commissioner, said that ``the tax man is
never going to be a beloved person.'' The Roth committee
``orchestrated this set of hearings so there was a groundswell of
public opinion,'' he added. ``But I think it's shallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, an April 15 poll by Louis Harris &AMP; Associates found that
76 percent of Americans who have had direct contact with IRS
employees said they were treated fairly.
</P>
<P>
   Coggins, the Dallas prosecutor, said he would gladly have given
the government's side, if called. ``I sat by the phone thinking,
`Surely someone from Washington will call and get our opinion on
this,' '' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
