<SLUG> BC-IRS-RECORDS-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING REDRESS FOR THE COSTS OF A DEFENSE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Okla.)  (af)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first test of a 1997 federal law that allows people to
recover legal costs of fighting ``frivolous'' criminal charges, a
federal judge in Oklahoma has ordered the Internal Revenue Service
and the Justice Department to turn over their records in a tax
fraud case that collapsed before trial.
</P>
<P>
   The case is extraordinary because the Justice Department dropped
all 21 tax and bankruptcy fraud charges against Richard Gardner, a
tax preparer in Tulsa, Okla. According to former tax prosecutors
and criminal tax defense lawyers, once an individual is indicted on
federal tax charges, prosecutors generally insist on a guilty plea
to at least one charge, however minor.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1997 measure sponsored by Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
individuals who prevail against federal prosecutions that are
``vexatious, frivolous or in bad faith'' can recover their legal
costs from the government.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Sven Erik Holmes ruled on July 7 in Tulsa
that Gardner had prevailed over the Justice Department, which
dropped the last three charges in January. That move came just as a
hearing was scheduled to begin on Gardner's motion to dismiss the
three charges on grounds of ``prosecutorial vindictiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   The record in the case ``does not inspire confidence'' in the
Justice Department and the IRS, Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner was one of three businessmen, including the oilman W.A.
``Tex'' Moncrief, who testified in April at Senate Finance
Committee hearings about IRS abuse of taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner prepares the sixth-highest number of tax returns in
Oklahoma, filing as many as 4,500 a year. In March 1995, at the
height of the tax season, armed IRS agents and federal marshals
raided his office, seizing all of his computers and files. Gardner
resumed business the next day with new computers, to the
astonishment of one IRS agent who told one of Gardner's employees
that he thought the IRS had closed the business.
</P>
<P>
   R. Thomas Seymour, Gardner's lawyer, said his client's office
was apparently raided because Gardner was chronically late paying
his income taxes and remitting taxes withheld from his employees'
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local IRS office regarded this as an affront,'' Seymour
said. He contended that the agency concocted false charges to
punish Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS would not comment on its conduct, but a Justice
Department prosecutor told Holmes that the new law was a ``radical
departure'' from two centuries of federal prosecution policies and
would invite a host of reimbusement claims by defendants who are
acquitted or against whom all charges are dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes set Aug. 14 as the deadline for the government to turn
over the records, which he will examine in chambers before deciding
whether to turn them over to Gardner. Whether Gardner could recover
his legal fees would be determined at a later hearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
