<SLUG> BC-CAR-GORDON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON STILL SAYS NO TO OPEN-WHEEL RACING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ To the absolute delight of his card-carrying
bashers, Jeff Gordon admittedly has considered abandoning his
lifestyle as a NASCAR rock star.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the reigning Winston Cup champion and current points
leader, has been approached during the past year about the
possibility of racing against Europe's elite in Formula One. He
also has seriously considered his open-wheeled options in American
Indy-car racing, only to reach this conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made it pretty obvious that I'm happy where I'm at and
with what I'm doing,'' said Gordon, lead driver for Hendrick
Motorsports' three-car Chevrolet stable and marquee personality of
the country's fastest-growing spectator sport. ``I've had several
phone calls and I have returned calls (about F1), but I think they
were well aware of what my position is and what my plans are.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon reiterated his desire to continue racing with fenders all
around while preparing for today's fifth annual Brickyard 400 at
the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. But the rumors concerning his
foreign intrigue, and vice versa, offer a fresh view of Gordon and
the attention his accomplishments have generated globally.
</P>
<P>
   Gunning for his third Cup championship in the past four years
and second in a row, Gordon will take a 62-point lead over Mark
Martin into the Brickyard 400. Winner of a series-leading five
races in 18 starts this season, and two of the past three, Gordon
and crew chief Ray Evernham appear poised to put a major
second-half points-hurt on perennial Ford nemeses Martin and Dale
Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his five victories, Gordon has racked up 12
top-five finishes in 18 starts. His average finish of 8.61 is best
among all drivers. He also has posted 16 top-10 qualifying efforts,
including five poles in 19 sessions. He has qualified on the front
row for eight of the past 10 races, and will start third in the
160-lap event today.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who turns 27 on Tuesday, has posted 32 of his career 34
Cup victories since 1995, the year of his first title.
</P>
<P>
   With all of that going for him, why would Gordon even consider
making the huge career transition represented by Formula One, or
Indy-car racing?
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the mega-million contracts, like the three-year, $35
million-a-year deal F1 icon Michael Schumacher signed with Ferrari
recently, Gordon widely is perceived as the only Winston Cup driver
capable of a make-over from Cup to F1. There has also been
speculation that Gordon and wife Brooke have grown weary not only
of the jealous boobirds among spectators who routinely greet them
on race days, but also of the loss of privacy created by their
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Green, owner of Team Kool/Green in the Championship Auto
Racing Teams FedEx Championship Series, thought enough of Gordon to
approach him about driving one of his Indy-cars for the 1996
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not? Is it still possible for Gordon? You're damn right,''
said Mario Andretti, the 1969 Indy 500 winner and 1978 F1 World
Driving Champion. ``I mean, the guy obviously has exceptional
talent. He would need the proper training. But top talent will show
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the winners, there's not that many guys that
are a factor week in and week out. He fits into that category. He
may not win every week, but he is a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon could have punched his ticket into F1 last year when Ford
Motor Co.'s Special Vehicle Operations division presented Gordon an
offer to go F1 racing last summer. The move would have served Ford
on two fronts _ by getting Gordon out of a Chevy Monte Carlo and
into a Ford-powered F1 car, and removing him from the Winston Cup
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, according to reports, was prepared to launch an
F1 program for Gordon _ just to keep him in the family.
</P>
<P>
   The wilder the rumor, the more pragmatic Gordon has become.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was making a serious effort at Formula One, I would have
been driving a Formula Ford about 10 years ago,'' said Gordon, who
rose through the U.S. Auto Club's open-wheeled, oval-track ranks to
become its Silver Crown champion in 1990. ``You just don't go and
compete with those guys. It would be like asking Michael Schumacher
(a two-time F1 champion) to run at Charlotte next week. It's
unheard of. It's not reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I'd like to drive a Formula One car, just to see
what it's like, I don't plan on doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The reigning powers in CART, Gordon said, dropped the ball on
his services after the 1990 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get into it at the first level, like Toyota
Atlantic or Indy Lights,'' Gordon said. ``But every time I talked
to a team or to somebody about driving a car, it was, `Yeah, you
can drive our car if you can fund it.' They weren't interested in
putting somebody in there just with the potential to win races.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony George's rival Indy Racing League did not exist then. So
Gordon pursued and landed a NASCAR Busch Grand National ride and
won rookie of the year honors in 1991. Two years later, Gordon
began racing for Hendrick Motorsports full time and full bore.
</P>
<P>
   John Hendrick, who is running Team Hendrick while his brother
Rick serves a probation for his part in a bribery scandal, said
Gordon has not allowed the buzz about his open-wheeled offers to
distract him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal this year was to win a fourth championship for Rick,''
said John Hendrick, whose brother also is undergoing treatment for
bone marrow cancer. ``We know that we have struggled in the second
halves of the season. So we have refocused ourselves, Jeff and Ray
and that team. They started off by winning and really dominating
the race at Pocono last week. They were awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon led 164 of 200 laps around Pocono Raceway, where he also
became the only driver to lead at least one lap in 14 of the 18
races run to date. Gordon also extended his streak of leading at
least one lap to 11 consecutive races.
</P>
<P>
   That's extremely bad news for Gordon bashers, and for the rival
drivers who believe Gordon and the No. 24 DuPont Automotive
Refinishes Chevy are operating in a whirl of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty much there now,'' said Jarrett, driver of the No.
88 Quality Care Service/Ford Credit Taurus, and runner-up to Gordon
by 14 points last season. ``But the NBA doesn't stop Michael
Jordan. (Gordon is) an exceptional talent with a really good
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Irvan, pole sitter for today's race, said he is counting
on Gordon to run strong at the Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, anything Jeff sits in he runs really good,'' said
Irvan, driver of the No. 36 Skittles Pontiac Grand Prix. ``They
have figured out something to make that Monte Carlo run better than
all the others, and better than almost all the other Fords and
Pontiacs, too. They've hit on something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
