<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-WORLDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite win, U.S. downcast
</P>
<P>
   Victory over South Korea tempered by setback against Lithuania
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Greece _ There was lingering disappointment on the faces
and in the body language of the U.S. players Friday.
</P>
<P>
   WoodAnd that was after they clobbered the South Koreans 88-62 in
the preliminary-round finale of the FIBA World Championship of
Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Putting their first loss in the tournament behind them proved to
be a difficult task. Even after pounding South Korea, the Americans
talked about missed opportunities 24 hours earlier in a two-point
loss to Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, South Korea was probably the weakest team we've played,
so we were supposed to beat them,'' said shooting guard Jimmy
Oliver. ``And Lithuania was the strongest team we've played, and we
lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'm not really overjoyed. People always talk about Michael
Jordan and guys like that who hate to lose. Well, there's a lot of
guys in the world who hate to lose, and I'm one of them, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I woke up, I was thinking about that loss. When I had
lunch, I was thinking about it. We felt like that was a game we
were supposed to win, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the United States finished the first round 2-1 in its
group. That is good enough to qualify for the second round, but
Lithuania (3-0) has a leg up on the United States going into the
second round, in which 12 of the 16 teams in the tournament have a
chance to advance to the medal round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little disappointed that we're not the No. 1 seed
after the first round,'' David Wood said. ``We're the least
experienced team in this tournament, and it showed in the close
game the other night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disappointment, but I'm not discouraged. We realized
after Italy played us close (in the final exhibition game) that
this wasn't going to be a cakewalk. It's a gift that the loss
doesn't hurt us. We're in the second round, so we go on from
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood said he hopes the loss has therapeutic value for the
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any coach would tell you that it's probably good to
have a loss once in a while like that,'' he said. ``It's like a
high-seeded college team losing right before the NCAA Tournament.
Sometimes, that can help.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt against the South Koreans. The United States was
in a tie at 15, then pulled away and was never in danger after a
15-6 surge put the U.S. ahead 30-21.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Sasser had 17 points to lead all scorers. But as usual, it
was a well-rounded effort by the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came to this tournament, our goal was to win the gold
medal,'' Sasser said. ``We'd be selling ourselves short if we
didn't think we could still do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the U.S. team goes into the second round as the No. 2
seed from Group C. Three teams each from groups C and D will vie
for four spots in the medal round.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina, Spain and Australia advanced from Group D. The United
States will play Argentina on Sunday, Spain on Monday and Australia
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team must look ahead, as its record after six games
will provide its seeding when the round of eight begins play
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans couldn't help but look back after the first
round and fret about what went wrong against the Lithuanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still feel like we're a better team (than Lithuania),''
Oliver said. ``If you don't think you can win the gold medal, you
shouldn't be here. If I didn't think we were a world-championship
team, a loss like we had to Lithuania wouldn't bother us.''
</P>
<P>
   As Wood said: ``The problem we had against Lithuania is that we
heard the game plan but it just went in one ear and out the other.
We didn't stick to it. We have to play smarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a situation where we have a good chance to win. And I
believe we're going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rudy Tomjanovich said the way his team responded to the
tough loss against Lithuania made him optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased with the way our team dealt with the
loss,'' he said. ``I could see the disappointment after that loss.
And we had a film session this morning to go over things that went
wrong. That's never an easy thing for a player. I didn't like those
things as a player. But you have to address the breakdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   If there were breakdowns Friday, the South Koreans were
incapable of capitalizing on them. They lost all three of their
preliminary games, and the average margin of defeat was 23 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
