A3208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-ELECT-500&AMP;AD     07-31 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-ELECT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIANS WHO OPPOSED RULING PARTY ARE FLEEING THEIR HOMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ For many Cambodians, a vote against the
ruling party in last Sunday's parliamentary election was an act of
physical bravery.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the party has apparently won, a growing number of its
opponents are fleeing their villages for the capital, Phnom Penh,
saying they have been threatened with reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   Their reports portray a climate of intimidation in the country's
thousands of isolated villages that political analysts said could
have contributed to the victory of the incumbent leader, Hun Sen.
The frightened villagers said they were supporters of Hun Sen's
chief rivals, Prince Norodom Ranariddh or Sam Rainsy.
</P>
<P>
   Though two dozen people were reportedly killed during the
month-long election campaign, human rights groups said Friday that
they had not received any confirmed reports of violence since the
election. But given Cambodia's history of political killings,
threats alone appeared to have been enough to sow fear.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary vote counts give Hun Sen's party a commanding lead,
but not enough to form a government without forming a coalition.
The three parties are engaged in a round of negotiations and mutual
recriminations.
</P>
<P>
   The reported threats included harassment by armed and sometimes
drunken men, nocturnal visits and reminders of past political
killings. Many of the threats were made in advance of the vote,
promising reprisals later.
</P>
<P>
   An opposition member who said he had received death threats told
a human rights investigator that he stayed in his village just long
enough to vote, then fled to Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was told, `If you lose, you had better get out of here _
otherwise we'll kill you,''' the investigator said. ``It's the same
story again and again, except that it comes from all around the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   An opposition organizer named Chay Chum, a 64-year-old farmer,
said he had fled because village officials told him, ``When we win,
we'll take you into the field and turn you into fertilizer.''
</P>
<P>
   Another, Choeng Khemera, said he was told, ``When we win, we're
going to kill all you dogs and eat you.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman named Heng Layheang, who had organized an opposition
rally, fled her village Friday when armed men began driving back
and forth in front of her house on motorbikes.
</P>
<P>
   On election day, she said, a man tried to keep her from voting
by telling her that because the polling place was in Hun Sen
School, it was closed to opposition members.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, she said, her children were turned away from the
home of a neighbor who has a television set and were threatened
with being shot.
</P>
<P>
   A diplomat said one opposition organizer received a call on his
mobile telephone and heard only the music of a funeral dirge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult to judge whether these people are
legitimately afraid or are jumping at shadows,'' said a U.N.
official who spent Friday afternoon interviewing villagers who had
taken refuge at Ranariddh's party headquarters. ``A lot of it is
the history of this country. When someone makes a threat, they take
it seriously.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Most of the villagers who fled here are old enough to remember
the mass killings that followed the takeover by the Khmer Rouge
Communists in 1975. All of them have watched the reprisals of Hun
Sen's forces, who have killed at least 100 opponents since a coup
one year ago in which Ranariddh was ousted as Hun Sen's co-prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the reports of violence and threats, information
is accumulating from opposition party election monitors of a broad
pattern of small-scale cheating that favored the ruling party
during the vote count on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   These reports included accounts of barring opposition monitors
from some polling places and miscounting some opposition votes as
votes for Hun Sen's party. The two opposition leaders have
protested against election irregularities, and Sam Rainsy has
demanded a review of some of the results.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign diplomats and political analysts said it was impossible
to know how much effect either the threats or any election
irregularities may have had on the outcome. But they said they cast
doubt on the clean bill of health that a number of foreign
monitoring groups have given the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is that July 26 and 27 did not in any
way demonstrate an improvement in the human rights and political
climate in this country,'' a Western diplomat said. ``That
assessment is still pending, and premature judgments are not
helpful in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to Hun Sen's campaign of political intimidation since
the coup, the diplomat said, ``It is impossible to determine with
scientific precision what impact the past year did or did not have
on the electorate. But we cannot ignore the context of the
election.''
</P>
<P>
   A Cambodian human rights worker, Sophearath Khay, said she was
discouraged at the quick arrival and departure of foreign election
monitors who proclaimed the election a success, then left the
people here to face its frightening aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for the foreigner,'' she said. ``Their life is
always assured. If something happens, they can take an airplane and
leave the country. But the Cambodians, where can they go? I'm sorry
to have to say this. But it is important in creating human rights
and democracy to protect the people who believe in you.''
</P>
<P>
   One of about 20 villagers she interviewed Friday at the
headquarters of Ranariddh was a farmer from Kratie province who
said he had fled because members of the ruling party said they
would kill opposition organizers ``one by one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to transplant my rice crop, but I am afraid to go
back,'' he said. ``My wife was weeping when I left. She said, `What
will I do without you? We have nothing to eat.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she won't tell the children why I left because she
didn't want to scare them,'' he said. ``I am happy to suffer to
help the prince. But when I think of the fate of our nation, I want
to cry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
