<SLUG> BC-GA-EPASIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Need to replace tanks may shut gas stations
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- About 15 percent of service station owners who have
undergone recent fuel tank inspections say they'll go out of
business rather than pay for the costs of upgrading or replacing
underground storage tanks, a state regulator says.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those stations are owner-operator businesses, many of
them hanging on with thin profit margins in locations with less
traffic, said Randy Williams, manager of the underground storage
tank management program at the state's Department of Environmental
Protection. Larger operators are more likely to have prepared for
the year-end deadline for upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took care of it years ago,'' said Charles Allen, who
operates a BP station on Roswell Road. ``Most of the big oil
companies have taken care of their people, but the mom and pops out
in the country are going to have problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of compliance with various state and federal
regulations is steep:
</P>
<P>
   Upgrades of existing tanks average about $15,000; replacing a
tank costs up to $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning up leaks costs, on average, about $125,000 and can
reach $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to meet the Dec. 22 deadline for required upgrades could
result in fines of $11,000 per day.
</P>
<P>
   Those potential costs, plus the requirements for $1 million in
liability insurance, can be a business-killing burden for some
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mom and pop operations in rural Georgia don't have the
volume or the money to cover these costs,'' Williams said. ``Up
until now, about 50 percent of service stations have been
independents, but that will change over the next year or so.''
</P>
<P>
   While there's a proliferation of retail gasoline and convenience
store chains around metro areas and along interstate highways,
don't expect to see them take the place of closed stations on back
roads, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tend to stay away from the low-volume areas,'' Williams
said. ``If you want to take a ride in the mountains, you'll have to
keep a closer watch on your gas gauge.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
