<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRICKYARD-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUYENDYK IROC CASUALTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Two-time Indy 500 champion Arie Luyendyk was
scheduled to spend last night under observation at Methodist
Hospital downtown after suffering a ``slight concussion'' in an
explosive crash two laps into the International Race of Champions
finale. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two spectators also were struck by debris from the wreck, but
they suffered only minor injuries before, according to some
reports, [ reportedly]claiming the debris as souvenirs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The carnage began when reigning Trans-Am champion Tommy Kendall
brushed the outside wall exiting Turn 4. His car bumped into
Luyendyk's, prompting a half-spin and heavy right-side contact with
the inside wall in front of the pit entrance. Luyendyk's car shed
its bodywork upon impact with the Speedway's new PEDS
energy-absorbing barrier, creating a shower of shrapnel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk's orange car shot back across the track, where it
narrowly was missed by the oncoming Firebirds of Indy Racing League
champion Tony Stewart and seven-time NASCAR Winston Cup champion
Dale Earnhardt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The race was red-flagged to a halt for 39 minutes, 58 seconds to
clear debris from the cars and the wall. But Kevin Forbes, the
Speedway's director of engineering and construction, said the new
barrier performed as predicted. The wall was installed before the
82nd Indy 500 in May, but yesterday's crash was the first time it
had been slammed into during a race. &QL; 
FRANCE LIKES REVISED TMS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR president Bill France Jr. said he was ``pleasantly
surprised'' by reports on the improvements made to Texas Motor
Speedway in Fort Worth for the Craftsman Truck Series race on June
5.
</P>
<P>
   France informed TMS owner Bruton Smith during the Texas 500 on
April 5 that he wanted the water seepage problems in turns 1 and 4
corrected before the nighttime truck event. Smith responded with a
massive rebuild of the 1.5-mile trioval, a project that included a
reconfiguration of the controversial 24-degree banked turns and a
complete repaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read what some of the truck drivers said (postrace), and
apparently there was quite a bit of improvement,'' France said
yesterday. ``We didn't have any water problem there. I was
pleasantly surprised. Our issue when I was down there was the
leakage on the track, not the configuration or the transitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, TMS officials announced that the newly sponsored
Primestar 500 will run on March 28, 1999, preceded a day earlier by
the Coca-Cola 300 NASCAR Busch Grand National race. &QL; 
SCHRADER TOPS PRACTICE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ken Schrader posted the fastest lap of the final Happy Hour
practice for today's Brickyard 400, touring the Speedway at 171.363
mph.
</P>
<P>
   Second-round qualifying saw reigning Brickyard 400 champion
Ricky Rudd and 1995 race-winner Dale Earnhardt elect to stand on
their Thursday qualifying speeds, rather than requalify. They will
start alongside one another in Row 14.
</P>
<P>
   Among the seven drivers burning provisionals were 1988 Cup
champion Bill Elliott (37th); inaugural Brickyard pole winner Rick
Mast (42nd) and three-time Cup champion Darrell Waltrip, who will
start 43rd and last in his debut for car owner Tim Beverley of
Tyler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
