<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3217 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALCONS-BENNETT-COX     07-31 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-BENNETT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playing at a higher level
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Monday was ``Biscuit Night'' at the Falcon Inn in
Suwanee, where you could come listen to the testimony of a man who
had sinned a great sin and lived not only to tell about it but to
teach from it.
</P>
<P>
   The only criteria for entry was that you be under contract with
the Atlanta Falcons and check your skepticism at the door.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius ``Biscuit'' Bennett, an 11-year NFL veteran and the
Falcons' weakside linebacker whose offseason was the envy of no
one, attended the team's training-camp Bible study group, and,
brother, did he have a story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   You know Bennett, the longtime Buffalo linebacker who was
outstanding at Alabama, played in four Super Bowls, five Pro Bowls
and consistently played well enough, including the past two seasons
in Atlanta, to rank 16th in NFL history in tackles.
</P>
<P>
   But his reputation took a pounding in the offseason, when he was
found guilty of sexual abuse and ended up serving 35 days in jail
for a May 1997 incident in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Good player, bad man.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Biscuit, so named as a toddler who gobbled up his mother's
baking while growing up in Birmingham, is reborn, and he's here to
tell you the presence of Jesus Christ in his life has turned him
straight. Not only that, but he's not drinking anymore, which, he
says, means he doesn't have to battle through practice anymore
after belting down beers the night earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through that little struggle, I became a Christian, and that's
the greatest change in my life,'' he said. ``What comes with that,
you can't ask for anything better. I'm a 100 percent better person
that I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Bennett was talking about what the Lord has done
for him.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Bennett, who will be 33 in a few weeks, said he was
reborn almost a year ago. ``I surrendered at a preseason game in
Detroit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That was about three months after the incident involving a
female acquaintance and one month before he pleaded guilty. He
later was sentenced to 60 days and ended up serving a little more
than half when he was rewarded for good behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett did his time quietly, but only after some confusion; he
told the judge he had a problem getting his airline tickets
straightened out, only to be referred to as a ``fugitive'' on
Buffalo television. Other than playing some basketball, the man was
a monk.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked to the jail in handcuffs, all he had with him was a
Bible and guilt. Friday, as he walked from the Falcons' locker room
to a linebacker meeting just hours before the team flew to
Jacksonville for a pair of scrimmages, he wasn't carrying a
playbook. Again he was carrying a Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``(While in jail,) I had a lot of visits from pastors in Buffalo
I know,'' he said. ``I started a Bible study in my unit. I fasted
for two weeks. At breakfast and lunch, I didn't eat anything and
just stayed in, praying and reading the word. Sometimes, good is
persecuted and evil prospers. I think that's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility remains of a civil trial in connection with
Bennett's case, and he won't go into detail about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Devil is a smart spirit. When you're trying to do
something to get away from him, he'll put all kinds of obstacles in
the way,'' he said. ``When you think you're strong, he'll put
something in your face a little different from what you're used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's exactly the way things went down. I thought I was past
the point in my life where I had to go out and seek other
pleasures. But I found out I wasn't strong enough yet. The whole
incident was a misunderstanding. The truth is going to come out
someday. I'm never going to speak about my side of it, because it's
going to come out on it's own.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no denying an outward change in Bennett. He's quieter.
Perhaps a little more intense. More giving of his time to young
players. Fullback Bob Christian, one of the leaders of the Falcons'
Bible study, became a born-again Christian in eighth grade, some 15
years ago. He's been impressed by what he sees in Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the utmost respect for him as a veteran who has played
on an extremely high level for a very long time,'' he said. ``But
coming to our Bible studies, he's very humbled to say, `Hey, I'm
just a baby at this; you're going to have to help me out.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's shown this humility, which I think is a beautiful thing.
It's hard for us as football players and men in general to humble
ourselves and say, you know, `Where do I need help?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Falcons coach Dan Reeves has been helpful, sending Bennett in
the direction of team chaplain Charles Collins, who has been an
important person in Bennett's life the last year as he and wife
Kimberly work to mend fences.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett has some things working against him as he tries to make
the roster. He and middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle, 33, both will
carry salary-cap charges of $3.45 million this season, the two
highest on the team. Together, the linebackers' $6.9 million in cap
charges make up more than 13 percent of the team payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Bennett had 115 tackles last season, the
second-highest total in his career, and he added seven sacks. Plus,
the only alternatives are third-year man Craig Sauer, who has just
21 career tackles, and rookie Keith Brooking.
</P>
<P>
   So, no, Reeves said, Bennett's off season will not be held
against him. ``To me, it's done with; he's paid his dues. All I
want to do is see him not have any more problems. (The conviction)
really won't have anything to do with it. Talent, salary cap, all
those things figure into it,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling has always been when someone is part of your
football team ... you're going to treat them just like you would
your family,'' the coach said. ``If they got in trouble, or have a
problem, I'm going to do everything I can to get them help, rehab
or whatever. They make that mistake again, I'll get them the help,
but they're not going to be part of our football team anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett insists he was not among the legion of professional
athletes who saw himself as bullet-proof before, only to end up
fearing for their careers later. ``I've always been a cautious
person. I was a sinner, though. Now, however, with Christ in my
life, I can make decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   That's easy to say, but Tuggle sees some proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never see anything negative when you're around him. He
doesn't drink anymore, doesn't go out anymore. I think he's more
focused,'' Tuggle said. ``I don't think you'd change your life as
dramatically as he did because you're worried about your career
ending. I think he just looked in the mirror, saw that man and
wanted to make a change. He found himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
