<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-NEWS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons, Jaguars scrimmage today
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ When the Atlanta Falcons scrimmage the
Jaguars twice today in the shadow of Alltel Stadium, it will in
most ways be an extension of training camp. That is to say, it will
be a teaching camp.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons coach Dan Reeves and Jags' coach Tom Coughlin plan to
run players through many of the same drills they've been doing in
camp, except that the Falcons' offensive players will match up
against the Jags' defensive players and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   That means a lot of one-on-one, two-on-two, and passing drills,
in which receivers and defensive backs go at it without linemen on
the field. There will be some full-squad work, but there are no
drills scheduled that would involve tackling.
</P>
<P>
   In short, both teams are looking for an opportunity to have
players practice technique on people with whom they aren't
familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really and truly, you shouldn't see a lot of difference in
what we've been doing,'' said Reeves, whose team opens the
preseason Friday with a 7:30 p.m. game against the Tennessee Oilers
in the Georgia Dome. ``What I'd like to see is guys ... just play
their techniques and don't worry about playing somebody new.''
</P>
<P>
   The tempo shouuld pick up today, when the Falcons take the
practice fields next to Alltel at 8:15 a.m. and 2:15 p.m. The Jags
will join them a little later both times, as Atlanta gets in extra
special-teams work.
</P>
<P>
   For a couple of Falcons, the trip will be old hat. Center-guard
Dave Widell and defensive tackle Esera Tuaolo played for
Jacksonville last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing Tom Coughlin, and knowing Dan Reeves as well as I do,
it's going to be a very intense two practices,'' Widell said.
``It's going to be almost a game tempo, without any chop-blocking.
For me, it's not going to be much different, because I'm going to
be practicing against the same guys I practiced against for three
years ... although I won't be giving (Jags' tackle John) Jurkovic
the snap count all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves will spend most of his time with the Falcons offense and
might pay special attention to quarterbacks and rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' Reeves said, ``some of the guys who've caught
your attention ... will carry that (intensity) over when ...
they're not covering somebody they've been covering, or blocking
somebody they've been blocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
