</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-NOTES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons scouting team ready to hit the road
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- It will be a while before the Atlanta Falcons start
cutting players, nearly four weeks in fact, but the look of things
in Suwanee will begin to change next week nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Falcons' scouts will begin hitting the road as the
NFL preseason starts, and college programs kick into gear.
</P>
<P>
   These carpetbagging men have been hanging around most of the
last 10 days as training camp has gotten under way, but the time
has come for them to hit the road. They will trickle back into
Suwanee one or two at a time once in a while the rest of the
season, but never again will they all be in the same place at the
same time _ at least not until the NFL draft approaches next April.
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing to an exception will be when several scouts
show up for some Falcons' home games in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Area scouts Ken Blair, Melvin Bratton, Dick Corrick, Boyd
Dowler, Elbert Dubenion, Bill Groman and Bob Harrison and director
of player personnel/college Reed Johnson spend most of the time
scouting college talent through the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But during the NFL preseason, each man will be assigned two NFL
teams to scout. This kind of scouting normally is the province of
director of player personnel/pro Chuck Connor, national scout Mike
Hagen and assistant pro scout Les Snead.
</P>
<P>
   Their jobs will be to attend scrimmages and preseason games to
scout the ``bottom 30'' players on each pro team, or players ranked
higher whom are known to be trade material or on the verge of being
cut.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: If somebody who gets cut is better than what the
Falcons have, and the team can afford him, they might try to sign
him.
</P>
<P>
   What's next?
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will scrimmage the Jaguars today at 8:15 a.m. and
2:15 p.m. on fields adjacent to Alltel Stadium in Jacksonville. The
work will consist largely of drills similar to those the team has
worked on the first week and a half of training camp. No tackling
is scheduled, but that doesn't mean there won't be some. Slow and
easy
</P>
<P>
   There was only one practice Friday, a one-hour, 50-minute
morning session in which players wore helmets and shorts, but no
shoulder pads. Much of the practice was spent on special teams
work, and a little bit of situational practice where offensive
lineman practiced their assignments against stunting defensive
linemen.
</P>
<P>
   The good, bad, and ugly
</P>
<P>
   Good: Today's change of scenery. Everybody needs it, though
flying is no fun.
</P>
<P>
   Bad: The two fake field goals the Falcons tried Friday morning.
On the first, first-string holder Dan Stryzinski took the snap from
Adam Schreiber _ which was fine _ and yelled ``fire.'' He rolled
out right, and threw a pass to right tackle Corey Louchiey. He was
covered by safety Eugene Robinson, but the ball was in Louchiey's
breadbasket. He dropped it. Oh, the heckling. When the second unit
tried it, holder Steve DeBerg overthrew left tackle Travis Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly: Rookie Keith Brooking's nose. It's been broken at least
four times over the years, and when it takes a beating, it gets to
looking nasty. There's a big bump in the middle, and since
Brooking's been mixing it up, he's got quite a knot on his schnoz.
He says offseason surgery is likely.
</P>
<P>
   QB controversy
</P>
<P>
   This borders on ridiculous, but it was a very slow day. There
were a few notes in this space Friday about quarterbacks throwing
interceptions and there was hysteria among the prima donnas because
of it. Yesterday it was noted that DeBerg threw a pick to Jessie
Tuggle when there was no offensive player within 10 yards, and that
Chris Chandler had one get away from him, only to have wide-open
defensive end Lester Archambeau drop it. Well, DeBerg -- not
Chandler -- threw the gimme to Archambeau, and both passes, and
four others, were designed to be interceptions. Chandler wants the
world to know he didn't throw anything remotely resembling an
interception, and DeBerg wants it made clear to his legion of fans
that he was only doing what he was told. The Falcons were one of
just a handful of NFL teams not to return an interception last
season and coach Dan Reeves said, ``That was my brilliant idea,
trying to get the quarterbacks to throw interceptions without
telling anybody else so we could set up the blocking and so
forth.''
</P>
<P>
   What he said
</P>
<P>
   ``230! Man, your lower body weighs 230. I'm not talking about
your rookie year, either.'' _ Safety William White, responding to
linebacker coach Don Blackmon's contention that his NFL playing
weight was 230 pounds when he was with the Patriots from 1981-87.
Oops! Dronett's cool
</P>
<P>
   You won't find any surgical scars on the knees of defensive
tackle Shane Dronett. It says in the Falcons' media guide that he
had a surgically repaired knee in '95, the last of his four seasons
in Denver. Didn't happen. Neither Dronett, nor the Falcons are sure
where the information came from, but it was included in the
seventh-year veteran's file when he came over from Detroit last
year. More research on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Aches and pains
</P>
<P>
   Four Falcons did not make the trip to Jacksonville, and trainer
Ron Medlin has gotten to know them well. Cornerback Randy Fuller,
who has missed seven straight practices with a badly sprained
ankle, starting cornerback Ronnie Bradford (hamstring), who has
missed six straight, defensive end Barry Mitchell (quad), who has
missed six straight, and receiver Keith Crawford (hamstring), who
has missed two in a row, stayed in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The boss talks
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Falcons president Taylor Smith doesn't always meet GQ
standards when he shows up at practice in his workout clothes. But
he had good things to say after practice one day this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year ... the coaches didn't know the new players, or even
the players we already had. The players didn't know the coaches.
Nobody knew the offense,'' he said. ``This year, there's no
worrying about switching from the run-and-shoot, and no worrying if
we can understand the new defense. Everybody just seems much more
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Loving life
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Swayda is a happier man these days. He was drafted in the
sixth round last year by the Bears after playing defensive tackle
at Arizona State. But the 6-foot-5, 290-pounder played only at end
in Chicago's camp, and got cut. He started out at end in the
Falcons' camp, but since switching to tackle Saturday, he's working
at No. 2 right tackle behind Dronett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm better suited to play inside,'' he said. ``(The Bears) ...
didn't give me a chance inside. I wasn't very happy. I can handle
not making it as long as I get a fair shot at where I think I
should play.'' ... On the flip side, tackles Henry Slay and Mark
Campbell are getting some reps at end, where they're both way out
of position, because Mitchell's absence fouls up the rotations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
