<HEADER>
A3220 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-EPASTATIONS-COX     07-31 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-EPASTATIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EPA steps up hunt for leaky tanks
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Environmental Protection Agency has dispatched
inspectors throughout Georgia because service stations and other
underground fuel tank owners are not meeting federal and state
standards for monitoring tanks for leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Gas station owners have faced increasingly strict regulations in
recent years on underground storage tanks, which can leak fuel into
ground water and streams. The EPA has found 358,000 leaking tanks
nationwide over the last 10 years, including 6,500 in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 33,000 underground storage tanks in Georgia,
most of them owned by gas stations and convenience stores. Other
tanks are owned by wholesale suppliers, fleet owners, car rental
firms and others.
</P>
<P>
   The current round of inspections is primarily a check on whether
proper inventory records are kept that would indicate fuel
disappearing from tanks. But the EPA action also is a prelude to
enforcement of a more forceful regulation that requires upgrading
or replacing tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting the requirements is expensive, with costs ranging from
$15,000 for an upgrade to $90,000 for replacement. Ten years ago,
the federal government mandated upgrades for tanks to improve
corrosion protection and add catchment basins, automatic shutoff
devices and overfill alarms to prevent spills when fuel is
transferred from tanker trucks to the underground tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year-old deadline for making the changes _ December 22 _
is fast approaching. As of June 30, about half of the 12,000
properties in Georgia that have underground storage tanks _ many of
them gas stations, which usually have several tanks _ had notified
the state that they have made the upgrades, according to the state
Department of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
   Tank owners who don't upgrade by the end of the year face fines
of up to $11,000 a day per violation, and fuel distributors are
prohibited from filling their tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The stepped-up federal inspections in Georgia began as the
result of an EPA review last year that indicated the state didn't
have enough inspectors to handle the workload on a timely basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at all the states in the Southeast and at how
frequently a state could inspect all of its stations, and Georgia
was at the bottom of the list,'' said Mike Hollinger, manager of
the EPA's underground storage tank enforcement and compliance
program.
</P>
<P>
   At the rate Georgia had been inspecting underground tanks, a gas
station operator could go nine to 10 years without an inspection,
Hollinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Following the EPA's review, the state increased the frequency of
inspections enough to visit all facilities with underground tanks
once every four years. But that still wasn't enough to satisfy the
EPA, which says stations should be inspected at least every two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They simply don't have enough inspectors,'' the EPA's
Hollinger said. ``All state governments are short-handed, but
Georgia is probably in worse shape than others in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has 13 full-time equivalent inspectors, said Randy
Williams, manager of the EPD's underground storage tank management
program. This year, state inspectors have checked 3,000 facilities
with underground tanks, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA wants the state to consider setting up a third-party
inspection program similar to how automobile emissions tests are
handled, Hollinger said. The EPA's inspections initially are
targeting service stations near interstate highways, then moving to
stations in rural areas near drinking wells, ground water and other
vulnerable environmental locations. The EPA plans to inspect about
300 gas stations in Georgia through January and can impose
on-the-spot fines of up to $1,000 if a facility isn't properly
monitoring its tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The federal and state inspections will also serve to warn owners
of the upcoming deadline for upgrades. ``A lot of owners are
waiting until the last minute to upgrade,'' Williams said. ``It's
going to be tough to meet the deadline at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   The state won't begin inspecting for that compliance until next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure they know this deadline is coming up,''
Hollinger said. ``Time is getting tight, and it's possible there
could be a shortage of contractors to make the upgrades.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
