<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon vs. the Fords
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS -- If the momentum Jeff Gordon brings to the
Brickyard 400 today has anything to say about who wins, Fords,
Pontiacs and other Chevrolets need not apply.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is excited about the prospect of taking home a second
Brickyard trophy, not to mention a generous chunk of the $5 million
purse and a No Bull Five $1 million bonus if he should win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have some confidence coming out of the Pocono
race, going to Indy for the Brickyard,'' Gordon said, referring to
last week's victory at Pocono. ``I love this track, love being in
Indianapolis and racing at this facility and winning here again.
Getting back into victory lane is what it's all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've brought a great race car here,'' he said. ``It
kind of brings back memories of '94 to me. We qualified third then,
had a good race car with good horsepower and won the race. We've
got those things again. Hopefully, it'll pay the same results
Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Only thing wrong with that scenario is that this one seems
likely to be a Ford parade, led by Dale Jarrett, Mark Martin, Rusty
Wallace, Jeff Burton and Jeremy Mayfield. In Gordon's favor,
though, is that his has been the only Chevrolet able to stay close
in points, and now leads through the first 18 Winston Cup races.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Chevrolet teams each have won eight races this year,
with Gordon taking five of them. Pontiac has two, both by Bobby
Labonte. The Brickyard, however, has been even between Chevrolet
and Ford. Gordon and Dale Earnhardt won the first two 400s,
followed by the Fords of Jarrett and Ricky Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this should make for an interesting race,'' said Jeff
Burton, who won at New Hampshire three weeks ago. ``I really
believe this is going to be as competitive as any race we've had. A
lot of guys can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of those guys _ the No Bull Five of Gordon, Jarrett,
Martin, Wallace and Bobby Labonte _ have more incentive than any of
the others. There's the $1 million bonus waiting if one of them
wins Saturday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll probably see someone win that million,'' Gordon
said. ``There are too great a chance for that not to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no given, however. The keys to running fast at the
Brickyard are being able to charge off the equally shaped second
and fourth turns and then to use the long straightaways. Gordon
showed at Pocono last week that his engine is superior on the
straights.
</P>
<P>
   The aerodynamic drag is more pronounced in the Fords, but the
Taurus makes up for it with increased downforce, allowing them to
shoot through the corners cleaner than the Monte Carlo or Grand
Prix..
</P>
<P>
   ``All these cars are very difficult to drive in traffic, but the
Fords are better,'' Darrell Waltrip said. ``When I got behind a
Taurus at Pocono last weekend, I was stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
