<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3222 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASCAR-NOTES01-COX     07-31 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-NOTES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nascar Notes
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five in the hunt for $1 mil bonus
</P>
<P>
   Five drivers are in position to win $1 million with a victory in
the Brickyard 400 today. Jeff Gordon, Rusty Wallace, Bobby Labonte,
Mark Martin and Dale Jarrett were the top five finishers in
Charlotte's Coca Cola 600, making them eligible for the Winston No
Bull incentive program.
</P>
<P>
   If one of these five drivers wins the Brickyard, he will pocket
an additional $1 million from Winston.
</P>
<P>
   Craven's 100th
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Craven will make his 100th career Winston Cup start in
today's Brickyard. He edged Robert Pressley for Rookie of the Year
in 1995 while driving for Larry Hedrick. He has three poles and has
finished a career-best third on four occasions this year.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Spencer's recent charity golf tournament raised more than
$30,000 for police and fire departments and a battered women's
shelter in his native Berwick, Pa. ... At a luncheon Wednesday,
Indy speedway president Tony Stewart presented 1997 champion Ricky
Rudd with one of the original bricks from the track... Charles D.
Strang has been named national commissionerfor NASCAR, replacing
Semon E. Knudson who died on July 6. Strang recently retired from
Outboard Marine Corp., where he was director and chairman of the
management committee.
</P>
<P>
   BUSCH SERIES
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, others form BGN team
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon, wife Brooke and Ray Evernham have formed a
partnership to field a Busch Grand National team in 1999. The team,
with Gordon driving, plans to run as many as five races. Evernham
will be crew chief. Michael Landis, former parts managerat Hendrick
Motorsports, will be team manager.
</P>
<P>
   Temper, temper
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Purvis was fined $5,000; his crew chief, Johnny Allen,
$1,500; crewman Jason Taylor, $2,500; and Kenneth Campbell, crew
chief for for Brewco Motorsports and driver Mark Green, $2,500 for
a fight on pit road during last week's race at South Boston. In
addition, Purvis, Allen and Campbell were placed on probation for
the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   The Green clan has welcomed another Green to Brewco Motorsports
clan. The third generation Green joins his father, two uncles and a
grandfather. Tyler Green, 9, competed in his first motorsports
event at Windy Hollow Dragway in Owensboro, Ky., in the Junior
Dragster division.
</P>
<P>
   CRAFTSMAN TRUCKS
</P>
<P>
   A busy week at the track for Bliss
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bliss pulled triple duty at Indianapolis Raceway Park this
week _ USAC Silver Crown on Wednesday, Craftsman Truck on Thursday
and the Band-Aid Busch series for Michael Waltrip on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Newsworthy
</P>
<P>
   Live pit stops, permitting tire changes under green- and
yellow-flag racing conditions,got high marks from NASCAR in its
inaugural effort in the Tempus Resorts 300. ... Seventeen of 36
crew chiefs performed over-the-wall duties during stops at Pikes
Peak. ... Troy Selberg has resigned as crew chief for Liberty
Racing. Shop foreman Doug George is serving in an interim role. ...
Andy Houston continues to lead the Cintas Rookie-of-the Year
standings.
</P>
