<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX WANT VAUGHN, HARRINGTON SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Harrington has kept his silence about Mo Vaughn and the Red
Sox first baseman's accusations about general manager Dan Duquette
long enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be out in the public about all of this
because I didn't want to fan any flames,'' the Sox' chief executive
officer said Friday. ``But it's time for me to step up and say
something about Dan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing personal between Dan and Mo from Dan's side.
It's just not true, and if I thought there was anything of a
personal nature, I'd move in and do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make the final financial decisions for this organization.
It's my call on what we offer Mo for a contract, not Dan's. I have
input from Dan and from Elaine Weddington, but in the end, I have
to approve it, as I do with all of the 40 players on our roster.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington also said the Red Sox never have hired a private
investigator or asked anyone to look into Vaughn's private life.
``We have had Mo for 10 years,'' he said. ``If we don't know what
Mo is like by now, we are in the wrong business. I don't know where
(Vaughn) gets this stuff about being tailed by a private eye, but
it is dead wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said that in spite of all the stories circulating up
to the trading deadline Friday night, the Sox have not tried to
deal Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the best thing to do so people can follow it is to go
back to last season,'' he said. ``We made an offer (on a new
contract) to Mo, and he turned it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the year was over, we sat down as an organization and
mapped out the future. We set our priorities. Our No. 1 priority
was getting Mo signed. And that's the first thing we set out to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Thanksgiving, we thought we had a deal. It was inches from
the goal line. When we couldn't get it done, we decided that we
couldn't wait any longer to get our business done. We did that with
(Roger) Clemens, waited for him to make up his mind, and it cost
us. A lot of free agents that year made other deals while we were
waiting for Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Dan went down and signed Pedro (Martinez). It was
expensive, but we made the commitment. Then we signed our own
people that we wanted as a nucleus _ (John) Valentin, (Tim)
Wakefield, (Troy) O'Leary, (Nomar) Garciaparra, (Tom) Gordon,
(Jeff) Frye, and some others. They were key to us and on our list.
Then we went out and got (Darren) Lewis and (Damon) Buford and some
of the other players that have helped us out. Everything we set out
to do _ except one, sign Mo _ we got done.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why I gave Dan a three-year extension in the spring.
Because he got done what we wanted him to do. And I think the
results are showing. He's done an excellent job.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington says the Red Sox have not given up on signing Vaughn
and will take one last shot at reaching a long-term agreement when
the season is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offer we made to him last Thanksgiving ($30 million over
three years) would have made him the highest-paid first baseman in
the history of the game. He turned it down. The offer we made to
him in Denver at the All-Star break would have made him the
highest-paid first baseman ever. He turned it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say we gave him an offer he couldn't take, one he
had to turn down. I consider both of those offers great deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last January, I went down to Mo's house one morning and had a
cup of coffee with him. I told him that we wanted him to stay with
the Red Sox. That hasn't changed. Right now he wants more money and
more years on his contract than we are willing to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a risk we are willing to take. Rather than try to trade
him for a couple of prospects, we decided it was better to keep
him. We figured on the last year of his contract, heading toward
free agency, he'd try to have a big year, and if he did, it would
be great for our team.
</P>
<P>
   ``To trade Mo Vaughn would have been folly. Last fall (after
negotiations stalled) a couple of clubs inquired, but then they
didn't do any more than that (after Vaughn was arrested in January
on a charge of drunken driving, of which he was later acquitted).
</P>
<P>
   ``When the year is over, we will lock in on getting Mo signed.
But it is my responsibility to do what is in the best interests of
the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mo decides not to sign here, then we will use that money to
go out and get some other good player or players to make this team
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we are either third or fourth in the major leagues
on average in payroll spending. This year we are in the mid-50s
(million dollars). Next year, without signing anyone else, we will
go into the 60s with the contracts we gave out last year. We have
made the financial commitment to have a winning team and we will
continue to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan has fulfilled every ounce of strategy we had, except
signing Mo. And he has worked his tail off to do that. It's unfair
for him to be taking all of the criticism that some people have
(directed at him) for this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said Friday, ``All these stories about us trying to
trade Mo this week at the trading deadline are just newspaper talk.
We never had any substantive discussions on trading him to anyone.
Every offer we have made to Mo has been based on the economics in
the game at that time. We did this with all of the other players we
wanted, and they signed. I have nothing personal with Mo. We never
asked anyone _ private investigators, Major League Baseball, or
anyone _ to spy on his private life. It's simple. He wants more
money and more years than we have offered him. There's no more (to
the impasse) than that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Long, a retired Massachusetts state trooper now running an
investigative agency, LCF in Braintree, finds it hard to understand
all the noise about background checks on some players about to make
tens of millions of dollars. ``It is done all of the time in big
business,'' says Long. ``That is what our company does. We are
hired by banks, financial institutions, big businesses to look into
the background of people that they are about to make a big
financial commitment to. If they are stockholders in the company
like the Red Sox have (limited partners), then whoever is in charge
has a fiduciary responsibility to make sure that everything is done
to check out that there are no problems that might expose the
company to serious risk.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kraft has said in the past that he would not stay in
Foxborough for the long term if he did not get state help in his
efforts to build a new stadium there, so you can expect talks with
Hartford to heat up in the coming weeks. People within the NFL had
asked Kraft to hold off in trying to move to Connecticut until the
Massachusetts situation played itself out. He did that. Nothing
happened. Now Connecticut has a clean shot to get the Patriots ...
We told you several months ago that Bruins owner Jerry Jacobs came
to Boston to meet with club personnel about a new campaign to sell
tickets to fill the FleetCenter. That is why you have seen
newspaper ads featuring NHL coach of the year Pat Burns and rookie
of the year Sergei Samsonov promoting a special advertising section
on the Bruins in Sunday's Globe. The Bruins never have mounted an
aggressive ticket-selling campaign in the past.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congrats to Medford's Jack Riley, recently inducted into the
International Olympic Hall of Fame in Lausanne, Switzerland. Jack,
who had a great hockey career at Dartmouth, played for the US
Olympic team in 1948 and was a player-coach in 1960 when the
Americans won the gold medal at Squaw Valley. Riley coached hockey
at West Point for more than three decades. To date, only a handful
of Americans have received the international Olympic honor ... NFL
officials think the Dallas-Patriots exhibition game in Mexico City
this month has a legitimate shot at being the most watched ever.
Dallas played Houston in front of 112,376 fans in Aztec Stadium
four years ago, but the early indications are that this game could
top it ... For years, the local NFL Alumni chapter has used an
annual golf tournament at Indian Ridge (to be held Monday) to raise
big money for charity. So president Dave O'Brien and his board came
up with a great idea. Why not give something back to golf? So this
year a ``Team Spirit'' scholarship will be given to a Ouimet
Scholar who overcomes unique challenges to succeed on the golf
course. A group of Ouimet Scholars will be used to score this
year's tourney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
