u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UKRAINE-IMF-500&AMP;ADD-N     07-31 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UKRAINE-IMF-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF TEAM BACKS A $2.2-BILLION LOAN FOR HARD-UP UKRAINE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ An International Monetary Fund team announced
on Friday that it would recommend a $2.2-billion loan to Ukraine,
where the United States has showered assistance for much of this
decade but where the economy remains crippled by corruption and a
lack of reform.
</P>
<P>
   The loan, small by the standards of recent bailouts by the fund
but significant because of the political implications, will help
Ukraine cover foreign and domestic debt payments due in August.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative loan package is subject to a vote of the fund's
board on Aug. 24, and the expected approval would clear the way for
a first payment of $200 million to $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement announced on Friday followed visits to Ukraine
last week by American officials, including Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with President Leonid Kuchma, Gore said that
Ukraine would find it difficult to get an agreement with the fund
unless the country made bolder economic reforms. Ukraine has a poor
record in keeping its pledges, and in January the fund suspended a
$542 million loan.
</P>
<P>
   There was some question whether the steps announced by the
Ukrainian government this week to comply with the fund's conditions
would translate into action.
</P>
<P>
   Among the IMF's demands for the latest loan is a requirement to
cut the Ukrainian budget deficit to 2.5 percent of its economy. In
response, Kuchma has issued a series of decrees to raise revenue
and slash expenditures. But these decrees could be overruled by
Parliament, which is headed by an avowed opponent of the monetary
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the best face on the situation, an American Embassy
official said Kuchma had told Gore that he would push hard to
insure that the fund's conditions would be met. The embassy
official said that lately the Ukrainians had been presenting a
``very different tone'' to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming independent in 1991, Ukraine has been a critical
focus of Washington's policy toward the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   One of the early successes of American diplomacy in the region
was persuading Ukraine to give up its nuclear arsenal, which was
the second-largest in the Soviet Union after Russia's.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has sent about $250 million in aid a year to Ukraine
in an effort to insure its independence and bolster its economy, an
amount that has made Ukraine the third-largest recipient of
American foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has justified the assistance by
asserting that it would be difficult for Russia to become an
imperial power again without Ukraine falling back into its
clutches.
</P>
<P>
   But foreign investors, citing rampant corruption, have largely
stayed away from Ukraine _ the country has attracted a paltry $2
billion in outside direct investment. Industry and agriculture
remain almost entirely state-run.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But under Kuchma, Washington says, Ukraine has followed through
on two important counts.
</P>
<P>
   First, Kuchma is ambivalent _ but unlike Russia not hostile _ to
NATO expansion. And this spring he agreed, under pressure from
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, to cancel the sale of two
turbines destined for a nuclear reactor in Iran. That made
Ukraine's record on deterring the spread of nuclear arms much
better than Russia's.
</P>
<P>
   In canceling the sale of the turbines, Kuchma found an effective
negotiating tactic with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Kuchma has complained that his country was not
compensated sufficiently for the loss of the $45-million order or
for the loss of other commercial opportunities in Iran. Privately,
Kuchma has told Washington that Ukraine should be rewarded for the
cancellation in ``units of IMF funding,'' a Clinton administration
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the fund's mission, Mohammed Shadman-Valavi, who has
been in Ukraine all week, said on Friday that Kuchma had agreed to
one of the fund's key conditions but that it would take time for
his agreement to have an effect.
</P>
<P>
   The fund demanded that the Ukrainians close a major loophole in
their tax code that allowed energy companies to escape the value
added tax, a kind of sales tax. Shadman-Valavi said at his news
conference that a decree issued this week by Kuchma closing the
loophole was subject to parliamentary veto.
</P>
<P>
   It so happens that some of the most powerful members of
Parliament are managers of Ukraine's major energy companies,
including Yulia Timoshenko, who is head of the Parliament's budget
committee and president of Unified Energy Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Also, American officials said they were counting on the sudden
good will of the speaker of Parliament, Alexander Tkachenko, an
avowed leftist and opponent of the monetary fund. In a letter last
Friday, Tkachenko ceded Parliament's authority to pass the budget
to Kuchma's Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   But there was debate among some financial analysts and diplomats
about the legality of the move, since the Ukrainian Constitution
says Parliament must pass the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachenko, who was elected speaker earlier this month, has
spoken repeatedly of his disdain for the fund, calling it of
``dubious charity'' and intent on swallowing Ukraine's
independence.
</P>
<P>
   But American officials were somewhat optimistic that Tkachenko
would keep his word and allow the executive branch to decide the
budget, if for no other reason than a special deal between the
President and the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Just after Tkachenko was elected speaker, Kuchma rewarded him
with a big favor. Tkachenko was charged by prosecutors three years
ago with embezzling about $70 million of Ukrainian and U.S.
Export-Import Bank money. The government issued a decree that wiped
away the debts of Tkachenko's agro-industrial enterprise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
