   (NYT19) BOSTON -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2 --
INVEST-MASS-TRUST, 7-31 -- A preference for carefully managed
companies has produced success for John Laupheimer Jr. at
Massachusetts Investors Trust. ``I'm a little bit of a throwback,''
says Laupheimer, who has been lead manager since 1993; the fund
started in 1924. ``I wear three-button suits and bow ties. I'm a
pretty conservative fellow.'' (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2 --
INVEST-CO-CEOs, 7-31 -- Citicorp's John Reed, left, and Travelers'
Sanford Weill plan to share power. It is hard enough for investors
to tell whether many of the recent corporate mergers make sense.
But figuring out whether the power-sharing agreements made by top
executives of the merged companies will work is nearly impossible.
(Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WHITESBORO, Texas -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
AUG. 2 -- IRS-ABUSE, 7-31 -- In April, Tex Moncrief told Congress
that the IRS used Gestapo-like tactics in its dealings with him.
Moncrief was investigated after Billy Jarvis, his former
accountant, spoke to the IRS about his suspicions of tax fraud.
Moncrief says this was a breach of Jarvis' professional
obligations. (Mark Graham/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
