<SLUG> BC-CAR-IROC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN CHARGES TO FOURTH IROC TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ When it comes to the IROC series, nobody rocks
like Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   That became official yesterday in the first appearance of the
22-year-old True Value International Race of Champions Series at
the 2.5-mile Indianapolis Motor Speedway. Starting from the rear of
the 12-car field by virtue of his points lead, Martin methodically
worked past CART stars Al Unser Jr. and Jimmy Vasser to clinch the
victory and an unprecedented fourth series championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to me. It is the pride of my career,'' said
Martin, who has also won the title matching 12 drivers from various
forms of motorsports for a record-setting third consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of great days this year, and this one was
special,'' said Martin, ace driver for Roush Racing in the NASCAR
Winston Cup Series. ``I've been sweating this championship a good
bit. I wanted to make it four, because I can't believe this is
anything but luck. My luck's going to run out one of these days in
IROC. When it does, I'll be able to say I had my day.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who began the day with a 12-point lead over Roush
teammate Jeff Burton, needed only to finish fourth in his aqua blue
Pontiac Firebird to clinch. Martin moved into fourth on lap 16 of
the scheduled 40 making up the 100-miler. He passed reigning Busch
Grand National champion Randy LaJoie on lap 19, leaving two-time
Indy 500 champion Unser Jr. and 1996 Championship Auto Racing Teams
champion Vasser in his way.
</P>
<P>
   Martin drove under Unser, who was racing at the Speedway for the
first time since his Indy 500 victory in 1994, in Turn 3 on lap 28.
Vasser's lead at that point was 0.750 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Running laps at 155-plus mph and exploiting his drafting savvy,
Martin shaved Vasser's advantage to 0.175 seconds on lap 36. Martin
set up Vasser for a pass exiting Turn 4 on lap 37 and neatly moved
into the lead down the long front straight. Unser followed Martin's
draft, dropping Vasser _ who led a race-high 36 laps _ to third.
</P>
<P>
   Unser closed to within two car lengths over the final three laps
but fell 0.247 seconds short of what would have been a storybook
return victory before a series record crowd of 90,000.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, whose IROC titles have come in 1994, '96, '97 and '98,
finished with 86 points _ 29 ahead of Burton. Martin earned
$225,000 from a total purse of $760,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
