<P>
   (NYT19) BOSTON -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2 --
INVEST-MASS-TRUST, 7-31 -- A preference for carefully managed
companies has produced success for John Laupheimer Jr. at
Massachusetts Investors Trust. ``I'm a little bit of a throwback,''
says Laupheimer, who has been lead manager since 1993; the fund
started in 1924. ``I wear three-button suits and bow ties. I'm a
pretty conservative fellow.'' (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2 --
INVEST-CO-CEOs, 7-31 -- Citicorp's John Reed, left, and Travelers'
Sanford Weill plan to share power. It is hard enough for investors
to tell whether many of the recent corporate mergers make sense.
But figuring out whether the power-sharing agreements made by top
executives of the merged companies will work is nearly impossible.
(Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WHITESBORO, Texas -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
AUG. 2 -- IRS-ABUSE, 7-31 -- In April, Tex Moncrief told Congress
that the IRS used Gestapo-like tactics in its dealings with him.
Moncrief was investigated after Billy Jarvis, his former
accountant, spoke to the IRS about his suspicions of tax fraud.
Moncrief says this was a breach of Jarvis' professional
obligations. (Mark Graham/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2 --
PERFUME-FUTURIST-2, 7-31 -- Seeking the scent of the future, trend
tracker Lori Smith inhales the aroma of a basket of white peaches.
``Olfactive epiphanies, new kinds of olfactive communication,
that's what I look for,'' says Ms. Smith, who often speaks in
epigrams like ``coffee smells like dating to the generation that
grew up in Starbucks'' or ``purity is sexuality today.'' (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2 --
PERFUME-FUTURIST-1, 7-31 -- Seeking the scent of the future, trend
tracker Lori Smith sniffs the great outdoors on lower Broadway.
``Olfactive epiphanies, new kinds of olfactive communication,
that's what I look for,'' says Ms. Smith, who often speaks in
epigrams like ``coffee smells like dating to the generation that
grew up in Starbucks'' or ``purity is sexuality today.'' (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) FREEPORT, N.Y. -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2
-- LILITH-FAIR, 7-31 -- If a man tries to crash a festival of, by
and for women, he can expect to crash, indeed. Even in its second
year, when the once-stunning idea of an all-women's concert tour
has worn off, the Lilith Fair is still the summer's hottest ticket.
(Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2 --
CAR-SMART-ROVER, 7-31 -- Reversing itself, Land Rover now plans to
sell its new Freelander sport utility vehicle in North America. The
vehicle will arrive in the United States in late 2000, three years
after going on sale in Europe and elsewhere. American versions will
have a 2.5-liter gasoline-powered V6 and five-speed automatic
transmission. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2 --
CHIC-GUM-2, 7-31 -- Openly, brazenly, people are chewing gum. At
work, gyms, restaurants and clubs, gum has become the big cigar of
the season, largely because the taboo surrounding gum chewing -
that it's tacky, especially in public - has burst. ``Gum chewing is
definitely cool,'' says Ruth Hiller, a trainer at Peak Performance
in Manhattan. ``It's everyone and everywhere right now.'' (William
Lopez/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2 --
CHIC-GUM-1, 7-31 -- Openly, brazenly, people are chewing gum. At
work, gyms, restaurants and clubs, gum has become the big cigar of
the season. Part of the reason is that smoking is forbidden in many
places. But mostly, it's that the taboo surrounding gum chewing -
that it's tacky, especially in public - has burst. ``Gum chewing is
definitely cool,'' says Ruth Hiller, a trainer at Peak Performance
in Manhattan. (William Lopez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2 --
DRAWSTRING-PANTS, 7-31 -- If the styles coming down men's runways
over the past weeks in Milan, Paris and New York are any
indication, slouchy drawstring pants, reminiscent of pajamas, are
going to be big in spring 1999. From left, plaid wool drawstring
pants by Cynthia Rowley; black wool by Yohji Yamamoto; DKNY's
cashmere and wool knit. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BOSTON -- July 31, 1998 -- CHEERS-FADES-BOS, 7-31 --
Holding bags of mementos from their visit to the bar featured in
the popular series ``Cheers,'' toursists walk past The Hampshire
House. Off the air except for reruns since the famous ``Last Call''
episode in 1993, ``Cheers'' appears to have lost some its luster
among tourists. (Jonathan Wiggs/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
