training teachers, Ms. Shaw returned to a high school classroom in
search of insight into the problem gripping her profession. (Carrie
Boretz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) HARVARD, Mass. -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2
-- SIZER-EDUC, 7-31 -- Theodore Sizer, the author and strategist of
school reform. ``I take real satisfaction with the extent to which
some of the ideas which in the mid-80's appeared far out are now in
the mainstream,'' he says citing the notion that children move
ahead based on their performance, not their age. (Ed Quinn/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WORCESTER, Mass. -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG.
2 -- DEFERRED-DEGREE-EDUC, 7-31 -- Heather Humphrey, 19, of Dallas
teaching a jazz-dance class at the Performing Arts School of
Worcester in an intership arranged by Dynamy. Dynamy provides an
alternative to an educational institution for many young people who
are not quite ready for the rigors of college. They arrange a
structureed living environment, counseling and three un-paid
interships. (Kirsten Elstner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW HAVEN, Conn. -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG.
2 -- FUND-RAISING-EDUC, 7-31 -- Henry Hansmann, a professor at
Yale's School of Law and an expert on the economic and law of
non-profit institutions. Hansmann is not against university
fund-raising, but he says that student, universities and society
would be better off if universities spent most of their money now,
rather than investing it indefinitely. (George Ruhe/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2 --
PARENTAL-ANGST-EDUC-3, 7-31 -- Learning through educational games,
Eric Murray, 5, sits on K.C. Genzamer's while his brother, Jake, 9,
concentrates on the screen in front of him. Ms. Genzamer is a tutor
who charges $90 an hour and works with children ages 3 to 14,
offers study hall at her apartment so students can drop by to work
on homework. (J. Emilo Flores/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2 --
PARENTAL-ANGST-EDUC-2, 7-31 -- At the living room coffee table
Elizabeth Trindade works with her son, Lorenzo, 6, on his reading
and writing. After being told in late May that Lorenzo needed to be
placed in a special education class because he was failing
kindergarten, Mrs. Trindade went on the offensive. She has
dedicated her summer to keeping her son from falling behind in an
increasingly competitive academic world. (Thomas Dallal/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ENGLEWOOD, N.J. -- July 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2
-- PARENTAL-ANGST-EDUC-1, 7-31 -- Marley Skroce, 5, studies her
printing at the Huntington Learning Center. This learning center is
just one of the for-profit tutorial and education centers that are
becoming increasingly common in cities and suburbs. (Philip
Greenberg/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
