<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3247 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HALL-SINGLETARY-H     07-31 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HALL-SINGLETARY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Singletary making Hall enshrinement a family affair
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CANTON, Ohio _ For the first time in the history of the Pro
Football Hall of Fame induction ceremonies, a wife will present her
husband today in the nationally televised event at 2121 George
Halas Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Singletary, whose husband, former Chicago Bears middle
linebacker Mike Singletary, will be immortalized as one of the
greatest ever to play the game, will make history when she steps to
the podium and makes her speech before a crowd of about 15,000 and
an ESPN2 audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not nervous about it,'' Kim said. ``Actually, I'm
very excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband grew up in Houston, played at Worthing High School
and became a three-time All-America selection at Baylor before
playing 12 years for the Chicago Bears, who lead the NFL in Hall
enshrinees with what will now be 24.
</P>
<P>
   Singletary set a Bears record with 10 Pro Bowl selections and
earned a Super Bowl ring with the 1985 Bears. He was voted NFL
Defensive Player of the Year in 1985 and 1988 and NFL Man of the
Year for his involvement in the community.
</P>
<P>
   Some thought Singletary would select Grant Teaff, his former
coach at Baylor, or Buddy Ryan, his former defensive coordinator in
Chicago, as his presenter. But there was no indecisiveness about
his choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is Kim my wife and mother to our seven children, but
she's been my best friend since we met at Baylor,'' Singletary
said. ``She was my biggest fan. I wouldn't be where I am today
without her.''
</P>
<P>
   The Singletarys reside in Barrington, Ill., a Chicago suburb. He
sits on the board of several prominent Chicago companies and spends
much of his time traveling the country making motivational
speeches. He also has authored a book on fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Singletary's mother, father, brothers and sisters reside in
Houston. All are in Canton for today's ceremonies, which precede
tonight's game between Tampa Bay and Pittsburgh. The game at
Fawcett Stadium is being played in prime time for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Singletary, Minnesota free safety Paul Krause, Cincinnati
offensive tackle Anthony Munoz, Miami center Dwight Stephenson and
Philadelphia receiver Tommy McDonald will be enshrined, increasing
the membership of the Pro Football Hall of Fame to 194.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no greater honor that a football player can have,''
said McDonald, who was recommended by the veterans committee and
voted in by the 36-member board of selectors.
</P>
<P>
   Like Singletary, McDonald and Munoz made unusual choices for
their presenters.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald chose former Philadelphia Daily News sportswriter Ray
Didinger, who now works at NFL Films. Didinger covered McDonald and
worked hard lobbying voters to convince them to vote for him. Munoz
selected his son, Michael, who at 16 is already larger than his
father, who is 6-6 and 285 pounds. Walter Payton is the only other
inductee to be introduced by his son.
</P>
<P>
   Krause, who played 16 years and is still the league's career
interception leader with 81, will be presented by former Vikings
coach Jerry Burns. Former Dolphins coach Don Shula, who was
inducted last year, will introduce Stephenson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
