<HEADLINE>
CLINTON IN NEW YORK'S HAMPTONS TO GOLF AND RAISE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. _ Having tried in the White House Rose Garden to
blunt questions about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky,
President Clinton flew to East Hampton on Friday afternoon to relax
on the golf course and raise money on the rubber-lobster circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was traveling with his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who
introduced him Friday night at the Long Island home of investment
banker Bruce Wasserstein. Over not only Long Island lobster but
also tuna and lamb, the Clintons raised $600,000 for the Democrats
from guests that the party calls ``major supporters'' who have
``the highest level of commitment to the ideals of the Democratic
Party.'' Each couple contributed $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   The president seemed determined to shake his woes in Washington
and have a good time. After boarding Air Force One, he stuck his
head in the aft cabin where reporters sit and said, ``Guys, you got
to have fun this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons are guests at the estate of filmmaker Steven
Spielberg, who recently screened his movie ``Saving Private Ryan''
at the White House. Saturday morning, Clinton planns to deliver his
weekly radio address, pushing legislation that he calls the
Patients' Bill of Rights for people enrolled in managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Forbes, a Republican from Long Island, is scheduled
to join the president as he delivers the address _ evidence, one
White House aide said, that Clinton has not been rendered
politically ``radioactive'' by this week's developments in the
Lewinsky investigation by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The president plans to spend most of Saturday golfing before
starring at two more fund-raisers. The first, a party at the home
of Jonathan Sheffer, founder of the Eos orchestra, is expected to
raise $400,000 from business executives.
</P>
<P>
   Then Clinton plans to raise $300,000 more at the Amagansett home
of Alec Baldwin and Kim Basinger, the actors. That fund-raiser is
one of the Democrats' ``Saxophone Club'' events, aimed at a much
broader audience. Guests were asked to contribute $250, and the
Democrats are expecting about 1,100 people to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than spend Sunday on Long Island, as originally planned,
the Clintons appeared to be leaning toward returning to Washington
on Sunday morning in time for church, White House aides said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton has managed for the most part to shake his large press
contingent this weekend, and only the small, rotating ``pool'' of
journalists that is always nearby has stuck with him.
</P>
<P>
   Because so many reporters, camera crews and others travel with
the president, whose plans are disclosed on short notice, a central
White House office reserves rooms for them. In this case, it placed
almost all of them here in Hauppauge, more than an hour's drive
from East Hampton. There simply were not enough rooms available
closer to Clinton's retreat, aides said.
</P>
</TEXT>
