<SLUG> BC-DRUG-MERGERS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE REJECTS TWO SEPARATE DRUG MERGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ohio)  (lh) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge has blocked two mergers involving four of the
nation's biggest drug wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Stanley Sporkin of U.S. District Court in Washington ruled
Friday that McKesson Corp.'s $1.72 billion purchase of Amerisource
Health Corp. and Cardinal Health Inc.'s $2.41 billion takeover of
the Bergen Brunswig Corporation would violate federal antitrust
laws.
</P>
<P>
   The judge sided with the Federal Trade Commission, which argued
that the two combinations would create too much market power for
McKesson and Cardinal and would substantially reduce competition.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson, based in San Francisco, said Friday that it was highly
unlikely that it would pursue plans to merge with Amerisource,
based in Valley Forge, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Cardinal, based in Dublin, Ohio, declined to
comment on the possibility of an appeal. Both companies said they
would review the decision, which was announced after the stock
market closed.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Parker, deputy director of the FTC Bureau of
Competition, hailed the decision. ``Competition in the market for
drug wholesaling is protected as a result of this decision,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the commission asked Sporkin to issue a preliminary
injunction blocking the mergers, arguing that they would lead to
higher prices and reduced service for hospitals, pharmacies and
other drug purchasers.
</P>
<P>
   The two mergers were announced within five weeks of each other
last August and September and could have given the combined
companies control of 67 percent of the $64 billion domestic market.
The Cardinal-Bergen merger would have created the biggest drug
wholesaler, displacing McKesson.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts speculated then that the merger announcement by
McKesson, which followed the Cardinal deal, might prompt government
action and ultimately sabotage both mergers.
</P>
<P>
   The companies argued that their profit margins were declining.
They said their customers would still have had ample choices by
creating their own warehouses and buying directly from
manufacturers, as some big drugstore chains do.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth S. Abramowitz, an analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP;
Co., noted that the manufacturers were the big earners in the
pharmaceutical industry, not the distributors or retailers. He said
consumers would have benefited from the mergers.
</P>
<P>
   But government officials questioned whether smaller retailers
would have been able to defend themselves against the market power
of the giant wholesalers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, before Sporkin's ruling, shares
of McKesson fell $2.9375, to $80.625; Cardinal was down $1.578125,
to $96.0625; Amerisource rose $1.8125, to $76.125, and Bergen fell
$1, to $53.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts said that many investors had taken account of
the possibility that the mergers might be thwarted.
</P>
<P>
   They said the share prices of McKesson and Cardinal already
reflected that possibility but that shares of Amerisource and
Bergen Brunswig, based in Orange, Calif., might decline somewhat
when the market reopens on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence C. Marsh, a health care analyst with Salomon Smith
Barney, said that even without the mergers, McKesson and Cardinal
were emerging as ``the two industry superpowers.''
</P>
<P>
   McKesson has expanded into the hospital supply business,
reaching deals with two big hospital groups, Premier Inc. and the
Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corporation. McKesson has also announced
agreements with the Rite-Aid drugstore chain and American Stores,
another big retail group.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal, for its part, recently said it would acquire the R.P.
Scherer Corp., which makes drug delivery products such as gelatine
capsules, in a $2.2 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh said McKesson and Cardinal might look for acquisitions
among smaller drug wholesalers such as Bindley Western Industries,
which might cause government regulators less alarm.
</P>
<P>
   But David Risinger, an analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
said he doubted that the four companies would soon aggressively
pursue other major acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``All four companies are worn out'' after their yearlong duel
with the FTC, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
