<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-495&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND OFFICER SLAIN IN CAPITOL SHOOTOUT IS BURIED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Mo., Texas)  (lb) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Officer Jacob Chestnut of the Capitol Police was
buried in Arlington National Cemetery on Friday under skies
streaked with gray after a funeral in which hundreds of police
officers wept and laughed alongside dozens of members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not the way he died that made him a hero,'' Gary
Albrecht, the chief of the Capitol Police, told the more than 3,000
people who had gathered to mourn, ``but the way that he lived.''
</P>
<P>
   The funeral took place a week after Chestnut and John Gibson, a
detective with the Capitol Police, were gunned down in the Capitol.
Russell Weston Jr., identified by law-enforcement officials as the
gunman, remains in serious condition at D.C. General Hospital,
recuperating from wounds he suffered in an exchange of gunfire with
Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   At Chestnut's funeral on Friday, the sounds of music and
mourning filled the Ebenezer AME Church in Fort Washington, Md.,
where a choir of more than 300 in white robes sang hymns that
echoed off the building's vaulted ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Many pews were filled with uniformed officers from police forces
throughout the United States. Members of Congress sat in one
section and Chestnut's widow, Wenling, and his children, as well as
Gibson's widow and children, sat in the front.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut's flag-draped coffin at the front of the church was
surrounded by elaborate floral arrangements sent by police across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``J.J. Chestnut did not see people as white or black, as liberal
or conservative, as rich or poor,'' said the Rev. Grainger
Browning, pastor at Ebenezer. ``He saw them as God saw them.'' His
remarks were punctuated by shouts of ``Amen!'' and ``You tell it!''
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut's younger brother, Henry, remembered him as someone who
had encouraged him and inspired others. ``He had a way of putting
his hand on people's shoulder even when he wasn't actually touching
you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Chestnut noted that his brother's funeral had even brought
together resolute political opponents. When Browning asked those in
the congregation to turn to the person beside them and hug, the
Democratic House leader, Dick Gephardt of Missouri, and the
Republican majority leader, Dick Armey of Texas, embraced warmly.
Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., found himself hugging Speaker Newt
Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the church, Attorney General Janet Reno and
Louis Freeh, the director of the FBI, embraced.
</P>
<P>
   To the strains of ``Amazing Grace'' from a Chicago police pipe
and drum corps, Chestnut's coffin was placed in a hearse.
Accompanied by dozens of police officers on motorcycles and in
other police vehicles, the hearse traveled more than 20 miles to
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Along the route, hundreds gathered and saluted as the cortege
passed. Chestnut, 58, a Vietnam veteran who served in the Air
Force, was given full military honors. Gibson, 42, who was not a
veteran, was buried at Arlington on Thursday with the permission of
the secretary of the Army.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Weston's lawyers said they expected him to be able to appear in
court on Aug. 18 to face charges of killing two federal
law-enforcement officers. Judge Deborah Robinson authorized four
mental health experts, two for the prosecution and two for the
defense, to examine Weston in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials said Friday that a security camera
inside the Capitol's Document Room entrance had captured part of
the action that resulted in Chestnut's death. The tape shows an
attacker's left hand, gun drawn, and then the officer, who was
talking to a tourist, collapsing to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The killer, whose face is obscured by a wide-brimmed hat, is
seen walking through a metal detector and then moving the pistol
into his right hand. After a few steps, his body contorts, as
though he shot or was shot at, before he runs out of the picture
frame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
