<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-HOSTAGES-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN AND IRANIAN TRY TO BRIDGE DECADES OF PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A former hostage from the U.S. Embassy in Tehran came
together here Friday with one of the former Iranian students who
directed the seizure of the embassy for 444 days from November 1979
to January 1981, for what the organizers hoped would be a dialogue
of reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Rosen, a 54-year-old New Yorker who was the embassy press
spokesman when he was seized and is now executive director of
public affairs at Teachers College of Columbia University, shook
hands after two-and-a-half hours of debate in the UNESCO
headquarters in Paris with Abbas Abdi, his 42-year-old former
captor who later became an influential political journalist in
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   But about all they actually agreed on, at least in public, was
that it would take a lot more talks like theirs to overcome the
hostility of the last 20 years and build a better future.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we call the hostage crisis was actually something closer
to a defeat for both sides,'' Rosen said, ``but must both sides be
bad losers? Let's not dwell constantly on who did what to whom, and
when.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosen acknowledged that U.S. support for the coup that ousted
Prime Minister Mohammed Mossadegh in 1953 and restored the shah to
power from 1953 to 1979 had alienated many Iranians, but said that
neither Americans nor Iranians could overcome the past without
acknowledging mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Abdi did not agree that occupying the embassy was a mistake, and
said it was a spontaneous decision made by students who feared the
United States was trying to thwart the Islamic Republic that had
replaced the shah's regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``A nation deserves more apology than a handful of hostages,''
he said, but concluded, ``I hope the relationship between Iran and
the United States should go back to what it was before 1953, before
the coup.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men talked privately in Paris for the last two days
under the auspices of the Center for World Dialogue, a group based
in Cyprus. Hooshang Amirahmadi, president of the American-Iranian
Council, Inc., a Princeton, N.J., group that promotes understanding
between the United States and Iran, said his organization had
supported the dialogue as well.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen said he had decided to come because, he said, ``I sensed
the time had come to put a close to the 444 days that had caused me
great pain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing can replace a direct dialogue between the two
governments,'' he said. ``I'm convinced that two decades of
animosity between our two countries is coming to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The past cannot be altered _ instead we must focus on the
years ahead and endeavor to build a better future,'' said Abdi, who
was imprisoned in Iran for eight months in 1993 but would not
discuss that Friday. ``While the rhetoric of the U.S. government
has softened, deeds remain far behind,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In January, Iranian President Mohammed Khatami called for
cultural exchanges to bring down what he called a ``wall of
mistrust'' between the two nations, and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright indicated June 17 that Khatami might be a man
the United States could talk with.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's public talk was held under tight UNESCO security, but
even so four people who had managed to make their way into the
auditorium were forcibly expelled after shouting anti-Iranian
slogans and calling Abdi a war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Britain reportedly refused to grant Abdi a visa so that the
encounter could be held there, but France has been urging the
United States for months to adopt its view that Khatami's election
marked a fundamental change in Iran. French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine plans a visit to Tehran later this summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
