A3276 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-MILITARY-SPEND-N     07-31 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-MILITARY-SPEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES MILITARY SPENDING WITH CURBS ON RIGHTS ABUSES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIM WEINER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate has approved a $252-billion military
spending bill that includes an amendment barring the Pentagon from
conducting training missions with foreign soldiers who have
committed human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military conducted training exercises with 102 foreign
armies last year, according to Pentagon records. Some of those
armies _ for example, the Indonesian military _ have a record of
abusing their own citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, proposed by Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., would bar
the Pentagon from holding joint exercises with human rights abusers
unless the secretary of defense finds an extraordinary need to
waive the law. The Pentagon did not oppose the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The spending bill, passed by a 97-2 vote late on Thursday,
includes $1.9 billion for the open-ended U.S. military mission in
Bosnia. The House version of the military spending bill provides no
money for military operations in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate rejected a bipartisan effort to reduce the American
military presence in Bosnia and neighboring countries to 5,000 from
more than 8,500 by October 1999. The Senate also moved to require
that President Clinton consult Congress before committing any
military forces to the Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The United States' military budget is by far the highest of any
nation. While the final spending figures must be negotiated in a
conference among members of the Senate and the House, the spending
bill passed by both chambers would increase overall military
spending by about $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on developing and buying weapons would increase to
about $84.8 billion in the coming year from about $79.5 billion
this year, according to Pentagon figures. Most of the rest of the
budget is spent on military operations and training, equipment
maintenance, and salaries for the nation's military officers,
soldiers, sailors, pilots, support personnel and civilian
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate and House bills call for military pay to increase 3.6
percent next year, instead of a 3.1 percent raise sought by the
Clinton administration. The higher salaries would be financed by
cutting operations and maintenance costs in the Army, Navy, Air
Force and Marines.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill also includes a provision to deny visas to
foreign officials who have engaged in religious persecution, forced
abortions or forced sterilizations, a measure directed largely at
the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment barring U.S. soldiers from conducting joint
training exercises with military officers who have engaged in human
rights abuses arose from news reports about the Pentagon's liaison
with the Indonesia military, according to Senate staff members.
</P>
<P>
   In March, The Nation and The New York Times reported that the
Pentagon had been training Indonesian military forces in
specialized acts of warfare and counterinsurgency, despite a
congressional ban intended to curb human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian forces included a commando unit that, according
to human rights groups, had a history of torturing and killing
civilians. The Pentagon said at the time that the purpose of the
exercises, known as Joint Combined Exchange and Training, was ``to
train and engage and interact and gain influence with successive
generations of Indonesian officers,'' as one Defense Department
official put it.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress who said they had been unaware of the
program moved to end the instruction and ban the Pentagon from
``training an army that has been implicated in cases of torture,
murder and disappearance,'' in the words of Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
