<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McGwire homerless but Braves still lose
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- They ducked Mighty Mark. They never saw Real Ray
coming.
</P>
<P>
   While Greg Maddux kept Mark McGwire in the infield all night,
Ray Lankford reached Maddux for a three-run homer in the sixth as
the St. Louis Cardinals opened a weekend series with the Braves
with a 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   With a Turner Field record crowd of 50,662 cheering even
McGwire's foul balls, the Braves succumbed in part to a Walt Weiss
error, that kept the sixth inning alive and brought Lankford to the
plate. The victory went to ex-Brave Kent Mercker (7-8), who beat
his old club on his fourth try, allowing Atlanta just one infield
single through the eighth after a two-run Tony Graffanino homer had
given the Braves a 2-0 lead in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three runs against Maddux (14-5) were earned but the
Braves No. 1 starter is 2-3 since the All-Star break, despite
giving up just eight earned runs in 38 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals threatened in the seventh after shortstop Placido
Polanco singled and Brian Jordan made it to first on a two-out
chopper off the plate. McGwire worked a full count against Maddux
and then missed a knee-high fastball on the outside corner to end
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis went ahead 3-2 in the sixth, though the inning should
never have gotten to that point. With Jordan at first with one out,
McGwire hit an soft 1-1 grounder to shortstop which should have
resulted in a routine inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   But Weiss, in his first start since July 19, dropped the ball as
he took it from his glove to throw to second, giving Jordan second.
He still had a shot at the heavy-footed McGwire at first but Weiss
lost the ball again and wound up lying face down in the infield
grass. Lankford then fouled away one pitch before sending his 18th
homer of the year over the wall in the deepest part of right.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux has only yielded five homers this year and had gone 84
innings since giving up his last one. That came June 4th in
Milwaukee, a ninth-inning shot by Jeromy Burnitz.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux's first encounter with McGwire was classic. The big first
baseman pulled Maddux's first breaking ball into Cardinals bullpen.
Maddux next served a change-up that McGwire hit into the second
deck but foul. Maddux then came inside with his cut fastball that
froze him as umpire Bill Hohn called the third strike.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves went ahead 2-0 in the third on Graffanino's fifth
homer of the year. Weiss singled in his first at-bat, moved to
second on Maddux's sacrifice bunt and was still at second when
Graffanino came up with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   He took a ball from Cardinals starter Mercker before pulling the
next pitch just over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
