<HEADER>
A3279 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK01-COX     07-31 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pride is sent to minors
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Curtis Pride's first surprise when he came to work
was he was being sent to Richmond. The second biggest surprise was,
the Braves still had the option to send him there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very surprised,'' said Pride. ``But I can see their reasoning.
I'm the only player with options left. What about Chipper Jones?
Doesn't he have options? ... I'm kidding.''
</P>
<P>
   Pride took it well, but the bottom line is the Braves have to
demote their leading pinch-hitter (7-for-33) to create a roster
spot for the newly acquired Greg Colbrunn. The team gains a more
potent pinch-hitter (9-for-26 or .346) who can handle right-handers
and as well as left-handers and can play catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost speed off the bench,'' said manager Bobby Cox. ``That
kid (Pride) can go. Lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   It had been assumed, even by Pride's agent Joe Strasser, that
the outfielder's minor-league options had expired after his
three-plus years of major-league service. Braves research showed
otherwise. While outfielder Danny Bautista, who like Colbrunn is
right-handed, might have been an easier choice to send down, the
club did not want to risk losing him to waivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get (Pride) back before (Aug.) 31, he's on everybody's
playoff roster,'' said Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Pride had made 16 starts with the Braves, hitting .275 with five
doubles and three homers and had gone 4-for-4 for stolen bases.
Since coming off the DL July 15 where he recovered from a lacerated
finger, Pride was hitting .476 (10-for-21), a heck of an average to
ship to Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be back September 1, but I'd like to be back up before
that,'' Pride said, ``because I want to contribute. I want to help
the team. They need a left-handed hitter with some power and speed.
I have no control over the situation but to go down to triple-A and
play hard and whatever happens, happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get on that plane
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Rockies had bussed to new Denver International
Airport Thursday evening to board a charter for Chicago, when a
club official approached Colbrunn and said, ``Hold on for a
second.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus played out the Braves' re-acquisition of their former top
right-handed reserve hitter, who walked into the Braves clubhouse
Friday to find his same old uniform (No. 23) he left behind when
the club failed to retain him last winter. After the Braves made a
low opening offer to Colbrunn, he turned to the open market where
he found a buyer's market for free agent first basemen. With Andres
Galarraga and Hal Morris finding the big contracts, Colbrunn wound
up signing a minor-league deal worth only $600,000 with Colorado
(after making $750,000 in 1997) as an insurance policy behind
rookie Todd Helton.
</P>
<P>
   After appearing in 61 games with the Rockies, he found himself
in the role he has tried to avoid _ right-handed bench player. As a
Brave, he'll get less time behind Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have more playing time but, I mean, its a job and
it's a role,'' Colbrunn said. ``As a player who's done what I've
done the last couple years, you don't ever want to say you're a
role-player or a bench player because then you become used to it.
You always want to strive for more.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers job secure
</P>
<P>
   General manager John Schuerholz said the club intends to keep
Mark Wohlers on the active roster in Atlanta. Then he reiterated
that with Wohlers' five years of experience, the club has no other
option. Wohlers stated Thursday he has no intention of returning to
the minors to find his control.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the reality,'' Schuerholz said. ``There's nothing
to do about that but hope that he gets better and hope that he
makes progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
