<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224.
WASHINGTON, July 31 -- The following chart shows how senators and
house representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the
last week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: GUNSAFETY
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, July 21, the Senate voted, 61-39, to table, or set
aside, an amendment that would have required handguns to be sold
with child-proof safety devices. Supporters said the amendment
would protect children from handgun accidents. Opponents said the
amendment was an unnecessary federal regulation and would not
accomplish its purpose. A ``yes'' vote favors setting aside, or
rejecting, the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: GUNS
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, July 22, the Senate voted, 69-31, to table, or set
aside, a measure that would have allowed federal prosecution of gun
owners whose weapons were used by children in a crime, if the guns
were stored insecurely. Supporters said the measure would have kept
guns out of children's hands by requiring people to keep their guns
out of reach. Opponents argued that innocent people could have been
held responsible if children found a way to access the guns, even
if the weapons were properly stored. A ``yes'' vote favors setting
aside, or rejecting, the measure.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
<P>
   --- ---
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: PATIENTS
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, July 24, the House approved, 216-210, a
Republican-sponsored patients' rights bill that would allow
patients to seek pediatric and gynecological care, complain when
they believe they have been denied adequate care and require
insurances to pay for reasonable emergency room visits. Supporters
said the bill would provide greater access to managed care and
allow people to set up tax-free medical savings accounts. Opponents
criticized the bill for not allowing chronically-ill patients to
visit medical specialists and for not protecting people who buy
individual insurance plans. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: GAYRIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 214-212, an amendment that
would effectively end federal housing support for San Francisco.
The measure would amend a housing appropriations bill by
prohibiting the use of federal funds ``to implement'' a San
Francisco regulation that requires all employers doing business
with the city to provide health and other benefits to same-sex
partners. Supporters said businesses should not be forced to adopt
policies they find morally objectionable. Opponents argued the
amendment was bigoted. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: HOUSING
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday passed, 259-164, a $94 billion veterans
and public housing spending bill that overhauls federal housing
policy and restricts spending on environmental programs. Supporters
said the bill provides needed spending for veterans' programs and
maintains the commitment to providing access to housing for
low-income families. Opponents said the bill fails to go far enough
to meet the needs of the environment and welfare-to-work programs.
A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: TRANSPORT
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday passed, 391-25, a $46 billion
transportation spending bill that provides more highway money,
increases funding for aviation improvements and supports Amtrak's
recovery plan. Supporters said it will help ensure that
transportation and safety needs will be met in the next century.
Opponents criticized the bill because it increases funding for air
and rail systems but reduces funding to the U.S. Coast Guard. A
``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4
</P>
<P>
   --- --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   The attendance record tracks the cumulative attendance of
members to date when they are physically present for roll call
votes.
</P>
