<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRICKYARD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Race puts Indy back on map
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's popularity, storied speedway boost Brickyard 400
stature
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INDIANAPOLIS _ While talking to a group of reporters on pit row
Friday, Rusty Wallace said he thought the Brickyard 400 soon would
equal the Indianapolis 500 in importance and interest.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted one reporter to say, ``No, Rusty. I don't think
the Indy 500 will ever be this popular again.''
</P>
<P>
   In its fifth year, the Brickyard 400 has become one of the
biggest races in America. Only the Daytona 500 still could be
considered more important and more prestigious than today's Winston
Cup event at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300,000 rabid NASCAR fans will fill the historic
speedway to see the 160-lap race every driver dreams of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I can describe what it would mean to win this
race,'' said John Andretti, who also has raced here in the Indy
500. ``It would be an emotional high you can't get anywhere else.
It's like trying to describe what it's like when you have your
first child. You don't know what a wonderful feeling it is until
you go through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Rudd experienced that feeling last year when he won the
event in his Tide Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something special about Indy that you don't feel at
any other track,'' Rudd said. ``It's kind of like walking into an
old ballpark, realizing all the greats who have played there. I
know one day when I'm through driving, I will come back and see my
name in that infield museum and be proud. It's something special to
win here.''
</P>
<P>
   Four drivers _ Jerry Nadeau, Steve Park, Buckshot Jones and
Kenny Irwin Jr. _ will be competing at Indianapolis for the first
time. For Irwin, who grew up in Indianapolis, just competing at
Indy is a dream come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad has wanted me to race here since the day I was born,''
said Irwin, who will start on the outside of row 2 in the Texaco
Ford. ``It's so special to me and my family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Driving here is just as challenging as I thought it would be.
Turn 1 takes a lot of nerve. It's like a tunnel because you can't
see your way out when you enter it. This track really lends itself
to experience. Starting in front is important, but it's only half
the battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting at the front of the 43-car field today will be Ernie
Irvan, who won the pole for the second consecutive year. But Irvan
has yet to win this race.
</P>
<P>
   The clear favorite to win today would have to be Jeff Gordon,
who will start on the inside of row 2. Gordon, the defending
Winston Cup champion and the points leader this season, won the
inaugural Brickyard 400 in 1994. He is coming off a victory last
week in the Pennsylvania 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff has set the standard, and it's up to us to go out there
and beat him,'' said Wallace, who will start on the outside of row
7 today. ``His team has it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has a 62-point lead over Mark Martin and a 128-point
advantage over Dale Jarrett, the only two drivers who are within
one race's points value of Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't slip much and still have a shot at it,'' Jarrett
said. ``We have to do like we did last year when we won five of the
last 15 races.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett won the Brickyard 400 in 1996 and came close to winning
two other times at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``With two thirds and a first, I feel like I know what it takes
to get around this place,'' said Jarrett, the only driver who has
won the Daytona 500 and the Brickyard 400 in the same year. ``It's
a fun race track for us. The last three years really have been good
here.''
</P>
<P>
   A win today would be better financially for Jarrett than any
victory in his career. The winner will earn more than $500,000 out
of a $5 million purse, but five drivers have a chance to take home
an extra $1 million in the Winston No Bull 5 promotion.
</P>
<P>
   The top five finishers from the Coca-Cola 600 at Charlotte in
May _ Gordon, Bobby Labonte, Rusty Wallace, Martin and Jarrett _
can win the $1 million bonus if they win at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't let something like that cause you to take
chances you normally wouldn't take,'' Jarrett said. ``We still have
to focus on the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's incentive enough here just to try to be the first
two-time winner of the race and add to the history of Indianapolis
Motor Speedway. It's just an exceptional place to race.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt, who won here in 1995, still finds it hard to
believe that the good old boys of stock car racing are driving at
Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought NASCAR would ever race here,'' Earnhardt said.
``But I think racing fans everywhere are glad we came. It's just a
tremendous feeling to say you've won a race at Indy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
