</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEIJING-OPERA-ART-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S PHANTOM OPERA HOUSE MAY FINALLY MATERIALIZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In a city where real estate prices have skyrocketed,
where developers compete to put up glitzy apartment complexes and
shopping centers, it is little short of stunning that this
capital's best-located empty lot has remained just that _ empty _
for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Situated across the street from the Great Hall of the People and
a stone's throw from Zhongnanhai, the secretive compound where
China's leaders live and work, this parcel of land is about as
prime as you can find in all of China. Today it serves as a sunken
parking lot for mail trucks, and is surrounded by dilapidated
shacks where a few dozen itinerant workers bunk.
</P>
<P>
   The news is that Beijing's leaders, in keeping with their
current efforts to appear more cultured than their predecessors,
are finally going to do something. They plan to build a world-class
opera house in this abandoned lot.
</P>
<P>
   But the real story is that the first plans to build an opera
house were made 40 years ago, then buried, revived, debated,
revoked and almost forgotten in an astounding maze of bureaucratic
wrangling. When approval finally came through for a theater
complex, the core of the plan was _ you guessed it _ the same as it
was 40 years ago: an opera house.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the torturous and winding path of China,'' said Wu
Zuqiang, a composer and advocate of the opera house.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese like to say they invented bureaucracy, and perfected
it over the centuries. In popular colloquy, there are innumerable
ways to describe official dawdling, like ``kick the leather ball.''
</P>
<P>
   But even for experts in bureaucratic procrastination, the
phantom opera house is an eye-opener.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a reminder of how complex even the simplest task can
become in China. Or maybe Chinese people just feel that way.
Wherever national, municipal and legislative bureaucracies mix it
up, there is bound to be trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it remains a question how long it will take to
construct an opera house, what with the political sensitivity and
national pride surrounding selection of an architect and a design
suitable for such an illustrious address.
</P>
<P>
   But Chinese leaders say they are serious this time. Current
plans, with a budget of $400 million, call for the work to be
completed in 2002. The project, to include a 2,700-seat opera
house, as well as a music hall and two smaller theaters, is called
the National Theater.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To gauge public opinion about the design, or perhaps to assuage
it in case an unpopular one is chosen by the committee so
entrusted, the authorities recently invited Beijing residents to
voice their opinions on 44 models. About half the proposals were
made by Chinese architects, and half came from overseas, including
four from the United States, three from Italy and three from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   All were displayed at the Museum of Revolutionary History, which
abuts Tiananmen Square. Shown in identical booths, the models
varied enormously, from an inventive bubble-shaped design to many
block-shaped designs. One looked like a near-replica of Lincoln
Center, another mimicked the Greco-Stalinist design of the
neighboring Great Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
   On the day the display opened, it was jammed with thousands of
curious viewers, and hundreds took the time to write out opinions
on blank white forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a momentous decision for our nation,'' said Yuan
Wenwu, one of the exhibition's organizers. ``It's important for our
leaders to know the opinions of the masses.''
</P>
<P>
   The first plan to build an opera house in Beijing came in 1958,
championed by Prime Minister Zhou Enlai, and was approved the next
year. Several lanes of low-lying residential homes were torn down,
and digging began on a foundation.
</P>
<P>
   But famine befell China in 1960, caused in part by a scheme by
Mao to speed industrialization in one Great Leap Forward by
creating backyard steel furnaces at the expense of farming, and
public spending on the arts seemed inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Digging resumed in the mid-1960s, only to be derailed again in
1966 by the fanatical politics of the Cultural Revolution, when Mao
and his leftist allies banned all traditional Chinese opera
performances, not to mention Western ones.
</P>
<P>
   It took until 1979 before efforts to build an opera house
resumed, and several more lanes of old homes were torn down. But in
1982, members of China's pro forma legislature, the National
People's Congress, pushed a plan to use the site for their own
office building. Proposals, counterproposals and
counter-counterproposals were submitted for discussion, yielding
little more than, yes, more discussion.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1990s, as a building boom enveloped Beijing, the
legislators were stymied by concern from the security-conscious.
The outpouring of protesters who had filled Tiananmen Square in
1989 made it seem unwise to create a place that would draw large
crowds of theatergoers to such a central location. The lot remained
vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Wu, a proponent of the arts who is a member of an advisory
council called the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference, said he tried to break the deadlock in 1996 with a
detailed proposal for reviving the idea of an opera house. He
credits President Jiang Zemin with pushing through the current
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Three finalists in the design competition are scheduled to be
chosen by Aug. 7, with a winner to be selected in the fall.
Construction is scheduled to begin next February. Then again, with
the history of the phantom opera house, it is anyone's guess if and
when that will actually happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
