<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-390&AMP;AD     07-31 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA AND PAKISTAN FAIL TO NARROW DIFFERENCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka _ An effort to open regular talks between
India and Pakistan on divisive issues including nuclear weapons and
Kashmir collapsed in acrimony Friday, with the two countries
accusing each other of setting conditions that made a sustained
dialogue impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to agree on terms for the talks came 48 hours after
Prime Ministers Atal Bihari Vajpayee of India and Mohammed Nawaz
Sharif of Pakistan met briefly during a regional summit conference
in the Sri Lankan capital, their first encounter since both nations
conducted nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, said by aides on both sides to have been stiff and
unsympathetic, ended with instructions to their officials to
discuss terms for reopening diplomatic talks that have spluttered
on and off through much of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But the foreign secretaries of the two countries announced
Friday that they had ended three rounds of discussions here without
breaking a deadlock over procedures for the talks. The sticking
point was the divided territory of Kashmir, as it has been
throughout the 50 years since the partition that created India and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The two governments pledged to continue diplomatic contacts in
the hope of breaking the deadlock and set an informal deadline for
reaching agreement, a summit meeting of the nonaligned states that
Vajpayee and Sharif are to attend in Durban, South Africa, in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif was particularly blunt, saying in an interview published
Friday in The Island, a Sri Lankan newspaper, that his meeting with
Vajpayee had accomplished ``zero.'' Sharif came into the talks here
apparently convinced that heightened international concerns over a
possible nuclear confrontation between India and Pakistan could be
used as a lever to force India to make concessions on Kashmir, or
at least to approach the issue more flexibly.
</P>
<P>
   He said in the interview that Vajpayee had rejected Pakistan's
demand that new talks should focus on Kashmir, a territory with a
Muslim majority that has been divided between India and Pakistan
since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   India's position, restated forcefully Friday, was that putting
Kashmir at the center of the talks would only ``highlight
differences, vitiate the atmosphere, and, therefore, likely disrupt
and jeopardize the entire process.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Sharif was adamant. ``If that was the position, what was the
point in having talks, because Kashmir has been the root cause of
all the conflicts between India and Pakistan,'' he said in the
newspaper interview. ``We did not want to hold talks for the sake
of talks but for the talks to succeed.'' Asked if there was a
stalemate, he replied: ``Yes, it is a stalemate. We are not here to
waste each others' time.''
</P>
<P>
   By ending the regional conference Friday without a formula for
broaching the issues between them, the leaders disappointed many in
the subcontinent and elsewhere who saw the nuclear tests, and the
angry polemics from India and Pakistan that accompanied them, as a
dangerous watershed. The United States, leading diplomatic efforts
to persuade New Delhi and Islamabad not to deploy nuclear arsenals,
has urged the two governments to open direct talks as soon as
possible to relax tensions and lower the risk of war.
</P>
<P>
   The acrimony brought a jarring end to the summit meeting of the
South Asian Association for Regional Co-operation, which also
includes Bangladesh, Bhutan, the Maldives, Nepal and Sri Lanka. The
meeting was held here under extraordinary security precautions
because of fears of violence by the Tamil Tigers, a rebel group
that has fought a protracted ethnic war for an independent state in
the north and east of this tropical island.
</P>
<P>
   The concerns prompted Vajpayee, for example, to bring in two
Indian air force helicopters for his own transport, along with a
force of several hundred Indian security personnel. Colombo, a city
of 2 million, was virtually paralyzed as entire areas of the city
were closed off, as well as a 50-mile stretch of ocean highway
connecting the capital to an Indian Ocean resort at the town of
Bentota, where the regional leaders met informally on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Several summit meeting leaders, including Vajpayee, struck a
note of self-reproach over the fact that the 1.3 billion people
represented at the meeting constitute a large proportion of the
world's poorest people. Vajpayee caught the mood with a phrase that
ended his speech to the conference Wednesday. Urging an end to
estrangements that have characterized the relations among almost
all of the countries meeting here, he declared: ``Let us grow rich
together!''
</P>
<P>
   But privately, officials of the smaller countries at the
conference said the energies that could be released by burying
historic differences would remain bottled up until the two
heavyweights of the region, India and Pakistan, made a turn away
from confrontation. One among many examples these officials gave
was the snail's pace that the seven countries have achieved so far
toward their goal of establishing a free-trade area by the year
2001.
</P>
<P>
   According to Indian statistics, only 3.7 per cent of more than
$140-billion in annual trade between the seven countries is
accounted for by trade among them, but efforts to create a
tariff-free zone seem likely to be doomed as long as India and
Pakistan refuse to even discuss ways of developing their minuscule
levels of trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
