<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3307 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-RAIL-440&AMP;ADD-NY     07-31 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-RAIL-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION PACIFIC TRACK-SHARING ORDER IS LIFTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Kan., Neb.)  (js) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saying that rail congestion in the Houston area had eased
considerably, the Surface Transportation Board announced Friday
that it would not extend its six-month-old emergency service order
on Union Pacific Corp., the nation's largest railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the order, issued in October, Union Pacific
was directed to share track in Texas with two competitors, Texas
Mexican Railway Co. and Burlington Northern Santa Fe. In addition,
Union Pacific was required to file special performance reports with
the board.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first emergency order issued by the board since it
assumed regulatory responsibility for the railroads in 1996,
following the dissolution of the Interstate Commerce Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Huge rail traffic jams, which were costing shippers more than
$100 million a month at certain points last year, led the
government to act. The tie-ups were chiefly a result of Union
Pacific's difficulties in absorbing Southern Pacific Transportation
Corp., which it bought for $5.4 billion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover has slowed traffic all around Union Pacific's
system, but the problems have been most pronounced around the Gulf
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Union Pacific-Southern Railroad combination created a road
that in the Houston-Gulf Coast area didn't work,'' said Edward
Emmett, president of the National Industrial Transportation League,
the nation's oldest and largest shippers organization. ``It created
gridlock.''
</P>
<P>
   While traffic has recently improved in the Houston area, he
said, ``some people are worried that if the Surface Transportation
Board pulls the remedies out, the problems will return.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Davidson, chairman and chief executive of Union Pacific,
said in a statement that the board's decision ``certainly confirms
that there is no longer a service crisis in the Houston Gulf
area.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, we aren't kidding ourselves about what's
ahead,'' Davidson added, saying that the company's job ``is far
from finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Shuster, a Union Pacific spokesman, said traffic between El
Paso and Tucson, Ariz., had been snarled recently because of train
derailments, but that the problem had been corrected. And a $400
million construction project, scheduled to be finished in October,
has slowed traffic in Nebraska and Kansas. But he said conditions
are clear elsewhere in Union Pacific's system.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Linda Morgan, chairwoman of the Surface
Transportation Board, said ``operational monitoring'' of service in
the West would continue, adding that rail service in that part of
the country ``is not at uniformly improved levels.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To insure a smooth transition, the board said shippers would be
allowed to use Texas Mexican Railways and Burlington Northern in
the Houston-Gulf Coast area for an additional 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   Three shippers requested an extension of the emergency service
order, which is set to expire Saturday. But Ms. Morgan said the
board had no legal grounds on which it could extend the Houston
provisions of the order. The shippers that requested permission to
get additional emergency alternative rail access were Entergy
Services Inc., an electric utility, and Entergy Arkansas, Inc.,
both units of Entergy Corp., and Cemex USA Management Inc., a
cement and aggregates shipper.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors said they recognized the board's problem. But they
expressed skepticism that the problems in and around Houston had
been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are better, I readily admit that,'' said Larry Fields,
president and chief executive of Texas Mexican Railway. ``But they
are not better than they were pre-merger. And the reason things are
better right now has more to do with the General Motors strike,
which has slowed things down. But we are about to enter our busiest
time of the year, and I hope the board does more than just watch
what is going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Sabourin, a spokesman for Burlington Northern Santa Fe, said
his company had not taken a position on whether the emergency order
should have been extended.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added: ``We remain convinced that the problems at
Houston and along the Gulf Coast have not yet been resolved.
Further action by the STB is required to assure that shippers are
able to receive, and Burlington Northern Santa Fe and other rail
carriers are able to provide, reliable and consistent rail
service.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same day that the Surface Transportation Board lifted its
emergency order, Union Pacific said it had postponed a planned
initial public stock offering for its Overnight Transportation Co.
</P>
<P>
   A poor market for initial offerings and labor unrest at the
trucking concern have weakened demand for the new issue.
</P>
<P>
   The company said a sale would be reconsidered when the market
for initial offerings improved.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Union Pacific rose $1.75 Friday, to $42. Still, in the
last 12 months, the shares have fallen 41 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
