<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stocks Resume Slide on Worries About Profits
</P>
<P>
   Share prices dropped sharply, more than erasing big gains from
the day before, on persistent concern about unimpressive corporate
earnings. Wall Street analysts said investors were finally
awakening to the effects of the slowdown in Asia, which could
diminish growth at home and stifle stocks for the remainder of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 143.66 points, or 1.59
percent, to close at 8,883.29. The sharp drop came a day after the
Dow rallied 111.99 points, or 1.3 percent. Broader indexes were hit
harder. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 22.28 points, or
1.95 percent, to 1,120.67, and the Nasdaq composite fell nearly 2.5
percent to close at 1,872.39.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Growth Slowed in Spring
</P>
<P>
   The United States' gross domestic product grew at a 1.4 percent
annual rate in April, May and June, the most sluggish quarter in
three years. But economists said the performance still showed the
economy's resilience in the face of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   New Microsoft-Justice Skirmish
</P>
<P>
   The government accused Microsoft of resisting requests to
provide technical information and to make 17 executives including
the company's chairman, Bill Gates, available for depositions as
part of the antitrust case against the software company. The trial
is set to begin Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital to Buy Reinsurer
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital plans to acquire Kemper Reinsurance Co., in a deal
estimated to be worth as much as $500 million. The acquisition will
broaden GE Capital's already strong presence in insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Crackdown on Options Trader
</P>
<P>
   Securities regulators in Texas, Ohio, Idaho and California,
aided by the FBI, have moved to shut down the Cleveland-based
Options Trading Group, a firm accused of defrauding investors of
millions through the sale of foreign-currency options.
</P>
<P>
   IBM Fined in Russia Export Case
</P>
<P>
   An IBM subsidiary pleaded guilty to illegally exporting 17
advanced computers to a Russian nuclear-weapons laboratory and
agreed to pay an $8.5 million fine. It is believed to be IBM's
first criminal conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Mass Layoffs at Korea Automaker
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai, South Korea's leading automobile manufacturer,
dismissed 1,569 employees, or 4 percent of its work force, making
use of new labor laws to cut wages and weaken powerful unions.
Hyundai is the first big South Korean company to dismiss workers en
masse, and other employees have gone on strike in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Worker Visa Vote Canceled
</P>
<P>
   Under the threat of a veto, congressional leaders canceled
planned votes on legislation to increase the number of visas for
high-technology workers.
</P>
<P>
   French Gamble on TV Sale
</P>
<P>
   For years, France's state-owned Thomson Multimedia was known
mostly for color television sets and losses. The government is
betting this will end with its deal to sell part of the company to
an international corporate alliance of Microsoft, Hughes
Electronics, NEC and Alcatel.
</P>
<P>
   Online Privacy Proposals
</P>
<P>
   Calling privacy in the age of electronic commerce a basic value
that ``must be protected,'' Vice President Al Gore announced
initiatives that seek to tighten the security of financial and
medical records and to protect the privacy of children who use the
Internet. But many of the proposals are simply endorsements of
existing bills, while others require new congressional action that
is, in some cases, uncertain at best.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
