<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-STATEHOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT BILL DEFINES OPTIONS FOR PUERTO RICO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska)  (lb) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Puerto Rico prepares for a plebiscite in
December, a Senate committee chairman on Friday released a
scaled-back draft bill that defines the three options:
commonwealth, statehood or independence.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was released by Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, who
heads the Committee on Energy and Natural Resources. Murkowski said
he had tried to use ``accurate'' and ``neutral'' definitions in the
bill for the plebiscite, which is to be held on Dec. 13.
</P>
<P>
   But Puerto Rico's governor, Pedro Rossello, said he did not
expect the plebiscite to be approved by Congress, because the
Senate would probably not pass a bill this year. The House has
narrowly passed its version of legislation that would recognize a
plebiscite, and Rossello has said he will use the House language in
the plebiscite.
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski's bill makes clear that whether Puerto Rico is a
commonwealth, or a territory of the United States, Puerto Ricans
are citizens by federal law, not by constitutional right, a
definition that commonwealth supporters vigorously oppose because
they argue that citizenship should be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   But Murkowski sought to allay concerns Friday by emphasizing
that Puerto Ricans should not fret about losing their citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as Puerto Rico remains under U.S. sovereignty,'' he
said at a news conference here, ``its residents will remain U.S.
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski said his committee would consider the bill in
September, after the August break. But he cautioned that few
legislative days remained for the Senate this year.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Ricans were granted U.S. citizenship in 1917 and their
island was incorporated as a commonwealth in 1952. They can be
drafted into the military but they cannot vote for federal elected
officials, do not pay federal taxes and cannot collect most federal
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed its version of the bill in March, and while it
includes definitions similar to those in the bill offered by
Murkowski, there are differences. His language is narrower and does
not direct Puerto Rico to hold a plebiscite or compel Congress to
act on it. Critics say both bills favor statehood, although
Murkowski tried to blunt that accusation with language in his
version.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello, who advocates statehood, has asked the Puerto Rican
Legislature in its special August session to approve his bill for a
plebiscite. If no U.S. law is enacted by December, Rossello asks
that the language from the House bill serve as the foundation for
the plebiscite, since it has already cleared that chamber. The
governor also said he favored the House bill, which Murkowski has
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello visited Capitol Hill on Friday to lobby for
self-determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Senate feels that this is a better version,'' he said,
``then the minimum the Senate should do is approve its version.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
