<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CORRUPTION-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAIL TERM FOR EX-MAYOR REVEALS A TOUGHER CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SETH FAISON  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The 16-year sentence given Friday to Chen Xitong, the
powerful former mayor and Communist Party boss of Beijing, is
intended to show that China's leaders are serious about cracking
down on the corruption that is eating away at the core of their
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Chen was found guilty by a Beijing court of corruption and
dereliction of duty, the state news media reported. He is the only
member of the party's ruling Politburo to be jailed since the show
trials of the so-called Gang of Four, the leftists who were ousted
from power 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Chen's demise is also the last chapter in a bitter,
long-running political rivalry with President Jiang Zemin. The fact
that it took three years to bring Chen to court reflects the
political sensitivity of his case.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, an intense power struggle led to the ouster of Zhao
Ziyang, then the party chief, after a military crackdown on
demonstrations in Tiananmen Square. Chen was known to be hungry for
the job, doing everything he could to distinguish himself to Deng
Xiaoping and other elder leaders who chose the new general
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Chen was the first among China's second tier of leaders to
publicly praise the army's crackdown, a ritual of kowtowing that
the rest of the nation was forced to follow in subsequent months.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the top job went instead to Jiang, then party boss of
Shanghai, a position that Chen apparently saw as inferior to his
own. The two men became intense rivals.
</P>
<P>
   In a political culture that demands traditional displays of
deference and respect for top leaders, Chen was known for failing
to act appropriately with Jiang.
</P>
<P>
   As the top man in Beijing's city government, and the man with
final say over building permits during a construction boom in the
early 1990s, Chen personally amassed a fund of $24 million, as well
as an extensive collection of private homes where he indulged his
taste for entertaining young female television presenters,
according to an internal report on his activities that emerged last
year.
</P>
<P>
   He was also implicated in a series of far larger financial
schemes that may have totaled as much as $2 billion, although the
sophistication with which officials shield their activities, and
the secrecy that guards senior leaders, makes an accurate total
impossible to ascertain.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's personal empire crumbled only after a financial scandal
in 1995 implicated one of his closest aides, a deputy mayor who was
soon found on the side of a hill outside Beijing with a bullet hole
in his head. His death was officially deemed a suicide, but the
exact circumstances were kept secret and inevitably stirred
speculation about the true cause of death. Chen was forced to
resign in April 1995.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Chen's son, Chen Xiaotong, president of a hotel in Beijing, was
sentenced last year to 12 years in prison for taking bribes and
misusing public funds.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Chen's personal secretary, Chen Jian, is serving a
15-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The court sentence orders Chen to serve 13 years in prison on
the charge of corruption and four years for dereliction of duty.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the official New China News Agency said Chen will
serve 16 years in total, but it did not explain whether this total
reflected a year of detention he had already served.
</P>
<P>
   The court also said Chen would be ordered to return bribes he
had accepted to the State Treasury, but did not specify an amount.
The state news media reported that, technically, Chen can appeal
the verdict in the next 10 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
