<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-MONTANA-ART-5     07-31 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-MONTANA-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDE-OPEN SPACES LURE THE BEST AND THE WORST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELENA, Mont. _ Montanans are learning that their ``last best
place'' label cuts two ways. It attracts land investors as
prominent as Ted Turner and Charles Schwab. But it also attracts
runaway loners as troubled as the Unabomber and Russell Weston, the
man charged with killing two Capitol Police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Montanans are now saying it is unfair for the nation to judge a
little-known state by its delinquents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't judge L.A. by O.J.; we don't judge New York by the
World Trade Center bombers,'' Andrew Malcolm, the spokesman for
Gov. Marc Racicot, said in the state's capital. ``Montana shouldn't
be judged by its kooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Montanans emphasized this week that many of their state's
notorious residents moved here from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Weston and Theodore Kaczynski, the convicted Unabomber, grew up
in Illinois. In trials of members of the anti-government Freemen
movement, based in eastern Montana, the state's juries have
convicted people who came here from Canada and from Arkansas,
California, Colorado, North Carolina and Utah.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s a sect based in California, the Church Universal
and Triumphant, moved to a ranch north of Yellowstone National
Park, dug bomb shelters and waited for the world to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy Weston isn't a native _ it doesn't have anything to
do with Montana people,'' Jim Allison, a retired cowboy, said this
week as he read a newspaper on Last Chance Gulch, the central
pedestrian mall in this former gold- and silver-mining city. ``They
had the same problem in Texas after the Civil War. Every renegade,
every outlaw, moved there. It got so bad they had to develop the
Texas Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   With a little prodding, Allison, a grizzled man in a straw
cowboy hat, admitted that he, too, moved here from out of state _
from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for the first time in decades, people who moved here
from other states now outnumber native-born residents of Montana.
Moreover, second-home owners are flocking to a state that is nearly
the size of California, but has only 900,000 inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   Boosters of Big Sky Country would prefer that Montana's name be
tied to these glamorous second-home owners: Stephen E. Ambrose, the
author and historian; Tom Brokaw, the NBC News anchor, and a slew
of Hollywood actors: Mel Gibson, Whoopi Goldberg, Michael Keaton,
Jeff Bridges, Andie McDowell, Meg Ryan and Dennis Quaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are drawn to Montana and Idaho because of the
isolation of the mountains, because there are fewer rules and
regulations, because there is a kind of mind-your-own-business
ethic out here,'' said Robert Balch, a sociology professor at the
University of Montana in Missoula.
</P>
<P>
   Montana is the nation's fourth-largest state in area (after
Alaska, Texas and California), but it ranks 44th in population. In
this state with only six people per square mile, automobile drivers
can cruise the Interstates in Montana during daylight unencumbered
by speed limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montana has a certain mythical attraction to it that allows
for 10 times as many people who live here to visit, to pass
through,'' Racicot said, referring to the 9 million tourists who
are drawn to the state every year, largely in the summer. ``The
fact about Montana is that a huge amount of open space provides for
a lot of privacy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some people say the Western penchant for self-reliance and small
government might have been why the state mental hospital apparently
did not conduct follow-up contacts with Weston in the 20 months
since he was released, in December 1996. Doctors at Warm Springs
State Mental Hospital released Weston after concluding that he was
not a threat to himself or to others, and with the understanding
that he would return to his family home in Illinois and continue
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montana has no more mentally ill than the rest of the nation,
but being so rural it is hard to keep up with them,'' said Dr.
Nathan Munn, a psychiatrist in Helena.
</P>
<P>
   But Racicot said the state was not at fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, the Illinois authorities did not reach a
conclusion that was distinctively different from Montana's,'' the
governor said. ``Apparently, the FBI and the Secret Service did not
see the need for a higher level of security.''
</P>
<P>
   T.H. Watkins, a professor of Western history at Montana State
University in Bozeman, also would not tar the region for its
deviants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy, like Kaczynski, is an anomaly,'' Watkins said of
Weston. ``He's a paranoid schizophrenic. I don't think the West did
it to him. Why do we simply assume that the West breeds these
characters? It doesn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
