<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVESTMENT-BANKERS-PROFILES-3TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4 PROFILES OF TOP INVESTMENT BANKERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Va., Mass., Minn.)   (af)  
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A decade ago, it was easy to name Wall Street's top
mergers-and-acquisitions specialists. They were swashbucklers who
craved the spotlight, and their role in major deals was often as
big as the chief executives'.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with investment bankers playing more subdued roles as
advisers and tacticians, identifying the cream of the crop is more
challenging.
</P>
<P>
   In an examination of the 25 biggest mergers this year and in
interviews with dozens of professionals in the mergerbusiness, a
handful of bankers emerged as standouts; by virtue of the year's
merger activity, their specialties are financial services,
technology and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   (Not included on the list are the heads of the
mergers-and-acquisitions departments of various banks; they can be
as much administrators as deal makers.)
</P>
<P>
   If these four bankers are not the best in the business, they are
certainly having the biggest impact. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gene T. Sykes may be the best-kept secret of Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co. And if it were up to him, he would keep it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Sykes is having the kind of year that most investment bankers
can only dream of. Since Jan. 1, he has: advised Royal Philips
Electronics on its pending $10.6 billion sale of Polygram to
Seagram; helped counsel Monsanto in the talks that led to its
merger deal with American Home Products; sat at the table on not
one, but two big acquisitions by AT&AMP;T, and helped defend the
Computer Sciences Corp. against a $9.8 billion hostile takeover bid
from Computer Associates.
</P>
<P>
   But the banker has not sought out the glory that this track
record might afford. Since his college days at Harvard, he has
known that he is constitutionally more comfortable behind the
scenes: although he was interested in politics, he was too
self-effacing to run for student office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to campaign for myself,'' he said. ``I like the
idea of having influence _ of taking responsibility for making
decisions _ but doing so with less public attention.''
</P>
<P>
   That preference led him to Wall Street instead of Washington.
Sykes, now 40 and a Goldman partner, counsels executives who make
bold moves without drawing himself into the spotlight. And his
desire to be near powerful people is a boon for Goldman's merger
business.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when C. Michael Armstrong was named chairman and
chief executive of AT&AMP;T last year, Goldman's telecommunications
bankers asked Sykes _ who knew Armstrong at Hughes Electronics _ to
arrange an introduction.
</P>
<P>
   Sykes did more. He read up on AT&AMP;T _ a company he did not know
well _ steeping himself in research before the team's meeting in
early November.
</P>
<P>
   At the session, the team convinced Armstrong that it could aid
him in his new venture _ which historically had been a Morgan
Stanley client. The bank ended up helping to advise AT&AMP;T in its
deals to acquire Teleport for $11.3 billion and Tele-Communications
Inc. for $31.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sykes can be elusive; he never reveals more than is absolutely
necessary. For two years, he chatted almost daily with Steve Stetz,
corporate vice president for mergers and acquisitions at Monsanto _
from ski slopes, airplanes, even a London hotel room at 3 a.m. But
when Stetz was asked to share a personal detail about the banker,
it took him a few minutes to recall that Sykes recently had
married.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gene is so confidential he doesn't even tell you what other
companies he works with,'' Stetz said.
</P>
<P>
   Sykes is at times clinical in his approach, and not inclined to
board-room histrionics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only saw him lose his temper once _ at 1:30 in the morning _
in a dispute over the TCI exchange ratio,'' said Laurence
Grafstein, a managing director at Credit Suisse First Boston who
worked with Sykes on both of the AT&AMP;T deals this year. ``The
episode lasted only 10 seconds and, although he raised his voice,
he still kept smiling.''
</P>
<P>
   But not every deal works out as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for instance, Sykes and bankers from Morgan Stanley
worked several months on a large technology transaction when, the
night before they were set to announce the deal, his client wanted
out. That deal was never struck.
</P>
<P>
   Sykes grew up in Los Angeles, the son of a World War II fighter
pilot who gave him the middle name ``Tiger.'' His father told the
young Sykes that he himself had wanted to be a tiger as a boy. But
that was just one of four explanations for the unusual name that he
heard growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep it on my business card,'' Sykes said, laughing. ``What
do you think that says about me?''
</P>
<P>
   That he is anything but a Wall Street drone. Indeed, it doesn't
take long for a conversation to digress into his true obsession _
outdoor sports.
</P>
<P>
   He was not athletic as a child; Michael Roberts, a Harvard
classmate who was best man at Sykes' wedding, said he used to tease
his friend that ``he must have been the last person picked on his
fourth-grade kickball team.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But since joining a rowing team in college, Sykes has been an
avid sportsman. As a young banker at Goldman in New York, he spent
lunch breaks running on traffic-heavy Third Avenue. He has also
competed in several triathlons, including two Ironman events, one
in Hawaii and the other in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   He backpacks for weeks at a time in Alaska, where he is on the
Nature Conservancy's board. He hang glides in Rio de Janeiro. For
his bachelor party last year, 23 friends from as far as Rome and
London joined him for a kayaking trip down the lower Salmon River
in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would depress me terribly to think I wrapped up my whole
life in business,'' he said, clearly proud of his athletic
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Sykes spends half his time in New York. But his home and his
wife, Tracy, who just finished her doctorate in physical therapy,
are in Los Angeles, where he has lived since 1987. He also has an
apartment in San Francisco, near Goldman's technology headquarters.
During their two-week honeymoon to the south of France last summer,
his wife requested that he confine himself to one business call a
week. He did.
</P>
<P>
   Sykes is thoughtful about his future. He is committed to
Goldman, Sachs, but might consider a job with a venture capital
firm one day.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, being a master of the 90s universe won't be his
legacy for the next century. ``We'll have to see what role fits me
then,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Frank P. Quattrone left Morgan Stanley Dean Witter to head
up Deutsche Bank's technology unit in 1996, the industry all but
wrote off Morgan Stanley's high-technology effort. Enter Chuck
Cory, 43, the banker who moved to Silicon Valley from New York to
take his place.
</P>
<P>
   How is he doing? So far this year, Morgan Stanley ranks No. 1 in
overall dollar value for high-technology mergers, according to the
Securities Data Co. Cory had a hand in such recent deals as the
pending $9.1 billion acquisition of Bay Networks, the data
networker, by the telephone equipment maker Northern Telecom, and
the pending $7.1 billion acquisition of the Ciena Corp. by Tellabs
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley's performance is quite a feat, given the sniping
nature of Silicon Valley, where bankers take pride in poaching one
another's clients. But Cory's no-nonsense approach clearly is
working in the fast-moving technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   Consider one recent merger negotiation. Cory and his client were
stuck debating price one night with the opposing company's bankers.
With no end in sight and the clock ticking to midnight, Cory stood
up, closed the briefcases of his colleagues and told the opposing
bankers he was going home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They chased us down the elevator,'' Cory said. ``Clearly there
are other ways that are more conciliatory. But you can't define the
middle ground unless you define what the ends are.''
</P>
<P>
   A lover of language and debate, Cory set out to be a politician
when he was a college student at the University of Virginia. But
after a summer internship at an investment firm, he completed his
MBA and obtained a law degree, then moved to New York City to work
for Morgan Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is extremely verbal,'' said Jane A. Risser, the corporate
treasurer for Bay Networks, who has known him for five years. ``He
is able to express the essence of issues very crisply.''
</P>
<P>
   Cory is a perfectionist who demands as much of others as he does
of himself. Once, when an associate failed to prepare a client
pitchbook to Cory's exacting standard, the book was redone several
times in a short 36 hours. And colleagues joke that it is difficult
for him to find a secretary who will stay for very long.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' Cory said, somewhat defensively.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of technology banking is grueling, even for a
high-energy deal maker like Cory, who has been known to take not
one, but two red-eye flights from San Francisco to New York in a
week. That is because deals today are measured in days, not months.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said, it took nine days to negotiate the $460
million merger of two technology companies, Scopus Technology and
Siebel Systems, and three weeks for the Bay Networks-Northern
Telecom deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small companies have a way of becoming the big companies,'' he
said, ``not in a metal-bending time frame, but in Internet
years.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, on Thomas C. King's second day in the
mergers-and-acquisitions department at Salomon Brothers, his boss
gave him his first assignment: to help the BellSouth Corp.in its
bid to acquire a license to operate a telecommunications network
for the Australian government.
</P>
<P>
   King, then barely 29 and fresh out of business school, packed
his suitcase and, along with 30 executives from BellSouth, left for
the first of what would be eight trips to Sydney over the next year
and a half.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, BellSouth had a $680 million deal, and King was on
the road to becoming one of a new generation of specialists in
telecommunications mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``Ice Man'' by one of his colleagues, King is known
for keeping his cool under pressure. It is not surprising, then,
that he has been involved in some of the highest-profile deals this
year; he was part of the Salomon Smith Barney team that helped
broker the $53 billion merger agreement last week between Bell
Atlantic and GTE, as well as the earlier $62 billion merger pact of
SBC Communications and Ameritech. He also represented Southern New
England Telecommunications when it agreed in January to be acquired
by SBC Communications for $4.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But he is probably best known for his work with Worldcom in its
$37 billion unsolicited bid for MCI Communications. On the Thursday
before Labor Day last year, King received word that the chief
executive of Worldcom, Bernard J. Ebbers, was coming to New York to
discuss the possibility of breaking up the pending merger of MCI
and British Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   King quickly pulled together a team of experts. It included a
proxy solicitor, to examine if the British Telecom deal was
vulnerable to breakup; lawyers, to evaluate the regulatory issues,
and bankers, to study several ways to value the companies. After
five days, they came up with a 125-page document that became the
blueprint for the Worldcom deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the meeting, Bernie went around the table and
asked us what we thought,'' King remembered. ``We said, `Yes, we
can do this.' '' On Oct. 1, Worldcom announced its offer.
</P>
<P>
   Donald R. Shassian, chief financial officer for Southern New
England Telecommunications, said he talks to King monthly, not only
to hear his suggestions about potential alliances, but also to
bounce ideas off him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not only reactive, but he's proactive,'' Shassian said.
</P>
<P>
   King grew up near Boston and worked as a broker for Smith Barney
before getting his acceptance letter to the Wharton School of the
University of Pennsylvania on the day after the stock market
crashed in 1987. Being a retail broker ``was really tough,'' he
said with a groan.
</P>
<P>
   But banking is no less stressful. To deal with that stress, King
runs _ including six marathons in the last decade. He has long been
a competitive athlete; he was recruited by the ice hockey coach at
Bowdoin College in Maine. He still plays on a team _ the Outlaws _
in a league at Chelsea Piers in Manhattan where, at 37, he says he
is one of the oldest players.
</P>
<P>
   King has a surprising aw-shucks quality more commonly associated
with Mayberry than Wall Street. A testament to his character?
Competing bankers actually like him, a rare situation among deal
makers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most important deal that J. Christopher Flowers
will work on this year is the one that affects him most personally
_ the initial public offering by his firm, Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Months before Goldman's partners voted to go public in June,
Flowers and a team of colleagues holed up to study the
partnership's options. But he took time out to represent Norwest in
its planned $34 billion takeover of Wells Fargo and helped defend
Mellon Bank when the Bank of New York announced its unsolicited
offer to buy the company.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers, a Goldman partner, has been head of the firm's
financial-institutions group since 1996, after serving as co-head
for two years. His team has been involved in almost all the largest
recent deals involving financial and asset management companies _
including the planned merger of BankAmerica and Nationsbank and the
pending combination of First Chicago NBD with Banc One.
</P>
<P>
   It was his idea to hire away Kendrick R. Wilson III from Lazard
Freres &AMP; Co., almost guaranteeing Goldman a place at any
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Richard M. Kovacevich, chief executive of Norwest in
Minneapolis, has been on the other side of the table from Flowers.
``I always felt at least Chris was listening,'' he said. ``He's a
good strategic thinker.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider Flowers' work in 1991, when Goldman was urging Banco
Santander of Spain to invest in what was then the First Fidelity
Bancorp., a big New Jersey bank. At first, the Spanish bank was
cool to the suggestion, but Flowers flew to Spain _ a trip he
thought was risky, because it was two days after the start of the
Persian Gulf war _ and persuaded company executives that an initial
$220 million investment would be prudent.
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Banco Santander acquired even more shares and hit
it big when First Fidelity was acquired by the First Union Corp. in
1995. It sold the last of its investment for $2.13 billion in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers plays chess and squash and enjoys sailing _ an interest
he acquired while growing up near Boston.
</P>
<P>
   And what does a man who can afford almost anything ask his
mother to buy him for his 40th birthday? Last October, she
delivered a box of books about New England, including the one that
he has been reading lately: ``The Country of the Pointed Firs,'' a
series of stories written in the late 1800s about life in Maine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
