<HEADLINE>
NO REJOICING FOR JOYCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The world's 547th-ranked player just missed making
the semifinals of the Mercedes-Benz Cup. And Michael Joyce was
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce, who had the shortest commute of any player this week _
from Brentwood to the Los Angeles Tennis Center at UCLA _ had
reason to be upset.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Monica native was ranked 64th as recently as two years
ago, and his expectations are high despite the struggles of the
last 12 months. A freak wrist injury last summer knocked him out of
action for eight months and nearly dropped him off the face of the
tennis world.
</P>
<P>
   But there he was Friday, taking Guillaume Raoux to three sets in
a quarterfinal match, eventually falling to the Frenchman, 6-7
(7-9), 6-4, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce's best week of tennis in a year? Easily. Reason to
celebrate? Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure later on tonight or tomorrow I'll probably look back
on the week and realize it was a great week for me,'' Joyce said
afterward. ``Right now it's disappointing after losing such a tough
match. If I would have lost 6-2, 6-2 or something, maybe it
wouldn't have been so upsetting, but to know I was so close at
getting to the semifinals, it's very disappointing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he noted, ``This is definitely a step in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The incredible part is that he was in a position to be
disappointed in the first place. This was just his third tournament
since March, when he returned to competition. And he had to play
his way in via three qualifying matches.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce then went through Australia's Michael Tebbutt and Armenian
Sargis Sargsian, both in three sets, to advance to the
quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   The arduous week took its toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like my eighth match in a week,'' Joyce said of the
marathon with Raoux. ``I felt pretty tired in the third set.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first set that nearly gave him a heart attack,
though. Lunging for a ball, he fell to the pavement, clutching his
left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared,'' Joyce said. ``My knee locked, hyperextended. I
didn't feel that much pain, but it was such an awkward fall that I
got kind of scared.''
</P>
<P>
   But the pain subsided during the match, and Joyce later said the
knee felt fine.
</P>
<P>
   His confidence is recovering nicely as well, and he looks
forward to the climb back to the top 100. Not that he's thinking
about rankings just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm more relaxed on the court now, because I know
now how lucky I am to be able to be out there competing and doing
what I love to do,'' he said. ``I don't even think about the
rankings and the money and all those things as much as I used to,
because I'm just happy to be out there playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's taken away from you, you realize how fortunate you
are to have this life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
