<HEADLINE>
PAULA JONES' LAWYERS ASK THAT HER SUIT BE REINSTATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Mo.)  (js) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for Paula Corbin Jones asked a federal
appeals court Friday to reinstate her sexual misconduct suit
against President Clinton, arguing, among other things, that a
lower court should never have excluded evidence about any
relationship he had had with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In their brief, Ms. Jones' lawyers maintained that Susan Webber
Wright, the federal district judge in Little Rock, Ark., who threw
out the suit four months ago, exceeded her authority in ruling
earlier that any evidence of a sexual liaison between Clinton and
Ms. Lewinsky was not material to the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Jones legal team said evidence of a Clinton-Lewinsky
relationship would have helped them show a pattern of how Clinton
treats subordinate women in the workplace. The lawyers said Clinton
had used his position of authority to engage in sex with Ms.
Lewinsky, a onetime White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The brief said evidence about Ms. Lewinsky was relevant to ``the
core issue of whether he engaged in the conduct alleged by Ms.
Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones' suit maintains that in 1991, at a Little Rock hotel
where a state economic conference was under way, a state trooper
summoned her to meet in a suite with Clinton, who was then the
governor. By the account of Ms. Jones, who at the time was a state
employee, Clinton propositioned her there, dropping his trousers
and asking her to perform a sex act. The president has vehemently
denied such an occurrence, although he does not dispute that he may
have met Ms. Jones at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   What might have been a sensational trial was averted on April 1
when Wright ruled that Ms. Jones had not presented any tangible
evidence of damage, even if the encounter had occurred as she
contended. ``While the alleged incident in the hotel, if true, was
certainly boorish and offensive,'' the judge wrote in dismissing
the lawsuit, ``the governor's alleged conduct'' constituted neither
sexual assault nor actionable harassment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Jones lawsuit had already caused enormous damage to Clinton,
both politically and legally. It became the basis for the current
investigation by Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel,
into whether Clinton had a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky
and then colluded with her to lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   In a deposition taken by Ms. Jones' lawyers in January, Clinton
denied under oath that he had had a sexual relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky. Starr is investigating whether Clinton committed perjury
that day.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones' appeal on Friday was filed with the U.S.tates Court
of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit, in St. Louis. The court has a
generally conservative cast of judges who have been consistently
unhelpful to Clinton in other cases. But those judges have also
been notably reluctant to entertain complaints of workplace sexual
discrimination like the one brought by Ms. Jones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
