<SLUG> BC-VA-BABIES-SWITCHED-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY SWITCH IN VIRGINIA IS INVESTIGATED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The authorities in Virginia are investigating
whether two girls born three years ago at a Charlottesville
hospital were deliberately switched and sent home with the wrong
parents.
</P>
<P>
   The switch was discovered several weeks ago, after the mother of
one of the girls received the results of a genetic test for
paternity and learned that the child, who was born on June 29,
1995, was not related to her or to the girl's presumed father. (The
couple are not married.) Two subsequent genetic tests confirmed the
results.
</P>
<P>
   The woman's lawyer contacted the hospital, the University of
Virginia Medical Center, on July 16. After tracking down girls who
might have been switched with her client's child, hospital
officials took a blood sample from another child who was born
around the same time, and it matched the blood type taken from the
first girl at birth.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital notified the police in what they now consider a
criminal case. In a statement this week, the university said it
``does not believe an accidental misidentification of infants could
have taken place.''
</P>
<P>
   Switches shortly after birth are rare but not unheard of. In one
of the best-known cases, a Florida teenager, Kimberly Mays, became
the focus of a heated custody fight after it was found that she and
another baby girl, who died at the age of 9, were sent home from
the hospital with the wrong parents. Without admitting any
wrongdoing, the hospital settled lawsuits by paying the families a
combined $13.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Custody became an issue when Kimberly's biological parents,
Ernest and Regina Twigg, sought to reclaim her. But in 1993, a
judge in Sarasota, Fla., ended seven years of litigation when he
ruled that she could remain with Robert Mays, the man who had
reared her. His wife, Barbara, died in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Virginia medical center said an inadvertent
mix-up was virtually impossible because of procedures used to
identify infants and their mother moments after birth.
</P>
<P>
   Marguerite Beck, a spokeswoman for the medical center, said
identification bracelets _ blue for boys, pink for girls _ bearing
the same number are placed on the baby's ankle and wrist and on the
mother's wrist in the delivery room. It is a common procedure
throughout the country, she said, and one that had been used at the
hospital for at least 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never leave the mother's arm or the baby's,'' Ms. Beck
said. ``Their numbers are even noted at discharge. We do not take
them off.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing issues of privacy, the hospital declined to make public
the names of the babies' mothers. But a news article in The
Richmond Times-Dispatch Friday identified the mother who sought the
genetic tests as Paula Johnson of Greene County, north of
Charlottesville.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper described her as bearing up well under the
circumstances and wanting to wish the parents of her biological
daughter well. ``I don't want to scare the other family in any
way,'' the newspaper quoted her as saying.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone message left for Ms. Johnson was not returned.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Her lawyer, Cynthia Johnson, who is not related to her, said in
an interview Friday that her client was going through ``tough
times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The uncertainty makes everything so difficult,'' the lawyer
said. ``We don't know what's going to happen next. We just hope the
investigation concludes quickly so that everybody can make sure
that the little girls involved have normal lives.''
</P>
<P>
   And what might ``normal'' mean for them, Ms. Johnson was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   Child psychologists say neither the status quo nor a reunion
with biological parents can shut out the emotional pain for a child
living since birth with other parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you have attachments to a biological family, but
attachments to a psychological family run very deep,'' said Nadine
Kaslow, an assistant professor of psychiatry at Emory University in
Atlanta. ``Either way you go, it's a huge loss. The child is losing
something. It will be painful no matter what happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
