<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A GAME? BUSINESS SIDE IS EVIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On this bright afternoon, three groups of young
ballplayers assembled in the outfield of Shea Stadium to hear
baseball talk from major-league players. This was the teaching
portion of the the Junior Mets-Emigrant Bank baseball program.
</P>
<P>
   In left field, Tom Robson, the hitting coach, talked about the
importance of balance. In right field, the conditioning coach,
Barry Heyden, talked about building strength. In center field, Turk
Wendell, the 31-year-old relief pitcher, talked about the game of
baseball. What was it like to be famous? What was it like to be a
major-leaguer?
</P>
<P>
   Wendell told them about when he was their age, growing up in
Massachusetts, how he sat and listened to Jim Rice and Carlton
Fisk.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell hadn't told them the entire story. He had not talked
about the fragility of being a major-league player. Wendell came to
the Mets in a trade last year. Why hadn't he talked about how it
felt to be traded? The jolt to self-esteem, the ruptured roots. He
did not mention that Friday was the no-waiver trading deadline, and
he could have told them that some of the Mets and Dodgers they had
been watching Friday night could be Marlins or Diamondbacks by
evening's end.
</P>
<P>
   Why hadn't he told them how it felt like to be dealt like one of
their trading cards? ``I wanted to keep it simple,'' Wendell said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Mets' clubhouse there was a happy pre-game scene of
players lounging, watching television. Bernard Gilkey and Butch
Huskey sat at a table in the middle of the room playing a spirited
game of dominoes. Two hours later, shortly before game time, Gilkey
learned that he was no longer a Met but an Arizona Diamondback.
Gilkey and a minor-leaguer were traded for a pitcher, a catcher and
a player to be named. Now in the Mets' clubhouse, Gilkey exchanged
farewells with teammates. For all the money-grabbing, hard-hearted
images of the modern professional athlete, this was a touching
scene. Lenny Harris hugged Gilkey and asked, ``Where you going,
dawg?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Going out there with the cactus, dawg,'' Gilkey said. ``Going
to Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let it get you down,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing but business,'' Gilkey said, ``Nothing but business.''
OK, business.
</P>
<P>
   In 1922 the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that baseball was a sport,
not a business, and therefore not subject to antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30 years ago, Curt Flood challenged baseball's reserve
clause. He lost his battle before the Supreme Court in 1972, but
three years later the reserve clause was thrown out and players
could move from one team to another without being traded.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Senate passed a bill acknowledging that
baseball is indeed a business and is subject to modified antitrust
restrictions. But baseball is also a game. A game with deep-seated
emotional attachments that find themselves at odds with business
decisions that move players around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian Bohanon got traded to the Dodgers; he has five kids,''
Wendell said, referring to the former Mets pitcher who was dealt
about two weeks ago. ``How do you pick up five kids in the middle
of the season, and then you're starting in two days? How do you go
from New York to L.A. in two days with five kids? A lot of people
don't see that. They see the money, the glitz, the glory, the
fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine remembers that by the time he was traded from
the Padres to the Mets for Dave Kingman in 1977, he was a hardened
veteran and greeted the news with a ``ho-hum.'' But when he was
first traded, from the Dodgers to the Angels in 1972, ``I had all
the emotions,'' he said. ``Elation, sadness, anxiety, anger _ the
whole gamut when it happens the first couple of times. If you're a
good, young player, it makes you question whether or not this was
because someone wanted you or someone didn't want you.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gilkey said his goodbyes, Mike Piazza, the Mets catcher who
has been the subject of trade talks, sat off by himself. There was
a time when Piazza thought he would be with the Dodgers forever. He
was rookie of the year in 1993, the fair-haired boy. Then, this
season, he was gone: from L.A. to the Florida Marlins to the Mets.
Piazza thought the team would fork over millions for all he had
done. The team said for him to do it somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lie,'' Piazza said. ``It's definitely been a
tough year, mentally. Maybe in a year or two when everything is
boring, I can look back on all this and joke about it, remembering
how everything was so up in the air. Boring would be good right
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
