<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WVA-POLITICS-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST VIRGINIA'S DISPIRITED REPUBLICANS STRUGGLE FOR A FOOTHOLD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:Fla., Va.)   (js) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, W.Va. _ Sally Kay is running for Congress this year.
But hardly anyone in her home state of West Virginia knows it.
</P>
<P>
   As the Republican challenger to Rep. Robert Wise , a popular
Democrat who has held his seat since 1982, she has no money, no
campaign staff, not even a bumper sticker of her own. She has yet
to make her first campaign speech and remains a virtual stranger to
groups that typically support Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fear is that I'll start to get checks and I'll have to
return them because I don't have a treasurer,'' she said, sitting
in the cramped office of West Virginia's Republican Party
headquarters here in the state capital. ``I'm not abdicating, but
without a treasurer, it's hard to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kay's inability to find a campaign treasurer is only one
example of the hard lot of Republicans in West Virginia, one of the
last remaining examples of a one-party state, and a stark contrast
to Republican gains elsewhere in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Democrats rule. As a legacy of strong coal-mining unions,
the New Deal policies of President Franklin D. Roosevelt and family
traditions of party loyalty, Democrats have held sway over most of
West Virginia's political institutions for more than 60 years. And
it is unlikely Republicans will achieve parity anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   In West Virginia, registered Democrats outnumber Republicans by
more than 2 to 1, a disparity that almost always works to the
Democrats' advantage.
</P>
<P>
   One exception is Gov. Cecil Underwood, who also served as
governor from 1956 to 1960. He won a narrow victory in 1996 by
defeating a Democrat who was widely perceived as even more liberal
than the out-going governor, Gaston Caperton, who had served two
terms. But since 1932, voters have elected only one other
Republican governor, Arch Moore , who served two terms from 1968
through 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Of the state's three members of the U.S.House of
Representatives, only Wise faces opposition in the general election
this year, as he did in 1996 when he won easily. Rep. Nick Rahall
II, who was first elected in 1976, faced his last challenger in
1992. Rep. Alan Mollohan, who succeeded his father in 1982, faced
his last in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican has not held a House seat since 1980, and Democrats
have held both Senate seats since 1959.
</P>
<P>
   At the state level, Democrats have controlled the House since
1928 and the Senate since 1930, a dominance that was fairly common
among Southern states until recently.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, for example, Republicans won control of the state
Senate in 1994 for the first time in 120 years and now have a
majority in both chambers. Three years ago in Virginia, Republicans
pulled even with Democrats in the Senate and with consecutive
Republican governors as a potential tie-breaking vote, now control
it for the first time since the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   In West Virginia, Republicans have made marginal gains in the
Senate, picking up eight seats since 1990, when they had a record
low of one. But House seats have been harder to come by.
Republicans picked up six in 1990 to reach 26 but no more since.
</P>
<P>
   And it is unlikely they will make significant gains in this
year's elections to fill all 100 seats in the state House of
Delegates and half the 34 seats in the Senate. For the second
election year in a row, the party failed to find candidates in more
than 50 races.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   The lopsidedness of a two-party system here has resulted in a
state Republican Party that seems to exist in name only. Betty
White is the executive director and sole full-time employee with an
annual salary of $19,000. She has a desk but no computer. Not that
she needs one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone wiped our computer out in March 1995,'' she said,
hinting at sabotage to erase the list of the state's Republican
voters. ``There were rumors about a virus, but I don't believe
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The size and shape of the state party office reflects a grim
reality for Republicans throughout West Virginia despite the recent
efforts of a new state party chairman and a new group, the
Republican Legislative Committee, to raise money and recruit
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of credible Republican challengers in more state and
federal elections reflects two chronic political conditions in West
Virginia, one feeding the other. The first is the star status of
the state's leading politicians. The popularity and tenure of Sens.
Robert Byrd and John D. Rockefeller IV have deterred potential
challengers from both parties, including the three House members.
And the House members' popularity has discouraged many state
legislators from taking the next step.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the overall dynamic has ushered in a certain
ennui among Republicans, who have felt helpless to change the
political balance, such as it is. In a long conversation, Ms. White
spoke several times of her unsuccessful efforts to raise money and
to encourage people to run against entrenched, well-funded
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party has been pretty weak,'' Underwood, who is 75,
conceded in an interview. ``I feel it needs to rebuild its base in
the legislature. That's the only way we can build. We just can't
depend on dissatisfaction from the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gould, a 40-year-old lawyer and state lobbyist, said the
party's lack of elective success led him to create the Republican
Legislative Commission in 1994 as a vehicle to identify new
candidates at the grass-roots level.
</P>
<P>
   He said his narrow loss in the 1992 state attorney general race,
his first run for public office, convinced him that many Democrats,
despite their party affiliation, are more moderate than liberal and
would be willing to vote Republican in certain elections. That
belief, he said, was bolstered two years ago when Underwood's
opponent, Charlotte Pritt, was widely perceived as a candidate too
far removed from mainstream voters. On the strength of his
political connections, Gould began arranging fund-raisers with the
goal of spreading the money among Republicans in elections where a
Democrat appeared vulnerable. Through this year's elections, he
said, the new group will have contributed $150,000 to Republican
candidates for the statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the state's new party chairman, David Tyson, who
was recently elected to a four-year term, said he has made great
strides in raising money and generating new interest among
Republicans across the state. He said he is planning six
fund-raisers to assist Gould's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But tugging against this kind of progress is the aversion of
Gould's organization and Ms. White to work together even though
Tyson insisted that he, not Ms. White, is doing the bulk of the
work for the state organization and that he enjoys a good working
relationship with Gould.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, sparks have flown, leaving at least a perception of
party disunity. Ms. White, who said she intends to resign soon,
contended that Gould has intentionally undermined her efforts by
``promoting his own candidates while shoving others aside'' and by
tapping Republican donors for his own purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Gould said his group is merely performing where the party has
failed, searching out viable candidates and helping them
financially.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever direction the Republicans are heading, Tyson and other
Republicans say any real measure of party progress will not come
before one of the Democratic congressmen resigns or runs for higher
office, creating a rare opening. Wise has acknowledged that he is
seriously considering a run for governor in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the wait is longer, party leaders acknowledge that
they have to do a better job raising money, finding candidates and
convincing voters that Republican positions are more in tune with
their moderate views than the Democrats'.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state is changing,'' Underwood said, referring to a
diversifying economy that no longer depends solely on the coal
industry. ``With new jobs and new people, we have a different mix
now. My instincts tell me that if we can capture that growth, we
can build a new party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
