<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-TRADES-450&AMP;ADD-NY     07-31 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TRADES-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE DAY: DODGERS AND RANGERS SHAKE UP RACES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While everyone in baseball waited breathlessly to learn where,
if anywhere, Randy Johnson was going, some teams engineered their
own trades Friday, the last day players could be traded without
clearing waivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers, scratching and clawing their way through the
American League West race, were the busiest club, creating half a
new infield and swapping starting pitchers. But the Montreal Expos
and the Los Angeles Dodgers executed the biggest and most
intriguing transaction, a seven-player deal that makes teammates of
the Guerrero brothers, Wilton and Vladimir.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, intent on winning the National League wild-card
race, acquired Carlos Perez, the Expos' best pitcher, for their
starting rotation and shortstop Mark Grudzielanek to shore up their
weakened infield. The Expos gained Wilton Guerrero, a second
baseman-outfielder, who at 23 is 16 months older than Vladimir, the
Expos' hard-hitting right fielder, and three minor-league
prospects. The Dodgers also got a minor-leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who were one game behind Anaheim when they made
their trades, acquired pitcher Todd Stottlemyre and shortstop Royce
Clayton from St. Louis for pitcher Darren Oliver and third baseman
Fernando Tatis. The Rangers also obtained third baseman Todd Zeile
from Florida for two minor-league players. They then released
shortstop Kevin Elster.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had talked with Toronto about Juan Guzman for their
rotation but preferred Stottlemyre, so the Blue Jays sent Guzman to
Baltimore for two young players.
</P>
<P>
   In what was basically a swap of center fielders, the San
Francisco Giants tried to improve themselves for the remainder of
the NL wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who recently added Joe Carter to their outfield, got
Ellis Burks from Colorado for Darryl Hamilton. Burks, with 16 home
runs to one for Hamilton, hits with more power, which is what the
Giants were seeking.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had talked with the Cardinals about Stottlemyre,
whose father is the Yankees' pitching coach, but the Cardinals
apparently asked for Hideki Irabu and the Yankees said no. Brian
Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, would not confirm Irabu's
involvement in the talks but said, ``A lot of clubs have asked me
about Irabu.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman added: ``I was talking to them just like I was talking
to everyone else. Nothing seemed to make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade with the Cardinals made sense to the Rangers because
they were looking to improve their starting pitching and their
defense at short. Oliver, a left-hander, had been a disappointment
with a 6-7 record and 6.53 earned run average, and Elster had lost
a lot of range at short.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   General Manager Doug Melvin, who two weeks ago acquired Esteban
Loaiza from Pittsburgh for the starting rotation, was especially
pleased to add Stottlemyre, a 33-year-old right-hander, who has a
9-9 record and 3.51 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at Todd's track record and competitiveness, we
feel he's going to help our ball club,'' Melvin said on a
conference call. ``We feel when you go down to the last 45, 50
games, it's important to have someone with that kind of attitude.
It's almost an arrogance, and it's good to have down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had hoped to sign Stottlemyre to a contract
extension and keep him, but he rejected their last offer of $21
million for three years because he wanted a fourth year. The
Cardinals had already come up from two years and an option year for
$16 million and were not willing to go to four years.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, operating out of a hotel room in Toronto, where the
Rangers had played the night before, said he had juggled the hotel
phone and his cell phone, talking to two general managers at the
same time. Dave Dombrowski, the Marlins' general manager, was on
the cell phone and Walt Jocketty of St. Louis was on the hotel
phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to make sure I could do both deals,'' Melvin said. ``I
couldn't give up Tatis without getting Zeile.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatis, who at 23 is nine years younger than Zeile, is a better
defensive player but does not hit as well as Zeile. Tatis is
batting .270 with 3 home runs and 32 runs batted in while Zeile is
hitting .276 with 13 homers and 66 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile compiled those figures for two teams, the Dodgers and the
Marlins. He was traded to the Marlins with Mike Piazza on May 15
for five players in the Marlins' continuing payroll purge.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza left for the Mets a week later, but Zeile remained for
two and a half months. Zeile was nearly traded to Boston, where he
would have played first base, with Mo Vaughn becoming the
designated hitter. But the Red Sox instead acquired Mike Stanley
from Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins' payroll, which they slashed from $53 million as
World Series champions at the end of last season to $33 million at
the start of this one, now is about $14 million. In trading Zeile,
the Marlins received a pair of Class A players, third baseman Jose
Santo and pitcher Daniel DeYoung.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman, who in recent starts has been a much better pitcher than
his  &QC; 6-12 season record would indicate, did not cost the Orioles
significant major-league talent.
</P>
<P>
   Nerio Rodriguez has pitched in six games, four of them starts,
for the Orioles this season with a 1-3 record and 8.05 ERA. The
other player the Blue Jays got is Shannon Carter, a Class A
outfielder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
