<HEADLINE>
RELIGION COLUMN: UNITARIANS DISPUTE BOY SCOUTS ON EMBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the many religious bodies in the United States, the
Unitarian-Universalist Association has long stood to the left.
</P>
<P>
   An organization with no creed that proclaims that each person
has a right to seek spiritual truth, the 215,000-member association
embraces members who call themselves humanists, deists, Christians,
and even agnostics and atheists. In recent years, it has also been
outspoken in supporting the rights of homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, its stands have put it at odds with the Boy Scouts
of America, which has told the association that it can no longer
award a religious emblem to Unitarian boys in Scout troops.
</P>
<P>
   Such emblems are given by national religious organizations to
Boy Scouts who have completed a period of study about their own
faith. The emblems may be worn like merit badges. Until now, the
Boy Scouts have never forbidden a religious body from awarding such
emblems to its youths, a Scout spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed in May, when the association's headquarters in
Boston received a letter from the Boy Scouts Religious Relations
Committee objecting to a Unitarian manual that explains how a Boy
Scout who belonged to a Unitarian church might attain the
association's ``religion in life'' emblem.
</P>
<P>
   The manual outlines a course of study and written projects about
Unitarian history and principles. The problem, from the Boy Scouts'
standpoint, is that the manual says some boys may have ``trouble
with the religious language'' in the Boy Scout oath, in which a
Scout pledges duty to God and country.
</P>
<P>
   The manual also contains a resolution, adopted by the
association's General Assembly in 1992, disapproving of the Boy
Scouts' policy barring homosexuals from being Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   In its letter, the Boy Scouts committee called the manual's
passages inappropriate and said it viewed ``with considerable
dismay'' the criticism of the policy against gay Scouts. Until the
manual is ``redrafted to a form acceptable to the committee,''
Unitarian youths may not be awarded the religious emblem, nor can
they wear one on a Scout uniform, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. John A. Buehrens, the association's president, said he
regarded the decision as an effort to interfere with
Unitarian-Universalist beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm responding to a demand for a change in our curriculum and
our practice with our own young people by saying no,'' Buehrens
said. ``I'm saying, `That's not your purview.'''
</P>
<P>
   He said the controversy was a test of the association's ``First
Principle,'' which declares that all people have equal worth and
dignity.
</P>
<P>
   But Gregg Shields, a Boy Scouts spokesman, said the organization
was not telling the association what to believe. ``The Unitarians
may teach their youth what they wish,'' Shields said. ``We never
presume to impose our beliefs on anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The manual's statements about the Boy Scout oath and the ban on
gay members, he said, ``directly contradict Scouting's values.''
</P>
<P>
   Disagreement between the Boy Scouts and the Unitarians goes back
to a resolution passed by the association in 1992. In it, the
association protested the Boy Scouts' ban on homosexuals by
withdrawing from the religious bodies that are chartering, or
sponsoring, troops or similar organizations in the Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They decided to remove themselves from Scouting,'' Shields
said. But individual Unitarian congregations can still be
chartering organizations, capable of sponsoring a Scout troop, he
added, ``if they feel their aims and purposes are compatible with
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Unitarian boys are welcome to join other troops, Shields said,
but the Scouts will not recognize the association's religious
emblem.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Weiner, a Unitarian-Universalist spokeswoman, said the
1992 resolution was intended to be symbolic, not to create a
rupture between the Boy Scouts and Unitarians. ``There are so many
Boy Scouts within our organization,'' Ms. Weiner said.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy in Ohio, Buehrens said, he was a member of a Scout
troop, and as a minister in New York in 1990 he helped organize a
troop for boys living in welfare hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Buehrens fondly recalled his troop in Ohio as a demanding group
that required members to spend 30 days a year camping. As a
12-year-old, he said, he attended the 1959 Boy Scout Jamboree in
Colorado Springs, meeting Scouts from around the world. It was his
first time away from home without his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of training and preparation in the Scouts just opened up
the world for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buehrens said that he had exchanged letters and telephone calls
with Boy Scout officials, and that he hoped to meet with them in
September to discuss the situation.
</P>
<P>
   But he said, ``I think I would encourage people to understand
that teaching kids to treat others with fairness, teaching kids not
to discriminate just on the basis of someone belonging to a
particular group, requires the stand we have taken vis-a-vis the
Boy Scouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Shields said the Boy Scouts also wanted to end the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working to resolve this since '92,'' he said.
``We've been hoping we can come to an amicable resolution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
