<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUYING A CAMPAIGN FOR VERY LITTLE DOWN  
 LOUISIANA TINKERS WITH CALENDAR AGAIN  
 GAY ISSUES ARE A PROBLEM FOR ILLINOIS DEMOCRAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Iowa, N.H., Mo., Mass.)  (lb) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A generally accepted rule in California politics is that the
state is so big and its television markets are so expensive that it
takes a minimum of $10 million to make a good run for the U.S.
Senate. And that doesn't include the $5 million or so, maybe even
$10 million, that can be spent winning a primary to get on the fall
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   State Treasurer Matt Fong managed to win this year's Republican
primary by spending a paltry $2.5 million. His main opponent,
Darrell Issa, spent more than four times as much, $11 million, most
of it from his electronics fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders figure that a candidate who can overcome a
rival's 4-to-1 spending edge in a primary deserves better backing
in the general. So they have ordered a full-court press for money
on behalf of Fong, a moderate, confident he has a real shot at
unseating the Democratic incumbent, Barbara Boxer, a liberal whose
job-approval rating has seldom pushed above 50 percent in her six
years in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Latest polls have the race almost a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' money-raising goal for Fong: no less than $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Senatorial Campaign Committee, intent on
expanding the party's hold on the Senate, has called Boxer's seat a
No. 1 target and is considering contributing $3 million. An
additional $1 million or so may be spent on the race by the
Republican National Committee, party officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some Republican luminaries are holding fund-raisers
for Fong in places as distant as New York and Washington, while
others are beginning to head for California.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kemp, the party's 1996 vice presidential nominee, worked a
San Diego crowd the other day, hailing Fong as a ``21st-century
Republican.'' Other high-profile figures who have agreed to make
pitches around the state include the Senate majority leader, Trent
Lott; Speaker Newt Gingrich; Sen. John McCain of Arizona, and Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists for Boxer, who is pretty good at raising money
herself, have a different take on the money press for Fong. They
contend it is a measure of how much trouble he is in.
</P>
<P>
   They also point out that the senator has a special ally when it
comes to putting the arm on Democrats for donations: President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Tinkers With Calendar Again
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 presidential campaign, Louisiana Republicans moved
the date of their caucuses to the front end of the election year in
a brassy effort to steal some of the attention and influence
usually accorded the first-in-the-nation Iowa caucuses and New
Hampshire primary. But when jealous Republican leaders in Iowa and
New Hampshire hinted that the party faithful in their states might
punish candidates who participated in the Louisiana caucuses, most
of the big names heeded the warning and avoided them.
</P>
<P>
   Now Louisiana Republicans are once again talking about
scheduling early caucuses, this time for Election 2000. And in the
absence, thus far, of any dark talk in Iowa and New Hampshire about
voter retribution, some White House prospects are beginning to make
appearances in New Orleans and elsewhere down on the bayou,
especially those eager to test-run their particular brand of
conservatism in one of the nation's most conservative states.
</P>
<P>
   Among them: Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri, former Vice
President Dan Quayle, the magazine executive Steve Forbes, Gary
Bauer, the head of the Family Research Council, and, perhaps most
telling, Sen. Robert Smith of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Gay Issues Are a Problem for Illinois Democrat
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the moment he won the Democratic nomination in this
year's race for governor in Illinois, Rep. Glenn Poshard, a
downstate moderate, has been under pressure to move to the left on
issues like gun control, abortion and gay rights. If he does not,
party leaders say, he may not run well in the more liberal Chicago
area to the north, which is where Illinois Democrats seeking
statewide office tend to win or lose elections.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the party leaders warn, if Poshard remains fixed in the
ideological middle _ his social conservatism is balanced by
economic liberalism _ he risks the loss of some of his Democratic
base to his Republican opponent, Secretary of State George Ryan.
Ryan, also a moderate, supports gun controls and recently
participated prominently in a gay-pride parade.
</P>
<P>
   Poshard, who in the past has opposed same-sex marriage and
expansion of anti-discrimination laws to protect homosexuals,
skipped the parade, a decision roundly criticized by the relatively
large and politically powerful Illinois gay community. State Rep.
Larry McKeon, the only openly gay member of the Illinois
legislature, announced that he would not join other Democrats in
endorsing Poshard _ just the kind of defection party leaders
feared.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with polls showing Ryan out front in the race by better
than five points, Poshard seems to be moving toward repairing some
of his fences on the left. His campaign manager, Josh Silverman,
says Poshard plans to ``open a dialogue'' over the next few days
with leaders of gay groups. Further, he has been discussing
possible campaign strategies with Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., who,
as the first openly homosexual member of Congress, is probably the
most powerful gay politician in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that one early way to begin repairing the damage,''
Frank said, ``would be to vote in favor of bills now before
Congress that would extend and strengthen gay rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay leaders are skeptical about Poshard moderating his views on
the issue. But Rick Garcia, a gay Democrat who is the political
director of the Illinois Federation for Human Rights, said the
congressman would deserve ``high marks'' should he open a
meaningful dialogue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
