<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUMAURIER-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCH THE BIRDIES: HURST'S 65 SEEMS PICTURE PERFECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario _ With Se Ri Pak grabbing so many headlines in
women's golf, Pat Hurst has been overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   It has nearly been forgotten that Hurst won the year's first
major, the Nabisco Dinah Shore, and that Hurst could join Pak as a
two-time winner of a major this year.
</P>
<P>
   But while Pak fell seven strokes off the lead Friday at the du
Maurier Classic, Hurst reminded everyone that she is among the best
players on the LPGA Tour. Shooting a 7-under-par 65, which included
a streak of six consecutive birdies, Hurst soared into a
first-place tie with Brandie Burton at 12 under (132) after
second-round play. Burton had Friday's best round (64), including
an eagle on the final hole at the Essex Golf and Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the final women's major of 1998 has hardly been a brutal
test of golf. The 36-hole cut was 2 under par, the lowest in
history at an LPGA major, breaking the previous mark of 1 over par
at the 1987 LPGA Championship. It was only one stroke more than the
lowest cut in LPGA history, set last year at the State Farm Rail
Classic. Aren't birdies supposed to be precious at majors? Not this
week, with ideal weather conditions on a 6,308-yard course that is
playing much shorter.
</P>
<P>
   It may take 20 under par or lower to win the tournament. And
with 41 players at five under or lower, the outcome was very much
in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens are much softer than in most majors,'' said Annika
Sorenstam, who was two strokes off the lead after shooting a 66
Friday. ``You can go right at the pin, which will make scores go
lower.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak's score will have to go much lower to win her third
consecutive major. After Friday's 70, Pak was 5 under for the
tournament and tied for 36th place.
</P>
<P>
   Pak's driving and iron play has been erratic, and she may be
fatigued from playing in her sixth consecutive tournament, coupled
with the fanfare surrounding her attempt to win three majors as a
20-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Pak is too talented to write off, but if she wins this weekend,
it will be the most phenomenal comeback of her phenomenal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a chance,'' said Pak, who has won four times this
year, including three of her last four starts. ``My game is not
good, but not bad. Maybe today or tomorrow, I can find solid
shots.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hurst and Burton hit solid shots all day, and it will take more
of the same for them to hold off their pursuers. Betsy King, the
first-round leader, was in third place at 11 under, one stroke
behind after a 69 Friday. Sorenstam and Meg Mallon, who also shot
69 Friday, were tied for fourth place at 10 under.
</P>
<P>
   But Hurst had the most impressive run of the day, making birdies
on hole Nos. 5 through 10. Hurst, a 29-year-old from San Leandro,
Calif., made putts from 8 to 40 feet in the birdie run.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it seemed as if her ball was being drawn
magnetically toward the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got on a roll where it felt like the hole was a garbage
can,'' Hurst said. ``I felt like I could make it from wherever I
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurst is sixth on the tour's money list this year with $443,424,
and she is enjoying the best season of her career. Winning a second
major would bring Hurst far more recognition, yet the limelight is
not something she craves, and she does not feel snubbed by the
attention Pak has received.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take it away from Se Ri,'' Hurst said. ``The run she
has had the past few weeks has been amazing. I like being in the
background. But I wouldn't mind winning a second major.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton has also won a major during her career, winning the 1993
du Maurier by defeating King on the first hole of sudden death. But
Burton has not won on the LPGA Tour since 1993, and she would like
to end that drought this weekend. The way Burton finished Friday
should boost her confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Starting her round on the 10th hole, Burton completed her day
with a 20-foot birdie putt on No. 8, followed by a 30-foot putt for
eagle on the par-5, 450-yard ninth hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see the scores being this low when I practiced
earlier this week,'' Burton said. ``I guess we're beating the
course.''
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS:
</P>
<P>
   Only two of the LPGA's top 20 money-winners, Lorie Kane and
Kelly Robbins, missed the cut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
