<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-TRADE-PROSPECTS-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS PONDER TRADE FOR RANDY JOHNSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Randy Johnson is regarded as one of the greatest
pitchers of his generation, and as Brian Cashman, the New York
Yankees' general manager, sat in his Yankee Stadium office Friday
evening, some six hours before the midnight Eastern trade deadline,
he had the opportunity to add the extraordinary Johnson to his
extraordinary team.
</P>
<P>
   All Cashman had to do was make one phone call, utter one word _
yes _ and meet the demands of the Seattle Mariners. Baseball
officials said the Mariners would trade Johnson for pitcher Hideki
Irabu and Mike Lowell, a minor-league infielder regarded as the
Yankees' best position prospect. One phone call, one word and
Johnson would be in pinstripes for the final two months of the
regular season and for October, when the Yankees will attempt to
establish themselves as one of history's most successful teams.
</P>
<P>
   But Cashman wasn't sure. Others said that in these hours leading
up to the deadline, he was trying to figure out a way to replace
Lowell in the deal. The Yankees were considering whether to add
outfielder Ricky Ledee and/or second baseman Homer Bush to the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman wouldn't discuss his options, but he acknowledged being
torn by them. He had the choice of trading a large portion of the
Yankees' best young and inexpensive talent for a dominant pitcher _
Johnson _ he may have for only three months, or staying pat and
gambling that Jeff Nelson will recover from his back trouble, a
risk that could leave the Yankees' bullpen extremely vulnerable in
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm literally on the fence with this,'' Cashman said. ``It
could go either way. There's a good chance I'll do something, and
there's a good chance we won't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman, too, has discussed the idea of trading for Toronto's
Roger Clemens, and at least one club representative was confident
Thursday evening that the Yankees had a chance to get Clemens. But
Irabu, initially proposed as part of a deal for Clemens, has a
contract clause that prevents him from being traded to Toronto. The
Blue Jays are among five teams Irabu cannot be traded to, according
to an American League official, and that stalled the negotiations.
Cashman apparently was still in contact with Toronto Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Johnson deal was there for the taking for Cashman, whose
primary competition for the pitcher seemed to be the Cleveland
Indians (possibly a deal built around outfielder Brian Giles) and
Houston Astros (outfielder Richard Hidalgo). Adding a twist, the
schedule happened to place the Yankees here in the Northwest. It
could be that by midway through Friday night's game, Johnson is to
be traded to the team on the other side of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Should Johnson come to the Yankees, he would join a rotation
that already includes the left-handers Andy Pettitte and David
Wells and the right-hander David Cone _ a group that would contend
with any team, including the Atlanta Braves. The Yankees may face
either the Boston Red Sox or Cleveland Indians in the playoffs, and
both teams rely on left-handed hitters. Johnson lords over
left-handed batters, holding them to a .169 average, with 35
strikeouts in 65 at-bats and only two extra-base hits, both
doubles.
</P>
<P>
   If Irabu is part of the Johnson trade, then Orlando Hernandez
could remain in the rotation. Presumably, however, Hernandez would
be moved to the bullpen, in preparation for the postseason, because
of his strong ability against right-handed batters. Hernandez would
effectively replace Nelson in the bullpen, if Nelson can't come
back.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees manager, spent part of his day on the
phone with Cashman, discussing potential trades that could fill the
hole in the bullpen. Torre didn't say as much, but it's safe to say
the Johnson deal came up, as it did two months ago. ``This has been
building up all year,'' Torre said Thursday, referring to the
anticipation of a Johnson trade. ``This was just a natural. He's a
marquee guy. It doesn't matter what he does, he's an event.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, most of Torre's players were oblivious to
all the trade talks. In recent days, however, curiosity has drawn
out the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we're curious,'' said Andy Pettitte, who pitched
seven innings in the Yankees' 10-inning, 3-0 victory against
Anaheim on Thursday night. ``We've been together all year, and
we're wondering who might be the three or four guys'' who might be
included in a trade.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While studying the bat rack Wednesday afternoon, Tino Martinez
spoke to a few reporters. ``So,'' he said, ``what trades are going
to happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Darren Holmes stopped quickly as he passed by a reporter Friday,
after seeing his name in a story about the Johnson trade talks.
``What do you think of that?'' he asked, a smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of acquiring Johnson is somewhat intriguing to the
players, but most have the same attitude of David Wells, who
suggested that, sure, it would be great to have Johnson. ``But
we've got a good enough team to win it without trading for
anyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   True. But as Cashman mulled his options Friday evening, his
office walls covered by placards bearing the name of every player
in the organization, Cashman knew he could get one of the game's
greatest pitchers, for a team currently considered the best in
baseball. Just one phone call, one word.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
