<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DODGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT METS 4-3 AT SHEA STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One out was all John Franco needed, and the weekend
would surely have been a memorable one. Sometime soon, possibly
Saturday, Franco is expected to sign a two-year contract extension
that will keep him with the Mets through the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
   But Franco could not record that final out. Trying to protect a
3-1 lead, Franco allowed three ninth-inning runs, and the Los
Angeles Dodgers rallied for a 4-3 victory over the Mets Friday
night at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, it looked as if Franco would have no problem
recording his 22nd save. After allowing a lead-off single to Matt
Luke, Franco came back to strike out the next two batters. But he
fell behind pinch-hitter Roger Cedeno, 3-1, with the game on the
line. Then Butch Huskey could not catch Cedeno's drive to deep
right field to record the final out.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the ball glanced off Huskey's glove at the warning
track and dropped for a run-scoring triple. Franco's very next
pitch, to pinch-hitter Tom Prince, skipped between catcher Mike
Piazza's legs. Cedeno scored from third. And Franco had just blown
his fifth save this season.
</P>
<P>
   Six pitches later, the 37-year-old closer would be facing his
sixth defeat against no victories. That was after Eric Young, just
off the disabled list, crushed a full-count double to score Prince
with what proved to be the winning run. That was it for Franco, who
was booed off the field by the crowd of 49,407.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Mets (56-50) to four games behind the
Chicago Cubs in the National League wild card race and the Dodgers
(57-52) now trail New York by one and a half games in the
post-season chase.
</P>
<P>
   The evening featured Piazza's first game against the team he
came up with, not to mention a post-game fireworks show. But the
most dizzying displays belonged to the opposing general managers,
Steve Phillips and Tommy Lasorda, who put together a blur of trades
before the midnight deadline expired.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Phillips dealt left fielder Bernard Gilkey to
Arizona for pitcher Willie Blair and catcher Jorge Fabregas. During
the game, the Mets acquired the utilityman Tony Phillips _ whom
they had passed on late this winter _ from Toronto for a minor
league pitcher to take Gilkey's place. And after the game, Phillips
was tirelessly working on another trade. The Dodgers, meanwhile,
acquired Carlos Perez and Mark Grudzielanek from the Expos for
Wilton Guerrero and a bevy of prospects just before game-time.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, however, Steve Phillips left Brian McRae be.
Friday night, McRae's two-run fifth-inning triple off Darren
Dreifort erased a 1-0 deficit and helped propel the Mets to a 3-1
lead before Franco's appearance. Lately, McRae has been doing it
all for the Mets, who lost for the fourth time in their last 12
games. Masato Yoshii (4-6) was denied his first victory since May
27.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii allowed six hits and one run in seven sterling innings,
walking one while striking out eight. But the Japanese right-hander
was trailing by 1-0 when McRae stepped to the plate against
Driefort (6-10) with two out and two on in the bottom of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   McRae ripped a line drive past center fielder Trenidad Hubbard
and through the gap in right center field. Four pitches later,
Lenny Harris chopped an infield single over the mound to score
McRae to make it 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   For the night, McRae was 2 for 4. In his last 10 starts, he is
20 for 48 (.417), with 11 runs scored, 2 homers, 2 triples, 7
doubles and 9 runs batted in. Once the object of heavy criticism
for his struggles at the plate, McRae's average is now a healthy
.265.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being the odd man out in the Mets' outfield, McRae is
now the anchor. His 48 extra-base hits easily lead the Mets. And
with Tony Phillips on his way to help take over the lead-off
duties, the Mets just might have a consistently dangerous lineup
for the post-season stretch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
