<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MERGER-MANIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ODD CORPORATE COUPLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Aug. 1:
</P>
<P>
   Politics, it used to be said, makes strange bedfellows. But that
process is nothing like the current wave of mergers, which are
creating convoluted arrangements that are chosen not to make the
business run better, but to get a deal done.
</P>
<P>
   No deal has produced a more bizarre arrangement than the
takeover of Rolls-Royce, the luxury-car maker. Volkswagen outbid
BMW to buy Rolls, then grew worried that BMW would refuse to sell
engines needed for Rolls models. The result was a truly Solomonic
decision. In five years Volkswagen will turn over the making of
Rolls-Royce cars to BMW, while keeping Bentleys for itself. In the
meantime, the siblings Rolls and Bentley will have a parent that
plans to keep only one of its children. Which of the brands do you
think Volkswagen will work harder to promote?
</P>
<P>
   Even when there are no plans to carve up a company,
responsibilities post-merger are often divvied up in ways that make
more sense to investment bankers than to management experts. The
plan to merge Bell Atlantic and GTE creates co-chief executives for
the next several years, with one of them already picked to take
full control in 2002. There has been a wave of such deals lately,
among them the Citicorp-Travelers and American Home
Products-Monsanto arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   The prize for most embarrassing management structure was won by
Cendant Corp., which owns such brands as Century 21 and Avis. It
was formed last year when two companies merged under an arrangement
where the boss of one company would run the combined operation for
a few years, then yield to the other.
</P>
<P>
   When it turned out the boss-in-waiting had run a company without
noticing accounting fraud, it cost Cendant $35 million to persuade
him to resign rather than exercise his right to take over the
entire company.
</P>
<P>
   In the rest of corporate America, there are only a few companies
that choose to have co-chief executives. Those arrangements are
usually based on a belief the two individuals can work together and
have complementary skills. The new run of co-bosses is being
created to get deals done. If and when they blow up, it will be
shareholders, employees and customers who suffer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980731.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
