<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: NANNIES WHOSE HEARTS ACHE FOR HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Honduras, Guatemala)  (lb) 
 By MIRTA OJITO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The day her youngest daughter turned 10, Dora Marta
could not help her blow out the candles on her frosty birthday cake
because she was hundreds of miles away. Her daughter and her other
two children were back home, in a speck of a town tucked away in
the northern mountains of Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   Dora Marta was in New York, pushing a swing under the hot sun in
an Upper East Side playground, ever mindful of the needs of her
charge: a 2-year-old boy who has trouble pronouncing her name and
instead calls her ``she.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I called her that night,'' Dora Marta said. ``And I wished her
happy birthday. And we both cried a little. But I cry every time I
talk to my children.''
</P>
<P>
   Dora Marta, 38, a nanny who lives in Jackson Heights, Queens,
has not seen her children, ages 10, 12 and 13, or her husband in
six years. Once a month, she sends them money. Every two weeks, she
calls them. Every night, before she goes to sleep, she says a
silent prayer for them. She bargains with God: ``Another two or
three years, God, and I'll be ready to come home. Just protect them
while I make more money.''
</P>
<P>
   Her story is common among the city's thousands of nannies. Even
as they earn more money than ever before, their lives are not
necessarily easier. A recent national survey found 74 percent of
nannies make from $300 to $500 a week, before taxes, and anecdotal
evidence suggests some make as much as $1,000 a week. Still, many
live with the pain of having to care for other people's children
while their own children are far away, often under the care of
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dora Marta, who is in the country illegally, would not
reveal her salary or her last name, she said she is happy with what
she earns. The money helps to keep her focused on her plan, which
is simple. The more money she makes, the faster she can be with her
children. These days she is contemplating not returning home, but
bringing her children to the United States if she can do so
legally, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Others are taking greater risks. A Mexican nanny named Elena,
who is in the country illegally, said she was so desperate to see
her daughter after a two-year separation that she paid $1,500 to a
friend of a friend to bring her 5-year-old daughter illegally
across the Rio Grande. She expects the girl in early September.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are nannies like Maria Rebeca, who puts up with the
long hours, the hard jobs, the painful separation from her family
with little complaint because, she says, she is thinking of their
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I feel like dropping everything and running back
home,'' said Maria Rebeca, 39, a nanny from Guatemala, who has not
seen her children, ages 12, 15, 19 and 20, in almost five years.
``I have to constantly repress the urge to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   When she left Guatemala for New York in search of a job, her
boys were 7 and 10 and the girls 14 and 15. She feared leaving them
behind with relatives. She suffered at the thought of separating
them; the girls went to the city with an aunt while the boys stayed
in the country with an uncle.
</P>
<P>
   But she feared more and suffered more at the thought of staying
in her war-torn country and not being able to provide for her
children. With a visitor's visa that allowed her to stay in the
United States for six months, she left her country and joined her
husband in Greenpoint, Brooklyn. He had illegally crossed the
border into the United States two years before.
</P>
<P>
   She became a live-in nanny and, because most of her needs were
provided by her employers, sent home her entire salary. She would
not say how much she made, but said it would take her six months in
Guatemala to earn what she makes in a week here. Maria Rebeca, who
has a sixth-grade education, proudly points to her children's
successes. Her oldest daughter is a nurse, her youngest is a
secretary in the capital, and the boys are in school.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she says, she gets through her days as if she were
wounded. She worries her brother may be too strict with the boys.
She worries about her daughters, two young women alone in Guatemala
City. She prays they do not fall in love with the wrong men.
</P>
<P>
   To ease her pain, she gets deeply involved with the children
under her care, she said. ``I take good care of them because I
think that, if I do that, God will make sure that my children are
treated the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Some days, she said, she can rationalize her choices and enjoy
her work. But most days, she feels a physical need for her
children. She touches the center of her chest. ``Right here,'' she
says, ``I have a big hole.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
