<HEADLINE>
BRICKYARD 400 FAST CLOSING THE GAP IN INDIANAPOLIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)  (lb) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ A day before May's Indianapolis 500, a ticket
scalper stood alone on a street corner near an entrance to the
speedway. He was holding up a sign that read, ``Buy one, get one
free.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a very different scene on that same corner Friday,
less than 24 hours before NASCAR's Brickyard 400. Mobbed by a dozen
race fans, a scalper stood on the curb, taking bids. The highest
bidder paid nearly four times the face value, the scalper said.
</P>
<P>
   The Indy 500 was the big race in town until 1996, when a bitter
rift between Indianapolis Motor Speedway and Championship Auto
Racing Teams tarnished its reputation. Drivers split into two
factions, representing either CART or the new Indy Racing League,
pulled by differing philosophies over issues ranging from engines
to the actual courses on which they race.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Indy 500 was no longer considered the unrivaled
championship of open-wheel racing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some would argue that the 500 is not even the track's
most popular race anymore. That title, it seems, now belongs to the
Brickyard 400, the annual stock-car race which will be run here for
a fifth year on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brickyard 400 is definitely a hot ticket right now,'' said
Jeffrey Belskus, the Speedway's vice president. ``It's a wonderful
product, and we're fortunate to have it. But the Indy Racing League
is only 3 years old; we expect that it will grow.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Ernie Irvan will start on the pole for the second
straight year. Dale Jarrett, the 1996 champion, will be on the
outside of row one; Jeff Gordon, who won the race in 1994, will
start from the third position.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that the winner of the Brickyard 400 could take
home a fatter purse than this year's Indy 500 winner, Eddie
Cheever, who got almost $1.5 million. Thanks to a $1 million bonus,
the winner of the NASCAR race could get $1.5 million to $1.7
million, which would be the biggest single payday in U.S.
auto-racing history.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Indy 500 still has more television viewers than the
Brickyard race, the gap is shrinking. This year's Indy 500 reached
5,400,000 viewers, its lowest total in recent memory, while
Brickyard 400's ratings continue to grow, reaching 5,180,000 in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great event for us,'' said NASCAR's president, Bill
France. ``Fans like it, drivers like it. But NASCAR is not going to
get into which race is bigger. They are two very different races.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons for the apparent decline of the Indy 500,
and the sudden surge in the Brickyard 400's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   All of the top NASCAR teams and drivers are here for Saturday's
race. At the Indy 500, the top open-wheel racers, CART drivers like
Alex Zanardi, Al Unser Jr. and Michael Andretti, were missing.
</P>
<P>
   The grandstands Friday were packed for NASCAR practice, and this
week, merchandise trucks selling T-shirts and hats of the NASCAR
teams have packed the gravel lots that were empty in May for the
Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   Scalpers have noticed the Indy 500's decline and the quick rise
of the Brickyard's popularity. Before the 1996 IRL-CART split, one
scalper recalled, Indy 500 tickets could be sold for as much as
four times to six times face value. Now, he said, scalped Indy 500
tickets are worth about face value.
</P>
<P>
   Expect this trend at Indianapolis to continue, unless the rival
IRL and CART series can reconcile their differences. That will not
be done easily, considering the ever-widening technology
differences between the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely want to come back here and race in a single-seat
open-wheeled car in the month of May,'' said Al Unser Jr., who was
here to compete in Friday's International Race of Champions, which
was won by Mark Martin. ``But any time you get to race at the
Indianapolis Motor Speedway is a dream come true. I'm glad to be
back, but I wish it was in a different kind of car.''
</P>
<P>
   PIT STOPS
</P>
<P>
   With his second International Race of Champions victory this
season on Friday, MARK MARTIN captured a record fourth IROC title,
his third straight. Passing the 1996 CART champion, JIMMY VASSER,
with four laps to go, Martin won the last stage of the four-race
series, capturing the $225,000 championship prize. ... Two
spectators sustained minor injuries when debris from ARIE
LUYENDYK's car flew into the stands after a violent crash.
Luyendyk, whose car hit the new energy-absorbing wall installed
before this year's Indy 500, sustained a mild concussion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
