<SLUG> BC-NY-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED IN BIRTH, 12 TWINS IN 30 HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The bulletin out of Beth Israel Medical Center on
Friday morning was intriguingly incomplete. ``At least'' five sets
of twins, the notice read, had been born there in the last 24
hours. The wording raised two possibilities: either doctors there
had no idea exactly what was going on, or a statistically
improbable occurrence was becoming even more so.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, set No. 6 was on its way by early afternoon, when a
small army of doctors, nurses and public relations people greeted
reporters with the vitals: more twins than had ever been born in so
short a time at the hospital had blinked their wrinkled way into
the world, starting at 7:40 a.m. Thursday. Half were the result of
fertility treatments. Four of the 12 parents were lawyers. One
father was a mailman. (``So both he and his wife deliver _ hah,
hah, hah!'' one of the public relations people said.)
</P>
<P>
   The numbers went on: by noon, two of the women had delivered
naturally, two had delivered by Caesarean section and one had had
what an obstetrician, Dr. Janet Stein, called ``the complete
obstetrical experience'' _ a natural birth and a Caesarean birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the last set,'' Dr. Stein said, ``we hope she'll push them
out any moment now.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important, everybody was fine, and the babies were
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   There were several reasons behind all the fuss at Beth Israel.
For one, the birth rate for twins in the United States has risen by
more than a third since 1980, in part because of the increasing use
of fertility treatments. So an entire social trend was compressed
into a hectic 29 hours and 42 minutes on the East Side of
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the event was a coup for Beth Israel as a competitor in
New York's carnivorous medical world. The hospital's reputation has
improved greatly in recent years, and it did not hurt for the
public to see six mothers who represented the diversity of New York
praising the work of doctors and nurses there. (Yet more
statistics: three of the mothers were white, one was black, one was
Hispanic and one was Chinese.)
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, hospitals compete wildly for pregnant women because
deliveries are profitable _ which helped to explain the general
solicitousness and the regular updates on the status of the
remaining parents-to-be as the afternoon wore on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The father of the sixth twins is suiting up!'' another public
relations person announced. Reporters raced, and cameras caught the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief photo opportunity in the neonatal intensive care
unit _ Sidney Capers, 30, the mailman, held two darling new
daughters _ it was time for the news conference. The parents got
bottles of water (the mothers were supplied with rear cushions) and
cheerily told reporters they were tired but exhilarated.
</P>
<P>
   Would there be reunions of the 12 children?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' said Mimi Brill, a 36-year-old legal aid lawyer
from Manhattan who gave birth to the first twins. ``It would be
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Were so many twins a surprise?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, said Marisol Portalatin, 32, of Manhattan, who gave one of
her new daughters the middle name Dazian (thrilling Beth Israel
because that is the name of the hospital building). ``My sister was
supposed to videotape the delivery but she was late,'' Ms.
Portalatin said. ``Now, I've got, one . . . two . . .'' and
indicated the other twins who ended up on the tape.
</P>
<P>
   How are the babies doing?
</P>
<P>
   ``They are sitting behind three sets of twin girls, so they're
happy,'' said Betty Troyetsky, 38, a Manhattan environmental lawyer
who gave birth to two little boys.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone having more children? Heads shook no all around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saving up for birth control,'' said Ms. Portalatin, who
already has four children.
</P>
<P>
   Before all the cameras were gone, Twin No. 11 was delivered, and
shortly thereafter at 1:22 p.m. came No. 12, both by Caesarean.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, here is the rundown (with parents' and babies'
names, babies' weights and delivery times:
</P>
<P>
   _ David Rountree and Mimi Brill of Manhattan: Isobel, 6.8
pounds, at 7:40 a.m. Thursday and Grace, 7.11 pounds, at 11:07 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marisol Portalatin of Manhattan: Alison Dazian Tiru, 3.11
pounds, at 12:47 p.m. and Alexis Tiru, 3.10 pounds, at 1:04 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mitchel and Betty Troyetsky of Manhattan: to Joshua, 3.10
pounds, at 1:09 p.m. and Daniel, 3.11 pounds, at 1:16 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Natalio Hanna and Anne Katz-Hanna: Joshua, 5.2 pounds, at 3:18
p.m. and Jacob, 4.2 pounds, at 3:19 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sidney and Tanjela Capers of Manhattan: Tireya Arne, 5.1
pounds, at 10:16 p.m. and Lanay Essence, 5.02 pounds, at 10:19 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kuong Kin Lao and Lan Chu Cheung of Brooklyn: Yun Chon at 1:09
p.m Friday and Yun Ioi at 1:22 p.m. (no weights available).
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said they could not yet tell which were fraternal twins
and which were identical.
</P>
<P>
   Rountree, also a legal aid lawyer, stood proudly over his two
new daughters, lying identically on their left sides with matching
striped blankets. He looked remarkably rested but a little amazed
by all the attention. Grace grunted, and Rountree rubbed her belly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK, sweetie,'' he said. ``It's just the media. Get used
to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
