<SLUG> BC-OPTIONS-TRADING-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS SHUT DOWN OPTIONS TRADING HOUSE FOR FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Ohio, Idaho, Calif.)  (af)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Securities regulators in four states, aided by the Federal
Bureau of Investigation, have moved to shut down an options trading
house that they accused of defrauding investors of millions of
dollars this year through the sale of options on foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators in Texas, Ohio, Idaho and California said Friday
that the Options Trading Group in Cleveland and two affiliated
firms were using aggressive and deceptive sales tactics to induce
investors to buy options on foreign currencies like the mark and
the yen.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of the huge investments returns promised, investors
were saddled with large losses and high commissions, with little if
any profits, regulators say. In some instances, investors _ some of
whom complained of losing hundreds of thousands of dollars _ were
told their investments had failed and that they would have to put
in more money to cover those losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We allege that the company told people about the huge profit
potential of these investments,'' said David Grauer, director of
enforcement at the Texas State Securities Board. ``But then they
were told they had huge losses and they were refused their money
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Regulators say the company, with branches in Austin, Texas;
Akron, Ohio, and Newport Beach, Calif., was working in concert with
two affiliates, Currency Trading International and Ronald Allan
Ltd., both of Newport Beach. All three companies were accused of
making ``cold calls'' to investors and then making fraudulent
representations.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, nine employees of the Options Trading Group,
including Jeffrey A. Moore, 32, the firm's president, were arrested
on racketeering and securities fraud charges by various state law
enforcement officials and FBI agents. Craig A. Cunningham, 41, who
has an ownership interest in all three firms, was also arrested in
California. Cunningham has a long disciplinary record, according to
the National Association of Securities Dealers.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone message left at the home of Moore was not returned.
Gerald Messerman, a lawyer in Cleveland who represented the Options
Trading Group in earlier litigation, said he did not know where to
reach Moore or Cunningham. Messerman said the nine employees were
being held on bail of between $2 million and $15 million. ``They've
all been arrested,'' he said. ``I can't tell you whether I
represent them or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The nine employees were indicted last month by a grand jury in
Idaho on charges of defrauding residents of the state. Over the
last few months, several other states have cooperated in
investigating the Options Trading Group, which was incorporated in
California in 1997. Currency Trading International and Ronald Allan
Ltd. were also indicted by a grand jury in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   In Orange County, Calif., a task force searched the offices of
Currency Trading and Ronald Allan Ltd. in Newport Beach, and seized
documents. They also froze the assets of the Options Trading Group.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, regulators obtained search warrants and a restraining
order preventing the company from doing business there, accusing
the firm of using unregistered agents and dealers to sell
unregistered securities. In Ohio, the FBI is investigating the
company, and state regulators have subpoenaed documents. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
