<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLS-INTEGRATION-4     07-31 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-INTEGRATION-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK PARENTS SAY LEARNING SUPERSEDES INTEGRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., Ohio, Pa.)  (js) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ African-American parents are more interested in
having public schools raise their academic standards than put their
energies into promoting integration, according to a new survey by
Public Agenda, a nonprofit research organization, and Public
Education Network, a national umbrella group of organizations whose
goal is to improve public education.
</P>
<P>
   While 8 in 10 parents, black as well as white, said they
believed that integrated schools could help improve race relations
and were a laudable goal, the consensus of both groups was that
schools should concentrate on academics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've spent a lot of time on race issues, and we need to
redirect some of those energies to getting our children better
educated,'' said a black parent from Pennsylvania in one of the
follow-up telephone interviews with parents who had taken part in
the survey, which was released this week.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the black parents polled and 72 percent of the white
parents said they thought integrated schools made little difference
in the quality of the education their children received.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, nearly three-quarters of black parents and 77
percent of white parents agreed with the statement that ``too
often, the schools work so hard to achieve integration that they
end up neglecting their most important goal _ teaching kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The report is based on a national telephone survey of 800
African-American and 800 white parents conducted this spring. The
margin of error was plus or minus three percentage points. In
addition, Public Agenda held eight focus groups across the nation
and interviewed 20 specialists in the field.
</P>
<P>
   The study also called attention to fear among some white parents
about integration. For example, one white parent in a Walnut Creek,
Calif., focus group said: ``They redrew the lines and brought in a
large section of low-income-housing kids into my children's
elementary school. Test scores dropped. These are kids that need
help and they get it. But it dumbs down the curriculum, and it
takes away from the gifted kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters of African-American parents said race should not
be a factor when choosing a teacher or superintendent for a
predominantly black school district. ``As long as he's doing his
job, I don't care if he's green,'' said a black parent in a
Cleveland focus group.
</P>
<P>
   Among other areas of agreement between black and white parents
was on the question of whether teachers should teach such values as
honesty, respect and civility: 84 percent of the black parents and
83 percent of the whites agreed it was a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   There was a sharp difference, however, in attitudes toward
diversity. Sixty percent of the black parents favored it, while
only 34 percent of the whites did.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Deborah Wadsworth, executive director of Public Agenda, said the
big surprise to her and her colleagues was ``the laserlike focus of
black Americans on the need for achievement, rigor and standards,
which must not be distracted by other considerations.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving Hamer , an African-American member of the Board of
Education of New York City, said the loss of interest in
integration that the report revealed was ``not surprising and
somewhat disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said, he shares the view that educational
quality should be the top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society is facing cataclysmic change, what with technological
development and the growth of the global economy, and once again
African-Americans are being left out. If we want to prevent that,
we have to focus, and the focus has to be on improved education.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey also studied views on standardized tests. Forty-four
percent of African-American parents said the tests that are used to
determine acceptance to college and eligibility for certain types
of financial aid measure ``real differences in educational
achievement,'' and an additional 18 percent said whites tend to
score higher because black students have less faith in their
ability.
</P>
<P>
   But only 28 percent said they believed that the tests are
culturally biased against African-American students.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next year, Public Agenda, which is based in New York
City, and the Public Education Network, which is in Washington,
intend to sponsor community discussions on issues raised by the
survey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-98 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
