<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-31 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-GRAND-CENTRAL-NY     07-31 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GRAND-CENTRAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE GRAND CENTRAL BID WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Aug. 1:
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers who understand the key role that business
improvement districts have played in the city's revitalization may
have been unnerved by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's decision to dissolve
the Grand Central Partnership, one of the largest and best-known
BID's. The mayor's action seems drastic, but his position is not,
on the whole, unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's chief complaint is that the partnership's president,
Daniel Biederman, is also the head of two other midtown BIDs, at
Bryant Park and 34th Street, creating a sort of mini-empire.
Biederman's defenders say the district operations are deeply
intertwined, and the smaller ones could not provide the present
level of services if they were forced to stand on their own. That
argument makes Giuliani's case. The money the city collects from
neighborhood property owners for a BID's use is supposed to stay in
that neighborhood _ something that is hard to guarantee when
operations are as blended as Biederman's seem to be.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Central Partnership's leaders seem ready to fight the
city in court, a decision that could create a long period of
uncertainty that would threaten all the gains the partnership has
made in improving the area around Grand Central Terminal. They
appear to regard their organization as a private company that can
do what it likes as long as the board of directors is pleased. But
BIDs are actually public-private partnerships. There are now 40
BIDs in New York City _ The New York Times is a member of the Times
Square BID _ and they have done a great deal to improve the
cleanliness, security and atmosphere of our commercial districts.
But if city hall begins to feel that the districts threaten its
prerogatives, the whole concept will be undermined.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's position appears to be based on a reasonable
conviction that BIDs should stick to a limited agenda, and remain
both community-based and self-supporting. To end this crisis,
Biederman must sever his ties with two of the BIDs he controls. The
Grand Central Partnership should respond to the administration's
other complaints about bidding procedures and keeping operations
open to government scrutiny. Property owners who finance the
partnership's operations must protect their own investment in their
community by making sure these things happen quickly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
